<HEADLINE>
PLANNERS MAY PUT HIGH-DENSITY, LOW-INCOME APARTMENTS IN
MIDDLE-CLASS SUBURBIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
By BETH BARRETT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Without public debate or a formal policy
directive, Los Angeles city officials are planning for massive
population growth based largely on providing high-density
apartments, mainly for low-income people, city housing projections
show.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the growth is targeted for middle-income areas, which
would dramatically alter parts of the San Fernando Valley,
including Sherman Oaks and Studio City, and other communities
throughout the city, a review by the Daily News found.
</P>
<P>
   The direction of city planning has surfaced since the Planning
Commission unexpectedly blocked adoption last month of the housing
element of the city's General Plan, a document required by state
law to show how a community expects to meet anticipated population
growth.
</P>
<P>
   City planners are relying on decades of past planning and zoning
decisions to formulate the housing element. At the same time, they
have made construction of affordable housing in the form of
apartments in residential neighborhoods across the Valley a central
focus of the new housing element.
</P>
<P>
   Their actions come without policy direction from the mayor or
City Council, an examination of the impact on neighborhoods or a
detailed study of the availability of transit, sewers, roads or
other municipal infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process is like a runaway train,'' said city Planning
Commission Vice President Bob Scott, a Woodland Hills attorney and
San Fernando Valley civic leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going in some direction on rails, but there doesn't seem
to be anyone at the controls, nobody is providing vision. It's a
bureaucratic-driven process. It's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Los Angeles is expected to grow from 3.6 million people to
more than 4.2 million by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   The San Fernando Valley is estimated to grow by about 233,700 to
nearly 1.5 million people by then, or nearly the size of Houston or
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, there were 1.3 million dwelling units in the city. That
number would climb by more than 10 percent if anticipated growth is
to be met without additional crowding.
</P>
<P>
   The planners' goal is to keep housing occupancy rates at 1990
levels, or 2.83 persons per unit. Construction of much of the
low-income housing would depend largely on the availability of
public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Richman, the manager of policy and planning in the city's
Housing Department, said nearly 150,000 new units, however, would
not ease Los Angeles' current overcrowding, which at 16 percent of
all households represents the highest rate of any major U.S. city.
</P>
<P>
   Adoption of the housing element _ normally regarded as a
technical document _ was temporarily delayed by the Planning
Commission in hopes it could be used to trigger a comprehensive
debate over growth and housing in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city talks about affordable housing, but what percentage
of the city's housing should be targeted low-income? Where should
the balance be struck?'' Scott asked. ``Does this mean we won't
stop until Sylmar has the same density as South Central? What's all
this going to look like in 20 years?
</P>
<P>
   ``The city adopts all these pieces of the General Plan, but they
are adopted in a vacuum. Then when it does something that seems
idiotic, officials point back to these elements and say, That's
what you adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   The apartment construction issue was raised Saturday at the
first gathering of San Fernando Valley Latino community leaders to
consider the possibility of Valley secession from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas J. Hogen-Esch, a University of Southern California
doctoral candidate writing his dissertation on urban secession
movements, suggested that Valley homeowner associations want
control over zoning to prevent the encroachment of apartment
buildings into areas dominated by single-family homes. He said some
cities exclude certain socioeconomic groups by prohibiting
apartments and multiple-family dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeff Brain, president of Valley Voters Organized Toward
Empowerment, which favors a study of Valley secession, said the
Valley already has a high degree of apartment development, with 50
percent of the Valley's residents being renters.
</P>
<P>
   Just how far L.A. officials are willing to go in publicly
debating the growth issue remains to be seen, but Mayor Richard
Riordan said a citywide housing policy remains high on his ``radar
screen,'' with the focus on rehabilitation of existing units, not
construction of tenement-like high-rises that could deteriorate
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Residents will not tolerate an overcrowded city,'' he said.
``We must continue to evaluate realistically how many people can
live in L.A. and under what circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   (second take to follow)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
