<HEADER>
A5860 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALLEY-APARTMENTS-2nd     12-07 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-APARTMENTS-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: what circumstances.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Examination of the housing element under consideration shows how
extensively communities have been zoned for high-density living
without community input or a policy consensus.
</P>
<P>
   The plan identifies room for 530,506 new dwellings in L.A. and
says there will be a need for 146,441 new units _ most of them
low-income _ by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley has room for 189,956 new units, it estimates. Demand
is anticipated to reach 35,795 new units within five years, nearly
half low-income.
</P>
<P>
   Such higher-density building would represent a sharp reversal of
recent Valley building trends. With most construction in
single-family homes, permits for only 132 apartment units have been
taken out this year.
</P>
<P>
   City planners acknowledge the arbitrary nature of their effort
to define how housing expectations will be met and point out that
calculations on where future housing might go are based on existing
zoning potential and current poverty rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has said how many poor people Los Angeles can handle,''
said Deputy Planning Director Franklin Eberhard.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one said: Gee whiz, West L.A. doesn't have enough, or some
other area has too much, let's give it to the Valley,'' he said.
``No one did that.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that there ``clearly is a tension between the need for
affordable housing and what communities would like to see happening
in their communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The housing element doesn't remove that tension.''
</P>
<P>
   The department said it will take years before an in-depth and
costly review of community plans is completed. A recent review
corrected mainly technical errors in the plans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Without coherent planning, officials said Los Angeles risks
creating slum pockets, overtaxing its streets and utilities and
destroying neighborhoods, many in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at our planning right now,'' said Council
President John Ferraro, who represents part of the southeast
Valley, including North Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't put people on top of each other. Before we adopt the
housing element, we have to look at all the problems of
infrastructure, schools, all the things that are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``These issues may not be important to someone living in
Brentwood or Pacific Palisades. But they're important to the people
living in other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Oaks, Studio City, Toluca Lake, North Hollywood and Van
Nuys are among the areas ripest for more apartment construction.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro said downzoning might be necessary to preserve some
communities' quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   West Los Angeles, by contrast, has an anticipated demand for
only 2,940 low-income units, just more than 3 percent of the city's
total.
</P>
<P>
   No developer is going to build low-income units in high-priced
communities, city officials said. But increasingly, community
leaders are rejecting the idea that poorer areas should be held
responsible for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, we can't continue to increase all the population
in the same few neighborhoods in the Valley and just south of the
Santa Monicas,'' Hollywood-area Councilwoman Jackie Goldberg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you overbuild you're breeding crime that no one wants. We
can't be creating large, gaping, soon-to-be-slum areas. The reality
is we're on a collision course between doing what is necessary to
support more population in existing areas, or expanding slightly in
other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood-Wilshire community already has 123,651 apartments,
condominiums and other units in its high-density corridor. The plan
estimates an additional 33,207 units _ two-thirds low-income _ will
be needed within five years.
</P>
<P>
   The state originally set a June deadline for completion of the
housing element, but has extended it until 2000, but Richman said
the low-income housing situation is urgent.
</P>
<P>
   She said that whatever affordable housing is built likely will
satisfy only a small percentage of the need in a city where four
low-income families are waiting in line for each low-cost apartment
on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Low income is considered $41,050 or less per year for a family
of four in Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really a matter of public policy,'' Richman said.
``How do you explain in the richest country in the world people
sleeping on the sidewalk? Do we have a narrow or an enlightened
self-interest?''
</P>
<P>
   (third take to follow)
</P>
</TEXT>
