<HEADER>
A5862 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALLEY-APARTMENTS-3rd     12-07 0462
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALLEY-APARTMENTS-3rd-take-LADN </SLUG>
  
LOS ANGELES: self-interest?''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Councilman Michael Feuer, who represents the Sherman Oaks area
in a district that straddles the Santa Monicas, said low-income
housing can be compatible with high quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   He said many people who qualify for such housing are
professionals and other working people who enhance, rather than
detract from neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Providing there are adequate streets and utilities, Feuer said
some kinds of density _ like a planned 85-unit senior housing
complex in Sherman Oaks _ can serve neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lower-income units actually have diminished traffic impact,''
he added, noting their residents typically depend on mass transit.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Oaks residents _ many of whom took the senior housing
project as a bitter loss _ say that without a reassessment of land,
the door remains open to far greater development, whether they like
it or not.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Close, president of the Sherman Oaks Homeowners
Association, said his group asked city planners to reopen zoning
discussions 1{ years ago and to consider housing and other
quality-of-life issues but were rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told that only inconsistencies and corrections of
errors in the plan would be addressed _ not major changes,'' said
Close, whose community had fought to keep the senior citizen
apartment at 39 units.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the debate,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who will have the power: the communities to focus on quality
of life, or the politicians and unions that want to maximize the
size of projects?''
</P>
<P>
   There already are 18,726 apartment units and homes built in
Southeast Valley multiple-family zones.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 33 apartment units per acre theoretically could be built
on properties that lap against the Los Angeles River, then meander
along major corridors like Moorpark Street and Colfax, Woodman,
Fulton and Coldwater avenues and lick at established, single-family
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Already the roads are grinding to a halt, parking isn't
available. To downtown, the quality of life in neighborhoods is a
low priority,'' Close said.
</P>
<P>
   Five public workshops were held on the housing element about a
year ago. Public turnout was low, despite 1,000 meeting notices
mailed to residents and an advertising campaign on television and
the Internet, planners said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said he objected that the system did not reach out to more
people and that it was designed to comply with state regulations,
not grapple with a planning vision for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials have joined him in calling for an open debate on
future growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get everyone in the room who cares about this and
to figure out a plan that does the least harm to the most people,''
said Goldberg. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
