<HEADLINE>
KILLER CALL AFFECTS MORE THAN OUTCOME OF ONE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Before Seattle fans commit to a full
week of kill-the-refs contempt, it's helpful to recall that the
Seahawks should not have been in position, during Sunday's game as
well as the season, to need the benevolence of fair judgment in
order to avoid a 10th straight playoff-free season.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that ... Kill the refs.
</P>
<P>
   Now, don't write me letters. I don't mean it literally. Hot
gravel in the pantaloons would be a fine alternative.
</P>
<P>
   And if that seems cruel, how about demanding something much more
mundane, yet a significant element in most everyone's workday life:
Accountability.
</P>
<P>
   It's not likely that the seven-man crew of officials who blew
the decisive moment in the Seahawks-Jets game will be held to a
public reckoning. The NFL works in secretive ways. For the most
part, that's a wise move, since these accountants, insurance
salesmen and high school gym teachers who rule weekly on America's
most popular spectactor sport would be creating a lot of widows and
orphans if they were publicly identified.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't seem unreasonable to ask they be available to
questioners, that their methods be scrutinized, their shortcomings
acknowledged and their reprimands published.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the NFL perpetuates a travesty that is beginning to
dominate its image, which had another dubious display at the NFL's
main stage in the shadows of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The best Sunday's blown call can be called is a damn shame. The
worst that some are calling it is Seahawk career-ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wins and losses have serious effects on people's lives and
careers,'' said Seahawk guard Pete Kendall, fuming. ``Bad as the
call was, what do you do about it?''
</P>
<P>
   What the NFL will do is fine Kendall and his teammates and
coaches for venting their outrage instead of sanctioning the
principals involved. While it isn't fair that referess be vilified
for every blown judgment call, the system, supplemented by video
(and, in the case of the Pittsburgh-Detroit Thanksgiving Day game,
audio) replay, needs a serious overhaul to restore public and
participant credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could have been one of the biggest wins in Seahawk
history,'' said Seahawk receiver Mike Pritchard. ``Playing on the
road in New York, against a good team, with a new, young
quarterback ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was, in coach Dennis Erickson's words, the ``most
disappointing loss'' of his career. Indeed, it will be the one that
demarcates the end of his Seahawk tenure. Although he will finish
out the year, the 32-31 defeat marks the season's seventh loss and
elimination from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   While any one of several agonizing losses can be put through the
coulda-shoulda-woulda test, Sunday seemed destined to be a win that
would at least buy Erickson some league-wide respect. To have
defeated in one season AFC rivals Marty Schottenheimer of Kansas
City and Bill Parcells of the Jets would have been worthy, if
ultimately futile, chips to take to the bargaining table with
Seahawk president Bob Whitsitt for a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the granting of a 5-yard touchdown run to Jets
quarterback Vinny Testaverde, when replays showed indisputably that
he traveled only about 4{ yards, invalidated not only a splendid
Seahawk effort but the point of these weekly exercises: Let the
best team win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my job, and I feel like people are toying with me,''
said linebacker Chad Brown. ``To have part-time guys do this is
crap.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a reference to the fact that NFL officiating is a
weekend gig done by guys with regular jobs. While it's debatable
whether more training would have changed the outcome _ it appeared
that only one of the referees had either the position or the guts
to make a quick call, and it was the wrong one _ the fact that the
game's decisive play occurred in a closed-in end zone with a
raucous home crowd demanding a touchdown raises the issue of
professionalism.
</P>
<P>
   The call was made only after a group meeting, suggesting there
was either a difference of opinion or no opinion among most of the
crew. And since a call against the home team on the game's decisive
play can be a life-threatening event in New York, it's not
difficult to imagine a less resolute member voting based on the
specter of a size-D battery deployed as a brain implant from 20
yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have it happen like that ... '' said Erickson, who topped a
full season of stricken postgame looks with a death-row pallor,
``it just makes you sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Real estate in New York is among the world's most expensive, yet
on this unusually warm afternoon some valued, hard-to-get swampland
was given away free.
</P>
<P>
   One need have no interest in the Jets or the Seahawks to have an
interest in fair play, and to realize that bit of real estate, and
all that takes place upon it, has to be treated with a little more
value and respect.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the Seahawks will have a call like that go their way
someday. When they do, a lot of the people who were victimized
won't be around for the karmic payback.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
