r S &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-JETS-SPI     12-07 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-JETS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS SNEAK OUT WIN ON BLOWN CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ As Cortez Kennedy was making his way
through the locker room, assistant offensive line coach Bill Meyers
stopped the Seahawks' defensive tackle in mid-trudge.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers put his hands on Kennedy's massive shoulders, stared
straight into his eyes and offered, ``You made a hellvua play. You
won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for Kennedy, Meyers and the rest of the Seahawks,
the officials did not agree.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed that Kennedy had dragged Jets' quarterback Vinny
Testaverde to the turf short of the goal line on fourth down in the
final seconds of Sunday's game at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest in a series of blown calls by league officials
awarded Testaverde the touchdown, giving the Jets a frantic 32-31
victory and snuffing the Seahawks' flickering playoff hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Losing this game would have been bad enough for the Seahawks,
now 6-7. Knowing a blown call had taken it away from them was much
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our season right there. Our season came down to one
play on the goal line,'' said strong safety Jay Bellamy, who helped
finish what Kennedy started by pouncing on Testaverde as he was
falling toward the goal line. ``It was a bogus call. If it's a
touchdown, it's a touchdown. Then all right, we got beat. But let
the players decide the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's plunge toward the end zone was not shown on the
stadium replay screen. But the players closest to the play knew the
Jets quarterback never crossed the goal line. Not with the ball.
Not even with his helmet.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys need to go to Oz to get some courage and to get
some heart,'' said defensive end Michael Sinclair, using a Wizard
of Oz analogy to describe the officials' indecisiveness on the
decisive play. ``You make the obvious calls, but what about the
tough ones? I don't feel they came through today. I really don't.
It was awful. Awful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys should be fined.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sinclair can expect to be fined by the league office
for his comments. Players and coaches are not supposed to criticize
the officiating. Not even this year, when blown calls are becoming
an epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   Sinclair obviously did not care.
</P>
<P>
   As for the officials, the worse they can expect is a reprimand _
even this crew headed by referee Phil Luckett, the same official
who botched the coin toss to begin the overtime period in the
Thanksgiving Day game between the Pittsburgh Steelers and Detroit
Lions.
</P>
<P>
   The league office will review videotape of this game, as its
does with all games. The Seahawks can expect a phone call, probably
on Wednesday, telling them the wrong call was made on Testaverde's
run.
</P>
<P>
   Then what?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no recourse,'' said Randy Mueller, Seahawks vice
president of football operations, who was slumped upon a stool in a
far corner of the locker room. ``No recourse at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the Seahawks' angst was the way the play was called.
As soon as Testaverde disappeared into a pile of players, two
officials signaled touchdown _ side judge Laird Hayes, who was some
30 yards away from the pile along the Jets sideline, and head
linesman Earnie Frantz, who was behind the play in the end zone.
Umpire Hendi Ancich, who was in the middle of the melee, never made
a call. Luckett later explained that Frantz's call was the
determining factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy in the middle never called anything,'' Sinclair said.
``They need instant replay. They need to bring it back.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have helped the Seahawks' cause Sunday. Repeated TV
replays from three different angles showed that Testaverde did not
break the plane of the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Some on the field came up with the same conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Vinny get hit probably around the 2 or 3 (yard line) and
I know for a fact that he was no way near the goal line,''
cornerback Shawn Springs said.
</P>
<P>
   When it was suggested that perhaps Testaverde had reached the
ball over the goal line after he was down, Springs' face contorted
in a yeah-right expression before he added, ``If they are going to
say he made a second effort or whatever, in that case he fumbled
and Jay Bellamy recovered the fumble. In that case, it should have
been our ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his effort after going down, Testaverde said, ``It was an
effort to get the ball over the goal line, and that's what the refs
saw.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' late rally erased what Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson
considered one of his team's most courageous efforts in the past
four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played their rear ends off,'' Erickson said. ``And to
lose it on a play like that, it's totally disappointing and it just
makes you sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks jumped to leads to of 21-10 and 31-19 as Jon Kitna
hooked up with Joey Galloway for two long touchdown passes (70 and
57 yards), Ricky Watters scored on his longest run since 1996 (37
yards) and rookie linebacker Anthony Simmons returned an
interception 36 yards for a TD.
</P>
<P>
   But Testaverde kept bringing the Jets back. He completed 42 of
63 passes for 418 yards. He threw TD passes to fullback Keith Byars
and wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson, and also made the throws to set
up a TD run by Curtis Martin and a pair of field goals by John
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde also passed himself into position for the final
quarterback sneak toward the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a perfect call,'' Johnson said of Testaverde's
run on fourth down.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the play surprised the Seahawks, Springs said,
``Obviously not, because we stopped it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unofficially, that is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of bobbled it as I was running through the line. I
wasn't able to reach the ball out,'' Testaverde said. ``The refs
called it good _ I heard the replays showed it wasn't _ and we had
some calls go against us as well. I thought it was going to be
close. But when you get knocked around, you can't see as good as
the refs.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Testaverde's career passing day, another impressive
showing by Kitna and a slew of big plays by both teams, what will
be remembered from this game is the blown call that cost the
Seahawks a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sucked,'' Sinclair said. ``The refs sucked.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
