<SLUG> BC-FBC-OAHU-BOWL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAHU PAIRS AIR FORCE WITH UW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The fallout from UCLA's upset loss Saturday at Miami
affected the postseasons of four Pac-10 football teams, last of
them Washington, which Sunday was named to face Air Force in the
fledgling Oahu Bowl in Honolulu on Christmas Day at 5:30 p.m. PST.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game of the first-ever bowl doubleheader, Oregon
will meet Colorado in the Aloha Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe yesterday,'' said Marcia Klompus, executive
director of the Hawaii bowls, referring to the upsets of UCLA and
Kansas State. Then, in reference to Kansas State (11-1) being
excluded from the eight-team Bowl Championship Series, she added,
``I couldn't believe this morning, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Kansas State and UCLA, the big losers from Saturday's
results were Central Florida and athletic administrators of the
Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Central Florida had earned a conditional bid to Hawaii if the
Pac-10 couldn't send the second team along with Washington it was
contracted for. But UCLA's loss knocked the Bruins from the
national-title game in the Fiesta Bowl to the Rose Bowl, while
Arizona fell from the Rose to the Holiday, and Oregon dropped from
the Holiday to the Aloha, replacing Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Washington likely would have played Colorado in the Aloha if
UCLA had won and Oregon had stayed out of Hawaii. But, said
Klompus, ``Oregon played Air Force last year (in the Las Vegas
Bowl), and ESPN wasn't interested in that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the second straight year a Pac-10 team that was a
nine-point favorite lost a final regular-season game and thus cost
each conference school about $500,000 in the league's bowl
revenue-sharing system. Last year, Arizona State was upset by
Arizona and fell out of the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first two reactions were, I felt bad for the conference,''
Klompus said, ``and then for Central Florida. Then my business
heart took over and I said, `Hey, that's why we made these two bowl
games, to have two Pac-10 teams.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force matchup pits Washington against a team it meets
next Sept. 18 in Seattle. The Falcons (11-1) run the wishbone with
quarterback Blane Morgan _ who played on a bad ankle in his team's
20-13 victory over Brigham Young in the WAC title game _ and led
the WAC in scoring at 36.6 points a game. They also were No. 1 in
total defense at 284.7 yards a game.
</P>
<P>
   This will be the fourth time Washington has played in Hawaii on
Christmas Day. Oregon will be making its first appearance in the
Aloha, and facing a Colorado team that beat the Ducks 38-6 in the
1995 Cotton Bowl, a game Oregon remembers for a fake punt run by
the Buffaloes in the waning moments.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies began bowl practices Saturday and also worked out
Sunday. Defensive end Josh Smith, who sustained a knee strain in
the Oregon loss Nov. 7, is not yet having contact work. His
position coach, Randy Hart, stayed out of the practice with a bad
back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
