</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REIGN COACHES EMBRACE LIFE `AT NEXT LEVEL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The coaches of Seattle's women's pro basketball team
are bona fide Southerners. Tammy Holder is from Richmond, Va.,
where she coached the University of Richmond Spiders until becoming
director of basketball operations for the ABL's Richmond (now
Philadelphia) Rage three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Wilson, the Reign's associate coach, is from a little
deeper down in Dixie. Wilson has 13 seasons as head coach of South
Carolina to her credit, not to mention a wondrous, rolling Southern
drawl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere we go around here, Nancy has to repeat everything
because people can't understand what she's saying,'' Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   True, in these Northwest environs, honey-coated Carolina accents
are about as common as sunny days in winter. But in this brave new
world of professional women's basketball, the Reign's two Southern
coaches have made their way West, getting some interesting lessons
in geography, among other things, along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for the Reign's road game against the Power, Holder
and Wilson were flying with the team down to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``And here was Nancy reciting all the names of the mountains,''
Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stewardess was trying to correct me, but I know which ones
are which. There was Baker, Rainier, Mount St. Helen's and Adams,''
Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, Wilson's ability to identify the volcanic peaks of
the Cascades was pretty darn good for a woman who vowed last
December that her stint in Seattle would last only until the end of
the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   For Holder, who was named head coach a year ago after the
midseason firing of Jacquie Hullah, it had been a semi-hard sell to
get Wilson to join her.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and Holder first met in 1982 during an Athletes in Action
basketball tour in Southeast Asia. Two years later, after Holder
got her master's degree from Richmond, Wilson invited Holder to be
one of her assistants at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the roles are slightly reversed, although Holder
refuses to call Wilson her ``assistant,'' since coaching duties and
leadership on the Reign are equal. Holder runs the offense, Wilson
the defense. Holder works the officials and runs the huddles.
Wilson diagrams plays and keeps track of the details.
</P>
<P>
   `We're just two ladies coaching a very great group of basketball
players,'' said Holder, who is just glad Wilson decided to help out
with the Reign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told Tammy I'd come out here, I had no intention of
being out here for more than those 2{ months,'' said Wilson, who
resigned at South Carolina in March 1997 to care for her ailing
mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'd have to say that 15 minutes after I was on the court
for that first (Reign) practice, I loved it. I had totally
forgotten, in those last years that I was in the SEC (the
ultra-competitive Southeastern Conference) beating my head against
the wall every day, how much I loved the actual game,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   In this new era of women's pro hoops, we've heard a lot of talk
about how great it is for the nation's top women players to have a
place to go once their college careers are complete.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Starbird and Niesa Johnson and Val Whiting and Shalonda
Enis all are former collegiate standouts whose job it is now to win
games for the Reign _ something they are doing with remarkable
frequency these days, going 7-2. They move the ball. They run and
shoot and believe they should win. They can play.
</P>
<P>
   But if women's pro hoops has broadened the horizons of the
athletes whose futures now extend beyond college, what can you say
about the coaches?
</P>
<P>
   Here in Seattle, Holder and Wilson are getting their opportunity
to dig into the game they love at a higher level, too. And both
women are more than pleasantly surprised about what they have
discovered about coaching a women's pro team, free of the
recruiting and academic issues that make college coaching so
exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   When Holder was working with Wilson at Carolina, she said it was
draining ``keeping up with the Joneses'' of the powerful SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the ACC was right next door, too. We had one of the
nation's top recruits tell us that she thought Geno Auriemma, who
as an assistant at Virginia at the time (now coach of the mighty
UConn women), was the most handsome man she had ever seen. So we
knew we were in for a tough battle to get her to sign with us,''
Holder said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, too, was astounded by the growing demands of running a
top-notch Division I women's program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty brutal in the SEC. I mean, there was no relief
anywhere in your conference schedule. And when South Carolina moved
into the SEC, yes, it opened the door for us to get into the homes
of a lot of top recruits, but that didn't mean we could get them. I
mean, (the University of) Georgia and (Pat Summit's) Tennessee were
one state away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Wilson did not score her share of top recruits, helping
Wilson become a mainstay with USA Basketball. Now, though, the
rigors of relentless recruiting are behind Wilson and Holder, who
are thrilled to be able to do more pure coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a coach's dream,'' Holder said. ``These women are
self-disciplined and they're all talented.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think on this level, you can coach to each player's
strength. In college, you coach to hide your team's weaknesses,''
Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing when not to overcoach may be the secret to success in
the women's pro game _ something the first Reign coaching staff did
not understand. Luckily, the Reign has two very pro coaches whose
experience and philosophy have unlocked the potential of this
winning team.
</P>
<P>
   And they can even recite the names of the Cascade's highest
peaks, in buttery Southern accents to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 0047EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5877 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BAYLOR-ROBERTS-HN     12-07 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAYLOR-ROBERTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
WACO _ After back-to-back 2-9 seasons, Baylor officials announced
Sunday night that head football coach Dave Roberts would be
reassigned within the athletic department.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baylor athletic director Tom Stanton was not available for
comment, but a faxed release from the athletic department said the
search for a new coach would begin immediately. No information was
provided on the status of the assistant coaches under Roberts, but
the release said Roberts would be given other responsibilities in
the department.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about Roberts being replaced have been circulating for
more than a week, and there has been speculation that school
officials are interested in former Texas A&AMP;M and Alabama coach Gene
Stallings, who has a ranch in Paris, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been contacted by Baylor,'' Stallings said Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Stallings, 63, said he is committed to coaching a college
all-star team that will play a series of games in Italy next
summer. When asked if he would be interested if Baylor contacted
him, Stallings said: ``I think the chances of me getting back in it
are slim.''
</P>
<P>
   Stallings retired from coaching three years ago, but he led the
Crimson Tide to the 1992 national championship. He was 70-16-1 as
head coach at Alabama from 1990-96. Stallings was head coach at
Texas A&AMP;M from 1965 to 1971 and also coached the Arizona Cardinals
from 1986 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Gunn, an administrative assistant on the Baylor coaching
staff, is Stallings' son-in-law. One source close to the Baylor
athletic program said school officials had considered bringing in
Stallings for two or three years to groom Dallas Highland Park High
School coach Scott Smith to take over the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not been contacted by anyone from Baylor,'' Smith said
when reached at home Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would entertain an offer to join the Baylor coaching
staff, Smith said: ``I can't comment on that, because we just
finished our season here last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 40, was a backup quarterback and defensive back for
former Baylor coach Grant Teaff from 1977 to 1981 and served as a
graduate assistant under Teaff for two seasons. Smith led Highland
Park to the Class 4A playoffs each of the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   It also has been speculated that Teaff, who coached the Bears
from 1972 to 1992, might be asked to come in on a short-term basis
if Stallings were not interested.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, 51, informed the players Sunday evening that he would
not be the coach next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys were disappointed, but some were relieved,'' Baylor
linebacker David Armstrong said. ``We're just tired of going
through all this losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor was 2-9 overall and 1-7 in Big 12 play in each of the two
seasons under Roberts, a former offensive coordinator at Notre Dame
under Lou Holtz.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears were 2-3 after five games this season, including an
upset over North Carolina State, which was ranked 25th in the
nation at the time after an upset of Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all downhill after a victory against Kansas on Oct.
10. The Bears lost their last six games, and attendance at Floyd
Casey Stadium was the lowest in more than 20 years. The team
finished last in the Big 12 in total offense and total defense.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, a former head coach at Northeast Louisiana and Western
Kentucky with a career record of 68-67-3, was hired to replace
Chuck Reedy, who was fired after the Bears recorded a 4-7 record in
the first year of the Big 12 Conference in 1996. Reedy was
finishing the fourth year of a five-year contract as the handpicked
replacement for Teaff.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor is in the process of spending millions to upgrade Floyd
Casey Stadium, including the addition of 34 luxury suites and a new
press box. Most of the suites already have been sold for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say some of the prominent alumni who have purchased
luxury suites were insistent that a change be made with the head
coach before next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like there was a big demand to get (Roberts) out,''
Baylor cornerback Gary Baxter said. ``I guess they felt they had to
make a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor officials never announced the length of Roberts'
contract, but he is believed to have had a three-year deal.
Roberts' tenure as head coach was the shortest at the school since
1913, when Norman Payne left after one season with a 4-4-2 record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
