<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BUG'S LIFE' REMAINS ATOP THE HOLLYWOOD FOOD CHAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Will also move in the ``n'' California news file.) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Moviegoers continued to swarm the nation's
multiplexes to see ``A Bug's Life'' as the computer-animated comedy
dominated the U.S. box office with an estimated $17.4 million at
2,701 theaters during the Friday-Sunday period, studio sources said
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The results gave the Disney project, co-produced by Pixar
Animation, a total of $69 million after 12 days in nationwide
release. The Friday-Sunday take for ``A Bug's Life'' declined 47
percent from the previous Friday-Sunday, in line with forecasts as
overall moviegoing followed its traditional pattern of sliding
sharply during the first weekend of December following Thanksgiving
vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Disney marketing executive Chuck Viane noted that the
weekend-to-weekend decline for ``A Bug's Life'' was the smallest of
holdover films. ``We are getting a very balanced demographic for
this film and we are starting to see a lot of repeat viewers,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Viane pointed out that one-third of the audience for ``A Bug's
Life'' has been between 2 and 11 years old and another third
between 12 and 25.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Arthur Rockwell said ``A Bug's Life'' would easily
outperform the past three Disney animated films _ ``The Hunchback
of Notre Dame,'' ``Hercules'' and ``Mulan'' _ but might not match
the $192 million domestic take of 1995's ``Toy Story,'' the first
Disney-Pixar collaboration, due to increased choices for
moviegoers. `` `A Bug's Life' has obviously done very well against
tremendous competition,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's opening of its ``Psycho'' remake, starring Anne
Heche and Vince Vaughn, debuted with a respectable $10.7 million at
2,477 theaters as it benefited from being the only major movie to
debut, the popularity of the horror genre and the novelty of
reshooting the 1960 Alfred Hitchcock release.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Psycho' is getting tons of press and the market is deluged
with family films right now,'' said Robert Bucksbaum, president of
the Reel Source forecasting service. He projected ``Psycho'' could
gross as much as $50 million domestically, which would make the $20
million movie highly profitable for its beleaguered studio.
</P>
<P>
   Three holdovers also performed solidly, led by Disney's third
weekend of ``Enemy of the State'' with $9.5 million at 2,458 sites
as the Will Smith vehicle neared $63 million after 17 days.
Paramount's third weekend of ``The Rugrats Movie'' followed with $8
million at 2,832 theaters to nearly hit $68 million and Disney's
fifth weekend of ``The Waterboy'' continued to draw decently with
$6.6 million at 2,778 locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Waterboy'' now has $130.8 million after 31 days and is the
89th film to take in more than $130 million at the domestic box
office.
</P>
<P>
   The overall weekend total hit close to $77 million, up an
impressive 35 percent from the year-ago period, as the top five
films accounted for two-thirds of receipts. Year-to-date business
has topped $6.1 billion, or about 10 percent ahead of last year's
total to this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of good product out there,'' Rockwell said.
``Christmas shopping did not derail the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The weekend's downside came from a pair of high-priced Universal
projects that continued to perform below expectations _ the fourth
weekend of ``Meet Joe Black'' with $2.6 million at 2,180 screens
and the second weekend of ``Babe: Pig in the City'' with $2.5
million at 2,385 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The negative press has just killed `Babe,' '' Bucksbaum said
of the sequel, costing a reported $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Babe: Pig in the City'' earned a mere $11.5 million after 12
days and its poor performance led to the recent departure of studio
chief Casey Silver. The studio has launched a massive push for its
next film, ``Patch Adams,'' starring Robin Williams in a medical
school comedy due out Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Gramercy's fifth weekend of ``Elizabeth'' continued to draw well
in eighth with $2 million at 540 theaters. Warner Bros.' second
weekend of Drew Barrymore's ``Home Fries'' followed in ninth with
$1.76 million at 1,925 locations, edging Sony's fourth weekend of
``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer'' with $1.75 million at
2,212 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   PolyGram's ``Very Bad Things'' followed in 11th with $1.6
million at 1,260 locations.
</P>
<P>
   Miramax's opening of Academy Awards hopeful ``Little Voice''
generated solid results with $91,400 at six theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Bug's Life'' could lead next weekend although it will face
solid competition from Paramount's opening of ``Star Trek:
Insurrection'' at more than 2,600 theaters. Also debuting will be
Warner's family comedy ``Jack Frost,'' starring Michael Keaton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
