<HEADER>
A5881 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-07 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LOPEZCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WE sat in our living rooms and couldn't believe our eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the most dramatic, decisive day of college football
we had seen all year. It just couldn't get any better.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA put on a wild show, with Cade McNown becoming a human
adjective, tossing heroic bombs all over the football patch.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Bruins watched their national-championship hopes go
south, to Miami, mostly because the Bruins' defense was like a
cheap horror movie _ it looked fierce but for the most part was
harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Texas A&AMP;M showed Bill Snyder's Kansas State Wildcats that
loose lips don't sink ships, but Aggies linebacker Dat Nguyen and
the better-late-than-never careers of seniors Branndon Stewart and
Sirr Parker do.
</P>
<P>
   After a season's worth of muzzling the spectacular Michael
Bishop, Snyder tried to put the disappointment into words once the
Aggies' shocking double-overtime upset was done. But it was all
just silent screams.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was the definitive and impressive Tennessee
finish to the Southeastern Conference title game. This Tennessee
team proved it deserves a shot at the national championship, no
matter what kind of close calls the Vols might have had against
Syracuse, Arkansas or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Shakedown Saturday sent the pollsters scurrying for a way to
make sense of it all and the Bowl Championship Series computers
wheezing and coughing in search of a way to squeeze four or five
deserving teams into a two-team Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, it was a day that deserved better treatment
than it received Sunday. Somebody should sue over the
bowl-selection debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps BCS chief Roy Kramer even should sue himself, calling it
Kramer vs. Kramer, because on the one hand he told us that
Shakedown Saturday only showed why the ``integrity'' of the current
system should remain untouched. But on the other, he responded to
the clear injustices of the bowl pairings Sunday by saying, hey,
this is just a business.
</P>
<P>
   What's it going to be, Roy? Integrity or business?
</P>
<P>
   Kramer and the BCS boys told us one thing but showed us another.
What's it going to be? More years of late-season bowl-pairing
letdowns? Or finally a playoff system that could make days like
Saturday lead to something other than frustration for clear title
contenders?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the glowing aftermath there should have been after
Saturday's remarkable games, it proved to be a Sunday, bloody
Sunday of fuming fans, bickering experts and coaches feeling
spurned and cheated.
</P>
<P>
   After not believing our eyes for all the terrific college
football moments, we could not believe our ears when the BCS tried
to tell us everything was fine with K-State getting snubbed and
Syracuse making it into a $12 million game.
</P>
<P>
   What should have followed Saturday's entertaining day was
another one the next weekend, as survivors moved on to the
semifinals, then those survivors to the final. Each round of the
remainder of the season would prove to be better than the previous
one. And no one could argue with the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Saturday should not have been the best thing
we'll see all year, it's going to have to be. The bowl system
failed again. Boy, Roy. You've gotta do better than this.
</P>
<P>
   Florida-Syracuse in the Orange Bowl? Kramer talked integrity but
then told us the Gators ``earned'' the at-large berth instead of
the higher-ranked Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State was on the brink of the national championship into
the evening hours Saturday and fought to the last man in double
overtime. Its reward was a trip to the Alamo Bowl against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   We heard about the business of it all, but it's all funny
business.
</P>
<P>
   And come Jan. 5, there will be questions asked, people wondering
and coaches, players and fans justifiably feeling cheated.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee-Florida State will be a terrific match in the Fiesta,
no doubt. If the Vols win, few could argue against their
national-championship rights.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't you have wanted to see what Ohio State could have
done over the next couple of weekends? Or what the Buckeyes could
have done in an eventual matchup with Tennessee? Or how Kansas
State would have reacted to its heartbreaker?
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you have sat there and watched every moment of the next
round of games? There would have been Arizona, Syracuse, Florida,
maybe even overlooked Tulane providing the kinds of thrills that
Miami, Texas A&AMP;M and Tennessee did Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been the logical next step. It's what Saturday
deserved but didn't get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
