<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE SPARKS PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Chad Eaton had just beaten up the best center in
the business, Pittsburgh's Dermontti Dawson, for a team-high eight
tackles and three sacks. His arms and neck were red and scraped
from the battle, and sweat was pouring from him.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton was pleased, and he was asked about Sunday's defensive
revival by the Patriots, who held the Steelers to three field
goals, kept Kordell Stewart to no rushing attempts, caused him to
rush his throws (21 of 45, 206 yards, two interceptions), and held
Jerome Bettis to 48 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally,'' said Eaton, who watched admiringly as his former
Washington State teammate, quarterback Drew Bledsoe, connected nine
times with Terry Glenn in a 23-9 victory over the Steelers.
``Finally, we were able to shut down a team. The last two weeks
were about our offense making the plays at the end of the game to
win, but today we finally got our defense right.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' third straight win, in balmy Three Rivers Stadium,
improved them to 8-5. They remained tied with Buffalo for third
place in the AFC East, as the Bills and the teams tied one game
ahead in first, the Jets and Dolphins, also won.
</P>
<P>
   But middle linebacker Ted Johnson tore his right biceps tendon
on the second play of the game and is lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the team rallied around that.
</P>
<P>
   Backup Marty Moore came on and helped fill the enormous void by
stuffing the run.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pete Carroll paid tribute to Johnson afterward, calling
him the ``heart and soul of our defense.'' But as Johnson watched
from the sideline, he probably saw more heart and soul than he's
seen from the defense all season.
</P>
<P>
   The containment game New England played, the blitzing from new
angles and on delays, all were huge in stopping the Steelers, who
have only six field goals to show for their last 14 red zone
chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers may not even make it to the playoffs now, with a
7-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed,'' said Steelers coach Bill Cowher.
``Right now we're going to find out about ourselves, this whole
football team. I'm going to sit down, look at it, and make some
decisions accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have no such worries. They found out a lot about
their character and their ability to finally win in Pittsburgh
after a 12-year drought.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge was theirs after the Steelers had snatched two
heart-breaking games from them last season, including the 7-6
playoff loss here.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe threw for 327 yards, with one touchdown and three
interceptions, and he found Glenn often. Glenn, who didn't speak to
reporters after submitting the greatest receiving performance in
Patriots history by going for 193 yards on those nine grabs, caught
an 86-yard bomb with 1:56 left in the first half that made it 13-3,
Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry is so explosive coming out of the break that people who
cover him have to give him some space and give up the underneath
stuff, but he just broke loose and I found him out there all
alone,'' Bledsoe said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn beat his coverage by a country mile as the Steelers
blitzed Bledsoe on the play. Glenn waited for the heave, caught it
at the 45, and sprinted the rest of the way with free safety Darren
Perry chasing helplessly. It was the fourth-longest pass play in
Patriots history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry continues to show how important he is to our club,''
said Carroll. ``And Drew, on that corner route that went for a
touchdown, was an exceptionally thrown ball, since he had to throw
it at the last possible second.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, Terry was one-on-one with the safety,''
said fellow receiver Shawn Jefferson. ``Any time you hook up a
receiver one-on-one with the safety, it's a win-win situation. They
have a tendency to blitz; that's how we ended up with that
matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were running a lot of stunts on us early in the game, and
then, after that play, they backed off a bit,'' said center Dave
Wohlabaugh.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots survived a sloppy third quarter, in which they were
penalized eight times (they had 12 for 77 yards in all).
</P>
<P>
   On their first possession of the second half, Bledsoe moved the
Patriots from their 25 to the 42 before he fumbled (and recovered
it), then had an interception, when he tried to step up in the
pocket and was picked off by Chris Oldham.
</P>
<P>
   At that point Bledsoe was having problems with the splint on his
broken finger, and balls were taking off on him.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers took over at the New England 46, but could manage
only a Norm Johnson 43-yard field goal to make it 13-9.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots got the ball back, more throws were sailing on
Bledsoe, giving rise to the possibility that Tom Tupa or Scott
Zolak might get the call. New England started the drive at its 19
following a holding penalty on a kickoff and went in reverse to the
5.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa was forced to punt from deep in his end zone, and he boomed
a 63-yarder that Courtney Hawkins returned 14 yards to the Steelers
49. But the Patriots' defense got tough. Eaton stuck Bettis on a
2-yard gain and then Stewart made two poor throws, one with Lawyer
Milloy and Larry Whigham hitting him right after.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots remained in poor field position until the defense
made a huge play. Willie Clay tipped a Stewart pass intended for
Charles Johnson, and it was picked off by Ty Law at the Steeler 18
as time expired in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots tried three runs by Robert Edwards, but he was
stuffed for a 3-yard loss on third and 2, setting the stage for
Adam Vinatieri's third field goal, a 35-yarder that made it 16-9.
</P>
<P>
   After the kickoff, with the crowd booing loudly, Stewart
completed a 7-yard pass to tight end Mark Bruener. But on second
and 3 from the Steeler 33, Bettis fumbled when Eaton forced the
ball loose and Milloy recovered at the 35.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, who didn't know how he reinjured his finger, now was
fitted with a longer splint, giving him more control of the ball.
He hit Glenn for a 9-yard gain, and one play later Derrick Cullors
hit the hole hard for a 6-yard gain for a first down at the 22. A
holding call on Wohlabaugh set the Patriots back 10 yards, but
Levon Kirkland interfered with Ben Coates near the sideline inside
the 5 and a flag was thrown. Edwards, who carried the ball 28 times
for 66 yards, then had his finest run of the day, being stopped
cold and then bouncing off Kirkland and Carnell Lake to get in the
end zone with 9:20 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers couldn't score, even with the help of a Bledsoe
interception by linebacker Earl Holmes at the Patriots' 22. They
got as close as the New England 9, but a breakup of a fourth-down
pass by Law ended that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very big,'' said Coates of the win. ``We just have to
take it and enjoy it and get ready for the Rams. We hold our own
destiny now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
