<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART LEARNS HARD LESSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Kordell Stewart sat alone for a long time Sunday
afternoon, stuffed deep into the darkness of his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback of the Pittsburgh Steelers leaned back into the
shadows of his locker to a place where it was quiet for the first
time all day and said nothing for a time. A long time.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally he would bite his lip or glance around a room
stuffed with players and sportswriters, but he addressed neither.
Instead he watched in silence, enjoying the brief absence of the
ugly cacophony that has surrounded him all season.
</P>
<P>
   For those few minutes, no one was cursing his name. No one was
screaming at him about his ineptitude. No one was throwing beer on
him. No one was saying anything to him, because what was there to
say after you have played badly and been treated worse by 58,000
people who call themselves your fans?
</P>
<P>
   Keep a stiff upper lip, mate?
</P>
<P>
   Fear not, pal?
</P>
<P>
   Et tu, Brute?
</P>
<P>
   What could anyone say to Kordell Stewart Sunday that would take
the sting away?
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour earlier, he had finished up a day in which he'd
thrown two killer inteceptions, been sacked three times, completed
less than 50 percent of his passes, ran for not a yard, and failed
to get his team a touchdown in a 23-9 loss to the Patriots on the
Steelers' home turf, turf that used to be friendly but this season
has turned unforgiving not to the Steelers' opponents but to
themselves, and most of all to a second-year starter who is
struggling the way second-year starters do at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   In his heart, Stewart understands what's happening at the
moment. He has a new offensive coordinator this year before he'd
even fully learned what the last one was trying to teach him. He
has an offensive line in front of him weakened by injury and
free-agent defections. Same is true of his receiving corps and his
running backs.
</P>
<P>
   So should it come as a shock that he is struggling to find
himself and in his struggles failing to produce the plays that
first won him the job, the same plays his team needs to keep itself
alive in the AFC playoff chase now?
</P>
<P>
   It must be to some, but not as surprising as it was to Stewart
to be walking off his home field Sunday and have someone throw a
cup of beer on him as if he was any enemy of the Roman government
leaving the Coliseum with the lions in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's agitating to walk off the field and have people throw
beer on you and call you things,'' Stewart said about Steeler fans'
reaction to their team slipping to 7-6 and all but eliminating
itself from the playoff race. ``I never have had that happen
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans are gonna be there when you do great and not when you
don't. We all know that. There's a lot of frustration right now,
and the only way I can handle it is to stay calm and not act out of
character. I have to wait to fight another day.''
</P>
<P>
   As the hour drew short Sunday in the fourth quarter, Stewart did
not seem to have much fight left in him after he threw an
interception that led to a Patriot field goal and fullback Jerome
Bettis followed six plays later with a fumble that led to a New
England touchdown that changed the game from a 13-9 nail-biter to a
23-9 beer-thrower.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Stewart started drives at the Patriot 22 and their
49 and failed to get his team another point, and each time the
crowd booed him incessantly when he went to the sideline. There he
stood alone, a baseball cap pulled down over his shaved head and no
one within 10 yards of him.
</P>
<P>
   This was Kordell Stewart's public pose as the game's final
minute wound down. A young man alone. Surely that is how a youthful
quarterback with little experience must feel. It was written on his
face. It was obvious as he sat naked but for two white ankle wraps
still taped to his legs for a long time in front of his locker,
speaking to no one and no one speaking to him.
</P>
<P>
   When he finally did emerge from that cocoon more than an hour
after the loss, the quarterback spoke quietly but from the heart.
His confusion at what has befallen a team he led to the AFC
Championship Game last year was clear. So, too, was the hurt he is
carrying with him because his own fans have turned on him, calling
for his benching on talk radio and pelting him with liquid
commentary as he simply tried to go home.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart spoke of something more than that, too. He spoke of
who he still believes he is regardless of how many critics now
curse his name in Pittsburgh. He spoke of who he is and who he
believes he still will be one day soon. Maybe not soon enough to
save the Steelers this season, but soon enough for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence is still there,'' Stewart said when asked if the
fact he'd thrown 11 touchdown passes and 13 interceptions this
season reflected a lessening in his belief in his arm's
trustworthiness. ``I feel I'm just as good as any quarterback in
this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a winner and you're used to success, it causes you
to wonder what's going on. To come so close and lose because you
didn't make plays is an emotional thing. But I understand the fans
are going to be the fans. They booed Neil O'Donnell, and he took us
to the Super Bowl. They probably helped run him out of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they're not going to run me out of here. They're going
to have to deal with me. I understand memories are real short. I'm
a young guy who is working hard with his teammates to get something
done, but I'm getting some knives thrown at the back of my head a
couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee you this: You put any of them in this position and
they are not going to get it done. That's why I'm here. I can get
it done. I will get it done.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as what the fans think, I don't care. You do (care),
but you don't, because if you think about it you'll go crazy. We're
not as bad as it seems. I assure you of that. I'm still the same
guy who took his team to the AFC Championship and came up 3 points
short. We just need to understand right now what we can do and what
we can't do with this offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what the Steelers did in the past. It doesn't
matter what the Steelers did in the '70s or last year. It's what we
can do today. I don't care about history. History can kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're not strong enough, so can your future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
