<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY FORGED BY SPEED OF GLENN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ He is not the fastest man in the NFL. At least not
officially. But it doesn't matter. Terry Glenn doesn't have to be
the swiftest man in his league. All he has to think about on Sunday
afternoons is this: Am I the fastest man in my stadium?
</P>
<P>
   Glenn stood in a Three Rivers Stadium mirror Sunday and asked
himself that question. The Patriots receiver is so fast that he was
gone before his reflection could stare back at him and give an
affirmative answer. OK, that's an exaggeration. But only by a
little bit. You want to check Glenn's speed credentials? Talk to
Chad Eaton. Talk to Shawn Jefferson. Check with Drew Bledsoe. And,
most important, chat with a man named Darren Perry. Glenn is so
fast that Steeler safety Perry still hasn't seen his face. All
Perry knows is that Glenn wears No. 88 and has his name on the back
of his white jersey, and that when you are 10 yards behind him on a
field, you probably aren't going to catch him.
</P>
<P>
   Perry was in that unwinnable position Sunday. In the second
quarter, Bledsoe noticed that Glenn was one-on-one with Perry. The
quarterback threw the ball from his 5, Glenn caught it at the New
England 45, and that was it. Perry was trailing, looking like a kid
wheezing and screaming, ``Wait up!'' to his big brother. But like
many big brothers, Glenn didn't wait. He just kept running. Fast.
So fast that he probably taunted Perry on his way to the end zone,
but it came so fast that Perry didn't hear him.
</P>
<P>
   Before the play, which would cover 86 yards, many people
wondered if Glenn's sore left hamstring was bothering him. But
there would be no pull-ups or limps on this run. Glenn ran toward
the end zone and slowed up, only to do an appropriately quick
dance. Fast guys can do that because the nearest defender is
usually 10 yards away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, did you see that?'' Bledsoe said after the Patriots' 23-9
win was secured. He went on to explain that he saw the Steelers
were blitzing on the play and that someone was going to be open.
``They blitz with the idea that I won't have enough time to find
someone,'' Bledsoe said. He first looked for Ben Coates, but the
tight end was covered. So he looked left to Glenn's side of the
field, threw toward him, and watched him sprint down the sideline.
By the time the day was over, Glenn had nine catches for a
team-record 193 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It might be a redundancy to mention that Glenn is far too fast
for lay people. You might already have told yourself: If Perry, a
professional football player, can't catch Glenn, how is some
slow-footed journalist going to catch up to him? If you had that
thought, congratulations. Glenn was so efficient with his movements
Sunday that many of the media types assembled here didn't even see
him. That's right. At least Perry was within 10 yards of him. But
after the game, Glenn apparently wasn't in the mood to talk. He was
able to shower, pick up his clothes, dress, and leap on the team
bus without being seen by many people. Then again, maybe he didn't
shower. And that's cool. Most pro athletes can definitely use some
soap, water, and, eventually, cologne after a game. Not Glenn. He
is so fast that he probably doesn't even sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton did see Glenn before the game. In fact, he was right next
to him. Their lockers were side by side Sunday. ``He's a great
neighbor,'' Eaton said. ``He doesn't say much. Just real focused.''
Eaton, a defensive lineman, says a lot. He is the same man who
swears he was abducted in 1984. He is the same man who swears he
was struck by lightning in May. So Eaton had to say something to
the Fastest Man In The Stadium. What was it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him to go out there and kick butt,'' Eaton said. ``I
told him that he could do great things with his speed.''
</P>
<P>
   And then what happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was like, `Yeah, whatever,''' Eaton said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   He probably said a lot more than that. But Eaton didn't hear it.
Remember: Terry Glenn is fast. Real fast. He walks fast and runs
even faster. He even looks fast. And you know what happens when
receivers have that track-star look about them? Cornerbacks react.
More specifically, cornerbacks back up. That's what the Steelers
did, often lining up 6 or 7 yards away from Glenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``That surprised me,'' Jefferson said. ``But maybe I shouldn't
be surprised. All of our receivers are fast.''
</P>
<P>
   This is true. Although Glenn may be the fastest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a difference when he's out there,'' Jefferson said.
``You can see it and so can everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Steelers, they won't have to see Glenn again
this year. What's so unfortunate about that is they won't see him
in the playoffs because, for the first time under coach Bill
Cowher, they probably won't be in the playoffs. The Patriots hope
they see Glenn for the rest of the season. And they want to see him
in his game gear, not the jeans, boots, and hooded sweatshirts they
have seen him wear on many Sundays while his teammates were in
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots need Glenn. They need him available for the final
three games of the season if they want to think about the playoffs.
He makes things easier for everyone. Even Robert Edwards was
claiming that Glenn helped the running game, which accumulated a
scant 73 yards. ``They don't put so many people (between the
tackles) when he is there,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   When he is there. That's the key phrase. When he is not, the New
England offense tends to sputter. Quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 0105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
