<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5893 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-CHIEFS-HN     12-07 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-CHIEFS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ For almost 54 minutes, the undefeated, untied Denver
Broncos were about to be undone by the Kansas City Chiefs in a
shocking upset that would have reverberated all the way to Miami
and New York.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Chiefs and beleaguered coach Marty
Schottenheimer, John Elway authored another unbelievable comeback
Sunday to secure the home-field advantage in the first round of the
playoffs for the third consecutive year.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's 24-yard pass to tight end Shannon Sharpe with 3:34
remaining was the decisive touchdown in the Broncos' 35-31 victory,
as they became the third 13-0 team in NFL history and tied a league
record with their 18th consecutive win.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably as fun a game as I've been involved in in a
long time,'' Elway said after throwing for 400 yards and two
touchdowns and engineering his 47th come-from-behind win, including
nine against Schottenheimer. ``It seemed like old times.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway's winning touchdown pass enabled the Broncos to overcome a
31-21 fourth-quarter deficit and remain unbeaten with games left
against the New York Giants, Miami and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the 1972 Dolphins, the only undefeated and untied
champions in NFL history, celebrate each season when the last
undefeated team is beaten. They will have to keep their champagne
on ice for at least another week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they never get to pop that champagne,'' said Elway, who
has thrown nine touchdown passes in his last three games.
</P>
<P>
   NFL and ABC executives in New York breathed a collective sigh of
relief because the Broncos remained unbeaten. They are hoping that
if Denver is 14-0 entering its Dec. 21 Monday-night game at Miami,
it could be watched by more television viewers than any
regular-season game in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This crown just keeps getting heavier and heavier,'' Broncos
defensive end Neil Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos flirted with disaster against the Chiefs, falling
behind by 14 in the first quarter and 10 in the fourth, thanks to
three touchdown passes by Kansas City quarterback Rich Gannon. In
between, they suffered two turnovers in the Chiefs' end zone _ an
Elway interception and a Terrell Davis fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of early and late adversity,'' Denver coach Mike
Shanahan said. ``They caught us off balance on both sides of the
ball, and we fell behind, but we kept our composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an opportunity to score almost every time we had the
ball, but bad things kept happening to us. We stuck together. John
made big plays down the stretch. The defense came up with some big
plays, and we were able to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The comeback began when Vaughn Hebron returned a kickoff 42
yards to Denver's 46. Before Elway trotted onto the field with 8:13
left, offensive coordinator Gary Kubiak told him, ``Boy, we haven't
been in one of these in a while, have we? Go get them.''
</P>
<P>
   On third-and-seven, Elway threw over the middle for wide
receiver Willie Green, who broke away from cornerback Dale Carter
for a 50-yard gain to the one. On the next play, Davis scored his
third touchdown. Jason Elam's extra point pulled the Broncos to
within 31-28 with 6:48 left.
</P>
<P>
   After the Chiefs went three-and-out on their next possession,
Darrien Gordon returned the punt 14 yards to midfield. Elway had
6:13 left.
</P>
<P>
   Davis carried for five yards and turned a short pass into a
12-yard gain for a first down at Kansas City's 33. Davis then
carried twice for nine yards. On third-and-one, Shanahan called a
timeout when he saw what kind of defense the Chiefs were using.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went into a short-yardage defense,'' Shanahan said.
``With third-and-inches, I thought we'd take a shot at the big
play, and if we didn't make it, we'd go for it on fourth down. If
we didn't make it on fourth-and-inches, we wouldn't have deserved
to win anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, who had been double-covered and shut out at that point,
got single coverage when the Chiefs blitzed the run. But Elway
faked to Davis and, with defensive tackle Chester McGlockton
closing in, threw a perfect pass to Sharpe, who beat strong safety
Reggie Tongue for the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Chiefs got the ball back at their 30 with 3:34 left. With
help from a 23-yard interference penalty on linebacker John Mobley,
Kansas City got a first down at the Denver 36.
</P>
<P>
   After Gannon threw three incompletions, the Broncos blitzed him
on fourth down. Safety Steve Atwater had a clear path to Gannon.
When Atwater leaped into the air, Gannon held the ball, and he was
sacked by defensive end Alfred Williams to seal the victory before
74,962.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not for Steve, I don't think I could have made that play,''
Williams said. ``If Steve hadn't jumped, I don't think I could have
gotten to him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams did get to Gannon, allowing the Broncos to win
their 16th consecutive home game, and their 23rd straight at home
in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when two streaks came to an end _ Davis had touched the
ball 836 times in the regular season before losing his
third-quarter fumble, and Jason Elam had a field goal blocked after
making 19 of 19 this season _ the Broncos had reason to be nervous.
</P>
<P>
   In their first 12 games, the Broncos allowed only 23 points in
the first quarter. They allowed 21 Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Gannon threw touchdown passes of 26 yards to Andre Rison and 11
to Kimble Anders, and Bam Morris scored on a one-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' one-yard touchdown and Elway's 13-yard pass to Ed
McCaffrey tied it 21-21 in the second quarter. Cornerback Mark
McMillian intercepted Elway in the end zone before the first half
ended.
</P>
<P>
   After Davis fumbled in the end zone in the third quarter,
Gannon's 26-yard touchdown pass to Joe Horn gave Kansas City a
28-21 lead. Pete Stoyanovich's 20-yard field goal made it 31-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time John has the ball in his hands, we have a chance to
win,'' said Broncos receiver Rod Smith, who had eight catches for
165 yards. ``When John got the ball on those last two touchdown
drives, he told us we were going to win, and we believed him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
