<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE SLOWS TO A DRIZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - After spending five days in balmy Tucson, the New
York Giants ventured into the great white north Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The visitors not only had to contend with the Cardinals, who are
trying to make the playoffs, but also the raw elements for which
the Giants appeared unprepared.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the poor New Yorkers _ they simply aren't accustomed
to our bitter winters _ huddled in blue parkas, wet and shivering,
their breath forming vapory plumes, the Cardinals took pity on the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   How else can you explain what the offense did?
</P>
<P>
   Or didn't do.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, the Cardinals had first and goal at the
Giants' 1-yard line and didn't score.
</P>
<P>
   With two minutes left and needing a touchdown and extra point to
win, the Cardinals lined up at the New York 7. Second and 4.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't score _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Jake Plummer threw two interceptions and had the ball stripped
from his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see, oh yes, Jake's best play, a 30-yard keeper to the
Giants' 3, was nullified by an offside penalty.
</P>
<P>
   After leading, 17-7, the Cards scored only two points in the
second half _ actually the Giants scored for them, on an
intentional safety.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Redbirds (6-7) lost for the second week in a
row. After the 23-19 defeat, several players dutifully recited the
company line, the one about controlling their own destiny. The
locker room message sounded every bit as positive as the bright
little sayings hidden inside Peking Noodle Co. fortune cookies
served in the Sun Devil Stadium press box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Luck Will Soon Be A High Point.''
</P>
<P>
   What luck?
</P>
<P>
   ``All Your Hard Work Will Soon Pay Off.''
</P>
<P>
   But will it?
</P>
<P>
   This is a young group unaccustomed to playing meaningful games
in December. The pressure is on. You wonder what this team is
``really'' thinking now.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals probably must win their last three games to make
the playoffs. But the defense is badly hobbled, and what are we to
make of an offense that stubbornly refused to open the door when
opportunity knocked?
</P>
<P>
   This game turned early in the second quarter after Plummer took
the offense to the Giants' 4 and the Cardinals settled for a field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   How confident is this team?
</P>
<P>
   Lomas Brown gave a quick glance around the inner sanctum of the
locker room and shook his head. ``Worried? Yes I'm worried,'' said
the 14-year veteran, who is unafraid to speak his mind. ``We need
to do some soul-searching. I don't know where everybody's mind is
at. But if we don't play better, we'll be watching the playoffs on
TV. We'll be saying `That could have been us. That should have been
us.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals saw more than their own breath Sunday. They saw
harsh reality. The offense remains a weekly question mark. As for
the battered defense . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't talk now,'' Andre Wadsworth said softly, asking
reporters for space with downcast eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive line can't afford to lose any more players. But
now Wadsworth is hurting. The rookie, who suffered a calf bruise,
pulled himself up from a stool and limped toward the training room.
He could barely walk.
</P>
<P>
   If every NFL club could play the Cardinals as well as the Giants
do, you could forget the playoffs right now. Jim Fassel is 4-0
against the team he once served as offensive coordinator. The
weather was different Sunday, but the result was the same.
Predictably, the Giants lined up in the second half and ran the
ball, exploiting the Cards' thinning defense.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Cards could have won. They ``would'' have won if the
offense hadn't come down with a bad case of bronchitis near the
goal line, coughing and sputtering to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   What does the future hold?
</P>
<P>
   I opened a cookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take That Chance You've Been Considering.''
</P>
<P>
   Run the reverse against the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   I opened another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your Winsome Smile Will Be Your Protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. That and some better blocking. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8636 or
david.casstevens(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
