<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-GIANTS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSEL-JINXED CARDS FADE TO BLACK, BLUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Jim Fassel, upon awakening Sunday, must have
taken a look outside and broken into a wide grin.
</P>
<P>
   He wouldn't even need his perceived magic this time. Fassel's
New York Giants had been given a Meadowlands kind of day in the
middle of the desert: A 41-degree, breezy, drizzly afternoon. Just
right, Fassel knew, for pounding the ball at a battered opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Three times since he left as Cardinals offensive coordinator
last year, Fassel and his Giants had manhandled the Cardinals.
Sunday's 23-19 pounding extended the reign of terror.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had talked about the mastery, how this was the
kind of thing a playoff-caliber team does something about. Yet the
Giants ran for an even 200 yards, 118 of them in the second half
after overcoming a 10-point deficit and entering into a game of
keep-away. The Cardinals' defense, fresh off offering non-stop
service to Washington and Kansas City, couldn't stop Gary Brown
(124 yards, 5.0-yard average) or Charles Way (60 yards, 4.6
average).
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' offense, which led the NFL in red-zone scoring,
produced three points on three trips inside the Giants' 10-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   It was a battle that left the Cardinals with as many emotional
scars as physical, a thrashing that left them drained and angry.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the reality of it is that it took them out of nothing _
except, perhaps, the services of several defensive starters.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 6-7, the Cardinals remain in the driver's seat for the
final NFC wild-card playoff berth. They visit Philadelphia on
Sunday, then come home to finish the season against New Orleans and
San Diego. If they win all three, they are in. If they win even two
of the three, as long as one of them is New Orleans, they're likely
in.
</P>
<P>
   That was of little consolation after being shredded in another
Fassel Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't control our destiny the way we played,'' Cardinals
offensive tackle Lomas Brown said. ``To me, it doesn't make sense
to say we control our destiny if that's the best we're going to
play. That team sure does have a stranglehold on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' defense already was nicked. Defensive tackle Eric
Swann is scheduled to have his seventh knee operation today. Middle
linebacker Ron McKinnon is probably out again this week because of
a strained knee. Cornerback Tom Knight has another strained
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined on the injury list by end Simeon Rice (bruised
ribs), who is out three to five days; tackle Mark Smith (sprained
ankle), out of the Philadelphia game; and end Andre Wadsworth (calf
bruise), out four or five days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they would try to pound us,'' Cardinals linebacker
Jamir Miller said. ``When it's rainy, wet and slippery, that helps
a team run the ball. Getting guys hurt didn't help us. Teams attack
your weaknesses.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter who suits up defensively next Sunday, the Eagles
seemingly are a group that Jake Plummer could outscore _ if only
Plummer doesn't play as he did against the Giants with three killer
turnovers. During one stretch, he threw 11 successive passes that
were not caught by a Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   That was after Plummer drove the Cardinals to a 17-7 lead with
scores on three consecutive first-half possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 21 seconds before halftime, Plummer served up an
interception that the Giants (5-8) converted into a field goal _
crucial points that later allowed the Giants to take a safety
rather than risk a blocked punt deep in their territory.
</P>
<P>
   In the third quarter, Plummer dropped back to pass and had the
ball stripped by reserve defensive end Cedric Jones. That led to a
touchdown that put the Giants ahead, 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after the Cardinals turned a first and goal at the 1 into
third and goal at the 4, Plummer was intercepted in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   In a game he needed to take over, Plummer completed 18 of 40
passes for 263 yards, one touchdown and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take a lot of the blame for this loss,'' Plummer said. ``If
we control the ball, we win. I gave them an early Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Plummer seemed to atone when he ran 30 yards to the Giants' 3
with 5:18 to go and the Cardinals seven points from regaining the
lead. But the gain was called back because wide receiver Ronnie
Anderson was ruled offside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie said he asked the official before the snap to give him
a thumbs up or thumbs down on where he was lined up, and he didn't
give him anything,'' Plummer said. ``That's the ref's job.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very odd, but it's the Cardinals. Oddities are part of
our game, I guess.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
