<HEADLINE>
AFTER BUILDING LEAD, COYOTES HAVE TO SETTLE FOR A TIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ The Coyotes have been talking
lately about how badly they need to learn how to put teams away.
Jump on them early, smell the blood, and then go for the kill.
</P>
<P>
   They've been finding ways to win without doing that, as their
franchise-record start has shown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' center Jeremy Roenick said, ``but we'd find it a lot
easier if was 6-0 or 6-1 at the end of two (periods). We can't
afford to keep making it close.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what happened Sunday night against the
Vancouver Canucks, who have been without three of their best
players, including All-Star holdout Pavel Bure. It was so close,
that it ended in a 3-3 tie before 14,490 at General Motors Place.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Chris McAllister scored his first NHL goal with 11:07
left in regulation to force the overtime after the Coyotes had
taken a 3-2 lead in the second period on the second of Roenick's
two goals, his seventh and eighth of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (15-3-3), who outshot the Canucks, 46-24, had a
golden opportunity to ice it in the final minute of regulation but
they couldn't score on a power play awarded at the 19:04 mark when
Brad May was called for holding.
</P>
<P>
   Canucks goalie Garth Snow stopped 43 shots in a show-stopping
performance, while Coyotes goalie Jimmy Waite remained undefeated
with a 5-0-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is, but a lot of times it's like we play
down the team's level we're playing,'' Roenick said. ``It's very
upsetting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes were seething with 7:25 left in the first period
after Markus Naslund had given the Canucks a 2-1 lead with his 13th
goal, his sixth in seven games and his fourth in the past two.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes thought they had tied it when, in a reversal of
recent trends regarding deflections in traffic, Keith Tkachuk sent
a hard slapshot through a crowd and Teppo Numminen tipped it in.
Referee Paul Devorski, however, thought Numminen was in the crease
and he went upstairs to video replay judge Malcom Ashford.
</P>
<P>
   Replays shown to the fans appeared inconclusive at best, but the
goal, which actually looked to go in off the skate of Vancouver's
Bill Muckalt, was disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   `My take on that is that our player was pushed into the
crease,'' Schoenfeld said. ``When I look at it again (on videotape)
I will maintain that same opion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it was a wild one tonight, but Vancouver
dominated us for the first seven minutes or so until we got our
game . . . but both team should be happy with getting the point.
We'll settle for .500 (1-1-1) on this trip and go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the Coyotes' fortunes started to turn shortly after
the controversial ruling. Up to that point, the Canucks clearly had
dominated the game. Phoenix scored first on a deflection by Dallas
Drake on a Numminen shot at 5:16, but that was the only shot the
Coyotes could muster against Snow in the first 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   `It's the same old story,'' Numminen said. ` It took us 10
minutes tonight before we got our legs going.''
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver, meanwhile, blistered Waite with all kinds of heat.
Bruiser Donald Brashear made it pay off first, reaching deep to put
back a rebound with a backhander 23 seconds after Drake's fifth
goal. With Roenick in the box for roughing, Naslund made it 2-1 on
the power play at 9:41.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing, 10-2, in shots, the Coyotes went on the attack with
the aid of three power plays. They wound tying it on a
man-advantage goal by Roenick with 21 seconds left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, who set up Roenick's first goal, set up his second as
well early in the second as Phoenix retook the lead, 3-2. Roenick
held the puck patiently along the boards before stepping up into
the left faceoff circle and drilling a slap shot that Snow couldn't
handle.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was painful for the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Center Juhe Ylonen got hit in the face with a puck, but returned
after receiving 10 stitches in the cheek. Roenick dove to block a
slap shot from Adrian Aucoin and the blast nailed his right foot.
After several tense moments lying on the ice and then leaving the
bench for treatment, he also returned.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes got a legitimate scare late in regulation, though,
when defenseman Gerald Diduck was checked hard into the back boards
behind the Phoenix net. It appeared as though he took most of the
impact with his head, and he left the game for observation. The
team said he suffered a bruised thigh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
