<HEADLINE>
POPOV IS ONLY FOE HALL CARES ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In a swift turnaround,  &UR; Gary Hall Jr. is on a roll. He
beat swimming's international governing body, FINA, in a Phoenix
court last week. Two days later, he beat one of the year's fastest
fields in the pool at the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   He's been beating everybody but  &UR; Alexander Popov.
</P>
<P>
   It's Popov, the angry Russian, who still stands between Hall and
vindication. Blame Hall for that.
</P>
<P>
   The off-beat, entertaining Hall has set himself up for an
inevitable confrontation that promises to define him. It figures to
come at the 2000 Olympics. For Hall, there will be victories along
the way. But, somehow, they'll loom as a prelude to the Sydney
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Fair or not, Hall's battles with coaches about his work ethic
and his fight with FINA over an off-and-on suspension for a
positive marijuana test created enemies. Popov is one of them.
There's also a perception that Hall is a rebel without a coach or a
clue.
</P>
<P>
   He's an intriguing athlete, who is saddled with a public
portrayal that often misses the mark. In front of the cameras, he
becomes a showoff who angers some people. It's an act. Nonetheless,
it has contributed, indeed confirmed, his decision to go it alone.
</P>
<P>
   Six months of trouble, lousy publicity and lost endorsements
seem to have toughened him. He says he's motivated by anger.
</P>
<P>
   Adversity might prove to be an ally, one of his few friends.
Above all, it seems to be forcing maturity onto a 24-year-old
Phoenix sprinter who two years ago was seen as a goofy kid with
four Olympic medals.
</P>
<P>
   Only an adult will beat the tough-minded Popov, who won two gold
medals in closely contested races with Hall in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: There will be more adversity.
</P>
<P>
   Hall has appealed the methods of FINA's testing and suspension
to the Swiss-based international Court of Arbitration for Sport,
which is expected to hear his case within four months.
</P>
<P>
   A restraining order that expires this week allowed him to
compete last week. He still has 12 days to serve of a suspension
that was imposed on June 15, lifted for weeks and reimposed.
</P>
<P>
   There are questions about how FINA will apply the remainder.
Will it suspend him for his next competition? Or will it let the
suspension expire out of competition? The issue probably could pass
quietly. But Hall won't let it, which only ensures further trouble
from FINA.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, U.S. Swimming will give Hall a chance to make the
team for the Pan-Pacific Games in Sydney, a key Olympic
steppingstone in August. He was unable to compete for a spot last
summer because of his suspension. If he's fast enough at the next
U.S. Nationals, he'll be added. But somebody figures to lose a spot
if Hall is as fast as expected en route to the only confrontation
that matters:
</P>
<P>
   Popov. &QL; 
Briefly. . .  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Popov: Hall's father, three-time Olympian  &UR; Gary Hall Sr.,
said he's still trying to put together a match race between his son
and the Russian at Phoenix Swim Club. But Popov wants at least
$50,000. He trains in Australia at the Aussies' expense, $250,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   USA Boxing sought and got support from Pakistan's  &UR; Anwar
 &UR; Chowdry, chief of the International Amateur Federation, for a
political post won by an American. It was Chowdry who loudly
defended the judges who robbed
 &UR; Roy Jones Jr. of a gold medal in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Bugs and drugs: A bug patrol at the Asian Games in Hong Kong is
busy keeping insects out of the pool. Dead bugs have littered the
surface. Wasn't the ingestion of bugs supposed to be a herbal
secret to China's success in running and swimming? Maybe the patrol
also is collecting the performance-enhancing species. &QL; 
Information form other media sources is included. Norm Frauenheim
can be reached at 602-444-8259 or norm.frauenheim(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
