<HEADLINE>
ANGER REMAINS TOWARD REFEREES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ They sneaked out of town with a
precious two points, but the Coyotes were still livid at the way
Saturday night's 3-2 victory in Calgary went down. The target of
their ire: referees  &UR; Mark Faucette and  &UR; Dave Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Neither called a penalty on  &UR; Jason Wiemer after the Canucks
center flew through the crease and knocked Coyotes goalie  &UR; Nikolai
Khabibulin to the ice. Calgary's  &UR; Jarome Iginla scored on the play
to pull within a goal with three minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a B.S. goal,'' complained Khabibulin, who was elbowed
by Wiemer and lost his balance. ``Referees should be more watchful
for that kind of thing. It should have been a penalty, and they
could have called just about anything on that play, from roughing,
to goalie interference, to elbowing. Why they decided to call
nothing, I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes defenseman  &UR; Keith Carney, who helped bail out the team
down the stretch with numerous defensive stops, has his own theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the refs wanted to make it interesting, who knows?''
Carney said. ``All I know is that was goaltender interference.
They're supposed to be trying to protect the goalies, so why let
someone take a run at him?'' &QL; 
Adams A-OK &QL; 
After going the first 14 games of the season without a goal,
veteran left wing  &UR; Greg Adams, a free-agent pickup from the Dallas
Stars, was starting to worry about his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come to a new team, it's hard to know what to expect
or what they expect from you,'' Adams said. ``But obviously, I've
scored goals in the past and I expected to contribute in that area
and also be reliable at the other end of the ice, too. I thought I
was playing well, but nothing was going in for me.''
</P>
<P>
   They have been lately. Pulling into Vancouver, where he spent
eight seasons, Adams had scored five goals in his past six games.
Almost every one of them has come at key moments, which has made
ending the slump even more enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' he said. ``I was getting lots of chances
earlier, but I didn't feel I was contributing in the way I was
supposed to. The team was still winning, but you want to
contribute. You want to be part of the team, especially being a new
figure on the team.'' &QL; 
Winning the draw &QL; 
Since being moved to center on an almost exclusive basis,
second-year pro &UR; Juha Ylonen is taking faceoffs for the first time.
And lately, he has been racking up the wins. Saturday night in
Calgary, he took 19 draws and won 13 of them (68 percent).
</P>
<P>
   ``Some games, that's the way it goes,'' the 26-year-old from
Helsinki, Finland, said. ``You win everything. Another game comes
along and you can't win anything. But this has been fun. It don't
think I really took any faceoffs last year.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is he implying? That Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld made a
mistake by not using him in the circle earlier?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, maybe,'' Ylonen said with a laugh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
