r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONA-BOWL-AZR &LR;      12-07 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-BOWL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOT AT HUSKERS IS UA'S CONSOLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona's disappointment at missing out on a Rose Bowl berth was
tempered Sunday by the prospect of playing traditional power
Nebraska in the Dec. 30 Holiday Bowl in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, all our fans, players and staff are very
disappointed that we didn't get to go to the Rose Bowl because we
felt we were very deserving,'' Arizona Coach Dick Tomey said. ``But
we understood that we didn't control our own destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want the best things to happen to us, we have to control
our own destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's hopes for its first Rose Bowl trip came apart with
UCLA's 49-45 loss on Saturday to Miami. That knocked the Bruins out
of the Fiesta Bowl and into the Rose as Pac-10 champions. The
championship was won by virtue of a 52-28 victory over UA on Oct.
10.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise Sunday was that the Holiday picked Nebraska
as UA's opponent instead of Kansas State, which lost to Texas A&AMP;M
on Saturday and fell from contention for a shot at the national
title in the Fiesta Bowl all the way to San Antonio's Alamo Bowl
against unranked Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   If the Holiday had selected once-beaten Kansas State, the bowl
would match the two highest-ranked teams not invited to a BCS game.
Kansas State is No. 3 in the BCS rankings and No. 4 in the
Associated Press poll. Arizona is No. 7 in the BCS and No. 5 in the
AP poll. Nebraska is 11th in the BCS rankings and No. 14 in the AP
poll.
</P>
<P>
   The bowl selections apparently outraged Kansas State. The school
canceled a scheduled news conference and said Coach Bill Snyder
would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, Kansas State experienced the biggest drop,'' Tomey
said. ``I really sympathize with Bill Snyder and his team.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential ticket sales were a key factor in the Holiday
decision. According to bowl President Weldon Donaldson, 10,000
tickets were sold in the two weeks since Nebraska was mentioned as
a likely team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the best match-up in our history,'' said
Donaldson of a game that is already assured of a record crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bowl officials said they are within 4,000 tickets of a sellout
at 70,500-seat Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Kansas State, Arizona's prospects were somewhat
predictable, despite speculative reports about interest from the
Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ended up where we knew we'd wind up if UCLA didn't win,''
said Tomey, who went on to express enthusiasm for the chance to
play the Cornhuskers, who shared last year's national title but
slipped to a disappointing 9-3 record this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get a chance to test ourselves against one of the most
prominent programs in the nation,'' Tomey said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomey said he spoke with many of his players after UCLA's loss
Saturday. He said it was tough for them to suddenly have a Rose
Bowl chance snatched away.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Keith Smith was with teammates at offensive lineman
Yusuf Scott's house to watch the UCLA game. Their reactions were
shown live by ESPN during the UCLA telecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bad, man,'' Smith said. ``I felt like they were doing
it on purpose just to keep us out of the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wanted to go to the Rose Bowl, but you can't let it
get you down because we still had a great season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we're 9-3 or something. We're 11-1, and we're
ranked pretty high. We were hoping we would get into one of those
BCS bowls.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
