A5929 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-PLAYOFFS-AZ     12-07 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-PLAYOFFS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S DOWN TO 3 GAME SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin simplified the NFL's
complicated playoff system for his confused team.
</P>
<P>
   He told his players after Sunday's 23-19 loss to the New York
Giants that if they win their final three games, they will get an
NFC wild-card playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically a three-game season,'' wide receiver Rob Moore
said. ``Nothing else matters. We need to win all three games. Going
9-7 will get us in.''
</P>
<P>
   It shouldn't have been this hard.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals were in great shape two games ago when they won at
Washington to improve their record to 6-5. But they lost at Kansas
City, 34-24, eight days ago and blew a 17-7 lead Sunday to fall to
6-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one hurts because we really needed this game,'' offensive
tackle Lomas Brown said. ``For us to lose this game (at home) is
inexcusable. . . . For us to have so much at stake at this point of
the season, and to go out and play the way we did, is
discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   The only points the Cardinals scored in the second half came in
the final 20 seconds when the Giants took an intentional safety.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they allowed the Giants to rush for 118 yards in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are looking behind to make sure that no one is going
to catch us in the playoff race,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals don't have to look far to find the New Orleans
Saints, who also are 6-7 after upsetting the Dallas Cowboys, 22-3,
on Sunday at the New Orleans Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   If the season were to end today, the Cardinals would be in the
playoffs over the Saints because of a better record in NFC games _
6-4 to New Orleans' 5-5. But the two teams play at Sun Devil
Stadium on Dec. 20, and the first tiebreaker is head-to-head
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints have a much tougher remaining schedule. They play
host to NFC West rival Atlanta (11-2) next week and finish the
season at home against Buffalo (8-5). Their remaining opponents are
a combined 25-14.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' remaining foes are just the opposite, 14-25. They
return to action next week at Philadelphia (3-10) and finish at
home against San Diego (5-8).
</P>
<P>
   Others still in the picture for the third wild-card spot are
Tampa, 5-7 going into tonight's game against Green Bay; and Detroit
and the Giants, both of whom are 5-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can look at it as a three-game season,''
tight end Chris Gedney said. ``We should start with the Eagles and
consider that a one-game season. If we win, we have another
one-game season the next week.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible the Cardinals could win just two of their final
three games and make the playoffs, but they aren't even considering
the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a silver lining in that we still control our own
destiny,'' defensive back J.J. McCleskey said. ``But there has been
a silver lining the last two weeks, and we've not done anything to
help ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you want to barely make the playoffs when you can do
something and really earn your way in?''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Jamir Miller said the players have to ``look inside
themselves'' if they want to become the first Cardinals team since
1982 to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a chance to do something special,'' Miller said.
``Do we want to fight, or do we want to lay down?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
