<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURIES TAKE TOLL ON CARDS' DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. -  &UR; Rashod Swinger was the only member of the
Cardinals' starting defensive line still standing at the end of
Sunday's 23-19 loss to the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle  &UR; Mark Smith was out because of a severely
sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive ends  &UR; Simeon Rice (bruised ribs) and  &UR; Andre Wadsworth
(right calf contusion) joined Smith on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were at the point of having to put (linebacker)  &UR; Patrick
Sapp in at defensive end in our standard defense,'' defensive
coordinator  &UR; Dave McGinnis said.
</P>
<P>
   Sapp already was in the lineup because of outside
linebacker &UR; Tony McCombs' sore toe.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals dressed only six defensive linemen and entered the
game without three other defensive starters _ tackle  &UR; Eric Swann
(knee), middle linebacker  &UR; Ronald McKinnon (knee) and cornerback
 &UR; Tommy Knight (hamstring).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a battered and bruised defensive football team,'' Coach
 &UR; Vince Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is the most serious of the newly injured. He will be out
seven to 10 days, meaning he is expected to miss next Sunday's game
at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, the team's first-round draft choice, also could be
out for that game. He is expected to miss four to five days of
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Rice will be out three to five days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, rookie running back  &UR; Michael Pittman suffered a
fractured hand that likely will end his season. He will be
re-evaluated today. &QL; 
Move backfires
</P>
<P>
   If the Cardinals had played conservatively and ended the half by
running the ball, they would have taken a 17-7 lead into
intermission.
</P>
<P>
   But after  &UR; Adrian Murrell's 28-yard run gave them a first down
on the Cardinals' 33 with 34 seconds left, they tried to score more
points, and it backfired.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback  &UR; Jake Plummer was intercepted by rookie safety
 &UR; Sherman Williams at the Giants' 49, setting up  &UR; Brad Daluiso's
51-yard field goal on the final play of the first half, cutting the
lead to 17-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interception down there was huge,'' Giants Coach  &UR; Jim
Fassel said. ``It could have made the difference coming down to the
wire. We might not have been able to take the safety.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants took an intentional safety with 17 seconds left to
keep the Cardinals from getting good field position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have been punting that ball in a different
situation,'' Fassel said. ``I wouldn't have been able to (take the
safety) if it's a three-point ball game at that time.'' &QL; 
Streak continues
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, the ex-Cardinals offensive coordinator, extended his
record to 4-0 against his former boss, Tobin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I knew what it was, I'd like to put it in a bottle and
carry it with me next week,'' he said of his success against the
Cardinals. &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   The 41 degrees at kickoff was the coldest ever for a Cardinals
game at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie cornerback &UR; Corey Chavous has interceptions in each of his
first two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Plummer missed 11 consecutive throws during a stretch in the
second and third quarters. &QL; 
Republic writer Bob Young contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
