<HEADLINE>
GRAHAM'S SILENT REVENGE: GIANTS' RUNNING GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Kent Graham was too busy playing football Sunday
to get a glimpse of the derisive banner a couple of Cardinals fans
were parading around Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Graham, you still suck,'' it read.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't miss the same message when it was profanely
delivered by some vocal Cardinals supporters who waited for Graham
at the tunnel leaving the field.
</P>
<P>
   Graham just grinned as he trotted up the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Why not? His New York Giants had just beaten the Cardinals,
23-19, damaging Arizona's chances for a wild-card playoff berth.
And inside, at least, he had to be chuckling at the knuckleheads
who cheered the last time he played at Sun Devil Stadium _ in a
Cardinals uniform _ when he went down because of an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Graham didn't so much beat the Cardinals as not beat
the Giants. He completed only 8 of 23 passes for 144 yards and a
touchdown. He was intercepted twice, and 87 of his passing yards
came on a single play, in which Graham simply tossed a screen pass
to Tiki Barber. The Cardinals were caught in a blitz, and Barber
went the distance.
</P>
<P>
   It was New York's running game, which methodically pummeled the
Cardinals' injury-decimated defense for 200 yards, that beat
Arizona on a cold, wet, New Jersey-gray day. Tailback Gary Brown
ran for 124 yards on 25 carries. Bullish fullback Charles Way
carried 13 times _ usually with a couple of Cardinals aboard _ for
60 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   So dominating was New York's running game that the Giants,
facing a first and 20 after a penalty, rushed three consecutive
times and got the first down during a fourth-quarter drive that led
to Brad Daluiso's 45-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Graham admitted it was a satisfying day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big time,'' he said. ``As far as coming back and winning a
year later, it's a great feeling. Especially the way we did it. It
was a tough game, a real tough game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being as wet as it was, it was tough to throw. But we still
came through with a win and hung in and fought, even when we were
down early.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham very nearly blew it when he tried to force a pass over
Arizona's J.J. McCleskey, who intercepted at the Giants' 40 with
7:33 to play. But New York's defense held on fourth and 3 from the
6 with 1:54 remaining to preserve it.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Giants Coach Jim Fassel didn't immediately
endorse Graham as next week's starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Kent wanted to play real well,'' Fassel said. ``I know
it was important to him. I think he probably tried to make some
plays, and early on, it was wet and sloppy. Things weren't
clicking, so I tried to get into the run game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice way of saying Graham didn't screw it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a good job of moving the ball and keeping it away from
their offense,'' Graham said. ``That was kind of the strategy going
into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Graham wanted to say anything to those fans who ripped
him, he resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say anything, because we're just happy to come
away with a win,'' he said. ``It was a bit ironic. I try not to
worry about the fans out there who weren't in support of me. I
expected that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad for the Cardinals in a sense _ for Jake (Plummer).
I know what it's like to throw for a lot of yards and then you lose
the game. I'm happy to be on the other side of it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
