<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS ADD INSULT TO CARDS' INJURIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Sure, they control their own destiny. But who are
``the''y? Who will be left now that Mark Smith is on crutches,
Andre Wadsworth has a problem with his right calf and Simeon Rice
can't find the strength to blow his nose?
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the boys from New York have sucker-punched the
optimism. Knocked the wind out of the Cardinals, and maybe for
good.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, the Cardinals are crying foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were cheap shots on me all game,'' Jamir Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way they play, man,'' Smith said. ``They've
been doing that the last couple of years we've been playing them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the warrior's code of professional football, there is nothing
so repulsive, nothing so damning.
</P>
<P>
   In the infirmary that served as a locker room, the Cardinals
were sickened by the loss, infuriated by the losses. Smith will be
out seven to 10 days. Rice and Wadsworth are questionable and could
miss a must-win game against the Saints two weeks down the road.
</P>
<P>
   The damage was severe, just like the accusations. That the
Giants played nasty and the Giants played dirty, a team that may
have prevailed in the murky shadows of fair play.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the matter is Giants tackle Roman Oben. In the
third quarter, Smith engaged with the Giants' Greg Bishop. The two
formed a human teepee, and in the space between their legs, Oben
saw an opportunity. He dived at Smith's legs, and 10 minutes later,
Smith left on a cart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had broken it,'' Smith said of his sprained ankle.
``I felt it crack. I heard it crack when I went down. But the
X-rays didn't show it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless there are further complications, Smith was lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see the cart, you think something is broken,''
personnel boss Bob Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, Oben claimed that Smith wasn't engaged on the play. And
maybe in the letter of the law, Oben's block was technically legal.
But it was definitely cheap. And ethically wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't right to go after a guy deliberately like that,''
Miller said. ``That's flagrant. I was telling them that all day
long. And when Mark went down, I told them that they were
bleep-bleep-bleep. Bad words, bad words, bad words.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Giants' locker room, Oben was asked about his motive,
one that seemed highly questionable on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were they showing it a lot?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it a slip block,'' Oben said. ``I was supposed to roll
and cut him. I guess his foot got caught in the turf. I was on the
field talking to him. It wasn't intentional.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked what Oben had to say, Smith glared ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't say (expletive),'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Cardinals, it wasn't an isolated incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw (Giants center) Lance Scott throw a cheap shot early in
the game on Andre Wadsworth,'' said one Cardinal executive. ``And I
mean cheap. C-H-E-A-P. I just talked to Andre, and he agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL police would be wise to examine this film. If the
Cardinals are right, they need to penalize the suspects. If the
Cardinals are wrong, they need to clear the air. Before this feud
gets out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there is no love lost between these two football
teams,'' cornerback Corey Chavous said. ``So whatever happened, I'm
not surprised. What we have to do is respond. Chop them back.
That's the key.''
</P>
<P>
   As night fell on a gruesome afternoon, Smith hobbled out of the
locker room, unable to put pressure on one foot. Rice grunted and
groaned, straining to breathe through bruised ribs. Wadsworth had
limped off the field and was holed up in the training room.
</P>
<P>
   And you had to wonder: Has the sun finally set on a once
promising season?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not slipping away, we can't even think that way,'' Miller
said. ``If we win out, then we get the spot. But that's the thing.
We have to win out. We can't have any more slips.''
</P>
<P>
   Right. With a potential front line of Cousins, Simpson, Swinger
and Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a battered and bruised defensive football team,'' Coach
Vince Tobin said. ``No question about that.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 0147EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
