<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAN IMPE ON A POWER PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He is not as flashy as Sergei Samsonov, not as highly
touted as Joe Thornton, and not as big as Hal Gill. But 25-year-old
Darren Van Impe has carved out a niche for himself and become a
valuable member of the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   The young defenseman arrived in Boston a year ago, Nov. 26,
claimed on waivers from Anaheim. Originally earmarked for
Providence, Van Impe got a long, hard look look from Bruins coach
Pat Burns and assistants Jacques Laperriere and Bob Francis, and
wound up sticking. Although he had been evaluated by the Ducks as
expendable, the Bruins had themselves a diamond in the rough.
</P>
<P>
   Though tentative at times when the club was auditioning him as a
second point man to complement Ray Bourque on the power play, Van
Impe has come a long way in a season. This year, he's been a
power-play staple. After missing two games because of a coach's
decision and two games because of injury, Van Impe has come into
his own. In his first 19 games, he had 11 points, three of them
power-play goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess when I came here I was just trying to show the coaches
I could play and just go from there,'' said Van Impe. ``I had a
strong playoffs last year and I was just hoping I could carry it
over to this year and have a better season than last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Like in many other pro sports, confidence plays perhaps the
biggest role short of pure talent. Last season, Van Impe seemed
reluctant to pull the trigger at times and was eager to surrender
the puck to his teammates. This year, he's playing with more
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a chance to play on the power play regularly and
I've gotten a few points, and that's helped,'' said Van Impe.
``When things are bouncing your way, obviously you get more
confidence, and that's been the situation for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Point-gathering has never been a problem for Van Impe. In 63
games with Baltimore of the AHL in 1995-96, he had 58 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always played it in juniors and in the minors,'' he said
of his special-teams role. ``I was known as a power-play guy. When
you come up to the NHL, obviously it's tougher. I've tried to
adjust to that and show I can play. But guys are smarter and you
don't have as much time and they play their positions so well. In
the lower leagues, you can find a way around that. The key is to
just move the puck around, keeping your head up and seeing who is
open, and not just try to throw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Impe sees his role in Boston as miles ahead of where he was
previously in his professional career. ``My first year I was a
rookie so at times I didn't get the opportunity,'' he said. ``Here
they've been showing some more confidence in me and I've tried to
feed off that and just do my best. They're giving me the chance,
and I'm trying to take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Impe said he was never even aware that when the Bruins
picked him up off waivers, they fully intended to use him to
improve their fortunes in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here, I met (Burns) and he told me it was a great
bunch of guys and I'd like them,'' he said. ``I never knew there
was an issue of going to Providence. I was trying to show them I
could play and I think I was kind of an eye-opener for them because
they kept me around the whole year.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Impe said in addition to his newfound confidence, other
factors have contributed to his success. One is being around
players such as Bourque, a future Hall of Famer, and the other is
working with Laperriere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bourque is just the power-play man,'' said Van Impe, grinning.
``He's been around a long time. Just being out there with him, he
teaches me to be more patient and relax and play. He's really good
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lappy has changed my game around defensively. He's great. He
worked hard with me last year and showed me some things I didn't
even know I was doing wrong, in situations down low, playing the
man. Like containing and when I was in front of the net, not being
too close to the goalie when the puck is behind the net. He keeps
pumping it into your head until eventually it just sinks in and
becomes a natural thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As Van Impe progresses and becomes a better-known quantity, he
said he always knew that all he needed was a chance to prove what
he could do. ``I knew I could play this way,'' he said, ``but
getting the opportunity to play and them putting me in those
situations just builds my confidence even more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
