<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-FIESTA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE END, FIESTA MATCH-UP IS NO-BRAINER  
 AFTER UPSETS, TEN NESSEE, FLORIDA ST. ARE TOP CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - In the end, it was not decided by decimal points,
quartile rankings or adjusted deviations.
</P>
<P>
   No one involved in college football needed a complicated formula
to tell them that Tennessee and Florida State should meet in the
Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4 at Sun Devil Stadium, with the winner all but
assured of becoming the consensus national champion.
</P>
<P>
   Fiesta Bowl officials could not have hoped for more. Entering
Saturday's games, there were three undefeated teams at the top of
the polls. If all had won, the chances of a split national
championship would have grown, as would have the sweat stains under
the arms of those yellow coats the Fiesta Bowl folks wear.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks to losses by No. 2 Kansas State and No. 3 UCLA,
Florida State jumped two spots in both the Associated Press and
coaches polls, as well as in the Bowl Championship Series
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Florida State's dim chance of a national
championship became a brilliant opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   No one at the Fiesta Bowl was complaining about the weekend's
course of events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence usually takes pretty good care of the old Fiesta
Bowl,'' said John Junker, the bowl's executive director.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the only one thanking a higher power for an exciting
Saturday afternoon of college football.
</P>
<P>
   While parked on a couch in his home, Florida State Coach Bobby
Bowden watched Miami upset UCLA and then Kansas State fall to Texas
A&AMP;M in the Big 12 Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   No one is shocked that No. 1-ranked Tennessee (12-0) won
Saturday and is playing in the game. But few people thought Florida
State (11-1) had a chance after Kansas State, Tennessee and UCLA
entered the final weekend undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   This was not lost on Bowden, whose team was upset early in the
season by North Carolina State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a situation where Tennessee came through the
front door,'' he said. ``We kind of feel like we came through the
back door. But now we're going to face off in the middle of the
room and it's going to be a heck of a shootout.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee was the unanimous No. 1 choice in the both the AP and
coaches final regular-season polls, and Florida State was No. 2 in
each poll by a comfortable margin.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, there will be those looking in who can't help think
they deserve a shot at the title.
</P>
<P>
   Third-ranked Ohio State has lost just once, but will settle for
playing Texas A&AMP;M in the Sugar Bowl. Kansas State's loss Saturday
proved costly, as the Wildcats dropped out of the four BCS bowls
all the way to the Alamo Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The school canceled a scheduled news conference, and Coach Bill
Snyder declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Other teams with one loss, including Arizona and Wisconsin,
could argue that they are as worthy as Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to be in the Sugar Bowl, but I think we can make
an argument that we're one of the top two,'' Ohio State Coach John
Cooper said. ``We were Number 1 for nine straight weeks. You stub
your toe one time, you've got to be a great team to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The BCS formula was created to determine the country's top
teams, which are guaranteed of playing in the national championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   The formula has four components: average ranking of the two
polls, the average of three computer rankings, schedule strength
and record.
</P>
<P>
   The Seminoles were a strong No. 2 team in the BCS standings,
partially because their schedule was rated the fourth strongest in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the Fiesta's fourth national championship game. Its
last title game was in 1996, when Nebraska beat Florida, 62-24.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State last won the national title in the 1993 season,
while Tennessee's only national championship came in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The Volunteers have danced on the edge of making it to a
national title game over the past few years and have finished in
the top 10 of the AP poll for four consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   With the departure of quarterback Peyton Manning to the NFL, the
Volunteers were not a preseason favorite to win the national title.
</P>
<P>
   But they've beaten Florida, won at Georgia, survived against
Arkansas and avoided being upset Saturday, which the other two top
teams couldn't do.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't do that by accident,'' Coach Phillip Fulmer said.
``We have been a resilient team all season, and we've found a way
to get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
