<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-STEELERS-COWHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWHER, STEELERS RUNNING ON FUMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Bill Cowher was fuming, expressing an emotion that
seems close to his heart much of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher had grown weary of watching his team trot in and out of
the huddle in lackluster fashion Sunday even though it was fitting
because that's the way the offense was playing.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, frustration and bitter anger in his voice, Cowher
called his offense together on the sideline and exhorted it. Later,
Steelers wide receiver Charles Johnson said, ``Bill wanted us to
come into and out of the huddle with tempo. But it's hard to get
tempo when it's always third down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was third down 13 times for the Steelers in 61 plays Sunday,
roughly 25 percent of the time. Of those plays, only four times did
Cowher's offense convert. The rest of the time, instead of going to
the huddle they went to the sideline, which is where they'll be
headed soon if they don't find some way to win their remaining
three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed in how we played,'' Cowher said after
losing to the Patriots, 23-9, at Three Rivers Stadium. ``Now we're
going to find out a lot about ourselves and this whole football
team. I'm not in position right now to make any assessments, but I
was not very pleased with our performance today.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point you have to make a play, and we have not done
that. I don't know if it's us putting players in the position to
make plays or us just not making them.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, Cowher knows he has little time to solve the
problem if the Steelers are to reach the playoffs again. In their
last 14 games since a big win over the Kansas City Chiefs a year
ago, Pittsburgh is 7-7. Since a big win over the division-leading
Jaguars this year, they've lost two straight and Sunday looked like
a rudderless ship offensively.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers couldn't score a touchdown. They couldn't convert
turnovers into points. They couldn't throw the ball much or run it
at all. They couldn't do anything, including win at home, and that
may have been the most disturbing thing of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we don't lose at home and we did today,''
Johnson said. ``That's not Pittsburgh.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately it has been, however, and Cowher knows it. Whether he has
a solution that can change that he has no idea, but there is no
denying that at 7-6 with three games to go and trailing the Jaguars
by a three-game margin in the AFC Central, the divisional title is
gone. All that's left is a wild run for an unlikely wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think 10 wins has a chance to get you in the playoffs,''
Cowher said. ``We're not mathematically eliminated. Mathematics
says we have very little margin for error, though. None.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathematics also says the Steelers' bread-and-butter _ their
inside power running game _ has deserted them. Sunday, the Steelers
rushed only 13 times, so although they averaged 4.2 yards a carry,
fullback Jerome Bettis was all but abandoned in large part because
the Patriots put seven and eight men in the box near the line of
scrimmage and challenged Kordell Stewart to throw.
</P>
<P>
   He did. He just didn't throw very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't get it done offensively,'' Bettis said. ``We went
down a couple of times and we couldn't move the football (in the
red zone). That created problems for us because we were unable to
score touchdowns. Later we made some mistakes _ an interception, I
fumbled the ball _ and when you do that against a playoff-quality
team you don't give yourself a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Steelers, Sunday's performance may have done worse than
that. It may have prevented them from making the playoffs for the
first time since 1991, the last season before Cowher took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's looking real shady,'' Steeler tackle Jermaine Stephens
said. ``If there's a chance, we're definitely going to have to win
out the rest of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
