u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-     12-07 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOORE, PATRIOTS DEFENSE FLYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ When it was over, and Patriots found Steelers and
Steelers found Patriots at midfield for postgame socializing,
Pittsburgh cornerback Carnell Lake gave a bear hug to New England
cornerback Ty Law at the 35-yard line and Lake said to Law, ``You
deserved it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's was the Patriots' best defensive game since New England
last played Pittsburgh, in the playoffs 11 months ago, and it came
at no bigger time and with no bigger physical crisis, merely the
latest, to hit the Patriots: the loss of middle linebacker Ted
Johnson with a torn biceps on the second play of the game, when
Johnson was tackling Jerome Bettis. Johnson, though, seemed hardly
missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that it's over, I guess it was a big loss,'' said
linebacker Tedy Bruschi in words that would be echoed by Patriot
defender after Patriot defender. ``But during the game it didn't
look like we lost much of anything the way Marty (Moore) was
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, the last player taken in the NFL draft five years ago,
Mr. Irrelevant himself, was immense as Johnson's replacement.
``We're proud of Marty,'' said coach Pete Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did was go back and look at the film of the last time
we played the Steelers,'' said safety Lawyer Milloy. ``And what we
saw in that playoff game last year was that we were flying around
the ball, something we hadn't been doing this year. And we saw that
we were putting a lot of pressure on Kordell Stewart (the Steelers'
befuddled QB), and we did that this time.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Stewart, after a decent start, was so out of
sync and inept in the late moments that the few thousand remaining
fans in Three Rivers Stadium booed him relentlessly and one fan
dumped a cup of beer on him as he left the field after firing one
last pass that was picked off by cornerback Steve Israel. Stewart
was 21 of 45 for 206 yards and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   That other interception was by Ty Law (his eighth of the
season), late in the third quarter. And with 2:48 left in the game,
and New England on shaky Astroturf despite a 23-9 lead, Law made a
great play to break up a pass to Hines Ward in the end zone. It was
great because Patriot QB Drew Bledsoe had just thrown an ugly
interception and Pittsburgh had more than enough time to catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to perform good in front of the home crowd,''
said Law, who grew up in nearby Aliquippa, Pa. ``I haven't picked
off Kordell since we've been playing together, and, you know, I
finally get one back from the Hail Mary (a Stewart pass to Michael
Westbrook over Law that gave Colorado a last-second win over
Michigan in 1994). This'll never replace that, but I'm just glad to
get the interception in front of the hometown folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Law, Israel, Milloy, and the rest of the beleaguered New England
secondary also made a huge improvement in what had been its
Achilles' heel all season: giving up first downs on
third-and-longs. The Steelers were only 4 of 13 on third-down
plays, much more like the Patriot defense that throttled Pittsburgh
in its 7-6 playoff loss to the Steelers here last season. Nonstop
pressure on Stewart, just as last season, was the key.
</P>
<P>
   But another key was the play of Chad Eaton, who just may be the
most improved defensive lineman in the NFL. For the second straight
week, Eaton led the team in tackles (eight), a statistic usually
reserved for linebackers. Eaton also had three sacks of the usually
unsackable Stewart and also put a hit on Jerome Bettis early in the
fourth quarter that caused (a) Bettis to fumble and (b) Steelers
coach Bill Cowher to gather his offense around him on the sideline
for a fiery tongue-lashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to do with Bettis what we always do,'' said Eaton of
the Pittsburgh back who was held to a puny 48 yards on 12 carries.
``And that's to get everybody around the ball when he has it. I got
lucky ... I just got him with the helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Eaton couldn't be modest about his sacks of Stewart, one
when he caught the speedy QB from behind, a play seldom seen. As
usual, the cheery Eaton had a unique take on the sack from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amazing,'' said Eaton. ``And I kind of let Kordell know about
it, too. I said to him, `Did you just let me catch you?' And, `Did
I just catch you from behind?'''
</P>
<P>
   And did Stewart say anything back?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I think Kordell was looking over to Bill, and Bill was
just giving him that chin.''
</P>
<P>
   Key plays by the defense were many, and perhaps few were any
bigger than when Willie Clay banged into Steeler receiver Hines
Ward on Pittsburgh's first possession of the second half, knocking
the ball loose and saving a TD.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
