</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS PASSER, STEWART FAILS TO MAKE GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Patriots have Kordell Stewart's number, and Sunday they once
again exposed him as not being a prime-time NFL passer.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was inept through the air, and because he could not do
anything against the Patriots' pass defense, his team had no
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The way to beat the Patriots is to score points on them with the
pass. They play the run well, but against the pass they give up
more first downs than almost any team in the league. New England
has trouble rushing the quarterback, but when the passer can't make
plays via the air, as Stewart demonstrated once again Sunday, there
is less need for pressure.
</P>
<P>
   In 3 1/2 games against the Patriots, here are Stewart's passing
numbers:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Att. &LR;   &UR;  &LR;   &UR; Com. &LR;   &UR; Yds. &LR;   &UR;  &LR;   &UR; TD &LR;   &UR; Int &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 0 0 0 0 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   48 26 266 1 2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   31 14 134 0 1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   45 21 206 0 2 &QL; 
 &UR; Totals  &LR;   &UR; 134 &LR;   &UR; 61 &LR;   &UR;  &LR;   &UR; 606 &LR;   &UR; 1 &LR;   &UR; 5 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In those games, dating back to the playoff game two years ago in
Foxborough (when he debuted with that 0-for-10 beauty), note the
one touchdown vs. five interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   And this all has happened while the Patriots have been geared up
to stop Jerome ``The Bus'' Bettis. When Stewart has had success
throwing, it has come when Bettis is having a big game on the
ground and the opposition has to commit more players to stopping
him.
</P>
<P>
   Bettis has not been able to run against the Patriots the way he
does against the rest of the league. The Bus has had a flat tire
against the local lads, gaining only 235 yards in his last four
games against New England, on 78 carries, with no touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers had beaten the Patriots two games in a row before
Sunday because their defense did a good job against the Patriots'
offense, pressuring Drew Bledsoe. Sunday, especially in the first
half, Bledsoe could have eaten a sandwich before he let the ball
go.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Terry Glenn, Ben Coates, and Shawn Jefferson were
able to make big plays in the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's defense lives by the zone blitz. Sunday, it was
ineffective. The zone blitz is predicated on the idea that the rush
is going to make the passer throw the ball prematurely. At the same
time, the defensive backs are supposed to run with the recievers
off the snap, so the quarterback will get hit before a man gets
open.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' offensive line did a great job of protecting
Bledsoe. The three interceptions he threw were his fault, not the
line's, although he was bothered by his broken finger during the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots still could not run the ball. But their attack was
wide open through the air. The Steelers produced no pressure, and
defensive backs afraid of Glenn and Jefferson deep gave ground
consistently when the Steelers executed a zone blitz, playing zone
instead of man-to-man on those occasions.
</P>
<P>
   On their first drive of the day, the key play was a 43-yard pass
to Glenn, when the Steelers blitzed and were blocked, leaving
Bledsoe a world of time and Glenn a ticket to get open.
</P>
<P>
   They went up, 6-0, because of the same situation with Jefferson.
The Steelers blitzed. Bledsoe got time, and the defender backed far
away from Jefferson, who gained 25 yards on a hook to set up
another field goal by Adam Vinatieri.
</P>
<P>
   However, the play of the day was the 86-yard pass from Bledsoe
to Glenn. Again the Steelers came with a blitz, and again Bledsoe
had forever. Glenn ran from the Patriots 14 to the 45 while Bledsoe
unloaded. No one on the Steelers can match Glenn's speed, certainly
not safety Darren Perry, and Glenn got 5 yards behind him to make
the easy catch and score.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Stewart was struggling. Aside from not being an
accurate passer, he always looks at the reciever he is going to
throw to all the way down the field. Twice, Willie Clay took
advantage of this to make great plays. On those occasions, Stewart
tried to hit receivers running down the seams of the zone and over
the goal line, when Clay, reading Stewart's eyes, made great reads
and moved over to knock away two potential touchdown passes. Each
time the reciever was open, but Stewart gave his target away
prematurely and threw late, allowing Clay time to react.
</P>
<P>
   The only time in the game Stewart had success was in the second
period, when he completed several stop passes in a row for short
gains. Outside of that, he could do no damage. It is difficult in
the NFL to throw 45 passes and have just 206 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers are not the Steelers of the past, way back or
recently. When they've had good teams, they have been able to run
the ball and rush the passer. This year they can do neither.
</P>
<P>
   Their offensive line is beat up and cannot get the job done.
Defensively, they cannot bring the heat the way they have in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   This week they were a great matchup for the Patriots, who are
weak defending the pass and got a weak passer, and stout throwing
the ball against a team that can't rush the passer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
