<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BLEDSOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE PUTS FINGER ON PROBLEM, ADJUSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ For the first half, Drew Bledsoe seldom had been
better, torching the Pittsburgh defense with 239 yards of passing,
including an exquisite sighting of Terry Glenn at the last possible
instant and a perfect pass from the Patriots 5-yard line to their
45.
</P>
<P>
   So exquisite that Glenn could dance away from safety Darren
Perry for an 86-yard touchdown. And, for the first six plays of the
third quarter, it was more of the same, Bledsoe finding Glenn three
more times with perfect passes and Robert Edwards for a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   New England had a first-and-5 at the Steelers 42, leading, 13-6.
All seemed well.
</P>
<P>
   But only Bledsoe knew that his broken right index finger was
hurting, even more than playing an NFL game with a broken finger on
his passing hand should hurt, ``and all I know is I didn't hit it
on anybody,'' he said. ``I don't know ... I don't know for sure
what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever had happened was not good. On that first-and-5, Bledsoe
dropped back and could no longer even grasp the ball. It slipped
out of his fingers, and he had to fall on it for a 13-yard loss.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was what Bledsoe would call ``that fiasco of the
third quarter.'' First the ball sailed on him on a short pass to
Glenn, and then, on third and 18, with Glenn open deep, Bledsoe
scrambled and fired a pass that was picked off by Chris Oldham.
Fiasco, indeed. The Steelers were ready to be picked apart even
more by Bledsoe, but the quarterback's passes were wandering and
wayward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was before that that my finger was already hurting,'' said
Bledsoe. ``That's why the ball slipped out of my hands and why the
passes were sailing. That last joint on my index finger wasn't
quite working the way it was supposed to be working.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical staff worked on Bledsoe's finger on the sideline. It
was clear to Bledsoe that his short cast, which left the tip and
top joint of his finger exposed, had to be altered. The decision
was to go to a longer cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put a splint on it, a longer splint, to hold it in
position and to cover that (top) joint,'' said Bledsoe. ``And that
helped me keep my hand on the ball a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem was not worked out immediately, as the
``fiasco'' continued on the next drive. With help from referee Dick
Hantak's flag-happy crew (it averages 20.1 penalties a game, the
most of any in the NFL), the Patriots steadily moved backward.
</P>
<P>
   New England started with a first-and-10 at its 19 because of a
penalty on the kickoff, and it degenerated into a fourth-and-27
from the 2. The Patriots were in control, but it seemed about to
unravel because Bledsoe's passes were sailing or bouncing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a broken finger,'' said Bledsoe, matter-of-factly. ``The
feeling wasn't the same (on his passes). It's a broken finger, and
it's not as accurate as it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, Bledsoe threw on the sideline, seeking to regain
the feel, the touch, with his finger. Finally, with the longer
splint in place, Bledsoe trotted back onto the field with the ball
again deep in his territory, on the Patriots 8, after the defense
had pitched a most timely three-and-out at the Pittsburgh offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know anything about it,'' said tackle Bruce
Armstrong. ``Drew didn't say anything in the huddle to us about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe felt better, thinking ``that with longer splint on
it, I should be able to get the job done. We played around and
tried some different stuff on the finger and eventually came up
with something that allowed me to get the ball out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Which he did. A 20-yard right-on-the-money pass to Ben Coates
quieted the Steelers fans and brought the ball out to the New
England 29. Two more passes, one to Coates and one to Glenn,
covered 25 more yards. The Patriots did not score on that drive,
but the offense did relieve much of the pressure on the team. And,
on the next two drives, the Patriots did score, first a field goal
and then a TD one play after Bledsoe threw a perfect 32-yard pass
to the left flat to Coates, who was interfered with on the play.
Edwards banged it in on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew had some problems with his finger, you could tell,'' said
coach Pete Carroll. ``The ball started flying on him and he had a
hard time controlling it. But the doctors made an adjustment on the
brace, which I think helped, and Drew came back and played well.''
</P>
<P>
   And, once again, courageously. As Armstrong put it, ``This team
is used to key guys getting hurt and coming back to make plays.''
The result was a win in Pittsburgh, a convincing win in Pittsburgh,
a win in Pittsburgh that was one of the Patriots' most significant
in the regular season for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's healing, and that's the most important part of
it,'' said Bledsoe, when asked if Sunday represented a setback
regarding his finger. ``I'm not doing any more damage to it by
playing, and all the evidence so far is that it is healing while
I'm playing. So hopefully in the next couple of weeks it will have
healed enough so that I don't have to wear the splint on it and
I'll be back to normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe did throw a horrendous interception late in the fourth
quarter, one that brought instant recall of Kevin Henry to all
Patriot fans, but New England's defense saved the Patriots from
deja vu of one year ago in Foxborough against the Steelers. And,
when it was all done, Bledsoe was most pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a particularly clean game for me _ I threw them
three balls, and I missed some easy throws,'' said Bledsoe. ``But
to come in here and get a victory feels very good and very
satisfying, especially with the history I've had here. It feels
good to leave this place with a victory rather than walk out of
here with your head down.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no equal of Bledsoe's miracle finishes of the last two
weeks, but his return to the field Sunday in the third quarter just
may be a metaphor for these battered and bruised Patriots.
Character abounds on this team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
