<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDWARDS SETTLES SCORE WITH TOUCHDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ They talked trash to the rookie all day. They said
things to him that we cannot repeat here. Robert Edwards touched
the ball 28 times Sunday, and on 27 occasions he heard some foul
words from the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the game,'' Edwards said with a shrug, ``I guess they
were trying to distract me. They should know I don't get distracted
that easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Steelers didn't see the Patriot running back's tattoo.
It is a Bible verse, seared into his left biceps. The verse, from
the book of Philippians, alludes to all things being possible
through a higher power. Edwards lives by those words when he goes
to work. So that might explain why one of his carries exemplified
the trend of the day: Edwards was the one making noise and the
Steelers were walking away, either muttering to themselves or
simply saying nothing.
</P>
<P>
   How did that happen? A touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards scored on a 4-yard run in the fourth quarter. It not
only ended the Patriots' scoring for the day, it ended a pleasant
70-degree day for many western Pennsylvanians. After the score,
thousands of people picked up their things and headed for the
inevitable traffic wars. That made the score 23-9, which is how the
game ended.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Edwards did not try to pretend he had a great day. It
was tough running for most of the afternoon. Those 28 carries
produced only 66 yards, an average of 2.4. The Steeler linebackers
are not the fastest Edwards has seen all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Miami twice,'' the rookie reminded everyone. But you
don't always have to be fast to stop the run. You just have to be
able to anticipate what's going to happen. The Steelers did that
about 26 times. They didn't do so well on a 17-yard Edwards run in
the first quarter. And they didn't know what to do with that
touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I haven't been in the end zone for a while,'' Edwards
said, ``but I haven't had that many opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Edwards had twice as many opportunities as Pittsburgh's
Jerome Bettis. A 250-pound runner nicknamed The Bus, Bettis rushed
for 48 yards. Many people would argue that if you had to choose
between runners, you'd take Bettis over Edwards every time. But on
a key fourth-quarter play Bettis, carrying the ball at his team's
34-yard line, fumbled and lost the ball to Lawyer Milloy. The
Patriots simply took the ball and finished off a four-play drive
with Edwards's touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   You should have seen the Pittsburgh sideline after the fumble
and, eventually, touchdown. Bettis shook his head on the way to the
bench. Bill Cowher, the coach who usually cajoles and cheers along
the field, stood with hands on hips with nothing to say. The game
was over.
</P>
<P>
   When the analysis began in the Patriots locker room, Shawn
Jefferson was saying that the offense needs to find a way to score
when it is only 20 yards from the end zone. ``If I had to look at
one thing we struggled with, that's it,'' Jefferson said. They
didn't struggle with it all day. Edwards didn't get many yards, but
he did find the end zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 0210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BOWLCHAMPIONSHIPS     12-07 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOWL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIESTA FOR VOLS, SEMINOLES 
</HEADLINE>
 CHAMPIONSHIP SERIES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ After a rash of upsets Saturday jumbled rankings and
crushed hopes of major bowl berths, undefeated seasons, and
national championships, college football restored order with
Sunday's release of the final Bowl Championship Series rankings.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, No. 1 and unbeaten Tennessee and No. 2 and
once-beaten Florida State will meet in the Fiesta Bowl in Tempe,
Ariz., Jan. 4, to decide at least part of the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   In the other BCS bowl pairings announced Sunday, Texas A&AMP;M, a
double-overtime upset winner over Kansas State in the Big 12
championship game, will meet once-beaten and Big Ten co-champion
Ohio State in the Sugar Bowl Jan. 1; Big East champion Syracuse
will meet Florida in the Orange Bowl Jan. 2; and Big Ten
co-champion Wisconsin will meet Pac-10 champion UCLA in the Rose
Bowl Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Fiesta Bowl will be declared the national
champion in the USA Today-ESPN coaches' poll, while the Associated
Press media poll will wait until after the game to vote on its
champion.
</P>
<P>
   And while the winner of the Fiesta Bowl is a heavy favorite to
be crowned national champion, there still could be controversy if
No. 3 Ohio State beats Texas A&AMP;M by a wide margin and Florida State
wins a lackluster defensive battle against Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, which became the first team this season to receive
all 70 first-place votes in the AP poll, can head off any
controversy by beating the Seminoles. That would give the
Volunteers their first national title since 1951.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS situation cleared up significantly after Saturday's
games, in which Kansas State and UCLA, which lost to Miami, were
knocked from the ranks of the unbeaten. That left it obvious who
was No. 1, but it opened a new debate: Who's No. 2?
</P>
<P>
   UCLA and Kansas State paid heavily for their losses, although
Kansas State suffered the biggest drop, falling all the way out of
the $12 million BCS bowl pool into the $1 million Alamo Bowl in San
Antonio, against Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, which lost a 49-45 shootout to Miami in the Orange Bowl,
received a nice consolation prize by landing in the Rose Bowl slot
traditionally reserved for the Pac-10 champion.
</P>
<P>
   If there were controversies in the aftermath of the upsets, they
were the elevation of Florida State into the Fiesta at the expense
of Ohio State; the exclusion of Kansas State; and the inclusion of
twice-beaten Florida, which didn't even win its division in the
SEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Florida State and Tennessee were the two best teams,''
said BCS chairman Roy Kramer, pointing to computer printouts that
ranked both of those teams far ahead of Kansas State, Ohio State,
and the rest of the field.
</P>
<P>
   Kramer was less specific about why Florida made it, especially
since it finished five spots behind Kansas State in the final BCS
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the BCS was to match the two best teams in the
country,'' he said. ``From there on down, there was a lot of
freedom for the bowls to do what they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Orange Bowl wanted was to choose Florida, which has not
played in the bowl since 1967, as an opponent for Syracuse, which
had three losses during the regular season but automatically earned
a BCS berth as the Big East champion.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators should bring plenty of fans to South Florida. Kansas
State has a similiar reputation of fan support, but Orange Bowl
officials may have doubted how much support would be left following
a loss of such magnitude to Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, who will take his team to its
third national title game in six seasons, and Tennessee coach Phil
Fulmer were delighted.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said his respect for Tennessee is genuine. ``They have
the symptoms of a national championship team,'' he said, meaning
the Vols possess quick defensive players who have made big plays
when needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things worked out for us,'' said Bowden. ``We're lucky, and
yet there are several other teams that deserve to be in there as
much as we do.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be repercussions. I've never been a
proponent of a playoff. I've always said I like the system. If they
voted us in, good. If they don't, we'll live with it. But I'm
getting to where I think we probably ought to be have a four-team
playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer is just happy to be heading west. ``We were a team that
did the job when it had to be done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A playoff system can wait. For now, the system in place will
feature at least one of the two best teams in its title game,
perhaps both.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
