<HEADLINE>
WHIPPLE HAS UMASS EXPECTING VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ The University of Massachusetts football team
is divided into two groups: those whose memories of last season
have gathered dust because of the success of this year, and those
who have enjoyed this season on its own merits because at this time
last year they knew virtually nothing about the program.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is first-year coach Mark Whipple. No one needed to
tell him how awful the Minutemen were in 1997; he was less than two
hours south, coaching at his alma mater, Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Whipple was hired at UMass last December, he
encountered several people who were more than anxious to inform him
of what he was getting into.
</P>
<P>
   ``People came to me so many times during the first few weeks,
saying, `You're going to be fine, but it's going to take about
three years,''' said Whipple, who guided the Minutemen to their
first 10-win season with a 27-21 win over Lehigh Saturday in the
second round of the Division 1-AA playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Minutemen (10-3) will visit Northwestern State (11-2) of
Natchitoches, La., Saturday at 3 p.m., in the second national
semifinal game in school history. Saturday's home playoff win was
the first for UMass in school history.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to compare what UMass has done this season _
rebounding from a 2-9 campaign last year _ to any other college
football program's resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the fact that the roster pretty much stayed intact
from last year. Whipple merely added a few talented players at the
skilled positions such as quarterback Todd Bankhead from a
California junior college and wide receiver Jimmy Moore from
Southern Methodist, as well as several excellent freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would say to me that we don't have very good players
here, but they knew I would get them, and they knocked how the
recruiting had been poor the last few years,'' Whipple said. ``But
I never bought that. I'm not going to live long enough to wait
three years to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to wait. The blend of exceptional newcomers who
didn't know about last year's demise and talented returnees bent on
doing something about it has served the Minutemen well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back at last year, I don't know what went on,'' said
Bankhead, who earlier this season said he had heard only about the
UMass basketball program while in California. ``But I know that the
guys that were on this team before could play and still can play. I
haven't seen any film of what happened last year, but we just have
all the confidence in the world that we can win.''
</P>
<P>
   It showed Saturday. Against previously unbeaten Lehigh, the
Minutemen rebounded from several miscues to take a 13-point
fourth-quarter lead and held on after the Mountain Hawks cut the
lead to 6 with 7:11 left.
</P>
<P>
   The UMass defense, as it had in several games down the stretch,
secured the victory by stopping Lehigh once it drove to the 9-yard
line with 2:01 remaining. ``UMass did a great job defensively,''
said Lehigh coach Kevin Higgins. ``We had a chance to gain
momentum, and that is a big part of any team's success and
confidence. Unfortunately, we didn't give ourselves enough
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The result set off a celebration not seen at McGuirk Stadium in
years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the last time UMass's players were involved in such a
frenzy was last season, when a Boston University team still reeling
from the school's decision to cancel football routed the Minutemen,
33-8, in BU's final home game, and Terrier players and fans
attacked the goal posts as UMass players left the field stunned and
dejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans, coaches, and teams are finally getting back
something for all the hard work we've put into this,'' said senior
linebacker Khari Samuel. ``This is my fourth and a half year here
and this is the best fun I've been having. I'm happy we have
another week to look forward to.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern State is the regular-season champion of the
Southland Conference. UMass beat Southland member McNeese State of
Lake Charles, La., 29-21, in the first round. Northwestern State
rallied from a 10-7 fourth-quarter deficit to defeat visiting
McNeese State, 14-10, in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been there, and I don't think we'll lack for
confidence,'' said Whipple about the return trip to Louisiana.
``It's going to be a tough, tough game. I think they realize how
tough it was after being down at McNeese. I think we will be better
prepared for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
