<HEADLINE>
CRUSADERS HOLD HOME GROUND 
</HEADLINE>
 CROSS-SETON HALL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WORCESTER, Mass. _ The Holy Cross women's basketball team has
been a rather polite host of the ECAC Women's Holiday Festival the
last couple of seasons, losing the championship game of its own
tournament in its own arena. Maryland took the crown last season
and Providence won it the year before.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, playing in its third consecutive ECAC tournament
finals at the Hart Center, Holy Cross held off Seton Hall, 71-65,
before 456 fans to capture its first victory this season against a
Big East team. The Crusaders had lost to Boston College (65-59) and
were pounded, 107-56, by UConn, the No. 1 team in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even with four players scoring in double figures, led by
tournament Most Valuable Player Amy O'Brien's 21 points, Holy Cross
still had to hold off a late Pirates push. Seton Hall pulled to
within 5 with 35 seconds left but would come no closer.
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross (5-3) also received double-digit scoring performances
from Anna Kinne (17 points) as well as Summer Ivan and Lara
Marcsisin (13 each). Freshman forward Starr Fuller of Burke High
scored 22 for Seton Hall (3-5).
</P>
<P>
   Neither team shot especially well _ Holy Cross at 39.1 percent
and Seton Hall at 40.6 percent _ but the Holy Cross defense,
employing a full-court press throughout, caused 22 turnovers, 13 in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Number one, after we got beat by UConn, there was some talk
that Holy Cross might be all done, that we aren't as good as usual,
but we've come back with three quality wins'' (Fordham, Rider, and
Seton Hall),'' said Holy Cross coach Bill Gibbons, whose teams won
three of the last four Patriot League titles, including last
season's. ``A third time is a charm to winning this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross's defense, mixing man-to-man and zone coverages, was
impressive. ``Our half-court defense was excellent,'' Gibbons said.
``We found a way to win, with the key being our starting five, the
way they played to decide the second half. Usually I substitute
more, but they were playing so well I had to play them those last
eight or nine minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross held only a 1-point lead, 34-33, early in the second
half, but then the Crusaders made five of six field goals to go up,
47-37, on an O'Brien layup with 15 minutes left. ``We had turnovers
and we've been doing that for six games,'' said Seton Hall coach
Phyllis Mangina. ``We seem to relax on defense and give up some
easy shots and get ourselves in a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Holy Cross braced for a Seton Hall comeback, similar to the one
the Pirates used in beating George Mason (77-73), despite building
a 23-point lead. ``But we made our free throws (seven of last nine
in the last 2:56),'' O'Brien said. ``That's the type (of) team that
can hurt you when you let your guard down. We knew they'd make a
run at us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
