<SLUG> BC-BKL-BLIZZARD-QUEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUEST PULL ONE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD _ The coach of the Columbus Quest resigned two weeks
ago. Three of the team's starters were out with knee injuries.
Another three missed the team flight here Saturday night and showed
up less than an hour before game time.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that mattered Sunday, as the Quest pulled out a
65-61 win over the New England Blizzard at the Civic Center before
8,112.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a third-quarter run by the Blizzard in which they surged
to a 47-43 lead, the Quest showed why they're the two-time
defending ABL champions and now are sporting an 8-2 record. Guard
Shannon Johnson poured in a game-high 20 points (including four
3-pointers), followed by player/coach Tonya Edwards (12) and Lisa
Harrison (10).
</P>
<P>
   Center Kara Wolters scored a team-high 16 points, but it wasn't
enough to get the Blizzard out of the hole they dug in the first
half. Both the 5 points in the second quarter and the 17 points in
the first half were franchise lows for the team in its third
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half, I think we were in awe of the ABL
champions, and one of the things you saw was our standing around on
offense and not having the discipline to go through plays,'' said
coach K.C. Jones. ``We made some adjustments the second half and
came out with much more determination and came back with the
offense and were moving. But they're the champions, they came right
back on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolters, who scored all of her points and grabbed all of her
game-high nine rebounds during the second half, said her team
scored too little too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``(They) play hard and have a great defense; you have to really
work a whole game (to beat them),'' she said. ``But a game is a
first and second half, and unfortunately we only played hard the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Blizzard went into the locker room at intermission,
they took a 12-point deficit with them. Nothing had seemed to go
right in the second quarter, as they were 2 for 8 from the floor
and committed seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Wolters said the mood at halftime was ```Come on guys, let's
go.' We knew we didn't have the fire that we needed. It was just a
pride thing, we don't want to keep losing.'' But the Blizzard fell
to 2-7.
</P>
<P>
   They did come out blazing in the first 1:43 of third quarter.
Suddenly it was the Quest who seemed out of synch as the Blizzard
went on a 5-0 run _ or as many points as they scored in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   As the theme from ``Rocky'' played, the crowd roared and the
Blizzard took a 41-40 lead with two minutes to go. Wolters grabbed
a rebound and made a layup with 1 second left, giving the Blizzard
a 47-43 lead at the end of three. They had outscored the Quest,
18-5, in the last five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the heroics would not last another quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Quest regrouped and tied it at 49. After that they never
looked back. Despite letting the Blizzard get within 2 points,
Columbus sealed the win with two free throws by Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the Quest might be hurting _ Edwards is the interim
player/coach since Brian Agler left to go the WNBA. Beverly
Williams, Valerie Still, and Katie Smith are all nursing ACL
injuries. But none of that mattered Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Edwards scored 28 points to lead the Philadelphia Rage to
an 85-68 victory over the host Seattle Reign.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Chasity Melvin added 21 points for the Rage.
</P>
<P>
   Niesa Johnson led Seattle with 18 points while Shalonda Ennis
had 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
