<SLUG> BC-BOX-PAGE-LOPEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAGE SHOWS GREAT SKILL, COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY _ Johnny Tapia's attempt to win the bantamweight
title was supposed to be the main event on Don King's homecoming
card Saturday night in Atlantic City, but after James Page and Jose
Luis Lopez were finished punching each other in the head,
everything else was a preliminary.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 rounds, Page defended the World Boxing Association title
he won two months ago in Paris with courage and skill. When he
relied on the skill he dominated Lopez, who is the kind of guy who
apologizes if you don't hit him flush.
</P>
<P>
   But when courage was required it was needed in handfuls, because
on those occasions when Lopez chose to be a pitcher instead of a
catcher he did great damage to the champion. Twice Lopez dropped
him, although one was suspect and appeared to be a slip, and four
other times Page went down on slips that were partly the result of
Lopez's wily trainer, Lou Duva, loading his fighter's trunks with
water each round.
</P>
<P>
   That kept up a constant spatter on the Budweiser logo in the
center of the ring, and because Page was a mover while Lopez was a
stalker, it was the champion who often found himself slipping to
the floor. Most of the time, Lopez had nothing to do with that, but
on several occasions he nearly bombed Page out with the kind of
fearsome right hands that have made Lopez one of the most feared
welterweights in the world despite the fact he entered the bout
with three losses and two draws and left with another of the former
after dropping a 12-round decision even he did not dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good fight, but Page deserved to win,'' Lopez
(42-4-2) said. ``I'll fight anybody. But tonight I was just a bit
off.''
</P>
<P>
   If he was, it was a good thing because just as he had done to
defrocked WBA champion Ike Quartey (who was stripped of the title
Page later won not long after fighting Lopez to a draw) Lopez twice
dropped the champion and on at least three occasions seemed to have
him out on his feet but never was able to finish him off.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Page refused to fall, but then again so did
Lopez, despite being strafed round after round with some nasty
combinations that would have sent lesser men to the emergency room,
let alone the canvas. But Lopez always has been as hard-headed
about being knocked backward as a cement pillar, and Saturday night
was no different. Although he might be willing to lose, he never
was willing to back up to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt how strong he was when I hit him,'' Page (23-3) said.
``I thought he would at least bobble, but he never budged. I had to
stay focused and keep my jab going.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not easy to do because whenever Lopez would land his
counter right hand _ as Page kept making the mistake of retreating
straight backward after throwing combinations that often left him
off balance _ he would wobble the champion or make him blink. By
the end of the night, Page was blinking like a lighthouse, but that
light refused to go out and that force of will carried the night
for Page and for King, who now controls two of the three major
welterweight titles as well as two of the heavyweight ones and most
of the middleweight champions.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday he also added the WBA bantamweight champion to his
stable when Tapia came out and won a workmanlike 12-round decision
from Nana Yaw Konadu. Konadu cut Tapia's right eye in the third
round and did some serious damage to his challenger's face when he
landed, rubbing his right cheek raw as well as patches on both his
shoulders and half-closing that right eye by the time the fight was
done.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for most of the evening, Konadu simply followed where Tapia
led like a willing dance partner. After Tapia first felt Konadu's
power he decided the three extra pounds he now was carrying since
moving up from junior bantamweight were doing him little good and
he chose the wise course, which was to box and stay away from the
champion as much as possible after he first tasted his power in
that third round.
</P>
<P>
   Because Tapia was so effective, he left the new Atlantic City
Convention Center with Konadu's title as well as his fingerprints
on his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't bleed and get a black eye, I haven't won
anything,'' said the tough-talking Tapia (45-0-2). ``I fought a
strong fighter, but it was very frustrating. He was not coming
after me. He wasn't doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to James Page and Jose Luis Lopez, neither was Johnny
Tapia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
