<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 03:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5998 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLLUTION-ASIA-SFCHRO     12-07 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLUTION-ASIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR POLLUTION CROSSING PACIFIC 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Clouds of dust and industrial pollutants from
Asia are showing up as air pollution along the West Coast,
scientists revealed Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first detailed look at the movement of air pollution
across the Pacific, new studies suggest that Californians may need
to look as far away as China to find the source of all the soot,
carbon monoxide and industrial toxins they may be breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Two sets of measurements in 1997 and 1998 found significant
amounts of smog and dust with an Asian imprint in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have shown before that dust storms in North Africa
can cloud the air along the eastern seaboard of the United States,
and industrial toxins have been traced from the American east coast
to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings, summarized Sunday during a meeting of the
American Geophysical Union in San Francisco, show for the first
time that pollution can even hitchhike all the way across the
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Such long-range transport is not a major source of air problems,
probably contributing less than 1 percent of the more common
pollutants, said Dan Jaffe, an associate professor studying
atmospheric chemistry at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the long-range culprits mean regulators should lighten up
on local polluters. But Jaffe noted that pollution blowing in from
Asia could become a growing problem as China and other east Asian
economies continue to industrialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be an important contributor to local air pollution
conditions now,'' he said. ``But we shouldn't just close our eyes
to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Findings by Jaffe and his associates are part of a three-year
research effort financed by the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Measurements taken in March 1997 at the Cheeka Peak Observatory
in northwest Washington showed substantially higher levels of
pollutants had managed to cross the Pacific than scientists had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Carbon monoxide levels, for example, were 10 percent higher than
found in normal Pacific marine air, particulates were 50 percent
above normal and a type of industrial pollutant called peroxyacetyl
nitrates was nearly double the expected concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Chemical analysis showed the source clearly was somewhere in
eastern Asia, although Jaffe said there isn't enough data to prove
whether the pollutants came from coal burning in China or an oil
source in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The contaminants appear to have traveled in the troposphere, as
high as about 10,000 feet, when a low-pressure system over the
Aleutian Islands combined with a high-pressure cell over Hawaii.
The effect was described as ``twin gears pulling a high-speed
conveyor belt'' laden with contaminants.
</P>
<P>
   Another set of measurements, taken in May, showed a large
expanse of the air above the northwestern United States choked with
fine soil dust blown in from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   On some days, it appears the imported dust accounted for as much
as two-thirds of the allowed standard for certain airborne
particulates, said John Merrill of the University of Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known that these materials can go a very, very long
way,'' he said, ``but this is the first time it's been documented
moving all way across the Pacific.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
