<HEADER>
A6139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     12-07 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Dec. 13.)  
 (rl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELECTED POEMS: 1960-1990
</P>
<P>
   By Maxine Kumin. (Norton, $17.95.) This collection by a
versatile elegist and observer of nature features vivid poems that
are, refreshingly, about something: Many tell stories that serve to
preserve her family's history. Last year in the Book Review,
Richard Tillinghast called the book ``a welcome addition to any
poetry library.''
</P>
<P>
   A JOURNEY WITH ELSA CLOUD
</P>
<P>
   By Leila Hadley. (Penguin, $14.95.) Invited to India by her
estranged hippie daughter, a demanding, perfectionist mother
embarks on a voyage of self-discovery that takes her from New Delhi
to the home of the exiled Dalai Lama, with epiphanies and emotional
awakenings along the way. ``Hadley is a gifted travel writer with
an artist's eye for the composition _ and the look, smell and
history _ of every scene,'' Diane Johnson wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   IN INDIA: FROM MIDNIGHT TO THE MILLENNIUM
</P>
<P>
   By Shashi Tharoor. (Harper Perennial, $14.) An expatriate takes
a hard look at his country's first 50 years of independence, and
explains why parliamentary democracy has done so little to relieve
poverty, illiteracy and disease. ``Few books in recent years, if
any, offer such a comprehensive overview of what ails India, its
politicians and its people,'' John F. Burns said in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   FOUR LETTERS OF LOVE
</P>
<P>
   By Niall Williams. (Warner, $13.99.) The narrator of this tale
of romance and fate is a Dubliner whose search for one of his
artist father's paintings leads him into the arms of a young woman
on the Irish coast. Last year, reviewer Katharine Weber called the
novel ``a luminously written, magical work of fiction ... filled
with marvelous characters, large and small.''
</P>
<P>
   THE END OF THE NOVEL OF LOVE
</P>
<P>
   By Vivian Gornick. (Beacon, $12.) Examining the works of writers
like Willa Cather and Grace Paley, a critic argues that literature
has lost its faith in the transformative power of love. ``Gornick
makes forceful and dramatic judgments,'' Elizabeth Frank wrote in
1997. ``Reading her essays, one is reassured that the conversation
between life and literature is mutually sustaining as well as
mutually corrective.''
</P>
<P>
   THE MERRY HEART: REFLECTIONS ON READING, WRITING, AND THE WORLD
OF BOOKS By Robertson Davies. (Penguin, $14.95) A posthumous
collection of lectures and essays by the Canadian novelist on the
literary life and matters of humane concern. Last year, reviewer
Sven Birkerts said that even though much of his public prose is
less successful on the written page, ``Davies was a relaxed and
winning raconteur, a beguiling autocrat of the rostrum.''
</P>
<P>
   TRAIN WHISTLE GUITAR
</P>
<P>
   By Albert Murray. (Vintage International, $13.) This novel, just
restored to print, is about a black boy growing up in Alabama in
the 1920s and his idol, a blues guitarist named Luzana Cholly. In
1974, John Wideman admired the ``long passages of dialogue,
monologue, the lyric descriptions of countryside and fireside,
which are nothing so much as the riffs and choruses of a blues
artist translated into speech and action.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FILE: A PERSONAL HISTORY
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy Garton Ash. (Vintage, $13.) A British historian tells
how he found a blurred image of his younger self in an old East
German secret police file, and how he tracked down the people who
had informed on him. The result is ``a political thriller,
reminiscent of Graham Greene and John le Carr, and a treatise on
memory, forgetting and forgiving in the great tradition of
Proust,'' Tomas Venclova wrote in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   HALLUCINATING FOUCAULT
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia Duncker. (Vintage International, $12.) This
intricate first novel focuses on a graduate student who tracks down
and falls in love with the subject of his dissertation, a French
novelist in an insane asylum. The result is ``a fascinating drama
of knowledge and power, reason and desire,'' Allen Lincoln wrote
last year.
</P>
<P>
   MURDER IN THE MUSEUM OF MAN
</P>
<P>
   By Alfred Alcorn. (Zoland, $13.) When a university dean is found
dead in the Museum of Man, the museum's courtly recording secretary
turns sleuth. The result is a ``stylish, occasionally fiendish
detective story ... out to skewer glitzy academic corruption,''
Nina Auerbach wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMAN CAPOTE: In Which Various Friends, Enemies, Acquaintances,
and Detractors Recall His Turbulent Career
</P>
<P>
   By George Plimpton. (Anchor/Doubleday, $16.95.) This chronicle
shows how the talented Capote turned fame into an art form, and
finally into a substitute for art itself. His lurid story is told
mostly through the firsthand accounts of fellow celebrities. In
1997 the reviewer, Julia Reed, found the book to be filled with old
gossip, but said ``some of the best bits reveal more about the
speaker than about the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   PILGRIMS
</P>
<P>
   By Elizabeth Gilbert. (Houghton Mifflin, $12.) Many of the
pilgrims in this first short-story collection are working-class
folks searching for redemption but skeptical of spiritual
enlightenment. The author ``embraces the bizarre and fabulous with
similar enthusiasm,'' Liam Callanan wrote in 1997. ``She moves
stealthily, avoiding the temptation to grandstand, moralize or,
especially, patronize.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 0833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
