<HEADER>
A6196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX     12-07 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Espy case another indictment against independent
counsels
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Can the independent counsel law survive the wipeout that saw a
jury blow off all 30 counts brought against former Agriculture
Secretary Mike Espy? Prosecutor Donald Smaltz was reduced, for
justification, to claiming indictment alone sends a cautionary
message to public officials. Well, yes, in the way that torturing
their innocent has always had a marvelously pacifying effect on
targeted audiences. The Inquisitors knew.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law is up for renewal next year and
already was tottering under the outlandishness of Kenneth Starr's
permanent investigation of all things Clinton. Smaltz's grotesque
performance could be the last straw.
</P>
<P>
   Espy, in effect, continued acting the congressman he had long
been when he moved into President Clinton's Cabinet. He accepted,
as he should not have, perks and favors from food companies his
department regulated and was rightly squeezed out for it. Smaltz
aggregated the value of the small-time goodies as $33,000 and
barraged Espy with 38 felony charges, but even before the issues
went to trial, it was clear that this, at best, was a case of gross
over-charging.
</P>
<P>
   Espy's ``crimes'' included limo rides, invitations to parties,
hitchhiking on a company jet, taking a couple of NFL tickets from a
natural history museum in Atlanta to attend a Smokey Bear promotion
that fizzled, and the like. The trial judge threw eight of the
charges out, and the jury wasted little time on the rest. Espy's
lawyers didn't even bother to put on a defense; the prosecution's
own witnesses had testified Espy was an independent secretary who
made decisions contrary to the interests of his casual benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   Smaltz had tried to weave a hanging rope out of small threads
and loose ends _ and spent four years and $17 million doing it. He
points, for further justification, to some 20 convictions and $11
million in fines from implicated agribusinesses, but one key case,
against Sun-Diamond Growers of California, is under appeal and some
companies _ Tyson Foods, for instance _ look to have pleaded guilty
mainly to cut their losses.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Starr, five more independent counsels are aprowl
in Washington. One will soon take former Housing Secretary Henry
Cisneros to trial on 18 counts having mainly to do with his
under-reporting _ not denial, mind you _ under-reporting of how
much he paid a former lover.
</P>
<P>
   This has all become quite lunatic, and Republicans are pushing
for still more special prosecutors to investigate Clinton campaign
funding. Easy for them to say. Auditors for the bipartisan Federal
Elections Commission recommend holding the Dole campaign to even
larger account _ $17 million to $7 million _ than the Clinton
campaign for 1996's excess, but the special prosecutor law wouldn't
kick in against Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   The law has become a gimmick for endless partisan harassment by
prosecutors without time and budget restraints or effective
supervision. If Congress can craft a replacement with higher
thresholds and sharp accountability, fine, but if not, well, the
old sport of throwing the rascals out didn't work all that badly.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
