<SLUG> BC-R-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jury Acquits Espy In Corruption Case
</P>
<P>
   Donald Smaltz spent four years investigating former Agriculture
Secretary Mike Espy, alleging that he had illegally accepted sports
tickets, luggage and other favors from companies he was supposed to
be regulating. A jury took two days to find Espy not guilty of all
30 charges. In the process, the jury provided powerful new
political ammunition for opponents of the law, set to expire in
June, that provides for the appointment of independent prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Espy said he wants to be one of the first witnesses when
Congress takes up the issue of renewing the independent counsel
law, probably in February.
</P>
<P>
   _ NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Serb General Arrested
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of a high-ranking Bosnian Serb general on charges of
genocide for directing the 1995 attack on Srebrenica, in which
7,000 Bosnian Muslims were marched off, presumably to their deaths,
provided a potent reminder that those responsible for the
atrocities of the Bosnian civil war cannot rest easy.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Radislav Krstic was indicted secretly by the
International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia. His
arrest prompted angry responses from Bosnian Serb politicians, who
vowed to limit their cooperation with the NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN ERLANGER
</P>
<P>
   Ickes Put on Hold
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ickes, the combative former top Clinton aide, will have
to wait to find out whether Attorney General Janet Reno will
request an independent counsel to investigate him. Undecided on the
final day of a three-month inquiry, Reno announced that she had
obtained a 60-day extension.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Ickes lied in a 1997 deposition when he said
he did not know of any administration efforts to intervene in a
strike by teamsters at a walnut processing plant in California.
Documents showed that Ickes lobbied Mickey Kantor, then the U.S.
trade representative, to phone the company for a status report.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Sniffs At New York's Garbage
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has always dealt with New York City's
problems with elegant simplicity. Pedestrians getting in the way of
cars? Reroute the pedestrians. Too many potholes? Well, fill them.
No place to put the city's garbage? Send it to New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   It would presumably have violated the spirit of simplicity,
though, to check to see if New Jersey actually wanted it. So when
Gov. Christie Whitman got a whiff of Giuliani's malodorous
offering, she responded with Giulianian simplicity: ``Drop dead.''
</P>
<P>
   _ HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Steinem Returns to Ms.
</P>
<P>
   A new media group founded by Gloria Steinem bought Ms., the
feminist magazine she co-founded in 1972. MacDonald Communications
Corp. sold Ms. to Liberty Media for Women, a group that includes a
pair of philanthropist teen-age sisters and Walt Disney's
grand-niece.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought seriously about whether the world still needs Ms.
magazine,'' Ms. Steinem said. ``I picked up armloads of women's
magazines and I looked at them and I thought: `Yes. The world does
still need Ms. magazine.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Time Out in Quebec
</P>
<P>
   It may be just a temporary truce, but Quebec and the rest of
Canada are looking forward to a respite from 30 years of rancor and
uncertainty caused by the predominately French-speaking province's
struggle for independence. Lucien Bouchard, the separatist premier,
who was re-elected with a disappointing level of popular support
last week, put off a third referendum on secession until at least
the second half of his five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANTHONY DePALMA
</P>
<P>
   Good News for Makers Of Silicone Implants
</P>
<P>
   The long battle over the safety of silicone breast implants took
a new turn when a panel of four scientists appointed by a federal
court reported that there was no evidence the implants caused
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Implant makers were delighted, expecting that courts would be
emboldened to dismiss lawsuits against them.
</P>
<P>
   As for the plaintiffs' lawyers, said Michael Green, a law
professor at the University of Iowa, ``this is as bad as it can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   _ GINA KOLATA
</P>
<P>
   In Display of Unity, European Nations Cut Rates
</P>
<P>
   Eleven European nations cut their interest rates to a nearly
uniform level in an unusual display of unity. The cuts are intended
to bolster European economies by making it cheaper for businesses
and consumers to borrow.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most coordinated action yet toward European monetary
union and it came just a month before the nations adopt the euro as
a single currency.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the 11 countries except Italy reduced its key interest
rate to 3 percent. Italy, which has had some of the highest
interest rates in Europe, dropped to 3.5 percent from 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. to Declassify Some Pinochet Files
</P>
<P>
   The United States, treading into a political and diplomatic
confrontation it tried to avoid, said it would declassify some
government documents on the killing and torture conducted by former
Chilean dictator Augusto Pinochet. The decision could open ``a can
of worms,'' in the words of a former CIA official, exposing U.S.
knowledge of Pinochet's crimes. The general, evicted from a London
hospital, awaits the British government's decision on whether to
expel him to face charges filed in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   _ TIM WEINER
</P>
<P>
   An Indulgent Pope
</P>
<P>
   For the year 2000, Pope John Paul II has introduced a fast track
to heaven. Throughout the yearlong millennium celebration, Roman
Catholics who quit smoking or drinking for a day can earn
indulgences to avoid punishment in the hereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Indulgences were sold by church officials in medieval times and
the practice helped drive Martin Luther to protest, starting the
Reformation. Indulgences are viewed as atavistic by some liberal
Catholics. But the pope wants penitence to be a major theme in the
third millennium, and he has broadened the criteria for earning
indulgences, allowing sinners to stop smoking for a day or visit a
hospital or prison. It is still no cakewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so easy for some to give up smoking for a day,'' said
Archbishop Crescenzio Sepe, a top Vatican official. ``It might be
easier to visit a prison inmate.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALESSANDRA STANLEY
</P>
<P>
   Chinese Dissidents Held
</P>
<P>
   Three prominent dissidents who had been trying to set up China's
first opposition political party were arrested and charged with
endangering state security. For the last six months, Xu Wenli, Qin
Yongmin and Wang Youcai have led a small network of activists
across China trying to win recognition for the China Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Although the White House and human rights groups decried the
arrests, senior Chinese officials defended them, reminding the
world that China is not a multi-party political system, and angrily
telling America to mind its own business.
</P>
<P>
   _ ELISABETH ROSENTHAL &QR;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
