<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer questions
 &HT;    By Jane S. Greig
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a lot of ribbons left over from my homecoming mum, and
I would like to save them for next year. How can I keep them from
discoloring? _Amy S.
</P>
<P>
   A: To keep the color fresh store it away from extremes of light,
moisture and temperature (no garage, no attic). The color should
remain fresh. It helps to store any fabric or paper in an acid-free
box or in acid-free tissue paper. Pick up a box at the Container
Store or from an archival supply house like Light Impressions at
(800) 828-6216. Storing ribbon on a roll will prevent creasing and
keep wire ribbon from crimping. Should it crease, a blow dryer or
careful (LOW heat) ironing usually gets the kinks out.
</P>
<P>
   Ribbon guru Camela Nitschke, at (419) 872-0073, sells books on
the history of ribbon as well as teaching videos for ribbon
projects and even kits for making ribbon flowers (including
bluebonnets!).
</P>
<P>
   Ribbon began as the Velcro of history _ holding sandals with
leather strips and wool capes in place. Ribbon also was a sign of
high station. When the Pope moved to Avignon the French pumped up
the ribbon industry. Victorian times were the golden age of ribbon,
and when the sewing machine became popular, common man finally got
a shot at this finery.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I caught the end of a radio clip announcing someone is
producing a Gen. Colin Powell doll. I searched the Internet and
contacted some local bookstores and can locate no additional
information. This would make a great Christmas gift for my
hard-to-buy-for husband. Any ideas how I can find out how to
purchase the doll?
</P>
<P>
   _Kim B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hasbro, maker of that 1960s icon G.I. Joe, has created the
doll honoring the former chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff who
oversaw military crises such as the Persian Gulf War and the
invasion of Panama. Proceeds from dolls are shared with Boys &AMP;
Girls Clubs of America.
</P>
<P>
   The doll comes with a U.S. Army flag and U.S. flag on flag stand
bases and a 23rd American Division patch and patch box. Suggested
retail price from Hasbro is $49.99. Kay-Bee Toys expects to carry
this doll and Toys R Us has had a few _ but they go fast.
</P>
<P>
   Bonus info: G.I. Joe debuted at 11 1/2 inches tall and had 21
moving parts _ although I am hard-pressed to name them all.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We do brown bag lunches at my office, and I am trying to find
someone to come to our company and demonstrate package-wrapping and
bow-making for this time of year. _P.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: No takers for this workplace demonstration but I bet you
could do it with a little help from the folks at the Container
Store. Call the store's mail order line at (800) 786-7315 for a
free ``Guide to Beautiful Bows.'' Instructions for four primary bow
types _ pompom, florist, big and basic _ are included. Need more
direction? Attend one of the Container Store's free bow workshops.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What amount is the national debt? Last I heard, it was $5.5
trillion. _R.A.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's still in the same high-dollar neighborhood. The Bureau
of the Public Debt clocks this figure and posts it daily about
10:30 a.m. CST. For to-the-penny figures, access
www.publicdebt.treas.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Want to make a contribution to reduce this mammoth debt? Write a
check to Bureau of the Public Debt and note on the check's face
``gift to reduce the Public Debt.'' Mail the check to Capital Area
Servicing Center, 1300 C St. SW, Washington, D.C. 20239-0001.
Testamentary bequests are also accepted. In the fiscal year 1997,
$955,897.15 was contributed to this reduction fund. Wonder who sent
the 15 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the correct dimensions for a king-size mattress? I
purchased one, and my king-size sheets do not fit. The mattress is
smaller than the box springs. The dimensions are 76 inches wide and
78 inches long. _E.S.
</P>
<P>
   A: A king-size mattress is 76 inches by 80 inches, says mattress
maker Serta. No wonder the sheets don't fit. I hope you got a
really good deal on that ``king.'' Serta, maker of mattresses for
more than 60 years, has made custom mattresses in a variety of
sizes _ from miniatures (15 by 15 inches) for a display of
historical monarchs' bedrooms to a 100-square-foot mattress for an
NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane S. Greig at P.O. Box 670, Austin, Texas 78767;
(512) 445-3697; e-mail jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512)
445-3968.
</P>
<P>
   For copies of Jane's book, ``Thanks for Asking!'' _ a
compilation of more than 600 favorite questions and answers _ call
(800) 424-6291.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
