<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Swatch branching out into pager business
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Swatch, the company that made the plastic watch cool,
has launched a line of plastic pagers. The Swatch Beep Box is round
with a regular-sized message screen placed above one round button.
</P>
<P>
   The beeper comes in three colors, airmail blue, black grape and
round table orange. Like America Online, the beeper lets you create
a ``buddy list,'' which lets you send group messages.
</P>
<P>
   The beepers are available on the Web, at http://www.swatch.com.
The Beep Boxes start at $100, which includes 1,000 pages and three
months of service. One thousand more pages cost $30. There is no
reactivation fee should you let your service lapse. The beeper
alone is on sale at electronics and Swatch retailers for $75.
</P>
<P>
   The Beep Box, made with help from Motorola, is a numeric pager.
It can store 16 messages, each with a time and date.
</P>
<P>
   A new way to attack 'mouse wrist' malady
</P>
<P>
   If the permanent aching wrist caused by keeping one hand on your
mouse all day is starting to bother you, a new device available
online might be your answer.
</P>
<P>
   Mousebar Co. out of Waterford, Wis., has a patented pad that
attaches either to your desk or your chair arm. The bar can be
moved backward and forward. It is made of plastic with a textured
surface for the mouse.
</P>
<P>
   The bar, which retails for $28.95 plus $4.95 for shipping, comes
in light gray or charcoal. The bar is mounted with either a clamp
or adhesive. Both are included in the package.
</P>
<P>
   The guy who invented the bar, James Baranowski, uses computer
design tools at work and was looking for a way to ease the wrist
pain he was feeling after hours at his computer.
</P>
<P>
   The bar comes with a 30-day money back guarantee. It can be
ordered over the Internet at http://www.mousebar.com.
</P>
<P>
   Car maintenance meets the computer
</P>
<P>
   Some dads used to keep excruciatingly detailed facts about their
cars: how many miles per gallon the old Galaxy 500 got for each
fill-up dating to 1965, when the tires were bought, who from and
how much he paid. Now there's a software program to take all that
out of the glovebox and onto the PC.
</P>
<P>
   Dew Technology's Peak Performance lets the Type A types track
scheduled maintenance, unscheduled maintenance, gas mileage
performance and includes a maintenance forecast that tells you when
to rotate your tires, change your filters, tune your engine, flush
your radiator and change your transmission oil.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which retails for $49.95, lets you keep histories
of 10 vehicles. Minimum requirements are 3 megabytes of application
memory, a 486/66 megahertz processor, 8 megabytes of RAM and
Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Peak Performance is available at the company's Web site,
</P>
<P>
   http://www.dewtech.com.
</P>
<P>
   Slice of Americana captured on CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   Norman Rockwell, among the most traditional and American of
artists, has been brought into the high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   On the 20th anniversary of his 1978 death, New Jersey's Cinegram
Media is offering an interactive CD-ROM called Norman Rockwell _
The Man and His Art. A disc of screen savers that includes more
than 30 of his better-known paintings is also available.
</P>
<P>
   The disc lets you ``tour'' Rockwell's Massachusetts studio,
``meet'' his models and view interviews Rockwell gave Edward R.
Murrow and others.
</P>
<P>
   The disc contains more than 450 images of Rockwell's paintings,
hundreds of photographs, an audio narrative, the complete series of
324 Saturday Evening Post covers and behind-the-scenes looks at his
more well-known works.
</P>
<P>
   The disc is available at software retailers, or online at
http://www.cinegram.com, for $69.95. The screen saver collection
sells for $29.95.
</P>
<P>
   Exploring the hottest Web business models
</P>
<P>
   Corporations compete with business models rather than products.
The folks at Amazon.com sell the same books as those at B Dalton
Bookseller, but Amazon.com is hot because its business model _
buying books over the Internet _ keeps you out of the malls. The
idea that models, not products, will pave the way to corporate gold
is the premise behind the cover story in the Dec. 7 issue of
Fortune.
</P>
<P>
   A special section called ``The E-Corporation: More Than Just
Web-based, It's Building a New Industrial Order,'' explores the
idea of that the ``hottest and most dangerous new business models
are out there on the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't program it, just try talking to it
</P>
<P>
   After years of making VCRs that were somewhat difficult to
program, companies have been making simpler machines. Now, Zenith
Electronics has taken that one step further. The company that
brought the remote control to market is offering SpeakEZ, a way to
control the recording function of your VCR with your voice.
</P>
<P>
   SpeakEZ will be available in seven Zenith VCRs. The feature will
talk the user through each function, from recording to
clock-setting.
</P>
<P>
   The feature will be available on Zenith VCRs in time for the
holidays. Suggested retail price is $149 to $249.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
