<HEADER>
A6213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-ROLES-TIPS08-     12-07 0196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-ROLES-TIPS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Avoiding the anxiety of holidays at home
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tips on coping with stress over family visits during
the holidays:
</P>
<P>
   _ Temper your expectations. The notion of the ``perfect''
reunion can set you up for frustration and depression.
</P>
<P>
   _ Call a friend if the family setting becomes unpleasant.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take heed of alcohol consumption. It may seem relaxing in the
short term, but its physiological effect can compound stress and
depression.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set comfortable limits. Determine how involved and
accommodating your plans should be well in advance, and make your
limits known to others involved.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reach out to those with whom you have healthy, nurturing
relationships. Get together with friends if a family setting is not
feasible.
</P>
<P>
   _ Change gift-giving procedures. Consider instituting a limit of
one gift per person.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Patricia Wheeler, an Atlanta psychotherapist; ``When
Holidays Are Hell: A Guide to Surviving Family Gatherings'' by
Mariana Caplan (Ingram Book Co., $7.95)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 0957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6214 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-ROLES08-COX     12-07 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-ROLES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For some, stress-filled traditional trip home has become too
much of an ordeal
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS, ILLUSTRATION, ATL-HOLIDAY-ROLES-TIPS
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The truth is, you can go home again. The question is,
do you really want to?
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with the ``terrible cooking'' of her mother in Ohio,
Christine Ronn, 41, of Marietta decided a few years ago that
telephoning home would be easier on her stomach, not to mention her
nerves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get nauseous just seeing the Toledo city limits sign,''
says Ronn, a mother of three. ``At some point as you get older,
it's just not worth it _ unless you get off on going nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   For millions of Americans, going home for the holidays has
become an arduous, stress-filled ordeal in which grown men and
women unconsciously revert to childish roles, elderly parents bark
orders like tyrants, and somebody else _ anybody but you _ makes
all the decisions, including when, where and what to eat, when to
open gifts, how to decorate the tree or even whether it's OK to
leave for a while without hurting anyone's feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday stress, brought on in part by such visits, is one reason
America's suicide rate starts rising in January from a low in
December. And why January is the busiest month for
psychotherapists.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Wheeler, an Atlanta psychologist, says her patients
seemingly can't wait to get holiday hell stories off their chests.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are confrontations over tinsel or icicles on the tree,
or turkey with corn bread or roasted chestnuts,'' Wheeler says.
``People worry, `Are my gifts good enough? Did I spend enough
money? Is Aunt Sara gonna be as horrible as last year? Is Dad gonna
get drunk?'
</P>
<P>
   ``It can all make you feel empty, depressed, alienated. It's now
a tradition to feel guilty for not feeling happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta stockbroker Pierce Hammond, 54, is a case in point. He's
trekked to Mobile, Ala., for longer than he can remember to spend
the holidays with his wife's folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's chaotic, is what it is,'' says Hammond. ``God,
everybody's there. All my wife's sisters and brothers and their
kids, a whole bunch of people floating around. It's kind of a haze.
I'm ready to leave when it's done _ even before.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses, then grins: ``But I'm supposed to say it's great,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   49 percent who visit feel stress
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, heading home really can be great, even relaxing,
says Dr. Rick Winer, a Roswell psychiatrist. ``In some instances,
you don't have to think, because everything's scheduled.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, difficulties loom. ``With your parents, there's always
that feeling, `Do I need to let them know where I'm going and when
I'll get back?''' Winer says. ``Parents will assert their authority
more: `You are under my roof, you are under my rules.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, we go. About 45 percent of us will visit faraway
relatives, according to the American Automobile Association. The
numbers may be even higher in metro Atlanta, where fully 42 percent
of the residents aren't native Georgians.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Thompson, 22, a salesman for Pugmire Izusu in Marietta,
is weighing whether to drive home to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, it's comforting,'' he says. ``I think I like it
because nothing ever changes. They try to fix my plate. They tell
me to wear my coat.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Wilber, senior analyst with the Roper Organization at
the University of Connecticut, says polls show that 49 percent of
adults who visit their parents report significant stress. They
report difficulties over being treated like children, over how to
trim the tree and how much to spend on gifts, over the trip itself
_ even lingering sibling rivalries. ``Who got the biggest raise?
Who has the best car? The best house? It's like comparing
curriculum vitae,'' Wilber says.
</P>
<P>
   Ronn has decided that home for the holidays is wherever her
``real house'' is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be my mom and dad were the big kahunas,'' she says.
But doing without the annual trip to Ohio turns out to be just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food is better. In Toledo, the sexiest thing we had to eat
was beef stew. Mom's idea of cooking was to get a can of vegetables
and boil them until they are so limp they scream to get out of the
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother is the queen of criticism'' she adds. ``I'll be
damned if I'm going to fall back into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bramham, 51, an executive at CNN, still enjoys his family
visits _ for the most part.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a change, and in a lot of ways it's really nice,'' he
says. ``Mom always reverts,'' he laughs. ``I had asthma as a child,
and she always says, `Put on a sweater, you'll get cold. Close the
window.' Her favorite comment is `Now listen to your mother.' We
still have a great time, and I still look forward to the
holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses and adds, ``But I'm really, really thankful for Jan.
2.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
