<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6215 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN08-COX     12-07 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Altered dreams just as good as those pure ones we had as kids
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ One of the greatest things about being a
little kid is that
</P>
<P>
   nothing is impossible. Dreams are the truth of the moment and
reality is only in the perception.
</P>
<P>
   My young playmates and I operated in a world of infinite
possibilities. In the days of our youthful make-believe, we worked
hard at the fantasy of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Tootie always wanted to play opera. We'd improvise an apartment
on my front
</P>
<P>
   porch complete with a toy stove, a sink (with running water if
we filled the reservoir on the back), a tin teaset, and a toy
telephone. The oversized, cushioned glider was our bed.
</P>
<P>
   Tootie's plan was to have a penthouse (we all wanted one of
those because in the movies, truly glamourous people lived atop
buildings filled with other
</P>
<P>
   glamorous people), sing at the Met, and live in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Ann insisted we play newspaper. She wanted to be Brenda
Starr, dazzling
</P>
<P>
   girl reporter, writing and searching remote corners of the earth
for her elusive ``Mystery Man.''
</P>
<P>
   We all thought she could have made it if only her mom would have
allowed her to dye her hair copper penny red.
</P>
<P>
   My burning ambition never wavered. I was going to be a test
pilot of such fame that no matter where I happened to be in the
world, and no matter what great cause I was serving, when a new
fighter rolled out of the hangar, I'd be the one called to ``take
it up and wring it out.'' Later, I kind of lost interest when they
took the propellers off of airplanes. Jets just didn't look fierce
enough to suit me.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, the three of us played on that porch, sharing our
dreams, confident that if we only believed hard enough, they would
all come true.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, as I was hoofing it around town, putting in my two
miles and trying to figure out what was with this spring-like
weather in December, I came upon a scene that took me back to those
times.
</P>
<P>
   Three little kids on a swingset were hollering at a fourth, a
little boy named Jimmy, who just happened to be standing in a
battered zinc washtub on top of a picnic table. ``Okay, now stay
still,'' a little girl yelled as they pumped their swings faster
and faster, stretching their toes to the limit to reach - what? In
a matter of seconds my question was answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop! Stop!'' the little girl screeched. The three swingers
dragged their heels, dug in their toes, and came to a halt. They
put their heads together and then walked over to Jimmy. ``Get out
of the tub a minute,'' the little girl ordered. Jimmy demurred but
after a brief discussion as to the possibility of moving the picnic
table closer to the swingset with him in the washtub, he gave in.
The kids put some muscle into it and began to shove the table
across the grass.
</P>
<P>
   After some dispute and a series of minor adjustments, the little
girl declared the operation a success and told Jimmy to get back in
the washtub which he did gladly, obviously enjoying his position as
top man in the tub.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy assumed an heroic stance, arms folded across his chest,
and declared
</P>
<P>
   himself ready. The kids pumped up their swings again. Faster and
higher, reaching with their toes toward Jimmy who appeared ready to
repel all encroachers on his washtub kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   But then the magic crumbled. Simultaneously and with shouts of
unbridled glee, three sets of feet collided with Jimmy's zinc
citadel and sent him flying, backside over tin tub, onto the grass.
He howled. Things hadn't quite worked as planned. Or maybe they had
- for the other three.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy wasn't hurt and I couldn't help but chuckle, thinking back
to the day I had come home from the movies with a new trick. I'd
just seen a man whip a tablecloth out from under four place
settings of fine china and crystal. I knew I could do it too, only
I wasn't dumb enough to risk smashing a table full of my mother's
dishes. Instead, I conned Tootie into standing on an old bedspread
while I snatched it out from under her. I assured her she'd be
unharmed. I was wrong. Tootie landed firmly on her backside and
went home yowling. I was in big
</P>
<P>
   trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But the dreams didn't die. Over the years we just altered them
slightly to
</P>
<P>
   fit new realities.That works too.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Address mail to
320 West
</P>
<P>
   Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
