</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Article helps stamp out Windows 98 bugs
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any piece of software, no matter how good, is a work in
progress. Every company ships programs with lots of bugs, and that
includes the current operating system Microsoft Windows 98. Learn
about what bugs are in Win98 and how to fix at least some of them
in the December issue of Windows magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The December issue of Windows also includes a comprehensive
guide to Windows NT5, which is Microsoft's industrial-strength
operating system, typically used to run server computers. You'll
find a detailed discussion of NT's strengths and weaknesses as well
as a recommendation on who should use it.
</P>
<P>
   On CD-ROM
</P>
<P>
   War and destruction remain popular, at least for computer game
makers. As always, many of the titles released this holiday season
feature war and are aimed at boys. Cavedog Entertainment, for
example, has released the ``Total Annihilation Commander Pack.'' It
includes ``Total Annihilation,'' a popular war game, and two
expansion sets. The pack retails for $44.99 and requires Windows 95
and a 100-megahertz Pentium computer.
</P>
<P>
   For something a little more benign, there's Wizardworks'
``Rudolph the Red-nose Reindeer's Magical Sleigh Ride.'' There's
not a single casualty in this computer CD game based on the
soon-to-be-released animated movie of the same name. In this game,
you help Santa gather toys for his ride, locate kids needing gifts
and print out holiday cards. Available for both PCs and Macs,
Rudolph retails for $19.99.
</P>
<P>
   Online
</P>
<P>
   If you are a fan of those little plastic replicas of people like
Darth Vader, check out a new site by Hasbro. It produces a lot of
these figures and now has a database of information about them
online. Called HasbroCollectors
</P>
<P>
   .com, the site will both sell these plastic figures and provide
a details about them. There are also chat rooms where collectors
can trade information and discuss their favorite figures. You'll
find the HasbroCollectors.com site at
http://www.HasbroCollectors.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
