<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Going once, twice ... auctions to treasure
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Online auctions prove one of the basic truths of human
nature: One person's trash is another's treasure.
</P>
<P>
   The Web auction game is relatively new, and might be a little
too much for Web surfers just getting comfortable with online
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you read the directions carefully and ignore the $250
Furbys (unless the money is going to charity), you can find your
own personal pot of gold _ or gold plate _ at an online auction.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most popular online auction houses are eBay
(http://www.ebay.com) and Yahoo! Auction (http://www
</P>
<P>
   .yahoo.com). On these sites, you'll be able to find nearly
everything your heart desires, from rare coins to collectible
Christmas ornaments, vintage Barbie dolls and Waterford crystal.
</P>
<P>
   If you are a collector, or know someone who is, purchasing a
hard-to-find treasure through an online auction can be fun and
rewarding. A quick survey of collectors of a variety of items
showed that for the most part, initial asking prices on the items
were what a person would expect to pay at a flea market, an
in-person auction or a retail store.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with all this in mind, newbies should take care to read
all the fine print before signing up or placing a bid. Once you
have purchased an item, you are conducting business with the person
auctioning the item. Yahoo! and eBay allow you to check up on both
buyer and seller. The eBay system has more checks and balances,
although problems are rare.
</P>
<P>
   There are sites such as Amazon.com, which have perfected the art
of one-click ordering, but eBay and other online auctioneers aren't
the sort of places where you log in, order up and log out. By their
very nature, these sites invite you to stay, take a look around and
see if they have any classic matchbox cars, Fiestaware soup bowls
or vintage rhinestone jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   If you see something you want to buy, that's great, but unlike
online retailers, you've got to register whether you are a buyer or
a seller. That way, if you develop a reputation as a con artist or
a welcher, the whole eBay community will find out via online
postings. And there truly is nothing worse than having a bad
reputation in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   For beginners, there's no better place to learn the ins and outs
of online auctions than eBay, which has an easy-to-follow tutorial,
a list of frequently asked questions and lots of other information
to help you before you bid. And even if you don't want to buy, it's
still fun to look. Recent items on sale at eBay included a 1983
DeLorean auto and a snuffbox featuring a painting of the Titanic
disaster. Yahoo! Auctions is equally easy to use and also requires
registration. There may be fewer items and the organization might
not be as efficient as eBay's, but if they have what you want, it
really doesn't matter what else they may have.
</P>
<P>
   With so much talk about sites that want to build community on
the Web, eBay and others create an instant community of like-minded
souls united by common interests. EBay founder Pierre Omidyar says
there may be only one or two collectors of a certain item in your
hometown, but there could be hundreds online. Here's where you can
find them and gather up some goodies along the way.
</P>
<P>
   What' New
</P>
<P>
   Appalachian Trail Home Page: Yeah, you dream about ``doing'' the
trail, all the way from Maine to Georgia, if you ever get the time.
Well, even if you never do, this is an inspiring site to hike
around. Check out articles about the legendary trail, books, maps,
videos, advice from other hikers, and links to related outdoor and
environmental sites.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.fred.net/kathy/at.html
</P>
<P>
   A Winter Web Wonderland: This mixed bag of holiday treats
contains some cute surprises in addition to more traditional fare.
Virtual stocking stuffers, screen savers, an interview with Santa
and the hilarious AOL recycled diskette gift collection should not
be missed, even if your last name is Scrooge.
</P>
<P>
   http://citylink.neosoft.com/xmas/
</P>
<P>
   Talk City: This site celebrates virtual ``communities'' on the
Web. Sift through the subject entries to turn up groups of fellow
fans for everything from books to boxing. Drop in on a sailing chat
or talk Top 40 music. Create a free home page or check out the Talk
City Calendar of Events.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.talkcity.com/
</P>
<P>
   Today
</P>
<P>
   11:30 a.m.: Ask the Pros at Fox Sports
</P>
<P>
   http://www.foxsports.com/
</P>
<P>
   3 p.m.: OnLine Today with David Lawrence at OnLine Today
</P>
<P>
   http://www.online-today.com/latertonight.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.yack.com/OnLineToday/165003016.html
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m.: ``Sunday Night Football'' with Joe Theismann at ESPN.com
</P>
<P>
   http://espn.sportszone.com/interact/chatter.html
</P>
<P>
   http://www.yack.com/ESPN.com/165002545.html
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m.: ``Coast to Coast with James Brown'' at SportsFan Radio
</P>
<P>
   http://www.broadcast.com/radio/sports/sportsfan/
</P>
<P>
   9:30 p.m.: Live In Concert: blues artists Tommy Castro with
Jimmy Thackery at LiveConcerts
</P>
<P>
   http://www.liveconcerts.com/lobby
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
