<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Encarta is tops, but still has errors
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Microsoft's Encarta has been at the top of the heap of
popular electronic encyclopedias since its first appearance, and
the 1999 edition will not lose that place.
</P>
<P>
   The interface has been tweaked, not all of it for the good. It
takes more mouse clicks now, in some cases, to get what you want.
But it remains easy to use, and all articles are displayed in
large, easy-to-read text.
</P>
<P>
   The deluxe version is now a three-disc set, one disc being used
entirely for installation and the inevitable attempt to stuff
Explorer down your throat. It does this with a vengeance _ no by
your leave, no ``would you like to.'' It just sets up Explorer as
your default browser. I find that infuriating.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Encarta is a fine encyclopedia, with a heavier
emphasis on the arts than most. There are, for instance, large and
well-done sections on ceramics, woodworking and furniture. All
music (that I listened to, at any rate) was presented in excerpts
from commercial recordings.
</P>
<P>
   The sections on flamenco and bullfighting remain essentially
unchanged, and quite good except for the usual incorrect captions,
questionable choice of photos and unfortunate tendency to try to
force the bullfight into the general category of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Entries on firearms, which I have not previously examined, have
some very strange problems. As curator of arms at the West Point
museum, Robert W. Fisch may not have been the best choice to write
the little section on shotguns; clearly he is out of touch when he
tells us, ``Modern pump-action and semi-automatic shotguns equally
share the field with the similar side-by-side and single-barreled
pieces ...''
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to be a museum curator to know pumps and
semi-autos rule the field, and the traditional double gun is no
longer made by major manufacturers, having been largely replaced by
over-and-under guns.
</P>
<P>
   The biography of John Moses Browning, the greatest arms designer
who ever lived, is unsigned. Probably a good thing, since it
contains ludicrous errors and, for want of a better term,
understatements. It says Browning invented ``two machine guns ...
the Colt Peacemaker and the Browning Automatic Rifle.''
</P>
<P>
   Peacemaker, of course, is the popular name of the Colt's Single
Action Army, the single most popular handgun of the American West
following the Civil War, and by no stretch of the imagination a
machine gun.
</P>
<P>
   The bio goes on with the offhand statement that Browning ``also
designed an automatic pistol.'' It is for this, embodied originally
in the Colt M1911A and refined later in the Browning Hi-Power, that
Browning is chiefly known today. Both weapons have been changed but
little since their inception and remain the most popular of all
semi-auto designs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
