<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN08-COX     12-07 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The X factor in parenting is knowing when to say 'when'
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ I've not been in the position, only in the
breathless spectator role. But I've come to believe that only when
the baby's head peeks out through the cervix is ``push'' a
clear-cut decision.
</P>
<P>
   Mom pushes. Child responds. Don't get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a dad, you'll do lots of pushing _ strollers, swings,
merry-go-rounds. But generally it will be on the wings of your
child's desire.
</P>
<P>
   You could be a control freak and force every decision on your
child. But at some point even the sternest parent must take ``no''
for an answer. That's particularly true when the child digs canals
in your neck with purple fingernails and won't let go.
</P>
<P>
   Some will say: ``You must lay down the law.'' But at some point,
wild boars cannot pull a resistant child from your neck.
</P>
<P>
   I'm thinking of a swimming lesson in which our eldest son, then
6, absolutely, positively refused to jump into the deep end. The
instructor was just as resolute. She wouldn't take no.
</P>
<P>
   She finally convinced him that she'd be there to catch him in
the water. He flung his quivering self right on top of her.
</P>
<P>
   It was like a mackerel landing on a lilly pad. Both went under.
Both grappled for something to hold. Fully clothed, I was crouched
to leap in to save somebody when she managed to right herself.
</P>
<P>
   She should have taken ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting a child to do homework, or brush teeth, or clean up a
room is not so much the issue. These are things that must be done.
</P>
<P>
   The real issues are endeavors like youth sports, or music
lessons, or other things you consider enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   'It's good for you'
</P>
<P>
   When do you push? When do you know that a child who says ``no''
is just being lazy, backing away from a challenge, or that he or
she really, fiercely, doesn't want to do it?
</P>
<P>
   I offer no answer. Maybe you have one.
</P>
<P>
   Our youngest son is a good athlete. But he's always resisted
organized sports. He's played no Little League. He went out for
soccer at 9, but felt disadvantaged against boys who'd been playing
since they were 5. He quit.
</P>
<P>
   I knew he could compete. Should I have pushed? I mined him for
reasons, gave him several chances to change his mind. He didn't.
</P>
<P>
   From my own experience and knowing his ability, I was certain
organized sports would be fun for him. But I have never pushed.
</P>
<P>
   And what do you know. This fall at the ripe age of 11 he decided
he wanted to take basketball skills honed on the driveway against
dad and join a league, which he did Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Mom decides to push
</P>
<P>
   Our oldest son is less of a jock, but is a dynamo in a host of
creative arts. He's also got the average teen bio-rhythmic pattern,
which wavers between manic zest for life and, ``Wake me when the
world ends. On second thought, you'll be extinct . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout their school years both boys have participated in the
PTA Reflections program _ a local, state, national competition with
categories in visual arts, photography, writing and music. They've
won their share of accolades. This year Michael, the oldest, had a
great idea for a Reflections poster, but as the deadline was
approaching his lower lip was collecting cat hair in one of his low
modes. His mom, who'd purchased materials for the project, decided
not to take no for an answer when he sloughed off encouragement.
She made it an order.
</P>
<P>
   Under duress, he started to work. It wasn't long that, great
idea as it was, he got immersed. What began grudgingly turned a
Michelangelesque epic. He had pencil grime on his chin. He stayed
up all night. The result was stunning:
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, Mom, for pushing me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And if you think that's stunning, you should see the poster. Why
doesn't someone tell us when to push?
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
E-mail address: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib. com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
