 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2505 - December 7, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2505 -- Dec. 7, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. FROM BROOKLYN TO KOSOVO, WITH LOVE AND AK-47s A single
photograph decorates the office walls of Triangle Contractors in an
old house on Cortelyou Road in Brooklyn. It depicts a young man
with a Kalashnikov slung across his chest, a pistol tucked into his
belt and another automatic weapon in his hands. He is a key to
understanding the Kosovo Liberation Army, the ethnic-Albanian
guerrilla movement fighting for independence from Serbia. By Stacy
Sullivan. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length (5,000
words) + edited article available. 2. DOROTHY DAY : TOO SAINTLY FOR
SAINTHOOD? Dorothy Day died in 1980, at the age of 83. A year ago,
to mark what would have been her 100th birthday, John Cardinal
O'Connor of New York announced he would take up the cause for her
canonization. Day was one of the greatest religious figures of the
century, and one of the most paradoxical. She founded the Catholic
Worker, a loose aggregation of ``houses of hospitality,'' communal
farms, newspapers and round-table discussions for ``further
clarification of thought.'' And if there was anything she did not
want, it was to be called a saint. By Paul Elie. From The New York
Times Magazine. Full-length (3,400 words) + edited article
available. 3. STORM IN THE ENGLISH CHANNEL : THE FIGHT OVER FEUDAL
SARK Life on the island of Sark, a speck in the English Channel not
far from the French coast, is a bizarre mix of the old and new. No
cars are allowed on the island, and a feudal-style lord still
retains archaic powers (e.g. deciding who may marry whom.) Yet Sark
and other Channel Islands have embraced the savage side of modern
capitalism by allowing dubious foreign firms to set up,''shell''
companies to avoid taxes or cover shady trade. Britain wants this
to end, but its authority to enforce change is limited. By Hans
Hoyng. From Der Spiegel. 1,000 words. (English translation
available.) 4. CARTOONIST'S SATIRE LOST ON SOME READERS Bill
Maxwell used to think that opinion columnists were the loneliest
souls at newspapers. ``I now believe that editorial cartoonists are
the ultimate outsiders,'' he writes. ``They are the most
misunderstood of all journalists because their craft - alternately
making us laugh, curse and think - is finicky and strange to us.''
From New America News Service. 1,000 words.
________________________________________________________ 5. FROM
NEW SCIENTIST MAGAZINE (N/A Brazil, Australia, New Zealand) A.
SELLING THE FAMILY SECRETS Iceland's 270,000 citizens are a dream
come true for genetics researchers. One thousand years of
near-isolation has meant their ancestry can be traced right back to
the original Viking and Irish settlers. Now Iceland plans to put
its people's genetic history in the hands of a single company to
create a special database. The deal could put privacy at risk, with
damaging consequences for genetics research everywhere. By Andy
Coghlan. 1,500 words. B. YOUR CHEATIN' HEART Monogamy and
infideltiy are not as incompatible as they might seem. Robin Dunbar
explains why it pays to cheat on your partner. 1,500 words. C. JUST
FOR YOU One person's cure can be somebody else's poison. To find
out which drug is right for you, doctors may soon turn to genetic
testing. By Karen Schmidt. 1,500 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
COMMERCIALS DIE IN MOVIE BLOODBATH HORROR! Advertisers who pay for
top-price TV slots in the middle of films like ``Reservoir Dogs''
could be wasting their money. Screen violence seems to impair
viewers' memory for advertising. By Sara Abdulla. Nature News
Service. 400 words. (N/A France and Spain.)
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
RAY BRADBURY INTERVIEW Sci-fi king Ray Bradbury talks about
Disneyland Paris, Los Angeles freeways, brainless society, the
future, education, astronauts, space travel and more. By John
Geirland. From Wired magazine. (N/A Japan.) 1,500 words. Q&AMP;A
format.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
From PROSPECT MAGAZINE (N/A U.K.) A. GETTING A LIFE Biography is
starting to display the quivering self-scrutiny which changed the
face of fiction 20 years ago. By Kathryn Hughes. 1,000 words. B.
FLUKES AND FLAWS Connections between salt and heart disease or
passive smoking and lung cancer are discovered in a new study ...
only to be disproved by another; and claims made for wonder drugs
are routinely disappointed in the real world. Too much research
seems to be based on flawed statistics. What's going on? By Robert
Matthews. 2,500 words. 
