``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: EIGHT COLOR SLIDES are available by mail (or overnight
delivery, using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) at NO EXTRA
CHARGE to purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want
the art when you order the article.)  
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORS OF DISCOVER MAGAZINE  
 c.1998 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   December can be a frustrating month for those who want to
proclaim the joy of science along with the joy of the season. It
can be especially difficult for parents looking for gifts to please
their little ones. What follows are some of the best toys on the
market for the up-and-coming scientists in your family.
</P>
<P>
   -----
 &UR; YEAR OF THE ROBOT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year NASA's Sojourner robot caught the world's attention as
it trolled across the Martian landscape, sniffing alien rocks and
radioing back information about their composition.
</P>
<P>
   Images of the intrepid rover at work not only gave us a new
sense of Mars _ they also conveyed a powerful message about how
robots are extending the reach of human exploration, and human
imagination, to other worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, robots are well represented among the
science-themed toys this season.
</P>
<P>
   By far the year's most radical new toy _ if it can in fact be
called a toy _ is lego's Mindstorms ($200, LEGO, 800-453-4652,
www.legomindstorms.com). This kit, the product of a lengthy
collaboration with MIT's Media Lab, lets aspiring roboticists (age
12 to very adult) build and program their own mechanical creations.
</P>
<P>
   Commands for the robot are written on a personal computer using
lego's custom-designed software. It assumes no previous programming
experience and incorporates a reassuring tutorial to guide novices
through the basics.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than writing actual lines of computer code, you string
together graphic blocks, each representing a single instruction for
the robot.
</P>
<P>
   When you are done, you download the program to the robot's
onboard microprocessor using an infrared transmitter, and it's
ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   The kit provides instructions for 12 projects, such as an
intruder alarm and a trail tracker. Two expansion packs, $50 each,
that will allow the construction of more complicated robots should
be available soon.
</P>
<P>
   Do not expect Mindstorms to be all plug and play. The print and
computer guides give you extensive help; further advice is
available on the company's Web site. But LEGO wants you to use your
brain and figure things out on your own.
</P>
<P>
   If your heart is set on actual NASA robots, Learning Curve has
the toys for you. The Robotix Mars Discovery Pack ($9.99, Learning
Curve, 800-704-8697) lets you build a tolerably accurate replica of
Sojourner, complete with antenna and alpha proton X-ray
spectrometer. You can add a power pack to make your Sojourner move
on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Learning Curve has instructions on its Web site
(www.learningcurve.com) for constructing a much more detailed
Sojourner using parts from several of the company's robot kits.
</P>
<P>
   The company also sells the Volcanic Crawler, $49.99, a
self-powered model of Dante, the volcano-explorer robot. With its
rolling, insectlike gait, the crawler conveys how Dante traversed
obstacles during its infernal mission.
</P>
<P>
   If you get bored following NASA's lead, you can snap together
the intricately molded Robotix parts into a mechanical brute of
your own design.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DYNAMICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even the simplest mechanical toys can still provide a great deal
of enjoyment if properly designed.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you can really let your imagination go with Zoobs
($39.99 for a 120-unit set, Primordial, 415-923-1895,
www.zoob.com). These brightly colored plastic parts snap together
in ball-and-socket arrangements fashioned after the plastic models
used to represent the atoms in a molecule.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying guidebook shows how to assemble the Zoob units
into various playful forms: a person, a Tyrannosaurus rex, a
helicopter, even a crown that looks like one of Harold Edgerton's
milk-drop photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Building the larger constructions takes some work. Fortunately,
the instructions are straightforward and the design of the zoobs is
inherently forgiving.
</P>
<P>
   In a lighter vein, Draganfly Innovations has brought to our
planet the Remote Controlled Flying Saucer ($87, 800-979-9794). The
saucer is a two-foot-wide silver Mylar balloon that must be filled
with helium. A dual-fan propulsion unit and ballast putty attach to
the balloon's underside.
</P>
<P>
   Using the remote control, you can make the saucer turn, go
forward, and ascend and descend (a breeze could quickly whisk it
away, so this toy must stay indoors).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UPDATING THE CLASSICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some seemingly immortal toys have recently taken on new guises.
Take the Frisbee, whose simple shape might seem immune to
modernizing. Guess again. Chuck Hoberman, the man who brought you
the expandable Hoberman sphere, now unveils the Pocket Flight Ring
($9.95, Hoberman Designs, 212-647-7656, www.hoberman.com/fold/).
</P>
<P>
   Folded, it is about the diameter of a compact disc and does in
fact fit into a large pants pocket; open it and it more than
doubles in size. Then pop it flat and _ voila _ you've got a decent
throwing ring.
</P>
<P>
   Does your kid have what it takes to strike out the likes of
Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire? He or she can find out by winding up
with the Radar Ball ($39, Rawlings, 800-729-5464,
www.rawlings.com), a softball with an electronic brain.
</P>
<P>
   A radar gun buried inside the ball measures the speed of a pitch
and indicates the results on a tiny built-in lcd screen. Serious
pitches are required to activate the circuitry, and beware: the
Radar Ball is designed for pitching only, not hitting.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO BATTERIES REQUIRED &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alternative-energy toys eliminate the dreary holiday ritual of
running to the store to find batteries for the idle gadgets lying
amid the wrapping paper. They can also address more serious issues.
Trevor Baylis, a British inventor, hit on the idea of a windup
radio to improve communications in parts of Africa where
electricity and batteries are unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting Freeplay radio ($79.95, BayGen, 914-258-5660,
www.freeplay.net) is built in a South African factory that employs
disabled persons. A full crank provides about one hour of playing
time. Outdoors, a solar panel molded into the radio's case
generates supplemental power. A single large speaker produces fine
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Another way to do without batteries is to make your own. The
Fruit Powered Clock ($13, Schylling, 800-541-2929,
www.schylling.com) and the Two Potato Clock ($17.95, Skilcraft,
available through Edmund Scientific, 800-728-6999) use copper and
zinc electrodes to transform various fruits and vegetables into
low-voltage power supplies, sufficient to run these small LCD
clocks.
</P>
<P>
   The Fruit Powered Clock has the more dramatic look and comes
with a proper scientific explanation of how it works. The Two
Potato Clock, on the other hand, is a more reliable timepiece in
our experience, and less likely to deposit bits of rotting apple on
your coffee table.
</P>
<P>
   Happy shopping!
</P>
<P>
   _______ &QC; 
