<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Monday, Dec. 7, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPACE-STATION (San Francisco) _ The International Space Station,
soon to undergo construction 285 miles above Earth, faces enough
hazards to fill a stack of paperback science fiction thrillers.
Fires, explosions, solar flares, power failures and collisions with
space debris could threaten the station _ history's grandest
construction project and humanity's first stepping stone to Mars
and worlds beyond. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   JFK-TEXAS (Washington) _ A year before his Nov. 22, 1963,
assassination in Dallas, President John F. Kennedy chatted on the
telephone with Texas Gov. John Connally about the hostile political
situation he faced there. ``I don't know why we do anything for
Dallas,'' JFK said after reviewing the midterm election results of
the day before. By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS.
</P>
<P>
   JFK-NIXON (Washington) _ In a taped 1962 telephone conversation
between then-California Gov. Edmund G. ``Pat'' Brown and President
John F. Kennedy, the two discussed the mental stability of Richard
Nixon, the man they had both defeated in back-to-back elections.
``You reduced him to the nut house,'' the 35th president said of
Nixon. By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOT-TOYS (San Francisco) _ Nearly every Christmas season one toy
is somehow decreed IT. Lines form, parents foam, the stores run
out. But the runs on Furbys or Tickle Me Elmos or Cabbage Patch
dolls aren't born, they are made. By DIANA WALSH.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL-SHOPPER (San Francisco) _ As the holiday shopping
season heats up, things get a little surreal for personal shopper
Jane Matsui. Part shopper, part image consultant, part gofer, part
therapist, Matsui shops for people who have more money than time.
By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPER-TIPS (San Francisco) _ Jane Matsui's advice.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-COMMERCE (San Francisco) _ If you want to shop at
www.macys.com instead of trudging down to the mall, don't bother
looking for Levi's jeans or its Dockers brand _ you won't find
them. Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., which started selling Levi's and Dockers
on its Web sites, won't allow Macy's _ or any other retailer _ to
sell Levi's or Dockers on-line. The company wants its cyberstores
to be the only place to buy Levi merchandise on-line. By VICTORIA
COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ During the holidays, rosemary
topiaries are popular miniature Christmas trees. These topiaries
can be displayed at the front door or used indoors as centerpieces,
by stairways or in kitchen windows. Simply snip to keep the conical
shape, and use trimmings in holiday dishes. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-CAMELLIAS (Undated) _ Camellias provide welcome winter
color, in shades ranging from white to red. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-CENTERPIECE (Undated) _ Centerpiece. Just the word
sounds so intimidating, so grand. But the dictionary puts a
manageable handle on it: an ornament, bowl of flowers, etc. for the
center of a table. It's as if Webster is saying, ``Don't be afraid.
You can do it.'' That's the message from designer Debbie Mumm,
whose line of Mummford holiday products are available in Mervyn's
California stores nationwide. By MADELEINE McDERMOTT HAMM.
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAY-BOOKS (Undated) _ A look at gift books for the holiday
season in all areas of interest _ sports, fashion, history and art.
By FRITZ LANHAM.
</P>
<P>
   BRASSAI-PHOTO (Houston) _ The Museum of Fine Art's Anne Tucker
has created a celebratory exhibition of the Hungarian master
photographer Brassai on the 100th anniversary of his birth. After
Houston, the show travels to the Getty Museum in Los Angeles and
the National Gallery of Art in Washington. By PATRICIA JOHNSON.
</P>
<P>
   ADVENT (Albany, N.Y.) _ Nathan Ferretti, an agile 2-year-old,
leans across the dining table to touch the carved wooden cross on
the Advent wreath as his parents, Lisa and David, gather their five
children for their evening Advent celebration. They exemplify the
families and churches returning to the traditional Advent season as
a time of preparation for Christmas, and the start of a sacred
season beyond the glare of the holiday's flashier lights. By GINGER
BRISTOW.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-CRITIC (New York) _ He's the scholar and the sage;
I'm the guy with the notebook. But despite Harold Bloom's lofty
status as a preeminent literary critic and aesthete, it feels like
I'm in the position of authority. Bloom can talk at length of
Shakespeare, and when he does, it's like a priest speaking of God.
He recently published his 23rd book, ``Shakespeare: The Invention
of the Human'' (Riverhead). By MICHAEL MALONE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Readers of the San Francisco
Examiner received 7,510 free tickets to the San Francisco Sports &AMP;
Boat Show last year, and 86 received prizes. For doing what? For
just trying to answer the questions in my annual quiz, and last
year 86 had all 10 right, the most in the past 10 years. Here are
this year's questions. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-HAWAII (Hawaii) _ A photographer discovers the diversity
of Hawaii's Big Island. By SMILEY N. POOL.
</P>
<P>
   With: SIDEBAR-HAWAII
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Here's all you need to know about
Microsoft: The company calls its line of high-tech toys ``learning
systems.'' ``Go to your room and interact with your learning
systems.'' It doesn't sound right, unless you're talking to Bill
Gates. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Mike Espy last week was
exonerated of criminal charges of corruption by a jury in federal
court, which the former Secretary of Agricultural naturally hailed
as a vindication of himself and a tacit endorsement of his behavior
while in office. Not quite. But Mike Espy's conduct in office
hardly qualifies him as a paragon of a worthy public servant. By
HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
</TEXT>
