<HEADER>
A6362 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-bettergas?-HNS &LR;      12-07 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-better </SLUG>
 gas?-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gas
</P>
<P>
   National debate on gasoline additive spills into Texas
</P>
<P>
   By BILL DAWSON &QL; 
Houston Chronicle Environment Writer
</P>
<P>
   A common gasoline additive is at the center of a national
controversy now spilling into Texas, where officials are
considering a mandate that could increase its use across the
eastern third of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The complex debate, mixing an inter-industry squabble with
concerns about both air and water pollution, typifies the tough
trade-off decisions that often confront environmental
policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical in question, usually known by the abbreviated name
MTBE, started being used in gasoline in the late 1970s as an octane
booster to replace lead.
</P>
<P>
   As a method for reducing vehicle emissions of smog-forming and
other air pollutants, more MTBE has been added in recent years to
gasoline sold in some areas with particularly bad air quality
problems, including Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   MTBE, however, is the focus of a growing outcry in parts of the
country _ mainly California and the Northeast so far _ because it
has contaminated some sources of drinking water there.
</P>
<P>
   The chemical dissolves readily in water, adding a foul taste and
odor at very low concentrations. At higher but still minute
concentrations in water, federal officials regard it as a
``possible'' cancer-causing agent.
</P>
<P>
   Texas officials are scheduled on Dec. 16 to begin considering a
rule ordering the sale of cleaner-burning gasoline in a wide region
including San Antonio, Austin, Corpus Christi and East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   As drafted, the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission's
new gasoline rule for that area would not require MTBE, but it
would allow refiners to use it to meet emission-limiting
specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires an oxygen-adding chemical in the even
lower-emission ``reformulated gasoline,'' or RFG, sold in the
Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth areas, and in other cities around the
country. MTBE, mainly manufactured in Texas, is the most widely
used oxygenate in RFG.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990 Clean Air Act required the sale of RFG in the Houston
area; that started in 1995. Dallas-Fort Worth, with a less severe
smog problem, chose to join the program.
</P>
<P>
   The TNRCC's initiative for cleaner-burning gasoline in a wider
area of Texas is part of its regional clean air strategy, partly
intended to help Houston and Dallas-Fort Worth comply with the
national health standard for ground-level ozone smog, which they
now violate. Another aim is to keep near-violation areas such as
Austin, San Antonio and Longview-Tyler-Marshall from slipping into
violation status.
</P>
<P>
   After the state agency announced early this year that it might
decide to order oxygenate-containing RFG in that region, a
coalition was formed in response. Its members included MTBE
manufacturers, some local officials such as Harris County Judge
Robert Eckels and some environmental group leaders. It initially
supported RFG, but later voiced only generally worded support for
``cleaner-burning fuels in East Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposing it was the state's leading oil industry group, the
Texas Oil and Gas Association, which calls instead for lower-sulfur
gasoline as a way to curb smog-forming exhausts.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrating the dilemma facing the state commission, the mayors
of Longview, Tyler and Marshall last week jointly called for the
TNRCC to ban MTBE outright in any new requirement for
cleaner-burning gasoline in the region.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the three TNRCC commissioners, the mayors said
they have ``grave concerns'' about the ``disastrous consequences
for drinking water supplies'' should MTBE use be increased in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also want to assure you of our willingness to work with you
to achieve air quality goals,'' the mayors wrote. ``However, we
cannot support a strategy that seeks to achieve a short-term air
quality benefit at the risk of creating a long-term water quality
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter echoed recent developments in other parts of the
country indicating growing opposition to MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Maine became the first state, among such areas that
had joined the RFG program voluntarily, to opt out of it. A state
study had found trace levels of MTBE in 15 percent of drinking
water supplies, and officials said they would move to replace RFG
with a different, lowered-emission gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   In California, where federal law requires RFG, a bill to allow a
gasoline blend without MTBE has strong support in the congressional
delegation. Last month, a university study commissioned by state
officials concluded that MTBE was not needed to achieve clean air
goals in the state _ where the nation's worst smog levels are
routinely recorded in Los Angeles _ and the additive poses
``significant risks and costs associated with water
contamination.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to such developments, the head of the U.S.
Environmental Protection Agency, Carol Browner, announced last week
that she was appointing a ``blue-ribbon panel'' to review the use
of MTBE and other oxygenates in gasoline and report on ``how to
ensure public health protection and continued improvement in both
air and water quality.''
</P>
<P>
   TNRCC Chairman Barry McBee said last week that he and his fellow
commissioners were ``very cognizant'' of the MTBE issue in
September when they ordered the agency staff to develop a rule that
would allow, but not require, the additive.
</P>
<P>
   McBee, who will leave the TNRCC shortly to head Lt. Gov.-elect
Rick Perry's staff, said he does not think there yet is enough
evidence to begin a serious discussion of banning MTBE in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, studies to date have not indicated any widespread
contamination of water supplies by the chemical, despite its
longstanding production and broad use in Texas, as well as the
documented presence in the state of more than 21,000 leaking
storage tanks for petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
   Such leaking tanks are widely regarded as the major potential
source of MTBE in water, and a pro-MTBE trade group, the Oxygenated
Fuels Association, has argued that fixing tank leaks, instead of
banning MTBE, is the best approach to safeguard drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   TNRCC officials began requiring water suppliers to start testing
for MTBE four years ago. To date, only 11 public and private
systems, out of hundreds in the state, have detected MTBE, mainly
at levels below the EPA's recommended limit for avoiding taste and
odor problems.
</P>
<P>
   The largest water system to discover the chemical in its
drinking water is the city of Dalhart, which serves a municipal
population of about 6,700. Officials shut down an affected well
after the finding.
</P>
<P>
   In the Houston area, two industrial wells and one municipal
utility district have found extremely low levels of MTBE, according
to the TNRCC. The city of Houston checked for MTBE most recently
this spring without detecting any amount of the chemical in water
from either underground or surface sources, a municipal official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two possible reasons that drinking water in Texas has remained
virtually free of the chemical is the depth of underground sources
of drinking water, which are situated below shallower aquifers and
protective layers of clay, and the protection afforded by
well-cased wells, TNRCC toxicologist Michael Honeycutt said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether refiners would make greater use of MTBE in the eastern
part of the state if the TNRCC adopts its draft rule for gasoline
in that region is a subject of dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The three East Texas mayors said in their letter to the TNRCC
that local refiners have told them that MTBE use is ``the most
likely scenario'' for meeting those requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Greenwood, director of government affairs for Valero Energy,
an oil refiner and major MTBE manufacturer with plants in the
Houston and Corpus Christi areas, said some companies such as his
might choose to use MTBE to meet the mandate. But he said he doubts
that a new rule would produce much more demand for the additive
among other gasoline producers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing debate, MTBE still has defenders who point
out that it has cut air pollution while replacing more toxic
alternatives, such as the cancer-causing benzene, in gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the two national organizations representing local and
state air quality officials have voiced such arguments in
advocating the right of areas not required by law to use RFG to
join that fuel program, as Dallas-Fort Worth did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
