<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPOSITIONING `IRON FELIX' 7 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If you had to pick three events that symbolized
Russia's democratic revolution in August 1991, they would most
probably be 1) people putting up barricades made of buses to defend
against tanks sent into Moscow by hard-line coup plotters; 2) Boris
Yeltsin addressing supporters from atop a tank whose troops
switched sides; 3) jubilant crowds watching as a crane took down
the towering statue of Felix Dzerzhinsky, founder of the ruthless
and ubiquitous Soviet secret police.
</P>
<P>
   The coup plotters were defeated, and Russian communism hit rock
bottom. Yeltsin went on to the Kremlin, where he promised to bring
the rule of law and a market economy to Russia. One of the buses,
crumpled from a collision with a tank, went on display outside a
museum on one of central Moscow's main streets.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dzerzhinsky statue was sent off to a dumping ground for
old, unwanted monuments of discredited Soviet leaders. ``Iron
Felix's'' place in front of the KGB headquarters was occupied by a
modest monument to the millions of victims of Soviet political
purges.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone wondering about how the events of August 1991 are seen in
Russia today could do worse than to might look at what is happening
to those symbols of Russian democracy now.
</P>
<P>
   We all know about Yeltsin, the sick man of Russia's corrupt and
feckless government.
</P>
<P>
   The bus rusted away until people started to complain that it was
an eyesore amid the high-rent storefronts on Tverskaya Street. A
few months ago, it was moved to a courtyard where it can rot out of
sight.
</P>
<P>
   And if Russia's Communist-dominated lower house of parliament,
the State Duma, has its way, Dzerzhinsky is headed back to his old
spot in front of the building on Lubyanka Square now occupied by
the KGB's successor, the FSB.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Duma's 256-102 vote Friday in favor of restoring the statue
occurred at a time of heightened public criticism of Russia's seven
post-Soviet years. The farther you get from Moscow, the easier it
is to find people who think things were not so bad, or at least not
this bad, back in the USSR.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Moscow, there are few symbols of the democratic era,
just lots of statues of Vladimir I. Lenin that no one ever got
around to taking down. Now, even Lenins are going back up. A new
one was unveiled near the Arctic port of Murmansk last week.
</P>
<P>
   The wave of nostalgia for a system that killed millions of
citizens in purges and concentration camps may seem strange.
Execution sites and mass graves are still being found.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia has never fully grappled with its Soviet past. The
KGB was never disbanded or seriously reformed, just downsized,
renamed, and told to not arrest political prisoners. FSB leaders
worked in the old, repressive structure. Its archives, detailing
countless crimes against the people, are still secret.
</P>
<P>
   Each Nov. 7, when thousands across Russia celebrate the
anniversary of the Bolsheviks' takeover, some carry portraits of
Josef Stalin, whose 30-year reign of terror claimed at least 20
million lives.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has another day to commemorate victims of the purges. But
only a few hundred people gather at the memorial on Lubyanka, one
of only a handful of such monuments in the country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One cause of the apathy is related to the reason the Duma wants
to put Iron Felix back. The terror Russians once felt that one
night agents might come knocking at the door is long gone. It has
been replaced by the fear of mafia shakedowns, remote-control car
bombs, and nighttime shootings in apartment stairwells, like last
month's murder of a prominent lawmaker, Galina Starovoitova.
</P>
<P>
   ``Replacing the statue will reassure the nation that the Russian
government is dedicated to the ongoing struggle against crime,''
said Duma member Nikolai Kharitonov.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the Duma's communists, playing on the public's new
fear, put through a motion that also helps them forget their lowest
moment in August 1991.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Filipov is chief of the Globe's Moscow bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
