<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-JUDICIARY-BOS &LR;      12-07 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-JUDICIARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDICIARY PANEL'S GOP DEFYING PARTY LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The math is elementary: All Bill Clinton needs to
end the impeachment odyssey is for three of the 21 Republicans on
the House Judiciary Committee to join the panel's 16 Democrats this
week in voting against charges that could end his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, it will never happen.
</P>
<P>
   In a quirk of congressional destiny, nearly all the 21
Republicans who control Clinton's immediate fate dwell to the right
of the political mainstream, representing highly conservative
districts where anti-Clinton sentiment runs deep.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans see the polls that show an overwhelming
majority of the public opposes Clinton's impeachment. But they hear
something starkly different in their districts, many of which span
the Bible Belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, the people in my district don't feel like the
polls say what they should,'' said Representative Howard Coble of
North Carolina, echoing his GOP colleagues on the committee. ``I
think impeachment is our best course.''
</P>
<P>
   So, for the first time in a generation and only the third time
in history, the Judiciary Committee is poised to recommend that the
House impeach a sitting president, where Clinton would face a trial
that could remove him from office. The House committee is
tentatively scheduled to debate and vote on proposed articles of
impeachment on Thursday, Friday, and possibly Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A request by Clinton's lawyers to lengthen their presentation to
the committee this week from one day to three or four days raised
the possibility of delaying the final committee vote. But the
Judiciary Committee chairman, Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, says he
will ``make a sincere effort to accommodate this last-minute
request'' without affecting the Saturday deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fully intend for the committee to discharge its
constitutional duties in this inquiry by the conclusion of next
week,'' Hyde said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   From the tobacco fields of Coble's district in central North
Carolina to Simi Valley in Representative Elton Gallegly's base in
Southern California, the committee Republicans sense little
resistance as they prepare to approve at least one charge of
perjury against Clinton for allegedly trying to cover up his sexual
affair with the former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And they fear no backlash. In the midterm elections that were
held last month amid the impeachment inquiry, every GOP member of
the committee who sought re-election succeeded, and they won an
average of 74 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Even Representative Lindsey O. Graham of South Carolina, one of
the panel's more flexible conservatives, said his constituents
harbor ``no shortage of outrage over the president's conduct in
terms of him losing his job.''
</P>
<P>
   With their solid bases and shared ideology, the GOP members have
formed an impenetrable front. Despite Republican election losses,
the dumping of House Speaker Newt Gingrich, and pressure from some
moderate GOP lawmakers for punishment short of impeachment, there
is no indication that a substantial number of GOP panel members
will oppose any proposed article of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, seven committee Republicans joined Democrats in
1974 in voting for some or all of three articles of impeachment
against President Richard M. Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the Republicans on the committee, their political base
is the far right of the Republican Party,'' said Representative
Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat on the panel. ``I've
felt since Day 1 there was no chance that any of them would vote
for anything other than impeaching the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the mix of blacks, Jews, and women among the 16 Democrats
on the panel, the GOP lawmakers all are white Christian men, except
for Representative Mary Bono of California, who replaced her late
husband, Sonny Bono, on the commmittee after he died in a skiing
accident. Only one GOP member is from the Northeast: Representative
George W. Gekas of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not Frank Sargent or Bill Weld Republicans,'' said
Steve Schwadron, chief of staff to Representative William D.
Delahunt, a Massachusetts Democrat serving his first term on the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   As examples of their conservative leanings:
</P>
<P>
   --Representative Bill McCollum of Florida has led every fight in
the House against the Brady gun-control bill.
</P>
<P>
   --Represenatative Charles T. Canady of Florida has led efforts
to ban race and gender preferences in federal hiring, prohibit
late-term abortions, and formally adopt English as the nation's
official language.
</P>
<P>
   --Representative Lamar S. Smith of Texas was the only lawmaker
on an eight-member House committee last year to vote against
reprimanding Gingrich and fining him $300,000 for ethics
violations.
</P>
<P>
   --Hyde, the chairman, has compiled a conservative legacy over 24
years that includes the so-called Hyde amendment, which has banned
federal funding of abortions for Medicaid patients since 1978.
</P>
<P>
   With the committee's top Democrats as far to the political left
as Republicans are to the right, the panel was considered the most
polarized in Congress even before the impeachment proceedings
began.
</P>
<P>
   For every liberal Democrat such as Representative Barney Frank
of Massachusetts, there is a GOP conservative such as McCollum or
Representative Bob Barr of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Barr, who began calling for impeachment hearings long before the
Lewinsky scandal, clashed last week with two Harvard law
professors, Alan M. Dershowitz and A. Leon Higginbotham Jr., after
a battery of legal scholars told the committee that Clinton's
actions, while possibly criminal, were not impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   In an exchange that epitomized differences between the
committee's partisan factions, Barr said ``the real America,''
which he described as ``unlike some of our law professors here
today,'' agrees with his position that Clinton should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz, who is Jewish, said Barr's reference to ``real
Americans'' was a code word for ``racism'' and ``bigotry.''
</P>
<P>
   And Higginbotham, a retired federal appellate judge who is
black, told Barr: ``My father was a laborer. My mother was a
domestic. I climbed the ladder, and I did not come to where I am
through some magical band. So I am willing to match you any hour
any day in terms of the perception of the real American.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank, who has stuck bipartisan deals in the committee over
issues such as intellectual property rights, argued later that Barr
is not typical of the committee's GOP majority. ``I wouldn't defame
the Republicans by raising him as representative,'' Frank said.
``He's kind of a strange guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Frank was not entirely conciliatory. ``I thought from the
start they would be for impeachment,'' he said of the committee
Republicans. ``But I underestimated the right wing's ability to
keep them from behaving rationally.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank was referring to moves in recent weeks to expand the
inquiry into seveal areas beyond the Lewinsky matter, which also
irked some moderate Republicans who do not sit on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Graham defended the committee's actions, saying the Republicans
are keeping faith with their constitutional duty rather than their
constituents' outrage toward Clinton. ``I want to a be a good
congressman who, 30 years from now, not just 30 days from now,
people thought did the right thing,'' he said. ``And the right
thing is to take this seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
