<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6496 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-07 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCKING BUREAUCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What would it take it prove your existence?
</P>
<P>
   For Martha Ghosen Goose, it took five months, 126 telephone
calls, 63 letters, a dozen faxes, the determination of her
75-year-old employer, and the intervention of a congressman and the
Bureau of Indian Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the bureaucrats in the passport office in Boston
finally acknowledged what the 56-year-old member of the Seneca
Nation has been telling them since July: She is an American.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,000 spent for phone calls, postage, administrative fees,
and legal advice to prove the obvious is incidental to the
emotional toll exacted on an elderly couple and a Native American
woman who was forced, in her words, ``to dig up the dead just to
prove I am alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha Goose's saga began simply enough last summer with the
desire of a devoted husband to give his ailing wife the trip of her
dreams. Mary and Edward Perry of Stow had spent much of their life
together under sail, over the years navigating 90,000 miles on a
40-foot sailboat. All that ended two years ago, when Mary, now 75,
suffered a paralyzing stroke that left her in need of constant
care. Goose is her nurse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't ones for cruising, but now that would be the only
way for Mary to get back on the water,'' says Edward Perry, the
still vigorous half of the sailing duo, who surprised his wife and
her nurse with two tickets for a cruise in January from Florida,
around the Caribbean, along the coast of South America, and through
the Panama Canal to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Securing a passport for his wife's caregiver seemed a
straightforward enough proposition at the start. Goose had no birth
certificate, but her driver's license, her Social Security card,
her marriage certificate, her two children's birth certificates,
and her Seneca Nation identification card all listed her date and
place of birth, Buffalo, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Not good enough, said the bureaucrats. ``All the documents
submitted were issued after your 20th birthday, and the information
regarding your place of birth was supplied by you,'' reads an Oct.
8 letter to Goose from the passport agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``First I don't exist, and then I am a liar'' is how Goose says
she read that letter, which insisted upon a record of her birth.
</P>
<P>
   That was not an easy, or painless, order to fill. Goose had been
abandoned at birth and adopted by relatives, who soon returned her
to the care of a grandmother on the Cattaraugus Indian Reservation
in Erie County, N.Y. The hospital where she was born is closed, its
records lost; her biological and adoptive parents and her
grandmother are all dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Vital Records Bureau for the state of New York sent the
passport agency a letter stating it had no record of Martha's
birth. But a 93-year-old aunt sent a sworn handwritten affidavit,
noting her presence at St. Mary's Hospital when Martha was born to
her sister, Albertine, and Thomas Ghosen. Goose and Perry even
tracked down one of her teachers from the reservation school.
</P>
<P>
   Not good enough, said the bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It now appears that each and every time I send some document
along to your office, I receive a reply asking for yet another,''
Goose wrote in exasperation Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   After dozens more letters and telephone calls, Goose wrote again
to the passport agency on Oct. 21, enclosing grammar school records
from the Buffalo school system, documenting her transfer from the
Indian school to the public school when she was 13.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no passport.
</P>
<P>
   The understandable mistake of Perry and Goose was thinking that
government bureaucracy responds to logic and common sense. But what
it does respond to is political pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Only after US Representative Martin Meehan notified the Bureau
of Indian Affairs of the obstacles being placed in Goose's path did
Edward Perry began to think that maybe his wife and her nurse would
get to take their cruise, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know which was worse,'' says Perry, ``the idea of
disappointing my wife or seeing poor Martha crying every time she
had a conversation with that awful woman from the passport
agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Goose describes the bureaucrat as ``a woman with charcoal in her
blood.'' But a conference call with the recalcitrant bureaucrat,
the congressman, and an incensed representative of the Office of
Tribal Services in the Bureau of Indian Affairs broke the logjam.
</P>
<P>
   Goose's passport arrived last week. The cruise ship leaves Fort
Lauderdale Jan. 20.
</P>
<P>
   (Eileen McNamara is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
