A6497 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-REFORM-BOS &LR;      12-07 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-REFORM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADA TORIES HOPE TO ASCEND WITH REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA _ Once there was a political powerhouse in Canada called
the Conservative Party. It won elections, produced prime ministers,
set national agendas.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the tattered Tories hold just 19 of the 301 seats in
Canada's House of Commons. The party is the smallest and least
consequential of the five in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But now there is a serious movement afoot to fuse the
once-mighty Conservatives with the upstart, Western-based Reform
Party, a marriage of convenience that supporters hope will produce
Canada's first formidable party of the right.
</P>
<P>
   The effort arises as Canada courses toward the 21st century,
essentially as a one-party state. The Liberal party is the
governing party and seems likely to remain the governing party for
decades to come, since it no longer faces any real rival for power.
</P>
<P>
   There are opposition parties, of course, but they are too
regional or too ideologically extreme to attract a wide spectrum of
voters from Newfoundland to British Columbia. No party except the
Liberals has a broad national base.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal majority in Commons may be slim, 156 of 301 seats.
But the second-largest party, Reform, holds only 59 seats. The
third largest party is the separatist Bloc Quebecois, which has 45
members in Parliament but no support beyond the restive
French-speaking province.
</P>
<P>
   Even the far-left New Democratic Party carries more
parliamentary heft than the Conservatives, with 21 seats. And yet,
there is talk of a Conservative comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to be done to unite the right,'' said Alberta's
premier, Ralph Klein, one of Canada's few remaining high-profile
Conservative Party leaders. ``If we don't, none of us will ever
live long enough to see anything other than a Liberal government
governing Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein, whose tight-fisted policies have made Alberta a byword
for lean government, startled observers last month by agreeing to
preside over a controversial ``united conservative alternative''
convention to be held by members of the Reform Party and
Conservatives next February.
</P>
<P>
   The convention represents the first major step in the merger of
parties whose members tend to regard each other with far more
suspicion and loathing than they usually muster for the Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   For in politics, as in love, nothing is more bitter than a
breakup. And the Reform Party is the product of divorce, founded
earlier this decade by breakaway Conservatives convinced that
Canada's grand old party had become too spendthrift, too prone to
leftist social agendas, too felicitous of minorities and, above
all, too willing to make constitutional compromises in order to
keep Quebec separatists in the federal fold.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who couldn't stay together in the first
place,'' said Allan Tupper, professor of political science at the
University of Alberta. ``For many in Reform, Conservatives have
dangerously liberal tendencies. To many traditional Tories, the
Reformers are right-wing zealots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might seem that nothing would be more obvious or natural
than a joining of forces between Reform and the Conservatives,''
Tupper said. ``But the right has never been fertile soil in
Canadian politics. Forming a major conservative bloc will be a very
difficult undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives produced Canada's first prime minister, John A.
Macdonald. When the country was born in 1867, and for 126 years,
the party served as the main political foil to the Liberals, a bit
like Republicans to Democrats in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the elections of 1993, in which Conservatives, after
nearly a decade in power under Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, were
not just defeated but nearly obliterated, and reduced to just two
seats in the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster partly reflected voter discontent with the Mulroney
government, widely perceived as corrupt, callous and, worst of all,
cravenly toadying to the United States. But a deeper problem was
that Liberals and Conservatives had become indistinguishable. Both
were committed to keeping Canada a social welfare state like the
nations of Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate Tory supporters switched in droves to the Liberal
Party, which is basically Canada's party of the middle, while
hard-core conservatives bolted to create the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Popular in Alberta, British Columbia and Saskatchewan but unable
to entice voters anywhere else, Reform is Canada's closest
equivalent to an American-style right-wing movement with its blend
of conservative Christian moralizing and strident attacks on big
government. It opposes abortion, gay marriages, increased immigrant
quotas, and, above all, the granting of special constitutional
status to Quebec, which many Canadians believe is the only way to
keep the province from seceding.
</P>
<P>
   Reform is led by Preston Manning, a polarizing politician whom
people either adore or detest. Voters in the Canadian Rockies and
the prairie provinces mostly fall into the first camp. Voters in
Ontario, Quebec, and the Maritimes seem almost universally put off
by his preachy, hectoring style.
</P>
<P>
   Manning is a pragmatist who recognizes that Reform will never
break from its regional base to become a major national force
without the Conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sincere attempt to build a movement that can lead
the country,'' he said recently, pressing for a united right front
against the Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Conservative Party is at once suffering from an
identity crisis and an almost total lack of national leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Until eight months ago, the party boasted at least one precious
political asset in the form of its boss _ a vigorous, eloquent and
highly visible Quebecer named Jean Charest, popular from
Newfoundland to British Columbia. Charest's charisma is widely
credited for the Conservatives' ability to crawl back from the 1993
debacle and regain ``major party'' status, which requires 10 seats.
</P>
<P>
   But Charest stunned Conservatives in April by quitting to join
the Liberals in a high-risk effort to unseat separatist Lucien
Bouchard as premier of Quebec. He failed in that mission, losing
the Nov. 30 vote to the separatists, but is expected to remain in
Quebec as head of the Liberal Party in order to wage a long-term
campaign against the secessionist movement.
</P>
<P>
   In a Conservative Party convention last month that drew mostly
yawns and derision, the Tories tapped former prime minister Joe
Clark as their new leader. The 59-year-old Albertan headed a
lackluster national government for a few months in 1979-80, and has
been seldom heard from since. It is as if US Republicans tried to
project a bold new image by recalling Gerald Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beyond being a nostalgia candidate, I don't see the electoral
appeal of this particular product,'' said Darrell Bricker,
executive vice president of the Angus Reid Group, a polling firm.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and his moderate-to-liberal-leaning ``Red Tory''
supporters adamantly oppose joining forces with the Reform Party,
which many Conservative loyalists see as a dangerous group of
right-wing renegades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conservatives, before they consider any united alternative,
will want to hear a different speech from the Reform Party
regarding homosexuals, visible minorities, and Quebec,'' said
Senator Pierre-Claude Nolin, a powerful Tory. ``I have some
profound problems with their positions on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Alberta Premier Klein and other Conservatives believe
drastic measures are necessary if the party is to be salvaged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
