<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS LAGS WAY BEHIND ON WELFARE REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On their recent co-jaunt to Israel, I am willing to bet Paul
Cellucci and President-in-waiting George W. Bush did not discuss
one fact that underlines the backward character of Massachusetts
these days.
</P>
<P>
   It concerns welfare, and the gulf between Massachusetts and many
other states as well as Uncle Sam on the vital subject of making
welfare reform work, not merely to ride out a solid economy and
Draconian rules that slash the rolls, but to make better lives
possible for former recipients of cash assistance and their young
children.
</P>
<P>
   In the all-important area of state effort to assist the
transition from welfare to full-time training and work, Texas under
Bush had received some $76 million from the federal government as
of Labor Day. Significantly, it was putting up half again as much
of its own money to fund the aglomeration of school, job-training,
transportation help, child care, and job placement services that
constitute real welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   By embarrassing contrast, the $20 million Massachusetts has
received is leveraging only a piddling 20 percent effort by the
state, a mere $5 million. And this comparison can be made with many
states, where time limits, the gradual end of cash aid to mothers
with young children, and other steps are being matched by all-out
state efforts to make sure that poor people with huge problems are
not simply dumped.
</P>
<P>
   But our state's record in the 1990s has been marked by an
embarrassing combination of recklessness and indifference. In the
Weld-Cellucci era, aggressive efforts have been made to take
advantage of opportunities spawned here in health care, but the
welfare record stinks. Earlier in the process, there was even an
occasion when the state did not bother applying for some $10
million it could have received to help families ease their
transition to work.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Massachusetts is a benefits-slasher, on the strength of
the economy and its often cruel rules. The state's idea of
``generosity'' was the recent decision to suspend the expiration of
time limits on assistance to the end of the Christmas holidays.
These non-actions miss the central point that with exceptions too
miniscule to mention, there is no mother on welfare who wants that
life, who won't respond in an instant to a set of real opporunities
for life in the workforce. Many simply need a job, but for tens of
thousands with no skills, with no way to get child or health care
for their kids, the transition threatens to be brutal.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there is a federal government, and a remarkable
network of community and business organization trying to fill some
of the void left by the state's abysmal failings.
</P>
<P>
   No one noticed, but late last month, Senator Edward Kennedy made
sure that a serious chunk of change was provided to _ among others
_ that very network in the Boston area. Out of roughly $4 million,
there will be a marriage between services and education on the one
hand and jobs on the other.
</P>
<P>
   On the services side are Boston's venerable and acclaimed
antipoverty organization, Action for Boston Community Development,
in partnership with Morgan Memorial Goodwill Industries. And on the
jobs side is the Boston Technology Center, where there is some
state involvement, that is going to be target welfare recipients
for high-tech production jobs in Dorchester and South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In securing the money, Kennedy notes that as the rolls are
pared, the people who remain are almost all the toughest to train,
the least educated, and the least work-experienced. Getting such
casualties of lousy education and family catastrophes into position
to work is hard enough, but there also have to be jobs that can
actually support a struggling family. And all of this takes serious
investments of professional time and public money.
</P>
<P>
   It is being done, to an extent anyway, nationally via $250
million in welfare-to-work grants as well as via President
Clinton's private sector jobs crusade. And it is being done
vigorously in numerous states with Republican governors _ from
Bush's Texas to Tom Ridge's Pennsylvania to Tommy Thompson's
Wisconsin, even to David Beasley's South Carolina and Fob James's
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   But Massachusetts lags way behind.
</P>
<P>
   ABCD President Bob Coard said that the expiring time limits in
the state are occurring at a time that makes the affected familes
unusually vulnerable. ``We're talking about something like 100,000
people, including children, who are already at the bottom of the
opportunity pile,'' he said. ``And in addition to this, they are
facing new pressures from housing costs and availability and from
the rising prices of other necessities.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's tireless work has made it possible for groups like
ABCD to make a real difference in filling the void. But the void
will remain and the embarrassing fact is that in welfare reform,
Massachusetts is a follower not a leader.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
