u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOCIAL-DEBATE-BOS &LR;      12-07 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATIZING' SOCIAL SECURITY CAN MEAN MANY THINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the lobbyists who want to make big changes to
Social Security get together, they sometimes try to dream up a new
term for what it is they are trying to do. ``Everyone wants to come
up with a word that means the same thing as `privatization,' but
which isn't such a liability,'' says Marty Regalia, chief economist
for the US Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   It is a big, ominous, and vague word _ but we can expect to hear
a lot more about privatization in the next few days. On Tuesday and
Wednesday, President Clinton and congressional leaders will meet at
the White House to begin working out a plan to stave off financial
problems that might cripple Social Security early in the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   As they struggle toward a solution, many politicians will argue
that Social Security can be saved by some form of privatization.
Others will argue that privatization would completely destroy the
program.
</P>
<P>
   And that should provoke an immediate question from those
watching the debate: What kind of privatization do they mean?
</P>
<P>
   Most often, but not always, privatizers like the Chamber of
Commerce want to give people the right to invest some of their
Social Security taxes in their own private accounts _ accounts
owned by them and not the government. But how would the accounts
work? Would there be limits on how we could use our savings? And
what would happen to people who are already retired?
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone tells me they're in favor of privatization, it
doesn't tell me much until I hear lots and lots of details,'' said
Joseph Quinn, an economics professor at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   If the the politicians remake Social Security, they will be
drawing up a new contract for our financial future, and no one
should sign a contract without reading the fine print. Precision in
language will be important. What follows is a guide to help make
sense of the debate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --When someone supports or attacks privatization, which kind are
they talking about?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To pay for Social Security benefits, the government imposes a
12.4 percent tax on the wages of nearly every worker. The tax is
split evenly between employer and employee.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the tax raises more money than Social Security needs
each year to pay benefits. The surplus money is given to the
Treasury for use in general government, and the Treasury in return
gives the Social Security system bonds that yield about 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When lawmakers talk about privatization, they most often mean
that people should be able to divert some of the 12.4 percent
payroll tax into privately owned, individual accounts in the
worker's own name. In their view, we would become investors instead
of just taxpayers, building individual wealth by buying stocks and
bonds of our own choice.
</P>
<P>
   But lawmakers sometimes use privatization to refer to something
else: allowing the Social Security system itself to buy stocks,
without creating a private account for each worker.
</P>
<P>
   Under this idea, Social Security itself would use tax money to
buy stocks on behalf of the system as a whole. The stocks
presumably would yield more than the 6 percent Treasury bonds _ but
there are no guarantees. If the stocks rise in value, the system
would have more money to spend on benefits for future retirees,
delaying financial problems that are scheduled to hit after the
year 2030. If the stocks fall, the loss would be shared by everyone
together.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --How ``individual'' would the individual accounts be?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under some plans, one person's account could look far different
than another person's.
</P>
<P>
   These plans see Social Security becoming like  &UR; today &LR; 's IRAs, or
individual retirement accounts, where people can buy pretty much
any type of investment they want from whomever they want _ banks,
brokerages, insurance companies, or mutual fund firms.
</P>
<P>
   The drawback, however, is that the government might find it hard
to supervise 148 million accounts spread among thousands of
financial firms, some of which might be pushing risky investments.
That is why some lawmakers favor individual accounts that look like
 &UR; today &LR; 's 401(k) plans, which businesses commonly offer to workers.
</P>
<P>
   In this system, workers would have as few as two or three
investment options, maybe only a single bond fund and a single
stock index fund. The government would choose two or three
investment firms to manage the 148 million accounts, probably
picking ones that offer the lowest management fees.
</P>
<P>
   --Would there be restrictions on using the savings?
</P>
<P>
   Someone who owns a television is free to sell it for cash at any
time, or to give it to the kids. It is unlikely people would
``own'' their Social Security accounts in the same way.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, after all, is to make sure that people save for
retirement _ not for other purposes _ and that people use their
savings to avoid falling into poverty and onto welfare. But those
goals might conflict with giving people full ``ownership'' of their
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   For example, some lawmakers say the system should bar people
from withdrawing money from their accounts until retirement. On the
other hand, how can Congress say no to people who want to use their
savings for current medical or college costs? Lawmakers have
already loosened the rules on the use of IRA and 401(k) money for
medical care, college tuition and home purchases.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear at this point whether ``ownership'' would mean that
people have the right to withdraw all their savings at once on
retirement. Congress might decide that it is better to limit people
to withdrawing only a certain amount each year.
</P>
<P>
   Under some plans, workers are forced to use their accumulated
savings to buy an annuity _ a contract, generally sold by insurance
companies, to pay a person a set amount of money for the rest of
his or her life. This would ensure that a person's retirement
savings produce income until his or her death. But it would also
deprives Americans of a key element of ``ownership'' _ the right to
leave money in the account for their heirs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --How much would a system of private accounts cost?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listen for whether a speaker is talking about private accounts
as a ``carve out'' or as an ``add on.'' In a ``carve out'' plan,
people divert _ or carve out _ a portion of the 12.4 percent Social
Security tax and invest it in their own private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Some people say ``carve out'' plans won't work, because they
divert money that is needed to pay for  &UR; today &LR; 's retirees and for
people who are close to retirement. Some say that private accounts
can be created only as an ``add on'' to the current system. In
other words, workers could start private accounts, but any
contributions would come in addition to paying the current Social
Security tax.
</P>
<P>
   Can we afford to start private accounts while maintaining
benefits for people who are in retirement, or for future retirees?
Some ``carve out'' supporters say that creating private accounts
will require additional taxes to help pay for current retirees, or
that retirees will have to accept benefit cuts. Others say the
transition will not cost much, because the government will have
fewer obligations to workers once they build up sizeable savings in
their private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners will have to decide which group sounds more credible.
And even if there is some pain involved in moving to private
accounts, listeners will have to ask if it is greater than the tax
increases or benefit cuts that might be required to fix Social
Security without creating private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   William Shipman, a principal with State Street Global Advisors
in Boston and a leading proponent of private accounts, compares the
transition to refinancing a home mortgage. Sure, you have to pay
closing costs, attorneys' fees and points, but getting the lower
interest rate means you are better off in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --What happens to the poor and vulnerable?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Social Security has been called the most successful social
program in the country, cutting the poverty rate among seniors
during the past 40 years from 35 percent to 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It has done this because it redistributes wealth: from
high-income to low-income workers, and from single people to
traditional families with stay-at-home moms. It also pays
disability benefits to injured workers and survivor benefits to
workers' families.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see Social Security as a low-risk, low-return
retirement system,'' said Sharon Daly of Catholic Charities USA.
``But really it is a mutual insurance program'' where we insure
each other against death, disability and poverty in old age.
</P>
<P>
   Private account plans might weaken this aspect of the program.
Currently, millions of stay-at-home parents (almost all of them
women) earn retirement benefits merely because they are married to
someone with a paying job. If workers save for their own
retirement, what happens to the mother who never joined the paid
work force?
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Social Security has been a good deal for low-income
workers. Compared to wages they earned when they were working,
low-income retirees get more from Social Security than do their
high-income counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Private accounts could change this feature. If everyone sets
aside 2 percent of wages for retirement, the low-wage worker will
accumulate far less money over a lifetime than would a high-wage
worker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Aaron Zitner is a member of the Globe's Washington bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
