<HEADLINE>
UNDERGROUND MAN AFRAID TO REJOIN SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ Thomas Johnson went underground 10 years ago
to bury his rage against the corporate vipers, clock-punching
consumers, and environmental rapists he saw in society.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, he separated himself from all but a few close
friends, afraid that living in a world he loathed would be
dangerous for him and for the people he encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Eight feet underground, Johnson says, he found a peace in
solitude that had eluded him throughout a tempestuous childhood and
a short-lived but frenzied criminal life.
</P>
<P>
   But now, his home discovered at last, Johnson says he is more
frightened of the future than of anything he has known. And this
man of the earth, as he sees himself, is afraid that rejoining
society may rekindle the rage.
</P>
<P>
   ``God told me it was time to come out of the hole,'' Johnson
said. ``But I don't know if I have the energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his fears, Johnson hopes his reemergence will be a
cathartic opportunity to share his thoughts with a world he sees
rushing pell-mell toward an empty future.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Johnson's neighbors in Nantucket's winter community
seem more inclined to view him as a charming eccentric, rather than
their version of the angry survivalists who take to the land in
more rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   As he fights to keep his underground home, Johnson has become a
local celebrity, the embodiment of the spirit of those who choose
to live year-round on an island.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happiness must be found in the moment, at the moment,''
Johnson said, resting his lanky 6-foot-4 frame against a bunker
wall. ``We must have a sense of rapture.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 38, says he carries that sense of wonder whenever he
walks among the bayberry bushes, scrub oak, blueberries, and scrub
pine of the remote corner of the Boy Scout camp he calls home.
</P>
<P>
   Since the recent discovery of the hideout by a deer hunter who
stumbled on its stovepipe, Johnson's peace has been shattered.
Police have inspected the three-room home. Federal and state agents
have demanded he return hawk talons and owl wings, which are
illegal to possess but which Johnson says were road kill.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Johnson said, a deputy sheriff served him with a 30-day
eviction notice.
</P>
<P>
   The Nantucket health inspector also has scoured the dwelling,
calling it a marvel of craftsmanship but issuing 23 code violations
nonetheless. Richard Ray, the health officer, has cited the Boy
Scouts for having a dwelling on their property that does not meet
state code for human habitation.
</P>
<P>
   The Nantucket district of the Scouts, which had been unaware of
Johnson's home, has until Dec. 23 to resolve the code violations,
which target Johnson's toilet, water, heating, ventilation and
exit, among other complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Graves, chairman of the Nantucket Boy Scout district,
declined to answer questions. Ray said that if the Scouts do not
evict Johnson and the code violations are not addressed, a health
board hearing will be held that could result in an order for
Johnson to vacate.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, for his part, said he is prepared to dig elsewhere on
Nantucket. And Dr. Timothy Lepore, a well-known physician on the
island, has even invited Johnson to dig a home in his backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should be left alone,'' Lepore said. `I don't think
he represents a threat to the community or the environment. If you
want an archetypal, low-impact guy, he's the one.''
</P>
<P>
   Lepore, who treats Johnson for free and receives advice on how
to make arrowheads in return, is concerned about Johnson's ability
to readapt to society.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is frightened of the walls closing in on him, and also
of the inner demons that he says drove him to international drug
smuggling. If he had not withdrawn to his bunker, Johnson believes,
``there was enough rage in me that I could have been a thorn in
society.''
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of that rage germinated in Binghamton, N.Y., where
Johnson says he grew up as one of seven children of a city judge.
``By the time I was 18, I was convinced I'd be the Antichrist,''
Johnson recalled. ``I was an arrogant little S.O.B. I wasn't born
with a silver spoon in my mouth _ I gagged on it.''
</P>
<P>
   For emotional release, Johnson would retreat to the banks of the
Susquehanna River, whose beauty he describes as the defining
influence on his life. Nearby, in Pennsylvania, he built his first
log cabin as a teenager. Alone in the woods, his interest in nature
blossomed with the remarkable outdoor skills and craftsmanship he
taught himself.
</P>
<P>
   He attended community college, but lasted one semester,
scribbling only the words ``When Johnny comes marching home again,
hurrah, hurrah'' on every test and paper he was given.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, at 20 years old, Johnson held his father in his arms
as he died of colon and liver cancer. The family fell apart,
Johnson says, his siblings scattering from the home as he stayed
behind to care for his grieving mother.
</P>
<P>
   About this time, drug use became a sinister, integral part of
his life, growing from mind-altering recreation into an opportunity
for easy but dangerous money. Johnson says he made three trips to
Europe, where he acted as a courier for Thai heroin. On the last
journey, carrying 2 kilograms of heroin stitched in a suitcase,
Johnson says he was met in Rome by machine-gun-toting policemen as
he exited a train from Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-seven days of solitary confinement followed, he says, and
then a seven-year sentence in a Rome prison. There, Johnson says
with a slight smile, he earned a doctorate in human relations from
a global stew of criminals who hated him for his middle-class,
American background.
</P>
<P>
   (Marco Bovo, attached to the Italian consulate in Boston, said
he could not confirm that Johnson had been imprisoned in Italy from
1983-1985 and has asked officials in Rome to check their records.)
</P>
<P>
   After 2 1/2 years in prison, Johnson says, he was released to
house arrest in the countryside. He soon fled Italy, Johnson
continued, and embarked on a three-month spree of check-kiting and
bank fraud before returning home to Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   After an attempt to fashion a mainstream living, even taking
insurance courses, Johnson decided to move to Nantucket, where he
believed the quiet pace would help him write a book about his
prison experience.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after arriving in Nantucket, a radically different Johnson
went underground, building one dwelling that was unearthed during
housing construction and then relocating to the Boy Scout land at
Camp Richard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genie was out of the bottle, and there was no putting it
back in,'' Johnson said. ``I decided to live in a hole in the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Bringing his materials in by hand, digging a hole by shovel, and
keeping the entire enterprise a secret both exhausted and thrilled
Johnson. He alternated his approach to the hideout by using 15
different trails, walking one foot in front of the other to mimic
animal tracks, fashioning shoes that resembled deer hooves to hide
his presence, and confounding deer hunters who tried to use
unauthorized land by plundering their platforms.
</P>
<P>
   He had found the solitude he craved, but the isolation came with
a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``This home cost me nothing to build, but it cost much that's
dear to me to stay here,'' Johnson said. Chief among those
sacrifices has been the love of a woman, he continued, because no
one he has loved has been willing to share life underground.
</P>
<P>
   His health has been taxed, with high stress, joint pain, and a
sciatic nerve problem among Johnson's complaints. Lepore, the
doctor, says Johnson also is at tremendous risk to contract Lyme
disease because of the many deer ticks in the brush surrounding the
home.
</P>
<P>
   With a weary sigh, Johnson says he is unsure if he can withstand
the physical punishment of building another home like this. ``In
some ways, I don't want to pound another nail,'' he confided,
recalling the other underground homes he says he has built in
Pennsylvania, Colorado, and the Catskill Mountains of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson knows he will be a much more visible presence on an
island he loves. And despite the risk of ``becoming a cartoon,''
Johnson said he will spread his message of slowing down,
appreciating nature, and leaving less of a mark upon the earth.
</P>
<P>
   If forced to move, Johnson says, he will build another home. And
with offers like Lepore's, Nantucket's underground man may have
several sites from which to choose.
</P>
<P>
   When asked where Nantucketers should expect him next, Johnson
replied with a smile: ``Coming to a patch of woods near you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
