<HEADLINE>
A YOUNG TAKE ON LOVABLE OLD   MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By M.R. MONTGOMERY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kirk Jones, first-time feature-film writer and director (auteur,
as the snobs used to say), did not set out to make a geezer movie.
But when you come up with two lead actors whose combined age is
over 150 years (but who's counting?), you have not made the
ordinary narcissistic about-my-life First Film.
</P>
<P>
   His comedy ``Waking Ned Devine'' was a quiet smash at Cannes
earlier this year. It is Irish, it is about a wake, but it really
is about the human condition, with an emphasis on the geriatric
imperatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually,'' Jones said, ``I didn't set out to write a movie
about old men.'' The plot revolves around who bought, and who's
going to cash, a winning ticket that's a huge hit on the Irish
National Lottery. ``The lottery idea was the beginning, and it just
made sense for them to be older. That's who buys the tickets. I do
think,'' he added, ``that some of the characteristics of one of my
grandfathers are in the film _ he was a little cheeky, and
mischievous, like Ian and David are.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Ian Bannen, a Scot who plays the first lead, Jackie
O'Shea; and David Kelly, a Dublin native who plays the second lead,
the master scene-stealer Michael O'Sullivan. Bannen is a veteran
stage and screen actor; so is Kelly, but he's something of a
Scarlet Pimpernel, always well disguised. He has never been less
disguised than in ``Ned Devine,'' including a motorcycle ride when
he is in, so to speak, a state of nature. Not only no makeup, no
costume.
</P>
<P>
   Director Jones is a young veteran of the television advertising
business, working out of London. Making the shift from 30-second
ads to 90-minute films was, he allowed, ``relatively easy. This is
simply because I worked so long and so hard on the script that
whenever a question came up, I knew the answer. I could be very
focused and very clear. After all, I'd been living with this for
more than four years and I just flat knew it.''
</P>
<P>
   Living with the script, and almost growing old with it in his
hands, he could have added. No one wanted to finance a film about
two geezers. Jones could have sold it a half-dozen times if only
he'd agreed to make the leads young and sexy. (They're old and
kinda sexy, by the way.) ``When I finally convinced one producer
that it would work with old actors, they got back to me. `Great
idea. Old guys. Now, Jones, all you have to do is change the
location from Ireland to Canada, and we'll get Jack Lemmon and
Matthau.' Well,'' Jones recalled, ``I knew it wasn't `Grumpy Old
Men 3.' And they're not grumpy, they're happy old guys having a
childhood they never had, growing up poor in rural Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sticking wth the script
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones offered that just as every newspaper reporter has a novel
in his or her desk (that's the old days; now it's a novel on his or
her disk), every advertising filmer has a movie script. ``The
mistake they make,'' he said, ``is they have lunch. You know, the
deal lunch. I wrote a script and I stuck with it. I could have sold
the script, but I wanted to direct. I hadn't spent four years just
to hand it over and walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Bannen and Kelly, who came through Boston earlier this fall on a
promotion gig, made nice about Jones without being prodded. Bannen
(like his movie character) did most of the talking and suggested
that they, and the movie, benefited from the ``absolute luxury of
spending two weeks on location before we started to film.'' That
was two weeks of walking through the scenery and the scenes,
talking through the script and the characters with Jones. They did
hit on a concept of their roles that works: Bannen is the
ringleader of this gang of two, Kelly is the comic sidekick. They
stay in character, even when the film approaches deep emotional
levels that might tempt another pair of actors to play for a quick
and cheap catharsis. They both remarked that the touching moments
in the funeral elegy scene (which is not exactly an elegy for Ned
Devine, who is not precisely dead) could have been played with
actors' tears running down their cheeks. ``But,'' as Kelly put it,
using a metaphor from the stage, ``we thought the tears should be
out front. This film required a balance between the emotions, and I
think it balanced out very well.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bannen and Kelly remember the two weeks on the Isle of Man
(an Irish dependency between northern Ireland and Wales) as the
time and place ``where the chemistry got going'' between them,
Jones remembers when and where the chemistry got started between
him and his actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent three days in Dingle, southern Ireland,'' Jones
explained, ``in part to help Ian with his accent. Frankly, I was
pretty nervous approaching these two great actors, and we had a
great time; I think we began to be friends there. We'd go to a pub.
Now, neither Ian or Michael drinks, not a drop, not even a lemonade
if they're in a barroom, and Ian would tape-record people talking.
He'd get some odd looks _ you have to imagine him with this hidden
tape recorder and the microphone under his shirtfront, so he's
going around the bar talking to people and sticking his chest out
so that the microphone would pick up what they were saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself, I would sit there and try to drink enough Guinness to
make up for them, and get quietly drunk, I suppose. But,'' Jones
summed up, ``because of Dingle and the two weeks on Man, where we
cemented the friendship, we started filming with no egos, no
stress. I got everything in just two or three takes, which,
considering the budget, was a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, almost everything. There was the motorcycle problem. It
begins with a skinny-dipping scene and proceeds logically enough
from that state of undress. After remarking on how remarkably cold
that scene was, Bannen felt obliged to say how careful they had all
been to make sure that ``Waking Ned Devine'' didn't end up being
regarded as ``Geezers Drop Trou.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't let them take publicity stills during the
skinny-dipping, or Michael's motorcycle ride. This movie is not a
farce,'' Bannen intoned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bike and the body stocking
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's ride, for plot reasons, requires him to be extremely
afraid about being delayed. Scared to death of being late, you
could say. And his expression, the wide eyes, the clenched jaw, the
fixed smile of desperation, is completely believable.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wasn't acting,'' Jones agreed, ``that was pure terror on
Michael's face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motorbike,'' he explained with enthusiasm, ``is something
new. It's on hydraulics, so it looks like you're really riding it.
And it feels like it. We were filming him in a body stocking,
trying to preserve a little of his dignity, and my cameraman would
say `Great shot, but I can see the stocking.' I did have to ask him
to take it off. He didn't mind at all; he didn't care a whit about
being stark naked if that meant we could finish the scene.''
</P>
<P>
   The one indisputable fact about ``Waking Ned Devine'' is that
the casting is a success. Bannen and Kelly, after untold years in
serious parts and minor roles in thrillers and dramas and even
Modern Existential Theater, are allowed to be very subtly funny.
``This is not a movie about avarice,'' Bannen said firmly. ``In
less sensitive hands, it could have been about the money. But it is
about these two old men. They are old children. They have come at
last, at this point in their lives, to where they can go out and
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly nodded agreement; he and Bannen agreed about everything.
``The nicest thing about our acting that any one said,'' Kelly
offered, ``and it's the nicest that anyone could say, is that it
was one performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy who played Ned Devine wasn't bad, either. You could say
the three of them gave one performance, although Ned Devine, for
most of the movie, is a prop. But that's the way it is when you're
at your own wake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
