<HEADER>
A6517 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-SOLMAN-2TAKES-BOS     12-07 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SOLMAN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SINGULAR SOLMAN 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``You've got to have the matzoh ball soup,'' Joseph
Solman declares. ``It's the best in the city. There's a special
today: You get half a sandwich, too. Go for the pastrami or corned
beef.''
</P>
<P>
   Solman is seated at a table in the Second Avenue Deli. A New
York landmark, the restaurant doubles as an East Village monument
to ethnic chic and the best-known remaining outpost of the old
Lower East Side world of Jewish immigration. It's also just around
the corner from the apartment where Solman and his wife, Ruth, have
lived for the past 46 years.
</P>
<P>
   They just don't make places like this anymore _ the Second
Avenue Deli or New York _ and, at an astonishingly vigorous 89, Joe
Solman is living testimony to that. In everything from his
seltzer-out-of-a-siphon speech to his steadily sturdy percolation,
he conjures up a long-lost Gotham, a lower-slung, higher-minded
city, one of bracing promise as well as brutal reality, the New
York of May Day demonstrations and automats, of the Third Avenue El
and a period when, as Solman recalls, ``all the galleries were on
57th Street . . . and there wasn't room for contemporary American
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, the whereabouts of New York's art galleries
mattered a great deal to a man who has plied the painter's trade
for nearly seven decades. Solman, whose work is held by such
institutions as the Phillips Collection, the British Museum, the
Whitney Museum of American Art, the Corcoran Gallery, and the
Hirshorn Museum, remains very much a part of ``contemporary
American stuff.'' He averages 20 paintings a year, as well as
numerous drawings, monotypes, and gouaches. A selection of his
recent work in all those media, except monotypes, opened Dec. 5 at
the Robert Brown Gallery in Washington, D.C. Starting Saturday,
it's Solman's past that will be showcased, in ``The Ten: Rothko,
Solman and the Birth of the American Avant-garde,'' which runs
through Feb. 20 at the Mercury Gallery at 8 Newbury St. (see box).
</P>
<P>
   His age notwithstanding, Solman is no nostalgist or art-world
fossil. ``When I see something good, I'm still as excited as when I
was young,'' he says. ``You don't see something good every day, but
I still see it.'' He gets on the bus to make his rounds of
galleries and exhibitions and is eager to discuss what's currently
on view. ``I just spent two afternoons looking at shows at
Sotheby's (a wonderful Monet's there) and Christie's (what a
Vuillard they've got!).''
</P>
<P>
   Each of those canvases would go for several million dollars at
auction, yet Solman remembers a day when paintings by the giants of
modern art seemed inducements to revolution (artistic and
otherwise) rather than contributors to eight- or nine-figure
investment portfolios. Certainly, there can't be many other people
alive who attended the inaugural show at New York's Museum of
Modern Art in 1929. ``That was some revelation,'' Solman says. ``I
was still a student at the National Academy of Design. I'd seen
some modern art, but that show was such an eye-opener. Gauguin
especially appealed to me, but also Cezanne, van Gogh. And Seurat:
He looked like a madman to me _ that huge canvas covered with all
those dots! Now I understand. That he should have died at 32 _ what
a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Boredom is something alien to Joe Solman generally, but a
special ebullience and even wonder fill his voice when he recalls
the New York art world of the years before the war. ``It animates
me, the memory of those adventurous days,'' he says. There was ``a
tremendous sense of ferment and excitement at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all in the same boat,'' he explains, ``and it was kind
of a leaky boat. There's no camaraderie anymore. Money makes a big
difference. People think they can make it overnight. Painters seem
to think they'll hit some style and make it'' _ he snaps his
fingers _ ``like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember at a party once, in the early '70s, there was this
well-dressed young man there, a yuppie we'd call him now, I guess,
and we got to talking. `One thing I admire about you guys,' he said
to me, `was you never thought of money.' We sure didn't! We didn't
know you could make any (by) painting.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Artists, photographers, critics
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was an art world in which everyone seemed to know everyone
else, and Solman's friends included Stuart Davis, Willem de
Kooning, and Mark Rothko, fellow member of the art group the Ten
(``He was a figure painter, with some pizazz, influenced by
Picasso, but no one would have dreamt he'd become what he later
did''); the photographers Berenice Abbott and Aaron Siskind; the
critic Meyer Schapiro. While he didn't really know Jackson Pollock,
Solman worked alongside him on a Works Projects Administration
assignment. ``We snuck out for a beer and talked about Henry
Miller. He was a dipsomaniac, you know, and tried to get me to buy
him some more beer. I said no, I have to go home to my wife, and
that was that.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Pollock, or Rothko and de Kooning, Solman never abandoned
representational painting for abstraction. He's too much a man of
the city, too much smitten with its variousness and the visual
possibilities it presents. ``The subway is a universal studio,'' he
says. He's also kept faith with portraiture (``A face interests me
or it doesn't,'' he shrugs), and portraits rival cityscapes for
pride of place among his work. Not that Solman's any hidebound
realist: He plays with shape and form and color, even in his
portraits, with a freedom and daring that announce his avant-garde
roots. But always there must be that recognizable attachment to an
external world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1340EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6520 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-FICTION-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-07 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-FICTION-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... in ``Freedomland.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ian McEwan, who won England's Booker Prize this fall for
``Amsterdam,'' a smaller work, wrote a gorgeously creepy novel
about obsession in ``Enduring Love.'' In ``The Antelope Wife,'' set
among Native American generations in the Midwest, Louise Erdrich
braided time and myth with love and tragedy. David Gates, acclaimed
for the world-weary narrator of his first novel, ``Jernigan,''
returned with equally wry mastery in ``Preston Falls.'' John Edgar
Wideman produced his usual mix of intelligence and passion in ``Two
Cities,'' set in Philadelphia and Pittsburgh, while Barbara
Kingsolver, in her vast story about the former Belgian Congo,
delivered her best novel in years in ``The Poisonwood Bible.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Hamilton's ``The Short History of a Prince'' captures her
lovable protagonist _ a gay man who has returned home to the
Midwest _ with prismatic depth. Widely admired for her story
collection, ``The Family Markowitz,'' Allegra Goodman turned her
sights to a summer community of Orthodox Jews in upstate New York
in her first novel, ``Kaaterskill Falls.'' Ethan Canin managed an
excellent friendship between a dentist and a self-destructive
blackguard in ``For Kings and Planets,'' while Dorothy Allison
followed a rock 'n' roll star home to Georgia in ``Cavedweller.''
The Irish playwright Sebastian Barry wrote a hauntingly mythic
little novel about a man trying to find his way in from the seas of
exile in ``The Whereabouts of Eneas McNulty.'' And Daniel Menaker,
beloved from his years as fiction editor of The New Yorker, wrote
an uproarious portrait of a Freudian shrink and his mostly helpless
analysand in ``The Treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   For the crowd who likes its fiction cerebral, the year also
offered intellectual bonbons from Peter Carey (``Jack Maggs,'' an
homage to ``Great Expectations''), Andrea Barrett (``The Voyage of
the Narwhal,'' where science and self-awareness collide in the
Arctic), Maureen Howard (``A Lover's Almanac,'' an ode to time and
modernity), and Cathleen Schine (``The Evolution of Jane,'' where
Darwin has a hand). There were new novels from old favorites, most
notably Joyce Carol Oates's ``My Heart Laid Bare,'' John Irving's
``A Widow for One Year,'' and Patrick O'Brian's ``The Hundred
Days,'' as well as the prolific Louis Begley (``Mistler's Exit'')
and Beryl Bainbridge (``Master Georgie''). Edwidge Danticat
revisited Haiti for the bracing truths of ``The Farming of Bones,''
while Gayl Jones, in ``The Healing,'' returned with her first novel
in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the heroes were local in 1998, for New England had a
pack of authors making welcome appearances, among them Howard
Norman's ``The Museum Guard,'' Elinor Lipman's ``The Inn at Lake
Devine,'' Eileen Pollack's ``Paradise, New York,'' George Packer's
``Central Square,'' Roland Merullo's ``Revere Beach Boulevard,''
Jill McCorkle's ``Final Vinyl Days,'' and _ oh, guv'nor! _ William
F. Weld's ``Mackerel by Moonlight.'' But most of us can't succeed
in (commercial) art and politics alike, so we are forced to rely
upon the mere sustenance of literature. Thank heavens, then, for
the fine harvest of 1998: for the creative challenges sought and
met, the ordinary moments exalted by such prose, and the splendid
traces left across the sky.
</P>
<P>
   To the richest legacies _ the finest fiction _ of 1998, we offer
these grateful accolades.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Hours''  &LR; by Michael Cunningham (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$22). In this lovingly rendered homage to Virginia Woolf's ``Mrs.
Dalloway,'' Cunningham weaves the discrete stories of three women
into a subtle and stunning commentary on the power of art to
influence and guide our paths. You get to reread ``Mrs. Dalloway,''
too.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``This Side of Brightness''  &LR; by Colum McCann
(Metropolitan/Holt, $23). Opening with the exquisitely realized
days of a homeless man in modern New York, McCann then cuts to the
building of the subway tunnels at the start of the 20th century.
The novel feels both monumental and luminescent, with a richness of
physical and emotional detail that captures the span (and cruelty)
of history within one man's story.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Charming Billy''  &LR; by Alice McDermott (Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux, $21). Admirers of ``That Night'' and ``Weddings and Wakes''
were thrilled when McDermott won the National Book Award for this
novel, which possesses her usual stylistic resonance as well as her
regard for the lure of the past. Billy himself is an Irish-American
raconteur of heart-swelling proportion, not least because his story
opens at his funeral.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Evening''  &LR; by Susan Minot (Knopf, $23). However commendable
her previous work, ``Evening'' is a quantum leap for Minot,
returning to the choices and passions of a woman's life through her
stream-of-consciousness memories on her deathbed. The novel renders
these two modes of being _ the life lived and the death faced _
with equal authority, and with a beauty that eulogizes both.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Birds of America''  &LR; by Lorrie Moore (Knopf, $23). Shimmering
with the reality of contemporary America, this collection of
stories is by turns hilarious and profound; the dialogue is nearly
always pitch-perfect, and at least two stories are on their way to
being classics. ``Birds of America'' accomplishes that task which
is the ineffable joy of art: It makes your life feel a little bit
wider when it's over.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The Love of a Good Woman''  &LR; by Alice Munro (Knopf, $24).
Canada's great architect of the short story (in her hands, a
cathedral) has given us eight powerful stories that owe their
artistic mettle to Flannery O'Connor and William Faulkner as well
as to Chekhov. All set in the hinterlands of Ontario, they are
thick as stone, and just as strong, and they have at their dark
center a searingly truthful blend of chaos and grace.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``A Man in Full''  &LR; by Tom Wolfe (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux,
$28.95). Oh, that Virginia Tory turned double-agent. Nobody in
Atlanta can trust Tom Wolfe anymore, nor should they: ``A Man in
Full'' is a scarily precise, epic portrayal of Georgia-cracker
provincialism _ the New South in all its failed glory and comic
disrepair. It also rides roughshod over the rest of contemporary
America, from its high-rise boardrooms to the inside of a
California prison. Say what you will about the man's high-lit
pretensions: No other novel this year is as funny, exacting, or
cursedly ambitious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1342EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6525 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-GIFT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     12-07 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GIFT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... the movie.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The performing arts are always popular subjects for the
publishers of gift books. Pride of place this year should go to
``Seiji: An Intimate Portrait of Seiji Ozawa,'' edited by Caroline
Smedvig, with photographs by Lincoln Russell (Houghton Mifflin,
$40). This is a celebration of Ozawa's 25 seasons as music director
of the Boston Symphony, with tributes from several of his prominent
friends, associates, and colleagues, including John Williams, Peter
Serkin, Mstislav Rostropovich, Jessye Norman, Yo-Yo Ma, Andre
Previn, whom you would expect to find; the BSO's legendary
tympanist Vic Firth, a refreshing choice; and some genuinely
surprising figures like James Taylor, William M. Bulger, and Bob
Kraft. The most moving contribution comes from Nobel Prize-winning
novelist Kenzaburo Oe, who describes Ozawa's electronically
world-spanning performance of the finale of Beethoven's Ninth
Symphony at the opening ceremonies of the Nagano Olympics, placing
it in the context of the rising tide of Japan's new nationalism.
``Against this backdrop, Ozawa daringly joined the Japanese town
with diverse areas around the globe and conducted one of the finest
musical works of all humankind. I saw Seiji Ozawa in prayer.'' Some
of Russell's photographs are occasional and illustrative; the best
of them are profoundly revealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tributes: Celebrating Fifty Years of the New York City
Ballet'' (Morrow, $50) collects tributes to George Balanchine,
Lincoln Kirstein, Jerome Robbins, and Peter Martins by other
artists _ poets, writers, painters, designers _ who were drawn into
the orbit of this great institution these men created and curated.
There's not much, really, about ballet, but there's a lot about how
important this company has been in the lives of those who
experience it.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Somerset-Ward's ``The Story of Opera'' (Abrams, $49.50),
lavishly illustrated, comes equipped with a preface by Dame Kiri te
Kanawa. Somerset-Ward is an intelligent, careful, comprehensive and
mostly accurate historian (How could he have omitted Magda Olivero
from the list of great Adrianas?), but his footing becomes less
secure as he approaches the present, where he finds himself
discussing works as diverse as ``West Side Story,'' ``Die
Soldaten,'' ``Einstein on the Beach,'' and ``Nixon in China,''
which he calls ``one of the most revolutionary operas ever
created.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two big books from the world of rock music. ``The
Billboard Illustrated Encyclopedia of Rock'' (Billboard Books, $45)
is exactly what it says it is and comes from an authoritative
source; the tone is reference-book neutral even when the subject is
Barry Manilow. The hyperactive designers were not concerned about
keeping the text readable. This was also obviously not an issue for
the designers of ``The Rolling Stones: A Life on the Road,'' which
even at $50 (Penguin Studio) is cheaper than a ticket to a Stones
concert. The pictures are spectacular, and the apparently unedited
interviews by Jools Holland and Dora Loewenstein sometimes push
beyond routine, but design overrules content rather than
contributing to it.
</P>
<P>
   The illustrations in ``It Happened on Broadway,'' by Myrna Katz
Frommer and Harvey Frommer (Harcourt Brace, $35), are not the
reason to acquire the book; they are poorly reproduced in
unglamorous sepia. But the text is highly entertaining in an
anecdotal way _ like a convivial evening at Sardi's, or a talk show
without the interruptions of commercials or an imbecile host. The
authors, oral historians, interviewed 107 figures connected to the
Great White Way, ranging from famous stars from several generations
(Delores Gray, Celeste Holm, Elaine Stritch, Gwen Verdon, John
Raitt, Donna McKechnie, Betty Buckley, Judy Kaye) to publicists,
designers, directors, stage managers, and critics; their
recollections have been pieced and quilted into thematic patterns.
The best story repeats the devout Ethel Waters's response to the
way Mahalia Jackson rhythmed religious music, and her comment on
how Jesus would respond if He were ever to run into Mahalia on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Wallace employs a similar technique in ``The
Autobiography of Baseball: The Inside Story from the Stars Who
Played the Game'' (Abrams, $35). This is a collage of anecdote and
advice culled from a whole shelf's worth of biographies,
autobiographies, and interviews in newspapers and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Travel is another staple of the gift-book business, and Italy,
Greece, Ireland, and Mexico are all represented again this year.
Tibet is a destination as much spiritual as physical, and Peter
Sis's extraordinarily beautiful and uplifting ``Tibet: Through the
Red Box'' (Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $25) celebrates this fact. In
1956, Sis's father, a Czech documentary filmmaker, was one of the
last visitors to the old Tibet; Sis has illustrated fragments of
his father's diary in a tribute to a vanished world that still
lives in spirit. ``The Tibetans: A Struggle to Survive'' (Red
Wheelbarrow, $45) has a more directly political purpose. The
photographs by Steve Lehman depict the despoiling of a great
culture, and its indestructibility; there is oral history, an
essay, and a preface by Robert Coles.
</P>
<P>
   Two new cookbooks are too beautiful to bring anywhere near the
Cuisinart or the stove. ``Ducasse: Flavors of France'' by Alain
Ducasse (Artisan, $60) is the first English-language cookbook by
the most celebrated chef in contemporary France, who has earned six
Michelin stars. Despite an editor's appendix of suggested
substitutions and techniques, the recipes don't look very practical
for an American home kitchen dependent on the American supermarket.
Still, Ducasse's book isn't just a collection of recipes but also a
gastronomic memoir (``Desserts unlock memories . . .'') and a
celebration of basic principles (``My cooking is about clarity of
taste, precision in execution, and respect for the product, which
to me means retaining its original flavor'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Culinaria: The United States: A Culinary Discovery''
(Koenemann, $39.98) introduces a prominent German art-book
publisher to the US market by surveying American food both
geographically and historically _ there are Native American recipes
here, and a tribute to the Korean market; there are recipes from
diners, brew pubs, and Delmonico's; you can find everything here
from bison chili to Buffalo wings. There are dishes you wouldn't
necessarily want to try (emu steaks with bacon molasses sauce, or
fried Rocky Mountain oysters), but nearly all the sumptuous
photographs look good enough to eat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
