<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6535 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-GREED-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     12-07 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GREED-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... says Cohl.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Again, though, listen to Joel on the subject. ``I got into a big
fight with Barbra Streisand's manager before her last tour,'' he
says. ``We were sitting around the table late night in New York
somewhere, and Barbra was talking about how she's going to tour.
The manager then said what they were going to charge and I said,
`Well, that sucks, what about all those little girls from places
like Brooklyn where Barbra grew up, who don't have that kind of
money?' And he looks at me and says, `Oh, I heard about you. You're
one of those troublemaker guys,' because I was telling Barbra it
was a rip-off. Here she was going around telling everybody to vote
for the Democrats, and then in the meantime, she's selling tickets
to Republicans. I thought that was a little hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Besides Joel, Pearl Jam is another act that keeps ticket prices
within reach of the general fan. ``The band remembers how
frustrating it was for them to get into shows as kids, so they keep
the prices low,'' says Pearl Jam manager Kelly Curtis from his
Seattle office. ``We were told (by promoters) that we could get
away with $5 more per ticket this summer, but we said no. We get
crap from people within the industry who are tired of our moral
standards, but that's what we believe.''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam also keeps its T-shirt sale prices refreshingly low _
only $18 per shirt, compared with an industry average of $25 to
$27. And the group has battled venue operators who expect to get 40
percent of those sales because they provide the band a place to
sell merchandise on site.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Dallas this summer, the (arena operators) were shocked when
we said we wouldn't do it for more than 20 percent,'' says Kelly.
``So we ended up selling our stuff across the street from the
venue. We did that once in Toronto, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Some acts, in truth, can make as much in merchandise sales as in
ticket sales, if not more. And the greed award for merchandise has
to go to Kiss, which has more than 1,000 licensed items to sell.
When a TV interviewer once asked Kiss's Gene Simmons about the
merits of a $700 Kiss tour jacket, Simmons replied, ``If you don't
want a Rolls-Royce, then don't go into the showroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Such arrogance is totally foreign to country singer Garth
Brooks, who freaks out when anyone suggests raising the prices of
his tour merchandise. He's the exact opposite of greed when it
comes to his audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll explain it this way,'' Brooks says. ``On our live tour,
the most expensive thing we've got is a jacket. And we were told we
could sell it for $120-something. But that was just going to kill
me. So I basically asked how much is it costing us? And they said,
well, it costs $40 or $45. And I said, well, you know, I was always
taught by the guys in retail when I was in college that if you just
double what it costs you, that's a fair thing to do. And they said,
we can't because we won't be able to keep them in stock. I said,
well, order more of them, then. So that's why our most expensive
thing out there is $80. And the next closest thing to it is $20.
I'm just not a fan of the bigger-priced stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Observers worried
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend Billy Joel and Garth Brooks for doing what they do,
but, unfortunately, there are very few who do that,'' says Bob
Grossweiner, senior editor of Performance magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the touring industry also has some observers
worried, especially since corporate giant SFX has spent $600
million to buy up many promoters and venues around the country.
There's a fear that SFX will inflate ticket prices, though
spokesman Tim Klahs says that won't be the case overall. He does
say, however, that at SFX's amphitheaters, which now include Great
Woods in Mansfield, there will be an increased number of
ticket-price points, meaning there will be five to seven different
prices per show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high end will be higher, and the low end will be lower,''
says Klahs. Asked if the high end would be in the $100-plus range,
he responds that this estimate is ``premature and speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   SFX is planning to increase advertising and sponsorship of its
tours and venues, as well as merchandising. ``We're talking to
large corporations who want to be associated with a very attractive
audience,'' says Klahs. ``We're talking to apparel manufacturers,
athletic shoe companies, financial service companies, credit
companies, and soft-drink companies. You'll find that all
entertainment is getting more and more associated with sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there's been any artist resistance to these plans,
Klahs replies, ``We haven't heard of any yet. That's not to say
that the more idealistic performers won't have a problem with some
of this.''
</P>
<P>
   And did we mention that the Rolling Stones are being sponsored
by Tommy Hilfiger on the arena tour, as if the group needs a
sponsor, given that ticket prices are so high?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I knew when I first got into the music business, this was
definitely not the Boy Scouts,'' Joel says in conclusion. ``There
was always greed. It just seems, though, that what was an
artist-driven business has not been like that for a long time. So
I'm not surprised that the bean counters have come in and found
ways to squeeze even more money out of the music lover.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
