<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-EDEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COEN'S `EDEN,' ANYTHING CAN GO WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
GATES OF EDEN 
By Ethan Coen 
Rob Weisbach/Morrow, 261 pp., $24 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a filmmaker, Ethan Coen has always possessed a pungent
inclination for the horrid, heartbreaking, and hilarious. He
embraces strange, battered souls skittering precariously on the
planet's fringe, forgotten people whose little lives are ever
cartwheeling wildly out of control. These aren't just dark lives;
they're so pitch-black it's as if they never enjoyed an honest
day's sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   They reside in Coen's funny, frightful hell of vengeful
husbands, bounty hunters, and inept hit men. Think of the ex-con
and police-officer couple so desperate to become parents they swipe
one of the newborn quintuplet sons of an unfinished-furniture
magnate in ``Raising Arizona.'' Or the blindfolded housewife, clad
in pajamas and slippers, running a frantic, futile dash in the snow
as kidnappers, hired by her weasel of a husband, gawk with glee in
``Fargo.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with his older brother, Joel, Coen is half of the
acclaimed filmmaking Coen brothers, responsible for some of the
most quirky, original films of the past 15 years, including ``Blood
Simple'' and ``Miller's Crossing'' as well as ``Raising Arizona''
and the Academy Award-winning ``Fargo.'' From screwball comedy to
film noir, their work been an intoxicating brew of the grisly and
farcical, the grotesque and comic.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case with Ethan Coen's first collection of short
stories, ``Gates of Eden.'' It's an uneven but fearless offering
about the disillusioned and damaged among us, lives marked by
false, sometimes fatal moves. A chill of horror lurks beneath the
surface of Coen's worlds, where anything can go wrong and usually
does. There are tomato-can college-boy boxers, Hebrew-school
troublemakers, fast-talking show-biz types, and an unfortunate
woman who may have been a nag but certainly didn't deserve to be
sprawled in a yard with her head lopped off.
</P>
<P>
   Coen employs a variety of styles for his collection, from linear
narrative to wordy soliloquies and confessional, fever-dream
monologues, even mini-plays complete with stage directions. At
their best, the stories are so vivid the stench of stale smoke and
sweat seems to waft from the pages.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Destiny,'' there's Joseph Carmody, a sweet kid trying his
hand as a boxer. Never mind that he calls his fights ``beatings,''
since ``fight implies an exchange of blows'' and all Joey does is
catch punches and kiss the canvas. He half-jokingly considers
promoting himself as ``The Human Speedbag.'' Believing he might be
better suited for a more delicate line of work, he foolishly
accepts a job as a private eye bent on snapping a shot of his
client's wife in an act of infidelity. It proves to be an even
worse career move.
</P>
<P>
   It's vintage Coen _ funny, violent, and a little sad.
Unrestricted by the natural limits of screenplays and moviemaking,
Coen has more room to flex and to develop his characters, who are
revealed in the dead-on dialogue that has always been a hallmark of
the Coen brothers' scripts.
</P>
<P>
   Coen has a field day with staccato, almost Mamet-esque
gangster-speak in the book's best story, ``Cosa Minapolidan.'' It's
a sort of ``Miller's Crossing'' meets ``Fargo,'' with a dim-bulb
Cleveland goodfella who, wanting to be a player, decides to set up
shop in Minneapolis. As Coen describes it, de Louie's reason for
moving to the ``virgin turf'' of mild-mannered Minneapolis (which
de Louie mangles into ``Minapolis'') is the gangster's
misinterpretation of the city's name as Chippewa for ``New Naples''
_ and he missed his native Italy.
</P>
<P>
   As his native state, Minnesota becomes a character in some of
Coen's work, especially the examples that seem more like personal
essays than short stories. In ``The Old Country,'' Coen writes of
Michael Simkin, a 10-year-old rabble-rouser. ``He was a Hammer of
God, defying not Rome or the crown, but the Hebrew school
principal. Like the great scourges of history _ Genghis Khan,
Oliver Cromwell, Omar Mukhtar _ he seemed invulnerable, in his case
perhaps because he was too young to execute. Or so we believed.''
Coen gently examines growing up Jewish in a land dominated by
Swedes, Poles, and German Lutherans, and how quickly individuality
can be silenced.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as anyone familiar with Coen's movies knows, there's
always a wild hit-or-miss quality to his work _ for every ``Raising
Arizona'' and ``Fargo,'' there's ``The Hudsucker Proxy'' and ``The
Big Lebowski.'' Still, even when his stories don't cut it, it's
usually because Coen has leapt too far or reached too high for a
memorable touch. He doesn't fail because he chose a safe, well-worn
path. His juicy, pulpy writing style simmers on a medium flame, but
it never boils over into cliche. And as with his films, his
failures are often almost as interesting as other writers'
successes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6545 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PAXTON-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     12-07 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PAXTON-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... to New York.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I shacked up with an old girlfriend and just completely
thought that I had run away from my life's calling. I called my dad
and said, `Dad, I don't know what to do. I left this play and I
don't ever want to get out of bed. And he said, `Well, son, I'd
like to help you, but I'm worried that your brother is going to
take his own life.' I flew down to Texas and took my brother up to
New York to live with me. By getting involved with my brother, I
got out of my own malaise over a period of months, which I think is
good advice to anyone who is prone to depression!''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Paxton was hired by James Cameron as a set
decorator on a Roger Corman film, ``Galaxy of Terror.'' ``The job
interview was something like, `Have you had some experience?' I go,
`Yeah, I worked for Roger in the past.' He said, `Well, can you
start now?' I said, `You mean right now?' He said, `Yeah. See that
wall over there? Go paint it brown.' I adore Jim. I know there are
a lot of stories about him, but he's got more integrity than just
about anybody I've met in California.'' The working relationship
has continued. Cameron cast Paxton as a punk offed by Arnold
Schwarzenegger in ``Terminator.'' He then appeared in Cameron's
``Alien,'' ``True Lies,'' and ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Another crisis
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While at work on ``Alien,'' Paxton underwent his second crisis
of confidence. ``I was playing the hysteric in the group. I
remember literally my guts would ache at the end of the day. It was
a tough energy to maintain over a 14-week shoot. I felt I had
completely overdone my character. I had another one of those, you
know, emotional situations, where I thought I had to do something
to change my life radically. I thought of joining the French
Foreign Legion as the most radical way I could change my life and
keep it romantically interesting. But they had a two-year waiting
list. Meanwhile, the film opened, and my character turned out to be
one of the most relatable characters. It was great, a real lift up
the ladder for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of anxiety between the time a shoot is finished
and the time a film is released. Jim said he read that I had a lot
of anxiety and he said, `You know, you never confided in me.' I
told him I would never have told him of these insecurities I had. I
think Sigourney (Weaver, the film's star) spotted it. She was
always introducing me to people and saying I was doing a wonderful
job. I thought, `Is it that apparent that I'm screwing up?' I
almost did an Oliver Stone movie, `U-Turn' _ I found him to be kind
of impenetrable and, ah, someone who wants to invite confrontation,
which is not my style.
</P>
<P>
   ``About two weeks away from starting, I felt like I was facing a
firing squad. Couldn't get my grip on the character. I'd probably
worked more on that part than on any I'd ever did, but I didn't
feel that our chemistry was such that it was gonna be a good
experience for me. He was grateful enough to replace me with Sean
Penn and that sent me crashing. I mean, here I told myself that I
had the lead in an Oliver Stone movie. My agency, I've got
everybody scratching their heads like this is the follow-up to
`Twister.' So I told myself, this isn't the time for a nervous
breakdown. But my heart was in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The pain continued with the soft landing of Paxton's pet
project, ``Traveller,'' in which he played a gypsy scamster. The
story was discovered by his wife, Louise. They met when he
approached her on a London bus during a break from shooting ``The
Lords of Discipline'' (1983) and almost scared her off. They
weathered five off-and-on years, then married 11 years ago. They
have two children, James, 4 1/2, and Lydia, born last Dec. 19, the
day, Paxton reminds us, ``Titanic'' opened.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Twister'' sequel?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Twister,'' Paxton says he loved doing it and would do a
sequel if the script was good. ``Would I have liked more character
development? Sure, I was ready to weigh in big time with that. I
grew up in north central Texas. Twisters were a big part of, you
know, the lore of the land. I've only seen the preludes of a
twister. The whole atmosphere changes. Dark clouds come over and
they almost start turning this kind of gangrene green color. All
the grass kind of starts to glow in the late afternoon, and the
atmosphere starts to thin out and the birds sit on the ground. You
hear the telephone wires start to hum. You see the whole change in
the air and that was something we did not capture, I thought. But
that's what I remember as a kid before we went down into the storm
shelters.''
</P>
<P>
   Paxton exchanged twister stories with Ben Johnson, the original
star of ``Mighty Joe Young,'' who began as a real cowboy delivering
horses to Howard Hughes, then went from stuntman to movie cowboy.
He and Paxton met in the '80s, got reacquainted on the set of
``Evening Star,'' Johnson's last film. ``We filmed `Twister' about
15 miles from his hometown _ Pawhuska, an Indian name _ in
Oklahoma. He told me stories of twisters there, told me about John
Ford and John Wayne. Now here I was, filming `Mighty Joe Young,'
playing the part he played in 1949. I play this guy from an animal
conservancy who tries to persuade Charlize Theron, this
primatologist, that the big gorilla's best chance of survival lies
in being taken back to the conservancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe's about as big as a live oak tree or a dump truck. He's
kind of a miniature King Kong. It really is a Beauty and the Beast
story. She's this beautiful siren who's soothed the savage beast,
and there's this love triangle that sort of forms. I'm trying to
work my way in, but she's so concerned about Joe, I can't get her
to notice me. Every time I turn around, I've got Joe staring at me,
which is a nice fun dynamic. Rick Baker, a famous guy, did an
animatronic. For the most part, we just had to pretend Joe was
there. That was an RKO picture, and Howard Hughes owned RKO and we
filmed part of it in the huge aircraft plant where he built his
famous Spruce Goose that only flew once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry Moore, who was in the original, and Ray Harryhausen, who
built the original Joe, are in this film, playing cameos in the
nightclub scene where Joe goes on a rampage. Terry told me Howard
Hughes gave her flying lessons in the parking lot. I told Ron
Underwood, the director, that we had to get Ben in for karmic
reasons, if for nothing else. So in one scene, if you look fast,
you'll see in a kiosk window a poster for `Wagon Master,' one of
Ben's films. First doing this brother movie with my father, then
reprising Ben Johnson's role in this other film has been a
wonderful twister of fate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
