<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6550 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-GREED-2TAKES-BO     12-07 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GREED-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK 'N' GREED 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rolling Stones once sang ``Street Fighting Man,'' a
signature song recalling their scruffy, working-class days. That
was a long time ago, for the Stones are now fighting another fight
by pushing rock 'n' roll ticket prices to stratospheric levels. The
Stones are charging up to $300 a ticket for their upcoming arena
tour _ a gesture that has made them the new poster boys for a
runaway greed that is infecting the music industry and changing its
very fabric.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stones are still street-fighting men,'' says Michael Cohl,
the Toronto promoter who is booking the band's 20-city tour. ``I
would think that street-fighting men would still charge the
wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but are they giving back to the poor? The answer is no, not
on this tour, Cohl admits, though he says the Stones do
occasionially contribute to charities in a ``private manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stones actually played a single Atlantic City show 10 years
ago for a $300 ticket. ``Another way to look at it,'' says the
brash Cohl, ``is that how come 10 years later we haven't raised
ticket prices?''
</P>
<P>
   Such spin control is becoming common in a music industry where
the rich are getting richer through fat contracts, compounded by a
self-indulgence that causes them to drop many filler-type products
on the public. These range from endless live albums (the Stones
just released their seventh) and greatest-hits packages to
outtake-filled boxed sets that clog the media's attention and
squeeze out new bands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an incredible sense of entitlement right now,'' says
Tim White, editor of Billboard magazine. Consumers ``are being
driven to the superstar acts to the exclusion of other things. The
marketing dollars are not going to the baby acts. They're going to
the superstar who is on a major tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the business needs to realize this and needs to stop
being so greedy,'' adds White. ``We've come to a crossroads in
terms of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stones tour has been called the ``Millionaires Watching
Millionaires'' tour by Variety magazine, which estimates the Stones
could get $30 million from their 20-city jaunt. And that follows
$150 million from their last stadium tour, which carried a $65
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   At Boston's FleetCenter, a $300 price applies to 3,000 seats
sold for each show to suite holders and other premium seat holders
(prices for the general public are $150, $90, and $50, with a token
400 seats priced at $39.50, says a box-office source). The $300
seats will account for a $900,000 gross all by themselves _ and
even more when you realize that 500 of those are going for $650,
which covers a pre- and post-concert party (beware: the Stones
haven't actually agreed to attend), parking, and some kind of tour
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also a $20 service charge, so anyone with a $300
ticket is actually paying $320 a ticket,'' says Dennis Arfa, an
agent with New York-based QBQ Entertainment, which represents Billy
Joel, Metallica, Luther Vandross, and Motley Crue.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that unprecedented service charge will go to the Stones,
says Arfa. ``They're going to walk away with the same (financial
grosses) as when they played stadiums,'' he adds. ``It's greed, but
the Rolling Stones can get away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Stones and some other acts from the '60s and '70s used to
do drugs, but now they're doing money,'' says Tim Collins, the
former Aerosmith manager who now teaches at Berklee College of
Music. Collins is refusing to see the Stones, though he was offered
a free ticket. ``It's out of control and it takes the soul right
out of it,'' he says of the pricing. ``It makes it only for the
wealthy. How can kids go to see this? It's alienating kids from the
whole concept of rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many acts have a fear that they're going to be gone soon,''
Collins says, explaining the cash-in mentality that now often
prevails. ``They're worried about all the consolidations and
mergers in the industry, and what that might do to them. It's just
money driving it now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been greed in this business _ and nothing
surprises me about it,'' says Billy Joel. ``I just feel bad for the
people who love music. I think in a way that all of this is causing
people to turn away from rock 'n' roll and popular music in droves.
I know I have. I'm just tired of being demographed and marketed to,
and spoon-fed and ripped off.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel, along with Pearl Jam and Garth Brooks, is among a
vanishing breed of superstar acts that keeps ticket prices down.
Joel's top ticket at the Fleet is $39.50, while Pearl Jam's last
tour had a top of $24, and Brooks's last stop at the FleetCenter
had a top ticket of just $17.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to keep the ticket price under $40,'' says Joel,
``because now a lot of these buildings have a building surcharge on
the ticket. And this is on top of the rent that the artist is
paying in the first place. So then you get that added to the
ticket. And then there's the ticket agencies. And there's scalpers
and whatever they want to charge. And then there's the parking
fees. I mean, by the time some poor guy gets into the arena, he's
been hit 50 ways from Sunday. And who else is going to look after
the audience except for the artist? The building doesn't care. The
managers don't care. The booking agents don't care. The promoters
don't care. The scalpers and the ticket agencies don't care. It's
the artist. That's his bread and butter. If he doesn't look after
them, then who will?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scalper defense
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A frequent defense of escalating ticket prices _ you've heard it
ever since the Eagles charged $100 four years ago, which really
broke the ice in this regard _ is that scalpers are going to get
these prices anyway, so why shouldn't the acts get the extra
dollars instead?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but two wrongs don't make a right,'' says Joel. ``Who
would you rather get ripped off by _ the scalpers or us? That's
just too much money. And you know what? Maybe (the Stones) are
worth it to enough people who want to pay that much money, but
that's not what the essence of rock 'n' roll is about. It seems
like you're cashing in your chips there, guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's another reason that I keep my ticket price under
$40,'' Joel says. ``It's so younger people can afford to get in.
The scalpers actually changed the nature of the show by disallowing
people under a certain age to be able to afford to buy tickets.
That dictates that the audience will be older; and I'm sorry, but
an older audience is just not as enthusiastic as a younger
audience. It's just a matter of physical energy. I used to look
down in the old days and see all of these fat cats in the good
seats, and we got around that by not putting them on sale. We'd
send the roadies to the back of the room and give those kids the
front-row seats.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stones' camp, however, rationalizes that Barbra Streisand
charged up to $350 a ticket at Madison Square Garden a few years
ago. Why shouldn't they follow suit? ``And she didn't average $75
for the other tickets, which is what we're averaging,'' says Cohl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1352EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
