<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS &LR;      12-07 0159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-GUIDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES REVIEWED BY GLOBE CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   !!! ``Hard Core Logo'' This mockumentary about a
self-destructive punk band reunited for an ill-fated tour will
likely draw comparisons to ``This Is Spinal Tap,'' but it's a far
different film. While there are laughs, it's a much more poignant
look at four band members trying to hold onto their unruly youth,
even as they edge toward middle age. (Unrated) (Renee Graham)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
! 1/2 ``Shattered Image'' Parallel-lives Hollywood gothic,
involving William Baldwin's obvious schemer and Anne Parillaud in
her ``Femme Nikita'' mode as a Seattle hit woman and,
alternatively, as a honeymooner in Jamaica menaced by ominous
portents. Which is real? You won't care. Filmmaker Raul Ruiz's
surrealist touch seems to have deserted him here, which is
understandable, given Duane Poole's pedestrian script. (Unrated)
</P>
</TEXT>
