<HEADLINE>
STAYING SANE AT CHRISTMAS IS NOT SO SIMPLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps you haven't noticed because you've been busy having your
annual pre-holiday walking nervous breakdown, but there's a move
afoot to simplify the holidays, to pare down the preparations, cut
spending to a minimum, reduce the whole shebang to its essentials.
</P>
<P>
   There are several books on the subject of seasonal
simplification, among them Elaine St. James's ``Simplify Your
Christmas,'' and Bill McKibbem's ``Hundred Dollar Holiday.'' What
does it say about us, as a people, that the notion of simplifying
Christmas is so complicated that we need to buy a book, or two, to
tell us how to go about it? That we're nuts? Well, we may be,
especially at this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   St. James is the queen of the simplicity movement. She's written
a couple of hot-sellers on the how-to-simplify theme, ``Simplify
Your Life,'' and ``Living the Simple Life,'' plus a title that must
be a foray into fiction: ``Simplify Your Life With Kids.'' The
proceeds have enabled St. James to live as simply as she likes, in
Santa Barbara, Calif., where the living is simple but far from
inexpensive.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not knocking St. James. She has some good ideas. And she
makes it all sound so . . . simple. One of the first things to do,
she advises, is tell family and friends you won't be giving gifts,
entertaining, sending cards, etc. ``You might be surprised at the
responses,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I wouldn't be at all surprised at the responses.
But, says St. James, you can't allow the expectations of others to
dissuade you from pursuing simplicity. ``Remember,'' she writes,
``the first year will most likely be the hardest. After that the
delight of celebrating a simpler, happier Christmas will quickly
minimize the guilt other family members try to lay on you. Then
you'll simply rise above it.'' Rise above family-induced guilt?
That truly would be a Christmas miracle for some of us.
</P>
<P>
   Those who want not just to rise above but to transcend the
commercialization of Christmas may find inspiration in McKibben's
``Hundred Dollar Holiday.'' McKibben, a former staff writer for the
New Yorker, lives in the Adirondack Mountains of New York, where
he's active in the Methodist church. A few years ago he and some
fellow church members decided to make Christmas more fulfilling by
limiting the amount of money each family would spend on the holiday
to $100. The result was a more joyous, family-centered, spiritually
meaningful holiday, ``a time of calm and happiness, a season to
linger in and not `get through.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It goes without saying there will be no Furby under the McKibben
tree this Christmas morning. There will be a tree, though. The day
before Christams the whole family trudges out in snowshoes into the
mountains to choose and cut the perfect tree. There will be
homemade gifts and goodies galore, candelit suppers, carol singing,
a midnight service at church. It all sounds idyllic, like some sort
of Christmas fantasy, which is what it must remain, for most of us.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you have to reach the point at which you're so fed up with
holiday excess that you're willing to go cold turkey, like the
Chicago woman who describes in St. James's book how she and her
husband cut back on Christmas. They figured they spent $2,500 each
year on the holiday, money they couldn't afford to squander. So one
year they decided to do nothing. No cards, no gifts, no
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   On Christmas Day they visited a relative's house: ``The moment
of truth came when we saw the pile of gifts addressed to us. `We
didn't bring gifts. Remember, we're simplifying this year,' I
announced cheerfully. To my delight, my brother-in-law piped up and
said, `That's what we all should do.' We spent the next half hour
discussing ways to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one of those heartwarming, inspirational holiday stories
that would make me go warm all over, if I had the time. But I'm due
at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
