<SLUG> BC-SCI-BONES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJECTIONS REPAIR DAMAGED BACKBONES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When 85-year-old Josephine Amenta tumbled from a stepstool at
her daughter's home last Oct. 12, a vertebra in her aged and
weakened spine collapsed on itself like a bony pancake.
</P>
<P>
   The painful ``crush'' fracture ``was like a toothache that aches
and aches,'' said Amenta, a stoic Peabody woman who likes to rake
leaves, sweep and ``keep the place nice.'' Medication didn't help.
Even a skin patch constantly releasing strong drugs couldn't blank
out the pain:
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't walk and I couldn't sleep,'' she recounted
recently.
</P>
<P>
   The standard treatment for such injuries is bed rest,
painkillers and a back brace, but it can take weeks for the pain to
subside. But at the Lahey Clinic in Burlington, Mass., amenta was
offered a relatively new nonsurgical procedure that has been
gaining popularity, though not universal acceptance, in which
radiologists inject a quick-drying bone cement inside the vertebra,
calming the hurting nerves and beefing up the bone.
</P>
<P>
   The next day she was sitting up and even walking a bit, and the
pain had all but vanished, said Amenta. By last week, she said, she
was ``almost back the way I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Enthusiasts say the procedure, called vertebroplasty, can
dramatically speed recovery from crush, or compression fractures,
as they're also known, which are common in women with bone-thinning
osteoporosis. By one estimate, osteoporosis causes 700,000
vertebral fractures every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you pick the right people, the results are awesome,'' said
Dr. Joshua Hirsch, an interventional neuroradiologist at Lahey who
has done vertebroplasty on seven patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're fixing a fracture from the inside, like putting a cast
on the arm,'' but in this case, strengthening the vertebra from
inside, said Dr. Mary E. Jensen. She is a radiologist at the
University of Virginia Health Sciences Center, whose team has the
largest US experience with it.
</P>
<P>
   The best candidates for the procedure, say Hirsch and Jensen,
include:
</P>
<P>
   --Older people whose bones have been weakened by osteoporosis
and either suffer compression fractures in a fall or in whom a
vertebra sometimes simply gives way under their own weight. Jensen
says at present it should be done only on patients for whom
conventional therapy hasn't worked. But she's about to begin a
study using vertebroplasty as a primary treatment right after a
fracture has occurred.
</P>
<P>
   --Transplant patients and others taking large doses of steroid
drugs, which can lead to weakened and crushed vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   --Patients with primary or metastasized cancer in the spine.
</P>
<P>
   When it's successful, vertebroplasty can reduce the need for
strong painkillers that can have unwanted side effects,
particularly in older people. However, it can't correct the spinal
curvature or shortened stature that osteoporosis can cause, Jensen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-year-old Santa Floridia of Quincy, Mass. suffered a
compression fracture in early October when she fell while climbing
into a van. Her daughter, Connie McGillicuddy, said the pain ``was
just unbelievable, and the pain medication made her kind of out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Floridia had been bedridden eight weeks when McGillicuddy heard
about the procedure and contacted Hirsch at the Lahey. The next day
_ during Thanksgiving week _ Floridia underwent vertebroplasty, and
that same day ``stood up and had no pain,'' said McGillicuddy.
</P>
<P>
   Floridia is getting physical therapy to strengthen her legs
after so much bed rest, but her daughter said the vertebroplasty
``was wonderful for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of injecting bone cement into crushed vertebrae
originated with French doctors in the 1980s, but didn't catch on in
the United States until it was described at a 1993 neuroradiology
meeting, said Jensen, who heads the UVA interventional
neuroradiology section. Interventional neuroradiologists use
techniques and devices similar to those for diagnosing nerve
problems to carry out certain procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial element is to have state-of-the-art imaging machines
to enable the doctors to guide the needles to precisely the right
spot, said Jensen.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia specialists began doing vertebroplasties in 1994
and to date have treated more than 200 vertebrae (sometimes more
than one in a patient), according to Jensen. The interest is so
keen, she said, that ``I've trained 60 people in the last year and
there's a big waiting list'' of radiologists from across the
country wanting to learn the technique.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Lahey Clinic appears to be the only center in the
Boston area performing vertebroplasty.
</P>
<P>
   But some specialists, including an orthopedic surgeon at the New
England Baptist Hospital, say they're not convinced that the
procedure will have a large role.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Banco said most patients with vertebral compression
fractures ``do quite well'' with the standard treatment, though he
agreed that some need hospitalization and aggressive pain
management in the first couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Severe fractures aren't amenable to vertebroplasty, he added. In
some of those cases, it's necessary to perform a complicated spinal
fusion.
</P>
<P>
   While vertebroplasty ``is a good procedure,'' said Banco, it
``is basically to get rid of pain for mild and moderate compression
fractures. Who is the right patient to have this thing done? There
may not be many of them out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hirsch said vertebropolasty takes about two hours to perform.
</P>
<P>
   The patient, who must be able to lie prone for up to three
hours, is given a sedating drug and a local anesthetic. The
radiologist then makes a small X-shaped incision over the bony
protrusion of the damaged vertebra, and, while watching
continuously on a fluoroscope (an X-ray machine that shows moving
images) and a CT scanner, inserts the needle into the center of the
vertebra.
</P>
<P>
   A larger needle, with a bore about the size of a ballpoint pen
tip, is slipped over the needle that's already in the vertebra, and
the smaller one is withdrawn. The large needle is the conduit into
the bone _ first for an injection of dye, then the bone cement. As
the dye flows out of the needle and spreads through the crushed
interior of the vertebra, ``you make a road map for yourself'' that
shows where the cement will end up, said Hirsch.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, technicians mix up the cement, called
polymethylmethacrylate or PMMA. It is is routinely used for bone
repairs, including to glue artificial hip joints in place. PMMA
powder and a solvent are combined, along with a powder that makes
the cement visible in an X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   There is no time to waste: The cement hardens in 10 minutes. The
radiologist injects the mixture through the needle and it spreads
throughout the fractured vertebra.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest risk is that the cement will ooze into the wrong
places and compress the spinal cord or a nerve root. If that
happens, emergency surgery is necessary to relieve the pressure,
said Jensen, but it is rare. She quotes a complication rate of
under 1 percent for vertebroplasty.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, she said, the cement gets into a blood vessel and
goes to the lung, but she's never seen that cause a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The CT and X-ray machines show whether the cement is correctly
placed. If so, the patient simply lies prone long enough for the
cement to set. Many patients go home the same day, some stay
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   While many patients get immediate pain relief, the procedure
isn't guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   In a study of 101 fractures in 84 patients treated at the
University of Virginia, Johns Hopkins Medical Institutions, and
Tampa General Hospital in Florida, Jensen said, there were
statistically significant improvements in activity and in reducing
medication. The only failures were in 12 fractures (not 12
patients) in which there was no response, and three that reported
worsening pain.
</P>
<P>
   Before treatment, only 3 percent of the patients said they could
do everything they wanted, compared to 35 percent after treatment,
said Jensen. And 50 percent of patients improved two or more steps
on a pain scale after treatment, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinarily, I'm a skeptic,'' said Jensen. ``But I'm a believer
in this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
