<HEADLINE>
TIME IS DEFINITELY ON 26-YEAR-OLD'S SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am 26. My wife and I rent an apartment and don't foresee a
house purchase in the next four years. We would like to get serious
about retirement planning, our goal being to retire with $1.5
million in 35 years. We also want to save a healthy down payment
for a home, $70,000 to $90,000, four years from now. I don't have a
401(k) program through my employer, but my wife will have access to
one in January. Her company will match up to 5 percent of her base
salary, which would represent $1,850 a year. Right now we have
$13,000 in savings. After all of our expenses, including leisure
money, we are left with $1,400 a month. This amount has been
increasing, and should continue to increase, at a rate of $300
annually. What's the best way to reach our goals?
</P>
<P>
   S.C., Woburn, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your goals should be easy to achieve _ probably too easy. A
$1.5 million retirement pool looks pretty big today, but it's not
likely to seem as grand in 35 years. If inflation averages 4
percent during that period, it would have the buying power of
$380,123 in today's money; even if inflation were only 3 percent,
it would still be worth but $533,075 in 1998 bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as you'll see, this isn't something that should daunt
you.
</P>
<P>
   First, you and your wife will want to grab that free $1,850 a
year her employer offers beginning in January. To provide the funds
to achieve that 401(k) match, she will have to commit $155 a month
of your free money.
</P>
<P>
   But with such a long investment period, she will have begun a
significant savings program. If she and her employer were to
continue to each contribute $1,850 a year for 35 years (presuming
monthly contributions and 10 percent average returns) the pool
would grow to $1,048,776.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't leave you needing a great deal more to get to $1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Going back to the real estate savings, let's put your $13,000
savings in this pool. After your wife's $155 monthly 401(k)
contributions, you would have $1,145 free. If you were to add
$1,045 of this to your savings each month, the sum would reach
$26,477 after a year.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, when you'll have another $300 monthly available,
let's add another $250 to the real estate savings pool, bringing
contributions up to $1,295. If you continue that pattern, the total
pool should be roughly $90,123 after four years. This presumes that
you use a mutual fund money market account and achieve average 5
percent returns.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to the $100 extra, and the $50 in additional
savings you would achieve in each of those four years? I set this
aside as the beginning of your own retirement savings. You're
probably eligible for a Roth IRA, and I suggest you use this
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   If you were to begin Roth IRA accumulations at a rate of $100 a
month, increasing the contribution by $50 a year annually, you
would amass $9,846 over four years. Not a huge amount, but consider
this: To fill the gap between the $1.5 million target and the
$1,048,776 from your wife's 401(k) plan, you would need to
contribute but $115 a month over the next 31 years.
</P>
<P>
   OK, now the scary part. Let's assume that what you really want
in 35 years is the equivalent of $1.5 million in today's dollars. I
ran this calculation at 3.5 percent presumed inflation, and the
number came out to a horrifying $5,000,385.
</P>
<P>
   But time is on your side. Remember, after you buy your home in
four years you will have $2,145 of ``free'' money in your monthly
budget. So how much of that $2,145 would you have to save to build
that $9,846 retirement account to $3,451,609? Only $1,428 per
month, presuming you achieve average 10 percent returns from the
retirement portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   As for investment vehicles for the retirement account, since
this has run very long I'm going to suggest only that you develop a
diversified portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
