<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
60 STARS IN THE STAR-SPANGLED BANNER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `How many stars do you think there will be in the American flag
25 years from now?'' asks Juan Enriquez, a researcher at the David
Rockefeller Center at Harvard University. ``A case can be made that
there will be 60, perhaps more.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of his adult life, Enriquez has immersed himself
in the study of borders. He is currently writing a book on the
subject. The first draft, three-quarters complete, is spell-binding
and authoritative. His data do not lie. Globalization and
technology are changing the world's boundaries in ways that would
have seemed unimaginable 25 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What was once the Soviet Union is now a collection of nation
states. The borders of what was once Czechoslovakia no longer
exist. The creation of the European Union makes possible the
emergence of independent states in Wales, Scotland, and the Basque
region of Spain. In the far East, everyone wonders what nations
will emerge after the inevitable collapse of the People's Republic
of China.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to home, Mexico is a nation of contradictions, capable of
splitting into three distinct parts. Its northern third is already
part of the fabric of south Texas. Puerto Rico will soon cast a
definitive vote for or against US statehood. The future of Cuba
awaits the end of Fidel. It is thought by most Americans that after
Castro departs the stage, Cuban Miami will move back to Havana. The
more likely scenario is that Cuban Havana will move to Miami. In
Florida and New Jersey, Cuban constituencies will lobby hard for
``the big island's'' inclusion into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   To the north, Monday's provincial elections left unanswered the
question of an independent Quebec. As Steven Pearlstein reported in
The Washington Post, ``Quebec separatists had looked on (these)
elections as the springboard for the final push toward independence
from Canada. Canadian federalists had sent in what they thought was
their best man to finally rout the separatists from power.
</P>
<P>
   ``About the only thing they agreed on was that neither side won.
(P)oliticians and pundits . . . saw in the final election tallies a
mandate from voters to let the question of Quebecs independence
simmer on the back burner for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   But for how long? English-speaking Canada is, in Pearlstein's
phrase, ``tiring of the seemingly endless dance with Quebec.'' A
top strategist for the separatists agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a bad marriage where one spouse wants to leave,''
Parti Quebecois adviser Jean-Francois Lisee opined in advance of
Monday's vote. ``Obviously we need to arrange joint custody of the
kids which in this case is the dollar, the national debt, certain
assets. But it's over. The truth is we will be better as courteous
neighbors than quarreling spouses.''
</P>
<P>
   Enriquez thinks it possible that English-speaking Canada could
separate from Quebec before Quebec separates from it. He notes that
the Northeastern governors of the United States have actively
engaged the Maritime provincial governments on trade, agriculture,
energy, and immigration issues.
</P>
<P>
   What prevents them from confederating with the United States,
first as protectorates, then as territories and finally as states?
For that matter, what prevents the western provinces of Canada from
confederating with the United States in like fashion? Culturally,
they are closer to the western United States than they are to
Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   How many stars will there be on the American flag in 25 years?
In 1776, there were 13. In 1876, there were 36. In 1976, there were
50, including the addition of Alaska and Hawaii in the 1950s.
America is unique among nations in this respect; it is the only one
that has grown steadily over the last 200 years.
</P>
<P>
   Before he got caught lying, President Clinton attempted to open
a dialogue on the subject of race as a means to discussing the
larger issue of national identity, borders, and ``immigration
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   America suffers from periodic outbreaks of xenophobia. We are in
the froth of such an outbreak now. The Immigration and
Naturalization Service employs more people than the FBI, more
people than the State Department, thanks to recent legislation. Pat
Buchanan and Ross Perot roil the waters with nativist appeals.
``Protecting our borders'' is proffered as political argument.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not how we ``control'' our borders. The issue is
how we erase them; how we add stars to the flag. The infrastructure
is there. Modern telecommunications obviates many boundaries. Free
trade agreements integrate territories. Economic growth eases
racial and ethnic tensions. Freedom begets possibility, which
begets hope.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration policy, as it is currently discussed, is largely
irrelevant. Integrating new states is the real issue. How we do
that will define the future of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   John Ellis is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
