<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEND INDEPENDENT PROSECUTORS BACK WHERE THEY CAME FROM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; While Kenneth Starr's four-year inquisition against President
Clinton and his friends is enough to warrant outright elimination
of the independent counsel law, the case of former Agriculture
Secretary Mike Espy is even more compelling.
</P>
<P>
   Espy's acquittal last week provides more evidence that the
independent counsel law is out of control and wreaking havoc not
only in Washington but also across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Any law that allows an independent counsel to spend four years
and $20 million on an investigation of a cabinet official based on
questionable, if not petty, charges is a law that is ill-conceived
and as dangerous as the Spanish Inquisition. Fortunately, that is
the way the jury saw the case against Espy.
</P>
<P>
   His acquittal further erodes the already waning strength of
Starr's and the GOP's case for impeachment against Clinton. The
charges against the president in the Monica Lewinsky probe appear
to be far less serious than the charges of conflicts of interest _
including accepting gifts from companies that his cabinet oversees
_ that were brought against Espy.
</P>
<P>
   Further evidence of how out of control the independent counsel
effort has become can be seen in the cases against other former and
current members of Clinton's cabinet. The list includes Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman, former Housing and Urban Development
Secretary Henry Cisneros and, before his death, Commerce Secretary
Ron Brown.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the independent counsel law even more chilling is the
way it has been used _ perhaps disproportionately _ against the few
people of color who have been able to rise to a level of power in
this administration. In addition to Espy, Herman, and Brown _ all
African-American _ and Cisneros, who is Hispanic, a case that
involved an African-American from the Reagan administration, former
HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce, is still open, even though Pierce
himself has been dropped from the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who support the independent counsel law, and how
Starr used it to go after Clinton, can argue that it was a Clinton
appointee, Attorney General Janet Reno, who appointed seven
independent counsels, or prosecutors, during her tenure. Thus far,
some 20 independent prosecutors have been appointed, at a cost of
more than $140 million, since the law was enacted in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who also has turned down several requests for independent
counsels, has incurred the wrath of both Democrats and Republicans
for her decisions. Democrats, for example, have been furious over
Reno's appointment of independent counsels to investigate Clinton
cabinet officials, while Republicans were infuriated with her
decision not to appoint an independent counsel to investigate Vice
President Al Gore's campaign fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps feeling pressure from both sides, Reno requested and was
granted a 60-day extension of her deadline for deciding whether to
appoint an outside prosecutor to investigate former White House
deputy chief of staff Harold M. Ickes's dealings with the Teamsters
Union.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno is not the problem. In an apparent effort to maintain
her own integrity and credibility on the job, she has used the only
law available to her that provides for an outside and independent
counsel. But Reno, the presidency, and the nation itself would have
been far better off if there were no such law.
</P>
<P>
   Since its beginning in the Watergate years, the law has served
no useful purpose; it has not enhanced, nor even maintained, the
nation's system of justice nor the integrity of the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   In the wrong hands, such as Starr's, it can be used as a
political weapon aimed at removing a president the opposing party
could not defeat at the polls. If anything, the law has hindered,
if not diminished, the nation's ability to maintain a judicial
system that is fair to everyone.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt the creation of an independent counsel law seemed to be
the right thing to do during the era of Watergate, when the crime
in question could do far more damage to the foundation of American
justice than the current ``sexgate'' scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But as impartial as the work of independent counsel Archibald
Cox was before President Nixon resigned, it is easy to see what
happens when the same law is in the hands of an unrestrained
partisan on behalf of conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has aptly demonstrated that the law, with its unlimited
time and resources, goes too far and must be reined in. Perhaps
after this impeachment inquiry is finally over, Congress will take
the time to review the independent counsel law and decide that
simply imposing limitations on it may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   In the wrong hands, a weapon that can fire bullets, whether
legal or lead, can be just as damaging at 50 yards as 100 yards The
prudent choice would be to eliminate this law before it destroys
our system of justice, and ultimately, our nation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
