<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6585 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOONEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-07 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOONEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DNC'S GROSSMAN GOES OUT ON TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN C. MOONEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Grossman's sense of timing may be even better than his
political instincts.
</P>
<P>
   After a boffo two-year run, the Newton businessman-activist
announced this week that he will step down as chairman of the
Democratic National Committee. He's going out on top.
</P>
<P>
   When he assumed the post, the party was staggering from a
fund-raising scandal, an $18 million debt, and the prospect of a
blowout in the 1998 election.
</P>
<P>
   When he departs next month, the fund-raising base will be
broader, the debt $5 million, and the party poised to reclaim a
majority in the US House of Representatives in 2000 after the
improbable successes in last month's election.
</P>
<P>
   In this space last May, Grossman cheerily predicted the 1998
congressional elections would be a win for Democrats because of
strategic targeting of resources and organization at the local
level. We thought he was delusional. Every so-called expert did.
</P>
<P>
   After all, only once since the Civil War had the party of the
president gained congressional seats in a mid-term election. After
all, the Monica Lewinsky scandal was gripping the country.
</P>
<P>
   But after all, Steve Grossman was right. Democrats picked up
five seats in the House and broke even in Senate fights.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is nothing self-aggrandizing in the timing of
Grossman's exit. That wouldn't be his style anyway. His 79-year-old
father, Edgar, is ailing, and Grossman wants to spend more time
with his wife, Barbara, a theater professor-historian, and
9-year-old son, Joshua, youngest of their three boys.
</P>
<P>
   He's earned the respite. In two years at the DNC, he logged at
least 300,000 miles in flight as prolific fund-raiser and
ambassador to the Democratic Party's core constituency groups.
</P>
<P>
   Grossman's done his job (foregoing a $136,000 salary, we would
note), served his party and his president remarkably well, and is
coming home to concentrate on his family, his business, the
Massachusetts Envelope Co., and many other interests. He sits on 16
civic, cultural, and philanthropic boards. They include the Museum
of Fine Arts, Brandeis University, Beth Israel Deaconess and
Children's hospitals, Combined Jewish Philanthropies, the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, and the Robert F. Kennedy
Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   In an increasingly grubby, grasping, and cynical business, this
52-year-old retains his idealism. He is partisan and passionate
about his politics, but he plays by the rules. And he plays to win.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who observed Grossman's work as chairman of the
Massachusetts Democratic Party in 1991-92, the national party's
successes on Nov. 3 should have been no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived after the Democratic disaster of 1990, when
Republicans were elected governor, lieutenant governor, and
treasurer and knocked off six Democratic state senators to win
enough seats to sustain Governor William F. Weld's vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   For the '92 election cycle, Grossman zeroed in on those key
districts, recapturing four of the lost seats and ousting two other
veteran GOP senators in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   He was dogged. On the Sunday before the election, Grossman, an
aide, and son Josh, then age three, tailed Weld's Republican
caravan across the state into five contested senate districts. At
each stop, he offered reporters the Democratic counterpoint.
</P>
<P>
   As the day wore on, the Republicans' pique grew, finally
exploding late in the day in Weymouth, when GOP congressional
hopeful Dan Daly angrily upbraided Grossman in front of the TV
cameras. That prompted young Josh to break into tears.
</P>
<P>
   Why was his son was crying, a reporter asked Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joshua always cries when Republicans lie,'' he responded,
creating the sound bite that topped the nightly news.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the DNC does not mean Grossman is retiring from the
game. He continues to be a major donor to the Democratic Party,
giving about $100,000 each of the past two years. (Is it any wonder
he supports public financing of campaigns?) Once he steps down, he
said he will end his strict neutrality and become an advocate for
Boston, over Denver and Los Angeles, as the site of the 2000
Democratic National Convention. And he remains active locally. On
his resume, between former state party chairman and director of
Combined Jewish Philanthropies, he lists ``Member, Ward 7, Newton
Democratic Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, last month, at a National Association of Secretaries
of State subcommittee meeting on presidential primaries, he
proposed a bipartisan commission, on which he'd be willing to
serve, to study ways to increase voter participation.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone should welcome that because politics needs people like
Steve Grossman.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian C. Mooney is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
