<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6599 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PAXTON-2TAKES-     12-07 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PAXTON-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAXTON'S `PLAN' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a story about fathers and brothers and fate and
gorillas. They all come together in the person of the quietest guy
on the A-list, Bill Paxton. When he was growing up in Fort Worth,
he ruefully admits, there was a Wild Bill Paxton stage. These days
he's content to soft-pedal his rise to stardom, describing it as an
up-the-back-stairs climb. In the last few years, he's appeared in
as many blockbusters as anyone: ``Apollo 13,'' ``Twister,''
``Titanic.'' We'll see him in two holiday movies. On Friday, he'll
be the farm-town Everyman who stumbles on a bag of dirty money in
``A Simple Plan.'' On Christmas Day, he'll be the save-the-gorilla
character in Disney's remake of ``Mighty Joe Young.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, he's sitting at a hotel dining room table in Boston,
too good a Texas storyteller to get around to eating, effortlessly
and fluently forging the links any good actor finds between his
material and his life. His own father was his link to acting,
Paxton says, and to ``A Simple Plan.'' Five years ago, his father
read Scott Smith's dark moral allegory, and told Paxton, ``You
gotta play this part.'' ``I said, `Dad, that's great, but they're
not going to be calling me. I know there's gonna be guys fighting
to play it.' There were. Nicolas Cage was the first choice to star,
Mike Nichols to direct. But when the Hollywood roulette wheel
stopped spinning, Paxton was aboard with Sam Raimi directing.
</P>
<P>
   Paxton's father, John, a retired traveling salesman for his
family's hardwood lumber business, is in the movie, too. He plays a
testy farmer who comes to the feed store where Bill Paxton's
character works, grumbling about being overbilled, only to be told
that the month he's complaining about had five Mondays in it.
``It's my dad's sixth or seventh picture,'' the younger Paxton
says. ``I got him a Screen Actors Guild card in `Brain Dead.' In
`Last Man Standing,' the remake of `Yojimbo' shot in Texas, my dad
was the town undertaker. He keeps tipping his hat to Bruce Willis,
who keeps his business flourishing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the connections are only just beginning. The linchpin
relationship in ``A Simple Plan'' is between Paxton's charater and
his older brother, who, to put it softly, has been less favored by
life. The discovery of the money does not promote harmony between
them. Billy Bob Thornton plays Paxton's brother in a remarkable
turn, and, Paxton says, a satisfying follow-up to their
collaboration in a breakthrough film for both of them and director
Carl Franklin, ``One False Move.'' Because Thornton had the
narrowest window of time, they had to shoot the scenes with him _
the film's most intense _ first.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jumping right in
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only their mutual familiarity made it possible to jump into the
sturm und drang they had to whip up on the wing. Something else
helped. The brothers' relationship in the film paralleled that of
his own life, Paxton says. ``My brother Bob is not unlike the
character Billy plays, which made the experience an intensely
personal one for me. We were always very close. We grew up
together. We shared a room together. We went to camp together. My
brother right now lives in a school in Kentucky. He's very bright.
He does volunteer work. He puts components together in a factory
there and he's kind of the unofficial mayor of the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother was really the emotionally sensitive child. When he
was 24, he was in a horrendous car accident. He had severe trauma
which left him with permanent damage. He damaged his optic nerve
and lost about 95 percent of his vision, so this compounded an
already emotionally sensitive person. So I can relate to the
situation with these two brothers. Also, in the film, the guy I
play is married and had a young family. I'm in a similar situation.
A lot of people say Bridget (Bridget Fonda, who plays Paxton's wife
in the film) kind of turns into a Lady Macbeth and all that. But in
my own relationship with my wife, there have been moments of
emotional crisis where I have been indecisive, and she has risen to
the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Paxton was taken to more movies and plays and art
galleries by his father than to football games. Unlike, say,
``Twister,'' in which he costarred against a screenful of
computer-generated wind, ``A Simple Plan'' is much more an actor's
piece, probably the most subtle he's done. The 43-year-old actor
reaches into the world of art to describe the changes in his
acting. ``When you start out, you're always saying, `Hey, look at
me! Look at my choices!' As you get older, you think more like a
craftsman. You kind of want to find a subtler way, to create more
impact with minimal effort. I admire artists like Picassso and
Matisse, who as they get to the end of their lives, start doing
line drawings, very minimal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A leap of faith
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn to trust the audience more. Without giving too much
away, in this film I do something bad, but I want the audience to
make a leap of faith with me and still hope we come out OK. I said,
`Sam, what if I just look away and try to think that I'm on a beach
in Mexico with a pina colada and I'm not really doing this? This
isn't me really doing it.' I sometimes try and remove myself from
the action, and that seemed to work a lot better, although I could
have used a little more finesse. It helped that this movie only
cost $15 million, so there was less pressure, and I could
experiment with trying to ask for sympathy while I was doing
something bad.''
</P>
<P>
   There were times when Paxton, who started in Hollywood in 1974
as a set dresser on the strength of a letter his father wrote to a
producer, actually did remove himself from the action. After moving
to New York to study acting, he returned to Los Angeles and got
what could have been his first break when, as understudy, he
inherited the lead in the West Coast premiere of Sam Shepherd's
drama, ``Curse of the Starving Class.'' ``Suddenly I was thrust
center stage,'' Paxton recalls. ``All I could think was that I
should be better. I literally pressured myself right out of the
part. I ended up literally running away from Hollywood and going
back to New York.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1408EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6601 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-SOLMAN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     12-07 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-SOLMAN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 NEW YORK: ... external world.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I don't know what a lot of these characters are painting these
days,'' Solman notes of abstractionists. ``They take one symbol and
just use it again and again: painters who know more and more about
less and less. I like artists who are moved by subject matter.
That's why I never went for abstraction: The (external) subject has
more interest than any shape we might invent. I take what's out
there, and that's what lights up my imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Art has been a part of Solman's life since boyhood. ``I always
loved pictures,'' he explains. ``I remember drawing kids on my
block when I was 12 or 13 years of age. When I went to the National
Academy, I had to ride the elevated trains from Jamaica, on Long
Island, then change to the subway, up to 110th Street, to the
academy, which would take a couple of hours. (I never dreamed I'd
later become treasurer of the academy. I looked down on the place:
It was academic, so stultified.) I drew on my pads during the ride
back and forth. On the way back it would be late at night, 10-ish,
and people would be asleep. That meant they would be posed
perfectly. So I learned more to draw on the subway than I ever did
in the academy!''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, Solman held various jobs to support his
painting. He worked as a night-elevator operator in the '20s and
first part of the '30s. The WPA let him work full time as an artist
during the Depression. Later, he'd work six months a year as a
parimutuel clerk at various New York racetracks. ``That was more
romantic to my son than my being an artist,'' Solman laughs. (That
son, Paul Solman, is economics correspondent for PBS's ``NewsHour
with Jim Lehrer'' and helped organize the Mercury Gallery show.) He
also taught, giving private lessons during the '50s and '60s, and
then served on the faculty at the City University of New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Negative on art criticism
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Especially during his WPA days, Solman wrote extensively on art.
He was coeditor, with Schapiro and Harold Rosenberg, of Art Front
magazine and was one of the first writers in English to discuss the
great French photographer Eugene Atget. Still, he professes
bewilderment at the vagaries of critical taste and contends that
art criticism holds little value for the artist. During his
teaching days, Solman had a standard response when students asked
him what to read: ``Pick a book where you like the pictures and the
text is in a language you don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Solman's ``main focus'' these days is that supremely New York
subject, the skyscraper. The buildings used to intimidate him, he
says, but now he's made hundreds of drawings of them, the shifting
visual relations among the towers, and the way they relate to the
sky, making for a subject of endless variety and intricacy. ``I
like to go out making notes,'' he says of these drawings. ``It's
part of the adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   He has a regular route, heading up to 59th or 60th Street, then
over to Fifth Avenue, where he takes the bus down to 38th Street.
All the while he works his sketch pad. ``The skyscrapers form a
pattern with the sky in between that at different times of the day
creates these sky shapes, surrounded by the canyons of the big
buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Solman distills the drawings for a much smaller group of
paintings. ``In some cases,'' he explains, ``I do it almost as
silhouettes painted against a strange sky, a lavender sky or a
yellow sky, something like that. With these paintings, I feel like
I'm at the beginning of a long trek, a new career. This new theme,
I feel I've hardly explored it. It's going to take a few years to
develop.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the sort of thing one expects to hear from a man who
turns 90 next month. Solman laughs. ``When I was 79, I bragged a
bit _ that seemed like a pretty substantial number. When I hit 80,
though, it was kind of a solar plexus punch. Now I've gotten used
to it. I don't think of age any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE TEN OPENS IN NEW YORK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ten: Rothko, Solman and the Birth of the American
Avant-garde,'' now at the Mercury Gallery, marks the 60th
anniversary of the New York exhibition ``The Ten: Whitney
Dissenters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dissenters'' was the right word. The Ten, comprising such
painters as Mark Rothko, Joseph Solman, Ben-Zion, Ilya Bolotowsky,
and Adolph Gottlieb, had one thing in common: a devout opposition
to the art establishment of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were important because, in the late '30s, when they were
painting and exhibiting together, there was not too much
avant-garde in New York,'' says Isabelle Dervaux, a curator at
Washington's National Gallery of Art. ``The Ten were among the few
artists who wanted to go against the dominant position of, for
instance, the Whitney Museum.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ten was founded in 1935, when it had its first exhibition. A
combination of political tensions and the growing success of
individual members led in 1939 to the group's demise. The only
thing that had united them was iconoclasm. Among the Ten, one can
find traces of Cubism, Surrealism, and Expressionism, and the
influence of artists as diverse as Milton Avery and Chaim Soutine.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't really have a leader, says Dervaux, ``but Solman and
Rothko were more active in keeping the group together and
organizing exhibitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Rothko, of course, went on to become one of the most famous
Abstract Expressionists. Solman, the youngest of the group, is its
sole surviving member.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1408EST &QL; 
