<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6603 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-VENICE-2TAKES-B     12-07 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-VENICE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE QUALITY OF MERCY IN `VENICE' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Imagine any contemporary legal proceeding _ say, a
scene from a high-profile criminal trial, or a snapshot of the
Judiciary Committee's impeachment hearings, or a glimpse of
testimony in the Justice Department's suit against Microsoft. The
opposing sides are lined up as usual; the lawyers are there,
starched and pressed and ready to pounce. And then in walks a
surprise witness, an unknown scholar who silences the room with an
unexpected plea. ``The quality of mercy is not strained,'' the
witness says, softly. ``It droppeth as the gentle rain from heaven
upon the place beneath.''
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, mayhem would ensue. The prosecution would surely
object. Who is this anachronistic soul, daring to wax eloquent
about the concept of mercy in a court of law? Surely, this person
must be either painfully naive or soft on crime. After all, the
dirty rotten rascals get away with it all the time and they deserve
what they get.
</P>
<P>
   Compassion? Mercy? Irrelevant. Next witness, please.
</P>
<P>
   In these cynical, litigious times, such a scene seems highly
unlikely, but it lies at the heart of director Andrei Serban's
production of ``The Merchant of Venice'' for the American Repertory
Theatre, which begins previews Friday at the Loeb Drama Center in
Cambridge and opens Dec. 16. This controversial drama, one of
Shakespeare's ``problem'' plays, is disturbing to contemporary
audiences for many reasons, most notably for the anti-Semitism
surrounding Shylock, the Jewish moneylender who demands a pound of
flesh from the errant borrower Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   But it is also a study of clashing cultures, of a world in which
the characters are so caught up in the nail-breaking, back-stabbing
struggle for money and power and acceptance that they lose sight of
the simple notion of forgiveness. That is what fascinates Serban
about the play, and he seems to be driving the actors to explore
the possibility of compassion in a merciless society where sides
are drawn quickly and firmly in even the most ambiguous of court
cases. He views the play as an allegory, and his rehearsal process
is raising painful questions for the actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rattling,'' says Kristin Flanders, who as Portia delivers
that beautiful speech about mercy. ``I find that my own issues of
faith are surfacing in ways that they haven't since I was very
young. I mean, really, what your beliefs are. It rattles. It
resonates. It forces you to ask really difficult questions about
cultural difference, and in America, that's very, very hard. It's
hard for us to have those conversations.'' She pauses, drops her
head into her hands, and stares long and hard at a spot on the
floor. For the actress who conquered Kate in last season's ``The
Taming of the Shrew,'' the words don't come easily. ``What am I
talking about? I'm talking about faith, about one's earliest
development. Because it's an allegory, it takes you back to that
simplest point, that place where faith first springs, which is very
young. I can't be more specific, and I don't want to be more
specific. It's just faith. Blind faith.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A challenging position
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Loeb, men with jackhammers are tearing up the brick
sidewalk. The ground rattles. It shakes.
</P>
<P>
   Like Flanders, Jonathan Epstein is also finding himself in a
disturbing yet challenging position as he prepares for the role of
Antonio. This summer, he played Shylock in Shakespeare &AMP; Company's
acclaimed production of ``Merchant,'' and he spent the summer
getting under the skin of a man who is taunted and persecuted in
Venice and who, as a result, becomes hardened and cruel. Epstein
found his own way for the character to make peace with himself and
with his God, but after spending so much time ``loading the dice''
for Shylock, he now finds himself on the other side. As Antonio, he
is the taunter, and he needs to grasp the roots of his character's
prejudice. For someone who has experienced anti-Semitism in his own
life, that's not particularly easy. It rattles. It resonates. ``As
a Jew in the everyday world, I spend more time thinking about how
not to be brought down by prejudice than I do about how to
understand it,'' Epstein says. ``I don't know if this will lead to
some great sense of forgiveness, but at least I'm beginning to
understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding has a price. ``Both roles are painful to play,''
Epstein says. ``It's not difficult to depict the behavior of
someone who says these things, but it's difficult to allow that
spirit to possess my own spirit. It takes courage to let them in
all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   In letting those feelings in, the actors hope to make a bigger
point. ``The reason for doing the play is to get at a universal
truth about mercy and compassion _ or the lack of it,'' says Will
Lebow, the actor playing Shylock at ART.
</P>
<P>
   All the actors, interviewed separately, are speaking the same
language, wrestling with the same question in their own way. Serban
is driving that struggle. ``A man who cannot find mercy in himself
is a man who has no heart,'' the director says quietly. ``From that
point of view, it is a morality play that teaches us that we have
to find mercy, which is higher than any law or logic of the mind.''
The director exudes a sort of calm in the uncommon quiet of the
Loeb lobby, but outside, the jackhammers do their dance of
destruction, rattling the foundation below the ground.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1409EST &QL; 
