<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6604 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JFK-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      12-07 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JFK-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS WORRIED JFK A YEAR BEFORE ASSASSINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year before his Nov. 22, 1963, assassination in
Dallas, President John F. Kennedy chatted on the telephone with
Texas Gov. John Connally about the hostile political situation he
faced there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why we do anything for Dallas,'' JFK said after
reviewing the midterm election results of the day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you,'' the Texas governor responded, ``they just
murdered all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Connally was unaware his blunt remarks were being taped. Twelve
months later, both men would be shot riding in an open car through
the same Texas city where right-wing politics had caused Kennedy
such concern.
</P>
<P>
   In the Nov. 7, 1962, tape, recently made available at the John
F. Kennedy Library in Boston, we hear the reason for Kennedy's
frustration. He was watching Texas, especially Dallas, as it began
the conservative drift that continues to this day.
</P>
<P>
   Connally chalked up the shift to economics. ``They're just a
bunch of ... junior executives ... and these society gals,'' he
said of the voters in booming Dallas. ``They just got 'em a crusade
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy: ``What did we, what did we lose Dallas by _ do you
remember? _ in 1960?''
</P>
<P>
   Connally: ``You lost (by) over 60,000 votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy: ``60,000 votes! Hell, I got ... You know they're up
there talking to me about having that federal building down there
and all the rest of that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Connally: ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy: ``I don't know why we do anything for Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, talking about the bad Democratic showing in the 1962
election, Connally warned Kennedy about the dire political
situation he would face in Texas seeking re-election in 1964: ``I'm
telling you, they just murdered all of us. Our party's gone down in
the past six years. They had a hate campaign going, very frankly.
They were running against Cuba and against you and the vice
president ... It was a protest, a helluva protest vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Connally was referring to Fidel Castro's Cuba, which recently
had tried to deploy Soviet missiles aimed at the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The following November, history grimly would record, JFK
traveled to Texas in hopes of healing the political damage that had
cut the president's statewide approval rating to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As Kennedy drove from Fort Worth to the airport that morning for
the short flight to Dallas, Jim Wright, then the local Democratic
representative, recalled Connally giving the president the same
analysis he had given him on the phone the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Riding alongside Kennedy, Connally _ then a Democrat but later a
party-switcher _ explained the rightward shift in Dallas politics
to the city's economic structure. He said the city had become a
high-rise boom town of banks and insurance companies, all filled
with men in white shirts who increasingly identified with the
Republican Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6606 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAGE-VENICE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     12-07 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-VENICE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... the ground.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Merchant of Venice'' was originally written as a comedy,
with Shylock portrayed as a commedia dell'arte clown, the perennial
outsider striving to fit in. You may remember the story. Shylock
lends 3,000 ducats to Bassanio, a Venetian gentleman down on his
luck. Bassanio's friend Antonio (the merchant of the title) agrees
to give a pound of his flesh if the bond is not repaid. Meanwhile,
Bassanio woos and wins Portia in her bucolic home in Belmont, which
is far removed from the mercantile world of Venice. When Antonio
cannot repay the money, Shylock sticks to the letter of the law and
demands the pound of flesh. Portia disguises herself as a man and
goes to court to plead for Antonio's life; Shylock refuses to
listen and is ultimately destroyed. His daughter rejects him and he
is forced to convert to Christianity. But Portia is also betrayed
by Bassanio.
</P>
<P>
   There's no denying the anti-Semitism in this ``comedy.'' In the
world of the play, Shylock is a ``devil'' and a ``dog,'' driven to
assert his own humanity in his moving ``Hath not a Jew eyes?''
speech. Given the atrocities of the 20th century, it is simply
impossible to see the play as Shakespeare wrote it. But while
Serban acknowledges the anti-Semitism running through the story, he
is not making that brand of hate the centerpiece of his production.
``I'm not at all interested in doing what many contemporary
productions have done, which is to emphasize and exaggerate the
racist aspect of the play by making the tension between the
Christians and the Jews more acute than it is,'' Serban says. ``I'm
not trying to apologize for Shylock. I think our world today is a
much more fragmented world than Shakespeare's world. It's much more
alienated. One feels exiled from one's own home, from one's own
parents. That kind of alienation, that kind of loneliness at the
end of the 20th century, is so apocalyptic. In that sense, we are
all Shylock. And where, in the middle of all this, can we find our
hearts?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the question that is rattling the actors. Flanders is
questioning her faith. Epstein is trying to understand the source
of prejudice he's faced all of his life. And Lebow, who considers
himself an ``ethnic Jew,'' is recalling his childhood growing up in
Richmond Hill in Queens, which was 90 percent Catholic, 8 percent
Lutheran, and 2 percent ``Other.'' He fit into the category of
Other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally, we were the only Jewish family within, I don't
know, a couple of miles,'' Lebow says. ``My whole life was about
fitting in _ or I guess the new politically correct word is
`assimilate.' I actually had a couple of years in elementary school
where I was _ what's the word? _ I was taunted, persecuted by a few
of my fellow students. I would get letters signed `Adolf Eichmann,'
and I would get printed invitations to barbecues where they said
they would be roasting the Jews. I dealt with this for a couple of
years and then, finally, I went to the principal and the assistant
principal of the school, and they investigated it.''
</P>
<P>
   We are all Shylock.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the kinds of memories that lurk beneath the surface of
any production of ``Merchant,'' but Lebow and the others contend
that the point is not to pound home the obvious anti-Semitism but
rather to explore the possibility of an alternative. And let's not
be naive: Possibility is not the same thing as probability.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `A beautiful hell'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Venice is like hell,'' Serban says. ``It's a beautiful hell,
but it's hell just the same. And that's very much our world.
Belmont, on the other hand, is a utopia, an arcadia, the place we
would all wish to live. That's the paradox of the play. Belmont is
a place of possibility. It doesn't exist, for sure, but it's
something we are all longing for. It's the island that we all hope
we can go to.''
</P>
<P>
   Serban is known for imposing his concepts through startling
visual images. In his 1989 production of ``Twelfth Night,'' he
juxtaposed a tomb and a tavern, creating a haunting world where
love can be as soothing or as fierce as waves on a beach, depending
on your point of view. Last season, he transformed ``Shrew'' into a
rock-'em-sock-'em boxing match, turning the play into an
unforgettable if ambiguous experience. And he says he is thinking
about ``Merchant'' like a dramatic canvas, set ``vaguely'' in the
20th century with the usual mix of eclectic costumes. ``It's like
an abstract painting with splashes of red and gold for Venice,'' he
says. ``The red is the passion, and the gold is, well, obviously
the gold. For Belmont, the colors are beautiful van Gogh yellows
and greens, like daylight. It's full of life and full of vibrant
color, which is almost like a Garden of Eden of our imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Belmont is precisely that: a figment of our imagination. It is
there that mercy ultimately comes into play. After the characters
utterly destroy Shylock, they all head back to Belmont, where
Portia is faced with a decision about Bassanio. He has betrayed her
by declaring his love for Antonio. Can she forgive him? Can she let
her husband _ and his lover _ into her heart and into her home? In
this imagined arcadia, can she practice what she preached in court?
If mercy eludes us in our civic lives, how can we embrace it in our
domestic lives?
</P>
<P>
   Those are the questions that are rattling the actors,
particularly Flanders. ``The notion of compassion is the most
important notion we have,'' she says. ``Portia goes from the
political conflict in court to the domestic conflict of her
husband's relationship with a gay man. Can she, in fact, accept the
Other in her own house? I mean, who is this woman? It's rattling me
because compassion is so _'' A pause. ``It's so hard. We live in a
world that's very severe. We keep drawing harsh lines. We're all
working. We're all stressed out. This play asks really big, big
questions about what we're capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   In the play, she's the one who pleads so eloquently for mercy,
but in this world, she's not so sure it's possible. She keeps
coming back to that speech _ ``The quality of mercy is not
strained.'' She's reminded of her conflicted reaction to the O. J.
Simpson verdict. She's reminded of the hearings in Washington, D.C.
She can't imagine strolling into a contemporary courtroom and
speaking those words. It's rattling, rattling like the clang of a
jackhammer digging at the neurons in her brain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
