<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6607 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-07 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIKE ESPY: NO MODEL FOR PUBLIC SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy last week
was exonerated of criminal charges of corruption by a federal court
jury, an action he naturally hailed as a vindication of himself and
a tacit endorsement of his behavior while in office.
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. Although the jury in Washington, D.C., had trouble
sorting out criminal and ethical violations, Espy's conduct in
office hardly qualifies him as a paragon of a worthy public
servant.
</P>
<P>
   Actions that he has acknowledged, while found not to have been
criminal offenses, nevertheless reveal a languid respect for
self-evident elementary ethics.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't take a saint to comprehend that a person serving in
the Cabinet should not be taking or soliciting costly gifts from
anyone, even though the laws and regulations may be ill-defined and
even contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   Espy had been the target of an investigation by yet another
indefatigable independent counsel, Donald C. Smaltz, who spent four
years and more than $17 million pursuing the corruption
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the finding of not guilty on each of 30 counts of
taking gifts or goods from business people and lobbyists, who had
interests and activities that came under the purview of the
Department of Agriculture, gave additional aid and comfort to those
who want to do away with the Office of Independent Counsel.
Opponents of that particular post-Watergate reform were already
turned off by the conduct of Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel
assigned to hunt down President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The overkill of the Smaltz prosecution does not validate Espy's
conduct in office. He was openly contemptuous of ethical strictures
governing federal employees, according to the testimony of a fellow
presidential appointee.
</P>
<P>
   His disregard of the rules that exist in statute and that
decency itself prescribe was demonstrated by the dollar value of
the gifts, tickets to sporting events as well as other goodies that
came to him or his girlfriend. Adding them all up, they amounted to
$35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Espy argued in his defense that the gifts came from friends and
as such were not illegal (although federal rules don't appear to
make that distinction).
</P>
<P>
   But it takes an uncommon kind of friendship that would produce
that scale of largess over a couple of years. Most friends are
inclined to send a buddy the occasional birthday card; they don't
shower a pal with thousands of dollars worth of freebies.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a friendship in which gift-giving of this magnitude
was part of the relationship would seemingly call for the
benefactions to flow both ways, in roughly equitable measure. This
did not appear to have happened with Espy and his friends in the
large food companies that were regulated by the Agriculture
Department.
</P>
<P>
   It is plain that a government executive should be circumspect in
all relationships to guard against favoritism. With old friends,
there is a need for particular rectitude to assure that the
continuing relationship is kept above reproach and untainted by
cronyism.
</P>
<P>
   Espy's attorneys further argued, with apparent success, that the
independent counsel did not and could not show any tit for tat for
the gifts. A different court, a federal appeals court, had ruled
that such a tradeoff would have to be shown for a proper
prosecution on corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other ways for a government executive to help out
his friends, by supporting policies and decisions that make them
friends in the first place. This is not a new practice in
Washington, and the point is not to make Espy the scapegoat for a
political culture that has had a long history, with many
distinguished participants in one form or another. After all,
Ronald Reagan's friends bought him a very expensive house as soon
as he left the presidency, and George Bush received astronomical
honoraria for speechmaking once out of office.
</P>
<P>
   But the Espy case highlights the necessity to examine the
political culture that tolerates the kind of mutual back
scratching, which, without exception, interferes with the public
being well served. That culture also embraces the scandalous manner
in which political campaign contributions are raised and used.
</P>
<P>
   Espy is far from the worst offending freeloader in the nation's
history. A host of miscreants have committed not only ethical but
also criminal violations of the public trust, for which some were
disgraced while others also went to the slammer.
</P>
<P>
   But his victory in court is not entirely a matter for rejoicing
that still another heavy-handed prosecutor has fallen on the sword
of his overwrought ambition. It is even more a signal indicating
how much the public needs to insist on maintaining high standards
for public service, and not be discouraged by how frequently that
appears daunting.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
