<HEADER>
A6610 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-GIFT-2TAKES-BOS     12-07 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GIFT-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR'S BEST GIFT BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gift books represent a special category of Christmas present _
each requires a sizable cash or credit investment and a full sheet
of wrapping paper, not to mention a strong back if you plan to buy
more than one or two. Gift books are easier to receive than give.
Some of them thrive on display, others offer pride of ownership;
some provide luxurious opportunities for the pleasures of leisurely
poring; and a few of the best may prove truly useful.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas celebrates a birth, so ``Babies Celebrated'' by
Beatrice Fontanel and Claire d'Harcourt (Abrams, $39.95) makes a
particularly appropriate choice. With the help of an international
team of 16 enthnologists, the authors and photographers document
how babies are cherished, and how the problems they present are
dealt with, in many world cultures. There is nothing sentimental
about this, and some of the images are heart-stopping; all of them
are pictures of love.
</P>
<P>
   David Macaulay's ``The Way Things Work'' has sold more than 1
million copies since it was first published, a decade ago. Now it
has been reprinted as ``The New Way Things Work'' (Houghton
Mifflin, $35). What makes it new is a chapter in which an amiable
mammoth, prehistoric and therefore no more slow-witted than the
average reader, explores the wonders of ``The Digital Domain,''
which include the digital thermometer, the fax machine, the swipe
card, the bar code, the CD, e-mail, the cash dispenser, the flight
simulator, and the supermarket checkout and inventory system.
``Tools: Making Things Around the World'' by Hubert Comte (Abrams,
$75) is a less individual and original book, but it makes a nice
complement, using photographs, paintings, and text to show some of
the implements people have devised throughout history to make their
jobs easier _ or even possible. Here you can see how a barrel is
made, or examine a Tibetan knife, the small, utilitarian blade
attached to a totemic tiger's tooth.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Tabori &AMP; Chang has reprinted Thomas Bulfinch's
pioneering collection of Greek and Roman myths from 1855 as ``The
Illustrated Age of Fable,'' with 100 ``illustrations'' of the
mythological stories drawn from the works of Michelangelo,
Botticelli, Titian, Rubens, and others down through the
pre-Raphaelites ($40). The reproductions are unfortunately
sometimes too small for mythic detail to register.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Folk: Classic Tales Retold'' by Charles Sullivan,
with watercolor illustrations by Warren Infield (Abrams, $39.95),
collects 60 folk tales from various regions of our country and
periods of our history. Some are invented, some are embroidered on
historical figures and incidents, on good guys (and gals) like Davy
Crockett, Paul Bunyan, Pocahontas, and the unsinkable Molly Brown,
or on bad guys like Billy the Kid and Jesse James, along with Rip
van Winkle, Johnny Appleseed, and Br'er Rabbit and Br'er Fox. It's
nice to have all these stories in one place, but Sullivan is more
inhibited by political correctness than any authentic folklorist
would be, and he provides no survey of his sources.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bill created his own myth, and much of the myth of the
Wild West. ``Buffalo Bill's Wild West: An American Legend'' by R.
L. Wilson with Greg Martin (Random House, $60), entertainingly
shows us how he did it, with many illustrations drawn from the
Michael Del Castello Collection of the American West. Annie Oakley
gets her own chapter, and there is a photograph of her shooting an
apple off the head of her fearless English setter Dave.
</P>
<P>
   In 1938, two kids from Cleveland, Jerry Siegel and Joe Shuster,
created one of the most popular modern American myths. Superman's
exploits have earned him a splendid new illustrated history by Les
Daniels, ``The Life and Times of the Man of Steel'' (Chronicle
Books, $29.95). This includes many reproductions of rare comic
books, and Daniels tells the story of the many metamorphoses of the
caped and almost-invincible hero with a light touch, always
remembering what is worth taking seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Marco Tosa's ``Barbie: Four Decades of Fashion, Fantasy and
Fun'' (Abrams, $19.95) depicts the history of a doll introduced to
the marketplace in 1959 (when it sold for $3). Barbie has been best
known as a fashion model, but she has been a rock star, a
pediatrician, a scuba diver, a firefighter, a paleontologist, a
Rockette, and a baseball player. She has become more anatomically
correct, and her features have adapted themselves to different
cultural values, with particular success in Japan. Tosa is nothing
if not serious about his work, introducing chapters with quotes
from Emily Dickinson, H. P. Lovecraft, and Marilyn Monroe. One
wishes he thought this was amusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Versace: The Naked &AMP; the Dressed'' (Random House, $50)
presents 20 years of the extravagant photographs Richard Avedon
took to promote the extravagant collections of designer Gianni
Versace. ``This is a glimpse of the impassioned, shameless,
opulent, titillating sewmanship of that daredevil magician of art
and artifice who was and will always be Gianni Versace,'' read the
few lines of text. Rock and pop stars mingle with the models, and
nothing is more alarming than the cover photograph of Elton John
throwing a bejeweled punch in high heels and an off-the shoulder
beaded black gown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confessions of a Window Dresser: Tales from a Life in
Fashion'' (Penguin Studio and Callaway Editions, $40) by Simon
Doonan, ``the Mercedes of window dressing,'' is a volume that
touches on real issues without taking itself too seriously. The
author describes his book as ``a celebration of my alternative
sensibility and validation for everyone who feels dissed by moral
majority norms,'' which are not often represented in his windows
for Barney's in New York. A papier-mache Jesse Helms adorned with
Santa Claus hat sat in a post-nuclear junkyard with a book of
Robert Mapplethorpe's opened on his lap; his reindeer were named
Homophobia, Racism, and Bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   In the field of history, two books stand out. Susan Watkins's
``The Public and Private Worlds of Elizabeth I'' (Thames and
Hudson, $40) treats a familiar, perpetually popular subject in a
fresh way by approaching it through the visual record left by
Elizabeth's world _ not simply portraits of the monarch but of her
homes, her collections, her possessions (her riding boots, her
saddle, her gloves); impersonal historic grandeur becomes immediate
and intimate here. ``Nicholas &AMP; Alexandra: The Last Imperial Family
of Tsarist Russia'' ($75) is the illustrated catalog of an
exhibition organized by the Hermitage Museum and the State Archive
of the Russian Federation that documents the life of the doomed
czar and his family in gorgeous and sometimes heartbreaking visual
detail; the book is better than the movie.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1411EST &QL; 
