<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN: THE ULTIMATE `LEARNING SYSTEM' 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here's all you need to know about Microsoft: The
company calls its line of high-tech toys ``learning systems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to your room and interact with your learning systems.'' It
doesn't sound right, unless you're talking to Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   At FAO Schwarz, 18-month-old Connor Patrick Kelly toddled up to
two of Microsoft's $109.95 Actimates learning systems, the
Interactive Barney and the Interactive Arthur. He pointed at each
and said ``Arthur'' and ``Barney'' for the benefit of his mother,
Berni Kelly of Turlock, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Connor then pressed a sample button under an Arthur doll (a PBS
aardvark with glasses that bears a resemblance to Gates). Arthur
said, ``Hey, let's say the alphabet backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur is aimed at kids between 4 and 8, but it also could be a
great learning system for adults who get pulled over by the police
and need backwards alphabet skills.
</P>
<P>
   As Connor pushed other buttons, Arthur kept suggesting memory
and self-esteem exercises. The furry little Windows-compatible
peripheral tried to make stilted conversation about arithmetic and
spelling with preprogrammed phrases from its 512 kilobyte memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me wonder how we survived childhood,'' said Connor's
grandmother, Betsy May. ``We always had to make both voices.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, our toys left a lot to the imagination, rather than being
programmed with exercises to teach ``creativity and imagination,''
like Arthur. They were toys, not ``learning systems'' or
``interactive'' stuffed animals like Furby ($34.99), Interactive
Winnie-the-Pooh ($109.95) or Real Live Babe ($39.95).
</P>
<P>
   The latter's box has a photo showing a girl patting Babe and a
boy operating the toy with a remote. What does that teach? I
thought that holding remotes was innate in males.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Vaughn of Gilbert, Ariz., was buying a $29.99 Sonic
Driver for a friend's 2-year-old. It's an ``interactive'' toy
steering wheel for a car seat. A kid can press buttons and it makes
the sounds of a siren, a horn and an engine turning over badly. It
also emits a few strange sentences like, ``Bye, bye, champion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep, it's made in China,'' said Vaughn, looking at the box.
She wanted one with a box in perfect condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-year-olds love playing with things like this,'' she said,
``but they'll end up liking the box just as much.''
</P>
<P>
   This got me thinking how I can make millions and defeat Gates
and his fuzzy henchbots Arthur and Barney _ maybe even the highly
prized Furby with its idiotic language called Furbish, which sounds
like a phony preacher speaking in tongues.
</P>
<P>
   I'm putting out my own learning systems, a line of interactive
toys called NonRoboMorsimates, each one priced at 99 cents, plus
shipping and handling.
</P>
<P>
   First we have Boite for a Tot. It's a learning system to get a
child through the important developmental stages of, one, thinking
inside the box, two, thinking outside the box and, three,
destroying the box.
</P>
<P>
   It's made of rugged cardboard, and with no chatty animal inside
to disturb adults and bore children. It's a car. It's a house. It's
anything when interfaced with your child.
</P>
<P>
   Fuzzby the Interactive Sphere can provide hours of fun. It can
interact with walls, Golden Retrievers and any number of children.
It always bounces back, has a huggable fuzzy finish and comes in
two distinctive colors, Wilson white and Dunlop yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Interfaced with Fido the family dog, Fuzzby is reliably
downloaded at your child's feet, and magically gets wetter.
</P>
<P>
   Third, we have Interactive Pointy, the toy of the past and the
toy of the future. It teaches fine motor skills like whacking,
aiming and not poking eyes out.
</P>
<P>
   It grows on trees, but it's been selected by experts in child
development. Besides, my child's Pointy can beat your child's Furby
into plastic pulp.
</P>
<P>
   At FAO Schwarz, Adrienne Berlin, a psychiatric social worker
from La Jolla, Calif., was telling me about her 2-year-old Bryan.
He likes boxes and balls, but he also has a little Playskool
computer. In fact, when he wants to play with it he can say the
word ``computer.''
</P>
<P>
   The very first word he learned was ``agua,'' from his Mexican
nanny. ``He pronounced it `awa,''' Berlin said. ``Actually that's
phonetically correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that was an accident of child language, but it's no
accident Bryan is growing up bilingual. Understandably, his
favorite word is ``zapatos'' for shoes. He can code-switch between
Spanish and English, and when he goes to a store, he'll wave from
his seat in the shopping cart and say ``Hola'' to Latino shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   That's the true meaning of interactive, and Bryan already knows
more about cultures in California than any Microsoft
learning-systems designer suspects.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how children learn, from their environment and from
exposure to languages and cultures,'' Berlin said. ``That's the
essence of it, to go where the child is going, not to say `Today
we're going to learn colors.'''
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, children are the ultimate learning systems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1411EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
