<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6613 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOT-TOYS-HNS &LR;      12-07 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-TOYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA BLITZES GIVE BIRTH TO SANTA'S HOTTEST TOYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA WALSH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Tickle Me Elmo and Furby didn't get to be toy
sensations purely by accident. As with many of the hit toys of
recent years, their star status was largely planned.
</P>
<P>
   While the craze for the once-popular Cabbage Patch dolls grew
gradually in the early 1980s, these days frenzies are carefully
cultivated by teams of publicists and marketing experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who stand in line and get in fistfights,''
said Diane Cardinale, assistant communications director for the Toy
Manufacturers Association, the national trade group for the toy
industry. ``They can say, `I have what 100,000 Americans want and
can't have.' And you know the silly thing is, after the holidays
nobody cares.''
</P>
<P>
   The birth of the ``it'' toy phenomenon can be traced to 1983,
when girls bombarded Santa Claus with requests for the homely
Cabbage Patch dolls _ orders that, for the first time, couldn't be
filled.
</P>
<P>
   Other generations had their fad toys _ Chatty Cathy, Hula Hoops
_ but nothing came close to the adoptable doll craze. In their
debut year, Cabbage Patch dolls raked in $60 million; just three
years later in 1986, they were earning $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Not all popular toys have produced lines of lathered parents:
Trolls in 1992 were plentiful and cheap at $2 each; Super Soaker
water guns at $15 to $25 remain a year-round favorite.
</P>
<P>
   But the marketers' goal is always the same: create a must-have
craze. That job begins in February at the annual Toy Fair in New
York City, and continues through summer with freebies to the news
media, without which no craze can be born.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines print their lists of hot toys in early fall, stories
that were written way back in June. Newspapers and television
report the hot picks, and soon there's a shortage.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Tyco Toys Inc. can thank talk show host Rosie
O'Donnell for Tickle Me Elmo. Hasbro Inc. can thank Wired Magazine
for Furby.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, O'Donnell was the proud mom of a recently adopted
child, and kept cute toys on her television studio desk to play
with between chats with guests. One day O'Donnell came out
chortling over a Tickle Me Elmo, and the rest is retail history.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell proclaimed Elmo the cutest toy she had seen. ``Adults
just fell in love with it,'' said Gene Gilligan, executive editor
of Playthings Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Cartier jewelers began offering a Tickle Me Elmo free with the
purchase of a $1 million diamond necklace and bracelet set, and
mobster son John Gotti Jr. was tracked on a late-night shopping
spree to buy _ you guessed it _ Tickle Me Elmo. Each fuss became a
national story, creating more demand.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Furby got off to a slow start until Wired magazine,
a must-read for the on-line computer culture, in September declared
it the hot toy of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Plush and gremlin-like on the outside, inside the 5-inch stuffed
animal a computer chip programs it to snore, giggle, ask for food
and burp, among other skills.
</P>
<P>
   The Wired article greased the way for Furby's national debut on
NBC's ``Today Show'' on Oct. 2, live in front of New York's famed
FAO Schwarz toy store.
</P>
<P>
   Publicists and show producers left nothing to chance, said Joan
Verdon, a columnist for the Bergan County (N.J.) Record, who
attended the event. They brought in 50 kids from nearby Public
School 59, and coached them on just the right smiles, just the
right way to wave their arms. ``OK kids, listen up. We're going to
practice again,'' Verdon recalls a production assistant saying,
``because that was pretty good but it wasn't really, really
happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The columnist overheard one kid tipping another: ``If you don't
smile and jump around a lot, you won't get on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The hype worked instantly. When the show began, three people
waited in line for FAO Schwarz to open. Within an hour, 200 more
people had joined the queue. Many confessed to Verdon that they had
no idea what the electronic animatronic was, but if it was hot,
they had to buy one for their daughter or nephew.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three weeks before Christmas, Furbys are so scarce that FAO
Schwarz keeps a waiting list and one Toys R Us manager in San
Francisco said each new case sells out within 15 minutes of hitting
the shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Already, manufacturers and publicists are working on next year's
hit toy. Guessing in advance which toy is going to be a hit is like
trying to win the lottery, said Scott Krugman, spokesman for the
National Retail Federation in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   After all, some 5,000 new toys are launched each year. So the
experts can't offer many tips from the lessons of Tickle Me Elmo or
Furby.
</P>
<P>
   Except this: ``If it's on the `Today Show,' stock up,'' Krugman
said, laughing. ``If we learned anything, it must be that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
