<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6615 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERSONAL-SHOPPER-HNS &LR;      12-07 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERSONAL-SHOPPER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOP TILL YOU DROP, AND GET PAID FOR IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With SHOPPER-TIPS)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the holiday shopping season heats up, things
get a little surreal for personal shopper Jane Matsui. An emergency
phone call for a black bow tie comes on the heels of an incoming
fax requesting 10 manicure sets. She quickly adds these items to
today's shopping list, which already includes a gold bustier, size
8 slacks and underwear for a mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   Part shopper, part image consultant, part gofer, part therapist,
Matsui shops for people who have more money than time. An anxious
client recently left a message explaining that her husband had just
asked her what she wanted for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ```So could you call and tell me what I should want?''' the
client asked Matsui.
</P>
<P>
   Matsui, 47, has built a career out of helping the have-alls
figure out what they want. She grooms their tastes, throws herself
in front of oncoming fashion disasters and provides a refuge from
the hectic shopping world by offering a form of retail therapy.
</P>
<P>
   One of her clients calls it ``Jane Time.'' It costs a $130 an
hour _ not far off the mark for traditional psychotherapy _ and
that doesn't include the cost of purchases.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent shopping excursion in downtown San Francisco, Matsui
has her mission clearly defined along with the order of attack.
</P>
<P>
   The gold bustier must match her client's pale blue satin Bill
Blass jacket (the one with Oriental embroidery). There are a few
returns to make, along with several Christmas gifts to pick out for
another client. And the bow tie call came just before she left her
office in Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a neat, gray trouser suit and sensible black oxfords,
Matsui trots off to Macy's to return six of nine watches she had
picked out for a client.
</P>
<P>
   Returning items with a professional is very different than what
most of us experience. No receipts, no credit cards, no hassle. She
just hands the bag back to a personal shopping assistant at Macy's
By Appointment, who appears to know her well.
</P>
<P>
   Matsui explains that it is so easy because she takes merchandise
out of the store ``on memo,'' meaning the store will let her walk
out with items and return whatever the client rejects. Whatever is
purchased will be charged to the client's credit card account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll walk in and say I need six sable coats and they'll say
OK,'' she said, still amazed at the level of trust.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus is like a second home to Matsui; she worked there
as an in-house personal shopper for about five years before
starting her own business three years ago. There, she has her own
dressing room in the personal shopping area and ventures into stock
areas off limits to the public.
</P>
<P>
   This morning's fax order was for a unisex manicure kit a client
saw in Neiman's catalog. The 10 sets (at $75 a pop) were waiting
for Matsui.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are these all takes?,'' asks an assistant at Neiman's, using
personal shopping lingo to ask whether Matsui's client will
purchase the items. ``All takes,'' Matsui confirms.
</P>
<P>
   The next mission: underwear for a client's 80-year-old
mother-in-law. Matsui has known the client for about 10 years and
describes her as a self-employed French history scholar.
</P>
<P>
   Matsui has about 30 clients in the San Francisco Bay area and
has no plans to take on any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between a personal shopper and a client is so
intimate _ it's the closest thing to being married,'' she said,
adding that she probably knows every item in her clients' closets.
``Most of my clients are petrified to go into a store without me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Matsui is clearly protective of her clients' privacy, but said
they are predominantly women. Some have drivers, cooks or nannies;
other clients are busy professional women who don't have time to
shop.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't usually charge for what she calls ``pull time'' _
time spent perusing the racks, choosing merchandise her clients
requested or that Matsui thinks they might like. She only charges
for the time she spends with clients while they try on and select
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   She meets individually with her clients, either at their homes
or in rooms set aside in the personal shopping sections available
in department stores such as Neiman Marcus, Saks Fifth Avenue and
Macy's. There, the clients can try on selected clothes without
having to weed through stacks of merchandise with the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Since department stores provide personal shopping services for
free, Matsui relies on her clients' loyalty and the advantage of
not being tied to one particular store's merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of her work involves convincing people not to buy the
wrong thing. And when she knows something isn't right, Matsui
doesn't sugarcoat the news: ``I say, `That looks dreadful.'''
</P>
<P>
   In Neiman's lingerie section, before she reaches the
mother-in-law underwear, Matsui's eye catches Italian art-inspired
nightgowns by Mary Jo Bruno, which may be perfect for the teen-age
daughter of another client. Matsui throws them over her arm.
</P>
<P>
   Then she spies a slinky black negligee by the same designer
lined with marabou, feathers from a large African stork.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want this,'' she said, pulling the last one in the size she
needs right off the mannequin. (She took time to redress it _
``It's rude to leave them naked.'')
</P>
<P>
   Back to the mother-in-law underwear. ``Marabou won't do. She's
80,'' Matsui said as she selected a handful of Hanro high-rise
briefs for $24 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   The same client wants to buy a pair of slacks as a Christmas
gift for her friend. Matsui selected a few matching sweaters to
create an ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a head for miscellaneous, stupid details for
this job,'' Matsui explained. ``I can't remember anything that is
important or life threatening because my head is full of stuff like
this person's friend is a size 8.''
</P>
<P>
   When Matsui combs the racks, she appears to go into a sort of
shopping trance. Normally gregarious, she becomes quiet as she
scans the selections, caresses the fabrics, ponders and dismisses
items before returning to her fitting room to store the
merchandise. She's fast, moving from department to department with
determination.
</P>
<P>
   Retail runs in Matsui's veins. Originally from Boston, her
family owned a now-defunct women's and children's clothing store in
Massachusetts and later in Los Angeles, where she remembers playing
as a child and making announcements about specials over the
loudspeaker.
</P>
<P>
   She was an elementary school teacher for seven years before
realizing that retail was her calling. She ran an accessories
boutique for nine years in Santa Barbara, Calif., and later,
between stints at Neiman's, a clothing store in Burlingame, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, she doesn't like shopping for herself. Accepting that her
job requires her to be a fashion ambassador of sorts, she shops
lower-priced stores for designer knock-offs. But Matsui does that
only out of necessity and as little as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anything. The stuff I want, I make my clients
buy,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
