<SLUG> BC-ADVENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVENT OFFERS ESCAPE FROM HOLIDAY COMMERCIALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GINGER BRISTOW  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Nathan Ferretti, an agile 2-year-old, leans
across the dining table to touch the carved wooden cross on the
Advent wreath as his parents, Lisa and David, gather their five
children for their evening Advent celebration.
</P>
<P>
   No greens adorn the simple wooden wreath, but as Christmas gets
closer, a poinsettia will be added and a red candle will be placed
in the center.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sixth year the Schenectady family has made the
Advent candle lighting and reading of family prayers part of their
Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   The three oldest children _ Zachary, 12, Amber, 9, and Jacob 6 _
take turns reading a scripture, then a short lesson or prayer. The
night that each child reads, he or she lights the candle. On the
first Sunday of Advent, they light one purple candle, then add one
each Sunday until Christmas. The wreath of three purple candles and
a pink one focuses the family, they say, on a spiritual Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   With stuffed Santas and twinkling bulbs on store shelves by
October, the commercial Christmas season gets started earlier each
year. But some families and churches are returning to the
traditional Advent season as a time of preparation for Christmas,
and the start of a sacred season beyond the glare of the holiday's
flashier lights.
</P>
<P>
   For people busy car pooling, shopping, working and preparing for
Christmas Day, the growing custom of celebrating Advent seems to
offer an avenue of tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of our church members are aware of the need to do
something this season rather than just shop and drop,'' said the
Rev. Linda Ruby of the First Presbyterian Church in Ballston Spa.
</P>
<P>
   Advent is the period including the four Sundays just before
Christmas. At the Ballson Spa church, members started on a journey
to Christmas called, ``How to transform trivial pursuits into
meaningful celebrations.''
</P>
<P>
   The sermon each week from now until Christmas will be on this
theme, with parishioners encouraged to continue this spiritual
journey throughout the week in their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a commercial component to the spiritual
reflection: Advent candles, wreaths, books and calendars are
available at bookstores and other outlets. There is also the
potential of a subtler trap in allowing the candles and Advent
wreaths themselves to become a focus of the celebration, cautioned
Sister Pat Mood, program director at the Dominican Spiritual Life
Center here.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sister Pat, quiet reflection is important for
spiritual peace at this time of year. The meaning of ``Advent'' is
waiting _ for the birth of Christ _ and she sees morning prayer and
just being as the focal point of her pre-Christmas days. In the
early morning while it is still dark, she lights a single candle,
spends a few minutes sipping a cup of coffee, just being. This
helps her focus on the reason for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ferretti family received its meditation and prayer book from
St. Paul the Apostle Church in Schenectady, as part of the parish's
Advent celebration, to encourage families to focus on this season
of waiting. The parish also lights the candles weekly, culminating
in a celebration on Christmas Day, when only one white candle is
lighted, symbolizing the birth of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   The family has taken the church tradition into its home, adding
special touches to make it unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children now insist that we leave the candle burning all
through the meal,'' said Lisa, who is excited that her children are
involved in this quiet evening time in their home. ``Benjamin, our
4-year-old, and Nathan, are allowed to put the candle out at the
end of the meal with a small candle snifter with an angel on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Eve, at the evening meal, the children and parents
will have a birthday cake and sing ``Happy Birthday to Jesus.''
Lisa said many parishioners of St. Paul the Apostle follow some
type of similar celebration during the holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at this as a time for deepening our faith with God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
