<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSEMARY TOPIARY REQUIRES SUNLIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I bought an expensive rosemary shaped like a Christmas tree.
How can I keep it alive?
</P>
<P>
   A: During the holidays, rosemary topiaries are popular miniature
Christmas trees. They're available at numerous nurseries. These
topiaries can be displayed at the front door or used indoors as
centerpieces, by stairways or in kitchen windows. Simply snip to
keep the conical shape, and use trimmings in holiday dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Indoors, place rosemary in a bright area. This herb likes
sunlight. Keep the soil on the moist side, but do not over-water.
Do not allow the soil to become so dry the plant wilts, either.
Avoid heating vents, as the warm air will dry the plant. Place the
plant outdoors for fresh air when possible. After the holidays,
find a place in the garden or on the patio for your rosemary.
</P>
<P>
   If you use the topiary outdoors from the start, give it sunlight
if possible, but some shade is acceptable. Follow the same watering
program. Rosemaries demand excellent drainage. They are best in a
more alkaline soil.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary, the herb of remembrance, friendship and love, is
steeped in myth, magic and medicinal use. Like the poinsettia, this
Mediterranean native carries religious significance during the
holiday season. One story originated in Spain. As the tale goes,
rosemary flowers were once white. When the holy family fled to
Egypt, the Virgin Mary spread her cloak over a rosemary bush and
hid behind it as soldiers passed. When she removed her cloak, the
rosemary flowers had turned blue. The herb is used in flavoring
meat, fish, potatoes, egg dishes, salads, vinegars and other foods.
Rosemary also is used in hair rinses, in baths to encourage better
blood circulation, in insect repellant and in potpourris. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to grow climbing roses. What are the best three
varieties? When is the best time to plant?
</P>
<P>
   A: Each gardener who grows roses will likely give you a
different ``three best'' list, so I'll give you the names I most
often hear as reliable favorites:
</P>
<P>
   _ `Blaze,' c. 1932, popular ever-blooming red climber.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Climbing Cecile Brunner,' c. 1881, heavy spring and fall
pink, fragrant flower.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Don Juan,' c. 1958, large, fragrant, dark-red repeat blooms.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Dortmund,' c. 1955, crimson single blooms with white center
and yellow stamens. Cut spent flowers to encourage reblooming.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Lady Banks' Rose,' c. 1807, double yellow spring blooms.
Rarer white form.
</P>
<P>
   `` `LaMarque,' circa 1830, an ever-blooming climber with white
flowers with yellow centers, bears the blooms in fragrant clusters.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Mermaid,' c. 1918, large sulfur-yellow spring-frost blooms.
Thorny.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Pinkie,' spring-fall pink flowers.
</P>
<P>
   _ `Old Blush,' c. 1752, spring-fall clusters of light pink
blooms that may blush a dark rose at the edge of petals.
</P>
<P>
   You can plant container roses most any time of the year, but
those planted during hot months will require extra attention. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am planning a tropical garden in a courtyard. I would like
to include bamboo as a background accent, but I've heard that it
can be extremely aggressive. Is there a way to contain bamboo?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are clumping and running bamboos, and some maintain the
clumping types are less aggressive than the running types, which
send underground stems to various distances from the mother before
the vertical shoots appear. Clumping bamboos produce rhizomes that
grow only a short distance from the mother plant before sending up
shoots.
</P>
<P>
   Bamboo is the tallest member of the grass family. There are
about 100 bamboo genera and more than 1,000 species. Water is a
natural barrier for running bamboos, as they dislike it. There are
80 millimeter plastic barriers, and some synthetic products are
chemically treated to divert roots. You can always cut new shoots
when they pop through the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Bamboos vary greatly in height, so you'll want to do a little
research before planting. Clumpers such as `Golden Goddess' mature
to only 10 feet in height while `Giant Timber' maxes out at 55
feet.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden question to Kathy Huber, Garden Editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston 77210. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
