A6655 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-CAMELLIA-HNS &LR;      12-07 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-CAMELLIA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMELLIA'S BLOOMS SO PERFECT THEY HARDLY LOOK REAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Given the interest in heirloom plants today, one
aristocrat of the Southern garden should not get lost in the
shuffle: the camellia.
</P>
<P>
   Large, handsome evergreens with blooms so perfect they hardly
look real, camellias have long been the calling cards in South
Carolina gardens. Camellia ``allees'' on Georgia plantations fill
winter with bloom. Alabama tapped the camellia as its state flower.
Louisiana, too, has reason to be proud of its camellia heritage.
</P>
<P>
   All along the southeast Gulf Coast, camellias thrive in
well-draining, acidic soil, abundant rainfall and high humidity.
</P>
<P>
   East of the Sabine River, one may joke, there's a camellia in
every yard. But, camellias in Texas? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have done their horticultural history say camellias
were actually in Houston before the 1900s. Thanks largely to the
River Oaks Garden Club's annual Azalea Trail, the plants gained
significant attention in the 1930s. Camellias are still grown at
one perennial trail highlight, Bayou Bend, the 14-acre estate on
the banks of Buffalo Bayou. Camellias seem to like gardens along
the waterway, where the earth is more acidic and better draining
than in those gardens with heavy gumbo for soil.
</P>
<P>
   But those with gumbo can get around that by growing camellias in
raised beds or containers of highly organic, acidic, well-draining
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Greg and Rosamay Davis have more than 200 camellias, in the
ground and in containers, at their southwest Houston home. The
couple, longtime members of the Houston Camellia Society, have been
accumulating camellia know-how for about 30 years. Greg Davis is
the chapter's president.
</P>
<P>
   Camellias are members of the tea family; in fact, commercial tea
comes from the leaves of ``Camellia sinensis,'' a plant that will
reach 30 feet in height.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 250 species in the Camellia genus, Greg
Davis says, but for the most part, ``Camellia japonica,'' which
flowers late fall/early winter into spring, depending on the
variety, and the fall-flowering ``C. sasanqua'' are the two species
most easily grown here. ``C. reticulata'' and hybrids also may be
found here, especially in the enthusiast's garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``C. japonica'' is a large species and is considered the
``traditional'' or ``common'' camellia. The shrubs are dense with
foliage and therefore ideal as specimen plants, in the garden or in
large containers. Gardeners like japonicas because they have large,
showy blooms. Old shrubs in some areas may tower to 20 feet, but
many here are in the 6- to 10-foot range.
</P>
<P>
   The sasanquas, on the other hand, have smaller foliage and
flowers that are attractive but not that suitable for cutting as
they quickly shatter. The shrubs, however, make handsome hedges or
background plants, and they can be espaliered on a fence or wall.
This species is more cold-hardy than the japonicas, and grafted
camellias are often grown on sasanqua root stock. Mature height is
approximately 14 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Camellia nomenclature includes thousands of varieties. Blooms
vary in form, and the flowers may be single, semidouble, anemone
form, peony form, rose form double or formal double.
</P>
<P>
   Camellias also vary in size and are classified as miniature when
blooms are 2 1/2 inches or less, small when 2 1/2 to 3 inches,
medium if 3 to 4 inches, large if 4 to 5 inches and very large if
more than 5 inches in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   The largest, Davis says, are reticulatas in the 7-inch range.
But this species can be testy here, since these camellias like cool
nights and dislike humid, 90-degree days. San Francisco, he says,
is the place for reticulatas. Gardeners here do best sticking to
japonicas and sasanquas. Besides, the rewards of growing these two
species is great enough.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Vietnam War, Davis says, China has released a yellow
camellia. But the home gardener will find camellias in the
white-to-red color range, and there are a number of variegated
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   Davis recommends a raised bed of equal parts topsoil, sand and
pine bark to help ensure good camellia health and growth. A
slightly acidic soil with a pH of 5-7 is important. Garden centers
sell soil meters that read alkalinity/acidity. Build the raised
beds right on top of the gumbo. Get them up 8 to 12 inches. This
will hold you for about five years, he says. By then the pine bark,
if not replenished, will have disappeared. This organic matter is
important as it boosts soil porosity, crucial to camellia health,
as well as acidity as the pine bark breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Camellias grow well in containers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Camellias need a moist but not soggy soil. City water is
alkaline, and when used on camellias, it often becomes necessary to
counteract the alkalinity by adding agricultural sulfur or a
quicker-acting chemical such as iron sulfate to acidify the soil.
Yellow, chlorotic foliage is a symptom of a too-alkaline soil.
Yellow leaves also can be a sign of poor drainage or too much sun.
</P>
<P>
   November to March is the ideal time to plant camellias. It's a
good idea to buy camellias at this time, while they are in bloom,
to be sure of color and flower form. The Houston Camellia Society
recommends that newcomers stick with proven varieties, selecting
healthy, vigorous plants _ 2-year-old grafts or 2-year-old plants
grown on their own roots. Look for clean, dark green foliage on
well-shaped, dense shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   A well-draining spot that receives morning sun and some filtered
shade is ideal. Pine trees create an excellent environment for
camellias. It's best to protect the plants from cold winds and hot
afternoon sun.
</P>
<P>
   Planting depth is crucial, too. Do not plant too deep. The roots
need a lot of air, and the crown should be at least a couple of
inches above ground level, Davis says. Mulch with pine needles,
pine bark or shredded oak leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Camellias are slow growers and therefore do not require heavy
fertilization. Rosamay Davis emphasizes the importance of not
overfertilizing. Do not fertilize the first year after planting.
Fertilization schedules then vary from gardener to gardener, and
those who grow to show may fertilize until August or September. But
for the general gardener, the Houston Camellia Society suggests
using a commercial camellia fertilizer after flowering and again
around mid-May. A light application of cottonseed meal, a
slow-release organic nitrogen fertilizer, is helpful in mid-April.
</P>
<P>
   Prune camellias after flowering.
</P>
<P>
   Proper culture will help keep camellias healthy, but pests can
attack. Scale, the white or brown insects found on foliage
undersides or stems, where they deplete plant juices, may be
controlled with oil sprays. Ask your nurseryman about products. The
Davises keep a clean garden to discourage outbreaks of petal
blight, immediately removing any fallen blooms. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
