<HEADLINE>
THESE CENTERPIECE IDEAS DON'T ADD TO HOLIDAY STRESS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MADELEINE McDERMOTT HAMM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Centerpiece. Just the word sounds so intimidating, so
grand.
</P>
<P>
   But the dictionary puts a manageable handle on it: an ornament,
bowl of flowers, etc. for the center of a table. It's as if Webster
is saying, ``Don't be afraid. You can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the message from designer Debbie Mumm, whose line of
Mummford holiday products is available in Mervyn's California
stores nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all stressed during the holidays,'' Mumm said during a
visit to Houston. ``That's why I have come up with some simple and
inexpensive holiday centerpieces that can make anyone look like a
decorating expert. They don't cost a lot of money or take much
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of Mumm's easy centerpiece ideas you can borrow or
incorporate into your own creations. Some feature Christmas themes,
while others just reflect the season of goodwill and abundance:
</P>
<P>
   _ Table of Plenty: Dry rolls and breads from the bakery for
about four days, then spray them with a varnish finish. Line a
large wooden bowl or basket with a cloth or napkins and fill with
the bread. Add apples, tangerines, gourds, nuts, cinnamon sticks,
autumn leaves or whatever goodies you can find. For a more elegant
look, spray the autumn leaves with gold metallic paint.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kids' Table: To make certain the children feel included in the
holiday dinner, set their own table with a theme tree and table
favors using their favorite collections. For the tree, adorn a
small artificial tree with items such as stuffed animals, baseball
cards, etc. Add candy canes and tinsel. For table favors, buy a few
more stuffed animals, cards or whatever is on the tree, wrap them
in cellophane or colorful paper, and tie with a ribbon and candy
cane.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cedar Bouquet: Collect mixed fresh greenery in the yard or at
a nursery. Mix red carnations, fresh cut poinsettias or even red
roses with the greenery in a water-filled vase for a simple but
festive look. Set the arrangement on a holiday napkin or cloth and
ring it with votive candles. You might want to spread a little more
greenery and holiday potpourri around the candles.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful to keep potpourri off the wood dining table top, as
it will damage the finish.
</P>
<P>
   And from decorative arts designer Louis Nichole comes the Handy
Dandy Decorator, a patented series of four clever wire style forms
for creating lavish centerpieces like the pros turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Put the wire form in a bowl or basket and fill it in with fresh
or dried fruits, vegetables, flowers, greenery, stems and vines.
The forms can be reused every season. For the holidays, try apples,
pine cones, holly and berries in a clay pot painted gold. In the
spring, imagine fresh plums arranged with dried hydrangeas and
gold-painted leaves, arranged in an antique urn.
</P>
<P>
   The Handy Dandy Decorator forms series includes a topiary, a
wreath, an oblong centerpiece with candles and a set of two mini
candelabra. The wire forms, which range from $19.99 to $24.99 and
come with instructions, can be ordered by calling (toll free)
877-289-5684. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
