<SLUG> BC-JFK-NIXON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPES SHOW JFK QUESTIONING NIXON'S MENTAL STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER MATTHEWS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a taped 1962 telephone conversation between
then-California Gov. Edmund G. ``Pat'' Brown and President John F.
Kennedy, the two discussed the mental stability of Richard Nixon,
the man they had both defeated in back-to-back elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reduced him to the nut house,'' the 35th president said of
Nixon, the man who would be the 37th. ``That last farewell speech
of his ... it shows that he belongs on the couch.''
</P>
<P>
   This was Kennedy's reaction to Nixon's infamous ``last press
conference,'' during which he declared, ``You won't have Nixon to
kick around anymore.'' The former vice president gave the speech
the morning after his 300,000-vote loss to Brown in the 1962
California governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   The JFK-Brown conversation about that outburst was among the
tapes released late last month by the John F. Kennedy Library in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Not knowing he was being recorded by the president, Brown
responded to Kennedy's comment about Nixon being driven ``nuts'' by
saying that humiliating his opponent was exactly what Kennedy had
wanted Brown to do: ``But you gave me instructions, and I follow
your orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy took great pleasure in Brown's victory, JFK's White
House press secretary, Pierre Salinger, recalled Friday. ``I
remember a lot of excitement at the White House that Nixon had lost
that election,'' said Salinger, who was later appointed to a
vacancy in the U.S. Senate by Brown.
</P>
<P>
   When Kennedy asked Brown in the taped conversation what he
thought would be Nixon's political future in California, the
governor said that the former vice president's ``terrible''
performance of that morning had doomed him in the state. ``I don't
see how he can ever recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Nixon carried California in his successful bid
for the White House against Hubert H. Humphrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very peculiar fellow,'' Brown continued. ``This is a
very peculiar man. I really think that he is psycho. He's an able
man, but he's nuts!''
</P>
<P>
   Brown went on to say that the man he had just beaten was ``like
a lot of these paranoids.''
</P>
<P>
   After discussing a possible Kennedy trip to California, Brown
asked the president to say hello to his son, Jerry, who had
returned from Yale Law School to help his father's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll take California by 10 times as much as you did
before,'' said the younger Brown, when the phone was passed to him.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that Kennedy had lost California to Nixon in 1960,
Jerry Brown, then just 24, said he meant to say that Kennedy would
do much better in '64.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to the tape of himself, his father and JFK
talking 36 years ago, Jerry Brown, the mayor-elect of Oakland, said
last week that he has never forgotten that phone call. He added
that no one since has matched Kennedy's force of personality, his
``charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   Nixon lost the 1960 presidential election to Kennedy 34,226,731
to 34,108,157 votes _ though the margin was wider in the Electoral
College.
</P>
<P>
   According to his last White House chief of staff, Gen. Alexander
Haig, Nixon ``believed until the day he died that Kennedy had
stolen the election.''
</P>
<P>
   That Wednesday in November 1962, the day of his speech, Nixon
was harboring two reasons for bitterness: his resentment of the
news media, which he believed had taken a dislike to him because he
accused Alger Hiss, an aide to President Franklin D. Roosevelt, of
being a communist agent in 1948, and his never-ending feud with the
Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that all the members of the press are so delighted that I
lost,'' a red-eyed Nixon said at the opening of the news conference
the morning after his 1962 defeat. ``And as I leave the press, all
I can say is this: For 16 years, ever since the Hiss case, you've
had a lot of fun _ a lot of fun _ that you've had an opportunity to
attack me, and I think I've given as good as I've taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``One last thing. What are my plans? Well, my plans are to go
home. I'm going to get acquainted with my family again. And my
plans, incidentally, are, from a political viewpoint, of course, to
take a holiday. It will be a long holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I leave you gentleman now, and you will now write it. You will
interpret it. That's your right. But as I leave you I want you to
know _ just think how much you're going to be missing me. You won't
have Nixon to kick around anymore, because, gentlemen, this is my
last press conference.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The more extensive, and more notorious tapes made by Nixon
during his presidency, now at the National Archives, show the
extent to which he blamed the Kennedys for his defeat, not just for
the presidency in 1960, but also for the governorship in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon believed Kennedy and his brother, Robert, the attorney
general at the time, had used files from the Internal Revenue
Service to leak the fact that Nixon had signed a ``restrictive
covenant'' _ one that banned resale to blacks or Jews _ when buying
his house in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember when the Kennedys ordered them to go after me
and that goddamned house I bought? Huh?'' he demanded of his chief
of staff, Bob Haldeman, in a conversation recorded in May 1971.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, Nixon was still angry about the Kennedys' role in
his California defeat. ``Look in '62, best test we ever had. How'd
I lose? They had access to every goddamned thing you could
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at this point, a year before the Watergate bugging and
break-in, that Nixon ordered his all-out campaign of snooping and
surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shouldn't be on and off. I mean, that's something we can
afford. Maybe we can get a scandal on any, any one of the leading
Democrats.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1510EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6726 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-07 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT COMMISSIONER HOLDS THE LINE AGAINST ATM FEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL AND PATRICIA WEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ John P. Burke is an unlikely hero in the
long-shot campaign against banks that seek to impose automated
teller machine surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Burke is the banking commissioner in Connecticut, part of a
Republican administration that prides itself on being friendly to
business. (Just ask Robert Kraft and the Patriots.) Prior to taking
the commissioner's post four years ago, Burke was a banker for 30
years, and his philosophy hasn't changed much. He still opposes
government meddling in marketplace decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Yet almost singlehandedly Burke has prevented Fleet Financial
Group, First Union and BankBoston from imposing a surcharge on
noncustomers who use their ATMs in Connecticut. The fees would
bring in an estimated $1.5 million a year to the three banks, which
together own 60 percent of the state's ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Iowa, where lawmakers passed a bill barring
surcharges, Connecticut is the only state in the nation where the
fees are not allowed. (However, banks in Connecticut as elsewhere
can charge their own customers when they use another bank's ATM.)
Surcharges spread throughout Massachusetts several months ago after
House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran refused to let a ban come up for a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a major crusade on my part,'' said Burke. ``My job
is not to be a crusader, but to enforce the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no law on ATM surcharges in Connecticut. And that,
according to Burke, is why he ruled in 1995 that surcharging was
not allowed. ``If it doesn't say you can do it, you can't do it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has been battling Burke ever since, in and out of court.
The bank got his ruling overturned in federal court in September
and started imposing a $1 surcharge Oct. 23. But on Nov. 9 the
federal court's decision was set aside by an appeals court, which
held that the issue belonged in state court.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet is now back in federal court accusing Burke and the state
of Connecticut of violating its civil rights. The bank is also
trying to get Burke's order to cease and desist surcharging
revoked, saying it would be irreparably harmed if it is unable to
collect $15,000 a day from noncustomers who use its machines.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Shepker, a Fleet spokesman, said Burke's interpretation of
the law is wrong. He said banks need surcharge revenue to avoid
losing money on their ATM networks. The fact that state law doesn't
mention surcharging means it is not prohibited, he said. ``We
believe we're on very, very solid ground,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet so far has not attempted to win passage of a law allowing
surcharging. Surcharge opponents, meanwhile, have failed to get a
surcharge ban passed.
</P>
<P>
   As in Connecticut, the statutes in Massachusetts dealing with
ATMs don't address the surcharge issue. Thomas J. Curry, the
Massachusetts banking commissioner, has not attempted to use that
omission to ban the fees administratively, even though his boss,
Governor Paul Cellucci, opposes them. Curry's spokesman said
legislative action is necessary because state law is too vague on
the fee issue.
</P>
<P>
   During an interview in his office, Burke stressed that he was
not taking sides on the ATM-surcharge issue, merely interpreting
the law as his job requires. Yet his perspective on the issue,
given his banking background, was interesting.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he thinks the banks' argument that surcharges are
needed to avoid losing money is overblown. He said ATMs save banks
money on tellers and allow them to serve customers around the
clock. ``I think what they've discovered (with surcharges) is
another way to make money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, who banks at a small bank with no ATMs of its own,
recognizes he may not win in court, but he says his ruling will
have forestalled the fees for more than four years. ``Even if we
lose, I think the consumer has been helped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Ruthauser of Cromwell, a lawyer who commutes to Hartford on
a daily basis, would agree with that. After withdrawing money from
a Fleet ATM downtown, he told us he hopes Burke prevails. ``The
banks are just looking for a windfall,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A sticky problem
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of tiny but annoying problems, some readers have
been asking us why it seems every piece of fruit or vegetable in
the grocery store has a small sticker. They say removing each
sticker is tedious and they often end up scraping up some fruit or
vegetable peel in the process.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out these stickers, which contain PLU (Produce Look-Up)
codes, are part of voluntary industry standards adopted by produce
farmers in the early 1990s to help store cashiers.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Humfeld, vice president of the Produce Marketing
Association in Newark, Del., said grocery stores were complaining
that clerks were not ringing up the right prices. They might look
at a nectarine and ring up the price of a peach. Or a higher-priced
Royal Gala apple, for example, might be sold at the lower-price of
a Red Delicious apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enables the retailers to find an easy way to ring up the
proper price at check-out,'' Humfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   Humfeld said that in 1993, only about 10 percent of produce
distributers were using the PLU stickers, which contain a code that
marks the particular type of fruit or vegetable. As of this year,
57 percent of produce distributers use these stickers, and Humfeld
said he expects the sticker use to only expand.
</P>
<P>
   Every industry has its quirky problems, and produce distributers
apparently are always looking for better glues that will keep
stickers on produce at the store, but also allow for easy removal
once the produce is brought home.
</P>
<P>
   What if you accidently eat a sticker? It's obviously not meant
to be eaten, but Humfeld said stickers are designed to pose no
health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Odds &AMP; Ends
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --MCI minimum charges. MCI WorldCom, blaming the cost of
servicing customer accounts, is following AT&AMP;T's lead. Starting
next month, MCI plans to impose a minimum charge of $3 to $5 on all
residential customers, depending on their calling plans. That means
you pay $3 to $5 if you fail to make at least that much in long
distance calls in a given month. People who make few calls _ and
MCI says only 10 percent fall in this category _ oppose the minimum
charges, in part because the fees can trigger the imposition of
additional monthly government fees. Those fees can transform a $3
charge into a $4.31 charge.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a consumer tip, e-mail mohl(at)globe.com or
wen(at)globe.com, or write Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
