<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-DECISIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS WILL GAUGE SOCIAL SECURITY TROUBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``The crisis is here, and it's very real,'' says
Economic Security 2000, a citizens group pushing to overhaul the
Social Security program. ``Social Security is going broke,'' says
the Cato Institute. ``The system is broken,'' says a group called
Third Millennium.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton and congressional leaders gather Tuesday
and Wednesday to discuss the financial health of Social Security,
one of the first issues they must decide is whether the problem is
really this bad. There is no question that the system needs more
money. But reasonable estimates range widely, from $3 trillion to a
devastating $10 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Is the nation's retirement program in crisis, or just hitting a
few bumps?
</P>
<P>
   The answer will bear directly on whether and how lawmakers
revamp the nation's most popular domestic program. If Americans
become convinced that Social Security is in crisis, they may be
more open to dramatic changes. Chief among them: allowing workers
to pay Social Security taxes to personal stock and bond accounts,
rather than to the government.
</P>
<P>
   But if the program is only a bit wobbly, the public might oppose
anything more than minor tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   That explains the ongoing battle over how to describe the
urgency of the problem. Groups that want to create private accounts
_ such as Economic Security 2000, the Cato Institute and Third
Millennium _ say Social Security is in dire straits. Members of all
three groups are among the 250 people invited to the first day of
the White House conference, and the director of Third Millennium
will be a featured speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis school has some prominent economists on its side.
``Yes, it's a crisis,'' said Laurence Kotlikoff, a Boston
University economist who has written on the subject. ``When you're
talking about something that would take a 50 percent tax hike to
fix, it's a real crisis. . . . . It's a terrible problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a coordinated campaign, prominent left-of-center
activists have begun a counteroffensive to say the problems are
overstated. ``Social Security is in fact in remarkably good
shape,'' the Rev. Jesse Jackson asserted last week during the
kickoff of a group that aims to block any move to private accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the cover of a fantasy funding crisis . . .
conservatives want to revise or even eliminate Social Security,''
said Patricia Ireland, president of NOW, who criticized the
``Chicken Little atmosphere'' surrounding the program.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters is that groups on all sides of the issue
fear that lawmakers will avoid making any changes to the
politically hypersensitive program unless the threat of a crisis
hangs over them. And almost everybody agrees that some type of
change is needed, or else Social Security will be unable to pay all
its promised benefits in about 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no short-term crisis,'' said Kenneth Apfel,
commissioner of the Social Security Administration. ``But it's a
hard issue because without that `crisis' word, the question is
whether we can actually bring the country forward to resolve this
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable people, making defensible economic assumptions,
arrive at different views of Social Security's financial health.
</P>
<P>
   Social Security raises money though a 12.4 percent tax on wages,
paid half by workers and half by employers. For years, the tax has
raised more money than Social Security pays out each year in
benefits to retirees. The surplus goes to the Treasury for general
purposes, and the Treasury in return gives Social Security special
bonds, which are held in a trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   The trust fund has collected $655 billion in bonds so far, and
it will add more in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   But soon, the nation's 76 million Baby Boomers will begin to
retire. By about 2013, so many Boomers will be drawing retirement
benefits that the system has to cash in some of the Treasury bonds.
And by about 2032, all the bonds will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   That does not mean the system will be bankrupt. Even with no
trust fund, the 12.4 percent tax will produce enough money each
year to cover about three-quarters of the benefits for retirees.
The problem is the remaining one quarter. The question facing
policy-makers is whether paying for that one quarter will be
relatively painless or catastrophically expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably as many answers as there are people looking
at it,'' said Michael Tanner of the Cato Institute, a libertarian
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Three factors have shaped the debate over the scope of the
Social Security problem: whether the goal is to fix the system
forever or for only a set number of years; forecasts of future
economic growth; and the reliability of the Social Security trust
fund.
</P>
<P>
   When economists add up all the income and obligations of the
system over 75 years, the shortfall comes to about $3 trillion.
That shortfall could be wiped out if payroll taxes were raised
today, and permanently, by about 2.2 percentage points. The tax
increase would erase the shortfall for 75 years, the longest time
horizon that many economists are willing to consider.
</P>
<P>
   But others say the nation should put Social Security into
balance forever. Social Security's own advisers have noted that the
nation will still have a growing number of retirees in 75 years,
and that a tax increase of 2.2 percentage points allows the system
to fall into deficit in year 76.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should you stop at 75 years and ignore the huge deficits
in year 76, 77, 78?'' asked BU's Kotlikoff.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing Social Security forever, he said, would take a huge tax
increase of 4.7 percentage points. ``How would you like to give up
a nickle of every dollar you earn, every day, for the rest of your
life, and your kids and grandkids have to do it, too?'' Kotlikoff
asked. ``That's the nature of our problem here.''
</P>
<P>
   The news gets worse, according to some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   To arrive at its estimate of a $3 trillion shortfall, Social
Security's internal analysts make certain economic assumptions.
They assume that the economy will grow by about 2 percent annually
in the next decade, down from about 3.8 percent last year. They
assume that inflation will rise to about 3.5 percent, up from about
2.3 percent today. By the year 2070, they say, women will live on
average to age 84, and men to age 79.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawmakers accept these numbers, but a vocal minority says
Social Security has a poor record for accurate predictions. They
favor using more conservative forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Tanner, for example, says the Census Bureau has predicted that
people will live two years longer than the Social Security
projections say, requiring the program to pay out more money in
benefits. Kotlikoff says the Social Security numbers overstate
future increases in worker paychecks, so they give an overly
optimistic view of tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   If lawmakers accept conservative forecasts, it would take a tax
hike of six percentage points to fix Social Security for 75 years,
Kotlikoff said _ far more than the 2.2 percent hike under the more
optimistic assumptions.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts also take different views on the Social Security trust
fund, the pool of Treasury bonds worth $655 billion.
</P>
<P>
   To some, it is real money that can be relied on to pay benefits
for future retirees. But others say the trust fund is merely a pile
of IOUs that can be paid off only by future tax increases or
spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
   If the cost of paying off the IOUs is included, these analysts
say, it would take a 6 percent payroll tax hike to fix Social
Security for 75 years. ``The trust fund is key,'' said Tanner.
``How you view the trust fund tells you whether you have a problem
in 15 years or in 34 years, and whether it's a 2 percent problem or
a 6 percent problem.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some say there is not much of a problem at
all. Last week, Jackson and Ireland said the nation could grow its
way out of its Social Security problem. If economic growth remained
at it current pace, they said, more people would work and would
earn more money, allowing the system to raise enough tax revenue to
cover its costs.
</P>
<P>
   Crisis or not, many lawmakers say that problems will only get
worse if they do not settle on a solution now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people want to define the problem as very doomsday in
order to support a radical overhaul,'' said Representative Earl
Pomeroy, Democrat of North Dakota. ``The fact is we've got the Baby
Boomers right now in their earning years, and we've got a federal
budget surplus. This is a problem we can fix, and we don't have to
scrap the system to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1512EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
