<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6808 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEPTEMBERLOVESTORY-12     12-07 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEPTEMBERLOVESTORY-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HIGH SCHOOL, IT WASN'T MEANT TO BE; 50 YEARS LATER, SHE FINALLY
SAYS YES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In California, Pat tells our story and her friends are
rhapsodic. It's the most wonderful, most beautiful thing they've
heard.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, I tell our story and people suspect I'm making it up.
I'm not, although Pat feels betimes that I exaggerate. Her memory,
though, is less keen than mine.
</P>
<P>
   Even before our July wedding, various friends _ hers, mine, ours
_ were urging me to write ``our love story'' from the very
beginning ...
</P>
<P>
   The beginning is Dec. 31, 1939. As footnote to the Great
Depression, we're refugees from Texas, newly arrived in Los
Angeles: my parents in their late 30s; my teen-age brother and
sister; and myself, rather small for 10 1/2 years. On this last day
of the year that is our first full day of California residence,
we've rented a two-bedroom house with sleeping porch ($30 per
month), and I have walked with my mother and sister several blocks
to a supermarket on Wilshire Boulevard to buy our first groceries.
</P>
<P>
   My mother liked to relate her version of that shopping spree.
Our four full sacks of groceries came to no more than $5, because
that's how much money my father had given her. But my mother soon
forgot all about the happening on the sidewalk that is forever
etched in my memory ...
</P>
<P>
   As we came out of the market with those full sacks, a little
girl on roller skates took a bad spill and hurt herself. She began
to cry, and someone sought to assist her. She wouldn't be helped.
With eyes ablaze, she said ``I'm all right!'' rather defiantly, and
picked herself up. She was about my own size; and as I watched her
skate away, I already admired her.
</P>
<P>
   She had her very own look, not to be mistaken for anyone else.
So I recognized her immediately a few days later, when I enrolled
in Mrs. Fullenwider's fifth-grade class at Brockton Avenue School
in West Los Angeles. We may not have exchanged words that spring
semester, nor does she recall my arrival at the school. In my view,
though, she was a roller-skating heroine. She was Patricia Ann
Volder _ a name quite lovely, I thought.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, when we were actually taught by Our Miss Brooks in
sixth grade, Pat and I became fast friends. She was quite saucy,
the first truly witty child I knew, terrific even then with
one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   I recall sixth grade so much better than she. Pat does not
remember that I was class president, leading the Pledge of
Allegiance every morning. She does remember passing my house every
day at lunchtime, on her way home. I could look up a paved alley
adjacent to my house and see hers, a long block away. Yet I was
never in her house, nor she in mine; sometimes we were together in
a neighborhood play group but always out of doors.
</P>
<P>
   Our romance _ please, let me call it that _ flourished in the
1941 summer before our seventh-grade assignment to Emerson Junior
High in Westwood. Twice, Pat and I made an eight-block walk to a
public library, where each of us would return 10 books and check
out 10 more (the maximum allowance). She remembers that; and she
recalls our attempt to play doubles tennis with Billy and Cherry on
the court at our eventual high school.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Bernhoft was my closest friend and Pat's was Cherry
Yamada, a vibrant Japanese girl. When we started at Emerson (which
collected pupils from seven elementary schools), I was disappointed
not to have any classes with Billy or Pat, but I was in homeroom
and all other classes with Cherry. She and I would cling to one
another, but her perception _ and mine _ was that Pat was my
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Pat believes otherwise. The minister who performed our wedding
ceremony articulated that although Larry considered Pat his
sweetheart, Pat denied having a boyfriend _ I was merely the best
friend she had among boys she knew at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Pat was in Cherry's home on the Sunday of Dec. 7, 1941, when
they heard via radio of the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor. The
next morning I was with Pat and Cherry at the bus stop at Wilshire
and Westgate, and the three of us wondered what would happen to
Cherry and her family.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry and our other Japanese friends all left Emerson four
months later to be interned at Manzanar _ a concentration camp by
any other name. When we lost Cherry, I lost a part of Pat; and I
supposed I was losing all of her forever in the following October.
My family moved to Santa Monica and I was withdrawn from Emerson,
soon after having started eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   As we got off the bus after my last ride home from Emerson, I
bade Pat farewell. I was 13, as she soon would be, and I requested
a goodbye kiss. It was accomplished ever so quickly, on the exact
spot where a little girl on skates had fallen almost three years
earlier. I thought I felt her lips on mine for hours afterward.
</P>
<P>
   My family's stay in Santa Monica lasted only three months. We
were back in West Los Angeles, but in a different neighborhood. I
was at Emerson again, but not riding the same bus with Pat; and our
reconnection on campus certainly was awkward. In those three months
away, I had gained 6 inches in height; and Patricia Volder was no
longer a child but a beguiling young lady, sublimely proportioned.
</P>
<P>
   From that point onward we were only casual acquaintances. From
Emerson we advanced to University High School, so named for its
proximity to UCLA _ where, eventually, we also would be students
together.
</P>
<P>
   Pat did not suspect the torch I carried. As we progressed into
the dating experience, she seemed beyond my reach. What little
social congress I managed with girls was on a double-date basis
requiring someone else's car. Pat dated boys more spectacular than
I perceived myself to be; one was Don Stewart, star second baseman
on the baseball team I failed to make. In college, she was
``pinned'' to Jack Miller, who had been the premier miler at our
high school.
</P>
<P>
   But I was hanging in there. In our senior year at Uni, we
finally had a class together. It was the a cappella choir and I
contrived to be near Pat, once managing to sit with her on a bus
trip to one of our singing engagements. She was friendly enough but
not aroused, because I was old news.
</P>
<P>
   At graduation time, we both squeaked into the top 10 percent. In
a class of 469, I ranked 45th scholastically, but there was Pat's
name, just ahead of mine at No. 44. Pat had prominence in our
class, was president of this and that, so was privileged to sit on
the front row at commencement, right next to Jane Powell. I was
several tiers back, clutching the diploma I had just received, when
I heard the name of Cherry Yamada called ... and saw a gorgeous
Japanese girl stride across the stage to accept her diploma. I had
not known of Cherry's return.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   In the summer after graduation, Pat and I had jobs at the same
place _ the Sears store in Westwood Village _ and she turned me
down when I invited her on a theater date. A few years later, at
UCLA where she worked in the student store, I made a vain bid to
take her to a football game. Pat says now that if she ever refused
a date with me, it was because she was otherwise engaged; but I
would not risk being a three-time loser.
</P>
<P>
   At UCLA I met the girl who, after my military conscription
during the Korean War, would become my wife and the mother of our
five children. As a GI in Germany, I wrote to Eleanor Eby every
day, and I was a letter-writing fool, corresponding with a
multitude of friends. I had lost touch with Pat but wished to write
to her, and enlisted aid in LA trying to finding her.
</P>
<P>
   No one did, although a friend sent a newspaper photo identifying
Patricia Volder as a model for Saks Fifth Avenue. When I married
Ellie in the fall of 1954, I did not know that Pat had married
fellow UCLA grad Carl Haag a year earlier, nor did I have any idea
where she was.
</P>
<P>
   But I never forgot her. There was the time when my wife and I,
snowbound in a Yonkers, N.Y., apartment while awaiting our first
child, got to talking for the only time about our bygone loves. I
told her of a childhood sweetheart who had not known the extent of
my affection. Ellie said, ``She was your Marjorie Morningstar,''
referring to Herman Wouk's then-current bestseller about the girl
who got away. True enough, there's a Marjorie Morningstar in almost
every man's life.
</P>
<P>
   Years passed _ 44 of them, from the last time I saw Pat at UCLA
until June 3, 1996, when I was surprised to receive notice of a
Unihi 50-year reunion in planning for the Class of 1947. Surprised,
because I had long been completely lost from my high school class
and had not known of reunions that occurred incrementally _
reunions Pat had attended. But somehow they had found me at last,
in Fort Worth, and I knew I would attend the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The classmate maintaining the data base was a long-ago friend _
Sam Haver, who beat me out of the tenor lead in the high school
operetta. I telephoned Sam to request addresses he might have for
persons with whom I wished to resume contact.
</P>
<P>
   He provided six addresses. Pat Volder was now Pat Haag, living
in Moraga in the Bay Area, across from San Francisco and close to
Oakland. Because Sam did not indicate that she was no longer
married, I wrote to Pat somewhat guardedly, encapsulating my
post-college history and telling of my beloved Ellie's death in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reply from Pat, although others responded
quickly to my letters. Bill Bernhoft got me on the phone. From ages
11 to 14, when baseball was the rhythm of our summer, Billy and I
went with our fathers to Pacific Coast League doubleheaders every
Sunday. Billy was the star of my California boyhood, and nowadays
we get on the phone and talk for hours. Cherry, too. She said in a
very touching letter that I have recaptured for her a girlhood she
lost. We're pals again, and Cherry's friendship with Pat is
redeemed.
</P>
<P>
   The reunion was only two months away when Pat finally answered
my letter in March 1997, having deliberated for nine months. Some
time later, she said the reason for her uncertainty in answering my
letter was that she felt instinctively she would be in my life
again, and wasn't sure either of us wanted that.
</P>
<P>
   Pat hadn't planned to attend the reunion in Culver City; but
after reading her six-page handwritten letter (which detailed the
end of her marriage after 23 years), I reached her by phone and
talked her into coming.
</P>
<P>
   The class reunion changed our lives forever. I expected nothing
beyond restoring a friendship, and Pat certainly ``wasn't
looking.'' But things happen. There really were two reunions _ for
the class, and just for us.
</P>
<P>
   She was white-haired glamorous. I was enraptured in the moment
of our meeting, and our time together was mutually stimulating.
After the buoyant three-day reunion ended with a Sunday brunch, I
drove Pat and her longtime friend/classmate Ellen Sherriffs Sparks
to the Los Angeles airport for their return flight to San
Francisco. Our farewell embrace carried a silent message to both of
us to want to be together again.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Pat telephoned my hotel, hoping to resume
conversation; but I was out to dinner with a friend, telling him I
was in love. When I returned to Fort Worth, a letter from Pat was
waiting for me. After several exchanges of mail, we resorted to the
telephone with increasing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Our first post-reunion rendezvous was in Albuquerque, N.M., two
months later. After my romantic greeting at the airport, Pat noted
that it was the first time I had ever kissed her. Reminded of our
goodbye kiss in eighth grade, she wondered why I should remember
what she could not. The long-ago event surely meant more to me than
to her.
</P>
<P>
   Marriage was an early prospect, but we didn't rush matters. Over
most of a full year we contrived to be together often, hardly
intimidated by the 1,600 miles between us. On an October day in Los
Angeles, we visited every school we had attended together; and we
floated in nostalgia that evening, sharing a glorious dinner
occasion with Cherry Yamada Uyeda and with Bill Bernhoft.
</P>
<P>
   We were married on July 25 in Moraga, in the serene home of a
friend of Pat's. Preceding the wedding ceremony was the playing of
Walter Huston's fabled recording of Kurt Weill's ``September Song''
_ ``our song,'' quite appropriately. Most of the 75 people who
attended have expressed what Pat and I believe _ that the ceremony
could not have been more heartfelt and meaningful. All of my
children were there with their families, and Pat's wonderful son
managed the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Pat and I are presently living in two states in an arrangement
that's working quite well. We manage to be together about
two-thirds of the time, and exploit the telephone when we're apart.
Soon, we'll be together full time.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel Garcia Marquez's ``Love in the Time of Cholera'' tells
of a woman and man who finally get together after 50 years of his
longing. We've surpassed those lovers, and Pat and I believe
absolutely that God brought us back together.
</P>
<P>
   Ours is not a placid convenience of companionship for two people
knocking on the door of 70. It is love in every romantic and
spiritual manifestation. We thrive in our today and rejoice in our
tomorrow _ certain, however, that both are inexorably attached to a
many-splendored childhood we shared.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
