<HEADLINE>
A KINDLER, GENTLER, BETTER-ARMED IRS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Internal Revenue Service is trying to improve
its image, but the agency is not winning any friends in some
circles by stocking up on shotguns and semiautomatic handguns.
</P>
<P>
   IRS contracts recently discovered by anti-tax activists give the
agency the option of buying $200,000 worth of Remington Model 11-87
shotguns and $1 million worth of Sigarms' Sauer semiautomatic
pistols.
</P>
<P>
   IRS officials said they have no intention of spending that much,
but they have ordered about 620 handguns and 175 shotguns, at a
total cost of about $448,000. A spokesman said that most of the
guns replaced aging weapons in an IRS arsenal that includes 3,000
pistols and 900 shotguns.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year contracts, awarded in 1994 and 1995, came to light
when a conservative columnist discovered them on a government
Internet site. The Web site is no longer accessible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something smells worse than second-hand tobacco smoke here,''
Jon E. Dougherty wrote in a July column in USAJournal, a
conservative Internet newsletter. ``IRS agents, who are already
operating under a prejudicial mindset against taxpayers, do not
need firepower to help enforce tax laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written response prepared for members of Congress, the IRS
explained that the $1.2 million figure is a high-end estimate that
includes possible weapons purchases for the Secret Service and the
Drug Enforcement Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS assigns the weapons to special agents, whose duties
include arresting tax evasion suspects and executing search
warrants. Agency spokesman Steve Pyrek said the IRS has about 3,000
pistols, one for every special agent, and 900 shotguns that are
issued as needed for raids and other law enforcement activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any plans to buy any more shotguns or
handguns,'' Pyrek said. ``We have enough right now.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ron Hutcheson is chief of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's
Washington bureau. You can e-mail him at
rhutcheson(at)krwashington.com or call him at (202) 383-6101.)
</P>
</TEXT>
