<P>
   HILLARY-POPULARITY (Washington) _ Perhaps it's symbolic that as
temperatures hit record highs in the capital, Hillary Rodham
Clinton unveiled the White House Christmas theme of ``Winter
Wonderland.'' As the impeachment move against her husband
continues, the first lady's year of lows is about to end with her
at a high. She is at 69 percent approval in the polls, on the cover
of Vogue and was the Democratic workhorse of the campaign season.
By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ The White House will call 14
witnesses _ including three members of the House Judiciary
Committee during the Watergate era _ for the defense of President
Clinton at hearings before the committee beginning Tuesday. The
hearings are expected to last for two days and could run until
midnight each day. By JOHN C. HENRY and GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-COUNSEL (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno is
unlikely to appoint a special counsel to explore President
Clinton's connections to campaign advertising financed by the
Democratic National Committee, Justice Department sources say. By
JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   YOSEMITE-CARS (Washington) _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt
discusses a plan, due for release next May, to reduce Yosemite
National Park's heavy traffic congestion. The plan would use a
voluntary bus service to reduce the number of cars passing through
the valley of the park. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHUTTLE-STATION (Houston) _ Astronauts from shuttle Endeavour
will take a walk in space to seal electrical and data cable
connections between the first two modules of the international
space station. By MARK CARREAU.
</P>
<P>
   MOON-ROCK (Undated) _ U.S. Customs agents in Miami say they have
recovered a chunk of moon rock that a Florida man wanted to sell
for $5 million, but failed to declare as he entered the United
States. The chunk of the moon, which was collected by the crew of
Apollo 17, was given by President Richard M. Nixon to the people of
Honduras. By TONY FREEMANTLE.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-ELECTION (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Populist leader Hugo
Chavez, who won the presidency Sunday in an election landslide,
signals that he plans to work on helping the poor, who provided the
bulk of his support. Former President Jimmy Carter, who helped
monitor the election, praises the election process and says he
would encourage foreign investment under Chavez. By JOHN OTIS.
</P>
