<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DENTISTRY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENTISTS WIELD LASERS AGAINST DECAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Ohio, N.C., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much of the dread in the dreaded trip to the dentist is being
removed: New treatments are bringing patients freedom from
drilling, freedom from anesthesia and freedom from pain. Moreover,
they appear to be, in their initial stages, safer more accurate and
faster than traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   Technological advances have, after decades of scientific and
engineering effort, produced laser beams that can cut efficiently
and without pain into the hardest surface of the body _ teeth _ to
remove decay and prepare cavities for filling.
</P>
<P>
   And computerized X-rays are greatly reducing the levels of
radiation to which patients are being exposed. At the same time,
the computers are producing a much larger, brighter, easier-to-read
image of a patient's cavities, displayed on a 17-inch computer
screen at the dentist's elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The lasers, used with a stream of water sprayed on the teeth,
have been successful in dental work done on 1,800 people in
clinical trials. All but one percent reported no pain or need for
anesthesia, compared with 70 percent of those treated with drills.
</P>
<P>
   The laser treatment was approved by the Food and Drug
Administration for use in adults in May 1997 and for children last
October.
</P>
<P>
   The development of technology that would apply laser light to
the repair of decaying teeth is the culmination of nearly four
decades of research and development. A variety of obstacles
presented themselves, chief among them the heat generated by the
laser that could damage the nerve of the tooth and destroy the
fiber optic material needed to deliver the laser beam to the tooth
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Momtaheni, an oral surgeon in New York and clinical
professor at the Columbia University School of Dentistry, said that
the new lasers were ``extremely important and opened a whole new
era'' to a field that for centuries has been associated with pain
and suffering to almost anyone whose teeth began to decay.
</P>
<P>
   Both Momtaheni and Dr. H. Jinder Khurana, a New York dentist and
program chairman of the annual New York Dental Meeting held last
week for some 24,000 colleagues, said the use of the lasers caused
no side effects in the clinical trials and early use in dentists'
offices, but cautioned that, as with all new technology, hidden
problems could emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The laser technology ``must be carefully watched for possible
adverse side effects that may arise in the future,'' Khurana said.
</P>
<P>
   A race to harness the new technology had been on since 1964,
when Dr. Leo Goldman, director of the dermatology department at the
University of Cincinnati, began experimenting with lasers _
powerful, highly focused beams of light. He tried placing various
combinations of chemical elements or compounds _ holmium,
neodymium, yttrium and lithium among them _ in crystalline
cylinders and shooting rays of ordinary light at them.
</P>
<P>
   The hope was to activate or excite the electrons in the
chemicals to create light with just the right wave length and
energy to cut tooth enamel without overheating. But the right
chemical combinations proved elusive.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the 1980s that a team of researchers from
academic and private business research groups, led by Dr. Myron
Wohlbarsht at Duke University and Dr. Robert Freiberg representing
academic and private research groups, hit upon erbium, which in
combination with other elements, produced the correct wave length
to cut tooth enamel, and the team received a patent for the idea in
1987. But the overheating problem persisted when they tried to use
it in animal studies.
</P>
<P>
   In the following four years Freiberg, and his team came up with
the idea of adding water to absorb enough of the heat before the
laser was shot out of the cylinder. The team also reported applying
air or water spray to the teeth during its experiments and clinical
trials for added cooling and to make the cutting more efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Colette Cozean, an original member of Freiberg's team, said
in an interview that the FDA then began a review of the laser data
and found it supported the claims made for it. Premier Laser
Systems of Irvine, Calif., was granted approval for the treatment
of adults and later for children.
</P>
<P>
   A second manufacturer, Biolase Technology of San Clemente,
Calif., which developed a slightly different technology, was given
the go-ahead in October for laser work on some but not all types of
adult cavities.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Wayne T. Wozniak of the American Dental Association's
council on scientific affairs, agreed that the laser was an
important new tool for dentistry, but added cautionary notes to
those of Momtaheni and Khurana. He warned that it is possible for
lasers to damage a tooth and cause pain if they penetrate too
deeply and strike at the heart of the nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Wozniak also said that the laser would not replace the drill
completely. It was not, for example, given approval for removing
metal-based fillings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But both Dr. Cozean, now the chief executive of Premier, and
Jeffrey W. Jones, chief executive of Biolase, said that approval
has never been given for drilling out metal fillings either,
because no one knows the effects that escaping gases or particles
may have on the mouth. The correct way to remove a filling, they
said, is to cut around it and remove it with a dental pick.
</P>
<P>
   They added that a laser in the hands of one who is not properly
trained to use it, can, as with the user of a drill, cause damage.
But they in normal and proper use it does not and, if it does hit
the nerve, they said, it causes neither damage nor pain.
</P>
<P>
   The computer-enhanced X-ray technology was developed in 1994 in
a cellar in Queens at the home of David B. Schick, now president
and chief executive of Schick Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Since then it has been refined so that, as of a few months ago,
the new bigger, brighter, easier to read X-ray image of the inside
of a patient's mouth, can be called up on dentists' lap-tops, if
they have more than one treatment room and want to carry the X-ray
images from room to room, or on a large computer on a console.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
