<SLUG> BC-SCI-SEX-HEALTH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO LESSER KNOWN SEXUALLY TRANSMITTED DISEASES ACCOUNT FOR MOST NEW
CASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By LINDA VILLAROSA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among sexually transmitted diseases, syphilis, herpes,
chlamydia, gonorrhea and HIV are probably the best known. However,
a report released last week shows that two lesser known infections
_ human papillomavirus and trichomoniasis _ actually account for
two-thirds of new cases of the diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers convened by the American Social Health Association,
who prepared the report for the Kaiser Family Foundation, said that
better detection of some sexually transmitted diseases, or STD's,
was responsible for a jump in new cases in the United States _ from
the often cited figure of 12 million, which was released by the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in the mid-1980s to an
estimated 15.3 million new cases in 1996, the last year for which
statistics are available.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is good news and bad news in the report,'' said Dr.
Willard Cates, Jr., president of Family Health International in
Research Triangle Park, N.C., and chairman of the research panel
that prepared the report. ``Better detection offers a great
opportunity to treat the spread of STD, but it has also shown that
the epidemic is bigger than previously thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that an estimated 5.5 million Americans
contract human papillomavirus every year and 20 million people
already have this incurable viral infection. It is generally
characterized by soft, itchy warts in and around the genitals, and
can lead to cervical cancer in women. Cervical cancer is
responsible for 5,000 deaths a year in the United States, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 90 percent of cases of invasive carcinoma of the cervix
there is evidence of HPV,'' said Dr. Vanessa Cullins, an
obstetrician-gynecologist and medical director of AVSC
International, a nonprofit organization involved in reproductive
health. New tests that detect the DNA of the virus have improved
diagnosis of the disease, Dr. Cullins added.
</P>
<P>
   Though awareness of trichomoniasis has increased over the past
decade, it remains difficult to detect. As many as five million
Americans contract it every year, but many do not know they have
this parasitic infection. In men there are often no signs of the
infection, while symptoms in women include discharge with an
unpleasant odor, which is often confused with yeast infection.
Trichomoniasis can be cured with antibiotics; untreated, it can
lead to preterm labor in pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women have never heard of trich, because they only know
about yeast,'' said Dr. Sharon Hillier, an associate professor of
obstetrics, gynecology and reproductive sciences at the University
of Pittsburgh School of Medicine. ``At our clinic, one-third of the
women treat themselves with an antifungal before they even walk in
the door,'' she said, referring to the over-the-counter medication
for yeast infection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
