<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SKIN-HERBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HERBS, A `FULLER PALETTE' FOR SKIN CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By NANCY BETH JACKSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid the recent blitz of scientific studies on the effectiveness
of herbal treatments, Dr. Alan Dattner, a dermatologist, stepped
back to take a look at several herbal preparations that have
sometimes been used to treat common dermatological problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the November issue of Archives of Dermatology, he and his
co-author, Dr. Donald Brown, a New Jersey-based naturopathic
physician and editor of The Quarterly Review of Natural Medicine,
noted that many doctors offered both prescription medicines and
herbal preparations to their patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a question of a fuller palette of treatment,'' Dattner
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two doctors from different traditions do not claim to break
any new ground in this paper. ``We discuss some common herbal
preparations historically used for dermatological conditions and
recent studies that support their use,'' the doctors wrote in their
review.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional practice of topically treating dermatological
conditions with plant-derived medicines predates the cultures of
ancient Egypt and remains vital today in the United States and
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the herbal preparations, associated with various skin
conditions, can be found in health food stores. Experts caution
that patients using herbs should discuss them with their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   DERMATITIS _ This condition, which Dr. Dattner calls ``the
wastebasket'' of skin inflammation, covers a variety of nonspecific
complaints, which can be as common _ and as annoying _ as diaper
rash and eczema.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional treatment for skin rashes has included powerful
topical steroids, antibiotics and Vitamin A. Brown and Dattner
suggest the pot marigold as an herbal substitute. Calendula
officinalis, as the marigold is called, is the basis for topical
creams used when an antiseptic or antifungal effect is needed.
Herbalists have traditionally used it in treating burns, bruises,
cuts and diaper rash.
</P>
<P>
   Chamomile, a member of the daisy family that is mainly known as
a calming tea, has been used in a number of topical products to
ease dermatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Studies using a chamomile cream produced in Frankfurt, Germany,
found it 60 percent as effective as hydrocortisone in one trial and
``about as effective'' in another, Brown and Dattner say.
</P>
<P>
   Plantain, not the banana but a low-growing perennial as common
in lawns as the dandelion, has a folk history of reducing the
swelling and pain of insect stings and treating rattlesnake bites.
Although clinical studies are limited to reports of its usefulness
in easing poison ivy rashes and healing wounds, Dr. Dattner has
found that applying crushed plantain leaves to the site helps
reduce the itch and swelling of bug bites.
</P>
<P>
   PSORIASIS _ The cause of this chronic scaling-skin disease is
unknown. Conventional treatment includes exposure to sunlight,
topical steroids, lubricating creams and coal tar ointments. In
more severe cases, patients are treated with ultraviolet light,
Dattner said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the topical anti-inflammatory herbal agents used to
treat dermatitis may help, but few studies have looked at herbal
treatment for psoriasis.
</P>
<P>
   A capsaicin cream, derived from cayenne peppers, is perhaps the
best plant-related product, the two doctors say. They point to two
clinical trials in which application of the cream led to a
``significant'' reduction in scaling and redness, but with the
adverse effect of a burning sensation where applied.
</P>
<P>
   Aloe vera, a familiar beauty and health product used to soothe,
heal and moisturize the skin, was tested as a topic treatment in a
Pakistani study of 60 subjects with slight to moderate chronic
psoriasis. The aloe group reported significantly greater
improvement than the placebo group.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLEX LABIALIS _ This recurrent viral infection, in which cold
sores typically appear around the mouth, has no known cure.
Standard treatment involves antiviral drugs that can speed the
course of the virus and reduce symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon balm, which herbalists also know as melissa, smells like
lemons and has been used as an herbal substitute.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors report a 1994 study in which a lemon balm extract
cream brought complete healing in 96 percent of the patients after
seven days with only three patients reporting a burning sensation
at the site of application.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors urge further study of herbal treatment to document
its effects in ``an acceptable scientific manner,'' and also remind
their fellow practitioners that many herbs have already been used
by patients who learned their applications from their parents and
grandparents. Understanding how doctor-prescribed and herbal
treatments can complement one another adds to effectiveness of
medical treatment, they said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1629EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
