<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRASSAI-PHOTO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRASSAI IMAGES REVEAL ARTIST'S PURSUIT OF PERFECT TRUTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (An idiaeresis, or double dot, needed over i in Brassai; accent
mark needed over second a in Halasz) 
 
(Attn: Los Angeles and Washington, D.C.) 
 
By PATRICIA C. JOHNSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Brassai did not make photography his medium until he
was 31 years old. But once claimed, it became the tool of his
passionate eye, oracular in its portrayal of a richly textured
world.
</P>
<P>
   Artists, opium smokers, thugs, children and aristocracy captured
in gelatin silver prints are part of it. So are the breathtaking
bridges of Paris, a humble thimble and the inopportune rear end of
a race horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brassai: The Eye of Paris'' runs through Feb. 28 at the Museum
of Fine Arts in Houston, then it will travel to the J. Paul Getty
Museum in Los Angeles and the National Gallery of Art in
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brassai: The Eye of Paris'' gathers the images into a major
exhibition 15 years in the making. Curated by Anne W. Tucker, head
of the museum's department of photography, the landmark show
celebrates the centennial of the artist's birth in 1899 and offers
the first in-depth look at his work since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Born Gyula Halasz in Brasso, the Hungarian town from which he
drew his pseudonym, the artist made Paris his home from the age of
25. Brassa, Tucker writes, ``had an intimate relationship with
Paris. Day by day, evening after evening for 40 years, he
systematically explored her with the leisure of a lover.''
</P>
<P>
   He was part of the heady intellectual and artistic ferment of
Paris in the 1920s and 1930s. His friends were writers such as
Henry Miller and Paul Reverdy, painters and sculptors such as Pablo
Picasso, Henri Matisse and Alberto Giacometti. He explored all of
the city, from its bridges and monuments to its hidden corners, and
all of its citizens, be they aristocrats, artists, prostitutes or
hoodlums.
</P>
<P>
   He made his mark with the series ``Paris de nuit'' (Paris by
Night). This outstanding collection of images shows Paris as we
dream it and want to remember it _ misty air, soft gaslight,
romantic bridges arching over the Seine, thick walls and broad
avenues shrouded in silvery tones and whispered promises. Published
in book form in 1932, it won Brassa the appellation ``the eye of
Paris'' _ coined by Miller _ and international admiration. It also,
and forever, influenced photographers shooting cities and night
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   He dissimulated carefully planned compositions in a veil of
spontaneity. He focused on scenes that interested him and waited
till that which he hoped would happen happened. Many times his
subjects were accomplices, fully aware of the photographer's
presence but forgetting or ignoring it, thus affording him the
moment of perfect truth he sought.
</P>
<P>
   This patient willfulness is most evident in ``Secret Paris of
the '30s.'' The series, which followed ``Paris de nuit,'' is a
composite portrait of the underworld of libertines and criminals of
all descriptions. Chorus girls in dishabille backstage at the
Folies Bergre, a pair of hoods smoking in the street, prostitutes,
a lesbian couple in a coffeehouse are among the unforgettable
pictures that remained unpublished for four decades. They may be
candid, but it is obvious that the protagonists had to tolerate, if
not necessarily collaborate with, the photographer.
</P>
<P>
   In two of the pictures, one of Brassa's bodyguards _ a necessary
precaution when he ventured into the demimonde that did not
necessarily welcome him _ posed for the lens. He's the man in the
famous photograph ``Introductions at Suzy's'' (a brothel in the
Latin Quarter), which shows three naked prostitutes from the back.
He is also the customer in another bordello scene who dresses while
the woman sits at intimate toilette. The camera's vantage point
couldn't be any other than bedside. One wouldn't suspect
playacting, so casual and believable do the scenes appear, yet they
are composed with the care and fine illumination accorded other
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Brassa's probing eye also focused on artists and their work. A
commission from Harper's Bazaar after World War II led him to
photograph sculptures in Picasso's studio. Among them is a plaster
cast attentively documenting the artist's hand, the hand that
redefined the 20th-century vision. &UR;  &LR; Another sculpture, the
emblematic bronze skull ``Death's Head,'' was taken for a book in
1943 at Picasso's request.
</P>
<P>
   Portraiture, many believe, is the photographer's greatest
strength. Here is a character study of Miller dated 1932-34. He
leans against a door frame in a light-colored trench coat,
characteristic owl-like eyeglasses and the unmistakable ``mandarin
smile'' that Brassa described. Picasso, with whom the photographer
shared a decades-long friendship, is the subject of many pictures,
two of which are included here.
</P>
<P>
   Also from this period is a portrait of Marianne
Delaunay-Belleville, or Madame D.-B., as Brassa referred to her.
She was an aristocrat and accomplished pianist who befriended the
impoverished young Brassa, new to Paris, and became his mentor,
patron and entre into high society.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1948 portrait of Giacometti, Brassa gives us a photograph
in shades of silver and black velvet, a privileged look at a
sculptor famous for his shyness. He is seated on a sagging, worn
mattress layered with newspapers. His intense eyes are clear and
look straight back at us from beneath black curls. He wears a dark,
dog-eared jacket and pants, and holds a sculpture against his knee.
This sculpture _ a skeletal, startling white arm _ extends across
the picture plane from behind the artist's right shoulder and
across his chest to seemingly grasp the left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of children, like the delighted little boy in ``Balloon
Seller, Montsouris Park'' (1931-34), and of elegant women at social
events counter the dark underworld Brassa frequented during the
same period. There is the graffiti he admired _ especially the kind
gouged out of walls, which he described as the poor man's sculpture
and which include the only two color photographs in the exhibition.
His pictures for Harper's range from the sober image of two cloaked
old men deep in conversation in Madrid to the humorous
juxtaposition of a comparatively tiny statue of Napoleon and the
large woman who promenades past it on a New Orleans street.
</P>
<P>
   Brassa began as a journalist and studied drawing in Budapest's
and Berlin's art academies before moving to Paris. Of his
commitment to photography, he wrote, ``It is not enough for the
artist of today to express the meaning of our age; he must express
it in the modern medium. Our generation can only recognize itself
completely in images expressed in the new languages of our century.
Hence the power (and) prestige of the cinema and of photography.''
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't forsake the written word or other art media when
he picked up the camera. Increasingly after the war, he returned to
those expressive routes. Tucker has included a handful of Brassa's
sculptures and drawings _ animated, sensual works that, like the
palm-size ``Almond Woman,'' recall Cycladic figurines.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1962, Brassa stopped making photographs and dedicated
himself to writing. By the time of his death in 1984, he had
published 17 books of his photographs and accompanying texts. Among
them are two on Picasso and two more on Miller. ``If you want to
know about me, read Brassa's book,'' Picasso said of ``Picasso &AMP;
Co.,'' published in 1966. His 18th book, on French novelist Marcel
Proust, was finished shortly before his death and will be published
in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had perfect memory,'' Tucker said, ``and he was a great
raconteur.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his subjects _ including Marie, his cleaning lady, and
the taxi driver who delivered a monologue during a ride one
Christmas Eve _ would recognize themselves in his narratives, and
whether it was important that they do so, Brassa replied no.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meaning of art is not authenticity,'' he wrote, ``but the
expression of authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   Always, the viewer walks away knowing more, understanding better
than before encountering his pictures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
