</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TEXAS CONSTITUTION FOR THE NEXT MILLENNIUM? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State Sen. Bill Ratliff and state Rep. Rob
Junell, two legislative heavyweights who have taken on one of the
most difficult tasks in the Free World, are correct.
</P>
<P>
   Texas needs a new state constitution. Texas is able to govern
itself under the present charter, adopted in 1876 at the end of
Reconstruction, only because the document has been amended more
than 370 times to try to keep pace with modernization.
</P>
<P>
   Today's urban Texas bears little resemblance to the rural,
frontier state that existed when the present constitution was
written as Texans were emerging from the darkest period in the
state's history.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Texas is preparing to enter not only a new century, but
also a new millennium. What better time, Ratliff and Junell ask, to
bring the structure of state government into the modern age?
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact that the two veteran, well-respected legislative
leaders _ one a Republican, the other a Democrat _ are sponsoring
the constitutional revision effort means that it will get a full
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But, having watched the last attempt at overhauling the
constitution go down in flaming defeat in 1974 and 1975, I am not
ready to place any bets on their success yet.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional convention of 1974 was not a pretty sight.
Its members, or delegates, were the 181 members of the Legislature,
who met for several months in the House chamber. It ended in
failure on its last night, coming up three votes short of the
two-thirds vote necessary to send a new constitution to Texas
voters for ratification.
</P>
<P>
   The key fight ultimately was over a business-backed attempt to
lock into the constitution the state's right-to-work law, which
prohibits union membership as a condition of employment.
</P>
<P>
   Organized labor bitterly fought the proposal. And although labor
ran a poor second _ and still does _ to business in the hearts and
minds of Texas lawmakers, unions had enough clout to block a
two-thirds vote.
</P>
<P>
   There also were other obstacles. County officials and numerous
special interests, who are protected by many constitutional
provisions, fought any effort to remove those provisions.
</P>
<P>
   And the legislator-delegates were very susceptible to
special-interest lobbyists, particularly since the convention was
held in an election year.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders tried to revive the revision effort during
the 1975 regular session by offering a new constitution to the
voters in the form of several constitutional amendments, with
right-to-work and other particularly controversial provisions
deleted.
</P>
<P>
   But the voters rejected all the amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the blame went to then-Gov. Dolph Briscoe, who came out
against all the amendments only three weeks before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Many observers also blamed the voters' reaction on a distrust of
any constitution written by legislators. The public's distrust of
government had been heightened by the Sharpstown stock fraud
scandal, which had recently rocked state government, and the
Watergate scandal, which had recently forced the resignation of
President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Ratliff and Junell aren't proposing a new constitutional
convention but a new constitution in the form of one constitutional
amendment, which would have to be ratified by voters if it wins
legislative approval on a two-thirds vote during next year's
regular session.
</P>
<P>
   And, with Sharpstown and Watergate little more than items in the
history books now, they hope the public will have more trust in
lawmakers this time.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative sponsors also have taken steps to defuse some
potential fights. Right-to-work, for example, isn't in their
proposed constitution. And although they would give the governor
sweeping new appointment powers over many judges and executive
officeholders, the offices of lieutenant governor, comptroller and
attorney general would remain elective.
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't much reason to think that the special interests
who helped scuttle the last effort to rewrite the constitution will
be any less willing to give up their special constitutional
benefits or protections now _ or that lawmakers will be any less
willing to listen to them.
</P>
<P>
   And any of numerous provisions could become controversial enough
to sink the entire effort if the Legislature does put a new charter
on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   One is a proposal by Ratliff and Junell to establish a salary
commission, which would remove the voters' long-held power to veto
legislative pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   Another key factor could be Gov. George W. Bush. With his
overwhelming popularity, the governor could become an effective
salesman for a new constitution. But Bush may prefer to avoid that
fight, particularly if he is preparing to launch a presidential
bid.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be accurate to say that Ratliff and Junell are
dreaming an impossible dream. But they are getting ready to have
one whale of an experience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
