<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-COMMERCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANUFACTURERS WRESTLE OVER ON-LINE SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you want to shop at www.macys.com instead of
trudging down to the mall this holiday season, don't bother looking
for Levi's jeans or Levi's Dockers brand _ you won't find them.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., which started selling Levi's and Dockers on
its Web sites (www.levi.com and www.dockers.com) within a week of
Macy's in November, won't allow Macy's or any other retailer to
sell the products on line. The company wants its cyberstores to be
the only place to buy Levi merchandise through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As an increasing number of manufacturers start to sell directly
to customers through the Internet, a growing concern emerges. It's
known as ``channel conflict'' _ the head-to-head competition
created between manufacturers and the brick-and-mortar retailers
that sell the manufacturer's goods.
</P>
<P>
   Channel conflict is ``a huge problem,'' said Barry Parr, an
analyst with the market research company International Data Corp.
``It is not easy to change a distribution system.''
</P>
<P>
   Many manufacturers have chosen not to sell on line, either
because they lack the infrastructure to sell and ship merchandise
directly or they don't want to upset the solid relationship they
have established with their resellers. Others are selling on line,
but lessen possible conflicts by opting not to offer any promotions
or special deals.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, channel conflict was more of a fear than a real
problem. Many manufacturers and department stores had World Wide
Web sites for the sole purpose of building customer awareness and
brand image, not for direct transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Web sales have been dominated by on-line retailers, such as the
video store Reel.com and giant bookseller Amazon.com., companies
whose entire business is Web-based. Also relatively quick to go on
line were such retailers as the Gap and L.L. Bean, which compete
with their own stores and catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Now traditional stores and manufacturers have realized they will
lose ground to on-line retailers unless they sell directly through
the World Wide Web. New York-based Jupiter Communications estimates
shoppers will spend $2.3 billion through on-line outlets this
holiday season, up from $1.1 billion last year. They also have
become less worried that on-line sales will cannibalize store sales
and are more confident in the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be hard pressed in a year or two to find a manufacturer
that doesn't sell something on line,'' said Erina DuBois, digital
commerce analyst for Dataquest Inc. in San Jose, Calif. ``It's an
area you cannot not play in.''
</P>
<P>
   But right now, manufacturer-direct on-line sales are still not
that common. According to an Ernst &AMP; Young study produced with the
National Retail Federation early this year, only 9 percent of
manufacturers currently sell on the Web; an additional 12 percent
have plans to do so eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will continue to be flare-ups, but retailers who get
caught up in that are missing the point,'' Ernst &AMP; Young spokesman
Keith Hark said. ``The point isn't whether or not they are cutting
a little here or there into each other's businesses. You have to
accommodate the customer.''
</P>
<P>
   Web watchers say the way this delicate relationship between
manufacturer and distributor will be played out will depend on the
companies, their products and their on-line goals.
</P>
<P>
   What Levi has decided is that a reseller may not have the time
or money to sell Levi products on line the way Levi wants it done.
Levi established www.levi.com in 1995 and www.dockers.com the
following year, but just started selling on the sites last month.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McSpadden, director of e-commerce for the Dockers brand,
said the company spent the past year interviewing customers about
what they want from an on-line store. The site offers such features
as interactive changing rooms and a ``fit calculator'' for women.
</P>
<P>
   McSpadden said Levi's decision to bar other retailers from
selling its products on line has nothing to do with its
relationship with its resellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not an issue between Macy's and Levi Strauss on
this,'' he said. ``This is just a different business model for both
Levi and Macy's.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Anderson, president of Macys.com, said there was no rift
between Macy's and Levi or Dockers. ``I can't explain and do not
know the entire explanation behind why they chose to go this
route,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said no similar problems have arisen with other
manufacturers. He admitted several vendors were reluctant about
Macy's on-line plans when first approached, but changed their minds
once the concept was explained.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking a different approach is New York-based Estee Lauder Cos.
Inc., which last month launched a selling site for its Clinique
brand. Estee Lauder is also the parent company of cosmetic
companies Aveda, Prescriptives, MAC, Aramis, Bobbi Brown and
Origins.
</P>
<P>
   Estee Lauder maintains that department stores have brought the
company to where it is today and it intends to be sensitive to
those retailers. That means handling on-line sales differently for
each of its brands.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Clinique can be purchased at www.clinique.com, a
site established three years ago that just started selling direct
last month. Estee Lauder also sells Clinique and Estee Lauder
products through Macys.com after successful pilot tests.
</P>
<P>
   But when Bobbi Brown customers log onto the site at
www.bobbibrowncosmetics.com and make a purchase, the transaction is
handled by Neiman Marcus through a joint venture arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   And in February, Origins becomes available on-line. The brand
already has its own separate, established distribution network
because it is sold through catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an either-or proposition,'' said Angela Kapps,
Estee Lauder's vice president of special markets and new media.
``The reality is our products will be sold on line in a lot of
places. You will be able to buy where it's convenient to buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapps likens channel conflict to what happened when designers
opened their own stores. ``Back in the '70s when Ralph Lauren
opened its first store down the street from Bloomingdale's, people
said, how could you do that?'' she said. ``But then it wound up
increasing sales in both places.''
</P>
<P>
   DuBois advocates a sort of ``happy medium'' approach toward
dealing with the manufacturer-reseller relationship. She said
exclusive selling sites are not ideal in forming those
relationships, but manufacturers may want to limit the number of
sites that sell their products to ensure quality control.
</P>
<P>
   Parr, of International Data Corp., said there are no easy
answers, but on-line selling will become virtually mandatory for
manufacturers and traditional stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not selling on the Web, you've got a big problem,''
Parr said. ``When these kind of shifts take place in the
marketplace, you may find you're damned if you do, damned if you
don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
