<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODEDTOWN-1200(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVEN WEEKS AFTER FLOOD, SOME IN SOUTH TEXAS TOWN STILL HOMELESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY BINGHAM 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUERO, Texas _ The old blue Dodge spews smoke from its muffler
as Miss Ora B. Wesley steers the car onto Hamilton Street. She
drives around heaps of trash piled in front of every house. Hers is
the last on the left.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Wesley, as everyone calls her, parks at the corner and
lifts a bucket of cleaning supplies and a pair of rubber gloves
from the back seat. She walks as far as the front porch before she
has to take off her bifocals and wipe her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Some days, she gets inside before the stench of river water
overwhelms her. Other days, she makes it through all the rooms
before the broken picture window, the buckled walls, the
mud-covered floors make her teary.
</P>
<P>
   It's been like this nearly every day since the October flood.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Wesley turns around and gets back in the car. On days like
this, she drives around the neighborhood and asks herself, If her
mother and daddy were still living, could they stand it? Could they
stand to see trash in the trees and houses washed off their
foundations?
</P>
<P>
   Her entire neighborhood flooded, even her church. Two of her
daughters lost their homes, too. On days like this, 75-year-old
Miss Wesley gets in the car and just drives. She wonders, Will this
place ever be home again?
</P>
<P>
   IT SWALLOWED EVERYTHING: The day the Guadalupe River overflowed,
Miss Wesley was not at home. It was Monday, Oct. 19. A weekend rain
had flooded some of the two-lane roads on the outskirts of town, so
school was closed.
</P>
<P>
   When Miss Wesley retired as assistant supervisor of housekeeping
at the Cuero Community Hospital, she agreed to baby-sit the
Shoemaker children. She cleaned the family's bed-and-breakfast inn,
so she already knew the two boys and the little girl.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Wesley was with the children at their house the morning the
river marched out of its banks. She had seen the rain in San
Antonio and in the Hill Country, but that was hours away. No one in
Cuero, an old farming town of 6,700 people, expected any serious
flooding, at least not for a couple of days.
</P>
<P>
   But the river grew swift upstream, and by the time it reached
the prison northeast of Cuero, it was swallowing pastures, downing
trees and gaining speed.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Wesley's son-in-law saw the river coming. He was at his
house, a few blocks from where she lives, when he left the car
idling and ran inside. By the time he got back out with his arms
full of clothes, the river had surrounded his car.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, Miss Wesley left the Shoemaker house to
check on her own. She turned the old Dodge down onto a side street
and found it flooded. She tried another and found the river there,
too. When she reached her house, her granddaughter was on the
porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Granny! The policeman said the water's coming fast. Granny, we
better hurry! The water's already in the back yard!''
</P>
<P>
   They were driving away when they met Miss Wesley's daughter, who
had come to make sure they were all right. That's when Miss Wesley
remembered that she forgot her high blood pressure medicine on the
dining room table.
</P>
<P>
   The river was circling the house when they returned. Miss
Wesley's daughter waded in for the medicine. The car wheels carved
a wake behind them as they left.
</P>
<P>
   Townspeople watched the river from a high spot on the main road.
They judged how fast it was moving by the things it carried: lawn
chairs and seat cushions first; doghouses and septic tanks later;
cars, sheds and finally a house from the corner of Hamilton and
Gonzales streets floated past them and was last seen in Carter's
pecan grove.
</P>
<P>
   Before the river crested, it kicked open the back door to Miss
Wesley's house. It forced its way through her window
air-conditioners, and it seeped behind her paneling and beneath her
carpeting.
</P>
<P>
   The river swallowed everything in her house except the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Cuero spent the next week in the Sands Motel &AMP; RV Park.
They ate meals in the parking lot of the old H.E.B. store, where
the Salvation Army set up. They got tetanus shots at the health
department, and they waited in line for permits to get back in
their houses.
</P>
<P>
   The weekly newspaper tallied the damage: 25 percent of the
town's houses flooded; hundreds of cattle drowned or missing; 85 of
the town's businesses closed.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Wesley moved into a room at the Shoemakers'
bed-and-breakfast inn. She wore clothes her sister sent from San
Antonio. She put the $12,096.69 the government gave her after the
flood into the bank.
</P>
<P>
   On the 10th day, Miss Wesley went home.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw, I said, `Lookie here, this is all gone. This is
something you can't patch up, and whatever you put here won't be
like it was.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Her dishes were dumped from the cabinets. Every drawer in her
house had been opened and emptied. Everything inside was covered
with a slick layer of shiny black mud.
</P>
<P>
   The living room furniture landed in the dining room; the
mattress landed against the wall. The couch stood up. The
refrigerator lay down. The telephone disappeared. Miss Wesley
wondered, ``How can this be?''
</P>
<P>
   She drove the few blocks from her house over to the little pink
house on Hamilton Street where she was born in 1923. The river had
swallowed it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The picture window used to be over there. Daddy kept his
sitting chair right here. Back there is where the boys used to
sleep. It used to be a screened-in porch, and Mother set the table
out there in the summer, and that's where we ate. It made it real,
real nice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew everybody in the neighborhood. There was a family back
there, and they had five children just like us, and we played
together. There was a chokeberry tree the boys climbed on. I
remember we used to have swings in that tree over there. We just
loved this little house.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG DECISION: Seven weeks have passed since the flood, and Miss
Wesley is still homeless, like a lot of her neighbors. One of her
daughters is living in a friend's hunting cabin, and another
daughter still lives at the motel. Miss Wesley is still at the
bed-and-breakfast in Room 3. She can't decide what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Shoemaker and some other men cleaned the mud out of her
house with a shovel and rake. They took everything she owned and
piled it at the street. They opened the windows to get rid of the
smell.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Wesley knows the money won't repair and replace everything.
One minute she thinks about making the repairs she can afford _ she
doesn't have the heart to tear the house down _ and another minute
she wonders whether the money is enough to buy a trailer. Some days
she thinks about her daughter, who begs her to move to Houston. She
can't make up her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought in that house, we loved in that house, we would all
be in that house and we would hug and make up, and you know, that's
the joy of a place.''
</P>
<P>
   On days like this, Miss Wesley gets in her car and just drives.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
