<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLOCK-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON POLLOCK SHOW RAISES MANY QUESTIONS, ANSWERS MOST IMPORTANT
ONES
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-POLLOCK-ELSEWHERE and BC-POLLOCK-OTHERS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ According to art-history legend, Jackson Pollock's
supple loops, spatters and gobs of paint lie at the heart of
American art's triumph over European painting.
</P>
<P>
   But attempts to verify that legend today, 42 years after the
artist's violent death, are burdened with high expectations _ as is
the case with the Museum of Modern Art's current Pollock
retrospective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackson Pollock'' is the first U.S. retrospective of the
artist's work in more than 30 years _ actually, the most complete
survey of Pollock's art ever assembled. It comes after his
contribution to American art has been elevated to the highest
heights by his advocates, then torn down to the lowest depths
ironical critics could manage. It's a time when conservators work
feverishly to prevent Pollock's trademark aluminum paint from
flaking. An era in which his paintings command millions of dollars
_ as did ``Number 8, 1950,'' when it fetched more than $11 million
at auction in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the questions hover. Will Pollock emerge from this show
a hero? Will the exhibition open viewers' eyes, once again, to his
greatness? Will it vindicate Pollock as the greatest American
artist of this century? Will it sustain his reputation as our most
controversial 20th century artist _ or will it prove him to be
merely interesting? And, finally, will enough people care about any
of those questions that ``Jackson Pollock'' will prove to be New
York's hot-ticket show this season?
</P>
<P>
   So far, published reviews suggest that, when he was good,
Pollock was scintillating and that, when he was bad, he was
borderline hopeless. Still, when I viewed the exhibition _ in
galleries that were far from crowded _ I was amazed and thrilled,
even with pictures any number of my peers found bad.
</P>
<P>
   I left MoMA thinking that Pollock could claim triumph for much
more than his glorious, notorious Action Paintings from his prime
years of 1947-50. I also decided that Pollock is not nearly as
quintessentially American as tradition would have _ he never
completely purged himself of Picasso, Siqueiros, the baroque and
other influences _ and that it doesn't matter whether he is or
isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Pollock's life was brief: He was born in Cody, Wyo., in 1912 and
died on the East Coast in 1956. It also was troubled: Intensely
charismatic, Pollock suffered from depression and alcoholism, and
effectively killed himself in a drunken automobile accident.
</P>
<P>
   In 1930, Pollock moved to New York to study painting with Thomas
Hart Benton at the Art Students League. In the early 1940s, he
gained the patronage of Peggy Guggenheim, who also represented
Pollock at her Art of This Century Gallery: It was for her that
Pollock painted his first large-scale painting, his breakthrough
``Mural'' of 1943.
</P>
<P>
   When Pollock moved with his new wife, artist Lee Krasner, to
Long Island, his approach to painting evolved _ within just two
years _ into his classic Action Paintings. Poured, flung and
spattered, executed on the floor rather than the wall or easel,
these paintings are so-called because Pollock considered them
arenas for, and documents of, his actions as an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Of the almost 160 works in the MoMA show, 46 are taken from
Pollock's classic period. This segment includes three monumental
works _ ``Number 32, 1950,'' ``One: Number 31, 1950,'' and ``Autumn
Rhythm: Number 30, 1950'' _ that erase any doubts as to why Pollock
was anointed the messiah of American art. These and others are
works of remarkable complexity and delicacy, executed on canvases
larger than the walls of most rooms. Between their dense, intricate
compositions and their grand dynamism, they seem wrought by the
forces of nature rather than man.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to encountering these miraculously resolved paintings,
however, viewers slog through a selection of early works that
include turgid attempts at both relative realism and total
abstraction. In them, we see Pollock wrestling, like Jacob with the
Angel, with a number of influences _ with the spatial compression
of cubism, mannerism and the baroque; with the heroic scale and
anguished struggle of the Mexican muralists, Michelangelo's ``Last
Judgment'' and Picasso's ``Guernica''; with the dark symbolism of
Albert Pinkham Ryder and the surrealism of Miro.
</P>
<P>
   But, in their earnest clumsiness, Pollock's early paintings
possess a quality, what some would call genius, that shines through
and sets them apart.
</P>
<P>
   That ineffable quality made me root for Pollock to pull through,
to go for it, as he experimented with spattering paint, mingling it
with relentless, urgent strokes of jarring color in ``The
She-Wolf'' (1943), Peggy Guggenheim's ``Mural'' and other works. As
his works became increasingly linear _ dense drawings in paint,
whether brushed on, flung on, squeezed straight from the tube or,
in the case of ``Croaking Movement (Sounds in the Grass Series)''
(1946), incised with the wrong end of Pollock's paint brush _ I
felt like cheering.
</P>
<P>
   Once he achieved his Action Paintings, though, many of the
classic works quickly seem aimless _ sporadic showers rather than
great, cleansing storms. Surely Pollock, too, felt his new way of
painting easily could degenerate into little more than a signature
style.
</P>
<P>
   In his last years, Pollock painted a number of black-and-white
canvases that combine dripped and brushed gestures and shapes, and
verge once more on representation of recognizable figures. At the
same time, he reprised most of his other approaches to painting,
and some of these _ including ``White Light'' (1954) and ``Untitled
(Scent)'' (circa 1953-55) _ are heartbreaking in their beauty.
</P>
<P>
   By exhibition's end, I was in an exhausted state of denial. I
didn't want to believe that Pollock had died according to the
fatalist motto of his era: ``Live fast, die young and leave a
good-looking corpse'' or, in Pollock's case ``corpus'' _ of work.
That would mean conceding that Pollock had overstayed his moment of
cultural relevance.
</P>
<P>
   To me, ``Jackson Pollock'' offered too many tantalizing
suggestions that, had he lived longer, Pollock would have done even
more for art _ and not just American art _ than legend claims.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFO BOX: ``Jackson Pollock,'' through Feb. 2: at the Museum of
Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd St., New York, NY. Information: (212)
708-9400
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact her at vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
