<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLLOCK-OTHERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST OF THE REST: NEW YORK'S OTHER FALL SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies BC-POLLOCK-EXHIBIT and BC-POLLOCK-ELSEWHERE) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Retrospectives for art stars like Jackson Pollock
easily get the lion's share of attention. But New York has several
other provocative shows this season, including ``Rendezvous'' at
the Guggenheim Museum, ``Edgar Degas, Photographer'' at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, and the Met's presentation of Flemish
paintings from its permanent collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rendezvous'' was a marvelous surprise, a rich brew of works by
artists great and small. Organized by the Guggenheim and the
Pompidou Center in Paris as a showcase for works from both
collections, ``Rendezvous'' levels the playing field shared by
modern artworks from America, France, England and other countries.
It mixes works by artists such as John Chamberlain and Cesar (both
of crushed-automobile fame), Robert Rauschenberg and Alberto Burri,
Joan Miro and Alexander Calder. In doing so, ``Rendezvous'' retires
the idea that American art achieved world supremacy in the years
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ``Rendezvous'' set me up with an almost global
context for viewing Pollock. It puts him in the company of artists
such as Andre Masson, Wifredo Lam, Roberto Matta, and others who
married expression of the subconscious with abstract compositions
that have no focal point or visual resting place, but fill the
canvas with lines and shapes in a constant state of flux.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rendezvous'' continues through Jan. 24. Information: Solomon
R. Guggenheim Museum, (212) 423-3500.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ``From Van Eyck to Bruegel: Early Netherlandish
Painting in The Metropolitan Museum of Art.'' While their Italian
counterparts used painting to impose ideal order upon the world,
early Northern artists like Petrus Christus, Jan Van Eyck and
Pieter Bruegel lovingly scrutinized the natural world and the world
of fantasy _ from the most mundane aspects of daily life to the
most disturbing reaches of the imagination _ without making visual
distinctions among any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Bursting with an encyclopedic scope of information _ with every
detail painstakingly painted and brought, as it were, to the
foreground _ their pictures appear irrational, strange and artless.
Paintings of holy events and human activities are set in the real
world without any strict focal point, any
</P>
<P>
   visual center of attention. As such, instead of seeming
centuries old, these works strike me as modern.
</P>
<P>
   A wondrous exhibition, the Met's collection is studded with
masterpieces, as well as with lesser works possessing their own
curious charm. Taken together, they provide visitors with a truly
altered state of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``From Van Eyck to Bruegel'' continues through Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   My only disappointment was Degas _ and that probably because I
expected so much from the show. For one thing, Degas' seemingly
random, snapshot approach to composing pictures makes him one of my
art gods. For another, I thought this show would reveal telling
relationships between Degas' photos and his other works, akin to
last winter's Picasso photographs show in Houston. But no such
luck. Despite a few such links, this was mostly a historical
exhibition that featured a few psychologically charged portraits,
but almost nothing of aesthetic interest. Too much life, not enough
fantasy or art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edgar Degas, Photographer'' continues through Jan. 3.
Information: Metropolitan Museum of Art, (212) 879-5500.
</P>
<P>
   (Janet Tyson is art critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Contact her at vizart(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
