<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITEHOUSE-HOLIDAY120     12-07 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITEHOUSE-HOLIDAY1208-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIRST LADY UNVEILS WHITE HOUSE DECORATIONS
 &HT;    PHOTOS to accompany this story are being placed in the National
folder on the Cox server.
 &HT;    EDS: Moving both in Washington (w) and Lifestyle (l) categories.
 &HT;    550 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the weather outside more delightful than
frightful, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton opened the holiday
season in the nation's capital Monday by revealing a Winter
Wonderland inside the freshly and festively decorated White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to try something different this year,'' said Mrs.
Clinton, showing reporters a White House gleaming with chilly
shades of white, silver and gold instead of the season's usual red
and green.
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures in the 70s and sidewalk Santas sweltering
beside their iron kettles, a family of snow folk welcomed White
House visitors to the East Colonnade. Mantels over fireplaces in
historic rooms were filled with penguins, polar bears, igloos, an
ice palace, an ice garden and Christmas packages wrapped in icy
silver and white.
</P>
<P>
   The mantelpiece decorations were all edible -- the sugary
creations of Colette Peters, a confectionery artist from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Beside being starkly beautiful, the decorations ``are wonderful
to smell,'' the first lady noted.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to announcing ``A Winter Wonderland'' as the holiday
theme -- a tradition begun by Jackie Kennedy in 1961 -- Mrs.
Clinton presented this year's White House Christmas card. A
watercolor painting of the State Dining Room, the card shows a
table set for a holiday dinner and a cheery fire in a hearth below
a portrait of Abraham Lincoln. The painting is by Ray Ellis, an
artist from Martha's Vineyard, the Massachusetts island where the
Clintons have spent several summer vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Winter Wonderland theme, this year's gingerbread
house is a castle with oversized versions of presidential pets
Socks the Cat and Buddy the Dog ice-skating at both ends. Resting
on a table in the state dining room, the completely edible castle
comprises 90 pounds of gingerbread, 40 pounds of chocolate and 20
pounds of sugar icing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a challenge -- especially the round tower,'' said
Roland Mesnier, the pastry chef whose culinary creations have
become another White House tradition.
</P>
<P>
   A chocolate Santa and laden sleigh, pulled by sugary reindeer,
are preparing to leave the castle while Mrs. Claus decorates a
Christmas tree inside its walls.
</P>
<P>
   The official White House Christmas tree -- so tall that the
snowman on top is pushed forward by the 20-foot ceiling -- is the
centerpiece of the Blue Room. Its ornaments were made by artists
from all 50 states, and a handmade green velvet tree skirt has a
panel from every state and territory.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Christmas trees abound in the White House. In the
East Foyer stands a tree decorated with ornaments made by hundreds
of Peace Corps volunteers stationed in remote spots around the
globe. The library features two trees decorated with pine cones
from every region of the country. The Grand Foyer is a glistening
forest of frosted birch trees.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional White House creche is the focal point of the
East Room. Made in Naples two centuries ago, it features 47 carved
figures and has been displayed every Christmas for the past three
decades.
</P>
<P>
   The White House will feature its usual array of holiday parties,
said Mrs. Clinton, but the president and first lady will not be
able to attend some because of their trip that begins Friday to the
Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
