<HEADLINE>
`JOAN OF ARC' SOIREE A FAMILY AFFAIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; A chance to meet Jodie Foster, Isabella
Rossellini and Winona Ryder? What a way to kick off the holiday
soiree season.
</P>
<P>
   The trio were the honorary hostesses for the Directors Guild of
America screening party for the newly restored 1948 film ``Joan of
Arc.'' Guests _ and press _ lined up around a fragrant 20-foot
Christmas tree awaiting their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Rossellini was the first to arrive, wearing about a dozen ropes
of pearls around her throat and a stunning black velvet-trimmed
pantsuit by MaxMara, the Italian design company that sponsored the
party. I don't know if she'd planned it or not, but the actress had
her hair cut super short with bangs, and many remarked how much the
style made her look like her mother, Ingrid Bergman, who played
Joan of Arc.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Rossellini if she'd ever seen her mom in the film when
she was growing up, and she told me she had a vague recollection of
it when she was about 4 or 5. She said the burning-at-the-stake
scene was what she remembered _ and was frightened by _ the most.
</P>
<P>
   She also explained that her mother had a lifelong love of Joan
of Arc and had more than 120 books on her. Adding, ``I think that
she felt the same thing about acting that Joan of Arc felt about
her mission, that it was a calling, just like Joan of Arc's mission
was a calling from God. It was the same strong impulse that ruled
her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster was next in the arrivals line, also wearing pants. ``It's
by Armani,'' she said of her gray pin-striped suit, accented with
the currently trendy Gucci loafers with a silver buckle, and big
diamond studs in her ears. Her choice of designers has nothing to
do with status, however. ``Actually, I hate to shop, so, when I do,
I look for clothes that will last 20 years. And Italians are all
about classics,'' she confided.
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar-winning actress said she's also a fan of film
preservation, which is what the party was all about. ``I don't get
involved in that many things, but I'm interested in saving obscure
little movie gems to introduce them to the world. Actually not
introduce them, as much as have them available for people to
stumble upon ... like I did in college,'' she said. Asked which of
her films she considered a little movie gem, she said she worried
that ``Little Man Tate'' eventually could disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, the UCLA Film and Television Archive, the Film
Foundation and Martin Scorsese won't let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Foster was at the podium, she said ``Joan of Arc,''
was finally going to be seen the way the film was meant to be seen,
adding that Bergman was a role model for her when she was about 9
years old.
</P>
<P>
   Ryder, wearing a black sheath in that new below-the-knee length,
spoke next, but Foster didn't leave her many lines. ``I'm proud to
be here, and want to echo everything Jodie said. She's a hard act
to follow,'' Ryder commented, adding that the film presentation
honors the memory of those who made the film.
</P>
<P>
   After the film, we gathered around the tree in the guild's lobby
and dined on salmon, chicken and roast beef with a bounty of
fattening desserts, including creme brule, maple mousse and
chocolate napoleans _ all provided by the chi-chi restaurant
Patina.
</P>
<P>
   At my table was British Consul General Paul Dimond, who
commented how wonderful it was to see the film again after so many
years. He didn't seem to mind that the English were the bad guys in
the film.
</P>
<P>
   Also in attendance was MaxMara chairman Luigi Maramotti, who was
in town to celebrate the opening of his new store in Beverly Hills.
Actors there to support the film preservation cause included Kyle
MacLachlan, James Woods and Elliot Gould. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
