<SLUG> BC-SPACE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE STATION IS A RISKY VENTURE FOR NASA AND PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The international space station that is being
assembled 285 miles above Earth faces enough hazards to fill a
stack of paperback science fiction thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   Fires, explosions, solar flares, power failures and collisions
with space debris could threaten the station _ history's grandest
construction project and humanity's first stepping stone to Mars
and worlds beyond.
</P>
<P>
   The risks may seem remote this week, as the world's largest
orbiting public works project gets under way. But the risks are
real, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Goldin, the administrator of the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration, expects to face ``countless problems and
countless issues'' during station construction.
</P>
<P>
   The station, which may eventually cost as much as $100 billion,
is a collaboration of 16 nations, including the United States,
Russia, Canada, Japan and European countries. It will be used for
conducting orbital scientific experiments and learning how humans
would endure a three-year mission to Mars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any large construction project on Earth where
there hasn't been injuries or deaths,'' said Dr. Julie Swain, a
surgeon and member of the NASA Advisory Council that advises Goldin
on space issues.
</P>
<P>
   In space, ``you're doing a bigger construction project in a
horrible environment,'' said Swain, who works at the University of
Kentucky. ``I think it's common sense that something bad will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The sheer size of the space station offers more opportunity for
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   When completed in the next few years, the station will measure
356 feet by 290 feet, big enough to glow like a bright star in the
night sky. It will have as much volume as two Boeing 747s.
</P>
<P>
   On board, a rotating crew of seven astronauts will live for
months at a time. They will work, eat, and sleep amid forests of
pumps, cables, and wires, electrically powered by highway-wide
solar panels. They will study their physiological, psychological
and orthopedic reactions to space flight, generating information
useful for long-term missions to Mars and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   With repeated retrofitting, it may last decades longer than its
official 10-year life span.
</P>
<P>
   NASA advisers appear to be preparing the public emotionally for
the possibility of problems during construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough program, it is ugly, it is difficult,'' Goldin
admitted in testimony to the House Science Committee on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of the shuttle Endeavour is on a mission this week to
assemble the first two components of the station _ the Russian
Zarya (``Sunrise'') power module, which was launched Nov. 20, and
the American Unity module. Unity, which was carried into orbit on
Endeavour, is a 25,000-pound, 18-foot section that will link to
other station components.
</P>
<P>
   In deft maneuvers, the Russian and U.S. shuttle crew connected
the two components Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dangers astronauts will face when the station is
staffed:
</P>
<P>
   _ Fires. In February 1997, the crew of the aging Russian Mir
space station, including American Jerry Linenger, fought ``an
impressive, life-threatening fire. ... It was very surprising how
fast the smoke spread throughout the complex,'' Linenger wrote in
his report to NASA.
</P>
<P>
   _ Collisions between space station components during assembly. A
spaceship rammed into Mir last year, crumpling its solar panels and
causing a slow air leak.
</P>
<P>
   _ Exposure to solar radiation. Around the turn of the century,
the sun is expected to enter a period of intensified solar
activity. As a result, crew members will be bombarded with a
higher-than-usual amount of radiation, which could have adverse
medical effects, such as cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Space debris. Millions of pieces from prior space flights
litter Earth's orbit. Traveling at many miles per second, they
could punch holes in the space station, asphyxiating astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Loss of heat and electrical power. As long as the space
station points within a 15-degree plane relative to its orbit, it
will capture enough sunlight to electrify its solar panels. If it
sways out of that plane, heat and power supplies could plunge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dangerous space walks or ``extravehicular activities'' (EVAs),
lasting a total of more than 1,000 hours, during which astronauts
will assemble station components. That's more than in the entire
previous history of NASA.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent NASA Advisory Council meeting, some members
expressed concern that ``the number of estimated hours of EVA ...
was getting longer,'' recalled former council member Elisabeth
Pate-Cornell, who chairs the department of industrial engineering
and engineering management at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   ``EVAs have some risks associated with them ... (although) I
don't think these risks are very high,'' said Pate-Cornell, a
specialist in risk analysis.
</P>
<P>
   James Oberg is one of the most distinguished experts to express
concern about the risks to the station. A former NASA engineer and
space writer, he left the agency this year.
</P>
<P>
   In June, in a little-noticed article for the magazine Spectrum,
published by the Institute of Electronic and Electrical Engineers,
Oberg wrote: ``In boasting about how much the Mir experience taught
them, NASA officials unwittingly highlight the shallowness of
pre-Mir preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   And if NASA officials think Mir taught them about space station
hazards, he said, ``this could be the road to more disasters.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American and Russian space programs have endured deaths and
disasters before, including the grisly explosion of the Challenger
space shuttle over Florida in January 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Disasters struck the first space stations. In 1971, the Soviets
launched Salyut 1; its three-man crew asphyxiated on re-entry when
their space capsule lost air pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the United States launched a roomy, cylindrical
space station called Skylab. NASA intermittently housed astronauts
aboard Skylab. While unoccupied, solar activity increased, causing
Earth's upper atmosphere to rise and to exert `drag'' on Skylab.
The result: In 1979, it prematurely returned to Earth and burned up
in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old Mir has acquired a reputation as the scariest
spaceship in history because of fires, power failures,
malfunctioning computers, and a collision with another vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   During assembly of the new station, a schedule mistake might be
disastrous. As with Skylab, atmospheric drag will slowly but
constantly nudge the station back to Earth. Astronauts must visit
the station at least once each year to raise it back to its
appropriate orbit. Otherwise, it would plunge into the atmosphere,
generating history's most expensive fireworks show.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials remain optimistic that they've done everything
they could to keep space station builders and inhabitants safe.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Swain said, any historic venture entails risk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1722EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
