<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN08-COX     12-07 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: We illustrious writers with the
initials `JM'
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Old Jay Milner of Fort Worth, who grinds out a
new book every 35 years or so, has finally come out with his
long-awaited second opus, ``Confessions of a Mad Dog,'' such was
the group of writers and musicians who ran in packs in Austin
during the 1950s-70s.
</P>
<P>
   Jay and I are old friends, going back some 25 years. He even
writes about me in the book, though never quoting me fully and
accurately, which I appreciate, and instead making me seem
something I never was _ interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jay, who is now in his mid-70s, has lived out 10
lifetimes or so, such are the roles he played ...
</P>
<P>
   _ High school state football champion, Lubbock, 1939.
</P>
<P>
   _ War hero. (He taught WACs how to swim.)
</P>
<P>
   _ College gridiron star at Southern Mississippi, later drafted
in the 100th round, thereabouts, by the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Desoto new car salesman working for the first of a succession
of fathers-in-law. (Never sold the first car).
</P>
<P>
   _ Managing editor of the fabled Delta Democrat in Greenville,
Miss., fighting some of the earliest civil rights battles.
</P>
<P>
   _ Helped edit the editorial pages of the beloved New York
Herald-Tribune in the days leading to its demise.
</P>
<P>
   _ Authored a long-forgotten novel, ``Incident at Ashton,'' which
in its time was compared with ``To Kill a Mockingbird.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Taught journalism at SMU and TCU back in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Edited a country music magazine that was the focus of Willie
Nelson's first Fourth of July picnic, a fund-raiser to try and keep
the magazine alive.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hid out in Lufkin (peaceful place for people who ``can't
afford Betty Ford's sanitarium,'' says Jay) for more than 20 years
while completing his second book.
</P>
<P>
   _ Published his book, ``Confessions of a Mad Dog'' ($29.95,
University of North Texas Press), a fascinating collection of
stories despite a major flaw.
</P>
<P>
   It leaves out what I consider the best Jay Milner story of all.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that I'll relate it here and now, what you won't read
in Jay's book.
</P>
<P>
   This was in the 1970s. The story comes from the wife of author
Dan (''Semi-Tough'') Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, a writer for Sports Illustrated magazine, and his wife
were in Saudi Arabia for part of a series of articles on the best
golf courses in the world. Their plane had been met by a limo,
which immediately proceeded to a private jet that also just landed.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the private jet was a beautiful young woman,
dressed as a princess might be, and with eyes so dark that a man
might wander into them and never find his way out. She entered the
limo and said not a word to her companions.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, as the wife told it, immediately went into his act _
his one-man show for impressing pretty women, that all but involved
his juggling while riding a unicycle and recounting his resume of
success as a novelist and all-around famous personage.
</P>
<P>
   The lovely woman seemed to take no notice at all _ not until he
happened to mention he was from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're from Texas?'' she asked, excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, yes ma'am,'' Jenkins replied, his hopes soaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you're a writer?'' she exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``True enough,'' said Jenkins, smiling his best Texas writer
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know Jay Milner?!'' she gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins sunk back into the seat of the limo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never heard of him,'' he mumbled.
</P>
<P>
   How Jay ever counted an Arabian princess among his fans is
something he never fully explained to me. Here's hoping the answer
lies in a possible sequel, ``Son of Mad Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News,
</P>
<P>
   is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
