<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7070 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-1208-COX     12-07 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-1208-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    GATES: TRUSTBUSTERS SEEK TO DESTROY MICROSOFT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    740 words
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Bill Gates charged the government Monday with
seeking to ruin Microsoft Corp. in court by coming to the aid of
its business rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In a satellite press conference beamed from Microsoft's Redmond,
Wash., campus, the company's chairman and co-founder said David
Boies, the lead counsel for the Justice Department, ``made it clear
in the negotiations leading up to the case that he's really out to
destroy Microsoft. He is out to take all the work we have done and
make us look very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The claim comes the same day as news was released that one of 20
states that had joined the Justice Department in suing Microsoft
had dropped out. The suit claims abuse of the company's monopoly
power in software for personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Boies said in an interview that ``Microsoft has only itself to
blame for making the colossal error of failing to call Gates'' as
one of its 12 allotted witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bill Gates were to be put on the witness stand, the 20-hour
deposition we took in August could not have been entered into
evidence,'' Boies noted. ``And if (Gates) didn't want to testify,
they should have at least warned him that all this stuff would be
made public.''
</P>
<P>
   To Microsoft chagrin, Boies has been playing excerpts of the
Gates deposition videotape at the trial, now entering its eighth
week.
</P>
<P>
   The government has sought to portray Gates as an evasive,
forgetful and surly figure whose testimony has often proved at odds
with once-secret Microsoft documents in which he comes across as a
fierce hands-on competitor. Microsoft's lawyers brand the segments
as ``snippets,'' aimed at destroying the world's richest man.
</P>
<P>
   With the trial due to resume Tuesday, Microsoft struck back
outside the courtroom by staging a virtual Gates press conference.
</P>
<P>
   The company's high command was further buoyed when news came
that South Carolina was dropping out of the suit, leaving 19 states
joined with the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent events have proven that the Internet is a segment of
our economy where innovation is thriving,'' said Charles Condon,
the state's attorney general. ``Further government intervention or
regulation is unnecessary and, in my judgment, unwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would appear as a witness to counter the poor
impression he created on the tapes, Gates said if the government
called him ``that would be fine.'' But Microsoft's witnesses, he
went on, were chosen from the executives most familiar with the
issues raised by the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I answered truthfully every single question that was put to
me,'' Gates told reporters, noting that he receives about 10,000
e-mail messages a year and often can't recall their details. But he
conceded he might have smiled during the deposition -- had he known
the government would play the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Gates said, consumers have not complained about the
company's products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our competitors are complaining,'' he said and added: ``Who is
the government representing? A handful of competitors or consumers.
We are trying hard to compete. Success today is no guarantee of
success tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's Condon struck a similar theme in disputing that
the suit would benefit consumers, as the government contends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers have not taken a leading role in this action,'' he
said. ``That's because there are no monopolies on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Gates and Condon cited America Online Inc.'s recently
proposed $4.2 billion takeover of Netscape Communications Corp. as
proving there was plenty of competition in cyberspace. Sun
Microsystems Inc., a bitter Microsoft critic, is also a party to
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   As Gates put it: ``When you look at the AOL-Netscape deal, it's
hard to believe that the government can still press their case with
a straight face. Three of the biggest competitors are banding
together, and yet the government is still trying to slow us down.''
</P>
<P>
   In further pressing their attack, Microsoft's lawyers filed a
motion with U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who
is trying the case without a jury, for permission to examine
confidential documents from the participants and their investment
bankers on how the three-way deal was put together.
</P>
<P>
   ``This discovery (process) may also give all of us a better
understanding about what was occurring with respect to this
alliance while witnesses from these companies were on the stand in
this litigation,'' said William Neukom, the company's general
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
