A7076 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MAGOO08-COX     12-07 0398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MAGOO08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magoo's `Carol' is treat from holiday past
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a whole lot of folks of a certain age, their first exposure
to Charles Dickens' ``A Christmas Carol'' was heaped with
razzleberry dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1962, before the Grinch stole Christmas (on TV anyway)
or Charlie Brown brought back that poor, bedraggled little tree,
NBC aired ``Mr. Magoo's Christmas Carol,'' an animated one-hour
special of Charles Dickens' oft-adapted tale of Victorian
redemption. The Grinch and the Peanuts gang became holiday
perennials, but poor Quincy Magoo was banished to some back room,
unseen on TV for decades and nearly impossible to find on video.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, though, it popped up on the Disney Channel, and
tonight it's on PAX Net, a new family-values network that's
available from all metro Atlanta cable operators (if you don't have
cable, it's Channel 14). Do yourself and your family a favor and
check it out.
</P>
<P>
   The animation is almost alarmingly primitive, but that's quickly
forgotten as you're swept up in the music of Jule Styne (who also
wrote the songs to ``Gypsy'') and the lyrics of Bob Merrill (who
went on to write the lyrics to ``Funny Girl''). It was Merrill who
wrote the lines for Tiny Tim to sing about his favorite razzleberry
dressing, and Styne's music is dazzling. This is a full-fledged
Broadway-quality score grafted on to an otherwise unsophisticated
little cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   The extremely myopic Magoo (who may take some explaining to the
little ones) hasn't worn well as a comic figure, but the late Jim
Backus can get surprisingly poignant when he sings in that
fakey-creaky voice. And bet you didn't know the late Jack Cassidy
was the voice of Bob Cratchit.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Christmas Carol'' can be both joyous and scary (as anyone
who's seen the current Alliance Theatre(Ga.) production can
attest), and this one is both. Toward the end, when that Ghost of
Christmas Yet to Come waggles the bony finger sticking out of its
shroud and Scrooge quavers before his own tombstone, a whole new
generation can have the Dickens scared out of 'em. It's about time.
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Magoo's Christmas Carol''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   7 tonight E.S.T. on PAX Net .
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: ``A Christmas far more glorious than grand.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1741EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
