<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7078 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSSTAND08-COX     12-07 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSSTAND08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Time declares movie hero a metaphor
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who was the real Moses and did he really perform all those
miraculous deeds? The soon-to-be-released animated film ``The
Prince of Egypt'' inspired Time ($2.95) to re-examine the facts and
fallacies about the Old Testament hero. Writer David van Biema
concludes that archaeological and historical evidence are sketchy,
but it really doesn't matter. ``It is our nature to search for
heroes, and Moses, rebel and saint, is as relevant today as he ever
was. He is a metaphor for our times, proof that a single flawed
human being can be chosen to change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cruise control: For a time, Nicole Kidman was better known as
Mrs. Tom Cruise than as a serious actress. That is changing,
Newsweek ($2.95) reports in a cover story about Kidman's daring and
critically acclaimed role in ``The Blue Room'' on Broadway. When
they're not acting and dodging paparazzi, the Cruises climb
mountains in Nepal, scuba dive and jump out of airplanes. And what
about the marriage? ``When you're loved for your flaws, that's when
you really feel safe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unsolved mystery: Nearly two years after the death of JonBenet
Ramsey, People ($2.99) reports on the investigation and provides a
glimpse of the Ramseys' new life in Atlanta. Things apparently are
as normal as possible under the circumstances, says family friend
Linda McLean. Son Burke Ramsey, 11, plays sports and attends the
Lovett School, Patsy remains the consummate homemaker, and John is
starting a new software business. Meanwhile, as a Boulder, Colo.,
grand jury considers the evidence, some experts doubt that District
Attorney Alex Hunter would take the case to trial even if there is
an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Star-studded party: You don't have to spend thousands of
dollars to study the stars. As David DeVoss writes in the December
Smithsonian ($4), the comet Hale-Bopp was discovered by Alan Hale,
an astronomer, and Tom Bopp, a parts-supply manager. Bopp, an
amateur stargazer, proved you don't need an expensive telescope to
go down in history. On the night he discovered the comet, Bopp had
driven into the Arizona desert to look at the night sky with
friends. Since then, other star parties have sprung up around the
country, but Arizona has become the center of ``astronomical
tourism'' because of the dark nights and high elevation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: According to U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95),
office romances are alive and well, despite the best efforts of
corporations to stifle love in the workplace. And one of the most
hazardous events at work is the office Christmas party. Experts
recommend setting a tone of moderation and omitting the mistletoe.
. . . Newt Gingrich probably didn't foresee stepping down as
speaker of the House when he gave some travel pointers to Men's
Health ($2.95), but they are still viable. In ``How Not to Be
Left,'' Gingrich advises travelers to pack conservatively, check
the performance record of your airline and make your own call to
the airline's 800 number if you're bumped from a flight. . . .
Business to Business ($3.50) is the first magazine to feature
Georgia's Gov.-elect Roy Barnes on its cover. In the article,
Barnes discusses some of the issues he plans to address (health
care, tax cuts) and includes some humorous advice from Zell Miller.
One example: ``You can't govern effectively if you tap dance.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Publishing note: Art &AMP; Antiques ($4.95) is moving its
editorial staff from New York to Atlanta by the first of the year,
according to Monte Plott, vice president and editorial director.
The new editor in chief is Barbara Tapp, formerly editor of Atlanta
Homes and Lifestyles. ``We're broadening the scope of the magazine
to cover lifestyle aspects of arts and antiques as well as the
objects themselves,'' Plott says. The April issue will reflect the
changes. The magazine's offices will be at 2100 Powers Ferry Road.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
