<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-07 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE AND OUTSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Outside the White House, life is neither festive
nor traditional as the House of Representatives lurches erratically
toward impeachment and the unseasonal hot weather produces furry
buds on the tulip magnolias outside First Lady Hillary Clinton's
office window.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the White House, 'tis nonetheless the season to be jolly
in a lavishly decorated winter wonderland enveloping the
president's house in fir boughs and wreaths, frosted magnolia
leaves and birch trees, gilded pine cones, glittering gold and
silver ornaments, and delicate, edible confections depicting
elaborate Christmas scenes.
</P>
<P>
   This year the great mansion gleams with 344 wreaths, 18
decorated Christmas trees, 2,700 lights on the central Blue Room
tree, 843 fancy bows and countless handcrafted ornaments. Plus a
chandelier dripping with gilded holly, golden swags, silver
icicles, golden garlands and silvery bows. And similarly draped
grapevine angels tootling their horns before each of the East
Room's four mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   This is a wow. It is the most elegantly dressed-up Christmas
White House in my memory, although the decorations there are always
spectacular. You cannot try to duplicate them at home.
</P>
<P>
   This year's display is pure fantasy in every sense. The
atmosphere is magical and serene.
</P>
<P>
   On the public floors of the White House, outside reality dare
not intrude. The holiday social cocoon is impenetrable.
</P>
<P>
   What life is like in the off-limits upstairs family quarters or
in the his-and-hers offices is strictly private. We cannot know
about that. The Clintons are practiced at compartmentalizing. They
never let their opponents see them cry.
</P>
<P>
   Composed and smiling, the first lady showed reporters the
cheerful seasonal transformation Monday, revealing nothing more
serious than a minor struggle to keep their dog Buddy away from the
tempting gingerbread castle in the State Dining Room. Blandly, she
said she hoped the White House parties and special events would be
``as beautiful and welcoming and hospitable as they always have
been.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening the Clintons were hosting their annual Christmas
party for Congress, a bipartisan affair that included some
Republicans panting to impeach the president. The parties for other
groups and even the press will also go on as usual.
</P>
<P>
   She had barely finished her tour when her husband's press
secretary, Joe Lockhart, began in a nearby undecorated room to
explain to other reporters how President Clinton's lawyers intended
to defend him before the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   This could well be the most dangerous period of the Clinton
presidency, with only a few days left of final impeachment
arguments before a committee vote the end of the week. It is not
inconceivable _ although not likely _ that this could be their last
Christmas as occupants of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is the symbolic burden of the president and his wife to
carry on in public as though all is well, no matter how trying the
moment, how ominous the future. Only in this way does the republic,
and the White House, endure. We cannot be strong if our presidents
are weak.
</P>
<P>
   That the Clintons are so skilled at keeping what the British
call a stiff upper lip is one of the reasons the public still gives
them both high marks for performance and does not want to see him
kicked out of office.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes. At last year's Christmas
celebration, Clinton was as strong and popular politically as he
had ever been. The Paula Jones suit was chaotic and stalled,
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr had been unable to produce an
indictment in the Whitewater probe that reached into the White
House, and Clinton had pulled off a widely hailed balanced budget
deal in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   He could not run again, which made him a lame duck vulnerable to
defiance from various political rivals. But he seemed comfortably
positioned to maximize the remaining three years of his second term
in productive ways.
</P>
<P>
   We learned of Monica Lewinsky the following month. And that was
that for the year 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is not the only president forced to soldier on
through the Christmas holidays with a smiling face and heavy heart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, President and Mrs. George Bush celebrated with outward
normalcy, although between their joyful holiday rounds the
president was weighing whether to go to war. One month later, on
Jan. 16, he opted to attack Iraq's Saddam Hussein for invading
Kuwait, mounting a risky military confrontation that had won Senate
approval by only five votes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as now, the mood in Washington beyond the White House was
one of tension, partisan suspicion and a mounting sense that the
president was a flawed link in the majestic sweep of history.
</P>
<P>
   History, however, takes care of itself. In the meantime, a
temporary holiday spirit of peace and good will is a good thing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
