<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Dec. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday afternoon, temperatures soared to 71 degrees at the
International Jetport in Portland, Maine, marking the first time
readings have reached 70 degrees in December since records at
Portland began in 1940. Farther south, the mercury climbed to 75
and 76 degrees at New York City and Boston, respectively, with each
reading breaking the all-time record high for December.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, high temperatures along the northeast seaboard will
be 25 to 35 degrees lower than Monday's record warmth in the wake
of a relatively bland cold front for December which will manage to
lower readings only to seasonal levels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, broken areas of rain will develop over the northern
middle Atlantic and southern New England seaboards as an area of
low pressure ripples northeast along the stalling cold front. A
stripe of light snow is possible on the northern fringe of the rain
over the hills of southern and central Vermont and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The bastion of unseasonable warmth over the East in the past
several days will be confined to the southeast seaboard as balmy
winds from the southwest build ahead of the slow southern flank of
the cold front moving across the eastern states. Showers and a few
thunderstorms will escort the cold front across Alabama and
Tennessee into Georgia and the Carolina mountains. Meanwhile,
southern and central Florida will be sunny and warm.
</P>
<P>
   Just west of the front, clouds and a few broken areas of chilly
rain will affect parts of the region from the central Gulf states
to the Tennessee and lower Ohio valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Desert Snow
</P>
<P>
   An inch of snow fell at McCarran International Airport in Las
Vegas early Sunday. Snowfall of an inch or more is rare in the
desert city, occurring, on average, about once every four years and
usually in January. Indeed, Sunday's snowfall marked only the
second December snowfall of an inch or more in Las Vegas since
records began in 1937. To add to the surreal setting on Sunday, a
peal of thunder was reported around the time snow began to fall. A
pocket of cold air at 18,000 feet, with temperatures as low as
minus 27 degrees Fahrenheit, sparked the thundery desert snow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7107 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CRAIG     12-07 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CRAIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON TURNS TO OLD LAW SCHOOL FRIEND TO QUARTERBACK HIS
IMPEACHMENT DEFENSE
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Greg Craig is known around the White House as
``QB'' _ the ``quarterback'' of President Clinton's final campaign
to avoid impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And when the White House begins its two-day defense of the
president Tuesday, Craig will lead the Clinton team onto the
treacherous field of the GOP-dominated House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Although he has spent the last quarter century becoming one of
Washington's blue-chip lawyers, Craig is the least known of those
attorneys who have represented Clinton on his six-year slide to the
edge of presidential history.
</P>
<P>
   While he may lack the marquee power of Bill Bennett or David
Kendall or the institutional gravatus of Charles Ruff, Craig is
uniquely qualified to defend Clinton. His experience is a potent
mix of the legal and the political. Confrontational by nature, he
has as much appreciation for a finely-honed public relations
campaign as for a ground-breaking legal argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of expertise and a lot of wisdom,'' said Mike
McCurry, the former Clinton White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Craig has been a chum of Clinton's since they were
classmates at Yale Law School. And when the president most needed a
friend _ the day after the lurid details of his affair with a
former White House intern became public _ Clinton turned to Craig.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in great pain,'' Craig recently told The Washington
Post as he recalled the two hours he spent with Clinton on the
balcony overlooking the South Lawn of the White House. It was the
evening of Sept. 10, the day after independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's report to Congress had been published on the World Wide
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, Craig agreed to leave his influential
position at the State Department to quarterback the White House
strategy to keep Clinton in office. He did so without much
enthusiasm, he confided to friends _ as well as to the president
himself.
</P>
<P>
   But like so many others who have known Clinton throughout his
life, Craig ultimately answered his friend's call for help.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, a boyishly handsome 53 years old with tousled grey hair,
is no stranger to politically-charged legal proceedings. He safely
guided Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., through the hazards of the
rape trial of his nephew, William Kennedy Smith, in Palm Beach in
1991. He also worked on the defense team of John Hinkley Jr., who
was acquitted by reason of insanity in the attempted assassination
of President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Craig was born at the Navy hospital in Norfolk, Va., where his
father, William Craig, was an officer during World War II. He grew
up in Palo Alto, Calif., near Stanford University where his father
was dean of men.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Craig was drawn to the civil rights movement. In
the mid-1960s, he registered black voters in Mississippi and later
tutored kids in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   It was Craig, not Clinton, who actually first gained national
attention for his activities at Harvard and Yale in opposition to
the Vietnam War. He was one of three antiwar activists at Yale who
were befriended by Hillary Rodham, the future first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his opposition to the Vietnam War, Craig ultimately
submitted himself to the military draft, but avoided service due to
a damaged shoulder _ the result of a prep school lacrosse injury.
</P>
<P>
   After law school, Craig joined the prestigious Washington law
firm of Williams &AMP; Connolly and was, at one point, the protege of
the late Edward Bennett Williams, a Washington legend.
</P>
<P>
   Craig has left the firm three times: first, to follow his wife
back to Yale for her graduate degree in art; second, to become a
foreign policy adviser to Kennedy; and finally, to become the
director of policy planning in the Clinton State Department, the
position he left to quarterback Clinton's impeachment defense.
</P>
<P>
   Craig and his wife, graphic designer Derry Craig, have five
children.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
