<HEADER>
A7143 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-960     12-07 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPACE-STATION-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULTIMATE HIGH-BEAM JOB SITE: 240 MILES UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(lb) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their hard hats are helmets, their safety goggles are
gold-coated visors and their boots are made of bulletproof fibers
instead of leather, but they are nonetheless construction workers
doing high-beam work.
</P>
<P>
   Far above Earth, test pilots, engineers and scientists have
begun practicing the building trades as they tackle the mammoth job
of assembling a space station at a truly remote site.
</P>
<P>
   The space shuttle Endeavour, launched on Friday with a crew of
six, began one of the most challenging construction jobs in history
on Sunday when it joined the first two pieces of the station
together while orbiting 240 miles above Earth.
</P>
<P>
   To complete the mating of the Russian-built Zarya module and the
American-made Unity connecting node, the National Aeronautics and
Space Administration assigned a team of astronauts to conduct three
space walks about the modules, joining electrical cables, removing
covers, bolting on handles, attaching safety lines and taking on
scores of other tasks.
</P>
<P>
   This begins a series of space walks over the next five years by
American and Russian astronauts that will test their endurance and
skills as they slowly bolt, screw, wire and snap together the 100
major components of what will become the largest object ever placed
in space.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts are training to make at least 162 planned space walks
during this period to assemble the station, and additional ventures
outside the outpost undoubtedly will be needed for unscheduled
maintenance or repairs. Experts say the expected 1,700 hours of
EVAs, for extravehicular activity, as NASA terms space walks, will
more than double the time people have spent outside spaceships
since human flights began 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the EVA wall,'' said Greg Harbaugh, manager of the
EVA Project Office at the Johnson Space Center in Houston. ``It is
a daunting task, but we are prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh said that many of NASA's 130 astronauts had general
training for space walks and that 20 to 25 were now practicing for
specific walks. The few hours a crew spends space walking on a
specific mission often require hundreds of hours of training on the
ground to make sure the job is done correctly and safely, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Bleisath, the NASA official in charge of space walks for
the current mission, said three astronauts had received a total of
540 hours of EVA training to hook up the Russian and American
modules in three space walks of six to seven hours each.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Jerry Ross of the Air Force and Dr. James Newman, a
physicist, received the bulk of the training as the primary space
walkers, but Maj. Frederick Sturckow of the Marine Corps also
practiced as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   This training included 240 hours in NASA's Neutral Buoyancy
Laboratory, a huge, 40-foot-deep pool in Houston where fully-suited
astronauts train under water with full-size replicas of
space-station components. Such submerged rehearsals are the closest
representations of working in the weightlessness of space available
on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Both the international space station and earlier American
designs have been criticized for requiring too many space walks to
build and maintain. Critics said so many space walks not only
increased risks to crews, but would also divert so much time that
scientific work aboard the station would be compromised.
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh acknowledged that the planned number of space walks
remained high, but said NASA had been firm about preventing more
from being added to the schedule. ``We have told contractors,
program people, everyone involved _ `No more growth in EVAs' _ and
we are serious about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   People are concerned about space walks because they are
physically difficult and inherently dangerous. Working in the
vacuum of space, an astronaut could be killed instantly if struck
by a piece of space debris or if he or she tears a pressurized suit
on a sharp metal part. There is also the danger of an astronaut's
floating away because of a broken tether line and dying if his air
is depleted before a ship can get to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it, building the space station is a big
construction project, and people get killed in construction
accidents all the time,'' said John Pike, director of space policy
for the Federation of American Scientists in Washington. ``I'd
frankly be surprised if we didn't lose an astronaut while building
the station.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials acknowledge the dangers, but say they can be
mitigated. ``No EVA is a walk in the park,'' Harbaugh said. ``It is
always a challenge. It is always somewhat hazardous duty, although
we can control the hazards.''
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately designed space walks, proper training and
attention to detail reduce risks, he said. For instance, starting
with the current mission, space-walking astronauts will routinely
wear a new backpack unit called Safer, for Simplified Aid for EVA
Rescue. This pack, propelled by jets of gas, acts as a space life
jacket or parachute by allowing a crew member who becomes
untethered to fly back to the station.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has also designed a new spacesuit for the station, one that
can be stored in orbit and used up to 25 times before having to be
returned to Earth for refurbishment. The current space-shuttle suit
must be inspected and serviced between flights by specialists on
the ground, but the enhanced station suit is designed to be cleaned
and serviced by regular astronauts serving on the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The new suit will also include other improvements, including
easily replaceable internal parts, a new radio that allows up to
five people to talk at once, gloves that allow more dexterity, new
helmet-mounted floodlights and spotlights and fingertip heaters for
more comfort when work is being done outside direct sunlight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To help prepare for the new era in space walking, NASA in 1991
started including practice space walks on shuttle missions to test
new equipment and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   On more than a dozen such walks, astronauts tested wrenches,
clamps, power tools, foot restraints, tool carts and other devices
that would apply to space-station construction and maintenance.
This included a remote-controlled, beach-ball-size free-floating
television camera propelled by gas jets that could survey
hard-to-reach areas of the station and possibly reduce the need for
some space walks.
</P>
<P>
   On the current flight, the Endeavour is carrying 135 tools
ranging from special torqueless power drills and liquid-filled
hammers that reduce recoil and vibration when striking something,
to standard wrenches and crowbars. At the end of the mission, the
space walkers will leave a large tool bag filled with some of these
items attached to the side of the Unity module for future workers
to use.
</P>
<P>
   The number of space walks associated with the space station
should steadily increase beginning next year and peak in the years
2000 and 2001, when many major components arrive to be attached,
officials said. The station is to begin permanent staffing in
January or February 2000, after the arrival next summer of the
much-delayed Russian service module, which contains living quarters
and laboratory space, and attachment of a large American solar
power array.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Russia currently have incompatible systems
for refurbishing spacesuits between walks. As a result, all
American space walks around the station will be shuttle-based until
the arrival in July 2000 of the Joint Airlock Module, which will be
equipped for both kinds of spacesuits. Before then, the only space
walks directly from the station would be from the service module
using Russian Orlan-M spacesuits.
</P>
<P>
   The joint airlock will be large enough for crews to stay
overnight at a lower atmospheric pressure than the rest of the
station so that astronauts can purge their bodies of nitrogen. This
will prevent decompression sickness, or ``the bends,'' when they go
to the even lower-pressure pure oxygen atmosphere of a spacesuit
and return to the station.
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh said station-based crews would be able to make routine
maintenance space walks, but heavy construction would remain the
duty of specially trained shuttle crews during work-packed 10- to
12-day visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a symbiotic relationship,'' he said. ``We will rely on
shuttle crews for the heavy lifting and station crews for cleanup
and maintenance sort of things. Remember, station crews are really
there for science.''
</P>
</TEXT>
