<SLUG> BC-PETER-FONDA-IN-THE-TEMPEST-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER FONDA: AN EASY RIDER TACKLES SHAKESPEARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Peter Fonda in a scene from ``The
Tempest.'' 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's the day before Thanksgiving and Peter Fonda is most
thankful.
 &HT;    The last year or so was one of his best. His book ``Don't Tell
Dad'' very publicly cleared the air on his relationship with his
father, the late actor Henry Fonda, while his Oscar-nominated turn
in ``Ulee's Gold'' (1997) rescued him from a long run of B movies
and big-budget turkeys.
 &HT;    Speaking by telephone from his Montana ranch, Fonda revels in
his renaissance, oozing charm in his trademark acid-trippy, folksy
way that mingles deep thoughts with a 1960s vocabulary that
includes plenty of ``cools'' and ``neats.''
 &HT;    He's particularly eager to talk about ``The Tempest,'' an
ambitious retelling of Shakespeare's final play that airs Dec. 13
on NBC. Fonda stars as Gideon Prosper, a wizard who lives happily
in the Mississippi swamps with his daughter, Miranda (Katherine
Heigl) and a freed slave named Ariel (Harold Perrineau),
indifferent to the Civil War and the machinations of Prosper's
deadly brother, Anthony (John Glover), both of which threaten their
idyllic existence.
 &HT;    ``I hadn't expected to do TV this year, and I ended up doing
both `The Tempest' and `The Passion of Ayn Rand' with Helen
Mirren,'' says Fonda, who will turn 60 in February. ``Who wants to
give up the chance to work with Helen Mirren? Or give up the chance
to play Prospero?
 &HT;    ``I mean, selfishly, how many times am I going to be asked to
play a sorcerer?'' the actor says, laughing. ```The Tempest' was
very autobiographical, so I also got to look at my own
autobiographical sense and was able to apply it to the work: Had I,
for example, protected my daughter Bridget in such a way that she
was blinded by reality?
 &HT;    ``I hadn't, of course, but I was able to understand the
process.''
 &HT;    Fonda came to ``The Tempest'' familiar with the material. He'd
seen several stage productions, as well as John Cassavetes'
``far-out'' 1982 film version and even ``Forbidden Planet,'' the
1956 sci-fi classic with Walter Pidgeon that loosely adapted the
play.
 &HT;    What makes ``The Tempest'' so ripe for diverse interpretations,
Fonda suggests, is that it offers us a chance to see ourselves in a
disguise, to look in a mirror without even realizing it.
 &HT;    ``That allows us to see the action and get caught up in the
emotions,'' he says. ``I'm personally fascinated by `The Tempest'
because it was Shakespeare's last play. It's called a comedy, but
it's actually a fantasy with some comedic stuff.
 &HT;    ``It's got a lot of melodrama and action, but it's really about
discovering your presence,'' the actor says. ``Shakespeare used the
stubbornness of Prospero to show how this man avoids the real
world, how he's invented all this stuff to scare away people, how
he keeps his daughter blind to society in a desire to protect her
from what he perceives as the world's injustice.
 &HT;    ``And again, I got to be this sorcerer who creates storms and
uses magic,'' he says, laughing. ``I got to live in this neat
treehouse in the bayou. When you see this treehouse, you'll want
one, too.''
 &HT;    Fair enough, but adaptations of classic drama are dangerous
creatures. Hollywood legends from James Cagney and Marlon Brando to
Mel Gibson and Leonardo DiCaprio have caught some slings and arrows
for daring to trifle with the Bard.
 &HT;    ``I'm sure some people will have their daggers out,'' Fonda
concedes, ``but I think the people out there who decide to watch
our version of `The Tempest' are looking for a different kind of
entertainment.
 &HT;    ``We've got an interesting story that's based on Shakespeare,''
he says. ``If nothing else, that lends us credibility. And I'm very
comfortable with my work. I played almost every scene at the level
I wanted to play them, and I loved doing it.''
 &HT;    The path to ``The Tempest'' was paved by ``Ulee's Gold,'' the
warm, simple story about a quiet beekeeper faced with a family
crisis that won widespread critical acclaim and earned Fonda a 1997
Oscar nomination for Best Actor.
 &HT;    ``It changed things tremendously,'' the actor says. ``I was
thrilled with the reception I got from `Ulee's.'
 &HT;    ``Actually, I was thrilled while making it,'' he adds. ``Listen,
it's a wonderful thing to want a project, to get it, to be excited
while making it and then, every time you see it, to feel, `God
damn, that's f--king great!' I don't mean my performance, but the
whole film.
 &HT;    ``The whole thing was a beautiful, wonderful experience,'' he
concludes. ``It was a cool year. `Ulee's' kicked off a lot of stuff
for me.''
 &HT;    The other tentpole of his year was ``Don't Tell Dad,'' in which
Fonda candidly addressed his childhood, the pros and cons of having
a famous father and sister _ actress Jane Fonda _ and the
emotion-charged days before the elder Fonda's death.
 &HT;    ``Jane was absolutely blown away by it, and my wife loved it
too,'' the actor says. ``Of course, the best, most important
reviews were those of my family.''
 &HT;    Many readers saw their own family lives reflected in the famous
acting clan, Fonda adds.
 &HT;    ``I get a lot of letters,'' he says, ``and people have been
wonderful in their responses. They tell me what it meant to them,
how it was nice to see that such very different people could share
the same types of experiences.''
 &HT;    Then there's the cable movie ``The Passion of Ayn Rand,'' set to
air in 1999 on Showtime. Helen Mirren stars as the famous
novelist/philosopher, whose affair with a young protege (Eric
Stoltz) wreaks havoc on her husband, Frank O'Connor (Fonda), and on
the protege's girlfriend (Julie Delpy).
 &HT;    It's definitely a supporting part, Fonda says, but he relished
the chance to work with Mirren.
 &HT;    ``It's not called `The Passion of Frank O'Connor' for a
reason,'' he says, laughing. ``But I found my place in the story,
and working with Helen was as good an experience as I'd hoped.''
 &HT;    Next up is ``The Limey,'' a feature directed by Steven
Soderbergh in which Fonda plays a music-industry figure who
accidentally kills his girlfriend.
 &HT;    ``My role was written for me!'' Fonda says, practically
shouting. ``Five years ago I was having dinner with Bridget and
some of her friends. One of her dear friends is married to a writer
and he said, `I'm going to write a role for you in this movie.'
 &HT;    ``I said, `That's cool. I hope it happens.' And here it is. And
it happens to be with Steven Soderbergh, which is really neat.''
 &HT;    As the conversation ends, Fonda waxes enthusiastic about
Thanksgiving, which he'll share with his wife Becky and their
children. Bridget won't be there, he adds, because she's still
unpacking boxes at her new home in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    The actor doesn't know for sure what he'll do next, but he
doesn't seem concerned.
 &HT;    ``Life is grand,'' he says, slipping back into his 1960s patois.
``In terms of the reality of the world, peace is still a good idea
and we're sure not near it.
 &HT;    ``Then, on the other side of my head, I can hear Bobby Dylan's
words: `Life is sad, life is a bust. You do what you do, you do
what you must. You do what you must do and you do it well.'
 &HT;    ``That's a pretty good statement.''
 c.1998 Ian Spelling  
