<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7158 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRIDGET-FONDA-IN-A-SI     12-07 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDGET-FONDA-IN-A-SIMPLE-PLAN-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGET FONDA'S NOT-SO-SIMPLE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Bridget Fonda with Bill Paxton and Billy
Bob Thornton in a scene from ``A Simple Plan.'' 
 By JEANNE WOLF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Being naked on screen is nothing new for Bridget Fonda.
 &HT;    ``I'm naturally uninhibited about that,'' she admits, laughing.
 &HT;    But ``A Simple Plan,'' opening Dec. 18, offers her first
pregnant nude scene.
 &HT;    ``It was strange,'' she says. ``I had a robe on, and when it
falls open you can see all of me _ but what you are really seeing
is about 40 pounds of silicone.''
 &HT;    In Sam Raimi's thriller, based on Scott Smith's 1993 novel,
Fonda is very much with child, but it took a lot of work to
transform her sleek body to fit the role.
 &HT;    ``They created this enormous fake stomach for me,'' she recalls.
``It was so real that when I stood in front of a mirror I could
really imagine how I'll look when I'm pregnant.
 &HT;    ``Then they gave me a suit full of lead weights,'' she adds with
a rueful smile. ``I didn't have morning sickness, but that pregnant
suit was a real pain in the back.''
 &HT;    In ``A Simple Plan,'' Fonda plays the wife of a small-town man
(Bill Paxton) who, with his brother (Billy Bob Thornton), finds a
downed airplane containing $4 million in cash. Should they turn it
in, or should they keep the money and fulfill their fantasies?
 &HT;    Fonda's character at first wants to call the police, but soon
reconsiders.
 &HT;    ``I think it could change anybody,'' the actress says. ``It's
not so much the money as the possibilities you see of realizing
your dreams. It's like all the hopes and plans you had as a kid,
when you'd put a few dollars in a shoe box and shove it under the
bed, can now come true.
 &HT;    ``We can all make moral judgments,'' she says, ``but that kind
of money presents an enormous temptation. I don't think you can
really know what you'd do until you're actually confronted with
it.''
 &HT;    Unless, of course, you have the financial rewards of Hollywood
stardom, a point which Fonda grants.
 &HT;    ``I've been fortunate, but what's been important to me is that I
have a career which is also my hobby and my passion,'' she says
with sudden intensity. ``I lucked out because I get to do something
that I love doing. A lot of people don't have that luxury.''
 &HT;    Fonda's success seems almost predestined. After all, she's the
daughter of Academy Award-nominated actor/director Peter Fonda, the
niece of Academy Award-winning actress Jane Fonda and the
granddaughter of legendary _ and, yes, Academy Award-winning _
actor Henry Fonda.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, she says, she didn't get the acting bug until she
appeared in a high-school production of ``Harvey.''
 &HT;    ``Go figure,'' she says. ``I played Nurse Harvey, and I was
awful, really terrible. But one day I threw out a line in a
rehearsal and the people who were building the sets actually
chuckled. I felt a connection _ it felt so good that they were
laughing at my line. That was the beginning of my addiction to
acting.''
 &HT;    That's acting. Stardom is another thing entirely.
 &HT;    ``Growing up, I remember being struck by the fact that everybody
seemed to know my father,'' she recalls. ``I was shy, and it was a
bit of an embarrassment to me. I kind of hid from it, even though I
could see that my father loved it. It made the world seem really
small for me.''
 &HT;    So committed is Fonda to her penchant for privacy that, when she
recently broke up with her longtime companion, actor Eric Stoltz,
the two managed to keep the split out of the tabloids for weeks.
 &HT;    ``We hadn't been together for a while,'' she says. ``But it just
got to the point where you knew you were going to be asked and you
might as well admit it. Ironically, we sort of felt we had to go
public because we had been so open about being together.
 &HT;    ``Now I'm learning how to keep my life my own,'' Fonda adds. ``I
guess the conflict came because my father was always so open with
the press. I felt like that was part of the deal of being a star.
Now I think my love life is nobody's business.''
 &HT;    So as far as her current situation ...
 &HT;    Fonda laughs.
 &HT;    ``Why do we care about romance among celebrities? I guess it's
like wanting to know who a friend is dating,'' the actress says.
``Anyway, I'm not with someone at the moment.''
 &HT;    It's something she's been thinking about, the 34-year-old
actress admits, in part because of ``A Simple Plan.''
 &HT;    ``It sort of cemented the fact that I wouldn't mind having my
own kids,'' she says. ``I want to be married, and I want to have a
family. But I'm not at the point where I'm desperate about it.''
 &HT;    In the meantime, she's keeping very busy on screen. She played
an abused wife in ``The Break-Up'' (1997) and a drugged-out surfer
chick in Quentin Tarantino's ``Jackie Brown'' (1997), and will next
be seen as a Marilyn Monroe impersonator opposite Harvey Keitel in
``Finding Graceland.''
 &HT;    ``Impersonating Marilyn was a lot of fun,'' Fonda says, smiling.
``I've always loved her and felt a lot of sympathy for her _
sympathy not in terms of feeling sorry, but empathy for what she
projected.
 &HT;    ``Some people thought she was a bimbo, I guess, but she had this
tremendous life force _ the studio people used to call it flesh
impact. There was something about her that was just alive. And
there was a sense that she was just burning up all her fuel, as if
she wasn't destined to live a long life.''
 &HT;    The role was another exercise in body sculpting, she admits,
almost as extensive as that in ``A Simple Plan.''
 &HT;    ``I was a special effect,'' she says with a laugh. ``I was
sculpted, molded and reformed. I wore a hot-pink dress, the one
that was Marilyn's trademark, and the upper half was definitely a
work of breast enhancement.
 &HT;    ``Unfortunately, my hips and butt couldn't be padded enough,
because I have to dance,'' she said. ``So below the waist I'm not
as curvy as I would have liked to have been.''
 &HT;    Fonda herself has no indelible onscreen image a la Monroe,
despite a career that has produced several memorable films,
including a sexy cameo in ``The Godfather III'' (1990) and roles as
a victim of the roommate from hell in ``Single White Female''
(1992) and a seductive killing machine in ``Point of No Return''
(1993).
 &HT;    ``I don't know what people are looking for when they go to see
one of my films,'' she says, brushing back her long hair. ``Is it
that they like to see me with a gun or see me terrorized by my
roommate? I don't know.
 &HT;    ``The only thing I hope I deliver is an emotional reality,
whether I'm in a comedy or a drama,'' she says. ``That's what I
expect from myself, and maybe that's what audiences are paying to
see.''
 &HT;    In a number of her films, she concedes, audiences have seen
quite a bit.
 &HT;    ``I don't take the nudity thing personally,'' Fonda says. ``I
guess there are very few ingenues that people wouldn't want to see
without their clothes. I've never felt particularly vulnerable as a
sexpot. As I said, I'm pretty uninhibited.''
 &HT;    She pauses.
 &HT;    ``But I've started to realize that it can affect people's
perception of me,'' she adds after a moment. ``Some people find it
distasteful. It can get really bad for an actress if the audience
thinks you're selling your body for entertainment. I'm careful
about my love scenes. I can feel when it's not right. And if it's
not right, I just don't do it.''
 c.1998 Pentacom Productions  
<TEXT>
