<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JERI-RYAN-IN-STAR-TRE     12-07 1453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERI-RYAN-IN-STAR-TREK-VOYAGER-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYBODY'S FAVORITE BORG 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Jeri Ryan in a scene from ``Star Trek:
Voyager.'' 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It's 4 a.m. in Las Vegas, and Jeri Ryan is seeing double.
 &HT;    The most talked-about star of ``Star Trek: Voyager'' is sitting
in a red booth, distinctly non-Borgian in jeans and a T-shirt.
She's eating a hamburger and fries, for heaven's sake. With catsup.
 &HT;    And then a guy comes up to her, gesturing toward a place where
no man has gone before. The ladies' room, that is.
 &HT;    ``I'm sorry to bother you,'' he says, ``but my wife is in the
john getting dressed as you.''
 &HT;    Ryan lowers her burger and thinks that one over.
 &HT;    ``Getting dressed like me,'' she repeats slowly. ``OK. And thank
you for being such big fans.'''
 &HT;    And sure enough, soon a second Jeri Ryan emerges, this time
costumed as ``Voyager's'' Seven of Nine.
 &HT;    This doesn't happen to Jenna Elfman or Calista Flockhart.
 &HT;    ``My life is so very strange,'' Ryan says.
 &HT;    Also very changeable. Only a few years ago, she was an
out-of-work actress with a husband and young son. Now she is a
``Trek'' phenomenon with a 4-year-old and a recent split from Jack
Ryan, the Chicago-based investment banker who had been her partner
in a commuter marriage since ``Voyager'' called.
 &HT;    Being America's favorite Borg has wide-ranging implications.
Even taking young Alex to preschool can be complicated.
 &HT;    ``It doesn't really occur to me how many kids watch the show,''
Ryan says. ``I go to school and the kids scream, `Oh, you're the
Borg mom! Where is your starship?' I have to sit all the kids down
and say, ``OK, now we know it's all pretend.'''
 &HT;    At 30, Ryan doesn't look like a mom. Seven of Nine's navy-blue,
Spandex uniform leaves little to the imagination, but the actress
says she's never been a fitness freak.
 &HT;    ``I've only recently started working out with any regularity,''
she admits. ``It's because I just turned 30 and I know things will
start moving and shifting.''
 &HT;    She'd rather exercise than diet, anyway. Ryan reveals that
cheesecake is a personal favorite. And barbecued ribs.
 &HT;    ``Anything from McDonalds and most things from Taco Bell are on
my list of snacks,'' she adds, sighing. ``Oh, I love bad food. I
have a soft spot in my heart for junk.''
 &HT;    Ryan never relocated completely to Los Angeles because of her
husband's job requirements. Now that will probably change.
 &HT;    ``I didn't really realize how exhausting it was until I started
getting a little break from the traveling,'' she says. ``Now I
realize, `My God, I must have been on autopilot for seven years.'
It wipes you out. Your exhaustion sort of sneaks up on you.''
 &HT;    Sort of like ``Star Trek,'' which Ryan never watched growing up.
 &HT;    ``I watched `The Brady Bunch' as a girl, which was in direct
competition with `Star Trek,''' she says. ``I used to call `Star
Trek' a boy's show.''
 &HT;    Two years ago, when her NBC series ``Dark Skies'' hit the skids,
she heard that ``Voyager'' was looking for a young actress to play
a non-human Borg who takes on human characteristics. Ryan went on
an audition as a lark.
 &HT;    To her amazement, she got the part. She and her husband were
equally taken aback.
 &HT;    ``His reaction was `Oh boy,''' she recalls. ``We weren't really
sure what we were getting into. My husband had the same fears I had
about the role _ we were both apprehensive.''
 &HT;    In two words, their concern was ``Star Trek,'' a franchise with
a life of its own.
 &HT;    ```Star Trek' has been around for 30 years,'' the actress says,
``so you don't have to worry that the show will be canceled on you.
But when you sign that contract you better know exactly what you're
doing, because you know you'll be there for the duration of the
contract.
 &HT;    ``You are almost making a commitment for life,'' Ryan says. ``I
do have to say it's been great fun. The way this character has been
written has really exceeded my hopes and my best expectations.''
 &HT;    As soon as Seven of Nine was introduced, rumors began flying of
personality conflicts between Ryan and series star Kate Mulgrew,
who plays Capt. Janeway.
 &HT;    ``We get along just fine,'' Ryan says firmly. ``We're friendly
with each other. I don't know where rumors started that we didn't
get along.''
 &HT;    Actually, Ryan says, her biggest problems on set have involved
her intricate Borg makeup, which includes a latex-foam face piece.
 &HT;    ``It's glued on for every episode,'' she says. ``It's not bad,
but it's annoying to have something glued to your face all day.
Later it's removed with alcohol, and then they have to remove the
residual glue with an oil. Then you wash your face.''
 &HT;    She also wears a Borg skeleton glove on her fingers.
 &HT;    ``The hand, for the most part, is OK,'' she says, ``unless
you're trying to eat, which is a real pain in the neck when your
fingertips are covered in latex.''
 &HT;    But it's worth it, Ryan says, for the chance to play this
character.
 &HT;    ``It's a terrific role,'' she says. ``I love the constant
discoveries this character makes. I love the challenge of playing a
character who has emotions but doesn't know how to express them
because she hasn't experienced them before. She's someone to whom
everything is new _ yet she is so wise and so smart and so
strong.''
 &HT;    There are rumors that Seven of Nine will get a romance this
season, but Ryan downplays them.
 &HT;    ``That's premature for her, because she's only been human
essentially for a year,'' the actress says. ``She's still almost a
child emotionally. Last season, we toyed with a little crush that
someone had on Seven. He couldn't handle it. Also, she doesn't
really have any concept of sexuality.''
 &HT;    All in all, it's a long way from home for a self-described army
brat who, by age 11, had lived in Germany, Kansas, Maryland,
Hawaii, Georgia and Texas.
 &HT;    During her years as a Northwestern University drama major, she
met Jack and got married in 1991. After a series of local
commercials in Chicago, Ryan headed for Hollywood _ part-time. She
showed up on ``Who's the Boss?,'' ``Murder, She Wrote'' and
``Diagnosis Murder.'' She wasn't exactly rivaling Meryl Streep _
one of her television movies was ``Coed Call Girls.''
 &HT;    Then there was that guest stint on ``Melrose Place.''
 &HT;    ``I was the lesbian singer/actress who had an arranged marriage
to my gay leading man,'' she recalls, smiling.
 &HT;    ``Dark Skies'' was her turning point. Though the
``X-Files''-influenced series failed, Ryan was noticed.
 &HT;    The next stop was ``Star Trek,'' and a new level of stardom.
 &HT;    ``I've been very lucky so far,'' she says. ``Everyone I've
encountered fan-wise has been very respectful, very curious, very
conscious of my time with my family, and they try not to be
intrusive. It's been very nice.''
 &HT;    ``Trek'' fans have sent marriage proposals, though, along with
portraits and even a hand-sewn bunny.
 &HT;    ``There was a Seven of Nine teddy bear sent to me which was a
riot,'' she says, chuckling. ``There was a little wig on the top
and high heels. It was very cute.''
 &HT;    Ryan is also getting used to being recognized on the street.
 &HT;    ``If I'm particularly tired, I'll do the standard baseball cap
and sunglasses,'' she says. ``In L.A., everyone is so hyper-attuned
to anyone in a baseball cap that they recognize you, whether they
know who you are or not, because you're wearing a baseball cap.
They figure you must be somebody trying to go incognito.
 &HT;    ``I swear, I'll be looking my worst and someone will come up and
scream, `It's Jeri Ryan!'''
 &HT;    Actually, having a double could come in handy ...
 c.1998 Cindy Pearlman  
