<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERI-RUSSELL-IN-FELICITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERI RUSSELL'S SENSE OF FELICITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 Includes a color slide of Keri Russell in a scene from
``Felicity.'' 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1998 Canadian TV Guide  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way Keri Russell tells it, she had only one qualm when she
was offered the title role on ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the WB Network show looked great on paper, but Russell _
although only 22 _ had already been on two other short-lived
series, ``Daddy's Girls'' and ``Malibu Shores.'' If ``Felicity''
suffered a similar fate, her career might go down with the ship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously, I was really worried about that,'' says Russell,
fresh-scrubbed and gorgeous even after a long day of interviews.
``If the show went bad I would really look bad, because I'm the
main character. If it bombed, people would say, `That Keri Russell
series was really bad.' Who needs that kind of pressure?''
</P>
<P>
   No need to fret. Since its September debut, ``Felicity'' has
lived up to much of its early hype and become a
solid-if-not-sensational hit. The critics have been kind, and
nearly all have credited Russell's presence for the show's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   For those who haven't seen it, ``Felicity'' casts Russell as a
precocious college freshman set loose in New York. Between classes,
she spends her time rapping with her dorm supervisor/emotional
mentor Noel (Scott Foley) and shyly trying to make a connection
with Ben (Scott Speedman), the former high-school classmate who's
the object of her unrequited affections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a joy to play someone like Felicity,'' Russell says.
``I don't think she's naive, per se. But all of a sudden she's in
the middle of New York and there's so much going on in her life.
But she's in control _ she's not in over her head.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the starlets on ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and other
youth-oriented shows, Felicity is not your typically glamorous
television teen _ which is just what Russell loves about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the fact she doesn't wear makeup, has baggy clothes and
has her hair stuffed into a ponytail,'' she says. ``Most young
girls out there look like her, not like the girls on `Baywatch.' I
think it's a positive thing to see someone like her who's smart and
funny, and can still be a basket case sometimes. She's human. They
can finally see someone who's like them.''
</P>
<P>
   And like herself. Since ``Felicity'' started production, Russell
has been encouraged to make suggestions regarding scripts and
dialogue, and has even been allowed input into the show's musical
score.
</P>
<P>
   ``No kidding,'' she says. ``I gave a little tape of my favorite
songs to the producers. And how cool that they were open to that!
They were totally interested in my ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   In person, the actress seems remarkably low-key about
practically everything, even her career. She credits her
down-to-earth demeanour to her background: Born in Fountain Valley,
Calif., she was one of three kids and spent much of her formative
years studying dance, without ever entertaining the notion of
becoming a child star.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never one of those kids with a stage mother _ `OK,
honey, you go in there and knock them out!''' she says. ``I just
wanted to keep dancing and studying dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell's dance experience won her an audition for the Disney
Channel's revival of ``The Mickey Mouse Club'' in 1991. She got the
job, and in short order was living at Walt Disney World in Orlando,
where the series was taped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty exciting for a 16-year-old,'' she says. ``Plus, we got
to go on rides for free.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, she received her first film role, in the comedy
``Honey, I Blew Up the Kid'' (1992). One thing led to another, and
in 1994 she was cast as Dudley Moore's daughter on the
flash-in-the-pan NBC sitcom ``Daddy's Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was definitely the rookie,'' she recalls, ``but I learned a
lot working with people like Dudley Moore, in terms of comedic
timing. He says anything and it's funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, she won a more adult role on the glitzy
prime-time soap ``Malibu Shores,'' which came from Aaron Spelling's
production company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something really unique about an Aaron Spelling
show,'' Russell says diplomatically. ``He totally knows his
audience, and he has this system he uses over and over. `Felicity'
is a different approach. There's less fantasy _ a lot less
fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly that's the world to which Russell herself belongs. Some
of her favorite scenes on ``Felicity,'' for example, involve not
the glamorous Ben but the more pedestrian Noel, who is always there
to offer Felicity advice or a shoulder to cry on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't he the greatest guy?'' she sighs. ``A lot of my friends
are just like Noel. I think I'm personally drawn to people like
him. I mean, who wouldn't be?''
</P>
<P>
   The main attraction, she says, is that Noel ``knows exactly who
he is. He has this great line _ it just broke my heart _ in one
episode. They're all going to some party, and Noel says to
Felicity, `Wow, you look really nice.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So she tells him he looks handsome,'' she continues, ``and
Noel says, `Oh, you had to say that. But you know what? I feel
handsome.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Only Noel could say that and get away with it. It was so
sweet.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell found similar realism in a scene from the pilot in which
Felicity's manipulative parents try to coerce her to attend prep
school by offering a BMW as bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's reality,'' she says. ``I have friends whose parents are
just like that. They want to mold their kids, but they can't. I
guess I'm lucky, because my parents were never like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from ``Felicity,'' Russell has a major role in the film
``Mad About Mambo,'' due out next spring. Drawing on her dance
background, she plays a young Irish dancer who teaches an awkward
soccer star (William Ash) how to dance, in order to help him with
his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ireland was so gorgeous,'' she says. ``I only wish I could
have been a bit less focused on work, because it's so beautiful. I
was stuck in a studio in the middle of Dublin most of the time.
Some days I just wanted to take off and sightsee and roam those
green hills.''
</P>
<P>
   In the immediate future, though, Russell plans to be fully
immersed in ``Felicity,'' which has so far translated into 15-hour
work days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's easy to believe her when she calls the series a
labor of love. In fact, she's not even worried about the
inevitability of her being viewed as a role model by millions of
young women.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a huge responsibility,'' she says earnestly, ``but
what's great about this show is that Felicity actually is a good
role model. She's true to herself and considers other people first.
I don't have to change her one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for Canadian TV Guide,
based in North York, Ont.) &LR; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
NIRDI RELIS in New York at 212-499-3333, or by fax at
212-499-3382.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1815EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
