<HEADLINE>
GOVERNORS CALL FOR SALES TAX ON INTERNET COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONOIO _ The popularity of the Internet, the one-stop
window into the world of culture, business and information, is
starting to hamstring state governments as more and more shoppers
go on-line to make purchases free of sales taxes, a panel of
governors said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every month, there's more commerce developed on the
Internet,'' said Illinois Gov. Jim Edgar, a Republican. ``I'm very
fearful for the states because sales taxes are our lifeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers in many states now avoid paying sales taxes through
mail-order catalogs. But state and local governments say they are
being bled of even more revenue by the point-and-click ease of the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   This holiday season alone, Internet purchases from mail-order
businesses like L.L. Bean in Freeport, Me., and Land's End in
Dodgeville, Wis., are expected to exceed $3 billion nationwide,
Edgar said.
</P>
<P>
   Some states have resorted to taxing on-line subscriptions and
transfers of data, but many state leaders say that doesn't make up
the difference for lost sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation that would have forced mail-order and Internet
businesses to collect sales taxes and return them to the states
failed in Congress this year. Opponents called the measure a hidden
tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   The technology industry has argued that imposing sales taxes
would stymie Internet commerce. But proponents of taxing Internet
sales say that the tax-free status gives on-line sellers an unfair
advantage over retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar made his comments during a panel discussion with Georgia
Gov. Zell Miller, a Democrat, and Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson and
Idaho Gov.-elect Dirk Kempthorne, both Republicans. They were
attending the annual meeting of the Council of State Governments.
</P>
<P>
   During the often free-wheeling, wide-ranging discussion on
Monday, they also decried unfunded federal mandates and other
measures they say restrict states' rights.
</P>
<P>
   When states are allowed to tackle problems on their own, they
said, innovative ideas such as welfare reform and welfare-to-work
programs are created.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest problem we face is trying to get
Washington to give us more authority,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leadership is going to our state houses more than it is to
Washington D.C.,'' he said. ``States have an unprecedented
opportunity to step into the breach and wrestle with the problems
that really affect people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kempthorne, who is retiring from the Senate to become governor,
said: ``The states will be those who come up with the solutions.
It's where the action is,'' he said. ``That's why I decided to take
this promotion.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1825EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
