<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW CAN A COMPANY INSTILL LOYALTY IN WORKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Q. The employees in our company do not have much
loyalty. There is no strong sense of commitment, and they are quick
to turn their back on us and leave, even though we have tried our
best to help them and make them feel they belong. What can we do to
increase loyalty? C.L. &QL; 
A. When the bonds of loyalty are loose, there is no quick fix to
mend them. Loyalty emerges as a result of a broad range of actions
that a company takes over time. In order to figure out why loyalty
in your organization may be low, you need to take an honest and
objective look at your organization and at the employees who are
turning their backs on it. The problem may be a matter of your
company's culture, or it may be as basic as your company's hiring
practices.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, companies that have higher levels of loyalty tend to
have a number of factors in common, and it may be helpful to match
your company with them. For example, such companies typically
strive to understand the objectives of the employees and link
individual objectives with organizational objectives. They place
strong emphasis on employee training and development, career
guidance and growth, fairness in pay and benefits, recognition,
equitable treatment, open communication lines, teamwork, input
opportunities, social consciousness and a balance between work life
and personal life.
</P>
<P>
   In a broader sense, while the idea of building employee loyalty
to the company is important, this is an age in which it is equally
important to focus on building company loyalty to the employee. &QL; 
Q. The company where I work has performance appraisal procedures in
place, yet no one, including the CEO and human resources staff,
enforces them. The only feedback my manager will give me is, ``I
don't like doing this,'' and, ``Please sign.'' How do I force this
manager and company to give me a performance appraisal that is
objective, fair and responsible? S.G. &QL; 
A. It sounds like management in your company merits a rating of
``needs major improvement'' when it comes to the way they handle
performance appraisals. You cannot really ``force'' management to
follow its appraisal procedures, and any appraisal under such
circumstances would not be particularly useful.
</P>
<P>
   The source of the problem is your CEO. The fact that this
topside leader places no emphasis on performance appraisal sends a
signal to all employees in leadership positions that the appraisals
are a second-tier item at best.
</P>
<P>
   This means that if you want to have real performance appraisals,
you need to try to get the word to the CEO. In fact, there are a
few words that the CEO should hear on this matter, including the
compelling motivational, administrative, goal-setting and proactive
reasons for conducting up-to-date appraisals.
</P>
<P>
   If you cannot access the CEO, and the company has no viable
outlet for you to have your inputs heard, then it may be time for
you to appraise more than the company's performance appraisal
system. &QL; 
Q. I do not have many personal calls at work, but it seems that
every time I'm on one, my manager walks in. Should I tell him that
this has been a bunch of coincidences, or should I just let it go?
T.L. &QL; 
A. Many employees have found that the best way to get a manager to
drop by is to be doing something other than work. It is almost a
law of the workplace that the less an employee would like to see
his or her manager, the more likely the manager is to show up.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you are making personal calls all the time or
practically never, the fact is that you have been making them, and
your manager has a misperception of your telephonic tendencies. In
order to figure out what to do, you may want to look at the degree
to which personal calls are expressly prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, since the issue is gnawing away at you, the next
step is to mention the personal calls to your manager, but they
should not be the subject of a meeting. Rather, when you meet with
him in the near future, preferably during a discussion that is
focusing on a successful outcome on one of your projects, you can
lightly and briefly mention the coincidence to him. Depending on
his reaction, you will quickly see if you need to go into more
detail or if this issue is actually a nonissue.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
