<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEARTHING HISTORY  
 PRAIRIE CHICKEN REVIVAL  
 OVARIAN TISSUE PRESERVED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mo., Minn., Iowa, Ill.)  (The Science Times) 
 (af)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking new clues to changes in vegetation and climate that
occurred thousands of years ago, scientists have gone underground.
Eighty feet underground, in fact, in a cave in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists, from the University of Minnesota and the
University of Iowa, analyzed stalagmites from Crevice Cave, in the
southeastern part of the state, for evidence of what things were
like topside 75,000 to 25,000 years ago. They reported their
results in the current issue of Science.
</P>
<P>
   A stalagmite tells a tale through time, growing on the floor of
a cave through the constant drip of mineral-laden liquid from
above.
</P>
<P>
   That liquid, of course, began as rain, and filtered through
decaying plant matter in the soil like water through coffee
grounds. Analysis of carbon isotopes in sections of the stalagmite
can reveal what kinds of plant matter the water dripped through.
And the sections can be dated by measuring the amount of a
radioactive thorium isotope they contain.
</P>
<P>
   All that analysis showed that the region around Crevice Cave was
mostly forest from 75,000 to 71,000 years ago, shifting to savannah
and then prairie for about 15,000 years before returning to forest.
</P>
<P>
   A similar analysis of oxygen isotopes in the stalagmites showed
average annual atmospheric temperatures varied by about 7 degrees
Fahrenheit, peaking around 57,000 years ago and reaching a low
point about 46,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prairie Chicken Revival
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows the story of the buffalo, how they once roamed
the Great Plains by the millions, only to be virtually wiped out by
hunters in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The greater prairie chicken may not have gotten the same press,
but it suffered the same fate, particularly in Illinois where it
was driven to near-extinction by westbound settlers looking for
food. In recent years, the prairie chicken population has thinned
even more as their habitat has disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   But like the buffalo, the greater prairie chicken is making
something of a comeback. A team of scientists from the University
of Illinois and state agencies has imported prairie chickens from
other states to diversify the gene pool, which had become
dangerously homogeneous due to inbreeding among the few remaining
birds.
</P>
<P>
   The importation is only the most recent facet of the
researchers' long-term study of prairie chickens, which they
discussed in a recent issue of Science.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that even though efforts were made to
eliminate predators and restore and preserve habitat, addressing
the issue of lack of genetic diversity was crucial to stemming the
population decline.
</P>
<P>
   Ovarian Tissue Preserved
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to preserving genetic material from many
endangered species for breeding purposes, sperm is the preferred
material. It is easy to collect, freezes well, and when thawed, is
practically as good as new.
</P>
<P>
   Not so the female component of the reproduction equation.
Mammalian eggs are very difficult to collect, and in many cases do
not survive freezing and thawing.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at Purdue University have experimented with another
approach to preserving female genetic material: freezing ovarian
tissue itself. In the latest experiment, the researchers removed
ovarian tissue from African elephants and froze it.
</P>
<P>
   When thawed a year later, it was transplanted into mice that had
had their own ovaries removed and their immune systems repressed.
The mice developed mature egg-producing follicles within three
months. In one case, an actual elephant egg was produced (which, in
theory at least, could be fertilized in a test tube and implanted
in another elephant's womb).
</P>
<P>
   While far from perfected, the technique of piggybacking ovarian
tissue on another species could provide a way to generate female
reproductive cells for endangered species in breeding programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
