</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-HISTORY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT GIFT BOOKS: HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (With sidebars history-books-music-sports, history-books-adventure
and history-books-lifestyle) 
 
 &HT;    Here's an idea. Buy a gift this year that isn't digital, that
doesn't require a Pentium processor, that won't have your recipient
flinging his eggnog against the fireplace when it crashes.
 &HT;    Buy a book. Or two or 10. There are plenty of good reads from
which to choose _ no operating manuals required.
 &HT;    The following surveys gift books on subjects ranging from
history and art to sports, music and fashion.: 
 
By FRITZ LANHAM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   The approaching end of the 20th century has spurred publishers
to offer picture-filled commentaries on the past 100 years. Two
notable contributions are ``The American Century'' by Harold Evans
(Knopf, $50) and ``The Century'' by Peter Jennings and Todd
Brewster (Doubleday, $60).
</P>
<P>
   Evans' book is truly a standout. Most coffee-table books tend to
be bland in their treatment of people and events. Evans, a
British-born naturalized American and one-time editor of the Times
of London, isn't afraid to be provocative as he surveys the
political history of his adopted country. Whether dredging up
almost forgotten episodes such as the Wyoming range war of 1892 or
describing American meddling in Latin American affairs, he's
delightfully tart and challenging.
</P>
<P>
   The book also carefully meshes text and pictures into
self-contained segments, making it easy to take in small doses.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration of veteran ABC news anchor Jennings and
Brewster, a former Life magazine writer and editor, has resulted in
a less sharp-edged book but one that covers a lot of ground, from
Frederick Jackson Turner's 1893 announcement of the closing of the
West to the death of Princess Diana. The emphasis is on the United
States, with international matters covered to the extent that they
affected this country.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``The Century'' and ``The American Century'' are on the New
York Times best-seller list _ remarkable given their hefty prices.
My guess is a lot of copies will end up under Christmas trees.
</P>
<P>
   More scholarly but still readable and attractive to a general
audience is ``The Oxford History of the Twentieth Century'' edited
by Michael Howard and William Roger Louis (Oxford University Press,
$39.95). The editors have assembled an all-star list of
contributors _ Jonathan Spence writes on China; William H. McNeill
on demography and urbanization; Steven Weinberg, the University of
Texas Nobel laureate, on physics; and so forth. Chapters deal with
themes (The Growth of a World Economy, The Visual Arts), as well as
events and individual countries. There are some illustrations, but
this is a book for reading rather than browsing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Heritage History of the United States'' (Viking,
$50) is both lavishly illustrated and crisply written. It would
make a fine gift for anyone wanting a handy overview of American
history. The author is Douglas Brinkley, the indefatigable young
historian at the University of New Orleans. This is the third
illustrated volume Viking has published in conjunction with
American Heritage in the past couple of years. ``The American
Heritage New History of the Civil War'' and ``The American Heritage
New History of World War II'' also continue to be available and are
well worth owning.
</P>
<P>
   For that baby boomer on the list _ the one who lived through the
'60s, but for some reason doesn't remember it that well _ there's
``The Sixties: Cultural Revolution in Britain, France, Italy and
the United States,'' 1958-1974 by Arthur Marwick (Oxford University
Press, $39.95).
</P>
<P>
   As the subtitle indicates, this book is distinguished by its
breadth (with the glaring omission, as Marwick admits, of Germany)
and by its emphasis on social and cultural rather than political
changes. Popular music, political protest, sexual experimentation
and dozens of other topics all get their due. At 900 pages this
looks like a forbidding tome, but Marwick writes clear, lively
prose. His is the most comprehensive history of the '60s that I
know.
</P>
<P>
   For Anglophiles, Antonia Fraser, the popular British historian,
has edited an expanded and updated version of ``The Lives of the
Kings and Queens of England'' (University of California Press,
$39.95). The coffee-table book, with 100 color and 75
black-and-white illustrations, consists of brief, readable
summaries by notable historians of the lives of Britain's monarchs.
Here's the perfect book to consult if you can't distinguish George
IV from George V or remember which Mary got her head cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Nominated for a National Book Award, Yaffa Eliach's ``There Once
Was a World'' (Little, Brown, $40) is a pioneering study. Subtitled
``A 900-Year Chronicle of the Shtetl of Eishyshok,'' it explores
the day-to-day lives, over nine centuries, of the Jews who lived in
the small market town south of Vilnius in what is now Lithuania.
</P>
<P>
   Eliach, a distinguished Holocaust scholar, was born in Eishyshok
and fled in 1941 as Nazi troops began systemically killing the
town's 3,500 Jews. Her mother and younger brother were among those
brutally murdered.
</P>
<P>
   She discovered that ``no serious, comprehensive, in-depth
account of ''shtetl`` life had ever been done,'' despite the
central role these towns played in the history of Eastern European
Jewry. Her investigations, which included archive research and
interviews with Holocaust survivors and descendants of Eishyshok's
residents, result in a richly textured portrait of a world gone
forever. A moving and important book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem: Stone and Spirit'' by Dan Bahat and Shalom Sabar
(Rizzoli, $60) narrates the city's 3,000-year history mainly
through works of art. The book's 220 illustrations _ 157 in color _
are gorgeous. The text, on the other hand, is in an irritatingly
small and hard-to-read typeface. Still, this would make an
attractive addition to the coffee table. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
