<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT GIFT BOOKS: ART AND PHOTOGRAPHY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Accent mark needed over i in Dali) 
 
By PATRICIA JOHNSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bounty of art books this season began as a trickle of little
publications. Literally little _ Abrams' ``The Essential'' series.
The mini-books measure 6 by 6 inches, and the first four titles are
``Jackson Pollock,'' ``Salvador Dali,'' ``Edward Hopper'' and
``Vincent van Gogh'' ($12.95 each).
</P>
<P>
   Each is written by a different author but follows a format _ 112
pages, 50 illustrations. The tone tends toward the snappy and
informative, and the books seem intended for the reader who
recognizes the name but maybe not the art, or the importance of the
art to which it is attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so great about Jackson Pollock?'' Justin Spring asks on
the first page of his mini-monograph. His book, he states boldly _
and accurately _ ``is a quick primer in: The Man, The Myth, The
Movement, The Art ... and it's a lot cheaper and quicker than grad
school.''
</P>
<P>
   Monographs, especially those dealing with photographers, are
plentiful this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacques Henri Lartigue, Photographer'' (Bulfinch, $95) is a
joyful celebration of the French photographer (1894-1986) of the
``belle epoque.'' He was a child prodigy who grew up to lead a
charmed life.
</P>
<P>
   The only text is a nicely wrought introductory essay by Vicki
Goldberg, photography critic for the New York Times. ``Jacques
Henri Lartigue thought that perhaps it was God who gave him his
first camera. Or at least someone who might have been mistaken for
him,'' Goldberg writes.
</P>
<P>
   Lartigue's interests were beautiful women and movement of all
kinds, especially speed. He was there with his viewfinder to
capture fledgling automobiles and airplanes, early races, soaring
kites, a playful young woman skipping down stairs. The book's ample
duotone photographs, several of them gatefolds, do justice to his
vision.
</P>
<P>
   Caught between two world wars, Lartigue managed to retreat from
the harshness of his time, effectively ignoring an ugly world to
rejoice instead in a beautiful life.
</P>
<P>
   American W. Eugene Smith, a world away from Lartigue
geographically and emotionally, turned his lens on people who did
things, simple or dramatic, that changed the world around them.
People such as Maude Cullen, a nurse midwife in the backwoods of
South Carolina, and Albert Schweitzer in Africa. Or people who were
changed by the world, such as the residents of Minamata, Japan,
victimized by an industrial pollution so distinctive and awful that
it gave birth to what's known as ``the Minamata disease.''
</P>
<P>
   ``W. Eugene Smith: Photographs, 1934-1975'' (Abrams, $75),
edited by Gilles Mora and John T. Hill, examines the remarkable
career of one of this country's heroes of photojournalism. He
worked on his own terms and indulged in what essayist Hill calls
``darkroom hyperbole,'' manipulating extreme effects of light and
dark for maximum effect. As Smith himself said, ``There must be the
realization that photography is the best liar among us abetted by
the belief that photography shows it as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The lie was only in dramatic effect; the subjects were all too
real. Smith worked for Newsweek and was a war correspondent in the
Pacific, but he is best known for the dramatic photo-essays he
created for Life magazine between 1938 and 1972, pieces for which
he also wrote the text.
</P>
<P>
   This new book is thorough in its images and its analysis of
Smith's life and work. As a bonus, it reproduces four of his
best-known Life stories, including the controversial 1954 piece ``A
Man of Mercy,'' about Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Margaret Bourke-White, Photographer'' by Sean Callahan
(Bulfinch, $65) tells the story of a courageous woman with a
remarkable eye. The American photographer established her
reputation early on with clean, graceful images of industry that
transformed the banal _ a plow blade, a spoon or a turbine _ into
sculptural aesthetic objects. She also made a name for herself with
her skyscraper pictures taken from daredevil angles _ looking down
on a DC-4 flying over Manhattan, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Bourke-White was fearless when traveling to the theaters of
World War II on assignment as one of Life magazine's four staff
photographers. She was also compassionate, as her portraits of
India in the late 1950s can attest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiritually Moving: A Collection of American Folk Art
Sculpture'' is simply lovely (if somewhat precious). Designed by
Tom Geismar and Harvey Kahn, it's an oversized production,
slip-cased and luscious (Abrams, $125). Its content is the private
and until now unknown collection amassed by someone never named in
the book itself. The collector, David Teiger, a management
consultant based in New Jersey, has come to light only in
post-publication stories.
</P>
<P>
   This disingenuous play for mystery aside, the superb color
photographs by Dave Hoffman are knockouts. They illustrate 78
traditional folk-art objects _ weather vanes and decoys, for
example _ with rich attention to overall form, texture, coloration
and frequent small details that surprise and delight.
</P>
<P>
   The images are arranged in thematic groupings such as ``Horses
Running/Jumping,'' ``Bannerets'' and ``Angels.'' Textual material
consists of a brief introduction by Don Walters, former curator of
the Abby Aldrich Rockefeller Folk Art Center.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-page catalog of the works with captions and provenance is
inserted at the back of the book and thoughtfully duplicated in a
pullout. In the absence of access to the objects themselves, this
volume is a worthy substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Baptiste Bacquart's ``The Tribal Arts of Africa'' (Thames
and Hudson, $50) is another seductive picture book, but one with a
strong didactic intent.
</P>
<P>
   ``African art is not just about an aesthetic, it is also about
meaning and function ... always related to magical or social
rites,'' writes Bacquart, art historian and former head of the
tribal art department of Sotheby's auction house in London. ``This
book has been created with the aim of helping professional and
amateur collectors alike to find visual and textual references. It
is based on photographs supported by a text whose purpose is to set
each object in a social, artistic and sometimes religious
context.''
</P>
<P>
   He breaks his subject into five primary geographic areas
subdivided into cultural or tribal groups such as the Asante and
the Fang. The selected objects are carefully reproduced to enhance
salient qualities, such as the scar pattern on the carved Luba
figure typical of the tribe. A handy reference indeed.
</P>
<P>
   No art-book season is complete without at least one book on
Pablo Picasso. ``Picasso and the War Years, 1937-1945'' (Thames and
Hudson, $50) was published as a catalog for the exhibition of the
same title organized by the Fine Arts Museums of San Francisco. Its
focus is on an intense period during which Picasso created what
many believe to be his most personal work. If not that, it surely
was a pivotal demi-decade during which he produced two of the
world's most compelling portraits of war: ``Guernica,'' in 1937,
and the ``Charnel House,'' in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   These two powerful paintings in grisaille are like brackets to
the horrors of World War II and to a period when, more than ever
for Picasso, making art constituted ``a declaration of free will
and a song of human perseverance,'' as museum director and catalog
essayist Stephen Nash puts it.
</P>
<P>
   This is an art in which death, destruction, fear and desolation
are expressed by crying women, flayed skulls and massive
distortions of form, but the artist himself appears distant and is
not so clearly understood. The narrative probes deeper and
ultimately produces a fuller profile of Picasso as a political
artist. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
