<HEADER>
A7201 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-MUSIC-S     12-07 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-MUSIC-SPORTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT BOOK GIFTS: POP MUSIC, CLASSICAL MUSIC AND MORE ... 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL, 
CHARLES WARD 
and FRITZ LANDHAM 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Rolling Stones: A Life on the Road'' (Penguin Studio, $50)
documents the Stones' adventures as a touring band, from its early
years as England's ruling blues-club band to its current status as
the world's top-grossing stadium-rock act.
</P>
<P>
   The oversize volume has page after page of dramatic photos from
the band's 35-year archive, with a text featuring commentary by
current and former members of the band and road crew. The
interviews were done by keyboardist and BBC radio host Jools
Holland and Dora Loewenstein, the daughter of Stones' business
manager, Prince Rupert Loewenstein.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing here that hasn't been revealed before, though
the collective reflections on founding member Brian Jones (who died
in 1969) and the band's late road manager Ian Stewart are humorous
and touching. But ``A Life On the Road'' stands as a visual
testament to the Stones' refusal to relinquish its title as the
world's greatest live rock 'n' roll band.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce Springsteen: Songs'' (Avon, $50) contains the complete
collection of Springsteen's recorded lyrics, from ``Blinded By the
Light'' to ``The Ghost of Tom Joad.'' The lyrics _ usually typed
but sometimes printed in Springsteen's handwriting _ are
accompanied by the artist's reflections on the relationship of his
music to his life and to the lives of his audience.
</P>
<P>
   The text is surrounded by old and new photos from Springsteen's
personal collection. Sandra Choron, Springsteen's longtime art
director, designed the book, and New Jersey free-lance writer
Robert Santelli edited the text.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs'' is the work of a true artist who represents the best
of America's traditional values _ honesty, integrity, loyalty,
honor _ without forgetting the part about ``liberty and justice for
all.'' The book is a striking visual complement to Springsteen's
new boxed set of previously unreleased material, ``Tracks.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
CLASSICAL MUSIC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Story of Opera'' (Abrams, $49.50) is a serious
coffee-table book. Instead of the customary parade of lavish
photographs with wisps of narrative, Richard Somerset-Ward's
history of Western opera offers a traditional text illustrated by
photographs reproduced with the excellence of Abrams, a publisher
known for its art books.
</P>
<P>
   Somerset-Ward doesn't pretend to offer new scholarship or
radical insights. His goal, achieved with grace and good speed, is
summarizing the 400 years of opera from its seeds in
late-16th-century Italy until today.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the Camerata and Claudio Monteverdi, the author
moves briskly through the people, places, opera houses, composers
and works that form the essential backbone of opera.
</P>
<P>
   The sprint from the Camerata to Mozart is necessarily brief, to
accommodate the 19th century and its bounty of familiar works.
Still, a reader not familiar with early opera will get a good sense
of the essential developments, quirks and social importance of
opera _ key composers, the castrati, and the royal marriages and
wealth that supported opera in its infancy.
</P>
<P>
   The chapter ``Opera in Nineteenth-Century Paris'' offers a
similar chance to become acquainted with the composers beyond
Georges Bizet who made the French capital such a cauldron of
musical excitement and scandal.
</P>
<P>
   What Somerset-Ward doesn't do is to cast off the essentially
conservative nature of opera. In his foreword he hints at a
revolution in the rise of the importance of drama as part of opera
in the last half of this century. He doesn't prove his case, and
his attitudes toward this century's music reflect traditional
tastes: He devotes as much space to Franz Schreker and Ernst Krenek
as he does to Alban Berg, though the latter's two operas,
``Wozzeck'' and ``Lulu,'' are two of this century's masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RELIGION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Attractive and informative, ``The Illustrated Guide to World
Religions'' edited by Michael D. Coogan (Oxford University Press,
$49.95) surveys the seven major living religions _ Judaism,
Christianity, Islam, Buddhism, Hinduism, Chinese traditions,
Japanese traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Each chapter is written by a different expert who discusses the
history, tenets and practices of his faith. Numerous color
illustrations give this oversize volume an inviting look. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SCIENCE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year dinosaurs were all the rage. This year, it's birds.
The evolution, social behavior, and eating and nesting habits of
birds are the subject of David Attenborough's ``The Life of Birds''
(Princeton University Press, $29.95), based on a 10-part PBS series
to air in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 180 color photographs complement Attenborough's lucid text.
Among the fun facts you'll learn from ``The Life of Birds,''
according to the publisher: ``One of the most spectacular and
vitriolic feuds in natural history raged for over a century about
whether or not vultures detect a corpse on the ground far below
where they circle in the air by sight or by smell. It was finally
resolved in 1964, when ornithologists, through rigorous experiments
with turkey vultures, excluded any possibility other than smell.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most visually striking reference books this season is
``The Simon &AMP; Schuster Encyclopedia of Animals'' edited by Dr.
Philip Whitfield (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $50). This massive 616-page
book, a guide to the vertebrates, features brief descriptions by
scientists and fine full-color paintings of the animals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SPORTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Love of the Game: My Story'' by Michael Jordanedited
by Mark Vancil (Crown, $50) is mostly pictures, but has some text
by the basketball superstar. Focusing mostly on his pro career,
Jordan describes his evolution as a player season by season. The
book's design _ with all manner of typefaces splashed over and
around photographs _ will either seem boldly fresh or irritating.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and his publishers must be doing something right. This
book is sitting at No. 4 on the New York Times best-seller list.
</P>
<P>
   Next is a book that describes a sports world as different as can
be imagined from that of Jordan and his millionaire fellows. Ty
Cashion's ``Pigskin Pulpit: A Social History of Texas High School
Football Coaches'' (Texas State Historical Association, $29.95) is
a sympathetic but not hagiographic examination of coaches from the
1890s through the 1960s, with the emphasis on those who entered the
profession around World War II or shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``While this work does not dodge the tough questions critics of
the game have posed, it is largely the coaches' own story, often in
their own words, describing the way they fit into this once
sacrosanct institution,'' writes Cashion, who teaches history at
Texas A&AMP;M-Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
