A7203 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-LIFESTY     12-07 1544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-LIFESTYLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT HOLIDAY BOOKS: LIFESTYLE, TRAVEL, FASHION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing, it has been said, is as big as the Texas sky.
Nevertheless, Wyman Meinzer, named Texas State Photographer in
1997, manages to pack a lot of it into his book ``Texas Sky''+
(University of Texas Press, $29.95). In more than 100 stunning
color pages, Meinzer records vistas across the state, on Mother
Nature's best and worst days. From lightning strikes to tornados,
sunrise to moon up, rainbows to rocks, we get a fresh look at why
we all brag and complain.
</P>
<P>
   Or travel farther afield. Three special books this holiday
season focus on Italy, two specifically on Rome. In ``Italy: In the
Shadow of Time'' (Rizzoli, $50), photographer Linda Butler captures
the nation in an old light in her black-and-white pictures,
projecting the reader into a cave near Naples or an opera box at La
Scala in Milan.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Private Rome'' (Rizzoli, $45), photographer Francesco
Venturi and writer Elizabeth Helman Minchilli go behind the faades
of the city's grand palaces, aged villas and charming terraced
apartments. With an introduction by designer Valentino, who has
long made Rome his headquarters, the book ranges from the
spectacular to the pastoral, from sculptor Mario Ceroli's bucolic
setting for his living areas and studio to Federico Forquet's
classic apartment a stone's throw from the Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Rome 360'' (Random House, $75), Attilio Boccazzi-Varotto
turns his rotating camera on 58 views of the city's ruins,
churches, palazzos, aerial cityscapes and fountains, many of them
shown on fold-out pages. This is a slightly different version of a
book first published in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   If something truly different is what someone on your gift list
craves for holiday perusal, try ``Railroad Voices'' (Stanford
University Press, $35). A tough take on the reality of modern-day
railroad work, this book was put together, surprisingly enough, by
two women.
</P>
<P>
   Lina Bertucci, a former brakeman and sometime photographer, read
Linda Niemann's book, ``Boomer: Railroad Memoirs,'' and called her,
as it happened, shortly before Niemann was to begin a round of
chemotherapy. With time on her hands, Niemann, who hired on with
Southern Pacific in 1979 and continues to work as a conductor for
Union Pacific, agreed to write the text to accompany Bertucci's
black-and-white photos.
</P>
<P>
   She did not write captions but rather narrative slices of life
on the rails, in the yards and in the locker rooms, pieces of a pie
women had formerly been forbidden to sample. Read it and laugh,
wince, cry and applaud.
</P>
<P>
   Another heady offering is Guy Davenport's ``Objects on a Table:
Harmonious Disarray in Art and Literature'' (Counterpoint, $27.50).
This translator, poet, critic, essayist and writer of short fiction
turns a discerning eye on cultural patterns in four meditations on
the still life.
</P>
<P>
   A blend of art history and literary criticism, Davenport's work
goes beyond pieces of fruit, a bust of Sherlock Holmes, an Egyptian
tomb or a Vincent van Gogh painting to find deeper, more ancient or
more modern meanings. Once you've read this, you may never again
look at an apple and a pear as fruit that happened to collide on
the space you call your kitchen table.
</P>
<P>
   So lighten up. Take a look at ``Hirschfeld on Line'' (Applause
Books, $49.95). The first collection of Al Hirschfeld cartoons in
nearly 10 years and the only one now in print, this big book
contains 400 black-and-white and color line drawings spanning the
artist's more than 70 years of illustrative commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Included is a biographical sketch of the artist, his personal
commentary and essays by his wife, his daughter, playwright Arthur
Miller, novelist Kurt Vonnegut, fashion doyenne Grace Mirabella and
actress Whoopi Goldberg. From the Broadway stages to the century's
great figures he covered for the New York Times, Hirschfeld's takes
were instantly recognizable and usually on target.
</P>
<P>
   Reach out to your roots or those of others this holiday season
with ``Las Christmas'' (Knopf, $22), in which favorite Latino
authors share their holiday memories. Editors Esmeralda Santiago
(author of ``When I was Puerto Rican'') and Joie Davidow do not
settle for poignant stories only _ although Junot Diaz's first
Christmas in America would qualify _ but search for the unusual,
with tales of Hanukkah and recipes for traditional sweet tamales
and Puerto Rican ``asopao'' (stew) and ``coquito'' (coconut
eggnog).
</P>
<P>
   For those who know the season as ``Las Navidades'' the book is
also available in Spanish in paperback from Vintage Espanol.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has dipped a toe into the history of architecture,
design and technology knows that structures built for world's fairs
often presaged major developments in those fields. Erik Mattie, a
Dutch architectural historian and town planner, looks at the
subject in ``World's Fairs'' (Princeton Architectural Press, $65),
examining some 30 fairs from the Great Exhibition of the Works of
Industry of All Nations in London in 1851 to the upcoming Hanover,
Germany, fair in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There is Joseph Paxton's great Crystal Palace, the Eiffel Tower,
Seattle's Space Needle and Buckminster Fuller's Montreal dome _ the
better known feats _ but don't miss the many buildings that once
surrounded the Eiffel Tower on the Champ de Mars or the beautiful
structures of the 1915 Panama-Pacific International Exposition in
San Francisco, first set back by delays in the Panama Canal and
then by the 1906 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Those who like armchair travel will appreciate Dr. John
Grimshaw's ``The Gardener's Atlas'' (Firefly Books, $29.95), in
which he traces the origins, discovery and cultivation of the
world's most popular garden plants.
</P>
<P>
   Leguminosae, for example, is the pea family and happens to
include the Texas State Flower, the Bluebonnet, but also the yellow
Indian laburnum, planted in the Asian tropics for its flowers and
shady canopy.
</P>
<P>
   How did tulips get to Holland, orchids to England and roses to
New York? You will find that perseverance, barter and international
friendships played a great part in the travels of flowering plants,
as did immigrants who left home with seeds and samples of their
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Donzel's ``Book of Flowers'' (Flammarion, $50)
reproduces charming photographs, paintings and illustrations that
attest to the seductiveness of flowers, the rage for bouquets and
the many languages in which you can say it with flowers. Also
included is a connoisseur's guide to the best flower shops and
markets around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stopping to smell the flowers'' will be more than a slick
self-help phrase for those lucky enough to receive Cathy Newman and
photographer Robb Kendrick's ``Perfume: The Art and Science of
Scent'' (National Geographic Society, $35). Not since Patrick
Suskind's murder story ``Perfume'' have noses been treated to such
delights.
</P>
<P>
   Newman follows the creation of a personal scent, explores the
puzzle of exactly whose noses formulate the hundreds of new
fragrances every year and what everything from the weather to the
price of labor in India to the customers at Sephora in Paris have
to do with how we smell.
</P>
<P>
   Dapper Quincy Jones writes the foreword to ``Men of Color''
(Artisan, $35), in which author Lloyd Boston takes African-American
style onto a runway of words and photographs. The impact black
style has had on the world of fashion has come from from such
diverse personalities as Wynton Marsalis, Jesse Jackson and LL Cool
J. This book is not a superficial chronicle but a serious discovery
of a style as deeply rooted in America as Calvin Klein jeans.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Country Wild'' (Houghton Mifflin, $35), author David
Larkin's Country Wisdom series turns its attention to the forest
and uncultivated open spaces of America. From recipes for Birch
Beer and cooked glasswort to determining what direction a rabbit is
heading from his tracks, Larkin's knowledge can turn a tenderfoot
into a savvy explorer who knows everything from the breeding season
of the moose to how far away he should stay from the business end
of a skunk.
</P>
<P>
   Winter reading is a fine way to explore the idea of life
elsewhere without making a mortgage investment. Elizabeth McMillian
allows the reader that pleasure in ``Living on the Water''
(Rizzoli, $50). She goes behind private doors and enjoys the vistas
from windows, balconies and patios of homes in Bali, Mexico,
Tahiti, even Cross Lake at Shreveport, La. This is one of those
yummy, glossy books that will make any landlubber want to set sail
for a weekend or get a summer home on the water.
</P>
<P>
   Treasures are on view in the Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang book ``The
World's Great Treasures'' ($60). Edited by Gianni Guadalupi, the
book contains 580 color photographs of the work of the world's most
outstanding goldsmiths and others who create objects of desire.
</P>
<P>
   Drool over the reliquary made to contain the skull of St.
Elizabeth of Thuringia, the daughter of King Andrea II of Hungary,
and unravel its complicated history _ or imagine wearing the
collars of jewels inscribed with the names of Mogul emperors. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
