<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-ADVENTU     12-07 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-BOOKS-ADVENTURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT HOLIDAY BOOKS: ADVENTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By FRITZ LANHAM 
and LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the winter of 1915, British explorer Sir Ernest Shackleton
and his crew found themselves and their ship, the Endurance,
trapped in ice off the coast of Antarctica. By the end of October
the grinding pack had reduced the Endurance to kindling.
</P>
<P>
   The members of expedition drifted on ice floes for months before
finally making it to Elephant Island. Shackleton then took five
crewmen and sailed 850 miles in a 22-foot boat to secure help from
South Georgia. On Aug. 30, 1916, he was able to rescue the men on
Elephant Island.
</P>
<P>
   Shackleton's voyage is truly one of the great adventure stories
of the 20th century (the explorer wrote about it himself in his
classic narrative ``South,'' published in 1919 and recently
reissued in two new paperback editions). Among the expedition
members was a photographer, Frank Hurley, who took astonishing
shots documenting the men's ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley's photographs have been married to text by author
Caroline Alexander in ``The Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary
Antarctic Expedition'' (Knopf, $29.95). Alexander does a fine job
in retelling the story, but the photographs are what make this
elegantly produced book.
</P>
<P>
   The Elissa, a ship with a happier fate, is the subject of the
engaging new book ``Sailing Ship Elissa'' by Rice University
history instructor Patricia Bellis Bixel (Texas A&AMP;M University
Press, $22.95).
</P>
<P>
   Launched in 1877, the Elissa served almost 100 years as a
merchant vessel _ under different owners and states of
modification.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1960s the scrap heap loomed. Then two maritime
historians, Peter Throckmorton and Karl Kortum, arranged to buy the
ship with the goal of returning it to its original glory.
</P>
<P>
   Bixel describes the process by which the ship found a home in
Galveston and was lovingly restored and returned to operation as a
sailing vessel. It's a heartening story, well-illustrated with
photos chosen by Galveston photographer Jim Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   For more on ships that didn't make it, there's Mensun Bound's
``Lost Ships: The Discovery and Exploration of the Ocean's Sunken
Treasures'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster Editions, $35). Bound, a professor of
marine archaeology at Oxford University, is no armchair explorer.
Readers will thrill to the story of how his wife's reading about
the auction of a pair of binoculars in a Sunday newspaper led to
his diving on the German pocket battleship ``Admiral Graf Spee'' in
its grave off Montevideo.
</P>
<P>
   For those who favor the mountains to the sea, Villard has
published ``Into Thin Air: The Illustrated Edition'' by Jon
Krakauer ($40).
</P>
<P>
   Published to critical and commercial acclaim in 1997, the book
tells the story of how 12 climbers died on Mount Everest during a
violent storm in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The oversize edition has more than 250 photographs and a new
postscript by the author, who is donating all the royalties from
this edition to the Everest '96 Memorial Fund.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
