<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7220 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOSEMITE-CARS-HNS &LR;      12-07 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOSEMITE-CARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERIOR DEPARTMENT SAYS NEW PLAN FOR YOSEMITE IS DUE NEXT MAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said Monday the
government will come up with a comprehensive plan next spring to
protect Yosemite National Park from the environmental damage that
millions of tourists and their cars inflict each year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which will be released in May, will combines separate
projects already under way that are dealing with transportation,
housing and commercial development and land use at the northern
California park, one of the most popular in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes sense that we roll things into a broad package that
can be reviewed in total,'' Babbitt said at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   He said that unless the number the cars entering the park's
valley is greatly reduced, the ``beauty and ecology of the Yosemite
will be destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   About 4.2 million people visit the park each year, and that
number is expected to grow to at least 6 million in the next 10
years. During the busy summer months, as many as 7,000 cars a day
cram into the 7-square-mile valley of the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times the valley reminds you very much of being in Times
Square in midsummer,'' said Babbitt, who was joined by
environmental leaders in discussing the new Yosemite plan.
</P>
<P>
   Massive flooding in the park in 1997 prompted officials to take
a closer look at congestion and other problems as part of the
restoration effort.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Meadows, president of the Wilderness Society, said
California's projected population growth threatens to overwhelm the
park. The state is expected to have 47.5 million people by 2020, up
from more than 32 million now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yosemite could be trampled in the next century,'' Meadows
said.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt said the key to protecting Yosemite was not to cut down
on the number of visitors but to ``separate'' the tourists from
their cars.
</P>
<P>
   To address that problem, park officials and the five adjacent
counties voted in August to establish a bus system that could
transport more than 800,000 visitors a year by the end of the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, the bus service will begin in limited form next
summer and will bring in visitors on Highways 140, 41 and 120. The
bus service would run hourly from the park's main entrance at El
Portal on 140 and four to six times a day from other locations,
including Fish Camp on Highway 41 and Tuolumne Meadows on 120.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the buses will be voluntary, but officials hope to entice
visitors to ride them by offering reduced park entrance fees for
people using the service. People arriving in their cars will pay
$20, while bus riders will have to pay only $3 per person or $6 per
family.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the buses will be able to bypass the long lines of
cars waiting to get in the park, and riders will be assured of
admission on those occasional days when the valley can't
accommodate more cars.
</P>
<P>
   If the test program is successful, park officials say around 200
buses would be added to the fleet over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   However Babbitt said at the news conference that the park's
transportation problems could not be solved without dealing with
other concerns such as lodging, the number of overnight park
visitors, overcrowding at popular sites and commercial development.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt also acknowledged that pressure from a lawsuit by the
environmental group Sierra Club, which had called for a planning
approach similar to the one announced Monday, helped push the
Interior Department to consider the cumulative impact of housing,
commercial development and transportation problems on Yosemite.
``It surely was a factor (in our decision),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Brower, former executive director of the Sierra Club, said
he was pleased with Babbitt's announcement. He added that the
department must ``look at the whole picture'' when examining ways
to protect the park and ``bring the public into'' the
decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
   Interior officials ``need to make sure that this beautiful park
can be seen by everybody who wants to,'' Brower said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 1842EST &QL; 
