<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELDERLY-SUICIDE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATE OF SUICIDE AMONG THE ELDERLY EXPECTED TO RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 20 long years John Sauls watched Parkinson's disease batter
his wife's body, watched the drugs lose their power to help,
watched the power of speech flee from Anna Sauls' lips.
</P>
<P>
   His seven years of retirement held no leisure. Instead, his days
passed in a small house outside Iberia, Mo., where he tended hour
by hour to a woman whose jaw went slack, whose eyes ceased to
blink, whose life in a wheelchair was tortured by neurological
disease.
</P>
<P>
   When he fell from a barn and broke some ribs in April 1990, the
69-year-old man surrendered to his burdens. He fired a .22-caliber
rifle into his wife's head and then put the barrel of a .410
shotgun in his mouth and pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt that he had come to the end of his rope,'' said their
son, Russ Sauls. ``He didn't see much choice.''
</P>
<P>
   These kinds of deaths among the elderly _ double-suicide and
murder-suicide cases, such as the Saulses and perhaps U.S. District
Judge Earl O'Connor and his wife, Jean O'Connor, found dead last
week in their Mission, Kan., home _ remain as rare as they are sad.
</P>
<P>
   And even though suicide _ often thought of in terms of
teen-agers employing permanent solutions to temporary problems _ is
really an elderly person's domain, fewer than 1 in 5,000 Americans
aged 65 and older kill themselves each year.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of elderly suicides has tumbled downward through this
century largely, researchers say, because elderly people now have
more money and better health care.
</P>
<P>
   Still, elderly Americans, especially white men, kill themselves
more than anyone. Of the handful of people who have used Oregon's
assisted-suicide law to hasten their deaths in the last year, the
median age was 71.
</P>
<P>
   And the raw numbers of elderly suicide balloon with the aging of
the American population.
</P>
<P>
   With baby boomers _ the most suicidal generation of this century
_ moving into their 60s in little more than a decade, experts
expect both the number and the rate of older people killing
themselves to rise.
</P>
<P>
   In general, they commit suicide when hopes of recovering their
health, their comfort or their independence vanish. Because older
people are healthier and wealthier today than their parents and
grandparents were generations ago, the suicide rate among those 65
and older is less than half what it was 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big news for elderly suicide is that it went down steadily
for decades,'' said Eugene McDowell, a psychologist and suicide
researcher.
</P>
<P>
   He credits programs like Social Security and Medicare for the
trend that has held steady _ with small exceptions in the 1940s and
1980s _ since the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give older people more money and good health care, and
they kill themselves less often,'' said McDowell, a co-author of
Suicide Across the Life Span.
</P>
<P>
   Hospice workers say the pain and panic that can set off suicides
among the elderly can be avoided with a little know-how about
dealing with a terminal illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can actually be a quality to those last months and days,
some quality spiritual, emotional, psychological kind of growth,''
said Thelma Sword, Liberty (Mo.) Hospital home health and hospice
director. In 20 years as a hospice nurse, Sword helped hundreds of
patients deal with death.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they come to us, there's so many things we can tell them to
make it all easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Little things, Sword said, such as learning how to use pillows
to make someone more comfortable in bed. Teaching a caretaker to
turn a patient over by pulling on the sheet rather than tugging on
sore limbs. Or telling the patient that if swallowing pills is a
problem, nearly all pain medications now are available in liquids.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide pacts and murder-suicides _ every one its own riddle _
are actually more common in early adulthood and middle age.
Typically, research shows, a man kills his wife or girlfriend and
then himself in a psychotic episode set off by sexual jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Murder-suicides among senior citizens _ far less common _
usually spring from different circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stereotype is that these suicide pacts happen among the
young like Romeo and Juliet,'' said psychologist McDowell. ``But
the reality is that it is old people who do this. And the risk of
suicide increases for them as their health fails and when they
experience money problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Agencies that track how people die tend to count suicides in one
category and murders in another while tending to overlook where the
two come together.
</P>
<P>
   Any understanding of what motivates a man to shoot his wife and
then himself is left to the imperfect science of psychological
autopsy. John Sauls left a note saying he thought God would forgive
him and asking the same consideration from those he left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Still, experts see trends. Murder-suicides among the elderly
nearly always involve a man shooting his ailing wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``These cases resemble `mercy killings' or simple suicide pacts
among the elderly in which both individuals ... are certified as
suicides,'' a team of psychiatrists wrote in the Journal of the
American Medical Association in 1992. ``These offenders also
resemble the profile of the `elderly white male suicide,' who is
usually widowed or separated, depressed and in poor health and
despair.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers have come to believe that murder-suicides tend to be
the result of the suicidal tendencies of husbands, McDowell said.
Men are about five times more likely than women to kill themselves.
That's even more pronounced in old age. For men over 85, for
instance, the suicide rate is almost 60 per 100,000, as opposed to
less than 4.5 per 100,000 women over 85.
</P>
<P>
   Women's suicidal tendencies peak in their 50s as they reach
menopause and their children leave home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's usually a desperate act by the husband,'' said the Rev.
John Paris, a medical ethicist and theologian at Boston College.
``Women do far better at living alone. They've always run the
household. So they have coped with the shopping and the cleaning
and the cooking and the finances....
</P>
<P>
   ``When men see their wives in pain and realize that it's up to
them to take care of a long-term situation, they panic. It's almost
always with a gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Russ Sauls says he suspects that his father could
have avoided a violent end for himself and his wife if he had
turned to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always somebody somewhere to give you help,'' he said.
``You can go through the churches or whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   While he believes John Sauls took a desperate measure out of
fear and frustration, Russ Sauls said it was also a compassionate
one. Husband and wife were buried together under a single
headstone. It reads:
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of love came the end of the storm.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
