<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7233 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-1100(2T     12-07 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRIGHT-COLUMN-1100(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITALIST CUBA?: ECONOMIC TIMES IN CUBA ARE A-CHANGIN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM WRIGHT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's an innovative twist, this idea that Cuba's leaders are
pushing. Government agency as entrepreneur, the catalyst that
brings capital and labor together. A corporation with all the
citizens as stockholders, promoting scores of joint ventures with
private business investors from at least 34 different countries as
its partners.
</P>
<P>
   Shall we call it an exercise in socialist capitalism? Whatever
label we put on the process, it appears to be working.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba last month, I saw a shipyard, a citrus plantation and
attractive hotels that came about through this novel mechanism. I
talked at length with Ibrahim Ferradaz Garcia, the Cabinet minister
charged with closing such deals on behalf of the government. His
official title: minister of foreign investment and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was a child of necessity. The basic concept, and the
human energies that have gone into promoting it, grew out of the
stark realization six years ago that something new must be tried.
Cuba's economy was in a tailspin. But this amazing economic hybrid
had its roots in Cuba's history and its peculiar blend of
resources, as well as its suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba is the largest island in the Caribbean, and its 11 million
people represent a third of all those who inhabit the 25 separate
countries, many tiny, that dot the sea. The island, about the size
of Pennsylvania, lies astride the seaward approach to the
continental land mass like a giant salamander sunning itself in the
warm Caribbean breeze. It's little wonder that the spacious natural
harbor snuggled into the curving northwestern shoreline at what is
now Havana attracted European explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Old Spanish forts with lookout turrets on either side of the
harbor's narrow mouth, today historic tourist attractions, once
made the city a defensible refuge from pirates and buccaneers. That
was great for Spanish settlers, but not necessarily for Cubans.
</P>
<P>
   From the systematized annihilation of the native Arawaks by the
followers of Christopher Columbus almost 500 years ago, Cuba's
inhabitants have been at the mercy of foreigners. Only briefly has
the land been free from some form of external domination. It was
the last of Spain's dominions to be relinquished after 50 years of
intermittent popular rebellions and, finally, the U.S. intervention
in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   After the Spanish-American War, Cuba fretted restlessly under
U.S. proprietorship for the first three decades of this century.
The hated Platt Amendment proclaimed America's right to intervene
militarily at will in Cuba's internal affairs. That fact rankled
Cubans, and still does. A playground and watering hole for wealthy
North Americans in the 1940s and '50s, Havana's glamorous hotel row
with its gambling casinos fell hostage to mob figures like Lucky
Lucianno and Meyer Lansky.
</P>
<P>
   After the overthrow of Cuban strongman Fulgencio Batista in
1959, Fidel Castro's confiscation of big properties, the abortive
Bay of Pigs invasion attempt and the abrupt termination of
relations with the United States in early 1961, Cuba became a
heavily dependent economic client of the Soviet Union. Russia
bought Cuban sugar and supplied Soviet oil and machinery at
concessionary prices. When the Soviet bloc began its swift
disintegration in 1989, ``we lost 80 to 85 percent of our market
overnight,'' Ferradaz tells me.
</P>
<P>
   Abandoned by Russia and spurned by the United States, the Cuban
economy declined by a punishing 35 percent during the next four
years. Life, always austere for the typical Cuban, became even
grimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Without established markets for its goods or sources of foreign
investment, without gasoline for its vehicles or Russian
replacements for aging machinery, Cuba was in an economic free
fall. Andres Oppenheimer, prize-winning writer for The Miami
Herald, was sure he saw the end. In January 1992, he foretold it in
his ambitious book, ``Castro's Final Hour.'' The prophecy, however,
was premature.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Cuba began to arrest the desperate downturn. The
economy that year eked out a meager 1 percent growth. With the
vigorous promotion of foreign investments, by 1996 it was growing
at a rate of 7.8 percent. ``Then came the Helms-Burton Act, El Nino
and the financial collapse of markets in Asia,'' says Ferradaz.
Each of these was a blow of hurricane proportions, according to the
trade minister.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba's recovery strategy has been to promote tourism, negotiate
joint ventures with foreign investors and find new foreign markets
for Cuba's goods. The three-pronged approach appears to be paying
off.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is starving. Cuba is surviving, though hardly yet
thriving. Life is hard for the average Cuban _ very hard by U.S.
standards. But progress is visible.
</P>
<P>
   The Helms-Burton law, which Congress passed in 1996, not only
tightened the embargo against U.S. trade with Cuba but sought to
intimidate foreign investors through threat of lawsuit. It also
forbade any foreign ship from docking at a U.S. port for 180 days
after it has visited Cuba. This has no doubt retarded Cuba's growth
in trade, but it hasn't stopped it.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, Cuba has cultivated the world like
an aggressive chamber of commerce, scouring for business prospects.
Castro himself has resembled a traveling salesman, constantly
promoting good will. He maintained a grueling schedule through the
spring and summer. To Europe, Africa, Latin America, patching up
old enmities and making new friends.
</P>
<P>
   Ferradaz and his ministry have been busy closing deals. Now he
tells me that he believes his country has turned the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has adapted a creative version of state-sponsored
capitalism. To carry out joint ventures with foreign investors, it
created a business corporation named Cubanacan. What makes this
unique, Ferradaz explains, is that Cubanacan has ``11 million
stockholders _ the Cuban people.'' In 1992, he says, ``we had only
50 joint ventures with foreign companies. Today there are 340.''
</P>
<P>
   One-third of these have been consummated in the past two years.
Under a typical agreement, Cuba supplies the land and Cubans the
labor, a foreign private corporation the capital.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   There are several models of cooperative participation. Cuba's
negotiators are flexible. But often Cubanacan retains 51 percent of
the stock, with 49 percent held by the investing company. ``No deal
has taken longer than 60 days,'' boasts Ferradaz, ``from
presentation to this department until final approval by both
partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Firms from Canada, Germany, France, Spain, Italy, Holland,
Britain, Russia, Israel, Australia, Brazil, Mexico, Jamaica and
other Latin American countries have embarked with Cuba on such
joint business ventures.
</P>
<P>
   A Dutch shipping company has joined with the Cubans to build a
large commercial ship repair and maintenance facility. Israeli
interests have financed a number of flourishing citrus groves,
selling the harvest in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Rodriguez, a foreign ministry specialist, shows me a
thriving orchard south of Havana. Farther east, he says, the joint
venture, employing Cubans, operates ``the world's largest citrus
plantation.'' Growing oranges, grapefruit and limes, it also is
developing bottling and canning facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Title to the land, I am told, remains with Cubans _ as does a
participating interest in the produce. Commercial citrus groves
help to diversify Cuba's agricultural production, once largely
confined to sugar and tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba has recently begun two new energy ventures _ one to work
natural gas deposits in eastern Cuba, another for a factory to turn
out bottled LNG (liquefied natural gas). The ministry considers
this development vital to industrial expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime reliance on Russian petroleum had left Cuba's motor
traffic practically immobilized. Now one sees buses again on the
highways. In Havana, taxis are abundant. Private automobiles drive
the city's wide esplanades again. Most of them are decades old.
Vintage 1950s Fords and Chevrolets stand out among smaller but
newer Russian autos. There still aren't nearly enough cars to
convene a traffic jam _ perhaps a mixed blessing.
</P>
<P>
   Most Cubans never expect to afford a new car. Bicycles are
everywhere. There is even a joint venture with Chinese interests
that manufactures bikes locally. They sell for about $2, I'm told.
</P>
<P>
   A colorful common sight along the sea wall and in the narrow
streets of Old Havana is the bicycle taxi. An energetic cyclist
pedals a neat carriage in which two customers sit side by side.
These are functional, cheaper than motor taxis and in demand by
tourists who liken the experience to a Cuban version of the
rickshaw, or a human-powered substitute for the romantic old
one-horse shay.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism grows by leaps, the number of foreign visitors virtually
doubling each year for the past three. Havana is becoming a
convention mecca for international societies of various kinds.
Tourist dollars are fast filling the gap left by abandoned Soviet
subsidies. Aggressive efforts are under way to create facilities,
compatible with Havana's romantic image, to accommodate the wave of
tourists that Cubans expect.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Malecon, a picturesque six-lane highway that runs
beside the sea wall, and in the narrow streets and ancient squares
of La Habana Vieja (the Old Havana), preservation and restoration
projects are everywhere evident. Workmen on scaffold landings work
to rehabilitate historic old native stone and concrete buildings
from the abrasive ravages of sand, sea salt and years of neglect. A
team of architects, working under the direction of city historian
Eusebio Leal Spengler, converts the restored buildings into hotels,
shops and restaurants. Some become office buildings catering to
foreign companies engaged in joint ventures with Cubanacan.
</P>
<P>
   Enter another novel corporation, Habaguanex S.A. Answering to
the city historian, it manages the restored properties. This public
entity is empowered to reinvest profits from its hotels, office
building rents, and restaurant and shop concessions into additional
restoration efforts on other abandoned historic buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In these and other ways, Cuba struggles to attract tourists and
to stay ahead of their advancing numbers. The country officially
welcomes Americans, although its leaders seem to feel a degree of
private ambivalence.
</P>
<P>
   ``In no country of the world will the American people be safer
than in Cuba!'' insists Ferradaz. He suppresses a barely detectable
sense of hurt and anger about the U.S. economic embargo and our
tight lid on travel to his island. But Cubans as a people, he
confides, are ``incorrigibly friendly'' to Americans.
</P>
<P>
   After five days of visiting freely with merchants, tourists and
taxi drivers, mixing with informal Cuban crowds in farmers' markets
and youthful patients at a free clinic, talking with waiters and
taxi drivers and workmen at construction sites, I had to agree with
Ferradaz. I came into random contact with a hundred or so private
citizens. Most had little notion of my identity _ I was only an
American. They were uniformly friendly.
</P>
<P>
   They like us personally. But they fear and distrust our
government. They blame it, not Castro, for their economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   As I ponder the number and variety of nations with whose
citizens Cuba has formed joint business ventures, I'm tempted to an
additional conclusion. Castro and other influential Cubans are not
only content but quite happy doing business with a scattered lot of
investors from throughout the world. They prefer a multitude of
medium-sized foreign ventures. They don't want a few giant
corporate megapartners from any single superpower. Yes, they'd love
to have some American investors _ so long as their size and number
don't begin to dominate Cuba's economy.
</P>
<P>
   It's my view, although it was never put to me in just these
words, that Cuba never intends to be dependent again on any one
foreign country _ neither ours nor anyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   Still, contrary to pure socialist theory, Cubans aren't averse
to marketplace economics. Taking a cue from the early success of
the foreign joint ventures, and with the government's blessing,
Cubans are experimenting with a limited form of home-grown
capitalism at the retail level: free-enterprise farmers' markets.
But that's a story in itself.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Wright of Fort Worth is a former speaker of the U.S. House
of Representatives. You can write him at P.O. Box 1413, Fort Worth,
TX 76101. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
