<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Archambeau is questionable after surgery to repair thumb
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons defensive end Lester Archambeau had
surgery Sunday night to insert pins in his broken left thumb and
won't know until later in the week whether he can play Sunday at
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The nine-year veteran was injured in the first half of a 28-21
victory against the Colts. After taking a painkiller and having the
thumb placed in a cast, Archambeau played in the second half,
finishing with a season-low one tackle.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on his status will be made after he tries to
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a possibility he could have some problems,'' coach
Dan Reeves said. ``We probably won't know until Thursday or
Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Archambeau, who is having the best season of his career, leads
the Falcons (11-2) with a career-high nine sacks and six forced
fumbles. He is fourth on the team with 70 tackles and is tied for
the team lead with two fumble recoveries. He also calls most
adjustments in the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects your grip,'' he said of the broken thumb, ``but
you're still able to hit people. I'll still have some grip. When I
practice some, I'll see how it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Colts driving for a potential tying touchdown Sunday,
Archambeau forced running back Marshall Faulk to fumble on the
second play of the fourth quarter. Defensive end Chuck Smith
recovered at the Atlanta 29-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   If the 6-foot-5, 275-pound Archambeau can't play, he will be
replaced by John Burrough (6-5, 275), who also is bothered by an
injury. Burrough tore a muscle in his right foot during the
preseason and has trouble putting pressure on it. Burrough has 25
tackles and a half-sack this season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when Archambeau had 66 tackles, 8.5 sacks and five
forced fumbles, he was named to USA Today's ``All-Joe Team,'' which
honors the ``unrecognized, overlooked, and hard-working stiffs'' of
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Chandler, who missed the Nov. 29 game at St.
Louis with a sprained ankle, limped off the field after the last
play of the game on Sunday, but he's healthy. And reserve
cornerback Randy Fuller, who missed the Colts game with a strained
and bruised shoulder, probably will play against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
