<SLUG> BC-MLS-WOES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Agents told they'll love new system
 &HT;    By Susan Harte
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ No pain, no gain. Real estate agents complaining about
problems with Metro Listing Service's week-old, Internet-based data
retrieval system were told Monday they will learn to love it.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, users said the system was slow, that it bumped
people off too easily and that it did not give enough information
on existing listings.
</P>
<P>
   Don Lacey _ president of MLS, a service of the DeKalb (Ga.)
Board of Realtors _ defended the innovation and said operator error
was to blame for some of the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the first multiple listing service in the country to
do this, and we have trained 8,000 people to use it,'' Lacey said,
explaining 4,000 more people still need to take a course to
understand the system.
</P>
<P>
   New features include comprehensive data on real estate listings,
contracts and sales in 19 counties; a five-year history of deed
transfers; data on school systems; and tax digests.
</P>
<P>
   While he acknowledged the new system was overwhelmed with users
when it went online last Tuesday, Lacey said 121,000 people had
used the new system successfully by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lacey said software was rewritten over the weekend, and the
system is moving rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Home buyers and sellers were not significantly affected.
</P>
<P>
   John Anderson of Bob Wood Realty said, ``It is not hurting the
sale of my listings ... but my ability to access the information I
need to function takes longer then I like.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Harte writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
