A7246 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV13-NYT     12-07 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-$ADV13-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARIS WITH TEEN-AGERS  
 THE FINAL FOUR  
 JERSEY SHORE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 13) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. (italics)I will taking about 30 teen-agers to Paris during
their Easter school break, and I have heard that Easter Sunday and
Monday are holidays in France. Can you list a few sites that will
be open those days? And do you know any dance clubs that do not
serve alcohol? _ Daria Price, New Hope, Pa.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You will find Notre-Dame Cathedral open, so you can apply in
person for sainthood for chaperoning 30 teen-agers. Seriously,
though, the churches of Paris might be a good choice for
sightseeing on Easter Sunday and Monday (April 4 and 5), since many
museums and shops will be closed, although that tradition has been
fading in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Paris tourist office, (33-1) 49.52.53.54, says
the Louvre should be open those days.
</P>
<P>
   You also expressed interest in the city's flea market, the
Marche aux Puces. Good news: It is scheduled to be open Saturday,
Sunday and Monday from 9:30 a.m. to 6 p.m., as usual, although
there may be fewer merchants than normal. The flea market is in
St.-Ouen on the city's north side. Get off at the Porte de
Clignancourt or Garibaldi Metro stop. For a layout of merchants,
try www.les-puces.com.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, your teen-agers can join their Parisian counterparts at
dance parties organized by the Rock 'n' Roll Dance Center,
telephone (33-1) 43.80.90.23. Every Friday at 10 p.m. in the
Gymnase Club Italie, the center holds group lessons in swing
dancing (called rock in French). The students are broken into
beginner, intermediate and advanced groups.
</P>
<P>
   Then it's a regular dance until 2 a.m. Admission is $10 (at
about 5.7 francs to $1), including one soft drink (no alcohol
served). The center also has Sunday-afternoon dances twice a month,
but call to see if Easter is one of them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics) For my boyfriend's 40th birthday, I want to send
him and a friend to the National Collegiate Athletic Association
men's basketball championships, the famed Final Four. Are there
companies offering trips to the Final Four with game tickets? _
Patricia Brigantic, New York, N.Y.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. Your boyfriend is a lucky guy. But you have to shop carefully
or you might not be a lucky consumer. Trips to major sports events
like the Super Bowl and Final Four that are advertised as including
tickets to the event are always risky, because demand is so high
and ticket sources for tour operators are never completely
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Look for an operator who has a long track record, which
indicates reliability in getting tickets. And ask for a written
guarantee, if possible. Buying these trips through a travel agent
adds a layer of protection.
</P>
<P>
   But you are more fortunate than usual because the 1999 Final
Four, scheduled for March 27 and 29, will be held at Tropicana
Field in St. Petersburg, Fla. This is normally a baseball stadium,
which means that many thousands more seats will be available than
in a typical basketball arena, which seats about 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   The disadvantage is that many seats along two of the basketball
court's four sides are much farther away from the action, and the
price of these packages rises sharply the closer the seats are.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Erban, owner of Creative Charters, (888) 612-0323, which
can arrange customized trips to the Final Four, says that game
tickets are expensive because they pass through several middlemen.
This year, seats will typically cost $300 to $2,000 each, Erban
said, and the cheapest three-day packages should be around $800 a
person.
</P>
<P>
   Here are other tour operators that are selling trips to the 1999
Final Four. In both cases, air fare is extra and you should book
through a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Professional Sports Travel, (800) 846-8687. It has three- and
four-night packages with tickets to the semifinals and the final,
daily breakfast, an Alamo rental car and lodging at the Ramada Inn
Gulfview.
</P>
<P>
   Cost per person: $1,207 for three nights, $1,360 for four
nights, double occupancy. Deduct $120 to $160 per room if your
boyfriend and his buddy share the rental car. Tickets are in the
upper deck, behind one of the baskets; upgrades available at extra
cost.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Empire, (800) 255-5258. Its four-night packages start at
$1,695 a person, double occupancy, and include tickets to the
semifinals and final, a rental car and accommodations at the
Holiday Inn Sunspree. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)We have spent summers at the Duck area of the Outer
Banks of North Carolina. But with traffic worsening each year, we
want a getaway closer to home. Do any towns along the southern
Jersey Shore offer similar facilities, namely more rental homes
than hotels, fishing, golf and no casinos? _ Allan G. Fletcher,
Stamford, Conn.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   A. There are some quiet towns along the southern Jersey Shore,
but only in the relative sense. Don't expect beachfront homes that
are not within shouting distance of one another.
</P>
<P>
   The Jersey Shore is fairly well built up. And traffic along the
main highway to the shore, the Garden State Parkway, is pretty bad
on summer weekends.
</P>
<P>
   But you will be much closer to home, and if you can leave on a
Saturday morning and return early Sunday afternoon, traffic should
not be too terrible. Gambling, restricted to Atlantic City, isn't a
real intrusion in these towns.
</P>
<P>
   The ones you might want to consider are Avalon, Ocean City,
Stone Harbor, Strathmere, Sea Isle City and Cape May Point. A quick
survey of real-estate agencies indicated that you can expect to pay
$600 a week and up for a home rental in summer, with $1,200 to
$1,700 more likely.
</P>
<P>
   Each town has its quirks. Homeowners in Avalon and Stone Harbor
are said to prefer long-term rentals, sometimes a month or more in
the summer. Ocean City is dry _ you can't even take wine to a
restaurant _ and it has some small amusement piers so it gets busy
in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Cape May Point is a quiet enclave beyond the bustling Victorian
community of Cape May. For a list of real-estate agencies in each
town that specialize in summer home rentals, call the Cape May
County Office of Tourism at (609) 465-7181. As for fishing, you'll
find charter boats along the road from the end of the Garden State
Parkway to the center of Cape May.
</P>
<P>
   Recommended golf courses include Avalon Golf Club, 1510 Route 9
North, Cape May Court House; (800) 643-4766, and Cape May National
Golf Club, Route 9 and Florence Avenue, Cape May, (609) 884-1563. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
