<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of Dec. 8 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818)
713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LLOYD-COLUMN -- Let the hire beware. Daily News columnist Ken
Lloyd, Ph.D., a specialist in organizational behavior, answers
readers' questions on workplace ethics and relationships.
</P>
<P>
   WHITE-JEWELRY (Los Angeles) _ The stuff glittering around the
nation's homes this holiday won't be tinsel; it'll be jewelry,
which is expected to be especially hot among cash consumers. And
it's not just any jewelry, but ``white'' jewelry _ white gold,
platinum and diamonds are the thing to have this year. ``Basically,
it's going to be a white Christmas,'' said Ken Gassman, a retail
analyst specializing in the jewelry industry at Davenport &AMP; Co., an
investment research firm in Richmond, Va. By Enrique Rivero. (Will
move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FILMS-OVERSEAS (Los Angeles) _ The continuing economic turmoil
overseas, protectionist policies in Europe and other factors will
take a substantial toll on the entertainment industry over the next
two years, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
   The key production categories such as television, features and
commercials are expected to an annual 8 percent to 10 percent
through 2000 before picking up again in subsequent years, said Cody
Cluff, president of the Entertainment Industry Development Corp.,
at the Valley Industry and Commerce Association's annual meeting
Monday. By Enrique Rivero. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
