<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-VP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURPHY ELECTED TEAMSTERS VP IN EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A labor official whose digging unearthed a Teamsters
campaign finance scandal last year that rocked the 1.4
million-member union has been elected vice president of the eastern
region.
</P>
<P>
   John Murphy, 50, a business agent at Teamsters Local 122 in
South Boston, received 61,851 votes in an election that catapulted
Detroit lawyer James P. Hoffa into the union presidency. In all,
420,000 union members, approximately 31 percent of the membership,
returned postage-paid mail ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's election resulted in the ouster of George Cashman as
vice president of the eastern region. Cashman, who ran as an
independent, received 7,491 votes. Cashman remains president of
Teamsters Local 25 in Charlestown, and also heads Teamsters Joint
Council 10.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman was in a meeting Monday and could not be reached to
comment. Murphy, who monitored the vote count in Washingto over the
weekend, also was unavailable, a campaign spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   University of Massachusetts at Amherst labor historian Thomas
Juravich said Monday it was still too early to say how the change
in leadership would affect the union locally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoffa has not actually articulated his goals,'' said Juravich.
``So, we still do not know what to expect. He has said that he
would like to return the Teamsters to the days of local control.
What does that mean for union members here? It's still too early to
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   Said James Green, a labor professor at UMass-Amherst: ``John
Murphy appealed to the sentiment of having the union be a new kind
of organization _ aggressive and democratic. He has been involved
in a lot of progressive activities around Boston, and I think
members remembered that. The union that past presidents presided
over is a very different union.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Cashman indicated an interest in running for the
presidency on a unity slate that would bring the Teamsters' various
factions together. Choosing not to support either of the candidates
for president, Cashman ran as an independent. Ironically, his local
voted overwhelmingly for Thomas W. Leedham, a reform candidate who
heads the union's 400,000-member warehouse division.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, a longtime supporter of Hoffa, son of former Teamsters
president James Riddle Hoffa, used amateur detective work to ferret
out information that plunged the union into turmoil. For days, the
feisty union official pored through campaign donation documents in
a stuffy room in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When he opened a file at the bottom of the pile, he knew he had
reached something big: The document contained information about a
committee that had donated more than $200,000 to the re-election
campaign of former Teamsters president Ron Carey in the final weeks
before the election.
</P>
<P>
   After a little more digging, Murphy discovered that $95,000 in
illegal donations had been made by the wife of Michael Ansara,
owner of the Somerville, Mass. company whose telephone bank had
helped Carey aides get out the vote. The trouble was, Murphy said,
it was illegal for an employer or his relatives to contribute to a
candidate's campaign. Moreover, Ansara's wife, Barbara Arnold, was
listed as a college student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided to break the pattern,'' Murphy said in a 1997
interview with The Boston Globe. ``I don't know why I did it. I
just went to the bottom of the pile and pulled (the file) out.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, evidence emerged that nearly $1 million in union funds had
been diverted to the Carey campaign. The scandal dealt a blow to
the union's reform movement, and Carey was expelled from the union
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy was a leader of an aggressive campaign against a major
brewery that wanted to distribute beer with nonunion drivers. ``He
had a highly visible campaign, and it was successful,'' noted
UMass' Green.
</P>
<P>
   A former student activist who worked closely with a campaign to
free the Black Panthers, Murphy had lost an earlier bid for union
regional vice president on the Hoffa ticket to Cashman, a moderate
who had supported Carey in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people who put Ron Carey in office, this may seem like
a setback,'' Green said of the election results and Hoffa's
victory. ``But I think the union is at a crossroads. It still
remains to be seen what will happen. The real question is whether
local fiefdoms will regain power and not be accountable to any
national agenda or whether we will see the continuation of a large
national union.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
