<HEADER>
A7288 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOON-ROCK-HNS &LR;      12-07 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-ROCK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA MAN TRYING TO SELL MOON ROCK LANDS IN TROUBLE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By TONY FREEMANTLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A tiny piece of the lunar surface presented in friendship by the
United States to the people of Honduras 25 years ago has landed a
South Florida man in what could be a heap of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Rosen of Aventura, north of Miami Beach, doesn't yet know
for sure _ it all depends on how he came to acquire the moon pebble
and how it came back into this country _ but for now the specimen
he unwittingly tried to sell to U.S. Customs agents for $5 million
in October is in government custody.
</P>
<P>
   Customs agents announced the seizure of the moon rock Monday at
a press conference in Miami, claiming it was the first case of its
kind in U.S. history. The chip of rock, which weighs 1.1 grams, was
picked up from the Taurus Littrow Valley of the moon in December
1972 during the Apollo 17 mission, the last U.S. flight to the
moon.
</P>
<P>
   Raphael G. Lopez, the Custom Services' special agent in charge
of the South Florida office, said the specimen was seized Nov. 18
at an Aventura bank after several meetings with Rosen during which
the transaction was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said the seizure was the outcome of an operation called
``Operation Lunar Eclipse'' that was launched in September and
which was intended to snag people dealing in bogus moon rocks.
Agents from NASA's Office of the Inspector General and from the
U.S. Postal Inspection Service established a fake business in
Houston called John's Estate Sales and began placing ads in a
national newspaper saying they were looking to buy moon rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of September a man identified as Alan Rosen
called John's Estate Sales and left a message saying: ``I think I
have something you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began two months of meetings and phone calls between the
agents and Rosen, whom Lopez would only define as being in his
early 60s and as a person who was ``involved in art deals.''
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear what the moon rock in question was worth
and that it had, at some point, come into the United States from
Honduras, the Customs Service was called in to determine if customs
laws had been violated.
</P>
<P>
   The piece of moon rock has been tested at the Johnson Space
Center in Houston and has been declared authentic by NASA
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   No more than half an inch long, the pebble was mounted on a
piece of black maple and presented to Honduras by President Nixon.
On the plaque was a description of where the specimen was gathered
and a warm greeting to the people of Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   The plaque was found in Rosen's car, but the inscription had
been changed to identify the specimen as merely a worthless sample
from a Honduran mine.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez said that Rosen was never taken into custody, but that
smuggling charges could be filed against him if it is determined
that he brought the specimen into the country. Other than that,
there is nothing illegal about possessing a piece of moon rock.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen, who could not be reached for comment, apparently has told
investigators that he purchased the sample from a Honduran military
officer. Lopez said Rosen has provided conflicting accounts of who
brought the rock into the U.S. and the investigation continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still looking at what other parties are involved,''
said the Customs agent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
