<SLUG> BC-KERRY-STAFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRY JUGGLES WASHINGTON STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry is changing his Washington chief of staff
and looking for new legislative and communications directors in a
reorganization being conducted with the help of his wife, Teresa
Heinz.
</P>
<P>
   The moves come as Kerry continues to consider making a
presidential bid. Monday, on NBC's ``Today'' show, Kerry said he
might set up an exploratory committee in the coming weeks as he
makes up his mind about whether to run.
</P>
<P>
   Helen R. Kanovsky, who was hired as Kerry's chief of staff about
a year ago, confirmed she is leaving the post but said she may stay
on with Kerry in some other position.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Kerry's staff, Kanovsky was general counsel for
the AFL-CIO Housing Investment Trust, headed by former Boston
Redevelopment Authority director Stephen Coyle.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Lewis, Heinz's chief of staff for the Pittsburgh-based
Heinz Family Foundation, called Kanovsky and suggested she move on,
according to people close to Kerry's office. It wasn't the first
time Heinz's office was involved in personnel matters in Kerry's
office. Last year, Kerry hired Richard Breyers, a former press
secretary and legislative director to the late Republican Senator
John Heinz, to work as his legislative counsel. Breyers has since
left Kerry's employ.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Kerry dismissed suggestions that his office was
in upheaval. He said he has been slowly and steadily working to
improve his operations over many months. He said he wants to bring
in a communications director, create a policy director position,
and name a new legislative director.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry declined to discuss his plans for Kanovsky, saying they
should be private.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a terrific, capable person who's done an outstanding job
for me in ways I want to continue to utilize,'' Kerry said. ``The
discussion between us is personal and I don't feel I need to share
it publicly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
