<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RENO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO WON'T APPOINT CLINTON FUND-RAISING PROBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno Monday decided not to
seek an independent counsel to investigate President Clinton's 1996
fund-raising practices, finding that the president did not intend
to violate campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reno made her decision despite a finding last week by Federal
Election Commission auditors that both the Clinton and Dole
campaigns engaged in massive violations of campaign finance laws by
illegally coordinating ads with their political parties. She also
overruled recommendations from FBI Director Louis Freeh and a
former top Justice Department official, Charles LaBella.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find by clear and convincing evidence a lack of knowing and
willful criminal intent required for criminal prosecution,'' Reno
said in a written decision.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was the question of whether Clinton engaged in a scheme
to get around the federal limit on campaign spending by
coordinating ads with the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Reno reasoned that Clinton and Vice President Al Gore were
advised by their lawyers that the DNC ads were legal, and thus they
did not knowingly violate the law. She said she was making no
judgment about whether the Clinton campaign should have been able
to go beyond the federal spending limits, as the FEC audit
indicated. Nonetheless, she noted that FEC commissioners said at a
hearing last week the law was ``fuzzy'' and ``hardly clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocacy groups such as Common Cause promptly condemned the
decision, saying it will ensure that future presidential campaigns
employ the same loophole to get around spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision effectively makes the spending limits
meaningless,'' Common Cause executive vice president Don Simon
said. ``That sets a terrible standard for the next presidential
campaign in which you can take public money, take a pledge to abide
by public spending limits, but not take it seriously because there
is an easy scam to get around them.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Dan Burton of Indiana, a Republican who oversaw a
fund-raising investigation by the House Government Reform and
Oversight Committee, said Reno's decision marked ``another sad day
for the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it deplorable that she seems to have placed the
president above the law,'' Burton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   While the White House was relieved at Reno's decision, the
official reaction was brief and low-key because it came just as
Clinton faces House impeachment hearings focusing on his
relationship with former intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have been saying throughout this process, the president
and the Clinton-Gore campaign observed the spirit and the letter of
the law, and we are pleased by this decision,'' said White House
spokesman Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996 campaign, Clinton agreed to spending limits in
the primary and general elections in exchange for millions of
dollars of public matching funds. But several investigations,
including those conducted by the FEC auditors and the Senate
Governmental Affairs Committee, found that Clinton worked with the
DNC to air advertisements boosting his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Those ads, many of them nearly identical to Clinton campaign
commercials, were paid for with unregulated and unlimited
contributions known as ``soft money.'' The DNC spent about $46
million on the ads, according to some reports. The Democratic
committee defended the commercials as generic party-building ads
because they did not call for the election or defeat of specific
candidates, although many of them blasted action by Dole and hailed
decisions by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC funding of the ads helped the Clinton campaign get
around campaign laws that limit individual contributions to $1,000
per election cycle. The same person who gave $1,000 to the Clinton
campaign could give an unlimited amount to the DNC, which used the
money to produce the campaign-style ads.
</P>
<P>
   While many Republicans have long called for the appointment of
an independent counsel in the case, the GOP was in an awkward
position because FEC auditors found that the Dole campaign broke
the law in the same manner as the Clinton campaign. Indeed, the FEC
auditors said the Dole campaign should repay the Treasury $17.7
million for its violations, compared to $7.5 million for the
Clinton campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno stressed that her decision Monday did not end the
department's separate probe into a variety of allegations that
campaign finance laws were broken. ``Today's determination only
ends our probe into whether issue ads paid for by the Democratic
National Committee violated federal criminal statutes,'' she said.
``It does not end our vigorous investigation into allegations of
illegal activity surrounding the 1996 elections.''
</P>
</TEXT>
