</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME IN HOUSE COUNT ON IMPEACHMENT FAILING IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The prospect the House will pass at least one
article of impeachment is growing partly because some swing-vote
Republicans are comfortable there is little chance the Senate would
vote to convict President Clinton, thus providing the GOP with a
historic way to punish the president without ousting him. A top
Republican leadership aide said Monday that the current ``psyche''
of the GOP is to punish Clinton with a move ``stronger than
censure.'' While it takes a majority vote in the House to impeach a
president, a two-thirds vote in the Senate is required for
conviction and ouster. Republicans control the Senate, 55-45, far
short of the necessary 67 votes needed for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   One senior GOP aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Republicans like this situation because it ensures that Clinton has
``an un-expungeable record as only the second president to be
impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are trying to use the complex rules of impeachment
to their advantage, taking the Clinton case as far as possible
while trying to avoid the voter backlash that could arise if the
Senate convicted and ousted the president. The strategy depends on
House members voting for impeachment regardless of how they think
the Senate should act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are only the grand jury,'' said Representative Marge
Roukema of Connecticut, one of a number of Republicans who intend
to vote for impeachment without regard to possible Senate action.
``The Senate has to make that decision, and I don't think what the
Senate does should have any influence on how we do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Roukema said she takes ``strong exception'' to other
Republicans, such as Representative Christopher Shays of
Connecticut, who have said they won't vote for impeachment unless
they feel certain the Senate should convict Clinton. The outcome of
the House vote could depend on whether undecided Republicans take
the Roukema or Shays viewpoint.
</P>
<P>
   All of this alarms Democrats, who charge that Republicans are
turning the impeachment vote into a form of punishment with no
intention of trying to oust Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard that argument,'' said Senator John F. Kerry. ``I
think it is a cop-out on constitutional responsibility. I don't
think the process should be trifled with that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat who has called
for a censure resolution, urged House members not to vote for
impeachment unless they really want to oust the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``One ought to do it as if there is a reasonable chance that the
impeachment will lead to removal from office,'' Lieberman said.
While Lieberman agreed there is a presumption the Senate won't have
enough votes to convict Clinton, he said the Senate is
unpredictable. ``No member I know of has declared how they would
vote on impeachment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Baron, who was the lead counsel in 1989 in the Senate's
last two impeachment trials of federal judges, said it would be an
``abuse'' for a House member to vote for impeachment while assuming
Clinton would be acquitted by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No responsible prosecutor would bring an indictment knowing
full well he doesn't have the proof,'' Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a Senate trial is complicated by the arcane
rules of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A Senate trial must start at 1 p.m. the day after the House
sends over the articles of impeachment. But Senate officials said
the process is more flexible, with the House first asking the
Senate whether it is ready to receive the articles. The Senate then
has time to ensure that all senators are assembled and ready to
begin the trial. Once the Senate is ready, it notifies the House it
is ready to receive the articles of impeachment. The House would
send the articles to the Senate, and the trial would begin the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, if the House does vote for articles of impeachment
later this month, Republicans expect a trial to begin shortly after
the new Senate convenes on Jan. 6. As a result, the House of the
105th Congress would be sending articles of impeachment to the
Senate of the 106th Congress. While there have been questions
whether such a timetable would be unconstitutional, House Judiciary
Committee Chairman Henry J. Hyde said Monday he was sure the
Supreme Court would allow it.
</P>
<P>
   The trial would be overseen by Supreme Court Chief Justice
William Rehnquist, with the senators sitting as jurors. There is no
prosecutor in the case because criminal charges are not being
brought. Instead, the House Judiciary Committee would appoint
``managers'' who would bring the case to the Senate. The managers
can be a House counsel, as well as one or more House members.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Constitution, the penalty for a Senate
conviction of a single article of impeachment ``shall not extend
further than to removal from office.'' While some analysts said
that leaves open the possibility of a lesser penalty than removal
from office, Baron said it is widely interpreted as the president
must be removed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
