<HEADER>
A7314 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RENO-CLINTON-12-08-CO     12-07 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-CLINTON-12-08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RENO TURNS DOWN INDEPENDENT PROBE OF CLINTON CAMPAIGN FINANCES
 &HT;    770 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno decided Monday that
President Clinton will not become the target of an independent
counsel for exceeding campaign spending limits in 1996 because the
president had been guided by advice from his lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Already embroiled in a historic fight against impeachment,
Clinton received news that neither he nor Vice President Al Gore
would be probed for coordinating a $44 million TV ad campaign paid
for by the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In her filing to a federal appeals court, Reno found that
Clinton and Gore were intimately involved in raising the money and
planning the so-called ``issue'' ads. However, neither ``acted with
the criminal intent ... because they were repeatedly assured that
legal counsel had approved the overall concept'' and because
lawyers were consulted along the way, Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general had ordered a preliminary probe after a
Federal Election Commission audit suggested Clinton and Gore may
have violated federal spending limits by allying their campaign so
closely with party spending.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision was the second in as many weeks in which she
declined to seek an independent counsel on campaign financing. Last
month, she cleared Gore in his telephone fund-raising from the
White House. She has delayed until early next year a third
decision, which is whether to seek an outside probe of former White
House aide Harold Ickes concerning allegations that he lied to a
Senate committee that investigated campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of stiff pressure from Republicans and from FBI
Director Louis Freeh, Reno has yet to name an outside investigator
for any of the various campaign finance scandals that emerged from
the 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The White House responded that ``We are gratified'' by the
latest decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have said all along, the president and the Clinton-Gore
campaign complied with the spirit and the letter of the law,'' said
spokeswoman Amy Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., lambasted the reasoning for
clearing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet Reno's argument that we should turn a blind eye to
potential wrongdoing by the president, because his lawyers told him
to do it, is outrageous,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is specific and credible evidence, including the
president's own words on tape, that indicate he engaged in an
effort to violate campaign laws by engaging in a scheme to exceed
spending limits,'' Barr said. He added that some of the money
raised for the ads came from questionable sources, including China.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, said ``the rule of law continues to
suffer'' and restated his intention to take the matter of an
independent counsel out of the attorney general's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., who has been Reno's chief critic on
Capitol Hill, said, ``I find it deplorable that she seems to have
placed the president above the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign-reform advocates expressed disappointment but not
surprise at the latest turndown for an outside probe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a very unfortunate decision that takes a big
step toward dismantling the federal election laws,'' said Don
Simon, counsel for the group Common Cause, which favors cutting
back the role of big money in politics.
</P>
<P>
   The decision ``makes the spending limits largely meaningless and
approves the means for evading those limits,'' Simon said.
</P>
<P>
   This means in the 2000 election, ``a candidate can take the
public money and not abide by the spending limit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under campaign laws enacted in 1974 to remove much of the
private interest money from presidential campaigns, candidates who
accept federal funds agree to spending limits. However, the FEC
audit found that both the Clinton campaign and his Republican
challenger Bob Dole evaded those limits by overseeing millions of
dollars' worth of political ``issue'' ads that were financed by the
political parties.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC auditors said Clinton should repay $7 million and Dole
should repay $17 million. However, members of the election
commission have expressed concerns that the rules were too
``fuzzy'' and have indicated that they may not seek the full
repayment. Dole was not a target for a possible independent
counsel, because he is not a federal official.
</P>
<P>
   Simon spread the blame for the failure to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Reno's) been resistent to looking at this question since we
first raised it in 1996, and she's being very conservative and
getting bad advice from her staff,'' he said. As for the bipartisan
FEC, Simon said, ``They are supposed to be an aggressive watchdog,
and they are more like a napping pussy cat.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
