<HEADLINE>
WATCH YOUR HEAD 
ON THE RAILS DOWN UNDER 
CALLING ALL LEPIDOPTERISTS 
ISLAND RESORT OPENS 
CUISINE TOURS IN ASIA
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Dec. 13)  
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many people fear airplane accidents, but they may be focused on
the wrong source of injury. A recent study indicates that thousands
of people are hurt annually in events that do not even meet the
aviation authorities' definition of an accident. By contrast, in
1997, the latest statistics available, the National Transportation
Safety Board listed two deaths and 21 serious injuries in what it
considered accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The leading sources of injuries are items that fall out of
overhead luggage bins. Once meant for coats and other light
articles, these bins are now frequently used for heavier items. A
doctor at the Flight Safety Foundation, a nonprofit group based in
Alexandria, Va., studied 462 incidents of injuries caused by
objects falling from the overhead bins on Boeing 757s belonging to
one airline, which he did not identify, and found bruising or
laceration in half the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Boxes and picture frames were the most dangerous items, followed
by sporting goods and wheeled objects, including carts, strollers
and wheelchair parts. As laptop computers become more popular, they
are a growing hazard, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of injuries were to the head, in many cases
producing minimal traumatic brain injury, according to the study,
which was written by Dr. Leo Rozmaryn, an orthopedic surgeon in the
Washington area.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATTHEW L. WALD &QR;
</P>
<P>
   An Australian Version of the Orient Express
</P>
<P>
   Fans of long-distance rail travel _ or just of the Orient
Express _ will soon be able to indulge themselves in style on a new
continent: Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Venice Simplon-Orient Express and Queensland Rail are teaming up
for the Great South Pacific Express, a luxury train that will run
along the eastern coast, between Sydney, in New South Wales, and
Cairns, in northern Queensland. Previews of the trips _ 18 hours
between Sydney and Brisbane or 45 hours between Brisbane and Cairns
_ begin Dec. 27, with the official inauguration in April. It is
possible to combine the two legs, a four-night excursion, with a
night in a Brisbane hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The train's northern leg _ Brisbane to just north of Cairns _
brings passengers close to two World Heritage sites: the rain
forest of the Great Dividing Mountain Range and the Great Barrier
Reef. Passengers can take excursions to both areas, including lunch
on a platform on the reef.
</P>
<P>
   The train has 20 cars, including 12 sleepers for 92 people.
Sleeping quarters include state compartments, with twin beds;
Pullman, with upper and lower beds; and commissioner's
compartments, with double beds. All have their own showers, basins
and toilets, and are air-conditioned. The cars feature red cedar
walls and stained-glass clerestory roofs. There will be two dining
cars and a lounge car, with a piano area.
</P>
<P>
   Rates _ per person, double occupancy _ until April range from
$820 on the Brisbane-Sydney leg and $1,150 for Brisbane-Cairns in a
state car, to $3,250 for a combined itinerary in a commissioner's
compartment. Afterward, rates will be $1,470 to $3,710, plus about
$70 for a Brisbane hotel room. Reservations: (800) 524-2420.
</P>
<P>
   _ RAY CORMIER &QR;
</P>
<P>
   It's Butterfly Weather on the Upper West Side
</P>
<P>
   Even as the winter solstice approaches, every day about 50 newly
emerged butterflies are making their first flights in Manhattan.
They are in an enclosed rain forest at the American Museum of
Natural History's exhibit ``The Butterfly Conservatory: Tropical
Butterflies Alive in Winter,'' continuing through Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Since the opening, Nov. 27, 300 to 500 butterflies have been
flying around a vivarium, a free-standing arched structure of
aluminum, fiberglass and transparent acrylic, where the temperature
is a constant 80 degrees. Visitors stroll through the 65-by-20-foot
habitat of leafy green plants with the recorded sounds of howler
monkeys, parakeets and other animals in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The average life span of a butterfly is two to three weeks, so
about 250 butterfly pupae are shipped to the museum each week from
butterfly farms in Florida and Costa Rica. Most butterflies will be
released in the vivarium after hatching, but some will hang in a
special case within the habitat so visitors can see them emerge
from the chrysalis stage. Butterfly reproduction, development,
evolution, defense mechanisms and conservation are explained on
displays.
</P>
<P>
   Entry to the exhibit requires a timed ticket, which includes
admission to the museum (usually a suggested donation of $8). The
tickets are $13, $9 for students and adults over 60, and $7 for
ages 2 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   The American Museum of Natural History, 79th Street and Central
Park West, opens daily, except Christmas, at 10 a.m. The last entry
time for the exhibition is at 4 p.m. Sunday to Thursday and 7 p.m.
Friday and Saturday. Information: (212) 769-5100 or www.amnh.org.
Tickets: (212) 769-5200.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Caribbean Island Is Deserted No More
</P>
<P>
   Parrot Cay, an islet in the Turks and Caicos that until recently
was graced only by white sand, mangroves and flamboyant birds, is
about get a luxury resort.
</P>
<P>
   The Parrot Cay Resort is to open Tuesday with 56 units and more
than three miles of beaches on 1,000 private acres rising from
turquoise waters just west of North Caicos. It is part of an
archipelago in the Caribbean and Atlantic with one of the world's
longest coral reefs, which guests can explore.
</P>
<P>
   The decor is mostly white on white and neutral colors in
two-story buildings with guest rooms and gardens, beachfront villas
with suites, and spacious beach houses with private plunge pools.
Four-poster beds are draped in mosquito netting, but all rooms are
also air-conditioned. Louvered white doors open onto private decks
or verandas. Inside, the floors are terra-cotta tile.
</P>
<P>
   Guests will have the use of mountain bikes, an air-conditioned
gym, two illuminated tennis courts and water sports equipment.
There's an 88-by-66-foot pool and a nature trail. An Asian-style
spa is scheduled to open in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   A resort was planned on Parrot Cay early this decade but never
built. The new owners, identified only as two couples with
interests in other hotels and restaurants, have hired Michel
Neutelings, former manager of the K Club on Barbuda, to run Parrot
Cay. The executive chef is Franck Aubert, who has worked at
restaurants in France, and the cuisine is international.
</P>
<P>
   Winter rates start at $540 for a double room, which includes
full breakfast and dinner, airport transfers by motor launch, and
nonmotorized water sports. It does not include a 19 percent
combined tax and service charge. For reservations, call Parrot Cay,
(649) 946-7788, fax (649) 946-7789, or Crown International, (800)
628-8929.
</P>
<P>
   _ FRANCES FRANK MARCUS &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Two Trips to Asia Bring Cookbooks to Life
</P>
<P>
   Serious fans of Asian cooking, including chefs in training, may
be interested in two small-group cuisine tours next year, one to
India and one to Vietnam and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Sahni, a cookbook author and teacher of Indian cooking,
will lead her annual tour to India from Feb. 5 to 21. Ms. Sahni
takes her 15 travelers into markets, bazaars and rice paddies, and
visits many of India's historic sights. She demonstrates regional
cooking and brings the participants to farm kitchens and spice
plantations for chances to observe other cooks, as well as
agricultural and horticultural customs.
</P>
<P>
   Delhi, Jaipur, Agra, Madras, Thekkady, Cochin, Madurai and
Bombay are on the itinerary. Deluxe or first-class hotels are used,
and ground transportation is by train or in large air-conditioned
buses.
</P>
<P>
   The price, $5,385 a person, double occupancy, includes most
meals, service charges, tips and flights within India. A seven-day
extension to Feb. 28 in eastern India and Nepal is available for
$2,585, double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Julie Sahni's Gourmet Tours, Post Office Box 023792,
Brooklyn, N.Y. 11202; (888) 548-9608 or (718) 625-3958.
</P>
<P>
   Absolute Asia, which has been organizing cuisine tours for one
or two people around the Pacific, now offers a 13-day group trip to
Vietnam and Hong Kong, with opportunities to see cooking
demonstrations and eat the results.
</P>
<P>
   The trip will leave the United States on April 16 and return May
1. Deluxe or best available hotels, including the Metropole in
Hanoi and the Regent Hong Kong, will be used, the company says.
Ground transport for the group, limited to 14, will be by bus, and
sometimes on local boats. There are some internal flights, for
example from Hanoi to Hue. Other cities to be visited are Hoi An,
Danang, Ho Chi Minh City (Saigon) and Hong Kong, as well as the
Mekong Delta.
</P>
<P>
   There will be visits to markets and back streets. One dinner
will be in a chef's home. Local English-speaking guides with
expertise in cooking will be provided.
</P>
<P>
   The cost for each person, double occupancy, is $5,500, including
all meals and air fare from New York on Cathy Pacific; from Los
Angeles, the price is $5,440.
</P>
<P>
   Absolute Asia is at 180 Varick St., New York, N.Y. 10014; (800)
736-8187. On the Web, information is available at
www.absoluteasia.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ BETSY WADE &QR;
