<HEADLINE>
2D DEMOCRATIC SITE-PANEL VISIT TO HUB SERIOUS BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Boston could still land the Democratic National
Convention for 2000; but the word on the street is it's LA's to
lose.
</P>
<P>
   If Los Angeles suffered a major earthquake or if Al Gore was so
worried about Bill Bradley's presidential bid that he decided to
keep the convention in the Northeast, insiders quip, Boston could
have a serious chance.
</P>
<P>
   Such cynicism is far from the Menino administration's message
for this week's visit by seven operatives of the Democratic
National Committee. But pragmatism may play a part in their
itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the June gathering of two dozen members of the site
committee, who got the royal treatment _ from the Reebok box at
Fenway to a private shopping tour at Filene's Basement _ this tour
will lack booty. There will be no hand-held computers bestowed at
the airport, Paul Revere bowls, or Rockport shoes sent in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   This gang will spend all of Thursday and Friday at the Parkman
House _ the mayor's entertainment domicile _ and the Fleet Center.
No Duck Tours or Kennedy Library cocktail parties will be thrown in
for respite as they were in June.
</P>
<P>
   That means Menino does not have to spend his political capital
to persuade business leaders to attend various events or seek
donations over and above the cost of lodging and meals for a
two-day stay.
</P>
<P>
   For the DNC it is time to play hardball in the home stretch,
using the head-to-head competition between LA, Boston, and Denver
to drive up the value of their packages.
</P>
<P>
   Boston has undoubtedly made an impressive showing in the
convention sweepstakes and has the telegenic backdrops and
cosmopolitan skills to throw the party, insiders agree. And Menino
has a secret weapon in his deputy chief of staff, Julie Burns,
whose former boss at the Dewey Square Group, Michael Whouley, is
expected to run Gore's campaign. Burns has strong White House
connections and was the second-in-command of the Chicago convention
for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Menino is widely thought to have surprised many people with
Boston's strong showing, especially given the usual reticence of
its business community and the city's lack of experience with big
conventions. But Massachusetts has been a cash cow for the
Democrats, as retiring DNC cochairman Steven Grossman personifies.
</P>
<P>
   Menino has pledges by corporate sponsors to raise more than $1
million, including $250,000 from both Fidelity Investments and Bank
Boston, to throw the big party.
</P>
<P>
   With the work of the site committee complete with the winnowing
of the list to the top three, now politics rules, observers said.
Philadelphia, once Boston's chief rival for the DNC convention,
ironically could help draw the Democrats to the Northeast since it
is hosting the GOP bash in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Hub's chief liability is that even combined with all of New
England, it cannot match California's 56 electorial votes and track
record as a presidential bellwether.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor is doing the responsible thing in putting forth the
effort to attract the Dems to Boston,'' said Peter Berlandi, a
major Republican fund-raiser. ``But it's a difficult decision for
the DNC to turn their backs on a large state like California.''
</P>
<P>
   John Sasso, a political strategist who handled Michael Dukakis's
1988 presidential bid, said, ``Boston passed the initial viability
tests with flying colors and now it's down to politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has a lot to say about it,'' he said. ``But I think we
have a chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
