<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-POPULARITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY'S YEAR OF LOWS TO END ON A HIGH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Perhaps it's symbolic of the disconnect in the
nation's capital that as temperatures hit another record for
unseasonable warmth, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton on Monday
unveiled the White House's Christmas theme of ``Winter
Wonderland.''
</P>
<P>
   As the impeachment move against her husband continues unabated
despite surveys showing that the public is opposed to it, Hillary
Clinton's year of lows is about to end _ with her at a high.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's public approval ratings recently topped 69
percent in the polls; she graced the December cover of Vogue in an
elegant Oscar de la Renta gown; and she served as a tireless
campaigner for Democrats who defied history by winning additional
seats in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever private anger remains from her public humiliation never
seems to leave the White House residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gives off an enormous, focused energy and, oddly enough, a
kind of radiant peace,'' gushed Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   As she stood in the State Dining Room, which is decorated with a
giant gingerbread castle guarded by a sugary Buddy the dog, she
thanked decorators for a ``wonderful partnership of people who come
in to help us kind of lend an air of fantasy and magic'' to the
White House. She spoke briefly to reporters to highlight the work
volunteers did on decorations but left before questions could turn
to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, she appeared on a pre-taped segment of ``The Rosie
O'Donnell Show,'' where she sang a duet with the star and hawked
her new book, ``Dear Socks, Dear Buddy: Kids' Letters to the First
Pets.'' And, much of her time remains devoted to saving America's
treasures that are in need of protection or refurbishment or
speaking on childrens' rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let her actions and her words speak for themselves,'' said
Marsha Berry, the first lady's spokeswoman, declining to provide an
interpretation of Hillary Clinton's current situation.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Bebitch Jeffe, a California commentator, noted Hillary
Clinton has become ``an object of fascination'' around the world.
Indeed, when President Clinton visited Japan recently a housewife
asked him if his wife and daughter had forgiven him and allowed as
to how she doubted she would have forgiven her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``The theme of the coverage was how well she has responded to
the problems of her husband and how well she is playing the role of
the wronged, but steadfast, wife,'' Jeffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffe added, ``There is a perception out there that `as Hillary
goes, so goes the nation,' and it's been that way since day one.
Had she not responded as she did and had she not rallied to him
then he would have been in graver danger than he is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffe attributed the first lady's continued embrace of her
husband following his acknowledgment of an affair with White House
intern Monica Lewinsky as a key reason the public has continued to
support the president.
</P>
<P>
   The political feelings toward the first lady have only lately
become warm. During the 1996 presidential campaign, Hillary Clinton
remained under wraps, traveling to the nation's smaller cities and
to groups where she would be welcomed. This year, she attended
hundreds of fund-raising events and was a relentless campaigner for
California Sen. Barbara Boxer and New York Senator-elect Charles
Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   Many people soured on the first lady during her handling of the
health care debacle in 1994 in which she led the effort to overhaul
the nation's medical care system. And, for much of independent
counsel Kenneth Starr's four-year investigation, the first lady has
been as much a target of his probe as the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rehabilitation of her reputation and image had been underway for
sometime but hastened dramatically in January once Starr's
investigation of Clinton's affair with Lewinsky became public.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, like the president, makes a public show of
sticking to a schedule of issues unrelated to the scandal and of
pushing her thoughts on rights for women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Last week at Georgetown University's Eleanor Roosevelt Lecture
Series on Children's Rights, the first lady spoke about the women
and children she has met on her many travels abroad where they
struggle daily for basic rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we talk about human rights and freedom, we have to ask
ourselves what does that mean to the 7 million children who still
die every year of malnutrition, what does it mean to the 585,000
women who still die of childbirth complications or the girls who
are fed last and fed least because they are not valued as much as
their brothers. What meaning can it have for a child who doesn't
have access to a school or is shut out of a school,'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   So in Washington this week, the bizarre heat wave is supposed to
break. Seasonal temperatures are supposed to return. The first
lady, also preparing for 180,000 tourists and guests to invade the
Christmas White House, will travel with the president on a historic
trip to Israel. The House Judiciary Committee debates impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And, there were reports that Hillary Rodham Clinton is being
considered as Time Magazine's Man of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
