<HEADER>
A7332 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LILLY-SEPRACOR-BOS &LR;      12-07 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILLY-SEPRACOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELI LILLI BUYS RIGHTS TO PROZAC SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sepracor Inc., the pharmaceutical company that gives old drugs
new life, said Monday it has sold development and marketing rights
for a successor drug to Prozac to the popular antidepressant's
originator, Eli Lilly &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is worth up to $90 million during its first three
years, Timothy J. Barberich, Sepracor's president and chief
executive said. With royalties he said could go as high as 15
percent, it could yield $250 million more in succeeding years for
the Marlborough, Mass. company.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also sets the stage for Lilly, for which Prozac
delivers $2.6 billion a year in sales, or about 30 percent of all
revenues, to keep a firm hold on the antidepressant market once
patents on its original drug expire, beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Without patent protection, other drug makers would be free to
make and market cheaper, generic versions, cutting into both
Lilly's market share and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Sepracor's version, called R-fluoxetine, is still in trials
being monitored by the US Food and Drug Administration. But it is
expected to have fewer side effects, as is the case with most of
the 18 other products Sepracor has been developing to replace
prescription drugs about to lose patent protection.
</P>
<P>
   Lilly, which will take over development of the product, said the
licensing agreement also provides a platform that could lead to
other depression therapies. ``R-fluoxetine is an exciting molecule
with a good chance of becoming an important new advance in treating
depression,'' Lilly's president and chief executive, Sidney Taurel,
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   For shareholders in the two companies, the news was mixed.
Lilly, traded on the New York Stock Exchange, closed at 86 7/8, up
3/4. But Sepracor, traded on Nasdaq, closed at 84 7/8, down 3 1/8,
after rising earlier in the day to an all-time high of 95 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Barberich speculated the market overanticipated the outcome of
the Lilly deal and the decline was only a correction. ``There was a
huge amount of expectation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was the latest in a series capitalizing on
Sepracor's skill in devising next-generation molecular
``near-twin'' or ``mirror'' versions of popular drugs for which
basic patents are due to expire over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   These versions offer an opportunity not only to produce a new
formula that will win a fresh patent, but also a chance to remove
or reduce side effects that may have held back usage.
</P>
<P>
   Other agreements announced in 1998 include one with
Schering-Plough Corp. for a successor to its Claritin
antihistamine, worth $1.7 billion a year to Schering, and another
with Johnson &AMP; Johnson for an improved version of Propulsid, a
heartburn drug that yields $1 billion annually in sales.
</P>
<P>
   On its own, Sepracor plans this winter to launch the US sale of
an asthma drug, Xopenex, as a successor to two other medications
that already have lost US patent protection.
</P>
<P>
   Together, these developments promise to deliver Sepracor its
first profits as soon as 2001, Barberich said. ``The Prozac deal
with Lilly is important because it can be another very large
royalty stream,'' he said in a telephone interview, ``but it
probably won't get large until about 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   Barberich said Sepracor always saw Lilly as the obvious buyer of
the R-fluoxetine technology. But Sepracor kept Lilly under
pressure, keeping the door open for a possible sale to another drug
maker, and developing its own plan to make and sell the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We began to develop the product ourselves to make it important
to Lilly that a timely agreement would be in their interest,''
Barberich said.
</P>
<P>
   Sepracor was founded in 1984 specifically to come up with mirror
versions of established drugs, using a principle that has been
known but underutilized for more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   But its work was largely ignored by the pharmaceutical industry
until recently. ``It was just a year ago that Lilly pooh-poohed
this technology,'' analyst David Saks of Gruntal &AMP; Co. said.
``Schering-Plough also pooh-poohed it. Now they (Sepracor) have
gone from nobody to the partner of choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Barberich said Separacor's market capitalization before the
Lilly deal topped $2.6 billion _ roughly five times the amount
investors have pumped into the company since its founding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
