</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-COUNSEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO REJECTS INVESTIGATION INTO CLINTON'S ROLE IN DNC ADS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno decided Monday not to
seek appointment of an independent counsel to investigate President
Clinton's role in so-called issue advertisements during his 1996
re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno notified a three-judge federal court late Monday that she
found ``no reasonable grounds'' to continue investigating
allegations that Clinton or Vice President Al Gore were involved in
planning the advertisements that were financed by the Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   In a 31-page report to the court that oversees independent
counsels, Reno wrote that she found ``clear and convincing
evidence'' that Clinton and Gore were unaware they might be
violating the law and had no criminal intent to circumvent campaign
finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Reno explained that Clinton and Gore had been assured by their
attorneys that the ad campaign complied with federal law. In
addition, lawyers for the Democratic Party screened the ads to be
sure they met legal requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's inquiry was triggered by draft versions of FEC staff
audits that concluded both Clinton and his 1996 Republican
opponent, Bob Dole, committed civil violations of federal spending
limits. Drafts of the audits were delivered to the Justice
Department in August. The audits, which were released two weeks
ago, recommended that Clinton repay the government $7 million and
Dole repay $17.7 million in misspent federal matching money.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC auditors argued that the issue ads, which both Clinton
and Dole personally helped coordinate, went too far and amounted to
advocating the candidate's election. If so, the advertising costs
should have fallen under campaign spending limits Clinton and Dole
agreed to when they accepted public campaign funds, the auditors
argued.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general noted that the bipartisan Federal Elections
Commission last week found that the legal standards for separating
candidates' campaign advertising from the ``issue ads'' financed by
political parties was ``fuzzy'' and ``hardly clear.'' In their
meeting Thursday, four of the six commissioners disagreed with the
auditors' recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, deputy press secretary Amy Weiss said
officials are ``gratified'' by Reno's decision. ``As we have said
all along, the president and the Clinton-Gore campaign complied
with the spirit and the letter of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision was the second in two weeks in which she ended a
90-day preliminary inquiry by declining to ask the court to appoint
an independent prosecutor to take a portion of the campaign finance
investigation her agency has run for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 24, Reno cited ``insubstantial'' evidence in rejecting a
call _ supported by some agency officials and the FBI _ for seeking
an independent counsel to investigate whether Gore lied about
telephone fund-raising calls from his office during the 1996
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, Reno was granted extra time by the three-judge
panel to determine whether an independent inquiry was needed into
allegations against former deputy White House chief of staff Harold
Ickes. The New York Democrat was accused of lying to federal
investigators about his efforts to lend administration support to
union leaders in a California labor dispute. The unions helped
finance Clinton-friendly advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's determination only ends our probe into whether issue
ads paid for by the Democratic National Committee violated federal
criminal statutes,'' Reno said. ``It does not end our vigorous
investigation into allegations of illegal activity surrounding the
1996 elections.''
</P>
<P>
   For two years, Reno has rebuffed Republican efforts to have her
turn over the Justice Department's campaign finance investigation
to an independent counsel. So far, the agency's 120-person campaign
finance task force has secured indictments against 14 people,
including key Democratic donors and fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision Monday drew another round of criticism from
Republicans, a chorus led by Rep. Dan Burton, an Indiana Republican
who chairs the House Government Reform Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it deplorable that she seems to have placed the
president above the law,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee Sen. Fred Thompson, chairman of a committee that
investigated Democratic fund-raising activities, said Reno's
decision ``is probably the final nail in the coffin of the
independent counsel law.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah Sen. Orrin Hatch, who chairs the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said he will continue to look for a way to revise the
attorney general's role in appointment of independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet Reno has sliced this broad scandal into narrower issues
so that common threads, patterns and facts are not considered when
weighing each decision whether to seek an independent counsel,''
Hatch said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
