<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7343 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BCS-ANALYSIS-COX     12-07 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BCS: A work in progress
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Bowl Championship Series might have come up a
little short on what many hoped it would deliver _ a clean,
uncluttered, uncontested game for the national title. But you have
to grant this much to the BCS: It was never boring.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing since the evolution of the facemask generated so much
debate in college football. Fans either liked it or they hated it,
and those who hated it, well, they hated it a lot. But nobody
ignored it or failed to offer an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   The final result after all the computer formulas were put
together is that the top two teams in the polls, Tennessee and
Florida State, will play for the national championship in the
Fiesta Bowl on Jan. 4.
</P>
<P>
   At 12-0, no one can contest Tennessee's right to be in Tempe.
The argument against Florida State (11-1) comes from fans of Ohio
State (10-1), Kansas State (11-1) and UCLA (10-1), but it is not
strong. The Seminoles' non-conference schedule was a killer with
No. 7 Florida (9-2), No. 8 Texas A&AMP;M (11-2), No. 24 Miami (8-3) and
Southern California (8-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly ended up with two tremendously deserving teams in
the championship game,'' said SEC commissioner Roy Kramer, the
coordinator of the BCS. ``There is no question in my mind that
Florida State and Tennessee deserve to be in the Fiesta Bowl, and
that's all we were trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic structure of the BCS, which calls for the national
championship game to rotate among four bowls _ Rose, Fiesta, Sugar,
Orange _ will not change for at least four years. ABC has a
four-year contract to televise all four bowls, with an option for
three years more. The next national championship game will be the
Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But the formula for the BCS rankings, which are used to
determine the two teams in the title game, could be in store for
some tweaking between now and next season, Kramer said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The current formula has four components: average ranking in the
two major polls, average ranking in three computer polls, strength
of schedule and record. The two teams with the lowest overall
ratings play in the national championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who followed the BCS seemed to have no problem with the
polls, the strength of schedule and the record components of the
formula. But the Seattle Times, New York Times and Jeff Sagarin
computer polls were difficult to understand or predict. The
computers sometimes differed widely in ranking teams, because of
differences in the formulas. To try to counteract those
differences, the BCS formula included a standard deviation
component, but it only served to confuse fans more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said that we will take a look at the formula at
the end of each season and, if there were adjustments that needed
to be made, we would study those areas and make the adjustments,''
Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers, including ESPN college football analyst Lee
Corso, are suggesting that a fifth component be added to the
formula, for margin of victory against Top 25 teams. That would
give a team credit for a strong performance against a nationally
ranked team but would not reward a blowout against a lesser
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been saying it all year,'' Corso said. ``There needs to
be some kind of recognition given when you beat a high quality team
and really play well. When there are a couple of teams that are
really tight, it could make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an idea would not receive universal acclaim. Some people
already are critical of the BCS rankings because they believe it
causes coaches to run up the score, thus causing bad blood in the
profession.
</P>
<P>
   Others advocate eliminating the automatic bids for conference
champions and argue that teams should have to play their way into
one of the four games based on their BCS rankings. Because Syracuse
(8-3), the Big East champion, was guaranteed a bid, other teams,
including Kansas State and Arizona (11-1), were left out.
</P>
<P>
   However, that change appears unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still believe that we should reward play in the regular
season, and teams that win conference championships deserve that
recognition,'' Kramer said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Saturday's losses by UCLA and Kansas State, the BCS
didn't have to face the prospect of leaving out of the Fiesta Bowl
an undefeated team ranked in the top four. But the debate over the
BCS and its selection formula kept college football in the
forefront all fall. With the NBA on strike and the NFL down to only
a few strong teams, college football was the hot topic on every
sports talk show in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, some coaches warned Sunday that fans might grow tired
of trying to figure out the complex formula that establishes the
postseason pecking order. In order to hold fans' attention, with so
many competing entertainment options, football might have to
consider a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think there should be a playoff at some point,''
Tennessee coach Phillip Fulmer said. ``This system has worked
itself out very well, and it is certainly better than what we had.
But I know what it's like to have a good team and get left out of
the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, a traditionalist, wonders
if all the complexity and debate that surrounded this season won't
move the game closer to a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things have turned out, you figure I have to like the
system we've got,'' Bowden said. ``But I've had the feeling the
past few weeks that we're getting closer to a playoff. I've never
been a proponent for a playoff, but it's getting to the point where
even I can see something with four teams, something small like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans who favor a Division I-A football playoff should not expect
it anytime soon. The television contracts aside, the powerful
President's Commission of the NCAA has gone on record in its
opposition to a Division I-A college football playoff. Opposition
from the presidents is enough to make sure that it won't happen.
Besides, Kramer argued, with a playoff, football would lose the
suspense and excitement of Saturday, when two of the nation's top
three teams _ UCLA and Kansas State _ lost and propelled Florida
State into the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you ever have a playoff, you lose that drama of the regular
season,'' Kramer said. ``This year, more than any I can remember,
we had a game every week that had some impact on the national
championship. In college football, the regular season is the
playoffs. It's one of the things that makes college football
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
