<HEADER>
A7344 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BCS-Q-AND-A-COX     12-07 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BCS Q and A
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: How is this Bowl Championship Series an improvement over the
Bowl Alliance we had last season? Wouldn't Tennessee and Florida
State have played for the national championship under that setup,
too?
</P>
<P>
   A: The No. 1 ranked Volunteers and No. 2 Seminoles would have
played in any Alliance bowl designated the national championship
game. In fact, the same result would have occurred five years ago,
too, before the BCS or the Bowl Alliance. Tennessee would have been
in the Sugar Bowl as the SEC champion, and Florida State would have
gone there as an at-large team.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS format would have made a difference this year if
Tennessee, UCLA and Kansas State all had finished undefeated, by
determining which two of the three should get into the title game.
</P>
<P>
   Also, unlike the Bowl Alliance, the BCS format includes the Rose
Bowl, which meant that the Pac-10 and Big Ten champions were
eligible for the title game instead of being committed to the Rose.
That change avoided last season's situation, in which No. 1
Michigan played in the Rose Bowl against Washington State and No. 2
Nebraska played in the Orange Bowl against Tennessee. When both
Michigan and Nebraska won, they shared the national title _
Michigan winning in the coaches' poll, Nebraska in the AP poll.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If Florida State beats Tennessee in the Fiesta Bowl, will the
Seminoles automatically be national champions?
</P>
<P>
   A: Florida State would automatically become No. 1 in the USA
Today/ESPN coaches poll, because the American Football Coaches
Association agreed earlier this year that the winner of the Fiesta
Bowl will be its national champion. The 70 writers and broadcasters
who vote in the Associated Press poll will cast their ballots after
the Fiesta Bowl, and they have the right to vote for any team.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After the Fiesta Bowl was set, how were the rest of the BCS
bowls filled out?
</P>
<P>
   A: The remaining BCS bowls _ the Rose, Orange and Sugar _ filled
their spots from the remaining conference champions (Big 12, Big
Ten, Big East and Pac-10) and two at-large teams.
</P>
<P>
   For the at-large berths, those bowls had the latitude to pick
the best game for their particular situation. Any team with nine
wins ranked higher in the BCS rating than the lowest-rated
conference winner _ in this case, Syracuse _ was eligible to be an
at-large team.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose automatically got Wisconsin and UCLA, the Big Ten and
Pac-10 champs. The Sugar then picked Ohio State (at-large), the
Orange took Florida (at-large), the Sugar took Texas A&AMP;M (Big 12
champ) and the Orange took Syracuse (Big East champ).
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about the other bowls?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most of the remaining bowls have commitments to pick teams
from certain conferences. The Peach Bowl, for example, has the No.
3 pick from the ACC and the No. 4 pick from the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Conferences differ in how those spots are filled. The ACC, for
example, goes strictly by order of finish, including head-to-head
competition to break ties. Florida State beat Georgia Tech, so it
got the BCS bid. Georgia Tech beat Virginia, so the Yellow Jackets
got the No. 2 spot in the Gator. Virginia beat N.C. State, so it
got the third spot.
</P>
<P>
   In the SEC, the No. 4 pick means just that _ not necessarily the
fourth best team in the conference, but rather the fourth choice of
eligible teams. The SEC works with its bowl partners to determine
the best matchups.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With all that in mind, why did the Outback Bowl , with the
No. 3 pick in the SEC, chose Kentucky over Georgia?
</P>
<P>
   A: Georgia went to the Outback Bowl last season, and Kentucky
has quarterback Tim Couch, who probably will be playing his last
college game. Kentucky has not been to a New Year's Day game since
the 1951 season, and Outback officials were worried whether Georgia
fans would travel after the disappointing loss to Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did 9-2 Florida end up in a BCS bowl, while one-loss
teams Kansas State and Arizona got left out?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Orange picked Florida over K-State and Arizona in order
to improve ticket sales, which have been down in recent years.
Florida has not been to the Orange Bowl since 1967, and chances for
a sellout are good. Bowls not hosting the national championship
game must do everything possible to sell out their games because of
the steep financial commitment _ $12 million per team _ for being
part of the BCS.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Once Kansas State missed on the BCS bowls, why did it fall
all the way to the Alamo Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   A: The logical place for Kansas State after losing in the Big 12
championship would have been the Cotton Bowl, which takes the No. 2
pick from that conference. But the Cotton took 8-3 Texas instead,
because the Longhorns have running back Ricky Williams, the likely
Heisman Trophy winner. The Holiday Bowl, which got the No. 3 pick
from the Big 12, was happy with the response it already had gotten
from Nebraska fans, and it also passed on Kansas State. The Alamo
had the No. 4 pick from the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And why was Tulane, the only other unbeaten team in Division
I, not included in the BCS?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tulane plays in Conference USA, one of the lowest-rated
leagues in Division I football. The Green Wave plays exciting
football, but the caliber of competition does not equal that of the
ACC, SEC, Big Ten and other top leagues. Tulane will play in the
Liberty Bowl, which gets the champion of Conference USA.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long is the current TV contract for the BCS, and can
anything be done to push football to a playoff before that contract
expires?
</P>
<P>
   A: The current TV contract between ABC and the BCS runs for four
years with an option for three more. Chances are very strong that
the contract will run its course. While fans and media are
clamoring for a playoff, the college presidents oppose the idea.
The general consensus is that Division I never will hold a 16-team
playoff, which is what they do in Division I-AA, II and III. A
possibility might be a four-team playoff after the bowls, but the
powers that be will fight it. Under the current system, the
conference commissioners control the revenue generated by the
bowls. Under an NCAA playoff, the NCAA would control the money.
</P>
<P>
   The only way the situation would change would be if a huge media
entity _ such as Disney or Turner _ offered the BCS a
multi-billion-dollar, multi-year deal dwarfing any other television
offer in the history of the game. That would get their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Q: After having to raise millions of dollars to be part of the
system, the bowls seem to be talking louder during this time of the
year. Has the BCS given the bowls more power over college football
than they should have?
</P>
<P>
   A: The bowls always had the right to take the two teams that
will help them stage the best possible game. A BCS bowl, for
example, must pay out $24 million to the two participating teams.
Of that total, only $8 million comes from television. The bowl must
raise the rest of that money through ticket sales and sponsorships.
Bowls were created not to rank the teams in the postseason but to
increase tourism and generate business during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
