</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons end year with not-so-certain schedule
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Not long ago, the Falcons appeared to have an easy
schedule down the stretch, something that might help in their
attempt to win just the second NFC West title in the team's 33-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   But the look of things has changed, and now road games at New
Orleans (6-7) and Detroit (5-8) don't look like cakewalks, and the
home finale against Miami (9-4) never did.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Falcons (11-2) will play at New Orleans, where the
Saints are 4-2 and coming off an impressive 22-3 win over Dallas.
New Orleans also is very much alive for the playoffs, currently
tied with Arizona (6-7) in a race for the third and final wild-card
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of looking to roll through an easy schedule, the Falcons
will try to get in a better frame of mind for the tougher
competition they'll see in the playoffs. The team has struggled
against three inferior teams in a row -- the Bears, Rams and Colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next three games are going to be key for us,'' coach Dan
Reeves said. ``New Orleans has their destiny in their own hands.
These three games should help us, because we're playing three good
teams and we'll see where we stack up.''
</P>
<P>
   Good adjustment
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons had problems early against the Colts when
Indianapolis went with three tight ends, largely because Atlanta
remained in a base defense that often left strongside linebacker
Henri Crockett covering Colts running back Marshall Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   Faulk, who leads the NFL with 76 receptions, faked Crockett for
an 11-yard TD reception to give Indianapolis a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Falcons went with four linebackers against that
set, adding reserve Craig Sauer and taking out cornerback Michael
Booker.
</P>
<P>
   It worked well.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts had 131 yards of offense and three touchdowns on their
first four possessions, as Peyton Manning completed 11-of-14 passes
for 120 yards, two interceptions and no interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he completed 8-of-13 passes for 39 yards, no
touchdowns and two interceptions. The Colts had just 113 yards and
no scores on their final six possessions.
</P>
<P>
   The quicker Sauer, who is better in pass coverage, also replaced
Crockett in the base defense. He finished with four tackles,
defended a pass, and had his first career interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crockett is very instinctive against the run,'' defensive
coordinator Rich Brooks said. ``When they started completing some
passes, we decided to bring Crockett to the sideline and try to
settle him down, and get Sauer some reps.''
</P>
<P>
   Crockett, probably a future middle linebacker, had five tackles,
and will return to the starting job on the strongside against the
Saints on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll probably find some playing time for Craig, but . . .
Henri did absolutely nothing whatsoever to lose his job,'' Reeves
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bad adjustments
</P>
<P>
   Brooks also decided to blitz Manning in the third quarter. It
worked, with the first play of the second half a perfect example.
Sauer and weakside linebacker Cornelius Bennett pressured Manning
into an ill-advised throw over the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Ray Buchanan got his sixth interception, tying
Minnesota's Jimmy Hitchcock for the NFC lead, to set up Chandler's
4-yard touchdown pass to Terance Mathis. That was good for a 28-21
lead that held up.
</P>
<P>
   But the negative side to the blitzing was that it allowed Faulk
room to run. He had 17 yards on eight carries in the first half. In
the third quarter he had 50 yards on nine carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against two or three tight ends, it's hard to blitz and remain
sound against the run, because you have gap-control problems'''
Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, before the Falcons went to their four-linebacker defense
against the three tight ends, Manning took advantage of a breakdown
in pass coverage on a 30-yard touchdown pass on a post pattern to
Torrance Small.
</P>
<P>
   Small was the only wide receiver on the play, and he lined up
wide to Atlanta's left. Buchanan was there, but his zone
responsibility was the left third of the field. On the other side
was Booker. But because the Colts had three tight ends, strong
safety William White rolled up for run support or to cover a tight
end on that side.
</P>
<P>
   When that happened, the deep middle third of the field became
Booker's responsibility. He was too shallow, though, and he and
free safety Eugene Robinson bit on Manning's play-action fake.
</P>
<P>
   Nice play
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's 3-yard scramble for a touchdown on the final play of
the first half tied the game at 21, but the Colts' third-down play
before it was just as important.
</P>
<P>
   Facing third-and-1 at their 29, Faulk swept left but was dropped
for a 3-yard loss by Atlanta defensive tackle Travis Hall to force
a punt.
</P>
<P>
   Nice numbers
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta and Dallas have allowed 239 points, the fewest in the
NFC and fourth-fewest in the NFL. Before the Packers (314 points)
played Monday night, Atlanta was fourth in the NFL in points scored
with 353.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing the Colts 244 yards, the Falcons have held three
consecutive opponents under 250 yards. Atlanta now ranks No. 7 in
total defense, allowing 297 yards per game.
</P>
<P>
   The pass defense, ranked last in the NFL three weeks ago, has
held three opponents in a row to 159 yards or fewer, and five of
the last six opponents to 207 or fewer. Atlanta is ranked No. 22
against the pass.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the game plan
</P>
<P>
   The game plan Sunday called for rookie Bob Hallen, the team's
second-round draft choice, to play every third possession in place
of left guard Calvin Collins. But that plan was scrapped by
offensive line coach Art Shell when the Falcons were facing a 14-0
deficit upon getting the ball for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves is big on sticking to plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Art (Monday) if you have a plan, you can't get involved
in the score,'' he said. ``If you have a plan, you've got to stick
with it. Bob Hallen is going to play next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Mathis' touchdown reception gave him eight for the season, and
41 in five seasons with the Falcons. He is tied with former running
back William Andrews for third on the all-time list, behind wide
receiver Andre Rison (56) and running back Gerald Riggs (48). . . .
While allowing five sacks, and having mixed success in the running
game for three quarters, the offensive line was erratic Sunday, but
Reeves singled out left tackle Bob Whitfield for a strong game. He
has played well for more than a month. . . . Middle linebacker
Jessie Tuggle, who has 42 tackles in the past five games, had a
team- and season-high 12 tackles Sunday. Tuggle trails Bennett
96-95 for the team lead in tackles. Bennett had eight tackles
Sunday. Tuggle has led the Falcons in tackles the past nine
seasons. . . . Reeves is only the second coach in NFL history to
lead three teams to the playoffs (Denver, N.Y. Giants, and
Atlanta), joining Chuck Knox (Rams, Bills and Seahawks).
</P>
<P>
   NEXT FOR FALCONS
</P>
<P>
   _ Who: New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   _ When: 1 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Superdome, New Orleans
</P>
<P>
   _ Records: Atlanta 11-2, New Orleans 6-7.
</P>
<P>
   _ Previous game: Oct. 18, Atlanta 31, New Orleans 23.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
