<HEADER>
A7346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-PRO-NOTES-COX     12-07 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PRO-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INSIDE PRO TENNIS: Sampras lacking on history homework
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pete Sampras should just say he doesn't want to play Davis Cup
and leave it at that. Instead, he made a couple of unforced errors
last week trying to justify his decision not to play this year or
to commit to the U.S. team for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' most persistent critic has been John McEnroe, whose 9-1
singles record in Davis Cup finals is the U.S. record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy for McEnroe to criticize,'' Sampras said, ``because
he was only playing 13, 14 events (per year). I'm playing 22
events, so it's a different ball game. I think these guys should
get their facts straight before they pop off.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon further review, it's Sampras who didn't do his homework. In
McEnroe's best six-year run (1979-84), he played 518 singles
matches, 19 more than Sampras has played during his current streak
of six consecutive years at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe's six-year singles record (456-62, .880) is superior to
Sampras' (415-84, .832). McEnroe was ranked No. 1 in four of those
years and captured seven Grand Slam singles titles while playing
for three winning U.S. Davis Cup teams.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has won 10 Grand Slam singles titles the past six years
but has played for just one U.S.-winning Davis Cup team (1995).
</P>
<P>
   Also worth noting is that McEnroe added to his workload by
winning seven Grand Slam doubles titles from 1979 to '84. Sampras
has only two pro doubles titles of any kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not knocking Pete, but just sit back for a minute and have
a look at the two records,'' said ITF president Brian Tobin, who
used former Aussie great Roy Emerson in the comparison. ``Pete has
11 Grand Slams and two Davis Cups (and didn't play in the final of
one of those). Emerson has (a record) 12 Grand Slams and eight
Davis Cup final wins on his record. So how would you compare the
two?''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras also argued that it's not feasible to be No. 1 today and
play Davis Cup full-time. ``If I play Davis Cup,'' he said, ``my
ranking goes to No. 4 or 5 in the world. You can't have
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   By that logic, though, Jonas Bjorkman could've been the tour's
best player last year. He finished No. 4 despite playing singles
and doubles in three rounds of Davis Cup for winning Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis Cup debate stirred again when last week's final, won
by Sweden over Italy in Milan, became the first played without a
player ranked in the world's top 30. The U.S. was without a top-25
player in its embarrassing 4-1 loss to Italy in the semifinals.
Last week, Tobin said the ITF, which runs Davis Cup, is considering
changes to ensure better Davis Cup participation. His ideas include
reducing early-round ties to a best-of-three-sets format, giving
previous year's finalists a first-round bye and awarding ATP Tour
points to players for their victories.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
