<SLUG> BC-AOL-TECHCENTER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL picks Smyrna site
 &HT;    By Kelly Simmons
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ America Online Inc. has chosen Atlanta suburb Smyrna
over two other sites in the Southeast as the location for its
computer operations center, a $500 million investment that could
mean 200 jobs for area residents, Cobb County Commission Chairman
Bill Byrne said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Although financial incentive agreements between the company and
the state have not been finalized, Byrne said he expected the deal
would be announced by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my viewpoint the deal is final,'' Byrne said. ``There will
be appropriate incentives from the state and county to bring it to
closure.''
</P>
<P>
   County officials said the AOL facility would be built in
Highlands Park, a 1,000-acre mixed-use development at I-285 and
South Cobb Parkway in Smyrna. Cobb County and the city of Smyrna
both have offered the company economic incentives, which could
include infrastructure improvements and waivers on construction
license fees.
</P>
<P>
   AOL also has asked the state to buy a site for the facility,
state budget director Tim Burgess said Monday. He said the state
was considering the request but had not made a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at AOL's Dulles, Va., headquarters declined to
comment. ``It's premature to discuss any future growth plans,''
spokeswoman Wendy Goldberg said. ``When we have something to
announce, we'll announce it.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL is the largest commercial online service in the United
States, with about 14 million subscribers and 20 million users. In
1998, the company reported $2.6 billion in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   State economic recruiters have shown restraint in the past in
offering financial incentives to woo businesses to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the state offers a standard package of tax incentives
and, sometimes, deals to add industry-specific research programs at
universities. But Georgia generally avoids providing free land or
deep tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Incentives offered by the state depend on the magnitude of the
project, but are viewed by Georgia as an investment that would give
a fairly prompt return, said Randy Cardoza, commissioner of the
Georgia Department of Industry, Trade and Tourism.
</P>
<P>
   While the project might not dramatically increase Atlanta's
status as a high-tech center, AOL is a well-respected company with
a hot brand name in a fast-growing industry, said William Todd,
president of the Georgia Research Alliance, a consortium of
government, industry and universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a continued validation of Atlanta, Ga., as a good place
to grow and develop a technology company,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   AOL would be the second high-tech company in recent years to
move into the Smyrna office park, said Smyrna Mayor Max Bacon. Two
years ago, IBM moved its call center _ one of only three in North
America _ from Atlanta to Highlands Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big coup for us,'' Bacon said. ``I hope this is a
done deal like everyone says.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Simmons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Matt Kempner, Peter Mantius and Kathey Pruitt
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
