u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.N.-550&AMP;ADD-NYT     12-07 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. ARMS INSPECTORS TO BEGIN SPOT CHECKS IN IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ U.N. arms inspectors are about to begin a week
of spot inspections at sites where Iraq is suspected of hiding
prohibited weapons, the head of the commission in charge of
disarming Iraq said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That work will start in the next few hours,'' the commission's
chief, Richard Butler, told reporters late Monday afternoon. He
said that his leading inspector in Iraq had told the Iraqi
government that a series of spot checks would take place with no
additional warning.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Iraq's foreign minister, Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf,
said in Baghdad that the government was about to begin test-firing
short-range missiles, which are permitted for defense. Iraq's
missile program has been a source of extreme concern to inspectors
because equipment used to make and test permitted arms could also
be used in banned systems. Iraq has balked at providing information
on missile parts and fuel supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's deputy prime minister, Tariq Aziz, is now in Moscow,
where he repeated Monday that Iraq has been cooperating fully.
After a meeting with Aziz, Russia's foreign minister, Igor Ivanov,
said at a news conference that he expected the sanctions on Iraq to
be lifted soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching the end of a long process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The phase of the inspectors' work now about to begin in Iraq,
however, is considered by diplomats here to be the most telling
test of Iraq's intentions of cooperating with the United Nations,
the prerequisite to any lifting of embargoes. Iraqi officials have
already branded as ``commandos'' the special teams that will
conduct the searches. In the past, sharp confrontations have
occurred when inspectors tried to enter sites not previously
designated and were therefore likely to catch the Iraqis off guard.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, executive chairman of the U.N. Special Commission, said
that no details surrounding the visits would be revealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are surprise inspections and that's how they must
remain,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These inspections are the last stage in a five-part process of
re-establishing the work of the international inspection system in
Iraq, which had been disrupted for several months and then cut off
entirely for two weeks in November by the government of Saddam
Hussein. The Iraqis backed down on Nov. 14 in the face of
threatened American and British military attacks.
</P>
<P>
   After the completion of this last round of inspections, led by
teams of experts from around the world now gathered in Iraq, Butler
will prepare a report on the level of Iraqi compliance, he said
Monday. Based on that report, expected in two weeks or less, the
Security Council is to decide whether Iraq has qualified for a
comprehensive review of all its obligations, a first step toward
lifting sanctions imposed in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Some Council members have begun to discuss among themselves what
should be done if Iraq does not qualify. ``What we're getting now
is not full cooperation,'' one of these diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   The Council is likely to be under pressure from Russia and
perhaps France to allow Iraq to postpone some unmet demands. Some
diplomats are looking for ways to prevent any delay, and to send
the Iraqis back for a better show of compliance before the Council
authorizes the review, though there are no calls for military
action from any quarter at this point.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At a breakfast with reporters Monday, Scott Ritter, the American
weapons specialist who resigned from the Special Commission in
August, saying that it was being gutted by U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and by the Clinton administration, said the danger of
the comprehensive review was that Iraq would succeed in whittling
down its responsibility for accounting to only a few crucial areas,
leaving many other potentially dangerous activities undisturbed.
</P>
<P>
   Butler on Monday outlined the five essential components of
inspection work requiring Iraqi cooperation: access to documents,
monitoring, interviews with knowledgeable officials, visits to
sites his commission has previously listed as requiring close
observation because they are places where weapons-related work may
take place, and, finally, disarmament inspections. Butler described
those as ``investigation of sites where prohibited weapons programs
may exist.'' The commission has the right to destroy any banned
item it finds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have restored our work in the first four areas,'' Butler
said. ``We are about to begin our work in the last of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler acknowledged that his inspectors had not gotten the
cooperation they requested on access to documents, but he refused
to begin ``slicing off'' parts of his overall report ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to make a judgment now on full cooperation,'' he
said. ``I told the Council that this is a holistic operation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 2006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
