<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7365 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH08-COX     12-07 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton's lawyers to argue against impeachment todayBy Rebecca
Carr and Bob Deans
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ White House lawyers open their defense of President
Clinton today before the House Judiciary Committee but appear to
have little chance to head off the panel's push for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   White House counsel Greg Craig and Charles Ruff are expected to
argue that Clinton's actions do not warrant impeachment and that
pursuing such a course would set a dangerous precedent.
</P>
<P>
   But Illinois Republican Henry Hyde, the chairman of the panel,
said Monday that it sets an equally dangerous precedent for the
White House to be so uncooperative in his panel's inquiry. The
White House and Democratic response to the impeachment inquiry has
been Shakespearean in nature, Hyde said, ``full of sound and fury,
signifying nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've made a compulsive, a compelling case'' for impeachment,
said Hyde, standing in front of four columns of boxes to underscore
the scope of the evidence that the committee has evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has 30 hours spread over today and Wednesday to
challenge that evidence. Under the plan, Craig will deliver a
factual and legal defense of the president, followed by three
panels of legal experts who will discuss a range of topics
including the impact of impeachment on the country and
prosecutorial misconduct. Ruff will conclude the White House
presentation on Wednesday afternoon, followed by questions from the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably absent from the witness panels is Clinton or any
member from the cast of characters involved in the Lewinsky affair.
There was growing speculation on Capitol Hill over whether the
president would deliver yet another public apology about his affair
with Lewinsky in an effort to head off the so-called impeachers.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum among the Republican-controlled House has been
growing in support of approving at least one article of impeachment
alleging that the president lied under oath. Two additional
articles are under consideration: obstruction of justice and abuse
of power.
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans for Clinton to address the committee or the
nation, but the White House would not rule out the possibility of
the president doing what he does best: taking his story directly to
the American public.
</P>
<P>
   But first the White House will try to present its case before
the Judiciary panel.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde plans to stay on schedule, saying his end of the year
deadline is in response to the ``mood of the country, which does
not want to spend its national life dwelling on impeachment
forever.'' If the committee refers the matter to the Senate, it
will take 67 senators to oust the president.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic committee members lambasted Hyde and the Republicans
on the committee for rushing the process and failing to give the
president the four days of testimony his counsel requested to
present a fair case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice has been denied,'' said Texas Democratic Rep. Sheila
Jackson Lee. ``The Republicans haven't even told us what the
allegations are.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have failed to win enough Republican support for a
proposed motion to censure the president and impose a financial
penalty. And Hyde said he had little appetite for such a measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not ruled out, but it's not a dead-band certainly
either,'' said Hyde, noting that he would not support such a
sanction because he does not believe it is constitutional. The
White House defense team was unsure if it would use all of the 30
hours it has been given over the next two days.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be two days of testimony, I don't know that it will
go to 30 hours,'' said Joe Lockhart, press secretary to the
president. ''They offered us the chance to go well into the night,
and we chose to use the daylight hours.''
</P>
<P>
   In a fresh sign of the political intensity of the issue,
outgoing Speaker Newt Gingrich will not likely preside over the
House vote on impeachment. There is some fear that his presence
could create the impression that the proceedings are a clash
between Gingrich and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has sent word to Rep. Bob Livingston, (R-La.), who is
in line to become speaker in January, that Livingston could take
the gavel.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses scheduled to testify before the House Judiciary
Committee today and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Today: 10 a.m. EST Introductory statement by White House Counsel
Gregory B. Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Panel No. 1, ``Historical Precedents and Constitutional
Standards'' _ Nicholas Katzenbach, former attorney general and
undersecretary of state; Bruce Ackerman, Sterling professor of law
and political science at Yale University; Sean Wilentz, the Dayton
Stockton professor of history and director of program and American
studies at Princeton University; Samuel H. Beer, Eaton professor of
the science of government emeritus at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   2 p.m. Panel No. 2, ``Abuse of Power'' _ Elizabeth Holtzman of
New York, Robert J. Drinan of Massachusetts and Wayne Owens of
Utah, former U.S. representatives who served on the Judiciary
Committee during the 1974 impeachment proceedings against President
Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   6 p.m. Panel No. 3, ``How to Evaluate the Evidence'' _ James
Hamilton, former assistant chief counsel in the Senate Watergate
Committee; Richard Ben-Veniste, former assistant special prosecutor
and chief of the Watergate Task Force and former minority chief
counsel to the Senate Whitewater Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday: 9:30 a.m. ``Prosecutorial Standards for Obstruction
of Justice and Perjury'' _ Thomas P. Sullivan, former U.S. attorney
for the Northern District of Illinois; Richard J. Davis, former
task force leader for the Watergate Special Prosecution Force;
Edward S. G. Dennis Jr., partner with Morgan, Lewis &AMP; Bockius in
Philadelphia; William W. Taylor III, former chair of the criminal
justice section of the American Bar Association; Ronald Noble,
associate professor of law at New York University Law School.
</P>
<P>
   1 p.m. White House counsel Charles Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
