<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7372 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-COLUMN08-COX     12-07 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Road incident drives home an unattractive generation gap
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of John Updike's early short stories was about a girl who
catches the eye of a boy working checkout at the A&AMP;P. The boy never
learns the girl's name, and she coolly floats off into the parking
lot with two friends, more an illusion than a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road from us is an A&AMP;P, and she was there last week in
the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   She shot me the bird, called me an SOB and 10 minutes later,
applying mascara through her rearview mirror, was telling me I
didn't look half-bad. Even at my age.
</P>
<P>
   We ended up shaking hands _ a reminder, it occurred to me later,
of a few dates I had when I was her age. You take what's offered,
and sometimes it's not much.
</P>
<P>
   But that was my generation, which had its own resentments and
insecurities. Her generation I don't expect to fathom.
</P>
<P>
   Did she say she was 18, or was it 20? One of the two. Some of us
also had cars when we were her age and drove just as recklessly.
But I don't recall (especially in a woman) the fury that contorts
the face into something grotesque. It could have been a pretty one,
and you got the idea that's what she cared about most. In the few
minutes we talked, she applied the mascara, then the lipstick, and
kept looking in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' she said, ``I have a bad case of road rage, OK? My
dispositions sometimes make me do things I can't control.''
</P>
<P>
   She had pulled in front of me on Roswell Road, exiting the BP
station and turning left. Checking the traffic coming from her
right, she was oblivious of anything coming from the other way.
</P>
<P>
   Which, at a little after 3 in the afternoon, was me. I braked
and gave her a quick beep that to me says, ``Watch yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when she whirled in the seat of her red Sidekick and
unloaded on me. Only an air bag could have been more instantaneous.
The middle finger and the face flew out the window, and the curse
came right behind.
</P>
<P>
   You can't execute something so coordinated without considerable
practice. It's hard to find it poignant when you're being cussed
out, but you felt sorry for her, however ugly she had made herself.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as chance would have it, her Sidekick shows up moments
later in the very parking lot I was driving to. It shows up in
front of the A&AMP;P, and she's in it.
</P>
<P>
   You can be too curious about certain people. ``Miss, why'd you
do that?'' I ask, walking up from behind. I say it in as gentle a
voice as I can manage.
</P>
<P>
   The seat swivels again, almost as fast as before, and she
doesn't seem surprised it's me. She even laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You flipped me off, man,'' she says, getting the mascara out
of a suede pouch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I what?'' I say. ``No, I didn't. I gave you a beep. I wasn't
even mad. I just wondered why you'd get so angry . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Now her buddy's coming out of the A&AMP;P. ``Hey,'' she calls out
the window of the Sidekick, ``didn't this guy flip me off? You saw
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The friend's laughing on cue, and she goes into exaggerated
mimicry. I thought of an umpire calling somebody out at home,
except he uses his thumb and not his middle finger. The friend hops
into the Sidekick, and the blonde at the wheel begins telling me
how she has some problems and didn't mean it. She looks healthy but
brittle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' she says as she caps the lipstick, ``maybe you didn't
flip me off, but I'm having a bad day and sometimes I lose it, you
know? But you probably wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Her clothes look expensive. The red Sidekick, I'm guessing, is
from Daddy. She looks pampered and as lost as James Dean ever did.
Neither the clothes nor the Sidekick has done a thing for her, and
the nitwit friend doesn't help either.
</P>
<P>
   But the shell was beginning to crack and I tell her it'll be OK,
still wondering how someone so young could be so angry about so
little. It comes out awkwardly. ``No big deal. Just be careful. I
was your age once too and . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, listen to this guy!'' she says to her friend. ``And how
old are you?''
</P>
<P>
   I tell her it doesn't matter, but older than I want to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't play games,'' she says. ``How old is that?''
</P>
<P>
   There's something raw about her voice that keeps it from being
charming, but I tell her she can wish me a happy birthday in a few
days. The truth is that I was imagining myself at her age, and
couldn't. What was harder still was imagining her at mine.
</P>
<P>
   She put the makeup aside and the Sidekick in gear, checked the
mirror one more time _ for traffic? _ and extended her hand. She
even managed a smile. You wanted to think someone sweet was in
there trying to get out.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
