<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0367 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER-COLUMN08-CO     12-07 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Boxer Robinson seen in lights and shadows
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A lot of us are suckers for this kind of story. It's
the male soap opera of choice: boxer rises from nothing to become
world champ; enjoys period of indulgent, rock-'em-sock-'em,
rock-star-style fame; dies broke and broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someday they're gonna write a blues song just for fighters,''
the late Sonny Liston, ex-con and heavyweight champ, mused before
expiring in his Las Vegas apartment from a heroin overdose. ``It'll
be for slow guitar, soft trumpet and a bell.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``Sugar Ray Robinson: The Bright Lights &AMP; Dark Shadows of
a Champion'' is a brilliant variation on this irresistibly tragic
theme. The hourlong documentary on the prizefighter many
aficionados consider the best ever is delivered at 10 tonight
E.S.T. with engrossing thoroughness.
</P>
<P>
   But the requisite troubling subtext that runs through it is more
troubling than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should remember Ray Robinson because he was the one perfect
fighter,'' an observer recalls tonight. ``He was an American
original, a genius at his art form, and there was a tragic dark
side, as there is to almost all geniuses.''
</P>
<P>
   We allow for flaws in our heroes _ expect them, even. But wife
beating and child neglect? Somehow being a great boxer _ even an
``artist,'' as filmmaker Woody Allen allows here _ doesn't quite
seem to balance things out.
</P>
<P>
   So by the end, when premature senility leaves Robison unable to
recognize family, we're left hugely conflicted _ in much the way
Robinson's ex-wife and kids are in their painfully profound
interviews. It's this unsettled (and unsettling) conclusion that
elevates this boxer-gone-batty tale into something far more
resonant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bright Lights &AMP; Dark Shadows'' hits all the biographical notes
needed for Liston's blues. Born into poverty in Georgia before his
mother moved the family to Detroit and then to New York, Walker
Smith became Ray Robinson when he subbed for an amateur boxer by
that name. ``Sugar'' was a natural: with size, speed and style
never seen before in a ring, Robinson became the sweetest
practitioner of the sweet science.
</P>
<P>
   His rise as welterweight and middleweight champ _ as well as
black pop icon in an era when attitude wasn't yet marketed by
sneaker companies _ is rendered with home-movie intimacy. Not only
do we see Robinson in his first pro fight, we see him dive into the
public pool where he met his first wife, who flirts for a camera.
It's as if we're witness to the seminal events that would form the
great contradiction Robinson became.
</P>
<P>
   Memorable images float by almost nonstop: Robinson driving his
famous pink Cadillac by his Harlem, N.Y., nightclub; the unmoving
body of Jimmy Doyle, who died after Robinson knocked him out
(Robinson dreamt he'd kill his opponent the night before the fight
and tried to cancel the bout); the entourage he took on a European
tour (including a jester); and film of his happily glazed visage
not long before he died, at age 68, in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's style in the ring, and his sad, addled end, give off
an eerie echo when a photo is shown of him being embraced by a
young Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the greatest fist fighter who ever lived,'' writer
Ralph Wiley says of Robinson. ``So if this is what happened to him,
this is what happens to them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds another: ``Muhammad Ali is an homage to Ray Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bright Lights &AMP; Dark Shadows'' wants to please two audiences:
connoisseurs of boxing and connoisseurs of tragedy. It succeeds for
both.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
