<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-X-MAS-HELPER08-COX     12-07 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-X-MAS-HELPER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Extra hands help manage holiday hustle, bustle
 &HT;    By Bette Harrison
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Santa's not the only one who needs elves during the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, most of us could use an elf or two. So, many of us
hire caterers, party planners and cleaning services to help out
with Christmas, Hanukkah, Kwanzaa and New Year's.
</P>
<P>
   Some people take that a step further, getting help for all
manner of holiday chores. If you know where to look, and can afford
it, you can pretty much buy your way out of all the unpleasant
details of the season.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you deplore addressing Christmas cards, you can call a
calligrapher. For example, Marion Moore of Abby's for All Occasions
in Dunwoody will address cards for you for $1 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting the house in order is no chore if you hire a
decorator. For $300 and up, floral designer Tony Whitlock will come
to your house and turn it into a winter wonderland, using existing
holiday decorations and new ones of your choosing.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Flournoy of Marietta(Ga.) has depended on Whitlock's
decorating expertise for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cut the Christmas trees. Then Tony comes in and saves my
life,'' says Flournoy, laughing. ``What's wonderful is, he gets it
all done in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always surprised (to learn) so many people hire a
professional. They think decorating is a family activity,''
Whitlock says. ``But my clients would rather spend their quality
family time dining out or shopping together.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For a fee, you can beat the crowds at the mall. Personal
shoppers, such as Michelle Penkava of Two Places at One Time, will
gladly pick up a gift for everyone on your list.
</P>
<P>
   All Penkava requires is your list and a brief description of
each recipient: Uncle Joe likes rock climbing; Aunt Sue loves to
needlepoint. She charges $25 an hour and will match the gifts to
your budget.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Too busy to wrap and mail the presents after your personal
shopper finds them? Wrap and mail stores will take the project from
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We literally have people come in straight from the mall,
shopping bags in hand, saying, `Please help me,' '' says C.J.
Daigle of Mail Boxes Etc. in Sandy Springs(Ga.).
</P>
<P>
   Daigle will take care of just about any gift. ``We've wrapped
and sent a 6-foot-tall teddy bear. And every year we do a few 5- to
7-foot Christmas trees, complete with ornaments.''
</P>
<P>
   Gift-wrapping fees range from $1 for a small gift to $15 for a
large one. Shipping costs vary widely by size and type of
transportation.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Still not ready for the holiday social whirl? Company's coming
and someone has to bathe Fluffy, your adorable if bedraggled
Persian cat.
</P>
<P>
   Best Friends Pet Resort and Salon in Alpharetta(Ga.) can put the
fluff back in Fluffy. It also can trim a standard poodle within an
inch of its life _ then dye it blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did that one year. The owner told us dyeing was big in
Europe. I kept thinking, `But this is Georgia,' '' Best Friends'
Maria Toro says with a laugh. Grooming prices vary, but a typical
big dog costs $25, a Persian cat $28.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is to banish the animals altogether. A one-night
stay at Pet Lodge Pet Resort in Alpharetta costs $16 for a dog and
$9 for a cat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Finally, someone must deal with the presents that come
``assembly required.'' Frustration Solvers, a Norcross(Ga.)
company, will send a crew to your home to build anything from
bicycles to barbecue grills.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Frye of southwest Atlanta bought a pool table for her
son to use when he was home from college for Thanksgiving break.
When it arrived in pieces, she called Frustration Solvers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great and they put it together in no time,'' she
says. ``My son loved it. If it weren't for them he'd have gone back
to college without playing a single game, and I would still be
trying to figure out where to put the first screw.''
</P>
<P>
   Jokes Jim Kovolsky, who owns Frustration Solvers with his
brother, Peter: ``We're the real elves.''
</P>
<P>
   Many companies and individuals can provide help during the
holidays. Here are contact numbers for the ones mentioned in this
article:
</P>
