A7376 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-TULANE-COACH-COX     12-07 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TULANE-COACH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA assistant to Tulane
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia's loss is Tulane's gain.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldogs assistant head football coach Chris Scelfo, a
35-year-old native of south Louisiana, was chosen Monday to replace
Tommy Bowden at Tulane. It will be the first head coaching position
for Scelfo, who also coached Georgia's offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like my life has gone a complete circle,'' Scelfo said.
''I am where I dreamed about as a kid, where I want to be for the
rest of my life. You've heard that said before, that's the last
time you'll hear it here.''
</P>
<P>
   Scelfo, regarded as one of the Bulldogs' top recruiters, will
take over the Green Wave program immediately. Instead of coaching
the No. 19 Bulldogs against No. 12 Virginia in the Peach Bowl,
Scelfo will spend New Year's Eve in Memphis, leading No. 10 Tulane
against Brigham Young in the Liberty Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ''My first order of business is to get our game plan for the
bowl in place and get ready for practice,'' Scelfo said. ''I'm glad
we have the game to work on. It'll give the players a chance to get
to know me.''
</P>
<P>
   Scelfo is the brother of Tulane tight ends coach and recruiting
coordinator Frank Scelfo. Another brother, Sam, is president of the
Green Wave booster club. Scelfo, Georgia's second-highest paid
assistant, at $110,000 annually, turned down head coaching jobs at
Southwest Louisiana and Northeast Louisiana earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Tulane athletics director Sandra Barbour's choice of Scelfo was
a surprise to the Green Wave players, who had endorsed offensive
coordinator Rich Rodriguez. Louisiana Tech coach Gary Crowton also
was considered, but he withdrew his name late Sunday night.
Rodriguez, also recommended by Bowden, said he was shocked by the
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a shock,'' Rodriguez said. ''I was so sure, I brought
in my green coat and tie this morning. This is so discouraging. I'm
disappointed. I thought I'd done all I could to prove myself. I'm
worried about the kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia coach Jim Donnan, who was in New York attending the
College Football Hall of Fame induction ceremonies, wasn't
available for comment. Donnan could shift defensive line coach Pat
Watson, who coached the offensive line for 26 years at various
stops, or tight ends coach Greg Adkins to the offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chris has been with me for every game I've coached as a head
coach and he's been very instrumental in the success we've enjoyed
together,'' Donnan said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting could be more of a concern for Donnan. Scelfo was the
Bulldogs' top recruiter the past two years, helping lure Louisiana
natives Terreal Bierra and Demetric Evans to Athens. This year,
Scelfo was recruiting offensive lineman Kevin Breedlove and wide
receiver Durrell Robinson, two of South Carolina's top prospects.
</P>
<P>
   THE CHRIS SCELFO FILE
</P>
<P>
   _ Hometown: Abbeville, La.
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: 35.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coaching experience: Assistant head coach/offensive line,
Georgia (1996-98); offensive coordinator/offensive line, Marshall
(1993-95); offensive line, Marshall (1990-92); receivers, Oklahoma
(1989); graduate assistant/offensive line, Oklahoma (1988);
assistant offensive line/tight ends, NE Louisiana (1986-87).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
