<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT CASE `COMPELLING,' HYDE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee has made ``a
compelling case'' for President Clinton's impeachment, the panel's
chairman said Monday, on the eve of a last-ditch effort by White
House lawyers to spare Clinton from the ignominy of joining Richard
M. Nixon as the only presidents this century to face formal
impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   With committee Republicans poised to approve as many as four
articles of impeachment later this week, the chairman,
Representative Henry J. Hyde, issued a final warning to the White
House ``to present some additional evidence that might demonstrate
the president's innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, Hyde said in a news conference on Capitol Hill,
Clinton's legal defense ``has been Shakespearean, `full of sound
and fury, signifying nothing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's legacy, if not his presidency, at stake, some of
his congressional supporters Monday began calling on him to abandon
his virtual silence on the matter and make a dramatic, 11th-hour
presentation, possibly a prime-time address to the nation, aimed at
reversing the apparent momentum toward his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat on the
Judiciary Committee, said he made the recommendation Monday night
during Clinton's annual Congressional Ball at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important for the president to speak directly to
the American people again before this is over,'' Meehan said. ``I
don't think the public recognizes the gravity of what the
Republicans on the Judiciary Committee are about to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's legal defense team announced plans Monday for
their marathon, 30-hour final presentation through Wednesday. The
White House will call a battery of 14 lawyers, scholars and former
Judiciary Committee members to support Clinton's premise that his
actions stemming from his sexual affair with Monica S. Lewinsky do
not meet the constitutional standards for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Notably absent from Clinton's front-line defense team will be
David E. Kendall, the president's private lawyer, who last month
angered some moderate Republicans who are undecided about Clinton's
impeachment by waging a highly confrontational assault on the
independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall's diminished role was seen as part of a shifting White
House strategy aimed more at conciliation than conflict. ``I can
assure you that the contrition is real and is there,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said when asked about Clinton's attitude and
his legal strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart also tried to ease the anger among many lawmakers about
Clinton's highly legalistic responses last month to 81 questions
from the Judiciary Committee asking him to admit aspects of the
allegations against him. ``We certainly regret those who took
offense by the way we answered them,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members in both parties said they do not expect
Clinton's lawyers to prevent the panel from approving impeachment
charges.
</P>
<P>
   But there are pivotal groups of 15 to 20 Republicans and five to
10 Democrats in the full House who are seen as undecided about
Clinton's fate, and several Democratic lawmakers said a public
address by Clinton could help sway them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is sense among the undecided members that the
president's conduct falls short of impeachable and is not
sufficiently serious to justify a prolonged, contentious trial in
the Senate,'' Meehan said. ``If the president focuses a message on
those issues and speaks in an appropriately contrite tone, it might
help his cause on the House floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Two polls released Monday showed overwhelming public opposition
to impeaching Clinton and broad support for an alternative such as
an official censure.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde said a Clinton address to the nation or the committee on
the Lewinsky matter ``certainly wouldn't hurt him, but it would
have to be much more comprehensive than anything we've heard thus
far.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House had no official response to the proposal,
although a source said the issue was ``under advisement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyde, standing amid stacks of boxes that he said once held
60,000 pages of grand-jury evidence on the Lewinsky matter,
confirmed that the committee is drafting at least three proposed
articles of impeachment related to perjury, obstruction of justice,
and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee Republicans said they expect the panel to
approve at least the charges of perjury and obstruction of justice.
They said an article charging Clinton with abuse of power probably
will pass the committee if it does not clash with the view of at
least two GOP members that Clinton did not abuse his office by
invoking executive privilege to prevent aides from testifying
before the grand jury. Starr had cited the executive privilege
claim as an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Hyde said, ``We've made a compelling case'' for
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In response, committee Democrats stepped up their attack on
Hyde's handling of the impeachment proceedings, arguing that
Republicans have designed a process that presumes Clinton's guilt,
at odds with the constitutional right of due process.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Hyde criticized the White House for failing to call a
single witness to directly rebut the allegations against Clinton,
the panel's Democrats said the GOP majority has relied solely on a
``hearsay'' account by Starr of the findings in his eight-month
investigation of the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's cheap press-conference theatrics notwithstanding,''
said Jim Jordan, the committee's Democratic spokesman, ``committee
Republicans have done nothing to assemble or present a case against
the president. These proceedings are not just absurd and chaotic,
they are an offense to the Constitution and a perversion of the
bedrock fundamental principles of the American legal system.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hyde appeared to soften his opposition to permitting
the Judiciary Committee to vote on an alternative short of
impeachment, such as a congressional censure.
</P>
<P>
   Several committee Democrats and a moderate Republican are
pushing censure plans, although House leaders have said they
believe lawmakers have a constitutional duty to vote on impeachment
before they consider any alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not for it,'' Hyde said of permitting the committee to
vote on a censure plan, ``but I'm not saying that I will go to the
death to resist it.''
</P>
<P>
   Committee aides said the panel's final votes on impeachment
charges, and a possible censure plan, are likely to occur on
Saturday, following opening statements Thursday night by committee
members and debate on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The White House special counsel, Gregory B. Craig, is expected
to launch the final presentation Tuesday by acknowledging misdeeds
by Clinton but asserting they are not impeachable. Several legal
specialists will follow, arguing that impeaching Clinton could harm
the presidency, the rule of law and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Then three former Democratic lawmakers who served on the
Judiciary Committee when it passed impeachment charges against
Nixon in 1974 will contrast Watergate and the Lewinsky scandal: the
Rev. Robert J. Drinan, formerly of Newton; Elizabeth Holtzman of
New York, and Wayne Owens of Utah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
