<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA DROPS OUT OF MICROSOFT SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The attorney general of South Carolina withdrew
Monday from the multi-state lawsuit against Microsoft, saying he
has become persuaded the government's antitrust case will not help
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can no longer justify our continued involvement, or the
expenditure of state resources, on a trial that has been made moot
by the actions of the competitive marketplace,'' said South
Carolina Attorney General Charlie Condon, referring to America
Online's recent acquisition of Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last year, it has become clear that the government's
case has been about Internet competitors, not about consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's announcement came on the same day that Microsoft
chairman Bill Gates held an unusual video news conference to blast
the Justice Department for attempting to destroy his company.
</P>
<P>
   The withdrawal of South Carolina is an important symbolic
victory for Microsoft, which for the past seven weeks has been on
the defensive in a courtroom featuring a parade of anti-Microsoft
witnesses and the repeated playing of the unflattering videotape of
the deposition of Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased that Attorney General Condon has made this
decision and we certainly hope that other plaintiff states will
pause and reconsider the wisdom of pursuing this litigation,'' said
Microsoft general counsel Bill Neukom. He said his company is
encouraging other states, especially those with newly elected
attorneys general, to drop out of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we've seen what a feeble case it appears to be and
how long it appears it will run in trial ... I would anticipate
that there will be some serious consideration by some other states
as to whether it's in the best interests of the constituents of
those state attorneys general to continue to participate in this
lawsuit which we think is going nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   But state and government officials said the withdrawal of South
Carolina will have no impact on the case against Microsoft, which
is still supported by the federal government, 19 states and the
District of Columbia. None of the other states said they intend to
follow South Carolina's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a non-event,'' said Marc Wurzel, spokesman for New
York Attorney General Dennis Vacco. New York is the lead state in
the case. ``It's an inconsequential development in what is one of
the most important antitrust trials of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, which has generally seemed to shrug off the
government's litigation against Microsoft, apparently did not view
South Carolina's step as a non-event. Investors sent Microsoft's
stock soaring to an all-time high of $133.5625 Monday, up $6.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft was able to gloat about the South Carolina
announcement at a previously scheduled news conference the company
had called to take advantage of a day when the trial was not in
session. At the news conference, the company attempted to persuade
reporters that the government's case is weak and getting weaker.
</P>
<P>
   Gates spoke briefly to reporters at the news conference by
satellite from Redmond, Wash., in his most direct attempt yet to
counter the image of him seen in the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks Gates has increasingly been visible, allowing
himself to be interviewed by talk show personalities such as Martha
Stewart. But Monday was the first time recently he has subjected
himself to the more adversarial questioning by reporters covering
the antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   Gates took three questions from reporters, all about his
performance at his deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The Bill Gates reporters saw Monday was carefully groomed and
positioned before a homey studio backdrop complete with
mantlepiece, bookcase and potted plant. Although Gates appeared to
be struggling with a cold, he smiled, took questions calmly even
when a reporter asked whether he lacked the ``intestinal
fortitude'' to testify, and kept mannerisms to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   The performance contrasted sharply with the deposition, where
Gates is dwarfed in an oversized chair, looks isolated against a
blank, dark wall, and rocks back and forth while looking down and
pausing at great length before giving unhelpful answers to
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Gates defended his deposition performance by saying that the
government misled him by telling him the videotape would not be
shown in court, and said government attorney David Boies ``had made
it clear ... that he is really out to destroy Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I answered truthfully every single question that was put
forward to me,'' he said. But Gates said that had he known how the
tape would be used, ``Would I have smiled a little bit, would I
have made sure that the camera work in this thing was decent? ...
Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates said he is willing to testify at the trial, but that
Microsoft has chosen to call 12 witnesses with more direct
knowledge of the issues being litigated. He said if the government
wants to call him as a witness, he will appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they choose to call me as a witness, that's fine,'' he
said. ``I will be there and address any issue that they ask for,
and you'll see that in that courtroom setting, the judge is
probably interested in getting explanations for what really went
on, instead of badgering to just try and get a `yes' or `no' to a
question that the questioner knows is very ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Microsoft filed a motion asking for permission to
subpoena documents and conduct interviews concerning America
Online's acquisition of Netscape and alliance with Sun Microsystems
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to what the government lawyers say, I'd say AOL
paying billions of dollars for Netscape's browser business shows
that the marketplace is working just fine,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department shrugged off Gates's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's latest press statements are another public
relations effort to distract attention from the overwhelming
evidence introduced in court showing that Microsoft has illegally
used its market dominance to block competition from innovative
technologies that threaten its operating system technology,'' said
Justice Department spokeswoman Gina Talamona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
