<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE YOURSELF A GOTTI GATTI CHRISTMAS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   A romp through the www.gotti.com &LR;   &LR; Web site is enough to raise
the spirits of gift-givers everywhere, especially the opening-page
offer of Free Gotti T-Shirts.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out they're $19.95. The ``free'' refers to joining the
campaign to get convicted mobster  &UR; John Gotti &LR;  out of the federal
hoosegow.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Very much elsewhere in the wide world of Web,
www.usmint.gov &LR;   &LR; is soliciting votes and suggestions for the image
of  &UR; Sacajawea &LR;  that will adorn a gold-colored dollar coin to be
issued in 2000. No one knows exactly what the 16-year-old Shoshone
who accompanied Lewis and Clark to the Pacific looked like, but
mint officials say the offerings ``are realistic depictions of
Native American women.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep.  &UR; Michael Castle &LR; , R-Del., who chairs the House monetary
subcommittee, says he's still hoping that Treasury Secretary
 &UR; Robert Rubin &LR;  will ditches &LR;  Sacajawea and opts &LR;  instead for the
Statue of Liberty, which he thinks is more familiar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Dan Tobin &LR;  forwards an excerpt from a 1943 issue of Time
magazine: ``In San Francisco, a harried bus driver, cracking under
the wartime rush of trade, refused to let his passengers off till
they said, `Please.' Inflated with success, he then tried to make
them say, `Pretty please.' They called a policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Signage: The First Lutheran Good Shepherd Church in Sacramento
is advertising on its outdoor board: ``The X-Mas Files _ A Special
Series.'' What's more, John Flather says a youth group in
Kensington has put up a streetside sign advertising ``Reafs for
Sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally,  &UR; Doug Farson &LR;  saw a billboard for Winstons in Corona
that made lighting up a political issue: ``Even Communists Are
Allowed to Smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In England, the maker of Heineken beer has taken down 5,800
posters that pictured a Nativity scene with the words ``It's a
girl. How Refreshing. How Heineken.'' A spokesman for the brewers &LR; 
told the Spectator that the ad ``was in no way a deliberate
advertising strategy to be shocking and gain publicity. We were
surprised and alarmed that the poster caused offense.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Spawning Start-Ups at San Diego State,'' a story in the
latest issue of Inc., might provide useful guidance for college
applicants looking for a party school.
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at Kansas State University have discovered that
garlic, clove, cinnamon, oregano and sage (in order of potency)
help kill off bacteria that cause food poisoning. According to
Health magazine, moderate amounts in food work to prevent food from
making one sick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE MERGERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Some inspiring imaginary mergers from  &UR; George &LR;  and  &UR; Brendan &LR; 
 &UR; Ward &LR; , tycoons of industry:
</P>
<P>
   _ New York Life Insurance, Pacific Dental and Blue Shield: NYPD
Blue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Seagrams, Ms. magazine, Leica, Old Crow and Early Times: Sea
Ms. Leica Old Times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Safeway and Saks Fifth Avenue: Safe Saks.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. A real-life merger: When  &UR; Alan Bodine &LR;  bought a pair of
Vasque hiking boots recently, he learned that Red Wing shoes had
bought Vasque. ``Could I have been duped in my purchase,'' he
writes, ``by agents of a Vasque-Red Wing conspiracy?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CALL THE WIND MARIAH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in Self magazine,  &UR; Mariah Carey &LR;  opened her
heart and her subconscious, revealing the contents of a dream she
deemed significant:
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a spa in Sonoma County, getting a massage, because
sometimes that helps my insomnia, and I fell asleep. In my dream, I
told the masseuse that I had to go to the bathroom and I'd be right
back. She asked me, `Do you want me to leave the light on for you?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `No. You can leave the lights off. Because being
in the dark equalizes us all.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Shannen Doherty &LR;  told Twist magazine of a recurring
nightmare that ``I swallowed my remote control. And it's a big
remote control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a pound pointer named Annie Oakley, close enough to a
purebred German shorthair that someone felt it necessary to dock
her tail. Though Oakley doesn't miss her appendage, I do, but I try
to romanticize the loss.''
</P>
<P>
   _ A San Francisco dog owner finds poetry in that which wags no
more, in the Berkeley Bark.
</P>
</TEXT>
