<HEADER>
A7395 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-ELECTION-HN     12-07 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-ELECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAVEZ MOVES FAST TO SHORE UP SUPPORT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN OTIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Just one day after Hugo Chavez was elected
president of Venezuela on a platform of radical change, the former
coup leader worked to soften his militant image and to win over his
fiercest critics.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez was lauded by business leaders and former U.S. President
Jimmy Carter on Monday following a lengthy, election-night press
conference in which Venezuela's new leader mapped out a
surprisingly moderate government program.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old cashiered army lieutenant colonel, who has no
previous governing experience, assured foreign investors that they
are welcome. He endorsed the notion of government spending cuts,
while promising to root out corruption and pledging to overhaul the
nation's judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Redmond, president of the Venezuelan-American Chamber of
Commerce and a vocal Chavez critic, seemed impressed. Chavez
``seemed to have a good grasp of a lot of issues,'' Redmond said.
``It's amazing. This guy has really polished himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gillespie, a former U.S. diplomat serving as an election
observer, said, ``On balance, he said a lot of positive things that
bode well for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's election, Chavez easily defeated his chief rival,
former state governor Henrique Salas Romer, by a margin of 56
percent to 39 percent. He will be sworn in Feb. 2 for a five-year
term.
</P>
<P>
   Before the election, one of the most divisive in Venezuelan
history, Chavez had been portrayed by the Venezuelan establishment
as a red menace intent on imposing an authoritarian regime. Most of
the country's entrepreneurs backed Salas Romer, a Yale-educated
businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Despite predictions of violence and vote fraud, the election was
relatively uneventful and was capped by a huge street party for
Chavez on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, Chavez' critics seemed to be coming to terms with his
victory, while Carter, who was in the country heading up a team of
international election observers, gave the former paratrooper a
warm endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said that Chavez' landslide win removed the ``stigma'' of
his role in a failed military uprising Feb. 4, 1992. Carter added
that he had ``no doubt'' that Chavez would be granted a visa to
enter the United States and that relations between the two nations
would be cordial. Oil-rich Venezuela, a nation of 23 million, is
the No. 1 supplier of crude oil to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez' earlier request for a visa was rejected by the State
Department due to his involvement in the coup, which nearly toppled
an elected Venezuelan government and left dozens of soldiers and
civilians dead.
</P>
<P>
   After spending two years and two months in prison, Chavez
received a presidential pardon. He went on to form a populist
political party that won widespread support from Venezuela's poor
majority, paving the the way for his victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not in favor of coups,'' Carter said, ``but I think it's
accurate to point out that the president-elect was never convicted
of a crime. He was completely pardoned.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The stigma has been removed,'' Carter said, ``not only by
those facts ... but also by the endorsement of the people of his
country yesterday in one of the most overwhelmingly free
expressions of opinion that I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez' victory marked the end of 40 years of dominance by
Venezuela's two largest political parties, and some political
observers speculated that that the corruption-tainted, old-style
parties across Latin America may be on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running scared. We have sweaty palms,'' said former
Bolivian President Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada, whose Nationalist
Revolutionary Movement party was defeated in national elections
last year. ``Venezuela is something that will have a great
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   After a campaign in which Chavez portrayed himself as a man of
the poor and promised to ``fry the heads'' of corrupt politicians,
he toned down his rhetoric as election day approached. In fact, his
first message as president-elect was aimed at international
investors.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview Sunday night, Chavez ``guaranteed''
foreigners that their investment were safe in Venezuela. Later,
during a press conference, he announced plans to restructure
service payments on Venezuela's $55 billion foreign debt, and to
impose tighter controls over the semi-autonomous state-run oil
company.
</P>
<P>
   He also ruled out imposing monetary exchange controls, pledged
to cut government spending and to reduce the number of ministries
from 26 to 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The legacy of a state that is accustomed to spend and spend
and spend in the name of (political) party patronage _ that's
over,'' Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   In a nod to his working-class supporters, Chavez promised more
public housing, negotiations for wage increases and social programs
for street children.
</P>
<P>
   At times during his rambling, 90-minute press conference, Chavez
veered away from political issues to discuss sports, psychology and
nutrition. He made reference to the ``inner child'' of Venezuelans
and complained that the national diet contains too much
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   All along, Chavez has said he has been the victim of a smear
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my adversaries try to use half-truths and lies to hurt
me in the election,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They created an image of Hugo Chavez that is not me, that I
was going to fry heads and expropriate everyone, so I understand
there is a lot of worry in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Soto, the executive director of the National Investment
Council in Caracas, called Chavez' macro-economic comments ``an
important message'' but cautioned that ``the world responds to
concrete actions.``
</P>
<P>
   But Michael May, a South America expert at the Center for
Strategic and International Studies in Washington, predicted that,
given the size of his victory, Chavez has won some breathing space
and that even his detractors now seem willing to give him a chance
to govern.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, the chamber president, said, ``He has a lot of people
on his side, so the benefit of the doubt is in order.''
</P>
<P>
   But there were also warnings that Chavez must stick to the rules
of democracy. He has promised to rewrite the constitution, starting
early next year, and some analysts fear that the move could lead
the temporary closing of the courts and congress.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Carter warned against against any such move.
``There would be a negative reaction,'' he said, ``if
non-democratic principles were used to implement changes in the
constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
