<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-CONSENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER GIVES ECONOMY THAT OLD CONSENSUS TRY  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BONN, Germany _ Consensus was long the backbone of Germany's
postwar economic boom, and Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder set out on
Monday to prove that it could form the basis of a fight against the
country's cripplingly high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 4 million Germans jobless, or 10.6 percent of the
work force, Schroeder summoned labor unions, employers and several
members of his Cabinet to a first meeting of a much-vaunted
``alliance for jobs.'' But the alliance looked tentative at best,
and its initial achievement little more than a list of good
intentions.
</P>
<P>
   As global competition has increased, while wage costs remained
high here, the economy _ based on both the free market and a high
level of social protection _ has frayed. The rich have grown
richer, but unemployment has risen to levels not seen since 1945.
Schroeder, who took office in October, will be judged largely on
his ability to get people back to work.
</P>
<P>
   His chosen method _ elaborate negotiations among unions,
employers and politicians _ amounts to an attempt to demonstrate
that the German model that has had great difficulty responding to
the challenges of the 1990s can be revived.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction of a common European currency, the euro,
now imminent, Schroeder also wants to show that Europe's largest
economy can generate employment while preserving a high level of
social benefits and avoiding the wholesale deregulation that has
helped spur rapid job creation in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The excellent atmosphere at the talks makes me optimistic,''
Schroeder said after the meeting. ``This alliance is necessary to
meeting the challenges of an increasingly globalized economy and
will prove anything but a flash in the pan.''
</P>
<P>
   A statement said the parties, who will meet again next Feb. 25,
had agreed to strive to lower labor costs, to reform the broad but
costly social welfare system, to create more workplace flexibility,
to provide better access to venture capital for small companies and
possibly to lower the retirement age, now 65.
</P>
<P>
   All these measures have already been talked about for several
years in Germany _ former Chancellor Helmut Kohl started a similar
round of meetings in 1996 that led nowhere _ and it was not
immediately clear why there should be more success this time. In
practice, reform of pension, health and unemployment systems, the
cost of which add more than 40 percent to wage bills, has met
strong resistance from unions.
</P>
<P>
   The only concrete steps agreed upon on Monday were to move up
tax reforms for small and medium-sized companies from 2002 to 2000
and to create 100,000 training positions for young people. How
these positions would be found, and how they would be paid for, was
not specified.
</P>
<P>
   A real test of the will to compromise is likely to come in the
next few weeks as employers and unions confront each other over
wages. IG Metall, the union that has more than 2.7 million members
in the auto and engineering industries, has called for a 6.5
percent pay increase.
</P>
</TEXT>
