<SLUG> BC-SCOTTISH-PACIFICORP-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO UTILITY DEALS COULD SPEED CONSOLIDATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Utah, Wyo., Wash., Idaho, Calif., Mass.)  (lb) 
 By AGIS SALPUKAS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two precedent-setting merger deals were announced Monday in the
U.S. electric power industry that could greatly accelerate the
consolidation among utilities. The deals are certain to receive
careful regulatory scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed takeover of Pacificorp, a major utility in the
Northwest, by Scottish Power PLC, one of the largest utilities in
Britain, would mark the first purchase of a major U.S. utility by a
foreign company. Scottish Power has slashed thousands of jobs at
its own operations, and analysts expect it to make cuts at
Pacificorp.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger of BEC Energy, the parent of Boston Edison,
which serves the Boston area, and Commonwealth Energy System, which
is based in Cambridge, Mass., would be the first between adjacent
utilities that only transmit and distribute power.
</P>
<P>
   How the combinations would affect consumers is unclear. Some
analysts, economists and leaders of consumer groups said Monday,
however, that the combinations could lead to strong new competitors
that would become more efficient and eventually be able to pass
more savings on to consumers and higher returns to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Power said Monday that it was acquiring Pacificorp in a
stock swap worth $7.9 billion based on Scottish Power's closing
price last Friday, when its shares cost 675 pence in London.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would pay 2.32 Scottish Power shares for
each Pacificorp share, worth about $25.85 at Friday's closing price
and well above its $20.75 closing price Friday. But Scottish
Power's shares fell 66 pence Monday to 609 pence and Pacificorp
shares ended down 18.75 cents at $20.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed merger of BEC Energy and Commonwealth Energy
System, the companies will form a new holding company in a
transaction valued at $950 million.
</P>
<P>
   BEC shareholders can choose to get one share of Commonwealth
Energy stock, or $44.10 in cash, for each share they own.
Commonwealth shareholders can choose either $44.10 in cash or 1.05
shares of the new company for each share they now own.
</P>
<P>
   BEC stock closed Monday at $41, down $1, and shares of
Commonwealth Energy closed at $39.875, up $2.0625.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rubin, an analyst with Bear, Stearns, said the Scottish
Power acquisition of Pacificorp would face ``an arduous regulatory
process.'' If it goes through, he said, other large European
utilities such as Powergen PLC of Britain and Tractebel of Belgium
would likely pursue acquisitions in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difficult part is that it would be precedent-setting,''
said Robert K. Johnson, the executive director of the Electric
Consumers Alliance, an umbrella group representing 260 consumer
groups around the country. ``Who owns essential infrastructure in
the United States is an acute issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Both transactions will lead to reductions in duplicate staff and
offices.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Robinson, the chief executive of Scottish Power, which has
cut its staff in the last four years from 10,000 to 5,000, said
that reductions in the staff of Pacificorp, based in Portland,
Ore., would be a key component of improving efficiency.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pacificorp, with 1.4 million customers in Oregon, Utah, Wyoming,
Washington, Idaho and California, has one of the largest
transmission systems in the nation and owns coal-fired and
geothermal plants that can produce 8,300 megawatts of power. It is
one of the biggest sellers of wholesale power in the nation.
Earnings have been reduced recently because of losses in trading in
the wholesale market where prices have been very volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish Power was advised by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter and
Pacificorp was advised by Salomon Smith Barney International.
</P>
<P>
   Under a deregulation plan implemented by Massachusetts, BEC
Energy and Commonwealth Energy have had to sell their generating
plants and become companies that only transmit power and service
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Gupta, an economist with the Natural Resources Defense
Council, an environmental group, said that while the merger will
lead to further cost savings and a more efficient system, the
benefit to customers will depend on how regulators oversee the
utilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
