<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENSE PROBABLY WILL MAKE LITTLE DIFFERENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and JOHN C. HENRY 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawyers for President Clinton will present his
defense to the House Judiciary Committee on Tuesday, but their
arguments and testimony from 14 scheduled witnesses over the next
two days is not likely to head off Republican efforts to impeach
him for his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., said Monday that
independent counsel Kenneth Starr has already built ``a compelling
case'' against Clinton alleging perjury, obstruction of justice and
abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said he is still open to hearing evidence from the
Clinton camp that will repudiate ``the facts'' presented thus far,
Hyde made it clear the committee will likely vote out at least one
article of impeachment by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman also said the Democrats had failed ``to contradict
in any way whatsoever`` the evidence of impeachable offenses
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House and the Democratic committee members' response
to the (Starr) referral has been Shakespearian _ full of sound and
fury signifying nothing,'' Hyde added.
</P>
<P>
   He met with reporters as the White House released a letter to
the committee outlining its plans to call 14 witnesses in an
attempt to persuade the panel of 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats
not to take action that could lead to the president's removal from
office.
</P>
<P>
   The witness list was released Monday along with a softer line
from the White House about cooperating with the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dropping witnesses who would have continued to
attack the credibility of Starr's investigation, presidential
spokesman Joe Lockhart sought to placate Republican lawmakers
angered by Clinton's legalistic answers to 81 questions posed by
Hyde to the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We answered those questions in good faith,'' Lockhart said.
``We certainly regret those who took offense by the way we answered
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton's team would address Starr's report ``but
mostly in the context of exculpatory evidence that was not used in
the referral and some issues where there are some questions of
interpretation of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Clinton witnesses are three former members of the
House Judiciary Committee that voted to impeach President Nixon:
the Rev. Robert Drinan, a Roman Catholic priest and former
Massachusetts Democrat; Elizabeth Holtzman, D-N.Y.; and Wayne
Owens, D-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Also scheduled to testify are former Attorney General Nicholas
Katzenbach, Yale law professor Bruce Ackerman, Princeton history
professor Sean Wilentz and Harvard government professor Samuel H.
Beer, who will discuss the ``historical precedents and
constitutional standards'' for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A third panel of witnesses will evaluate the evidence gathered
by Starr and contrast it to the process used in the Watergate
investigation. That group will include former Watergate prosecutor
Richard Ben-Veniste.
</P>
<P>
   The last witnesses called will be five former federal
prosecutors, including former Treasury Department chief of
enforcement Ronald Noble. They will discuss prosecutorial standards
for obstruction of justice and perjury. Another former Watergate
prosecutor, Richard Davis, will answer questions on that panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two days to make a case here, and we will spend a good
bit of time talking about the constitutional issues (of
impeachment),'' Lockhart said. ``We will discuss what our view of
both the facts and the law are at great length.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House asked for three or four days to present the
president's defense. But Hyde, under some pressure to wrap up the
impeachment inquiry before Christmas, held Clinton's legal team to
a total of 30 hours over two days. Under those guidelines, the
hearings could run until midnight today and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the panel's GOP members have already made it clear that
they intend to vote for at least one article of impeachment either
accusing the president of perjury, obstruction of justice or abuse
of his presidential powers. The only question that remains is what
the final impeachment resolution will say and whether the White
House can attract enough Republicans to defeat the measure on the
House floor next week.
</P>
<P>
   Articles of impeachment have already been drafted by Republican
lawyers, but won't be finalized until after Clinton's defense. The
articles include charges of perjury in connection with a court
document he signed last December denying a relationship with
Lewinsky, a deposition he gave Jan. 17 in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment lawsuit, and his videotaped testimony Aug. 17 before the
federal grand jury investigating the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   They also include charges of obstructing justice in which
Clinton is accused of interfering with Starr's investigation by
trying to get Lewinsky to deny their relationship, hiding gifts
they exchanged, and coaching his secretary Betty Currie to say he
and Lewinsky were never alone.
</P>
<P>
   In his news conference, Hyde said that he has not ruled out
allowing a vote on censure as an alternative to impeachment. But he
suggested that the Republicans on the committee were unlikely to go
along with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't ruled out, but it's not a dead-bang certainty
either,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on both sides of the aisle said Monday that the
outcome of a vote in the full House is too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   But even if a majority of House members support impeachment, it
would still take a two-thirds majority in the Senate to convict and
remove Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., one of the moderates who
opposes impeachment, said ``more contrition'' from the president
would help persuade more GOP members to support him. He encouraged
Clinton to drop his legal arguments and admit to lying under oath
about his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president committed crimes. I think they are
serious crimes. But I don't think he committed impeachable
offenses,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
