<SLUG> BC-PATTERNS-FASHION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASHION NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARYLOU LUTHER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fit for a First Lady &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton may be the first first lady to pose for
the cover of Vogue, appearing in the December issue, but that
doesn't mean her gown is treated differently from those of other
cover models. The design is for sale. Readers wishing to own a
dress of their own _ a burgundy velvet design by Oscar de la Renta
_ may do so by special order. So, how many have bought it?
</P>
<P>
   De la Renta modified the gown, chosen by Anna Wintour, Vogue's
editor in chief, from one in his fall haute couture line for Pierre
Balmain, removing the train from it. The original costs $19,600;
the de-trained version, $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the first lady, who is a size 8, paid for hers, de la Renta
said. ``She pays our company the wholesale price,'' he said, ``and
what she buys is ready-to-wear. She cannot afford to buy haute
couture.'' (At normal wholesale prices for designer clothes, or 53
percent of retail, it cost Mrs. Clinton about $2,120.)
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswomen for the three stores where the dress will be
available _ Bergdorf Goodman, Saks Fifth Avenue and Neiman Marcus _
said that there have been inquiries about it but that no one had
placed an order yet. De la Renta is not discouraged. He plans to
include it in his ready-to-wear line for fall 1999, available in
stores next June and July.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Handbags for a Cause &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The elephant-head minaudiere with garnet eyes and rhinestone
tusks created by Judith Leiber and once owned by Nancy Reagan may
be the most politically appropriate accessory at Sotheby's
first-ever auction of handbags Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Reagan, who is donating it, is not expected to attend the
auction, a benefit for Community Research Initiative on AIDS, to
see whether it brings in the estimate of $3,000 to $4,000. But
other donors have told Tiffany Dubin, Sotheby's fashion department
director, that they will be there when the sale begins at 6:30.
They include Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece, her sister Alexandra
Von Furstenberg, Anne Bass, Helena Bonham Carter and Patty
Cisneros.
</P>
<P>
   Their gifts are in the first 37 lots of celebrity-donated bags,
which also include a green leaf-patterned silk crepe bag worn by
Madonna to the London premiere of ``Evita.'' Its estimated sale
price: $1,000 to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Dubin says the sale will make it possible for the AIDS group
to pack its bags and move to a new site. She expects 600 bidders.
Gucci, Hermes, Ms. Leiber and Louis Vuitton represent more than
half of the labels.
</P>
<P>
   Collecting high-fashion accessories as an investment may have
been spurred by the Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis auction, but the
real impetus may be the difficulty in finding things with great
craftmanship. ``It's getting more and more difficult to find
clothes and accessories handmade with the same care as the old
artisans created,'' Ms. Dubin said. ``Besides, people love
collecting things as social history.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; New Designer at Barneys &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The game of musical chairs set in motion when Alber Elbaz left
the Paris design house of Guy Laroche in November to become the new
ready-to-wear designer for Yves Saint Laurent continues. Elbaz's
replacement, Ronald Van der Kemp, who was the designer of the
in-house collection for Barneys New York, was succeeded last week
by Behnaz Sarafpour, the former senior design director for Isaac
Mizrahi.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sarafpour recently found herself out of a job when Mizrahi
closed down. Despite reports of lagging Mizrahi sales at many
stores, Judy Collinson, an executive vice president at Barneys,
called the Mizrahi business there ``wonderful.'' ``We obviously
have the customer for his clothes, and we look to grow that
business with Behnaz,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Collinson said that Barneys also plans to increase sales of
its in-house line substantially in the next two to five years. A
typical jacket is $495 to $1,200, depending on fabric.
</P>
<P>
   And how does Ms. Sarafpour's former boss assess her talent?
``She is better at what I was supposed to do than I was,'' Mizrahi
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
