<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-HONOREES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stinchcombs, Stanfill make Hall first for Dogs
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jon Stinchcomb will never play alongside his older
brother, Matt, with the Georgia Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, however, the freshman lineman will join the senior
tackle and Bill Stanfill, the 1968 Outland Trophy winner, to make
Georgia football history. For the first time, three Bulldogs will
be honored by the National Football Foundation and Hall of Fame
with three of its most prestigious awards at the Waldorf-Astoria in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Stinchcomb brothers will receive scholar-athlete
recognition, while Stanfill will be become the 10th Georgia athlete
inducted into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful,'' Jon Stinchcomb, 19, said. ``It's one of the
best honors we could've received together. For us to be here at the
same time, it couldn't be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he hasn't played a down yet in Athens, Ga., Jon
Stinchcomb is the High School Scholar Athlete for 1998. The award
honors the top scholar athletes in four regions of the country for
their academic, athletic and leadership for the 1997-98 school
year. He maintained a perfect 4.0 through his 12 years in public
schools and, like Matt, also was a Parade and USA Today high school
All-American lineman. Jon Stinchcomb enrolled at Georgia in March,
where he once again got straight A's. This summer, he received the
only B of his life, in calculus. ``First and, I hope, my last,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Next fall, he probably will be a starting offensive lineman as a
redshirt freshman, but he will have some huge shoes to fill; not
just on the field, but in the classroom as well, where Matt
Stinchcomb is one of the most decorated student-athletes ever to
play Georgia football. Today, Matt Stinchcomb will become one of 17
National Football Foundation Scholar-Athletes nationwide and will
receive a graduate scholarship worth $18,000 to $25,000. Matt
Stinchcomb has been selected an All-American twice, and, with a
3.96 GPA, he should repeat as an Academic All-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been proud of him,'' Jon Stinchcomb said about his
brother, who will play his final game in the Peach Bowl on Dec. 31.
``He has maintained a high standard of excellence.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanfill was a consensus All-American and an Academic
All-American in 1968, before an All-Pro career with the Miami
Dolphins. He was starter on the 1972 and 1973 championship teams
and holds the team record for career sacks (67 1/2) and sacks in a
season (18 1/2 in 1973).
</P>
<P>
   Other Bulldog Hall of Famers are former coaches Vince Dooley,
Wally Butts and Glen ``Pop'' Warner and former players Bill
Hartman, Bob McWhorter, Frank Sinkwich, Vernon ``Catfish'' Smith,
Fran Tarkenton and Charley Trippi.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
