</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF NEEDED _ AND NOT THE BCS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, before the BCS android was created and
national title-mania became the rage in college football, a coach
tried to explain why he liked the old system.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, reasoned the since-retired coach, half of the
Division I-A teams in the nation could put the shoulder pads away
feeling good about some part of their season. There were multiple
levels of success available.
</P>
<P>
   Teams could reach a goal if they had a winning season. They
could fulfill a goal by beating a rival or upsetting a ranked team.
</P>
<P>
   They could win their conference. Even if they didn't, they could
still earn a bowl bid. About a third of the Division I-A teams in
the nation could say they went bowling, and half that number would
win its last game.
</P>
<P>
   If you put all of college football's emphasis on having a
well-defined national champ, Terry Donahue believed, then you
devalue all of these other goals and accomplishments. And why would
you want to do that? Why would you want any system that creates one
winner and 100 losers?
</P>
<P>
   More than once this season, the former Bruin coach was mocked by
some media critics and the whiny contingent of UCLA followers.
Every time Bob Toledo encouraged the notion of shooting for the No.
1 moon, someone would remark what a refreshing change it was from
Donahue's mannered approach.
</P>
<P>
   Well, how refreshing are things now?
</P>
<P>
   For the first in the history of the Rose Bowl, a team will slink
into the game, wishing it was anywhere else. The fact that it's
UCLA just multiplies the refreshing nature of this bogus
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   I have no idea how Cade McNown or any Bruin will find the
strength to Trudge On against Wisconsin after the devastating loss
to Miami. The only thing which could excite McNown now would be the
chance to play against his own defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins certainly will not find solace in beating a
non-descript Wisconsin team that's only Pasadena-bound because it
didn't play Ohio State. Perhaps they will follow the lead of UCLA's
basketball team and wear black uniforms, fitting for a team in
mourning.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison to the Bruins, USC is absolutely elated to be
heading to I'll Paso
</P>
<P>
   for the Sun Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Things are so refreshing, in fact, that I can accurately tell
you how Bruin fans will respond: Many of them will sell out their
team by selling their tickets to the hoard of Badger fans headed
west, just as they did five years ago. ComeJan.1, the Rose Bowl
will become the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose here isn't to mock anyone's desire to be No.1 or to
make Donahue sound like a prophet. I may like the chaos of the
past, but I know I'm in the minority, and Donahue himself now
advocates a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that the system being imposed by the Bowl
Championship Series (BCS) is sucking the life out of college
football while also giving student-athletes an education in
hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   As bad as the Bruins may feel today, their pain doesn't come
close to the anguish Kansas State is feeling. The Bruins at least
bounced back to the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, Kansas State was ranked No.1 by one of the
major polls. Saturday evening, it lost to a good Texas A&AMP;M team in
double overtime. Sunday afternoon, it was left out of the
BCS-controlled Big Four bowl games altogether
</P>
<P>
   This has to be a Guinness freefall record, doesn't it? If I'm a
lawyer and a K-State alum, then I wake up this morning and sue
someone, because I have just been assaulted in broad daylight.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS system pretends to have the best interests of college
football in mind, but it truly only cares about how many tickets
can be sold and hotel rooms filled. Why else would a two-loss
Florida team be in the Orange Bowl ahead of one-loss Kansas State,
or one-loss Arizona? K State got the same shaft this year that UCLA
did a year ago by the Sugar Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't there a conflict of interest when the President of the
SEC, Roy Kramer, is also the CEO of the BCS? Isn't it intriguing
that the BCS, like the bowl alliance and coalition before it, has
rules giving member bowls the right to pick the teams they want and
not according to the final BCS standings?
</P>
<P>
   This sport needs to either take a step back and rediscover the
mythology of its past, or take a step forward with a full and fair
playoff system.
</P>
<P>
   A playoff system can work, and on the kind of multiple levels
Donahue spoke about. A 16-team tourney would not have to kill the
other bowls, and it would create a new level of success (playoff
berths) that is an easy sell in other sports.
</P>
<P>
   With a playoff, a loss like UCLA's against Miami or Ohio State's
to Michigan State does not necessarily kill the season. With a
playoff, Kansas State is not a victim of ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Step forward or step back, but under no circumstances can
college football afford to stand still. Kill the BCS, before it
kills the sport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
