<SLUG> BC-ICICLES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ICICLE LIGHTS' RULE THIS CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN GILBERTSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Forget about Furby.
</P>
<P>
   This holiday season's must-have _ and therefore can't-find _ is
icicle lights, those dainty white lights that dangle off the house.
</P>
<P>
   Stores have already sold out despite loading up on them after
strong sales during their big debut last year, disappointing
countless consumers who went shopping for decorations over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tripled or quadrupled our order this year and they just
flew out the door,'' said Marty Feldman, assistant manager of
Artie's Paradise Valley Ace Hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The store, at Tatum Boulevard and Thunderbird Road, sold its
last set of white icicle lights a week ago. All that's left on the
display are the less popular colored ones, and then only a few.
</P>
<P>
   The Target store in Peoria ran out of the icicle lights Saturday
morning, manager Joe Larson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the Target stores here in the city are experiencing the
same thing,'' he said. ``I have no idea who has them anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Larson, who says he ordered 10 to 15 times as many icicle lights
as a year ago, said he thinks they are so popular because they're a
novelty.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see them (on somebody's house) and go, `How cute.' ''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For transplants from the Midwest and Northeast, the lights bring
back memories of real icicles, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Biffie Kelly of Phoenix picked up a big box of the lights at
Toys `R' Us more than a month ago, and a couple of more at a
Michaels arts and crafts store.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just looked fun,'' she said. ``They remind me of the
things that we've seen at ZooLights'' at the Phoenix Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, whose 13-year-old son Robbie is known as the neighborhood
light man because he covers the family's house with them, wanted to
pick up more when she saw them on sale at Kmart a week ago. The
store nearby didn't have any, and neither did another Kmart she
tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really aware that they were such a rage,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Target and other retailers in the Valley spent the weekend
turning light-seekers like Kelly away, in person and on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone, gone, gone,'' is what Donna Walker, manager of the
Michaels in Chandler, told anyone inquiring about the lights.
</P>
<P>
   The store had been referring customers to a nearby craft store
but it sold out, too, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Wal-Mart at Tatum Boulevard and Bell Road in north
Phoenix on Sunday, the switchboard was filled with callers checking
to see if the lights were in stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a few calls ahead of you and they're all asking the
same thing,'' a receptionist warned as she placed a caller on hold.
</P>
<P>
   A neighboring Osco drugstore took down a banner advertising the
lights Sunday, as the shelves were empty. A couple of Phoenix-area
Osco stores, including the one at Shea Boulevard and Scottsdale
Road in Scottsdale, said they had some in stock Monday.
</P>
<P>
   John Baker, an associate in the seasonal department at the
HomeBase in Tempe, said, ``Every other question (this weekend) was
if we had them.''
</P>
<P>
   Target's Larson said nothing matches the icicle light fervor,
not even the hunt for that interactive stuffed toy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of requests for Furby, but not anywhere near
the icicle lights'' requests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet sites that sell Christmas decorations also are flashing
some sold-out signs.
</P>
<P>
   At Betty's Christmas House (www.bettyschristmashouse.com), &QL; 
all but one of four offered are sold out.
</P>
<P>
   At www.christmasdepot.com, which bills itself as the largest
Christmas store on the Internet, three of the eight sets offered
were sold out.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the shortage, one Phoenix woman got creative. She
bought Ace Hardware's display of icicle lights Saturday, shelling
out $144. The store took the lights down for her and she picked
them up Monday. The lights generally sell for $10 to $20 for a
150-light set.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people asked. She had the gumption to do it,''
Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hot demand, Feldman isn't planning on increasing his
order for next year. He figures the fad will probably fade after
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is sold now,'' he said. ``Maybe we'll go with the
same amount as this year and pray that we get rid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Gilbertson can be reached at 444-8617 or at
dawn.gilbertson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
