<SLUG> BC-FBN-INSTANT-REPLAY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL ready to bring back instant replay for playoffs
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coming off a second straight weekend of officiating blunders,
the NFL decided Monday to seek approval from its team owners to
implement an instant replay system for this season's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Although commissioner Paul Tagliabue could not be reached for
comment, league vice president Greg Aiello confirmed the unusual
move. Several owners contacted Monday by the Journal-Constitution
said they were unaware of the action.
</P>
<P>
   The league office worked much of Monday formulating a proposal
it feels will win the support of many of the owners whose teams
have been affected by officiating snafus. A vote, likely within the
next 7-10 days, is expected to be conducted by conference call.
</P>
<P>
   The components of a proposed ''challenge-based'' system would be
similar to those used during preseason experimentation with replay
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Then-Dallas Cowboys president Tex Schramm attempted in 1985 to
have replay adopted for postseason play but the proposal was
rejected. The NFL implemented replay in 1986 and used the system
through the '91 season. It was voted out in 1992 and recent votes
have failed to return it.
</P>
<P>
   The game officials, along with senior director of officiating
Jerry Seeman, have come under fire much of this season for
questionable calls. The furor reached unprecedented levels the past
two weekends and, in the wake of what one high-ranking league
official agreed was a crisis of credibility, the NFL has been under
pressure to respond.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident occurred Sunday when New York Jets
quarterback Vinny Testaverde was credited with the game-winning
touchdown against the Seattle Seahawks when TV replays clearly
showed he failed to cross the goal line. The league admitted Monday
the touchdown call was erroneous.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle players told the Journal-Constitution that coach Dennis
Erickson, whose job is on the line, wept bitterly after the loss.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution confirmed Tagliabue has
deferred $50,000 fines levied last week against owners Ralph Wilson
of Buffalo and Detroit's William Clay Ford, and that those
penalties probably will be rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
