<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7448 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOL-MAY-LADN     12-07 2121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOL-MAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAY'S CAREER COMING TO END AT LONG BEACH STATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM McCURDIE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ It all began with a little girl, a balloon,
and the living room of a modest Santa Monica apartment. The little
girl would repeatedly bat the balloon into the air, refusing to let
it hit the floor. Her father, who had some experience in games like
this one, watched and beamed.
</P>
<P>
   This was how Misty May first learned the basics of a game she
would come to master. Her parents, proud holders of Ph.D.s from the
old school of volleyball, taught their daughter well. By the time
she reached her teens, she was looking for older kids to play with,
because those her own age couldn't give her much of a game.
</P>
<P>
   She's all grown up now, and the ball only touches the floor when
she decides it is time. May runs the show for Long Beach State's
women's volleyball team, which is unbeaten and ranked No.1 in the
nation. Oh, she has an assortment of talented athletes on her side
of the net. But make no mistake about it. It is Misty's show.
</P>
<P>
   And the curtain is slowly coming down. The 49ers play host to
the Mountain Regional finals beginning Thursday night against
Illinois at the Pyramid. The Misty May Era will end when their time
in the tournament ends. They hope that doesn't come until Dec.19 in
Madison, Wis., in the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   So pardon some of the patrons and participants at the Pyramid if
they seem a bit Misty-eyed these days, for they know their time is
short. As Coach Brian Gimmillaro put it, there is this sense of
urgency to ``exhaust all possibilities'' before May leaves. The
players feel it. Every point, every practice, every team meeting
has become more precious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every minute we have?,'' asked 49er senior outside hitter
Jessica Alvarado, May's teammate for the past four seasons.
``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about that since August I only have one more
season with her,'' said 49er assistant coach Debbie Green, perhaps
the biggest reason May came to Long Beach four years ago. ``I
already miss her, and she hasn't even left yet. Yeah, I'm counting
every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach officials paid tribute to May last Saturday night by
retiring her jersey before the 49ers' sweep of Illinois State. May
is the seventh 49er to be so honored, but the first to have a
replica of her jersey hung from the ceiling before she was finished
wearing the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   May had offered to sing the national anthem before that ``Senior
Night'' match, figuring that she and her high-pitched voice could
step up to the mike. She had sung in the choir in junior high,
after all. But she was politely told to stick to setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian and Debbie said I couldn't do it, because they thought
it would turn into a Roseanne Barr deal,'' she said. ``I do have a
serious side. I guess they don't believe me when I say I can be
serious.''
</P>
<P>
   That is seldom at issue once the first serve crosses the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she has a great perspective of what's important and
what's not,'' Gimmillaro said. ``She has a perspective of life that
I wish a lot of us older people had. She isn't bothered by trivial
things. And she's able to be incredibly serious when she needs to
be, and not serious when she doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has all the qualities to be a great friend, and a great
teammate.''
</P>
<P>
   And if she comes away with a national championship and gets
selected the nation's player of the year for the second consecutive
season, one could make a compelling argument that the little girl
with the balloon grew into the most celebrated athlete Long Beach
State has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that this university's ever had an athlete that's
been more recognized than Misty,'' said Dr. Robert Maxson, the
school's president and a regular at courtside for 49ers home
matches. ``She obviously is the best college player in America (No,
Dr. Bob doesn't have a vote for player of the year), but she's just
such a wonderful representative and ambassador for the university.
She represents everything I believe a student athlete ought to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) Beautiful Mist
</P>
<P>
   She was born Misty Elizabeth May, but her parents still hope she
will one day incorporate ``Kehaunani'' into her legal name. Her
father is nearly half Hawaiian and, to natives of the islands, the
word means ``Beautiful Mist.''
</P>
<P>
   May spent much of her childhood on or near Santa Monica's State
Beach, one of the true Meccas of volleyball. Her father, Butch,
played on the U.S. Olympic team in 1968. He and her mother,
Barbara, coached briefly at Santa Monica City College, and both
spent many a long weekend toiling in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Although Butch May said the family lived a mostly ``paycheck to
paycheck'' existence in those days, the Mays became sort of
honorary members of the Sand and Sea Club, a social and athletic
gathering place with a largely Jewish membership. There, they
rubbed elbows and played volleyball and paddle tennis with wealthy
Angelinos, and let their daughter swim in the Olympic-sized pool
and play in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to compare incomes,'' Butch May said, ``ours
probably wasn't much more than the people who were taking care of
the grounds. We were always thankful that we had a place like that
to go. We tried to give back to the club, play with some of the
older people no one else would play with ... we made lifetime
friends, people who let us into their lives to watch their kids'
successes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mays came into some inheritance money, so they bought a
house and moved from Santa Monica to Costa Mesa when Misty was in
the eighth grade. She was already developing into an extraordinary
volleyball and soccer player, but had to fit in and find new
friends at that awkward-adolescent age where growing up is hard
enough when you know your surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was tough was that a lot of girls in the eighth and ninth
grade would have birthday parties, and Misty wouldn't get
invited,'' Butch said, ``just because she wasn't part of the
group.''
</P>
<P>
   But by the time she reached Newport Harbor High, she was fast
becoming the life of the party. It didn't hurt that she could pound
a volleyball to the floor from the moment she walked onto campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for freshmen to step in and play varsity,'' said Dan
Glenn, who is in his 13th season as the coach at Newport Harbor.
``She wasn't unique in that way. But I haven't had a kid who was as
talented as a freshman as she was. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn admits that it wasn't always smooth sailing at Newport
Harbor between he and May's parents, who had strong opinions about
how their daughter should be coached. Parents will be parents, but
the Mays were a bit different. One had played the game at Olympian
heights. The other had played it and coached it. This is a coach's
worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, that's what we're labeled,'' Barbara said, half
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've never interfered with any of her coaches,'' Butch
said. ``We've just kind of debriefed her.''
</P>
<P>
   Misty said she let's old Dad have his say.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's tried talking to coaches before, but egos get in the
way,'' she said. ``So he kind of tells me things I should try to do
differently. I listen to him, because he's smart and his coaches
were good. The stuff he says makes sense. I've never really shunned
anyone out. I listen to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Told that some of his coaching philosophies may be getting
``debriefed'' out of his star player, Gimmillaro took a diplomatic
high road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that it's really, really difficult to be a parent,''
the father of two said. ``You want so much for your kids. No matter
what's going on ... you're always worried about your kids. It's
just so hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I completely admire the professionalism of her parents and
their support of me and this program. My God, between Butch and
Barbara, I think they've sent 100 kids to our camps. I told them at
our banquet last year how proud they must be of their daughter. Do
you have kids? Could you imagine if they turn out to be as good as
Misty May as a volleyball player and as a person?''
</P>
<P>
   (subhd) Aloha and Mahalo
</P>
<P>
   ``Kehaunani'' May had to say no to Hawaii, and Hawaii didn't
appreciate it much.
</P>
<P>
   May decided to attend Long Beach before her junior year in high
school. Gimmillaro said he got the word on an August afternoon when
he was gathering his new team at his home for a get-acquainted
barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of in shock,'' he said. ``We thought the
(recruiting) war was just going to get started.''
</P>
<P>
   But May called a truce, and decided there was no point in going
through the charade of visiting three or four other campuses. Long
Beach was getting the player who was at the top of the wish lists
of most of the powerhouse programs of major college volleyball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always come to their camps,'' she said. ``I had been to
the campus a lot to come to games. Maybe because I had been around
it so much, I just felt at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the schools that had hopes of landing her took the news
hard. Butch May said Hawaii coach Dave Shoji cq
</P>
<P>
   appealed to her to consider her heritage. ``He said, `You're
part Hawaiian, Misty. You owe it to the state, you owe it to
everybody here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Misty's never forgotten that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor has she forgotten how maddening that time was for a
17-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, because you've got to say no to all the other
schools, and you're scared,'' she said. ``You get yelled at on the
phone. A lot of coaches are disappointed in you. They say, `I can't
believe this. You never gave our school a chance,' and this and
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, when you play them, they're really nice to you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was her relationship with Green, an inductee in the
Volleyball Hall of Fame and former setter for the U.S. National and
Olympic teams, that helped push Long Beach over the top. They met
when May began coming to the 49ers' summer camps at 13, and quickly
formed a bond, one that has only grown stronger over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always talk and hang out together on road trips,'' May
said. ``We share girlie things. She's not just a coach, she's a
friend. She's like my mom away from home. I can talk to her about
boyfriend problems ... anything. Maybe she was like me when she was
my age. Just crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Green is understandably proud of her prized pupil.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something that I see,'' she said, as May signed
autographs for a group of adoring children after a recent match at
the Pyramid. ``These little girls - they want to be like Misty May.
From adults down to the young girls, she (creates) an excitement.
She's just so much fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   As the focal point of a high-profile program, May gets a lot of
the attention. She was selected player of the year by the American
Volleyball Coaches Association and Volleyball Magazine last year.
She keeps winning all those tournament MVPs. She gets most of the
media attention. It's her show.
</P>
<P>
   But if all that hype has created any jealousy among her
teammates, it is certainly wearing a clever disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be jealous of her,'' said Alvarado. ``It's
impossible. ``She has a way of knowing how to treat others. She has
a sixth sense about her. She just ... knows
</P>
<P>
   . On the court, off the court, someone else's feelings, what to
say to them when, how to get the best out of you as a player, how
to get he best out of you as a person, just everything. She's
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Said junior middle blocker Brandy Barratt, one of May's
roommates in a rental house near campus: ``She doesn't really get
upset with anyone. She knows she's a team leader, and Brian does
enough of that, so she doesn't need to reinforce it. You know that
you did wrong, and she'll let you know about it. But she does it in
a way that doesn't put you down.''
</P>
<P>
   With May at the controls, the 49ers have built a 30-0 record,
and enter the NCAA Tournament having swept their past 17 matches.
They have lost only six games all season. They are the top-seeded
team in the tournament, and are well positioned to win the national
championship that eluded them last year, when they lost to Stanford
in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our year,'' May said. ``This is the first team since I've
been here that, when we play a team that's really not at our level,
we still play with the same intensity. Past teams I've been on will
maybe have a 15-11 game with one of those teams. But this team has
all been on the same page, just going for one thing. I feel like
the time is right.''
</P>
<P>
   For May, it is one more chance to rise above the mist, and enjoy
the view from the top of the mountain. Don't let those pigtails
fool you. This little girl is all grown up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
