<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BARNES &AMP; NOBLE IN DEAL THAT COULD HURT AMAZON
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft and Barnes &AMP; Noble announced an agreement to weave
together their online products and services in a
multimillion-dollar marketing arrangement that makes Barnes &AMP; Noble
the exclusive book merchant on Microsoft's popular MSN network. The
deal could prove damaging to the Internet's largest bookseller,
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms of the deal were not disclosed, but analysts
said it could give Barnes &AMP; Noble significant reach in an area
where it has lagged. Shares of Barnes &AMP; Noble surged 10 percent and
Microsoft rose nearly 5 percent. Shares of Amazon rose 1.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ CLIMBS TO A RECORD
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index set a record as stocks rose, led by
software, computer and telecommunications equipment companies such
as Microsoft, Compaq Computer and Lucent Technologies. The Nasdaq
climbed 37.48 points, to 2,040.64. The Dow Jones industrial average
rose 54.33 points, to 9,070.47, and the S&AMP;P 500 gained 10.96
points, to 1,187.70. In the bond market, Treasury prices rose as
the yield on the 30-year issue fell to 5.03 percent.
</P>
<P>
   DEADLINE LOOMS UNDER OPTION RULE
</P>
<P>
   Companies that want to reprice options because their stock price
is depressed, but thought that they had months left to act,
scrambled on Monday to get the job done before next Tuesday, when
favorable accounting treatment will end.
</P>
<P>
   ELI LILLY TO LICENSE NEW FORM OF PROZAC
</P>
<P>
   Eli Lilly said that it would pay Sepracor up to $90 million to
license a molecule that is a purer form of Prozac, Lilly's
market-leading anti-depressant. The drug, R-fluoxetine, could
extend the competitive life of Prozac, whose patents begin expiring
in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   SUN MOVES TOWARD SHARING CODE
</P>
<P>
   To both broaden support for its Java programming language and
nurture innovation, Sun Microsystems plans to announce a new
business model on Tuesday that moves the company a step closer to
freely sharing the work of computer programmers, including the
original source code for Java.
</P>
<P>
   HITACHI AND NISSAN TO COOPERATE
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi, Japan's largest electronics maker, and Nissan Motor
announced that they planned to collaborate on developing advanced
technology for cars.
</P>
<P>
   BIG KOREAN GROUPS TO SHED UNITS
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's five largest conglomerates promised to shed more
than half their subsidiaries, bowing to intense government pressure
aimed at reorganizing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   WB PROGRAMMING CHIEF STEPS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Garth Ancier became the third top programmer in the last month
to leave his network, when he announced that he was stepping down
as president of entertainment for WB. He will be replaced by
Susanne Daniels, who will become the third woman to hold the job of
president of entertainment at a network.
</P>
<P>
   CONSOLIDATION AT MORGAN STANLEY
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter said that its three asset-management
divisions would now report to one executive. Mitchell Merin will
oversee $356 billion in assets by heading the combined division,
which includes institutional and individual asset management and
the firm's mutual funds. The move unites divisions that had
remained separate after the May 1997 merger of Morgan Stanley and
Dean Witter, Discover.
</P>
<P>
   PLANNED JOB CUTS INCREASE 9.3 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The number of planned job cuts by U.S. businesses rose in
November from a year earlier, putting the annual total on track for
the largest number of planned cuts in five years, a survey showed.
Announced job cuts rose 9.3 percent last month.
</P>
<P>
   Lear, an automotive supplier, will cut 2,800 jobs, or about 4
percent of its work force, and close 18 plants.
</P>
</TEXT>
