<HEADLINE>
ASTRONAUTS CONNECT ELECTRICAL PARTS OF SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Astronauts Jerry Ross and Jim Newman scaled the first
components of the new international space station during a
seven-hour spacewalk late Monday, connecting thick electrical power
and computer cables.
</P>
<P>
   The excursion, the first of three planned by the men this week,
began shortly after 4 p.m., CST, as the astronauts crawled from an
airlock in the cargo bay of the shuttle Endeavour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, oh my,'' gushed Ross, his attention momentarily drawn to
the brilliant rays of the sun setting on the Earth's horizon 240
miles below. ``We're going around the world awfully fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The American ``Unity'' and Russian ``Zarya'' modules, joined by
the shuttle crew Sunday, towered nearly eight stories above the
airlock, secured to Endeavour's docking mechanism for the series of
spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's stroll was considered by far the most crucial of the
three excursions. Without the nearly 40 cable connections at three
locations, power generated by Zarya's winglike solar arrays would
not reach the computers and other electronics called avionics
aboard Unity.
</P>
<P>
   Power is essential to Unity, a 33-foot long cylinder with a
half-dozen docking ports that will link future station components,
including stabilizing gyroscopes, the U.S. laboratory, an airlock
and more powerful solar arrays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The assembly sequence stops if we can't get these avionics
working,'' said Bob Castle, NASA's lead flight director for the
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The first hours of Monday's spacewalk went well, reflecting the
more than 500 hours of ground training the veteran spacewalkers
invested in their preparation for the often tedious work.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, a 50-year-old Air Force colonel who had logged four
previous spacewalks, secured himself on the tip of Endeavour's
50-foot robot arm, which afforded a mobile platform from which to
connect the cables.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, a 42-year-old physicist who conducted a previous
spacewalk five years ago, released each of the snaking 20-foot long
cables to hand to Ross. He worked from a portable mechanical foot
restraint that he moved and plugged into fasteners located around
the work sites.
</P>
<P>
   Assisting them from inside the shuttle were Nancy Currie,
Endeavour's robot arm operator, and pilot Rick Sturckow, their
timekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's spacewalk called for Ross and Newman to work first at
the base of the Unity module, which was latched to the shuttle's
docking mechanism. They spent nearly two hours attaching eight
cables.
</P>
<P>
   Each time his colleague handed him a new power line, Ross would
remove a protective cover installed before the equipment was
launched to prevent debris from lodging between the connector pins.
Using a flash light, Ross also inspected the dozens of fragile pins
in each connector to ensure they had not been bent. He carried a
``pin straightener'' tool to correct any problems.
</P>
<P>
   Cold temperatures, as low as 200 degrees below zero, stiffened
some of the thick cables. More than once, Ross and Newman jokingly
referred to the electrical bundles as ``the octopus.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the cables were plugged to a receptacle, a twist of Ross'
wrist moved a locking collar into place. He also slipped a sleeve
of fabric thermal insulation over each connection.
</P>
<P>
   Ross and Newman then moved to the top of Unity, where the U.S.
module was joined to Zarya where most of the connections awaited
them in the final hours of the spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   The final half-dozen connections will make it possible for the
power generated by Zarya's solar arrays to flow into Unity. That
power will make it possible for the shuttle astronauts to turn on a
pair of computers mounted on the left and right sides of the
American module.
</P>
<P>
   If their efforts were successful, NASA planned to give
Endeavour's six astronauts a half-day off Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The mission's second spacewalk was scheduled for Wednesday.
After donning spacesuits, Ross and Newman will install a pair of
communications antennas on the outside of Unity, allowing mission
control teams in Houston to monitor activities aboard the new
station over a satellite network.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Endeavour commander Bob Cabana and his crew will
enter the two station modules for the first time to complete the
installation of the communications gear and to prepare its interior
for station crews.
</P>
<P>
   During the third spacewalk Saturday, the astronauts will place
tools and other equipment on the outside of the station, ready for
space station construction workers.
</P>
<P>
   NASA planners estimate that building the new station will take
six years and require 162 spacewalks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
