<HEADER>
A7454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CRAIG-COX     12-07 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CRAIG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nurse's internet posting becomes White House protest
 &HT;    By Julia Malone
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just over two months ago, Michelle Hellgeth, a
nurse from Marietta, Ga., was in her home, tapping out Internet
messages urging the impeachment of President Clinton. That was too
passive, she concluded.
</P>
<P>
   So she sent out a call to on-line conservatives. ``I said,
'Let's have a march,''' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   And although she admitted she had no idea how to pull it off, on
Monday she was standing on a platform between giant loud speakers
to welcome a modest lunch-hour protest across from the White House
in Lafayette Park. For more than two hours, a dozen Clinton critics
assailed the president in front of a crowd bearing signs such as
``Impeach the rat.''
</P>
<P>
   A vote to impeach Clinton is ``by no means'' certain, Howard
Phillips, chairman of the Conservative Caucus, told the gathering.
``Bill Clinton will use all of the power of his presidency'' to
stop it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As she watched the results of her first-time political
organizing, Hellgeth said she would have liked to have had a bigger
turnout than the roughly 70 people who showed up. But Hellgeth, the
mother of three grown children, allowed that she wasn't
disappointed. ``We're glad we had some to come and hear the
message,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, her political activism had extended to telephoning
the White House to offer comments. But using her bedroom computer
to search conservative Web sites on the Internet, Hellgeth made
enough contacts to set up the Washington rally.
</P>
<P>
   Her partner was another self-proclaimed political neophyte,
Debbie Cragg of Virginia Beach, Va. ``Michelle and I got together
over the Internet,'' she said. ``I'm just a normal person. I just
got mad. I'm not part of the 'vast right wing conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The two women hooked up with veteran Clinton foes, including
Garland Favorito, a computer consultant from Peachtree Corners,
Ga., who linked them with speakers and ordered up the loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   The two women then worked the Internet sites to send out the
word.
</P>
<P>
   That message got through to Susan Sarver, of Parkersburg, W.Va.,
who brought her four children, ages 4 to 11, who joined a march
around the park with signs, including one saying, ``Dear President,
My parents punish me for lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
