<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LAWYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE LAWYERS STAY FOCUSED AMID SEASONAL FESTIVITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Days before a vote on whether to impeach President
Clinton, the atmosphere at the White House Monday was as surreal as
celebrating the Christmas season when the temperature outside is 70
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton was showing off the glittery holiday
decorations at the White House, where the theme this year is ``A
Winter Wonderland.'' The president was in a downstairs room taping
his appearance on a television special called ``Christmas in
Washington,'' a show he won't attend live this year because of his
trip to the Middle East later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   While the Clintons went through the motions of the holiday
season, the buzz from the House impeachment vote seemed to create
more noise than a Marine Band trio's playing of `` 'Tis the Season
to Be Jolly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the possibility that Clinton could be impeached has not
registered with much of the American public, White House aides
said, the point has not been lost on the president's aides and
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking this very seriously indeed, and I think we are
working on it in the appropriate manner,'' said Ann Lewis, director
of White House communications.
</P>
<P>
   So alarmed are the president's aides and lawyers by the growing
prospect that the Judiciary Committee and full House will vote this
week and next to impeach Clinton that not only are they warning
about the ``grave and serious consequences'' of impeachment, but
they are also modulating their criticism of Republicans who want to
impeach Clinton to avoid turning off critical GOP moderates, some
of whom are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   They are also emphasizing to members of Congress how the
impeachment vote is likely to be the most important they will cast
in their career.
</P>
<P>
   And in a counterpunch to the Republican argument that voting for
impeachment would be the equivalent of censure, since conventional
wisdom is that the Senate will not remove the president from
office, aides are stressing that sending the matter to the Senate
has the potential to paralyze the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically would be a longer version of the goverment
shutdown,'' a senior White House official said. ``With all the
focus on the . . . partisan squabbling, sometimes people forget
this isn't just a vote over a trade bill.''
</P>
<P>
   The seriousness with which the White House has come to view the
process was evident in its announcement Monday that White House
lawyers Charles F. C. Ruff and Gregory B. Craig will present
Clinton's defense Tuesday and Wednesday before the House Judiciary
Committee's impeachment hearing.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said it was more appropriate for
government lawyers to represent Clinton before the committee rather
than Clinton's private lawyer, David Kendall, who cross-examined
the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, when he appeared before
the committee last month. Kendall, however, is expected to be
present at the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   And rather than criticize Starr, White House lawyers will
present a defense that is ``serious, that doesn't attempt to lay
blame with someone else, and makes a case that both on the facts
and the law and on the constitutional standards . . . the president
shouldn't be impeached,'' said the White House press secretary,
Joseph Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining this turnabout, he said, ``We are moving into a
different phase. . . . Given the fact that what the House of
Representatives is discussing is removing the president, removing
him from office, overturning the will of the people, it's important
that this be done in a serious way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart did not entirely dismiss the possibility that Clinton
could decide this week or next to amplify his expressions of
contrition over lying to the country for eight months over his
affair with the former White House intern, Monica S. Lewinsky. ``If
it's appropriate to say something, he will,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some speculation has centered on whether Mrs. Clinton
might also make some statement of support for her husband before
the House vote, a source close to her said Monday: ``That would
surprise me very greatly. I haven't heard anything that makes me
think that's the case.''
</P>
<P>
   The source, however, said of Mrs. Clinton: ``Obviously, she is
one of his advisers on a very basic level . . . obviously one of
the people he talks to,'' about the evolution of his defense
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said White House officials, based on polling data, are
worried that many Americans have not grasped the fact that the
president may be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know one of the responsibilities is to say to people, `This
is real,' '' she said. ``That's one of the things this hearing is
going to do. The biggest effect, the most important, is likely to
be people learning from the news and seeing it for themselves . . .
that a significant number of members of Congress want to go forward
and do something that the American public emphatically said it
doesn't want to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those members of Congress were the Clintons' guests
Monday night at the annual Congressional Ball at the White House,
to which all 535 members of the House and Senate were invited.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said, ``This is a tradition at the White House to, on
Christmas time, bring down members on a bipartisan basis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the people's house; it's not a Democrat White House or
a Republican White House,'' Lockhart said Monday before the ball.
``And I hope that Republicans feel welcome to attend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
