<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, DECEMBER 8
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ISRAEL-U.S.-NYT (moved on Friday, Dec. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Dec. 4,
about President Clinton's scheduled trip to the Middle East this
week referred incorrectly in some copies to the Israeli-Palestinian
talks on a final settlement. They have in fact begun, with one
procedural meeting.
</P>
<P>
   BC-VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ-NYT (moved on Saturday, Dec. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Dec. 5,
about Hugo Chavez, a candidate in the Venezuelan Presidential
election (since declared the winner), referred incorrectly in some
copies to the tenure of President Rafael Caldera, who in 1994
dropped coup charges against him. Mr. Caldera was not leaving
office in 1994; his term ends in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   BC-GIRL-KIDNEY-TRANSPLANT-NYT (move on Friday, Dec. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Dec. 4,
about Renada Daniel-Patterson, whose father wants to give her his
remaining kidney after the failure of the previous one he donated
to her, misspelled the surname of an ethicist at Stanford
University. It is Hank Greely, not Greeley.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-NYT (moved on Sunday, Dec. 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Dec. 6,
about work on the International Space Station misstated the
frequency with which astronauts on the orbiting space shuttle
experience sunrise. It occurs every 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PSYCHO-FILM-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Friday, Dec. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Dec. 4,
about Gus Van Sant's remake of ``Psycho'' referred incorrectly in
some copies to the actor who played the lover of the murder victim
in the original Alfred Hitchcock film. He was John Gavin, not John
Saxon.
</P>
</TEXT>
