<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ART-2NDTAKE-N     12-07 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
WASHINGTON: he said.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrats insisted that the committee was marching ahead with
impeachment even though it had never called factual witnesses of
its own or done anything to settle some of the discrepancies
between witnesses who testified before Starr's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not up to someone accused of wrongdoing to prove his
innocence,'' said Rep. Jerrold Nadler, D-N.Y. ``It's up to the
person who says he's guilty to prove his guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats would like the House to censure the president instead
of impeach him. But Hyde said Monday that he had not yet decided
whether he would allow a committee vote on censure. ``It's not
ruled out but it's not a dead-bang certainty either,'' he said. He
said that he does not believe censure is ``an appropriate
sanction.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the House Judiciary Committee hears from Clinton's
defenders on Tuesday, it plans to vote to make public the videotape
of Clinton's deposition in the Jones case. Republicans say the vote
is designed to allow their chief investigative counsel, David
Schippers, to show portions of it, if he chooses, in questioning
the president's representatives or in making his summation Thursday
of the case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats were also expected to seek the release of other
information still under seal that they consider exculpatory or
embarrassing to the president's accusers. Both Schippers, and Abbe
Lowell, the Democrats' chief investigative counsel, are to sum up
their cases Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the committee looking to finish its work by Saturday,
strategists for both parties began turning their attention to the
full House. House Democrats and the White House began focusing on
the 20 to 30 Republican moderates who they believe could be
persuaded to oppose impeachment either on the merits or because
their districts had voted for Clinton in 1996. ``We've got 10 days
here,'' said one House Democratic official. ``There's ample time to
convice them on the politics and the facts themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The list of moderates is heavily tilted to the Northeast. It
ranges from Republicans who have already come out against
impeachment, such as Rep. Jack Quinn of New York and Rep.
Christopher Shays of Connecticut, to ones who have kept their own
counsel such as New York Republicans Rick Lazio and Michael Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes Republicans like Rep. Brian Bilbray of
California who only narrowly won re-election and Rep. Nancy Johnson
of Connecticut, who faced a tough race four years ago when she when
she led the ethics inquiry into Speaker Newt Gingrich. Democrats
were also looking at Rep. Jay Dickey of Arkansas, on the theory
that any Arkansas member could be vulnerable at home if he votes
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   In his own effort to keep a censure measure from the House
floor, Rep. Tom DeLay, the House Majority whip, circulated a letter
Monday that argued against censure. It was co-signed by Shays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we disagree on whether President Clinton's lying
constitutes an impeachable offense, we both think every member of
Congress should make that judgment,'' the letter said. ``We oppose
establishing a new precedent _ censure _ when there is an
established method in existence and underway.''
</P>
<P>
   While Shays opposes both impeachment and censure, many other
moderates would like to show their disapporval of the president's
actions without going so far as to impeach him. If censure is
banned from a floor vote, they have to make the hard choice between
impeachment or nothing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 2121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981207.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7480 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REPLAY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     12-07 1139
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REPLAY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... it back.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The game is played on the field between 22 people,'' he said.
``That's 22 human beings, and human beings are prone to human
error. The game's played on the field, not in the press box. I
officiated four Super Bowls in my time. I worked one in Miami when
Jackie Smith was in the end zone with nothing between him and Fort
Lauderdale, and he dropped a touchdown pass, bounced right off him.
You know why he dropped it? Because he's human, prone to human
mistake. You could replay that 100 times and he'll drop it 100
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about officiating is, we're the only people who
can't make mistakes. And when you do, everybody wants to crucify
you, they want to stone you, they want to put you in a stockade in
a public square and throw rocks at you. I stuck around for 30 years
and I didn't cause a team to lose a game. My feeling is, if you
make too many mistakes, it's like any job _ they should fire you.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past implemenation of replay, there were some annoyances,
such as the sometimes protracted timeouts necessary for the replay
judge to review various camera shots. Unspoken, too, was the
possible resentment that could fester between officials if a replay
judge, cloistered in his private viewing box, overruled the
decisions made by the on-field crew.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Young pointed out, the science of replay technology
occasionally proved inexact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the six years we used it, it worked out to be about 80
percent accurate,'' he said. ``By Wednesday of each week, you'd
start getting film of all these different angles and you'd find out
that about 20 percent of the calls shouldn't have been reversed.
So, yes, it took a long time and it had its different problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriots general manager Patrick Sullivan, opposed to the
use of video replay in his days with the club, said he now would be
in favor of using it. In the late '80s and early '90s, he said,
there was a great disparity between the broadcast technology used
in a regionally televised game and one that was aired nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``That regional game 10 years ago would have only four or five
cameras assigned and maybe only one or two tape machines working,''
said Sullivan, now owner of Game Creek Video in Amherst, N.H., a
remote TV production company. ``Now even the regional game has
maybe nine cameras and six tape machines. Before, the difference
was just too much. It was as if you had one game worked by two
extra officials.''
</P>
<P>
   With increased technology and stakes so high, said Sullivan, the
league should reinstitute replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important to make the corrections when you can,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A rush to judgment?
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 10 of the league's 30 owners, meeting in their annual
March congress, vetoed a proposal to bring back video replay. In
March 1998, 9 of the 30 shot it down. In March '99, provided it is
proposed again, it will take a three-quarters majority of 31 owners
(a total of 24) to ratify the reinstitution of video replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been proposing it, and the thrust of each proposal has
not been to use it as a panacea, not try to right every wrong,''
said Young. ``In what we've proposed before, we didn't want to try
to micromanage the officials. If it comes back, it would apply to
certain big plays _ plays that might change a game, a change of
possession, a catch or no-catch situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde's controversial TD had pundits speculating Sunday
night that replay could be rushed back for this season's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have to do it before the playoffs start,'' said
ESPN's Tom Jackson, commenting on the network's ``NFL PrimeTime''
show Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Such a prospect, said Young, is virtually impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The league always has maintained the same rules of competition
in the regular season right through the playoffs,'' he said. ``The
only change is, in the playoffs, we play overtime to sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I don't run the league, but how in the world, if we're
still working on perfecting instant replay and we're not yet
comfortable with it, how could we then go into the most critical
part of the season with it? What kind of logic is that?''
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press report out of New York Monday said the
league is considering some use of replay for the upcoming playoffs.
The AP quoted league spokesman Joe Browne as saying that if owners
approve, ``a limited form of replay for use in the upcoming
postseason is a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners could approve it in a phone vote, but none has been
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman, who now works for the Big 12 college conference,
helping to rate officials, believes NFL officials could improve
their on-field performance by working more as a team when it comes
to making difficult calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole crew as a unit has to be more involved,'' he said.
``Right now they don't want to get involved in someone else's call.
They're afraid how their rating might be involved. Personally, I'd
throw the entire rating system out. I'd rate their mechanics and
their positioning, whether they're in the right place to make the
call. But I wouldn't rate them on right or wrong calls. If they all
got more involved in making a call, take maybe 20 or 30 seconds to
discuss it, ask what this guy saw, what that guy saw, that could
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's controversial call was made by head linesman Earnie
Franz. As soon as Testaverde crashed the line on his keeper, Franz
flashed high his arms to signal the TD. There has yet to be a TV
replay that supports Franz's call. Every angle shows the Jets
signal-caller being repelled at least 12 inches shy of cracking the
goal-line plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what he's going through and what he'll go through,''
said Bergman, who worked that linesman position for three decades.
``In 1975, I worked a game in Miami _ Miami against Buffalo _ and I
made a call, a fumble. Everyone said it wasn't a fumble, and Ralph
Wilson (the Bills owner) wanted me fired immediately for
incompetence. The headlines screamed for three weeks, calling for
my neck. But for three weeks, the commissioner and the supervisor
of officials stuck by me, and eventually, I was proven right _ by a
picture taken by a still photographer in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``So unless you're right there, looking straight down that goal
line, you can't make the call. The game's not officiated in the
press box. Sometimes it's just one person who sees it.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Aiello, his office received several dozen calls
Monday from media members and fans seeking explanations and voicing
opinions after the latest controversial call, Testaverde's phantom
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mostly listen,'' said Aiello, asked what the callers were
told. ``Hey, we know it's our responsibility to get it right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
