<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7482 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REPLAY-2TAKES-BOS     12-07 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REPLAY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME CALL FOR THE RETURN OF INSTANT REPLAY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Young, the NFL senior vice president in charge of
football operations, reached across his desk for his new folder.
Subject: Instant Replay.
</P>
<P>
   A possible subtitle could be: ``Officiating Faux Pas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I've got it labeled: `Instant Replay Panic!' ''
Young said Monday, contacted by phone at the league's New York
headquarters. ``I get these calls, people asking, `Why can't we
have replay?' So now I've got the folder _and it's in red ink.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of instant replay in NFL games, which ended after the
1991 season, is back in the spotlight after a recent rash of
controversial officiating calls. The subject reached a roiling boil
Sunday when Vinny Testaverde was credited with the winning
touchdown against Seattle _ despite the fact that video replay
clearly showed that the New York Jets quarterback never broke the
imaginary plane of the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Young emphasized Monday that the league continues to consider
the reinstitution of replay, and in the last two years, club owners
only narrowly shot down proposals by the league's Competition
Committee to get the technological gadgets back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something the league has addressed and will continue to
address,'' said Young, the former New York Giants general manager
who is considered the game's quality control engineer. ``It's not
something we've hidden under the rug somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Young added, ``We are trying not to have controversial
games.''
</P>
<P>
   But controversy and the gridiron have become inseparable of
late, especially since Thanksgiving Day when a botched coin toss
prior to overtime in Detroit helped lead the Pittsburgh Steelers
down the path of defeat. On that afternoon, referee Phil Luckett,
who also was in charge of Sunday's Jets-Seahawks game, incorrectly
awarded the Lions the right to receive or kick the ball, though the
Steelers won the coin toss. The Lions elected to receive and soon
were celebrating victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``A coin toss would not be a replayable event,'' said Young.
``We've probably had, what, 500,000 coin flips. I don't know why
that was the way it was.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way to guard against such incidents, said Young, would
be to ``put a microphone on everybody.'' He was not being
facetious.
</P>
<P>
   Since the miscall in Detroit, the league has changed its coin
flip procedure. The referee now asks for a ``heads'' or ``tails''
call before the coin is flipped, as opposed to asking for the call
while the coin is in the air. Two other game officials, one
standing next to each team captain, will serve as added witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for asking heads or tails before the flip is so you
don't have people calling two different things,'' said Greg Aiello,
the NFL's vice president of public relations. ``Some of this stuff
. . . it's almost comical.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The status quo
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the coin toss procedure, the league has not called for
any changes in officiating, or in officating personnel, in the wake
of recent controversial incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing else I can point to, as of today,'' said
Aiello.
</P>
<P>
   All NFL officials have a minimum of 10 years of officiating at
the college level. Many, if not all, also would have worked high
school games. In recent years, said Aiello, the league has expanded
its number of full-time employees assigned to the officiating
department, administrators and supervisors working under director
of officiating Jerry Seeman.
</P>
<P>
   None of the NFL's on-field officials is employed full-time by
the league, a point that is often debated in times of controversy.
One school of thought is that full-time professional officials
would make for a cleaner, better-officiated game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that whole subject will get another thorough
discussion,'' said Aiello. ``It could be, though, that the only
thing that might make officials better is if they're able to work
more games. Otherwise, if they only sit and watch videotape of
games, that's not going to make them better officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bergman, retired after 30 years as an NFL head linesman,
doesn't believe full-time officials would make for better
officiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get game experience from watching films,'' said
Bergman, reached by phone Monday night at his home in Pittsburgh.
``You only get experience by working games, and there are only so
many games. It's not like baseball, basketball, and hockey. Do you
think the New England Patriots would like to see, oh, seven
officials standing on the sidelines watching over their practices
two and three days a week? Of course they wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Aiello added that Young often has said over the years that he
likes the fact that the league's on-field officials are not part of
the NFL corporate mainstream. Their independence from the league,
in that sense, could be viewed as an asset, eliminating suspicion
that they could be corrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if we went (exclusively) to full-time officials, we'd
likely lose a lot of good people,'' said Aiello. ``Some of the
people working our games are lawyers, business executives,
educators, admininstrators. Many of them wouldn't want to give up
that part of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It might help _ sometimes
</P>
<P>
   Two other highly controversial calls came to the fore Nov. 28
when the Bills faced the Patriots in Foxborough, a game New England
won, 25-21, with no time on the clock after the officiating crew
penalized the Bills for pass interference in the end zone. On the
play prior to the interference call, the officials let stand a
catch by Patriots receiver Shawn Jefferson, on which television
replays showed he was out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Replay, if brought back as it was used earlier in the decade,
could have been applied on the pass to Jefferson, said Young.
However, he said, it would not have been implemented on the Hail
Mary pass to Bledsoe that triggered the interference call. Judgment
calls, such as pass interference, holding, and illegal contact,
would not be reviewable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem with using replay before was that it was
viewed as a panacea,'' said Young. ``We wanted to eliminate every
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergman was no fan of replay when it was used, and he remains
against the idea of bringing it back.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
