</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PLAYOFFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF PICTURE OPAQUE WITH MEDIOCRITY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are so many losing, undeserving teams still in the
National Football Conference playoff hunt one would think the game
officials were calling the race.
</P>
<P>
   But even instant replay couldn't fix a situation that has five
losing teams _ none with more than six victories _ chasing the
final wild-card spot in the conference. It's a playoff race so
clumsy that the 5-8 Giants are still in it.
</P>
<P>
   If the Giants could somehow defeat Denver at Giants Stadium on
Sunday, you could even call them contenders because an NFC team
with an 8-8 record by season's end could practically be the runaway
winner for the third wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   While they're flailing away in the NFC, the American Football
Conference picture is a contrast in proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   If the season ended today, four AFC East teams &UR; _ &LR;  the Jets,
Miami, New England and Buffalo &UR; _ &LR;  would qualify for the playoffs.
Three winning teams from other AFC divisions _ Pittsburgh,
Tennessee and Oakland _ would be excluded.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets win at Miami this weekend, they clinch a playoff
berth. And if they go on to win one of two remaining games after
that, they win their first division title in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent for one division claiming all the wild-card
spots _ the NFC Central sent four teams to the playoffs in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out the current NFC playoff possibilities, however, is
far from a study in aptitude. Before Monday night's Green Bay-Tampa
Bay game, the 6-7 Arizona Cardinals would qualify for the playoffs
over New Orleans (6-7) or the Buccaneers (5-7 entering Monday's
game) because of a slightly superior conference record.
</P>
<P>
   For the Cardinals, it would be their first post-season
appearance in a nonstrike season since 1975, when they lost a
division playoff game. The Cardinals franchise, which has been in
the National Football League for 79 seasons, has established an
amazing penchant for avoiding the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   They have qualified for the post-season only five times and have
only one playoff victory, a league championship won 51 years ago
when the then Chicago Cardinals defeated Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The other ``contenders'' for the final NFC wild-card spot are an
assortment of teams struggling to make something positive of
otherwise gloomy seasons. One of them seems poised to become the
first .500 team to qualify for the playoffs since the 1991 Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Saints put themselves back in the playoff picture with their
surprising rout of Dallas Sunday afternoon, a remarkable turnaround
for a team that had lost seven of its previous nine games. New
Orleans' victory sets up a pivotal game at Arizona on Dec. 20, if
you can call a game between two teams that could have losing
records pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans plays host to high-flying Atlanta this weekend and
the Buffalo Bills on the final Sunday of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Cardinals, the Saints are dogged by some sorry
post-season history. New Orleans has never won a playoff game in
four attempts.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, the 5-8 Lions have won only one road game and are
yielding an average of 23 points a game. They had a three-game
winning streak halted Sunday at Jacksonville, and with a poor
conference record (4-6) they are not well positioned to challenge
Arizona, New Orleans or Tampa Bay, who each already have at least
five conference victories.
</P>
<P>
   Conference record is the second tie-breaker after the
head-to-head record between teams.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit may also have the most difficult remaining schedule: at
San Francisco on Monday night, home to Atlanta and at Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay, which was considered a sure playoff team during the
preseason, is home against Pittsburgh on Sunday and finishes its
season at Washington and at Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the Giants. Their conference record is poor
(4-7), but if they somehow tied with the Cardinals _ and only the
Cardinals _ they would advance because they defeated the Cardinals
twice this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not mathematically eliminated, so we're still fighting
for the playoffs,'' Giants Coach Jim Fassel said after his team's
victory in Arizona on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if, practically speaking, he considered his team part of
the playoff chase, Fassel, perhaps with a nod to Yogi Berra, said:
``Until you're out of it, you're in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
