<SLUG> BC-INTUIT-Y2K-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEAR 2000 SUIT AGAINST INTUIT IS DISMISSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Online banking functions in some versions of Intuit Inc.'s
Quicken personal-finance software may stumble when the year 2000
arrives, but this is no basis for suing Intuit now, said a New York
state judge who dismissed three class-action lawsuits against the
company last week.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Ira Gammerman's ruling that software companies cannot be
sued for Year 2000 problems before actual damage has occurred
echoed the conclusions reached in August by a Santa Clara County
judge in California in the first such suit against Intuit.
Gammerman also said software companies cannot be sued before being
given a chance to fix year 2000 problems.
</P>
<P>
   Intuit has announced that Quicken upgrades that prevent the year
2000 problems will be available without charge by June.
</P>
<P>
   The cases have been closely watched by lawyers, who say similar
suits could generate $1 trillion in damages and fees if the year
2000 date transition creates widespread computer problems, as has
been widely predicted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
