<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7500 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLANKETS-AZR &LR;      12-07 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLANKETS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLANKETS FOR HOMELESS IN SHORT SUPPLY AS PHOENIX TEMPERATURES
DROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ On the coldest nights, as many as 40 blankets are
given to homeless teenagers, their only protection against the
wind. But the stash of blankets at Homebase Youth Services _ as
well as at other Arizona non-profit agencies _ is running low, and
soon there could be no blankets to hand out.
</P>
<P>
   In a cost-cutting measure, Congress this year eliminated Project
Freeze, a federal program that provided blankets to non-profits
that deal with homeless people and others in need.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the state received 29,000 blankets from the program,
said Vic Hudenko, homeless coordinator at the state Department of
Economic Security. This year, it didn't get any.
</P>
<P>
   State officials did manage to squeeze some money out of the DES
budget to buy 2,928 discount blankets from a mill in North
Carolina. They arrived in Arizona on Friday and were distributed
Monday _ too late for Sunday's cold snap, when temperatures dropped
into the 30s throughout metropolitan Phoenix. So, with shelters
crammed, many people spent the night on the street uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt so bad that they didn't arrive on time,'' Hudenko said.
``We just didn't expect it to get this cold this fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Agencies in Tucson have been hit the hardest. They asked DES for
8,000 blankets and received 1,000 of the newly arrived shipment,
Hudenko said, leaving even more people out in the cold.
</P>
<P>
   Most Phoenix agencies will go without. Those who work directly
with people living on the streets will get first dibs on the
blankets distributed in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates are that there are 10,000 homeless people in the
Valley and 15,000 statewide, though agencies that work with that
population say those figures are probably too low.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Homebase _ which helps homeless young people with
food, shelter, clothing, counseling and other services _ received
300 blankets. This year, it got none.
</P>
<P>
   The kids don't care what color the blanket is or even if there
is a hole or two in it, said Kristin Bolken, director of outreach
services for Homebase. They just care that it's warm.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in temperatures this week _ including light snowfall in
central Phoenix on Sunday _ left more blue-lipped teenagers than
usual clamoring for blankets, as many as 40 in one night instead of
the usual five or six. All did manage to get a blanket, but the
supply won't last long, Bolken said.
</P>
<P>
   At Central Arizona Shelter Services Inc., a non-profit homeless
shelter at 1209 W. Madison St., workers are having to refuse people
looking for a place to stay, and they don't have enough blankets to
supply those turned away.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, CASS received 900 blankets through Project Freeze.
Like Homebase, it got none this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're appealing to the public for help,'' said
David Hammond, director of development for CASS. ``If anyone wants
to donate any blankets or warm clothing _ hats, coats, gloves _ we
need everything we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   One woman gave CASS 100 blankets that she had purchased at
thrift stores, even having them cleaned before dropping them off.
</P>
<P>
   Wool-blend blankets are best for outdoors, although shelters
also need blankets for beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time of year it is very critical,'' Hammond says. ``The
cold weather came on suddenly _ I know it caught me off guard _ and
I could imagine that for a person who chooses to live on the
street, it must be devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Vincent de Paul Society, one of the Valley's largest
non-profit agencies serving the homeless, received a truckload of
blankets last week to distribute to its programs, community
relations director Jennifer Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency has not yet experienced a shortage, Walker said,
though this is the first major cold spell of the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Karina Bland can be reached at 444-8614 or by e-mail at
karina.bland(at)pni.com &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
