<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REFEREES-NYT &LR;      12-07 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REFEREES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL WANTS INSTANT REPLAY USED IN PLAYOFFS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The National Football League said Monday that it
would ask owners to vote on instant replay for the playoffs and the
Super Bowl, a decision that came barely 24 hours after an official
ruled incorrectly that the Jets' Vinny Testaverde had scored the
game-winning touchdown against Seattle with 20 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   The system would permit coaches two challenges a game and would
most likely include a provision allowing referees to review a
disputed play within the last two minutes of a game after a coach's
challenges have been expended.
</P>
<P>
   Such a system would have enabled Seattle Coach Dennis Erickson
to challenge the ruling by Earnie Frantz, the head linesman at the
Seahawks-Jets game, that Testaverde had scored on a quarterback
sneak. The television replay definitively showed that the ball did
not break the plane of the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's greatest fear is what happened yesterday happening
in the Super Bowl,'' said Greg Aiello, a league spokesman. He
added, ``We acknowledge today again that Testaverde hasn't
scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Changes to the rules governing games are generally adopted
during the off season, and the league's decision to call for an
in-season adjustment reflected the seriousness of the situation,
and the league's acknowledgment that the credibility of its
competition was being compromised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're aware of what's going on and the reaction to it, and
we're trying to be responsive,'' said Aiello, who added, ``We're
doing this quickly, but not in a panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar proposals to reinstitute instant replay have failed with
owners before the past two seasons, falling short of the 23
required votes. Now, with a 31st team, the Cleveland Browns, the
proposal will need 24 votes to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has not set a date for the vote but intends to spend the
next few days framing the proposal. The issue, as it has before, is
certain to generate intense debate over the imposition of
technology on human judgment, and the added burden on coaches to
manage replay challenges as they do timeouts, and do it for the
first time in the playoff pressure cooker.
</P>
<P>
   Aiello said the league canvassed the nine teams that spurned
instant replay last March, and ``several who voted against it
voiced a desire to vote for it for the post-season, as an insurance
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue and his senior staff met for several
hours to discuss the proposal, amid intense pressure from aggrieved
teams, the news media and fans to bring back some form of instant
replay. It was in effect from 1986 to 1991.
</P>
<P>
   One vote that Tagliabue can count on will come from Ralph
Wilson, the Buffalo Bills' owner who voted against the use of
instant replay last March. ``Anything is better than we have now,''
Wilson said. ``Jeez, I'll vote for somebody spotting the calls
going over the field from a blimp.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson raged at the league last week for ``awful'' officiating
in last Sunday's game against New England; Tagliabue subsequently
told him that he would be fined $50,000, leading Wilson to
fulminate, saying: ``I do know I don't need pompous lectures from
the commissioner, and I feel that the $50,000 is not only
unwarranted, but punitive in nature. The next time, he may ask me
to stand in the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners are specifically prohibited from criticizing officials.
</P>
<P>
   The other teams that voted against instant replay last March
were Arizona, Chicago, Cincinnati, Kansas City, the Giants,
Oakland, San Diego and Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets voted for replay last March, a reversal of a previous
position. How the Jets vote for the playoff proposal remains to be
seen. Monday, Coach Bill Parcells said: ``I don't want the old
system back. I don't want coaches' challenges. I only want the
calls right.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Moore, a spokesman for Kansas City, said that Chiefs Coach
Marty Schottenheimer opposes the challenge system ``because it puts
coaches in the official business.'' Jack Brennan, a Bengals
spokesman, said that Mike Brown, the team owner, always felt too
much time was spent on replay in its earlier incarnation without
much of a result _ ``and sometimes it wasn't even right.''
</P>
<P>
   But Carmen Policy, the Browns' president and a longtime advocate
of instant replay when he was the 49ers' president, said he will
vote for the plan. But he added: ``What concerns me is it might not
be staged as positively as if it had more time. I hope this doesn't
hurt it going into effect next season.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the past two weeks of criticism of league officiating,
which began with the botched coin-toss at the Pittsburgh-Detroit
game on Nov. 26, had turned the tide of league thinking toward
trying to bring instant replay back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if we didn't have instant replay for the playoffs, I
think the chances of voting it in in March were good,'' Policy
said. ``But if it goes well in the playoffs, it's a slam dunk for
March.''
</P>
<P>
   The league has experimented with the challenge system in 10
games each in the 1996 and 1998 preseasons. In that system, coaches
received two challenges. If they used a challenge during the last
two minutes of each half, they were penalized with a timeout if
their claim was proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The system was a compromise between the 1997 plan that failed to
get enough votes, in which each challenge cost a timeout, and the
1998 plan, which also fell short of approval, in which a timeout
was lost if the challenge proved wrong.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden, the Fox Sports commentator, and a critic of league
officiating, said: ``You just hope the league's ready to implement
the system and do it right. What's happened during the last two
weeks, is the league's become vulnerable. The pile is open and you
can pile on.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, the new proposal is expected to limit challenges
to plays involving ball possession; in-bounds calls; whether a
touchdown is a touchdown; whether a ball has been fumbled, and
whether a ball was actually caught.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a possible return to instant replay, the 16
officiating teams of seven men apiece _ who are paid $1,431 to
$4,300 for regular season games and $11,900 each for the Super Bowl
_ will still be the subject of carping by unhappy coaches, players
and owners. Not every questionable call, like penalties, would be
covered by instant replay's parameters.
</P>
<P>
   If the league returns to instant replay, it would join the
National Hockey League as the only major sport to have it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
