<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7505 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORGON-SPI &LR;      12-07 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORGON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSSIL FOUND OF GORGONOPSID, PRE-DINOSAUR RULER OF EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the top predator on Earth hundreds of millions of years
before Tyrannosaurus Rex and so horribly ugly it almost makes you
happy for mass extinctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of the biggest, most ferocious lion you can imagine, but
with lizard skin,'' said Peter Ward, a University of Washington
paleontologist.
</P>
<P>
   It's a gorgonopsid, or gorgon, named after the beast of Greek
mythology whose terrifying gaze would turn anyone who looked at it
into stone.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and Roger Smith, a paleontologist at the South African
Museum in Capetown, have discovered what is believed to be the only
complete fossil ever found of this half-mammal, half-reptilian
creature that ruled the land before dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's absolutely fabulous,'' said Robert Bakker, the maverick
paleontologist made famous as the inspirational model for the lead
character in the movie Jurassic Park. ``It's an incredibly
important find.''
</P>
<P>
   James Hopson, a University of Chicago expert in these ancient
``mammal-like reptiles,'' said the discovery of a complete gorgon
skeleton is exciting because it will provide new information about
this strange creature and perhaps even new insights into the debate
over whether dinosaurs were warm-blooded.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a skeletal structure that shows an upright gait
indicates a faster metabolism, which would suggest the creature was
warm-blooded.
</P>
<P>
   Bakker, a leading proponent of the warm-blooded theory, is
looking for evidence that gorgons were these fast-moving,
warm-blooded predators. If so, he contends evolution wouldn't have
favored cold-blooded dinosaurs to take over as top predator after
the reign of the gorgons.
</P>
<P>
   Hopson says the evidence on both gorgons and dinosaurs, so far,
tends to support a ``lukewarm'' attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were something in between,'' he said. ``Not fully
warm-blooded but not cold-blooded either.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all still debatable, he said, but perhaps Ward and Smith's
new find in the Karoo Desert of South Africa will shift the debate
in favor of one side or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``This appears to be a very complete skeleton and an enormous
one for this kind of animal,'' Hopson said. He talked to Smith over
the weekend about the find, who estimated the creature to be about
seven feet long.
</P>
<P>
   The largest gorgons weighed as much as 800 pounds, though some
were as small as house cats. They were the first saber-toothed
animals on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things were really well-adapted killing machines,''
Hopson said. ``They had blade-like and serrated teeth that could go
through your flesh like a warm knife through butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorgons were wiped out by one of the planet's massive
extinctions, the worst one known, which occurred some 250 million
years ago. Ward, funded by the National Science Foundation, has
been in the Karoo Desert looking for fossil evidence from this time
period known as the Late Permian.
</P>
<P>
   This was about 50 million years before dinosaurs appeared on
Earth, when the planet's continental land masses had yet to drift
apart from the primordial supercontinent known as Pangaea.
</P>
<P>
   The Karoo Desert is one of the best places to dig for fossils
older than 250 million years because it was a basin that rapidly
filled in with sediment _ preserving the dead _ and has remained
relatively undisturbed by geological change since then.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and Smith's expedition in the Karoo, which began in a
snowstorm and ended in blistering heat weeks ago, was focused on
finding fossil evidence of the planet's worst mass extinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest question is about the rapidity of that
extinction,'' Ward said. Their digging, he said, was focused on
establishing how quickly species died off during the largest mass
extinction ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows what caused this massive die-off, but it killed all
the gorgons and much of the rest of life on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Just below the sedimentary level marking the extinction, Ward
said, are numerous fossils telling of a world full of activity and
diverse forms of life. Just above this geological demarcation, Ward
said, the sediment is empty. Signs of life are disturbingly
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is there,'' Smith said. ``That's what Peter and I were
looking at ... We want to know what happened just before and just
after the extinction event. We weren't looking for gorgons.''
</P>
<P>
   Their project was drawing to a close several weeks ago, after
the team had already spent a month in the desert and collected some
70 fossil skeletons. On a walk, Smith spotted a small scrap of bone
sticking out of the dirt. He dug a bit more and could see that it
appeared to be the skull of a gorgon.
</P>
<P>
   Ward joined him in the digging and, with every new inch of
skeleton uncovered, their interest blossomed into the full-blown
ecstatic thrill of a major discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some here in South Africa are calling it the find of the
century,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good probability it was buried with its skin
intact,'' Smith said. That would be a major discovery by itself,
Smith said, because one of the areas of debate on gorgons is
whether they had scaly skin like reptiles or leathery skin like
mammals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the thing's complete is probably of most
importance to paleontology,'' Ward said. ``We're looking at a key
transitional animal here, the top predator of the Permian world.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be many people interested in having a look at this
gorgon, Ward said, because a complete skeleton promises answers to
many more questions.
</P>
<P>
   Bakker wanted to know if the fossil's toes were all there and
the structure of its limbs, since these both offer clues to how it
moved _ which offers clues about warm-bloodedness. Hopson seemed
interested in finding out if the feet were intact.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's special interest is in coprolites, fossilized excrement.
He's hoping to find these in the belly of the gorgon, which will
provide crucial dietary information.
</P>
<P>
   But it will be months before even these simple questions can be
answered, and years before the fossil is fully prepared for public
display.
</P>
<P>
   Ward and Smith's team couldn't remove the large fossil with the
field equipment they brought with them. So they re-buried it _
making it appear to be a human grave to discourage curious digging
_ and will return next spring with the larger equipment needed to
excavate it.
</P>
<P>
   Time reversed the Greek myth in this case, turning the gorgon to
stone and rewarding mankind's curiousity with a new look into the
deep past.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really cool,'' Ward said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-07-98 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
