u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      12-07 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS LUXURY SEAT DEAL TO GET SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to head off any dissent at Wednesday's public hearing on
their proposal to lure the New England Patriots to Hartford,
Connecticut officials Monday said they are taking a second look at
a controversial part of the plan in which the state would guarantee
the sale of expensive luxury seats at the new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That guarantee, one of the most financially lucrative aspects of
the deal for team owner Robert Kraft, could cost the state $175
million over 10 years if the team cannot sell the seats outright.
Under a preliminary agreement Kraft signed with the state last
month, the state would pay him $2,500 for each of the 4,000 club
seats unsold out of the 6,000 expected to be built; and $100,000
for each of the 75 luxury suites not sold among the 150 expected to
be built. In a worst-case scenario, the state would be forced to
pay Kraft $17.5 million a year for the duration of the lease.
</P>
<P>
   But those numbers may be revised before the deal goes before the
public at Wednesday's scheduled hearing at the Connecticut State
House.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guarantee is the last remaining part that's generating a
lot of discussion,'' said House Speaker Thomas Ritter. ``We're
trying our best to keep the agreement intact. But they are talking
about the guarantee and that may be something we're going to have
to take a look it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kraft and Governor John Rowland have said they expect
the memorandum of understanding both signed Nov. 19 to be approved
by the Legislature unchanged, other specifics in the document could
come under scrutiny, officials said Monday. The General Assembly is
scheduled to vote on the package next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other issues being scrutinized is the 30-year
commitment Kraft made to keep the team in Hartford. Moira Lyons of
Stamford, the majority leader, has successfully lobbied to tighten
the exit clause on the 30-year lease to include early withdrawal
penalties. Should Kraft move the team before the 30 years were up,
he would have to pay for any unpaid portion of the stadium debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we talk today, there have been no changes,'' said Patriots
vice president Jonathan Kraft. ``Our deal is, we're there for 30
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's hearing is expected to be a marathon session. The
first four hours are reserved for proponents of the deal and
consultants.First up will be Kraft, Rowland, and KPMG Peat Marwick
consultants whose report showed the state would break even on the
$350 million-plus stadium project, which the state will pay for
entirely through borrowing, ticket taxes, and perhaps a portion of
the revenue surplus. They are already gearing their testimony
toward defending some of the more controversial issues, including
the seat guarantees, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be good to let people know how negotiations went,''
Ritter said. ``For instance, originally, Kraft asked to have every
seat guaranteed. The governor said no. It will be good for people
to see how we came to that deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft is expected to reveal how much money he expects to take in
from the stadium. Because NFL teams shares most other revenues,
stadium deals are the most important factor in a team's bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium revenue in 2002, Kraft said in documents provided to
Rowland's office, will be about $56 million a year. This includes
$18 million in regular ticket sales and $18 million in club seat
sales if all are sold. The team will get about $9 million from
playing at other venues and, if all luxury boxes are sold, the team
will get $11.25 million in revenue a year.
</P>
<P>
   TV and radio revenue will total about $85 million per club,
including Internet and satellite television; $9 million in
advertising, including $1 million to $2 million in possible naming
rights; and $6 million in net revenue from concessions. The total:
$157 million in net revenue.
</P>
<P>
   But after paying taxes, giving visiting teams their share of
gate proceeds, player payroll of $102 million, coaching, staff and
$6 million in operational expenses, Kraft says the team will be
left with about $16 million a year _ money he says would help pay
for signing bonuses and other factors to make the team more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, this year the team took in a little more than $90
million in revenue, including $23 million in annual gate proceeds,
$2.5 million in luxury suite sales, $62 million in TV and radio
deals, $5 million in advertising and $2 million in concessions,
according to individuals close to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the team paid players about $65 million and spent
another $22 million in team expenses, including other staff and
travel, and operational expenses for the stadium are about $4
million, totaling $91 million, making the team just about a
break-even enterprise, those individuals said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Rowland spokesman Dean Pagani, the governor will be
the first witness called before the legislative panel Wednesday at
3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are bracing for the largest public hearing in recent
memory. The hearing will be held in the biggest room designed for
such functions at the Capitol, with other areas wired with closed
circuit television to handle the overflow crowd, which could be
watching the proceedings unfold until well after 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The last time so many people crammed a hearing was in 1991, when
the state took the historic step of instituting an income tax,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kraft's testimony will be important because people still want
to see how serious he is,'' said Larry Perosino, a spokesman for
the House Democrats. ``I think he'll explain why he feels it's a
great thing for Hartford and the state to have the Patriots come
and that if he thought it was bad for the taxpayers he wouldn't
have gone for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the hearing will address all questions raised so far,
including environmental and financial concerns, and timing issues
surrounding the move, which is targeted for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the questions, though, the bill is expected to pass
easily next week, mostly because it is the centerpiece of a $1
billion downtown revitalization that the legislature has already
enthusiastically endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   More than 80 percent of Republicans and at least half the
Democrats are expected to approve the stadium plan.
</P>
<P>
   There are opponents, however, though many of them will not be
heard from until later in the hearing, well after the 6 p.m.
newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's unfair,'' said Debbie Weinstein, a retired shop
owner from Essex, ``if they give all the daytime hours to the
people who are speaking for it and make the opposition wait 'til
the evening . . . that is not a fair way of structuring this.''
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein and group of friends from southern Connecticut plan to
attend the hearing to voice their concern over what they view as
``corporate welfare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
