<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-AD-COLUMN-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: OPTIMISTIC OUTLOOKS FOR '99 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The light at the end of the tunnel may not be an
approaching freight train after all, two respected forecasters of
advertising spending predicted Monday in offering optimistic
outlooks for 1999 despite the recent concern about worldwide
economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Coen, senior vice president and forecasting director at
McCann-Erickson USA in New York, and John Perriss, chairman and
chief executive at Zenith Media Worldwide in London, presented
their upbeat assessments at the opening session of the 26th annual
Paine Webber Media Conference. The conference, at the McGraw-Hill
Building in midtown Manhattan, continues through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The peaks and valleys of advertising expenditures by marketers
in the media are carefully followed because they are considered an
important gauge of the strength of the economy. The global
financial difficulties since the summer _ particularly in Asia,
Latin America and Russia _ had thrown into doubt earlier forecasts
made by Coen and Perriss about the robustness of ad spending next
year.
</P>
<P>
   But in their presentations, Coen and Perriss agreed that barring
any drastic worsening of the world economies _ particularly
disruptions in the United States or Europe _ ad spending ought to
reach record levels in 1999. And Perriss predicted accelerating
rates of growth through 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think 1999 will be a pretty good year for advertising,''
Coen said. ``Not as good as 1998, but still a good year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the percentage gain for 1999 will be the lowest in
six years, he added, ``the overall trend certainly looks better
than any of us thought possible'' during the steep stock market
slump in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for the improved outlook, said Coen, who has
been tracking advertising and media trends since 1948, is that
American consumers ``will be in a position to feel fairly secure
and spend'' as a result of low inflation rates and low
unemployment. Ad spending closely tracks consumer spending and as
American ad spending goes, so usually goes worldwide ad spending.
</P>
<P>
   Perriss, who sometimes differs with Coen in his forecasts,
echoed him.
</P>
<P>
   Though ``there are some cautionary clouds on the horizon,''
Perriss said, ``broadly, I'm not going to say anything to
contradict Bob's pretty great outlook.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In September, we were looking for pretty grim times in 1999
and 2000,'' he added. ``Thankfully, I am able to stand here today
and say that's not our view.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the very worst has now passed in Asia,'' Perriss
said. ``Nineteen ninety-eight was our `soft landing' and in 1999 we
will go forward virtually everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Coen predicted that marketers would spend a record $212 billion
in the United States next year, an increase of 5.5 percent from the
$200.8 billion that he now forecasts for 1998. The 1998 figure
represents a 7.1 percent gain from the $187.5 billion spent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The 5.5 percent increase for 1999 would be the smallest in
percentage terms since a 5.2 percent increase in 1993. Still,
advertising as a percentage of gross domestic product in 1999 would
reach 2.40 percent. That would set a record, beating the figure of
2.36 percent for 1998. Before this year, the record had been 2.35
percent in 1987 and 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Coen's figure of $200.8 billion for 1998 marked the third time
he had raised his forecast for the year since an original
prediction in June 1997 of $196.5 billion. That was increased to
$198.4 billion in December 1997 and to $200.3 billion in June. Coen
adjusts his figures every time he makes a semiannual forecast,
based on updated data.
</P>
<P>
   Among the national media that Coen predicted would do
particularly well in 1999 are cable television, radio, syndicated
television and newspapers. Among the local media, he cited radio
and television, fueled by growth in retail advertising from store
openings.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas in 1999, Coen forecasts ad spending of $223.9 billion,
up 3.5 percent from a revised figure of $216.3 billion for 1998.
The figure for this year marked the third time that Coen revised
downward his total for international ad spending.
</P>
<P>
   The figure of $223.9 billion is lower than a prediction of
$228.2 billion made by Coen in June. That reflects continued
ad-spending weakness in countries such as Indonesia, Japan,
Malaysia and South Korea, which he said would offset strength in,
say, Hungary and Poland.
</P>
<P>
   Coen's worldwide total for 1999, then, is $435.9 billion, which
would represent an increase of 4.5 percent from a revised worldwide
total of $417.1 billion in 1998 _ the first time world ad spending
has exceeded $400 billion. The 1998 figure marks an increase of 4.9
percent from the $397.5 billion spent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Perriss, who uses a different methodology, tracking only major
media, said the Asian economic tumult had caused him to shave about
$3 billion off his prediction for 1998 worldwide ad spending, which
now totals $300.3 billion, and about $7 billion from his forecast
for 1999, which now totals $312.9 billion. Last December, he
predicted that the 1998 total would be $317.8 billion and the 1999
total would be $336.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, his revised forecasts are ``pretty optimistic
against where we thought things would be'' at the deepest point of
the summer gloom when ``great horrors'' were foreseen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To illustrate that, when Perriss mentioned Russia, he said,
smiling, ``That's a word I've hardly heard mentioned in the last
six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``all forecasts are highly dependent on the United States
continuing to grow,'' Perriss said. ``A hiccup here, a loss of
consumer confidence here, and it will change around these
forecasts.''
</P>
<P>
   The worldwide total of $300.3 billion for 1998 from Perriss is
up only 1.9 percent from the 1997 total of $289.1 billion, which he
said was the smallest gain since the recession of the early 1990s.
But the gains are then to increase from year to year in constant
prices, he added, to 2.2 percent in 1999, 2.5 percent in 2000
($329.5 billion) and 2.7 percent in 2001 ($348.7 billion).
</P>
<P>
   Among reasons listed by Perriss for those gains were
accelerating economic growth in European nations like Germany and
Italy and recoveries in some economically battered Asian markets.
There will be a stronger second half in 1999 than a first half, he
said, as Asia gradually recovers from the problems of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   McCann-Erickson is part of McCann-Erickson World Group, a unit
of Interpublic Group of Cos. Zenith is a joint venture of Cordiant
Communications Group PLC and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC.
</P>
</TEXT>
