<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7517 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      12-07 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Robertson Stephens Fund Group Fetches a Paltry $20 Million  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
What's in a name?
</P>
<P>
   Roughly $10 million if you happen to be BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   The Beantown bank has agreed to pay $10 million to the
management buyout group led by Robertson Stephens Investment
Management President Randy Hecht for undisputed rights to the
Robbie Stephens moniker, BankBoston sources confirm.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, of course, shelled out about $800 million to buy the
former Robertson Stephens brokerage and trading units last summer
from Bank of America, leaving the money management arm of Robertson
Stephens to fend for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, the fund group still had dibs on the Robertson
Stephens brand name, and that didn't sit well with BankBoston's
brass. In fact, failing to secure total control of the brand
bothered BankBoston enough for it to seriously consider buying the
entire fund group, investment banking sources say.
</P>
<P>
   However, once BankBoston's bid for the fund group was derailed,
the bank opted to settle for acquisition of just the name from
Hecht's buyout group.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why the Hecht-led LBO has agreed to cede the
``Robertson Stephens'' name in exchange for &UR;  &LR; its new name: RS
Funds. (It should be noted that the name change had been mulled by
previous management for a few years.)
</P>
<P>
   The $10 million price tag for the nameplate will cover half of
the nearly $20 million that Hecht has agreed to pay for the entire
fund business.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the new Bank of America (formerly NationsBank) is
so eager to unload the leftover fund group that it is willing to do
the deal for nearly nothing. In addition, the severely slashed
price tag is also indicative of the degree to which the performance
of the Robbie fund complex has slumped.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America has agreed to Hecht's LBO bid for the struggling
fund group, but there are still plenty of loose ends to the
transaction, including how many of the funds' well-known portfolio
managers are going to work for Hecht after the buyout. Most of the
portfolio managers' contracts expire at the end of 1998. A date for
a Bank of America board vote on the sale of the fund group has not
yet been announced, a Bank of America spokesman says.
</P>
<P>
   What's even more intriguing is that Bank of America considered
pulling the plug on the funds. As it turns out, internecine rivalry
within the premerger Robertson Stephens family almost derailed
Hecht's LBO bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the possibility that Bank of America was going to
shut down the fund business,'' a BankBoston source says.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, Robertson Stephens co-founder Sandy Robertson
aligned with Robertson Stephens Investment Management fund manager
Jim Callinan to make unsuccessful multiple bids for parts of the
fund group, according to sources at BancBoston Robertson Stephens,
Bank of America and Robertson Stephens Investment Management.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, there is little love lost between Robertson, who no
longer works for any current incarnations of his former firm, and
Hecht. Few dispute that Sandy Robertson and Callinan discussed
putting together buyout bids to counter Hecht's initiatives. But
after that, the picture gets a little murky as to whether Callinan
approached Robertson or the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the competing bids divided sentiment among the fund
managers to the extent that it was difficult for either side to
garner majority support for their proposals, sources say. Sandy
Robertson was unavailable for comment, and Callinan referred
inquiries to a spokesman at BofA, which is his current employer.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite their differences behind closed doors, Hecht and
Callinan are now doing their best to display a unified front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect Mr. Callinan to play a senior executive role at the
new group,'' says Hecht through a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``(And) I am working closely with (Jim) to craft a new
organization that will serve our clients and shareholders well,''
Hecht states.
</P>
<P>
   Question is: How many of Callinan's money-manager colleagues
will go along for the ride?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
