<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7521 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIOSTOX-SFCHRON &LR;      12-07 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSTOX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Bottom-Fishing in Biotech  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Biotech stock indexes have risen as much as 60 percent this year,
leaving little apparent room for bargain hunters.
</P>
<P>
   What the indexes don't tell you is that the biotech market has
split like a strand of DNA. The top-tier companies that dominate
the indexes, such as Genentech, Chiron and Amgen, have soared. But
midsize and smaller biotech firms have actually stagnated or lost
ground this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 20 or so largest stocks have done very well,'' said Mark
Lambert, who manages the Biotechnology Value Fund in San Francisco.
``But going forward, I believe the greatest values and the biggest
returns are going to be from the small stocks that have been left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambert and others believe the bottom half of the industry may
be poised for a comeback, largely because many of these overlooked
companies have drugs that are close to being approved.
</P>
<P>
   Since the industry was born, about 100 biotech drugs have been
approved. Today, more than 200 products are awaiting U.S. marketing
approval, according to consulting firm Ernst &AMP; Young.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the rule of thumb holds true, and just one in five
candidates passes FDA review, that still leaves 40 or more winners
out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 20 years in this business, I've never seen a better crop of
promising young startups,'' said Scott Morrison, a biotech industry
consultant with Ernst &AMP; Young in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Small stocks have been shunned largely because Wall Street's
volume traders _ institutions and mutual funds _ cannot buy them
without affecting their price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big funds need to move large blocks of money in and out of
stocks quickly, and a lot of biotech issues just don't have the
market cap or the trading value to make this possible,'' Morrison
said.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison thinks a biotech firm needs to have a market value of
$200 million to $250 million to catch institutions' attention.
Other analysts think it takes a market cap of $500 million or even
$1 billion to interest big money managers.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cutoff point, the fact is that out of nearly 400
publicly traded biotech firms, 250 to 350 have been left out of the
stock rebound that has occurred since September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to think that a rising tide lifted all ships,'' said
David Flores, publisher of the BioCentury industry newsletter in
San Carlos. ``Now, what you see is that the market cap makes a huge
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't be misled into thinking that picking biotech winners
is as easy as hooking the minnows that have slipped through Wall
Street's net.
</P>
<P>
   Flores said it can take a biotech firm 10 years to take a
promising biotechnology drug through the three phases of scientific
trials that the Food and Drug Administration requires a drug to
pass before it can be sold to the public.
</P>
<P>
   During that long development cycle, which can cost up to $250
million, most biotech firms run in the red, using proceeds from
venture capital and stock sales to cover their losses.
</P>
<P>
   That means biotech shareholders must wait and worry that factors
ranging from unexpected scientific setbacks to the vagaries of
FDA's drug review process could sink the company.
</P>
<P>
   Flores likened investing in young biotech firms to putting money
into one of the mercantile companies of 17th century Europe. Both
investments were bets on explorations into the unknown, be it the
frontiers of science or the passage around Cape Horn.
</P>
<P>
   As Flores said: ``Once those ships went out over the horizon,
you never knew when or whether they'd return.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the unusual risks and long lead times of investing in
small biotech firms, Karen Bernstein, editor of the BioCentury
newsletter, suggested wannabe investors ask themselves this
question: ``Is this money I can afford to lose?''
</P>
<P>
   If the answer is yes, and you can stand the risks, investing in
the small biotech firms overlooked by Wall Street could lead to big
returns in the long run, said Matt Berry, a biotech analyst with
the Medical Technology Stock Letter in Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of young companies that have drugs in pivotal
Phase III trials that we think are undervalued by the market,''
Berry said. ``A lot of them have tiny share prices, but they can
shoot up in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the issues his newsletter recommends are these two small
and one midsize companies:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Immunogen.  &LR; This Massachusetts firm is in the very early
stages of testing a new cancer-fighting technique that targets
tumor cells directly, promising fewer side effects. The stock
gained 3 cents yesterday to close at $2.19.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Cor Therapeutics.  &LR; The South San Francisco firm recently won
FDA approval to sell Integrilin, a drug that can be used to scour
blood vessels of plaque, perhaps in conjunction with angioplasty.
Integrilin competes with similar drugs from Merck and Centacor. The
stock, which was below $10 last month, slipped 44 cents to close at
$12.31 yesterday. ``We still think there's lotsa room for it to
move,'' Berry said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Agouron.  &LR; This midsize biotech firm based in La Jolla (San
Diego) is making a run for the top tier. Its anti-AIDS drug,
Viracept, grossed $466.50 million in fiscal 1998. ``That was the
most ever for a biotech drug in its first year,'' Berry said. With
other promising compounds in the works, Berry thinks it's a bargain
at $47.88. The stock gained $2.38 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts declined to share their picks and pans but did
offer some tips for how to research young biotech firms:
</P>
<P>
   _ Check the company's market cap and trading volume. The smaller
these numbers are, the less likely the company is going to get
noticed by Wall Street, which could mean you'll hold the stock a
long time before seeing a gain.
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure the company has at least two years worth of cash on
hand to cover its current rate of annual expenses (called the burn
rate).
</P>
<P>
   _ Try to find companies with more than one or two promising
drugs going through the clinical trial process.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be prepared for plenty of ups and downs. Investing in a small
biotech firm is like pulling chance cards in a Monopoly game.
Unexpected news events, like the success or failure of a clinical
trial, could double _ or halve _ the value of your shares in a day.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if picking individual issues seems too daunting,
Morningstar, the mutual fund tracking company in Chicago, has data
on several funds that specialize in the sector.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Select Biotechnology has the longest and best record
over the past three years, when it returned an average of 14.6
percent per year. This year, through November 30, it's up 14.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Monterey Murphy New World Biotech has also been around three
years, but it's lost an average of 1.8 percent per year during that
period, and so far this year it has lost 14.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dresdner RCM Biotechnology, one of the newer funds, is up 6.6
percent this year, while Franklin Biotechnology Discovery, another
new fund on the block, is up 4.7 percent year to date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
