<HEADLINE>
STEWART EARNS SUGAR BOWL START FOR TEXAS A&AMP;M
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A strong performance in the Big 12
championship game has allowed Texas A&AMP;M quarterback Branndon
Stewart to regain the starting job he lost at midseason.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said yesterday that Stewart, who threw for
a season-high 324 yards and three touchdowns Saturday in a 36-33
upset of Kansas State that sealed the conference title, will start
Jan. 1 in the Sugar Bowl against Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart lost the starting job Oct. 3 to Randy McCown, who missed
the Kansas State game because of a broken left collarbone. Slocum
said uncertainty about McCown's availability, plus Stewart's
crunch-time dissection of the Wildcats' secondary, made the
fifth-year senior from Stephenville the clear choice to handle the
offense when No. 8 A&AMP;M (11-2) meets No. 3 Ohio State (10-1) in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things look very doubtful for Randy,'' said Slocum, noting
that the medical prognosis puts McCown out of action for another
three weeks. ``That eliminates him from any practice time before
the bowl. We'll go on with Branndon and get Shane Lechler ready to
go as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all proud of Branndon Stewart. We had confidence he
could do the job, and he played extremely well. I'm happy to see
him get some recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   During the fourth quarter and two overtime periods against
then-unbeaten Kansas State, Stewart completed 11 of 20 passes for
235 yards, three touchdowns and a pivotal two-point conversion in
leading A&AMP;M back from a 27-12 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Lechler, the Aggies' punter, is 2-of-2 passing this season for
37 yards and a touchdown. Slocum said Lechler, a former high school
quarterback, can run only ``about 50 percent'' of the Aggies'
offense, but will be brought up to speed as much as possible before
game time. Snyder sounds off Kansas State coach Bill Snyder, whose
team is 11-1 and ranked No. 4 in The Associated Press college
football rankings, joined school president Jon Wefald in objecting
to the Wildcats' omission from a Bowl Championship Series game or a
Jan. 1 bowl. Instead, Kansas State will play unranked Purdue (8-4)
in the Alamo Bowl on Dec. 29 in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Wefald voiced his concerns Sunday. Snyder declined to comment
until a conference call for Big 12 coaches yesterday. Then he
unloaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to be able to say life is fair. Obviously, that's
not the case,'' Snyder said. ``This is an example ... where the
system does not work. But I can't blame anybody. I can only blame
myself for not having the football team prepared enough to win the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   If Kansas State had defeated A&AMP;M, the Wildcats would have earned
a berth in the Fiesta Bowl to meet top-ranked Tennessee (12-0) on
Jan. 4 for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he is concerned about his team's mental state,
Snyder said: ``Yes, I certainly am. Somehow, I have to make sure I
don't allow our youngsters to lose sight of the tremendous things
they have done.'' Tech doubles its efforts Texas Tech defensive
coordinator John Goodner said he plans to prepare his players to
face two offenses when the Red Raiders (7-4) meet Mississippi (6-5)
in the Independence Bowl on Dec. 31 in Shreveport, La.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi will be coached by David Cutcliffe, who took over
the team yesterday after serving throughout the regular season as
Tennessee's offensive coordinator. Goodner said Tech coaches are
unsure whether Cutcliffe will run the offense of former Ole Miss
coach Tommy Tuberville or institute his system during prebowl
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they'll use what their coach did at Tennessee, but we
have to try and get ready for both,'' Goodner said. ``It'll be a
little different for us, but we're looking forward to the
challenge. The one good thing is, the Tennessee offense isn't that
far from what Mississippi has done in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
