   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- NY-CITY-HALL-PROTEST, 12-07
-- A group of City Council members, rebelling against the unusually
tight security at City Hall on Monday by holding a news conference
on the building's steps, receive only a smile and a shake of the
head from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as he walks past. An aide, right,
clears the way by literally pushing a Council member aside. (Angel
Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) NEW YORK. -- Dec. 7, 1998 --WARM-WEATHER-FLOATER-2,
12-07 -- Dejan Jesic waits for customers to buy some of his
Christmas trees. However with the mercury hitting the 70's,
Christmas was very hard to fathom. (James Estrin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) SEA BRIGHT BEACH, N.J. -- Dec. 7, 1998
--WARM-WEATHER-FLOATER, 12-07 -- Mario Orriols does some sunbathing
on the beach as a woman in the background walks her dogs by the
shoreline. The temperature just 18 days before Christmas reached a
balmy 75 degrees Fahrenheit. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) STEPNOGORSK, Kzakhstan -- Dec. 7, 1998 --
IRAN-GERM-WARFARE, 12-07 -- The former Soviet germ warfare plant in
Stepnogorsk. The chief of the facility was among those who was
approached by Iran regarding germ warfare production. Iran is
scouring the former Soviet Union to hire scientists who once worked
in laboratories associated with Moscow's vast germ warfare program
and has succeeded in recruiting several to take jobs in Teheran,
according to Russian scientists and American officials. (Judith
Miller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) SEATTLE -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- DECO-FERRY-2, 12-07 --
Sculpter Peter Bevis stands on the deck of the art-deco style ferry
Kalakala docked at the Seattle waterfront after a long and arduous
journey from Kodiak, Alaska. The Kalakala was saved by the
obsessive decadelong quest of Bevis who was working as a commercial
fisherman when he encountered the ferry and spared it from the
salvager's torch. (Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) SEATTLE -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- DECO-FERRY, 12-07 -- The
art-deco style ferry Kalakala is docked at the Seattle waterfront
after a long and arduous journey from Kodiak, Alaska. The Kalakala
was saved by the obsessive decadelong quest of Peter Bevis, a
sculptor, who was working as a commercial fisherman when he
encountered the ferry and spared it from the salvager's torch.
(Larry Davis/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- ARTISTS-ARCHIVES-2, 12-07
-- Some of the artifacts availalbe in the Smithsonian's archives'
collection includes Jackson Pollock's letter seeking a draft
deferment in World War II and a guest book from one of his shows.
Though the archives constitute a tiny agency, all but unnoticed by
the public, its cache is crucial to some 3,000 scholars, curators
and writers who use it each year to define art history. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- ARTISTS-ARCHIVES, 12-07 --
Richard J. Wattenmaker, director of the Smithsonian Institution's
Archives of American Art, at his Washington office commenting about
the closing of several of the archive's offices around the country.
Though the archives constitute a tiny agency, all but unnoticed by
the public, its cache is crucial to some 3,000 scholars, curators
and writers who use it each year to define art history. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- SCI-SPACE-STATION, 12-07 --
An artist rendering of the completed International Space Station.
Astronauts are training to make at least 162 planned space walks to
assemble the station, and additional ventures outside the outpost
undoubtedly will be needed for unscheduled maintenance or repairs.
Experts say the expected 1,700 hours of extravehicular activity, as
NASA terms space walks, will more than double the time people have
spent outside spaceships since human flights began 37 years ago.
(NASA/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- SHOE-FASHION, 12-07 -- Manolo
Blahnik's variations, right, and Jimmy Choo's boots. If you want to
know what sets fashionable women's hearts aflutter, just look at
their feet. More even than clothes, shoes are the not-so-obscure
objects of desire that cause many women to throw logic to the wind
and succumb happily to temptation. (Marilynn K. Yee/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- FBN-REFEREES,
12-07 -- Vinny Testaverde falls holding the football just short of
the goal line on Sudnay, but officials called it a touchdown that
gave the Jets a 32-31 victory over Seattle, keeping New York tied
with Miami for first place in its division and drawing new calls
for instant replay. (Michelle V. Agins/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) PEABODY, Mass. -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- SCI-BONES-BOS, 12-07
-- Josephine Amenta, 85, is one of the first Boston-area patients
to undergo a new, minimally invasive operation for a crushed
vertebra. Enthusiasts say the procedure, called vertebroplasty, can
dramatically speed recovery from crush, or compression fractures,
as they're also known, which are common in women with bone-thinning
osteoporosis. (Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NANTUCKET, Mass. -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- UNDERGROUND-MAN-BOS,
12-07 -- Thomas Johnson, 38, sits in the bedroom of his underground
home. Johnson went underground 10 years ago to bury his rage
against the corporate vipers, clock-punching consumers, and
environmental rapists he saw in society. But now, his home
discovered, Johnson says, ``God told me it was time to come out of
the hole. But I don't know if I have the energy.'' (John
Tlumacki/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- BARNARD-MARRIAGE, 12-07
--Shannon Herbert sits in front of Sandra Chefitz, on the campus of
Barnard Collage. Herbert and Chefitz led a petition drive to drop a
comment in the college's brochure that boasted about how graduates
of women's colleges were more likely to marry and have children
than women graduating from co-ed colleges. ( Librado Romero/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BETHLEHEM, West Bank -- Dec. 7, 1998 --
ISRAEL-POLITICS-3, 12-07 -- Palestinians demonstrators take cover
as Israeli soldiers opened fire with rubber bullets at a checkpoint
near Rachel's Tomb on Monday. Demonstrations demanding an immediate
release of Palestinian prisoners held in Israeli jails turned
violent on Monday, just five days before President Clinton's visit
to the region. Some 70 people were injured. (Rina Castelnuovo/New
York Times Photo)
