head of his own DNA and gene research company, Human Genome
Sciences, Inc. Haseltine, seen in one of his laboratories, said
during a recent interview that his company had now isolated more
than 75 percent of all human genes in full-length form. (Ann
Grillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) CAMBRIDGE, England -- Dec. 7, 1998 -- SCI-WELLS-SQUIDS,
12-07 -- Martin Wells, an expert on cephalopods and grandson of
H.G. Wells, poses on the campus of Cambridge University. Wells can
speak for hours about the wonders of cuttlefish, squids and
octopuses, his specialty and great passion. Wells says that
practically everything known about how nerves work has been worked
out from experimenting on squid nerves. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
