<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHOUSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THRILLING WEEKEND REVEALS BCS IS WINNING FORMULA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Other than perhaps New Year's Day 1984 when
Texas let a national championship slip away and Miami upset
Nebraska, I can't remember a more exciting day in college football
than Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Upsets. Drama. Big plays. Mood swings. Reversals of fortune.
Would it have been a perfect first round of a playoff? Yes. Would
the following games be better? Doubtful. Will another season of
deciding a ``national champion'' instead of a playoff-produced
national champion lead us to a playoff? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the vaunted football experts and talking heads were
screeching about how the Bowl Championship Series was flawed, how
there were going to be three (or more) undefeated teams and how the
BCS computer rankings were a failed bit.
</P>
<P>
   Am I a ``BCS guy?'' Guess so. But I'm more for patience and
seasonlong perspective. All I know is that the BCS was criticized
from its inception. Had these critics been around Kitty Hawk, the
Wright Brothers would have said, ``Ah, forget this'' and gone back
to fixing bikes.
</P>
<P>
   What needed to happen, happened. The season _ the entire season
_ was played. The Fiesta Bowl national championship game is
unanimous No. 1 Tennessee facing No. 2 Florida State. In the end,
all the BCS system did was help designate Florida State as the team
most worthy to face the undefeated No. 1 team. The Seminoles'
strength of schedule was far superior to the other contenders.
</P>
<P>
   What if there had been no BCS rankings? The national
championship game would have pitted the teams ranked No. 1 and No.
2 in the polls. And those teams are _ well, how about that? _
Tennessee and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   More and more coaches favor a playoff. Of course, the coaches
want it both ways. They want a playoff ``and'' the bowl system.
Making those two compatible not only requires Solomon-like wisdom,
it ignores the fact that a playoff system would probably kill the
bowls.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't matter how much the coaches, fans and news media
yap about wanting a playoff. It won't happen until Division I-A
presidents say it will happen. The presidents, who tend to blow
with the wind, might eventually give in to public opinion. But
those scales haven't tipped far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Is college football's postseason a perfect system? Far from it.
Is the NCAA Tournament perfect? Nope. It has flaws. Are NFL
officials infallible? Well, duh.
</P>
<P>
   This is sports, people. A microcosm of life. Life is not fair,
ergo the games we play are not fair. Deal with it. Ask UCLA if that
was a fumble or Kansas State if Sirr Parker actually broke the
plane of the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to this season's Designated Victim (which, as
our judiciary process teaches us, is a necessary component to any
argument). That loud, jet-engine-type noise coming from up north is
the whining of Kansas State and its fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``''We just can't \Rsniffle\S believe that \Rwhimper\S we wound
up in the Alamo Bowl \Rsob\S just because we lost one game
\Rwail\S.''''
</P>
<P>
   This game of musical bowls occurs every year. TCU got to find
out what it's like to sit down because they were lucky enough to be
near a chair (the Sun Bowl) when the music (Kansas State and UCLA
losses) stopped.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way the game is played. Kansas State shouldn't be
unhappy; the rules weren't changed at the last minute. It's like
the IRS: If you don't like to pay taxes, find another country.
These are the rules and the laws; deal with it.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 9-2 UCLA and 10-1 North Carolina were unhappy because
they weren't invited to alliance bowls. A 10-1 team that brings
tons of fans got an-large berth in the Fiesta. The team? Kansas
State.
</P>
<P>
   Did Kansas State get a raw deal, falling from a BCS bowl to the
Alamo Bowl? Yes. Did Kansas State deserve a better bowl? Yes.
Should the Wildcats be kicking and screaming about fickle fate?
Yes. But not after today. Then it's time to get on with life.
</P>
<P>
   It was heartbreaking to see Kansas State come so close to a
national championship only to see it slip away. But the Wildcats
can blame no one but themselves. Here's my advice: Next time you've
got a 15-point fourth quarter lead, don't blow it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
