<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES GOES ON ATTACK AGAINST ANTITRUST EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Launching a fierce media campaign to try to rebuild his
company's tattered image, Microsoft Corp. chairman Bill Gates
Monday accused the government of trying to ``destroy'' the software
firm by pressing an antitrust suit he claimed was calculated solely
to bolster the interests of his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   For seven weeks, Microsoft has been under siege from federal
prosecutors and business rivals as the government pressed its case
that the world's largest software company used predatory tactics in
an effort to maintain a monopoly in personal computer operating
software and expand its dominance over software designed to
navigate the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Gates, who has offered little public comment since the
antitrust trial began in US District Court in Washington, struck
back, taking direct aim at David Boies, the Justice Department's
lead trial lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Boies has made it clear in the negotiations leading up to
the case that he's really out to destroy Microsoft,'' said Gates,
speaking to reporters at the National Press Club in Washington via
a satellite hookup from the company's headquarters in Redmond,
Wash. ``He is out to take all the work we have done and make us
look very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates added that the suit, joined by 20 states, was designed to
provide relief to companies like rival Netscape Communications
Corp., which claims Microsoft used its monopoly power to try to
drive it from the Internet browser market. But Gates said Microsoft
was being punished for defeating its competitors in the marketplace
and that there was no evidence its business practices had harmed
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is the government representing?'' he asked. ``A handful of
competitors, or consumers?''
</P>
<P>
   Gates's attack on the antitrust suit received a boost Monday
when South Carolina Attorney General Charles Condon announced the
state would withdraw from the antitrust action. In a written
statement, Condon, a Republican, said America Online Inc.'s
decision to purchase Netscape for $4.2 billion ``proves the forces
of competition are working'' and that further government
intervention is ``unwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Condon questioned whether it ever made sense to bring the case.
``Over the last year,'' he said, ``it has become clear that the
government's case has been about Internet competitors, not about
consumers. The government's witnesses are either Microsoft's
competitors or paid government experts. Consumers have not taken a
leading role in this action.''
</P>
<P>
   News of Condon's decision sent Microsoft stock soaring by 6 3/16
to 133 9/16 on the Nasdaq exchange, an all-time high, as investors
expressed optimism about the company's chances of winning the
antitrust suit, which resumes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But other state attorneys general, including Massachusetts's
Scott Harshbarger, said South Carolina's decision would have no
impact on the case. ``We're still in the case,'' said Harshbarger's
spokeswoman, Debbie Banda. ``We respect South Carolina's decision,
but we feel the merger doesn't resolve all the issues the case
raises.''
</P>
<P>
   The office of New York Attorney General Dennis Vacco called
Condon's withdrawal ``an insignificant event,'' and a Justice
Department spokeswoman said it would have ``zero impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates also pointed to America Online's proposed acquisition of
Netscape and alliance with Sun Microsystems Inc. as proof that the
computer industry is still intensely competitive, contrary to the
claims in the government's antitrust complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the AOL-Netscape deal, it's hard to believe
that the government can still press their case with a straight
face,'' Gates said. ``Three of our biggest competitors are banding
together and yet the government is still trying to slow us down.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gates spent much of the news conference attempting to
counter the portrait Boies has painted of him at trial as a chief
executive who has been less than forthcoming about his company's
tactics in dealing with competitors. Although Gates has not been
scheduled as a witnesses by either side in the case, Boies grilled
him during a pretrial deposition in which Gates repeatedly dodged
questions and quibbled with Boies over the meaning of words such as
``ask'' and ``compete.''
</P>
<P>
   During his deposition, Gates often used lengthy pauses before
saying he didn't know the answers to even simple questions about
Microsoft's business plans.
</P>
<P>
   Boies has used videotaped portions of the deposition five times
during the trial, to great effect, as he has attempted to show that
Gates and Microsoft set out deliberately to harm its rivals. During
one presentation, US District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
shook his head in disgust at Gates's answers.
</P>
<P>
   Seizing the opportunity to explain his appearance and behavior
during what he called the ``three long days'' last August when he
was questioned by the government's lawyers, Gates said: ``I
answered truthfully every single question that was put forward to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates characterized many of the questions put to him as
``strange'' and defended asking Boies to explain what he meant by
the word ``compete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my question there is an absolutely legitimate
question, which anybody in that situation . . . would have asked,''
Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft continued its attack on the antitrust suit following
Gates's remarks. The company issued a 16-page single-spaced press
release entitled ``A Trial in Error'' that charged the suit is
``the last refuge of antitrust plaintiffs who do not have a viable
case: The government is throwing every bit of mud from Microsoft's
competitors at the wall, in the hope that at least some of it will
stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the company also filed a motion asking Jackson to
allow Microsoft access to documents connected to the proposed deal
involving AOL, Netscape, and Sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to see the documents from all three of these companies
. . . so we can defend ourselves against the notion that somehow
Microsoft or any other single company could possibly hope to
control access to the Internet,'' said Microsoft's general counsel,
William Neukom. He argued the documents may help Microsoft counter
the testimony of some of the government's previous witnesses,
including Netscape's chief executive, James Barksdale.
</P>
<P>
   But ProComp, a Washington-based lobbying group that supports the
antitrust lawsuit, said the AOL-Netscape-Sun merger is not relevant
to the real issue at trial. ``The issue in this case is whether
Microsoft has a monopoly in the operating system and whether this
harms consumers,'' said Kevin Arquit, an attorney for the group.
</P>
<P>
   (Material from Bloomberg News was used in this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
