<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOWITZKI-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOWITZKI SAMPLES NBA ACTION DURING VISIT TO DALLAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Dirk Nowitzki received a shovel pass from Derek Harper,
thundered to the basket and threw down a tomahawk dunk.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of the few highlights for Nowitzki, the German
wonder boy the Mavericks' acquired in a three-team trade on draft
day in June, during a pickup basketball game at the Tom Landry
Center. Nowitzki arrived Saturday in Dallas from Germany to look
for a place to live. He will work out the next two days with
Mavericks players and current and former NBA players.
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki was averaging 21.6 points and 8.3 rebounds for
Germany's senior national team. The 20-year-old Nowitzki and his
coach, Holger Geschwindner, decided to skip their German team's
Sunday game to fly to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is new to me,'' Nowitzki said. ``There are a lot of
good players out here, so I have to get used to it because they're
much more athletic than myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowitzki might have struggled at times, but former Mavericks
player Harper said he expects Nowitzki to get used to the NBA game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands the game quite well, and I think he's going to
do well,'' Harper said. ``With 20-year-old kids, you have to be
patient with them and give them room for errors, because they're
going to make a few mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   His moves might not be all there yet, but his future teammates
admire his move of coming to Dallas to get used to the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a smart move on his part to come over here and
practice,'' Mavs guard Steve Nash said. ``He got a chance to play
against some NBA players today and got used to his teammates a
little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day when he starts playing _ his first new training camp
and his first day of the season _ is going to definitely be
influenced by his time out here.''
</P>
<P>
   The NBA lockout, which has reached 161 days, mystifies Nowitzki.
He doesn't understand what the union and NBA management are
squabbling about.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a lot of money involved,'' Nowitzki said.
``Hopefully the season will start in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if it doesn't, that's not the biggest problem for me,
because I have good competition in Europe. I have a lot of time to
grow and develop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
