<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7531 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEAR-MISS-BOS &LR;      12-07 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEAR-MISS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER FAILURE PRODUCES JUMBO JET NEAR MISS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A computer that Boston center air traffic controllers rely on to
provide them with identifying data about the aircraft they direct
malfunctioned Sunday night, resulting in two Europe-bound jumbo
jets nearly colliding off Long Island, air traffic controllers
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration, which has consistently
asserted that the nation's air traffic system is protected by
numerous backup systems, said it is investigating the incident but
has not yet determined whether the loss of safe separation between
the two aircraft was the result of a system failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The matter is under investigation, and until that
investigation is complete, we cannot attribute the error to the
(computer) outage,'' said FAA spokeswoman Arlene Salac. ``The air
traffic system in the United States is safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The two aircraft _ a British Caledonian L-1011 with 271 people
on board heading from Montego Bay to Manchester, England, and a
Delta Airlines Boeing 767 going from Atlanta to Zurich with 101 on
board _ came within a little more than 1 mile of each other while
flying at more than 500 miles per hour, both at 33,000 feet. At
that altitude, safe separation is either 2,000 feet vertically or 5
miles horizontally.
</P>
<P>
   Controllers at the Boston air-traffic control center in Nashua,
N.H., who have had to deal with repeated computer outages in the
last year, were literally in the dark about the near collision
until the pilot of British Caledonia Flight 5199 said he was going
to file a report upon landing, controllers said.
</P>
<P>
   The on-board computer systems on the two airplanes, known as
TCAS, for Traffic Collision Avoidance System, alerted each flight
crew of the approaching aircraft. The Delta jet, Flight 66, was
told by its TCAS to climb _ it went to 33,600 feet _ and the L-1011
plane was told to descend. It went to 32,700 feet. The two planes
passed within 1.07 miles of each other, according to the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is being independently investigated by the airlines
involved.
</P>
<P>
   William Johannes, Boston center president of the National Air
Traffic Controllers Association, credited TCAS with averting a
tragedy. But he placed the blame for the incident squarely on the
computer failure at the Boston center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the (FAA) wants to say that safety was never compromised,
that is their point of view,'' Johannes said. ``When you can't
separate airplanes because the tools you use are no longer there
and you are having rapid system failures, I think they are failing
to acknowledge there is a major problem there.''
</P>
<P>
   The system usually operates with a mainframe computer known as
the Host, which processes flight information, and another system
known as the Computer Display Channel, a 1972-era computer that is
the main radar processing computer at Boston center. Its
replacement system is still at least a year away from being
operational.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, which officials have not yet determined, the
interface between the Host and CDC was lost around 9:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Officials went to a backup computer system known as DARC, but
that was partially disabled, so controllers were forced to
handwrite notes about flight information, including the flight
number, type of aircraft, destination, altitude, and airspeed.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, a computer screen flashed the message ``DARC
disabled,'' heightening tension among the controllers who were
uncertain if DARC, the backup, was working at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of hollering and people were saying they were
locked out,'' said Johannes. ``There was a lot of confusion about
who was supposed to do what. Surrounding facilities were calling
attempting to hand off airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Michael, manager for quality assurance in air traffic
control at the Boston center, depicted the atmosphere during the
computer outage as calm: ``Controllers are trained for this, and in
a nutshell, operations continued normally at the center.''
</P>
<P>
   But the confusion stemming from the computer failure in the
sector, which handles planes east of New York's John F. Kennedy
Airport, apparently deteriorated even further, resulting in the
near collision, controllers said.
</P>
<P>
   Under normal conditions, if two planes are on a collision
course, the data blocks containing the flight information begin to
flash. Controllers then have 2 1/2 minutes to intervene. But that
system was disabled.
</P>
<P>
   If controllers have to rely on handwritten notes, they can
slowly rebuild the system by keyboarding the information back in.
But in this one sector, where three controllers were juggling 15
planes, the keyboard was locked up and controllers could not
operate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this sector, there was an additional problem with the
keyboard,'' Michael acknowledged. ``Exactly what the problem was,
is still under investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   The data blocks on some planes began to disappear, as well as
the flight tracks of some of the planes, including Delta Flight 66,
controllers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all of what was happening, they might as well have been
sitting there blindfolded,'' said Johannes.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston center, which controls about 165,000 square miles of
airspace from out into the Atlantic into New York state, and from
Canada to south of Long Island, has had numerous computer and radar
problems this year.
</P>
<P>
   During one period this spring, the center was averaging a
disruption in normal function on a daily basis. The interruptions
would last from seconds to 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   While the on-board TCAS systems on the two planes may have
averted a tragedy Sunday night, those systems nearly caused a
mid-air collision south of Albany on Tuesday. On Saturday, The
Boston Globe reported that an Air Ontario de Havilland Dash 8 came
within 300 feet of a Northwest Airlines Airbus A-320, when its TCAS
told it to climb to avoid a US Airways Boeing 737 and the Northwest
plane's TCAS told it to descend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
