<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Tory Backs Down on Key Plan
</P>
<P>
   William Hague, the leader of Britain's Conservatives, has
abandoned plans to press for a new regional Parliament to represent
England. The proposal, a centerpiece of his program at the annual
party convention two months ago, was aimed at being a counterweight
to the new Parliaments that the Labor government of Prime Minister
Tony Blair has created in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Standing Firm on Kashmir
</P>
<P>
   On his first visit to Kashmir since becoming prime minister of
India in March, Atal Behari Vajpayee said India would never
relinquish any of it to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Election Plan Challenged
</P>
<P>
   The opposition National Party said it would ask the High Court
to rule on the constitutionality of requiring citizens to have new
``bar-coded'' identity documents before they can register to vote
in next year's national elections. The ruling African National
Congress is insisting on the documents, but this could result in
fewer white voters getting to the polls, because many have not
applied for the new documents.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda: President's Brother Quits
</P>
<P>
   The brother of Uganda's president resigned as the nation's
security adviser after admitting his involvement in a secret deal
to buy a 49 percent interest in the Uganda Commercial Bank. Maj.
Gen. Salim Saleh, a military adviser to his brother, President
Yoweri Museveni, has been criticized for corruption and the
military's support of the rebellion in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   St. Vincent and the Grenadines: Marijuana War
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean troops backed by six U.S. Marine Corps helicopters are
beginning a two-week campaign to eradicate an estimated 12,000
acres of marijuana on St. Vincent, BBC News reported. It said the
island's marijuana growers' association, warning that the
destruction of the crop would drive up the island's 40 percent
unemployment rate, has written to President Clinton demanding
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   United States: Gore's Global Conference
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore is inviting law-enforcement and other
officials from more than 60 countries to what his office calls the
world's first conference on fighting corruption and safeguarding
integrity among justice and security officials. The conference is
scheduled from Feb. 24 to 26 at the State Department.
</P>
</TEXT>
