<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS TALKING TO PITCHER CLARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Rangers, who continue to be involved in
the pursuit of Toronto Blue Jays right-hander Roger Clemens, might
be close to strengthening their rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Calm down.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander in question is Mark Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've discussed Mark Clark,'' Rangers general manager Doug
Melvin acknowledged yesterday. ``We've talked figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin did not divulge whether an offer has been tendered to
Clark, but the Rangers' general manager mentioned it to Joe Bick,
who represents free-agent right-hander Bob Tewksbury.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that they were involved in the Clemens trade
possibility and that he had one additional offer to a free agent
out there,'' Bick said. ``Doug said he would get back to me by
Wednesday at the latest.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who this past season earned $5.05 million, went 9-14 with
a 4.84 earned-run average during 33 starts for the Chicago Cubs.
The 30-year-old right-hander went 28-19 with a 3.62 ERA during the
1996-97 seasons with the New York Mets and Cubs. CLEMENS' LIST CUT
</P>
<P>
   Blue Jays general manager Gord Ash spent this weekend narrowing
the list of Clemens' suitors from 14 to six organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a couple of offers for more than I expected,'' Ash
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ash identified only one of those organizations _ the New York
Yankees _ and for the first time acknowledged that a trade for
Clemens could involve three organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin, who spoke briefly yesterday with Ash, declined to
divulge whether the Rangers could be involved in a multiple-team
trade for Clemens. ARBITRATION OFFERED CLARK, PAVLIK
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers offered salary arbitration yesterday to two of their
six free agents: right-hander Roger Pavlik and first baseman Will
Clark, who Saturday signed a two-year contract worth $11 million
with the Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Offering Clark arbitration ensures the Rangers two draft
selections _ a sandwich pick between the first and second rounds
and what now stands as the Orioles' fourth-round choice _ as
compensation for losing Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers offered Pavlik arbitration ``to give us a little
more time to determine whether there's interest from our level
later on,'' Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlik, who earned $1.6 million this past season, likely
guaranteed the Rangers that he would not go to arbitration in order
to have an opportunity to return.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers did not offer salary arbitration to left-handers
Scott Bailes and Greg Cadaret, right-hander Xavier Hernandez and
catcher Bill Haselman. The Rangers cannot re-sign those four to a
major-league contract until May 1, and therefore likely ended their
stint with the organization. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Juan Gonzalez married recording artist Olga Tanon
last night in San Juan, Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks' signing of free-agent center fielder
Steve Finley did not hurt the Rangers. Finley, a Type A free agent,
was rated lower than right-hander Todd Stottlemyre by the annual
Elias Player Rankings. That means the Rangers still will receive
the Diamondbacks' fourth-round draft selection and a sandwich pick
between the first and second rounds for losing Stottlemyre as it
stands now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
