<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VACCO-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ASKED TO VISIT 100,000 HOMES TO CHECK VOTER ELIGIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Claiming fresh evidence that thousands of New
York City residents had cast ballots illegally, lawyers for
Republican Attorney General Dennis Vacco called Monday for police
officers to conduct door-to-door visits to verify the eligibility
of more than 100,000 voters.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Vacco asked a state judge to declare him the
winner of the Nov. 3 vote over Eliot Spitzer, the Democratic
challenger, or to order the state to conduct a new election.
Spitzer holds a narrow lead in the state tally, including a sizable
advantage in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In requesting the police visits, lawyers for Vacco took
advantage of a seldom-used provision in the state's election laws.
</P>
<P>
   The request drew a strong response from Spitzer, who charged
that Vacco was trying to intimidate voters in heavily Democratic
areas, particularly black and Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Vacco campaign based its request on a computer database
search that compared the names of registered voters in New York
City with a list provided by a private credit reporting company.
Thomas Spargo, Vacco's lawyer, said the search turned up 103,000
people on the voting rolls ``for whom there was no apparent record
that they had engaged in routine activity in the community or
otherwise existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Thomas Keegan did not rule on the requests to hold a new
election or to declare Vacco the winner. He asked the two sides to
return to court next Monday, the day before the election results
are to be certified by the State Board of Elections. At that
hearing, on the basis of findings from the police canvass, Keegan
is expected to determine whether there is merit to the attorney
general's complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The State Election Board reported Monday that it had completed
its tally, with Spitzer leading by 26,011 votes out of 4.2 million
votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   The judge asked lawyers for both campaigns to meet with the
police department, the city corporation counsel and the City Board
of Elections on Tuesday to scale down the number of voters whose
eligibility is to be verified. Keegan suggested that it was
impossible for police officers to visit the homes of more than
100,000 people in the six days that the election laws mandate for
such investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Spargo said the Vacco campaign discovered ``a substantial number
of irregularities which would either cause this election to be
decided in favor of Dennis Vacco or to cause doubt to the outcome
of the election to be reason enough to hold a new election.'' He
charged that some voters had cast ballots twice, and that there was
a large number of voters registered at the same apartment or at
companies that provide mailbox services.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said he was outraged that the Republican Party has
``demanded that the police knock on the doors of over 100,000
voters who don't show up in the files of a credit-reporting firm
that doesn't keep records on economically disadvantaged voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer made it clear that his representatives had no intention
of participating in the meeting with Vacco's lawyers and the
police. ``I have also asked my attorneys to investigate whether the
Republicans' conduct is a violation of the United States Civil
Rights and Voting Rights Acts,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Under state election laws, a commissioner of the board of
elections may challenge the eligibility of a voter who is suspected
of registering illegally. When such a challenge is registered, the
police department is asked to visit the home of the voter and file
a report within six days.
</P>
<P>
   If the officer reports that there is no evidence of a voter
living at the address where he is registered, the board of
elections is required to send a letter to the voter, informing him
that a hearing will be held to determine his eligibility to vote.
If he is found ineligible to vote, his name is then expunged from
the rolls.
</P>
<P>
   In Vacco's case, Vincent Velella, a longtime Republican
commissioner, signed an order asking for such a process to extend
to 103,000 voters in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Connor, the state Senate minority leader and a lawyer for
Spitzer, said that under state law the police findings, whatever
they may be, would be irrelevant in determining the outcome of an
election that took place more than a month ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
