<SLUG> BC-LOSANGELES-POLICE-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL RECOMMENDS STRONGER ROLE FOR POLICE INSPECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A City Council committee asked city legal
officials on Monday to draw up plans to strengthen the police
department's inspector general, a job created in the wake of the
worst riots in Los Angeles history.
</P>
<P>
   The committee acted after advocates for changes in police
procedures and city officials testified at a hearing of the
council's public-safety committee that the inspector general should
have unfettered access to police documents, be free to conduct
investigations of police conduct and report directly to the board
of police commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   The committee asked the city attorney's office to draft a City
Council bill to put those proposals into effect.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing was called after the department's first inspector
general, Katherine Mader, resigned last month, accusing the board
and its executive director, to whom she reported, of undercutting
her authority. Ms. Mader also complained that aggressive monitoring
of the police department was no longer welcome since a popular new
police chief, Bernard Parks, took office last year.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of a police inspector general, who oversees the
police disciplinary system and citizen complaints against police
officers, was recommended by a commission that examined the
department after the beating of the motorist Rodney King in 1991.
The office was created after riots were set off when police
officers were acquitted in the beating the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mader, who served less than three years in the job,
testified at the hearing that the position needed more power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interests of the inspector general do not always coincide
with the interests of the department,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that whistle-blowers in the police department
needed better protection. In one instance, she said, police
officials came to her office to retrieve an anonymous letter that
requested an investigation. She said the officials wanted to check
the letter for fingerprints.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, police commissioners, who have been accused of
forcing out Ms. Mader, said they too favored a stronger
inspector-general position that would report directly to them and
have unfettered access to documents.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the board and the board's executive director,
Joe Gunn, though, have called Ms. Mader's work substandard and said
the commission wanted to dismiss her before she resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, The Los Angeles Times reported that Edith Perez, the
president of the commission, had been sending anonymous letters and
press clippings to police-reform experts condemning Ms. Mader in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And several commissioners who spoke at the hearing said the
inspector general's autonomy should not compromise confidential
police activity or undercut the police commissioners' authority.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A central point of the controversy over Ms. Mader's resignation
is that the commission that recommended the creation of her job
left unclear to whom the inspector general would report.
</P>
<P>
   The fine print of the proposition creating the post, which was
approved by Los Angeles voters in 1995, said the inspector general
would report to the executive director of the board of the police
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mader and some members of the investigative commission,
which was headed by Warren Christopher, who went on to become
secretary of state, have advocated having the inspector general
report directly to the police board.
</P>
<P>
   That, they said, would lessen the potential for interference,
provide a clearer line of communication on sensitive investigations
and enhance the inspector general's appearance of independence,
both with the public and with the police that she investigated.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mader's resignation raised concerns that the city's
commitment to police reform was fading. Several prominent civil
rights leaders, including Ramona Ripston, the executive director of
the American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California, said the
city need to do more to change the police department.
</P>
</TEXT>
