<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BOMB-THREATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE POLICE, SCHOOL LEADS NEW JERSEY IN BOMB THREATS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By KIRSTY SUCATO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINE HILL, N.J. _ When Shayna Barford was transferred from a
parochial school to Overbrook Regional Senior High School here last
April, she had never experienced a bomb threat. She did not even
know what one was. But on her first day of school, the ninth-grader
was forced outside with 1,800 other students for more than an hour
as the police scoured the brown brick building for nonexistent
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the threats have become almost as common as physical
education or study hall. Last year, there were more than 30 such
evacuations, all sparked by anonymous telephone calls to 911. And
last week, Overbrook High received a bomb threat every day, causing
students to lose eight hours of class time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dumb because it takes away from the kids who want to
learn,'' Shayna said.
</P>
<P>
   But to law enforcement authorities and school administrators, it
is more than stupid, so when students arrived for class on Monday,
their campus resembled the scene of a hostage standoff: Armed
officers wearing black combat pants stood guard atop the roof,
while four patrol cars and uniformed police officers monitored the
grounds, amid video cameras and microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Police Chief Judd Booker said the show of force was intended to
ease the fears of students and parents who have threatened to keep
their children at home. But it apparently did little to deter the
hoaxers, who issued two more bomb threats during the day. ``Enough
is enough,'' Booker said. ``I mean we have to end this pattern of
every day. We'll do whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the spate of bomb threats began last year, the Camden
County school, situated about half way between Atlantic City and
Philadelphia, was known for little more than its successful
football team, the Rams, which this weekend won the Group Four
state championship.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when the first calls trickled in a year ago, the
temptation was to write off the hoaxes as a symptom of suburban
ennui _ a nuisance, but far more manageable that the guns and
violence plaguing many inner-city districts. But the threats have
persisted for so long and involved so many different students that
even those not given to introspection wonder what has made
Overbrook the bomb threat capital of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Michael Shreiner said the threats did not seem to
be the work of students angered by particular grievances but rather
a snowballing series of pranks that had left faculty members
frustrated and angry. ``We pride ourselves in our teacher-student
contact,'' he said. ``That's what education is all about, teachers
working directly with kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students theorized that the hoaxes were a diversionary
tactic carried out by those who wanted to avoid class.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Rodgers, an 11th-grader who had skipped class to smoke a
cigarette with friends Monday morning, said he hoped the school
would be evacuated again because it was ``perfect bomb-threat
weather.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit out there in the field and do nothing,'' he said.
``It's time off from class, and they can't do nothing about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But some students said they had grown weary of the disruption.
Karen Abernathy said she had to make up three papers as homework
last week after missing three straight world history classes. She
also complained that the police presence made it harder for her to
skip class.
</P>
<P>
   Booker said the police had had difficulty tracing the calls,
which were made from various pay phones around the county and from
cellular phones. To check students' phone records, officials have
been forced to obtain search warrants, he said. The department has
also relied on undercover surveillance, including stakeouts, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the department has identified dozens of suspects,
largely through other students' informing on them. Booker said two
students were expected to be arrested on Tuesday. But he said the
investigation was being hampered by a lack of witnesses despite a
school reward of $500 for information.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the serious nature of the threats, the authorities
have not turned up any explosives in their searches. The closest
they came was last February, when a fake bomb was found on the roof
of the gymnasium. The device, a plastic packing crate with an
antenna sticking out of it, contained wires sprinkled with
gunpowder, said Principal Paul Harmelin.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the gunpowder was intended to attract
bomb-sniffing dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The incident led to the arrest of two 18-year-old students,
Kevin Matthews and David Ottaviano, who were sentenced to five
years in prison after pleading guilty to causing false public
alarm, said Greg Reinert, a spokesman for the Camden County
Prosecutor's Office.
</P>
<P>
   In other incidents, 12 students, all juveniles, were arrested
last year; they either served probation or paid fines, Reinert
said.
</P>
<P>
   Booker said the police would stay at the school until the bomb
threats died down.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the faculty has begun to adapt to the new way
of life, said Nancy C. Young, an English teacher who was
interrupted by bomb threats while teaching ``The Crucible'' by
Arthur Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the teachers are thinking about having lessons
outside,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
