</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOWES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lowe's uses Home Depot 'blueprint' to compete
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In the battle over Austin's burgeoning home
improvement market, the lines are being drawn in bright orange and
red.
</P>
<P>
   They are marked on places on the map like North Austin and south
Williamson County.
</P>
<P>
   From its massive warehouse on Research Boulevard, The Home Depot
used to own the market in that part of town.
</P>
<P>
   Then, seven months ago, Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse opened
just a few miles away at RM 620 and Highway 183.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the two stores are duking it out for the business of
do-it-yourselfers like John Valkenaar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shop at both stores, Valkenaar said recently while walking
into Home Depot. ``I like having a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Austin and throughout the country, similar scenes are
playing out in between the aisles of lumber and carpet and
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   As in Northwest Austin, Home Depot and Lowe's elsewhere are
known for opening stores next to each other, like burger
restaurants or gas stations looking to corner a market. They've
been known to copy what works in each others' stores. Sometimes,
they even sue each other for the prime retail spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``All's fair in capitalism,'' said Home Depot spokesman Don
Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot, the Atlanta-based behemoth that pioneered the
warehouse home improvement concept, was the first of the two to
reach the Austin area. It has four area stores already and is
planning others from South Austin to Cedar Park, including one just
a mile from a Lowe's. Nationwide, it operates 742 stores in four
countries.
</P>
<P>
   North Wilkesboro, N.C.-based Lowe's is no newcomer to Texas,
having opened its first store 13 years ago in Tyler. It arrived in
Central Texas in January 1997, with a big store in San Marcos.
</P>
<P>
   It plans to open several more stores in the Austin area,
including stores at the proposed Forum retail center planned at
William Cannon Drive and MoPac Boulevard and in La Frontera, a
shopping center planned at Interstate 35 and RM 1325. Nationwide,
Lowe's has 474 stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see Austin as a strong growth region of the country,'' said
Lowe's spokesman Brian Peace. The two companies face smaller
competitors everywhere _ in Austin they range from local players
like McCoy's Building Supply Centers and Calcasieu Lumber Co. to
bigger companies such as BMC West Corp.'s Stripling-Blake Lumber
Co. Inc. and HomeQuarters, formerly Builders Square. They also
compete with small hardware stores and home improvement departments
of big discounters like Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Kmart Corp. But in
the $300 billion home improvement industry, there's no fiercer
battle than the one between Home Depot and Lowe's, which are No. 1
and No. 2 in sales, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, these are the only two companies in the
home center industry that are growing,'' said Daniel Wewer,
managing director of Robinson-Humphrey Co., an Atlanta investment
banking firm.
</P>
<P>
   'Big box' concept
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Lowe's and Home Depot would have seemed unlikely
rivals _ like apples and oranges when it came to home improvement
retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Founded 20 years ago, Home Depot pioneered the ``big box''
concept in the home improvement industry. The idea was to offer
multiple stores under one roof, Harrison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Depot is the innovator in this industry,'' Wewer said.
</P>
<P>
   It worked.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Home Depot had 35 stores. Today it has more than 21
times that number. The company just recorded its 51st consecutive
quarter of double-digit growth, and its astounding stock growth has
made millionaires out of employees and early investors.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its 52-year history, Lowe's sold building supplies
and lumber from stores that were one-tenth the size of its current
100,000-square-foot-plus warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, seeing Home Depot's successes, the company reinvented
itself into a chain of large home improvement stores. Lowe's has
spent the past decade closing and relocating its older stores,
replacing them with the new warehouse format. ``Customers have told
us they want one-stop shopping,'' Peace said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the number of Lowe's stores has not grown dramatically,
the total square footage that the company operates has jumped
nearly 30 percent over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to increasing the size of its stores, the company
has broadened its scope. While it once concentrated on smaller
markets in outlying areas, it has been moving into major urban
markets in recent years. It has invested more than $250 million in
the Dallas area alone over the past 2 1/2 years, Peace said.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's, which now has stores only as far west as Lubbock, plans
to open more than 100 stores in the Western United States between
1999 and 2003. Last month, it announced plans to buy Eagle Hardware
and Garden, a chain with 32 stores in the Pacific Northwest, Alaska
and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few major differences between Lowe's and Home Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's sells appliances, from washers and dryers to VCRs; Home
Depot doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowe's in Austin has several aisles of holiday decorations
and gifts; Home Depot sells Christmas trees but has a limited
selection of holiday goods.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot recently launched its Expo Design Centers, home decor
stores aimed at upper-income shoppers; Lowe's has yet to spin-off a
separate store concept.
</P>
<P>
   But except for their names and colors _ Home Depot favors bright
orange, Lowe's likes red _ the chains are almost indistinguishable
from one another to many customers.
</P>
<P>
   They have similar formats, similar product lines, similar
advertising and have roughly the same number of employees per
store. They both carry 40,000 to 50,000 products, with access to
hundreds of thousands more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lowe's used Home Depot as its blueprint,'' said John
Caulfield, executive editor of National Home Center News, a New
York-based publication that tracks the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Both chains say they place a premium on customer service and
innovation. They both offer such services as fax-in orders, how-to
clinics and free computer design services for kitchen remodeling
projects, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   They both also boast about their low prices. Signs at both
Lowe's and Home Depot stores offer customers 10 percent discounts
on products if they find them at a lower price elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   With all the similarities between the two, the choice comes down
to convenience for shoppers like Jeanne Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lowe's is closer,'' said the Cedar Park resident.
</P>
<P>
   At least for now.
</P>
<P>
   R. Michelle Breyer writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
