<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: OPERA TWINBILL; TRAVELING CIRQUE; SLOW MAIL;
SEASONAL CELEBRATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The doubleheader, almost passe in baseball, remains
alive and well in opera. Nevertheless, audiences accustomed to
``Cav'' and ``Pag'' are in for something different when Gustav
Holst's ``Savitri'' is paired with Leonard Bernstein's ``Trouble in
Tahiti'' for three performances, Wednesday, Friday and Sunday, by
the Manhattan School of Music Opera Theater. Holst's 30-minute
opera, composed in 1908-09, is based on a Sanskrit text taken from
the ``Mahabharata.'' It deals with a woodman, his wife and death.
Bernstein's 45-minute work, composed in 1952, depicts a day in the
deteriorating marriage of a suburban couple.
</P>
<P>
   Riparian Rites
</P>
<P>
   Contortionists, acrobats, jugglers, aerialists and illusionists
are coming to the New Jersey Performing Arts Center in Newark
beginning Wednesday when the Cirque Ingenieux, out of Hollywood,
Fla., opens an eight-performance run through Sunday. With
choreography combining ballet, gymnastics and Broadway, music by
Kitaro and a story that transports a little girl into a dream
world, Cirque Ingenieux mixes entertainment traditions of the Old
World and the New.
</P>
<P>
   Postal Note
</P>
<P>
   The new Museum of Scotland in Edinburgh would like delivery of a
letter sent in the 13th century. The letter, written by the
Scottish hero William Wallace, whose life inspired the Academy
Award-winning 1995 film ``Braveheart,'' was recently discovered in
Lubeck, Germany. Written in Latin after Wallace's victory over the
English at the Battle of Stirling Bridge in 1297, it notifies the
people of northern Germany that Scotland is free from the ``power
of the English'' and invites them to reopen trade routes through
Scottish ports.
</P>
<P>
   Marking Time
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Though doubters may have proliferated recently,
winter is on the way. Paul Winter's 19th Annual Winter Solstice
Celebration at the Cathedral of St. John the Divine offers Uilleann
pipes, Irish pennywhistles and flutes, and classical guitar in
welcoming the season with three performances, Thursday through
Saturday. At Symphony Space on Broadway at 95th Street, 75 singers,
dancers, musicians and children and Ralph Lee's puppets will
celebrate with Scandinavian music, folk tales and carols in five
performances on Friday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And for the third consecutive year at 8:56 p.m. on Dec. 21, the
moment of the solstice, Japanese bamboo flutes played by musicians
in kimonos and led by the instrumentalist and composer James
Nyoraku Schlefer will observe the changing of the seasons in a
performance at St. Mark's Church at Second Avenue and 11th Street
in the East Village.
</P>
</TEXT>
