<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-INLAW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Appeal filed on behalf of elderly man in 1975 murder case
 &HT;    By Pat Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STUART, Fla. _ Attorneys for the brother-in-law of the late
Robert F. Kennedy, filed an emergency appeal Monday trying to block
the elderly Hobe Sound man's court-ordered appearance Friday
morning before a grand jury in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Circuit Judge John Fennelly last month ordered Rushton
Skakel Sr., 75, to testify before the grand jury investigating the
1975 murder of a teenage neighbor in which his sons are suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Fennelly found Skakel healthy enough to travel after hearing
testimony Nov. 10 from Skakel's wife, priest and psychiatrists that
he exhibits bizarre and eccentric behavior, including
``belly-bumping'' strangers, picking food from other people's
plates in restaurants and frequently using expletives.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut police identified Skakel's sons, Thomas and Michael,
as suspects shortly after 15-year-old Martha Moxley was found
beaten to death with a golf club that belonged to their late
mother. Both have denied involvement in the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   No one was ever charged in the crime, which has been the subject
of three books _ including Murder in Greenwich by former Los
Angeles police detective Mark Fuhrman _ and a television
miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's attorney, Richard Lubin, returned to Fennelly's court
Monday, asking him to suspend his order directing Skakel to testify
Friday or be held in contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   Fennelly said he would not delay Skakel's court-ordered
appearance beyond 5 p.m. Thursday and suggested Lubin file an
emergency request with the 4th District Court of Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The one-man Connecticut grand jury, Superior Court Judge George
Thim, began investigating the case in June, a month after Furhman
theorized Michael Skakel killed the girl in a jealous rage after
seeing his older brother kissing her.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Moore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
