<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT STOP QUEENS  
 NICE WHEELS  
 LUKE AND LAURA COME FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Mitchell, the former senator who was
instrumental in arranging the Northern Ireland peace agreement in
April, is going to spend some time in Queens, and not just the time
it takes to get from an airport into Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do a lot of that,'' he said Monday, but next spring he will
stay in Queens long enough to preside over a conference on the
peace agreement. He is joining the faculty of Queens College and
will have two titles: senior fellow at the Michael Harrington
Center for Democratic Values and Social Change, and visiting
professor in international studies.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had issued invitations for the conference last week,
while he was in Dublin. ``I think we'll have a very good
representation of people who were at the table,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A Deluxe Hybrid for a World Tour
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sahara Desert and the streets of New York are the worst
conditions we're going to face,'' Jim Rogers, investment banker and
author of ``Investment Biker'' (Random House, 1994), said.
</P>
<P>
   He was bumping along 50th Street between Eighth Avenue and
Broadway Monday at the wheel of a $500,000 Mercedes-Benz
convertible sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, a convertible sport utility. The high-riding lemon-yellow
car was designed by a former Mercedes executive, Gerhard Steinle,
who said the design took shape when his telephone rang and the
voice at the other end said, ``I'm Jim Rogers, and I need a sports
car to drive around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinle married the outside of a Mercedes-Benz sports car to the
inside of a sport-utility vehicle to enable Rogers to drive across
mountains and deserts on his three-year round-the-world trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The millennium was coming up, and I thought, nobody documented
the last one,'' he said. ``In the year 3000, I'll be in big demand
on the talk-show circuit, if I can find a cave to hibernate in
until then.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he tried to drive from a Mercedes dealership at 41st
Street and 11th Avenue to the Grand Hyatt Hotel, on 42nd Street
next to Grand Central Terminal. ``I hope you don't mind if I drive
gingerly,'' he said as the car rolled off the showroom floor and
into the street. ``The last thing I want is a smashup before the
car even gets to the boat.'' The car is scheduled to leave
Wednesday for Iceland, where Rogers will pick it up _ and drive off
_ next month.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Side Highway, he had to pull around a Honda Civic
that stopped at a check-cashing store across the highway from the
Passenger Ship Terminal. His car was a head-turner, though nothing
that happened Monday matched what happened when he and Steinle
drove it from California to Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``A California highway patrolman stopped us,'' Rogers said. ``He
wanted to take a photograph of the car. A Texas Ranger stopped us.
He wanted to photograph the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Sticking to Soaps
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee may not want to
hear this.
</P>
<P>
   There are people out there who do not want to sacrifice their
daily diet of Luke and Laura for whatever the committee has to say
about Bill and Monica if impeachment hearings begin. Soap Opera
Digest is already distributing T-shirts that say, ``Don't impeach
the President if it interrupts my soaps.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Bonderoff, the magazine's online director, said the idea
for the T-shirt came from comments from diehard fans. ``We were
responding to the frustration we sensed from visitors to our site
and readers of the magazine,'' he said, ``who tell us on an ongoing
basis that they're unhappy with constant news pre-emptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonderoff, 52, remembers how frustrating the Watergate hearings
were in 1973. ``At that point in time,'' he said, using a Nixonian
phrase, ``when shows were interrupted for substantial portions of
time, a lot of story lines got totally disrupted.'' But he insisted
that the T-shirt was nonpolitical.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend not to discuss politics on our message boards,''
he said. ``They just don't want interruptions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
