<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7580 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ELKINGTON-HNS &LR;      12-07 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ELKINGTON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ What goes around comes around. But it
sure has been a large, sweeping curve for Steve Elkington.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington was Australia's own long before Houston could claim
him as a favored son. The former University of Houston star may
have perfected his skills on the practice field next to Hofheinz
Pavilion. But the guts of his game were constructed on Australian
turf, the same turf on which Elkington joins the international team
this week for the Presidents Cup against the U.S. squad.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington is back home, even though he's a few hundred miles
down the road from where he grew up. Being back in Australia for
Elkington is sort of like getting back to Texas for a Texan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be great for me,'' Elkington said before he
departed Houston for the 24-hour ordeal required to get to
Melbourne from Houston. ``I'll spend a lot of time in Wagga Wagga,
which is about halfway between Sydney and Melbourne. I've got lots
of Wagga people coming down for the Presidents Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of family and friends he'll be visiting while Down
Under.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington went to his homeland more than a week before the start
of Presidents Cup festivities. He took his family and visited with
his parents and a lot of friends near Sydney. He did not play in
the Australian Open, which was in Adelaide.
</P>
<P>
   There are a million stories Elkington could tell about his
boyhood home and growing up in Australia. But one sort of sums up
his youth. It is told in Elkington's book, Five Fundamentals, and
captures the essence of what Australia was like for Elkington.
</P>
<P>
   The story is told by Peter Kennedy, who caddied for Elkington in
his first professional tournament, the Tasmanian Open in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were walking down the fairway, and Steve asks me, `Did you
play cowboys and Indians when you were a kid?''' Kennedy remembers.
``And I wondered, `What the hell kind of question is that?' I
didn't answer him right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he asks me again, and I said, `Of course I did. Every kid
does.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Not me,' he says. `All I remember is hitting a golf ball.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When Steve won the PGA Championship, he gave me a picture of
himself holding the trophy, and on the picture he wrote: `Cowboys
and Indians was never my game.'''
</P>
<P>
   That story, which came after Elkington already had been a
two-time All-American and helped UH to two NCAA championships,
gives plenty of insight into Elkington's adolescence. He would ride
a train, sometimes eight hours each way, to meet the man who would
later become his coach, Alex Mercer, and play golf in tournaments
or just for practice.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ``coach'' would be the wrong word for Mercer.
Elkington shies away from using terms such as guru or coach, but
Mercer probably is Elkington's closest confidant on matters of golf
and pretty much anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Elkington, who turns 36 today, visited with Mercer at length in
the week leading up to the Presidents Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to Alex all the time from the States, and sometimes
golf will be 90 percent of the conversation,'' Elkington says.
``Other times, golf won't even come up.''
</P>
<P>
   To say the least, Elkington is thrilled about the opportunity to
play a major golf competition in his homeland. He believes it will
be a hugely successful event in Australia, and also an eye-opener
for people around the world about how important golf is on his
continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all sold out, which is great,'' Elkington says. ``It's by
far the best array of players we've ever had in Australia at one
time. And the fans down there really are fanatical. They've seen
all these players before, whether it's on television or whatever.
But this time, they're all together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Melbourne is one of the best golf towns in the world. A lot of
clubs in America are proud about celebrating their 30th or 40th
anniversary. We've got clubs in Melbourne that have been there for
100 years or more. Royal Melbourne is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Elkington says the historical perspective that Australians have
will be both a blessing and a curse for them this week as they try
to root for their native heroes _ Greg Norman, Elkington and Craig
Parry _ but also have to be supportive of players from Fiji (Vijay
Singh), South Africa (Ernie Els), Japan (Shigeki Maruyama) and
other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Australia, we've got lots of historical milestones that
Americans don't understand,'' Elkington says. ``We've had matches
against New Zealand and South Africa in cricket and rugby that are
just like the 'Horns playing the Aggies in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm worried about is whether it might be hard for all the
fans to get behind us as a team. Greg (Norman) obviously will be
the anchor of our team. He's the No. 1 guy in Australia. I'll
probably be the No. 2 anchor, not because I'm the second-best
player but because I'm from Australia, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we've got players from many different countries on our
team. It would be nice if our fans can get a common thread and pull
together for us, and I think they will.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured, they will be as excited to have one of their main
homeland heroes back in Australia as Elkington is to be there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
