<SLUG> BC-DRIVETHRU-BAN-VOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Council rejects controversial ban; most members say they support
its goals
 &HT;    By Alfred Charles
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta City Council on Monday rejected a
controversial proposal to ban new drive-through windows in the city
even though most members said they supported the proposal's goals
to reduce air pollution and create a more pedestrian-friendly city.
</P>
<P>
   The 8-5 vote to keep drive-throughs capped nearly an hour of
debate about the proposed ordinance, which had been offered by
Councilman Lee Morris as a way of getting the city to rethink its
dependence on automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 50 years, we have promoted auto-dependent policies,''
Morris said. ``And we have dirty air, traffic congestion, an unfit
population and global warming as a result.''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, representatives of the industries that would
have been the most affected by the Morris legislation _ fast-food
restaurants, banks and dry cleaners _ declared victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with the vote and confident it will hold,''
said Anna Copello, vice president of the Hospital Authority Credit
Union, the credit union for Grady Memorial Hospital that has a
drive-through window.
</P>
<P>
   But Copello said the industries would be willing to work with
city leaders if they decide to attack the problem through its
zoning rules, as some council members suggested. During the debate,
some members said the ban would send drive-through businesses to
the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Others said the move would unfairly burden new businesses that
would not have drive-throughs while their older competitors did.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred Charles writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
