<SLUG> BC-RUSSELL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSELL RETIRING AS CENTRAL NEWSPAPERS INC. CHAIRMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Duplication warning: Story moving in news and financial
categories)   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Frank E. Russell, 78, a low-key but forceful executive
who led the parent corporation of ``The Arizona Republic'' to
robust growth in an era of modern technology, is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, chairman of the board of Central Newspapers Inc., will
step down at the end of December after 39 years with CNI.
</P>
<P>
   The corporation also operates ``The Indianapolis Star'' and
``The Indianapolis News,'' as well as other newspapers and
enterprises in Arizona, Indiana and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the growth of the company, it was Frank's
fine and quiet hand that was always steadily on the helm,'' said
CNI President and Chief Executive Louis A. Weil III.
</P>
<P>
   Russell served as a trusted counselor to CNI founder Eugene C.
Pulliam. After Pulliam died in 1975, Russell shaped CNI into a
competitive, publicly owned corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank was the pilot who guided the SS Pulliam through a very
difficult passage to a promising future,'' said Phoenix lawyer
Richard Mallery, a longtime friend of Russell's.
</P>
<P>
   Russell will continue as a key overseer of the trust that
controls CNI and of a charitable trust begun by Pulliam's widow,
the late Nina Pulliam. He will remain a CNI director.
</P>
<P>
   A genial man with a sharp business mind, Russell called on his
training as an accountant and lawyer in serving the newspaper
company.
</P>
<P>
   His stewardship helped keep the Pulliam newspapers on firm
financial ground, and in recent years, his behind-the-scenes
leadership contributed to CNI's growing profitability.
</P>
<P>
   CNI stock recently traded at $68 a share, and had traded at more
than $76, up from $21 when the corporation went public in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who always maintained a low profile, said last week
that his philosophy has been ``to step back far enough so that the
good people you've hired can do their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Weil described Russell as a keen observer, someone who listens
to the ideas of the people who work for him and backs them up. An
ex-Marine, Russell values and exhibits loyalty, Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a decision is made, he's there to support you all the
way,'' Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   Though devoted to business, Russell never forgets how to have
fun, said Marge Tarplee, former corporate secretary for CNI who
retired in 1994 as head of the CNI Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Russell is an avid golfer and ballroom dancer and loves to
socialize with CNI employees, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always said I never knew anyone who worked harder or played
harder than Frank Russell,'' Tarplee said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell will continue in his role as one of three trustees of
the Eugene C. Pulliam Trust, which has voting control of CNI. The
other trustees are Weil and Eugene S. Pulliam, executive vice
president of CNI and publisher of ``The Star'' and ``The News.''
Eugene S. Pulliam is Eugene C. Pulliam's son.
</P>
<P>
   Russell also will help distribute grants to charities in Phoenix
and Indianapolis as one of the three trustees of the $380 million
Nina Mason Pulliam Charitable Trust. The other trustees are
Russell's wife, Nancy, and Carol Peden Schatt.
</P>
<P>
   Among his accomplishments at CNI, Russell pushed the adoption of
cutting-edge technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' has emerged as one of the most technologically
advanced newspapers in America. It was one of the first and largest
newspapers to be completely paginated, meaning that all its
elements _ text, graphics, photos and advertisements _ are composed
with computers during the production process.
</P>
<P>
   Though Russell has embraced the computer age and the growing
field of online journalism, he said he believes the traditional
newspaper will never become obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think there's always going to be a place for the
printed page,'' Russell said. ``I think we have to do everything we
can to complement the printed newspaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell got involved in the newspaper business almost by
accident after having tried out other careers.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Kokomo, Ind., on Dec. 6, 1920, he graduated cum laude
with a bachelor's degree from the University of Evansville in
Indiana in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he served in the Marine Corps, and was a
first lieutenant when discharged in 1945. In 1946, he earned a
certificate from the International Accountants Society in Chicago
and in 1951, graduated with a juris doctor degree with honors from
the Indiana University School of Law.
</P>
<P>
   He worked for the George S. Olive and Co. accounting firm and
was later vice president of Spickelmier Industries, Inc., a
diversified construction business in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959, he decided to apply for a job as business manager of
CNI and ``The Indianapolis Star'' and ``News.''
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour interview with Eugene C. Pulliam in an
Indianapolis hotel room, Russell decided he wanted the job and
Pulliam decided he wanted to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   He was business manager until 1977, when he became vice
president and general manager of CNI, then moved to the presidency
of CNI in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Russell retired as president and CEO of CNI in 1995, and then
became chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   He said his greatest accomplishment with CNI was handling the
original public offering of CNI stock in 1989, conducting a
three-week selling trip to all the principal financial centers of
the U.S. and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The stock available sold out, a market value for it was finally
established, and the demand was so great that half again as much
could have been sold, Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   His other major accomplishments were closing out Eugene C.
Pulliam's estate without straining corporate finances and bringing
modern, professional management to CNI.
</P>
<P>
   Weil said that through it all, Russell's devotion to CNI
employees has been paramount. He noted that a friend of Russell's,
newspaper publisher and former Marine Gen. Victor ``Brute'' Krulak,
used to say there are only three rules of leadership, and each one
is ``Take care of the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Frank has followed that to a fault,'' Weil said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said his retirement will give him and his wife a chance
to travel more and will allow him the opportunity to play more golf
and possibly to explore Civil War battlefields, which have
fascinated him for years.
</P>
<P>
   But his new role won't remove him from the communities of
Phoenix and Indianapolis, where he and his wife maintain homes.
</P>
<P>
   Russell has been involved in civic activities in both cities,
including past service on the board of the Arizona Community
Foundation and work on the board of the Phoenix Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Russell puts as much of himself into his work with the zoo as he
does with his business, and does so with gentlemanly grace and
attentiveness, said Jeff Williamson, executive director of the
Phoenix Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a trustee you can always count on,'' Williamson said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell and his wife have also supported the Indianapolis Zoo
and Russell is on the board of the Eiteljorg Museum of American
Indians and Western Art in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Museum president and CEO John Vanausdall said Russell is
``deeply devoted to (the city's) future and its quality of life _
arts, social services and higher education.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said he enjoys civic service, but he might have to
reconsider his future activities out of deference to his duties as
a trustee of the Nina Mason Pulliam trust.
</P>
<P>
   The trustees will meet Thursday to distribute $5.3 million in
grants to charities in Phoenix and Indianapolis, Russell said, and
they will also discuss whether they need to give up affiliations
with civic organizations to avoid conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, Mallery said, Russell's role with the trust will
allow him to continue to make an impact on his two home cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Russell is going to have as much influence on the future
of Phoenix and Indianapolis as head of the (trust) as he has had on
Central Newspapers,'' Mallery said. ``I personally think he's going
to have a lot of fun and it's going to be good for all of us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
