<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-REEVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCONSISTENT COWBOYS HAVE CONCERNED FANS ON EDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The ledge we're teetering on today is as crowded
as a Bourbon Street balcony on a Saturday night in New Orleans'
French Quarter. Not much elbow room. Lots of folks down below
screaming, ``Jump!''
</P>
<P>
   Don't do it, Cowboys fans.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panic,'' coach Chan Gailey said yesterday at Valley Ranch,
``but don't panic.''
</P>
<P>
   Makes perfect sense to me.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message Gailey will try to get across to his players
this week after the most pathetic and dismal performance of the
season in a 22-3 loss to the gawd-awful Saints on Sunday in the
Superdome.
</P>
<P>
   You say it's time for Gailey to get in their faces. Don't be
surprised if he has already done just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That,'' Gailey said, ``is between me and the players.''
</P>
<P>
   His message is as important to fans, however, as it is to
players, maybe more so. The Cowboys, in their hearts, know exactly
what happened in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't just quit, they never came to play.
</P>
<P>
   Most fans, on the other hand, are totally confused. And why
wouldn't they be? They're not sure whether this team is a bona fide
division champion with a legitimate shot at advancing to the NFC
Championship Game or a collection of no-heart pretenders who have
padded their record by beating up on a long list of tomato cans.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, it's a little bit of all of the above.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times I do \Rsee an identity emerging,\S and then there are
setbacks,'' Gailey said. ``The key is to try to put it all together
at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, you start with the emotional part and the team psyche.
You've got to get that part going before you can get the rest of it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   That goes right to the heart _ or lack thereof _ of what
happened in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, when it comes to the Cowboys, the tendency is to
analyze and over-analyze. We never look for the simple answer, even
when there is one that explains precisely what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention:
</P>
<P>
   With the NFC East championship all but assured and a playoff
spot in the bag, coming off a 10-day layoff, playing in a city with
lots of distractions and with many players' families along for the
Mardi Gras atmosphere, the Cowboys took an extra day off.
Emotionally, they simply weren't ready to play, and they aren't
good enough to get away with that.
</P>
<P>
   It was a case of bad timing, because the Saints, on the other
hand, had recently had their manhood challenged by coach Mike Ditka
and been confronted by owner Tom Benson. They came out highly
motivated, fighting for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   The mixture was more potent than a Pat O'Brien's hurricane:
Saints 22, Cowboys 3.
</P>
<P>
   Sickening, but relatively simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a football team that went out there, not expecting an
all-out war,'' Gailey said of the Cowboys, ``and that's what we
got. It's my responsibility to make sure they're ready for war
every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it disturbing to see the Cowboys go belly up because the
Saints were fired up and threw some blitzes they weren't expecting
at them? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   Do Gailey and his coaching staff deserve part of the blame for
not realizing that the team wasn't emotionally prepared?
Absolutely, and he freely admits it.
</P>
<P>
   What Gailey is trying to tell us, if we'll quit gnashing our
teeth and rending our clothes (all proper Bourbon Street things to
do, by the way) long enough to listen, is that, until proven
otherwise, what happened Sunday should be filed under
``aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   I.e.: Is Larry Allen going to be slapped silly every week like
he was by Joe Johnson in New Orleans? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at any one game and say, that's this team, then
you're making a mistake,'' Gailey said. ``I think you have to look
at where you are and who you are after 16 games and then make an
evaluation of your performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had two \Rgames\S that I thought were defensive
\Raberrations\S, and I'm assuming that this one was offensively.
You want to get that across and, at the same time, create a sense
of urgency.''
</P>
<P>
   What we have here, then, is a team probably headed for a 10-6
finish (don't you dare tell me you wouldn't have taken that and
been deliriously happy before the season began). And it will hit
the playoffs, still wondering whether it can play with the big
boys.
</P>
<P>
   Should you worry? Darn right. We all know that quitting can
become a habit. It gets easier with practice (see December 1997).
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, why don't you crawl on in off that ledge. If
one more fool steps out there, the whole thing might come crashing
down.
</P>
<P>
   Panic, but don't panic. It's the theme of the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
