<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ON ALERT TO IMPROVE BY PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman said the 22-3
loss to New Orleans on Sunday ``stung'' more than any this season,
called the performance a setback for the team, and agreed that the
offense is better than it showed against the Saints but must get
things corrected quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of us trying to win one game out of the next
three,'' said Aikman of the Cowboys needing one victory in their
last three games to clinch a playoff berth. ``We want to play well
going into the playoffs. It starts against Kansas City. There is an
urgency to play well this week because of what we want to be doing
in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   So, was the abominable performance by the Cowboys' offense
against the Saints, marked by a season-low 182 yards, the beginning
of a trend or an aberration?
</P>
<P>
   The real answer might not come until the Cowboys (8-5) play at
Kansas City (5-8) on Sunday, considering the traditionally
defensive-minded Chiefs are certain to employ the same blitzing
schemes the Saints used to shut down the Cowboys' offense.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey, citing 30-point outputs
in four of the past five games, is treating Sunday's failing, which
included a 38-year low eight yards rushing and a seven-year low
three points, as a variation with an asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Cowboys' biggest problems against the Saints were
not adjusting to the blitzing alignments and allowing too much
penetration. However, he believes the problems will be corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming that this was an aberration on offense,'' Gailey
said. ``I have to get that across to the team. At the same time, I
want to create a sense of urgency. Don't panic, but do panic. If we
don't have a sense of urgency to get things done, we are going to
waste a big opportunity that we've got here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys need one victory in the final three games to clinch
the NFC East title and a playoff berth. They could also clinch the
division with another loss by the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   The rushing ineptitude was considered the biggest disappointment
by the Cowboys. The eight-yard total beat the previous
franchise-low by 12 yards. Gailey and running backs Clarence
Shelmon both said the Cowboys never adjusted to the Saints' blitz
package, which featured aggressive stunts through the middle of the
Cowboys' offense line.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey called it the worst performance by the Cowboys' offensive
line this season. Rookie center Mike Kiselak, who played the
previous five years in the Canadian Football League and has started
only four games for the Cowboys, and rookie right guard Flozell
Adams, who is starting for injured veteran Everett McIver, had the
toughest time adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, however, refused to use inexperience as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to get them to do it,'' Gailey said. ``It doesn't
matter how long somebody's been in the league. It doesn't matter
what the situation, whether you are an All-Pro or whatever. You gotto do it. We are going to continue to see this stuff until you
prove you can beat it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shelmon said the line wasn't all to blame. He said the running
backs have to have better recognition of the blitzes, as well, and
sometimes have to make plays when the holes aren't there.
</P>
<P>
   Making big plays on the outside by the receivers also could have
helped make the Saints back off of their aggressive style. However,
Aikman, who passed for only 192 yards, had little time to throw the
ball, and when he did, the receivers were unable to do anything
with it.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman said the Cowboys missed having the services of
game-breaking star Deion Sanders (sprained toe) and veteran
receiver Ernie Mills, who is out for the season with perforated
small intestine. But he also said the Cowboys had enough players to
get things done against the Saints.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders should be ready to play against the Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman, however, said the bottom line is execution, and he
believes a lack of mental preparation was the biggest problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has to learn something from the game,'' Aikman said.
``That we have to execute. That we have to play well. We are not
good enough to not play well and win games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
