A7758 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENATOR-FORT-HOOD-VIS     12-07 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENATOR-FORT-HOOD-VISIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Senators promise to defend Fort Hood
 &HT;    By Pamela LeBlanc
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT HOOD, Texas _ Stopping at Fort Hood during a weeklong tour
of Texas military bases, U.S. Senators Kay Bailey Hutchison and
Phil Gramm vowed Monday to fight for increased defense spending and
warned of another round of base closures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a virtual certainty we'll be forced into at least one
possible base closing commission,'' Gramm said Monday during a
luncheon at the Officers' Club of the Killeen army post. ``We want
to be sure when the bad news comes about base closings it comes
down somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Four rounds of base closings starting in 1988 cost thousands of
jobs and shut down more than 70 major military bases, including
several in Texas. Victims of the cuts included Bergstrom Air Force
Base in southeast Austin, which is being converted to the city's
new airport, and Kelly Air Force Base in San Antonio, which is
scheduled to close in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The closings are necessary if the military is to keep pay and
benefits up, and they won't threaten Fort Hood, Gramm said. With
42,000 soldiers, the Killeen facility is the largest army post in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fort Hood will be here and be operating when Jesus comes
back,'' Gramm said. ``Fort Hood will never be closed as long as we
have military in America.''
</P>
<P>
   At a time when military recruitment is down and retention is a
growing concern, Hutchison said she would work to attract and keep
military personnel. Health care, housing, pay and equipment all
will be examined, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure we're doing everything we can to keep
this base strong,'' said Hutchison, a member of the Senate
Appropriations subcommittees on defense and military construction.
``If we are going to ask our military to do more _ and we are _
we're going to have to give them more.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm agreed, saying the trend in the past decade to cut defense
spending appears to be changing. ``We cut defense spending too
much. We're starting a trend to reverse that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The senators commended the Killeen community's support of family
members of soldiers deployed on a peace-keeping mission to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fort Hood is doing its part to carry out the U.S. mission in
Bosnia, and I am proud of the way the communities and schools here
have expressed such solid support for the families of those sent
overseas,'' Hutchison said.
</P>
<P>
   The senators later participated in a private video conference
with family members of soldiers deployed to Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The senators sidestepped questions about the ongoing
Congressional impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in the hands of the House of Representatives,'' Hutchison
said. ``Until they have done what they're going to do, there's not
a role for the Senate to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the senators will visit Corpus Christi Naval Air
Station, Corpus Christi Army Depot and Naval Air Station Ingleside
at Corpus Christi, Naval Air Station Kingsville and Laughlin Air
Force Base in Del Rio.
</P>
<P>
   Friday they will tour Fort Bliss in El Paso, Dyess Air Force
Base in Abilene and Goodfellow Air Force Base in San Angelo. They
plan to visit military bases in San Antonio early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela LeBlanc writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
