<SLUG> BC-NORTHROP-LAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHROP TO CUT 1,500 JOBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAN PILLER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
GRAND PRAIRIE _ Northrop Grumman told workers at its Grand Prairie
and Dallas plants in Texas Monday that it will cut 1,500 jobs from
those operations next year because of cutbacks in the work they do
for the Boeing 747 jumbo jet.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another 1,100 Northrop workers at plants in Hawthorne, Calif.,
and Perry, Ga., will lose their jobs because of a decline in orders
for the 747. Northrop is the plane's prime subcontractor.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Prairie and Dallas plants, which employ 5,400 workers,
have made the tails for the Boeing 747 since the airplane went into
production 30 years ago. Boeing said last week that it is slicing
production of the 747 to two per month, down from 3.5 per month
announced last summer and five per month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Northrop told its employees during the summer to expect 300
layoffs next year because of cutbacks in 747 production; that
number is included in the 1,500 total disclosed Monday. After
Boeing announced deeper cutbacks last week, Northrop told its
workers to expect more cuts, too.
</P>
<P>
   Employees were told the size of the planned cuts Monday in a
memo from Jim Hoover, the Northrop vice president for
aerostructures.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of news is difficult for everyone, for those whose
jobs are being eliminated and for those who will remain,'' Hoover
said in the memo.
</P>
<P>
   But layoff notices won't be given to workers until January,
Northrop spokeswoman Georgia Maddox Engle said.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks will be divided about evenly between production
workers and support staff in engineering, human resources,
accounting and other functions.
</P>
<P>
   Workers will be given 60 days notice, but no formal severance
package. Northrop will provide employee outplacement and other
assistance for the laid-off workers, Engle said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of United Aerospace Local 848, which represents 2,441
hourly workers at the local plants, said employees with the least
amount of seniority in various job groups will be laid off first.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts announced Monday represent 4.8 percent of
Northrop's work force of 54,000 people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
