<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-07 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-LEAFS-NYT     12-07 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS DEFEAT MAPLE LEAFS, 6-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On Nov. 25, the Rangers were transformed into
contenders. They did not win on that day, the day Petr Nedved was
acquired, but it is clear now that he was the piece the Rangers
were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Nedved scored a goal and had two assists as the
Rangers won their fifth straight game, defeating the Toronto Maple
Leafs 6-2 at Madison Square Garden. The Rangers, now 10-9-7, moved
one game above .500 for the first time since Oct. 11, 1997, and
into a three-way tie with Ottawa and Pittsburgh for seventh place
in the Eastern Conference with 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   In the seven games since Nedved arrived in a five-player trade
that sent Aleksei Kovalev to the Pittsburgh Penguins, the Rangers
are 5-1-1. Nedved, a flashy center who plays between the
defense-minded Niklas Sundstrom and the gritty Mike Knuble, has
three goals and seven assists for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved sat out more than a year because of a contract dispute
with the Penguins and was playing in the International Hockey
League when he was traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Petr is happy to be back in the NHL and he wants to
prove to everybody that he's an elite player,'' Rangers Coach John
Muckler said. ``And he's doing a very good job of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nedved's third-period goal, on a wicked wrist shot from the
slot, staked the Rangers to a 5-2 lead at 12 minutes 32 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nedved has been outstanding since he's been here,'' said Wayne
Gretzky, whose load has been lightened with Nedved's arrival.
``He's been as good as anybody could be, especially with the fact
that he's been out for a year and a half. I couldn't be happier for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Mike Richter has also helped the Rangers with strong
performances lately. On Monday, he made 24 saves to improved to
5-0-1 in his last six games. Curtis Joseph, the Maple Leafs'
goalie, made 23 stops.
</P>
<P>
   Sundstrom and Knuble have benefited from playing with Nedved;
Sundstrom has a goal and three assists while Knuble has a goal and
two assists. Over the last six games, they have formed the Rangers'
best line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a team effort,'' Nedved said. ``We've been working
hard and winning some games.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunny and Mike are smart players,'' Nedved added. ``It's fun
to play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and the Maple Leafs are two of the hottest teams in
the NHL. The Rangers, who lost their first four games and were
so-so the next month and a half, entered last night's game having
won four straight. (Last year's team never managed a four-game
winning streak.)
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs, who began the night having won seven of their last 10
games, sit atop the Northeast Division and were tied with the
Devils for the Eastern Conference lead in points at 32.
</P>
<P>
   The first period was fast and crisp. The Rangers took a 2-1 lead
on goals by Knuble and Todd Harvey, who scored with eight seconds
left. Toronto's Fredrik Modin scored the game's first goal at 22
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers came back nine minutes later when Knuble blasted a
shot through Joseph's pads from the slot. The goal, Knuble's fourth
this season, came on what may have been the Rangers' best shift all
year. Knuble, Sundstrom and Nedved were relentless in their pursuit
of the puck, and it paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey's goal gave the Rangers their first lead. The rugged
right wing threw a board-bending check on Yannick Tremblay, who
turned over the puck to Adam Graves. Graves fired the puck off
Joseph's chest pad. Harvey, bouncing off Tremblay, knocked the puck
under Joseph's stick.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, Sundstrom and Brian Leetch scored for the
Rangers and Sergei Berezin tallied for the Maple Leafs as the
Rangers extended their lead to 4-2. Nedved assisted on both goals.
</P>
<P>
   John MacLean scored the Rangers' sixth goal late in the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
