<HEADER>
A7841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-ART-1ST     12-07 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH SPACE STATION JOINED, ASTRONAUTS TURN TO WIRING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to rewrite 7th and 8th grafs. No other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By WARREN E. LEARY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two astronauts became electricians Monday as they
left the shuttle Endeavour and meticulously assembled dozens of
electrical cables to connect the first two sections of the
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from Endeavour's airlock a half-hour ahead of schedule,
at a little before 5 p.m. ET, two experienced space walkers floated
up the sides of the two-station modules stacked above the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Jerry Ross of the Air Force and Dr. James Newman, a
physicist, ventured into the shuttle's cargo bay for tools and then
hooked themselves up to safety tethers before moving up the space
station modules docked to Endeavour.
</P>
<P>
   While Newman maneuvered up the sides of the modules using
footrests and handholds, Ross moved about the seven-story structure
attached to the end of the shuttle's 50-foot robot arm, which was
controlled from inside by Lieut. Col. Nancy Currie, a former Army
helicopter pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Although their space walk had been billed as one of the most
complicated in the history of spaceflight, the astronauts moved
through their tasks so quickly that NASA Mission Control officials
said they were far ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The space-walking team members appeared in good humor as they
methodically worked through their duties, frequently joking with
each other and laughing as they checked off work completed from
their lists. Taking a moment to look up at the space station
segments looming above, Newman remarked: ``This is sure a beautiful
piece of hardware.''
</P>
<P>
   After just 4 1/2 hours into the spacewalk, the astronauts
completed connecting 40 cables that are to carry power and data
through the growing space outpost. At 10:30 p.m. ET, Russian ground
stations sent commands to Zarya to turn on power converters to send
electricity through the new wiring. And at 10:49 p.m., the
Endeavour crew noted that data coming from Unity indicated it was
activated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good connection with good data,'' said Marine Col.
Robert Cabana, the shuttle commander.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts' work began when they joined eight connectors
from the American Unity module to a docking adaptor at one end that
connects the unit to the shuttle. Then they installed a permanent
safety wire up the side of the three-story Unity on which they and
future astronaut-builders could slide their tether straps.
</P>
<P>
   The space walk, the first of three planned for the mission,
comes after Sunday's successful mating of the Russian-made Zarya
logistics module with the American-made Unity connecting module.
After Endeavour, with Unity mounted in its cargo bay, rendezvoused
with Zarya 240 miles above the Earth, Currie used the robot arm to
grab the 40,000-pound cylinder and pull it down to meet with the
American module.
</P>
<P>
   The units together form a seven-story, 35-ton tower perched on
Endeavour's bay, ready to be fitted with the 40 electrical
connections that will allow both modules to operate together with
electricity generated by Zarya's solar power panels.
</P>
<P>
   Newman unclamped each of the connectors, which are attached to
cables 20 to 30 feet in length, and handed them to Ross. Before
putting the connectors together and locking them in place, Ross had
to inspect each end to make sure the tiny pins inside were not bent
or blocked by debris. When the connection were completed, he
attached a protective cover to each joint.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen nations, led by the United States and Russia, are
working together to build the space station, which is expected to
cost between $40 billion and $60 billion. The venture will require
connecting more than 100 major components, hauled into space on 45
shuttle and rocket flights and assembled during 162 planned space
walks, or EVA's, short for extra-vehicular activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first EVA is by far the most critical one,'' Ross, a
veteran of four previous space walks, said in a pre-flight
interview.
</P>
<P>
   After the astronauts complete all of the electrical connections,
space station controllers in Houston and near Moscow were to send
signals to the modules to activate them and to verify the links.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts also were going to remove thermal covers from two
exterior computers on Unity during the space walk.
</P>
<P>
   On a second space walk, set for Wednesday, the same astronauts
are to install several handrails and footrests on the outside of
the modules. They will also remove the restraints and connectors
that helped hold Unity in the shuttle bay during launching. And
they are to install two antennas for a communications system,
connect more cables and place a sunshade over the Unity computers.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, members of Endeavour's crew of six will venture
into the station for the first time, slowly working its way through
numerous hatches, making sure the pressure and air in each unit are
acceptable before moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Station officials say they should find the insides like the
unfinished interior of a new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long corridor, basically, that doesn't have a lot of
features from one end to the other,'' Frank Culbertson, operations
manager for the station program, said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last jobs of this mission will be to transfer
supplies and tools from Endeavour that will be left behind for
future crews.The first crew to use the units will go up in January,
2000, after a Russian service module with living quarters and an
American power array are in place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
